r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-VACATION-KAN &LR;      06-11 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-VACATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC SEEMS TO BE TAKING A VACATION FROM Y2K WORRIES, EXPERTS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Go ahead, grill those burgers and then take a
little nap in the hammock. The last thing you want to worry about
is Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   After all, you're thinking, the problem is far away and besides,
it's almost fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, say experts who are beginning to worry that the summer
vacation that people are taking from Y2K will cost us all later. In
fact, a survey of 337 Y2K professionals released Thursday shows
most experts still are concerned about the impact of the computer
bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's summer and we're trying to chill out and relax,'' says Ed
Yardeni, a leading Y2K expert with Deutsche Bank Securities in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile, the complacency on Y2K will persist right through
the summer,'' he said. ``We're almost getting lazy. It's a Greek
tragedy in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that the public, by snoozing now, will wake up too
late to make calm and common-sense preparations.
</P>
<P>
   And almost everyone agrees that interest in Y2K has dropped off
the chart.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Vera Jr., generator sales manager at Cummins Onan
Mid-America in Kansas City, received 20 calls a week through March.
Now, he gets about six calls a week from people looking to purchase
5,000- to 6,000-watt home generators.
</P>
<P>
   Banker Larry Kucinick of NationsBank Kansas City says there have
been no takers in a week-old Small Business Administration Y2K loan
program to provide $5,000 to $25,000 loans for vulnerable small
companies.
</P>
<P>
   And judging by the number of people attending local Y2K forums,
Dean Katerndahl, head of the Mid-America Regional Council's
Government Innovations Forum, also senses a lull.
</P>
<P>
   The same phenomenon is occurring nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet survey in May of 100 grass-roots activists in 28
states shows the ``pendulum is unmistakably swinging toward apathy
and complacency,'' said Liza Christian, former director of the
Rogue Valley Y2K Task Force in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the country's most recognized Y2K trackers has
taken himself out of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long, hot, quiet summer of Y2K denial,''
said ``Timebomb 2000'' author and 30-year computer expert Ed
Yourdon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is moving into the Y2K end game with the prevailing
attitude that government and industry are in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every industry has forecast certain victory over the
computer bug in recent months, but often without independent,
third-party verification of their claims, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read them carefully, it's quite clear they're putting
an awful lot of positive spin on the positive news and not putting
any negative spin on the negative news,'' Yardeni said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the American Hospital Association released a
statement two months ago that it was ``confident'' all hospitals
would meet the Y2K deadline, even though only 13 percent were
actually Y2K-compliant at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have issued confusing pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   After warning last fall of potential disaster, the President's
Year 2000 Conversion Council began sounding more optimistic, saying
that industry had heeded the forecast and gone to work. John
Koskinen, chairman of the council, then began issuing Y2K
statements using phrases such as ``all is well'' and ``don't
worry.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the co-chairmen of the Senate Special
Committee on the Year 2000 Technology Problem were sounding much
more dire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K is one of the most serious and potentially devastating
events this nation has ever encountered,'' according to a joint
statement in March from Sen. Robert Bennett, a Utah Republican, and
Sen. Christoper Dodd, a Connecticut Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said in an interview this week that he never meant to
put a glossy spin on Y2K. The problem, he says, is that the message
is complex: National systems such as the power grid,
telecommunications network and air-traffic control are safe, but
people should be prepared for some localized disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of 337 Y2K professionals released Thursday by the
Washington D.C. Year 2000 Group shows that many experts still worry
about the bug.
</P>
<P>
   Total responses to all the poll questions show 45 percent think
computer problems will have a ``significant impact,'' according to
the group, while 10 percent think it will be ``the end of the world
as we know it.'' The remaining 45 percent think Y2K is going to be
a ``bump in the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, a poll taken by USA Today in March showed that 78
percent of the public expected no problems or only minor problems
because of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni, who continues to believe the computer glitch is likely
to cause a 70 percent chance of worldwide recession, senses the
public optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, people want to believe that Y2K will be a
complete and total non-event,'' he said. ``We have gone from
fearing the worst to assuming the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that may be explained by how people process information,
says Allan Hanson, a cultural anthropologist at the University of
Kansas. The steady drumbeat of Y2K news is beginning to take its
toll on public attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people hear the same message over and over again,'' he
said, ``they tune it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson, as well Yardeni and Yourdon, all agree the public will
begin paying attention again this fall.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: By that time, it may be difficult to calmly plan
and obtain all the items that organizations such as the American
Red Cross say you should set aside for the days following Jan. 1.
Unpredictable surges in last-minute demand could create chaos in
supply lines and inventories, they say.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, drug suppliers, grocers, bankers and discount retailers
all fear their biggest problems may not come from their computers,
but from the ensuing panic from those who have not outlined a Y2K
game plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
