<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-ADVOCATE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKER WILL ADVOCATE LESS COSTLY, MORE PERSONALIZED FUNERALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When the husband of national consumer
advocate Lisa Carlson died in 1981, local authorities in Vermont
had trouble coping with her insistence that she would handle the
details herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they asked which funeral home I was using, I told them to
bring the body back to the house. ... They were flabbergasted,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But they finally did as Carlson requested, she said, because the
law allowed it _ and still does in many states.
</P>
<P>
   The family, which had little money at the time, saved thousands
of dollars by forgoing standard expenses for embalming, a casket,
and other funeral and burial costs, Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   She transported the body herself _ in a pickup truck _ to a
local crematorium, and later held an open house and memorial
gathering at the family home.
</P>
<P>
   The experience set Carlson on a new career path as writer,
advocate and, for the past three years, executive director of the
Funeral and Memorial Society of America.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson will be in Kansas City on Sunday to deliver a free
lecture. She will discuss federal laws and state laws in Kansas and
Missouri, and how consumers can protect themselves from what she
says are typical funeral industry abuses, including high prices and
manipulative sales tactics that are difficult to resist while
grieving.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson's latest book, Caring for the Dead: Your Final Act of
Love, will be available for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The 600-page book has chapters on each of the 50 states'
requirements regarding death.
</P>
<P>
   Other chapters explore issues such as burial on private
property, organ donation, funeral packages purchased in advance,
cemeteries and federal consumer-rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson said there was growing awareness of consumer rights as
well as a budding do-it-yourself funeral movement in recent years,
especially among baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the generation that wrote their own wedding vows, did
natural childbirth and is into homeschooling of their children,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a need to personalize the funeral experience, and
those that do are finding it to be therapeutic and healing.''
</P>
<P>
   And cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson's appearance is sponsored by the Funeral and Memorial
Society of Greater Kansas City, which monitors local funeral home
prices and provides public education on industry issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
