<SLUG> BC-CANNIBAL-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDICT IN CANNIBALISM CASE IS SET ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Albert Fentress, a former Hudson Valley
teacher who tortured, killed and cannibalized a teen-ager 20 years
ago, will remain in a state psychiatric hospital in Suffolk County
despite a jury's decision that he should be set free, a state judge
has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Fentress, 57, who was found not guilty by reason of insanity in
1980 in the killing of the teen-ager, Paul Masters, persuaded
jurors in April that, though he remained mentally ill, he no longer
posed a threat to society and should be treated in a halfway house
with little supervision.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Justice Harry E. Seidell of state Supreme
Court set aside the jury's decision at the request of lawyers for
the state Office of Mental Health and the Dutchess County district
attorney. Seidell reasoned that the six jurors had acted
irrationally both in accepting and rejecting parts of the testimony
of expert psychiatrists for each side.
</P>
<P>
   The state's experts had said that Fentress remained ill and
continued to need inpatient care, the judge explained, while
Fentress' experts, who included some of his doctors at Pilgrim
State Psychiatric Center in Brentwood, testified that he was no
longer ill and did not require such care.
</P>
<P>
   ``To believe that petitioner was mentally ill but did not need
inpatient care and treatment,'' Seidell said, referring to
Fentress, ``the jury would have to believe that outside the
hospital setting petitioner would somehow, on his own, develop
self-control and not pose a danger to others.''
</P>
<P>
   To appeal, Fentress would first have to seek permission from the
Appellate Division, according to lawyers in the attorney general's
office, which represented the Office of Mental Health.
</P>
<P>
   Fentress' lawyer, Kim L. Darrow, of the state's Mental Hygiene
Legal Service agency, did not respond to telephone messages
Thursday. But Michael L. Perlin, who specializes in mental
disability law at New York Law School, faulted the judge for
failing to explain in his decision why he had dismissed outright
the contention by Fentress' experts that he could be harmless in a
less restrictive setting.
</P>
<P>
   Perlin added that, while the judge's ruling would not set any
binding precedent until it was reviewed by an appellate court, it
could nevertheless unfairly hurt the interests of other mental
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time, in a vivid, well-publicized case, a trial judge
rejects a finding by a jury that a person is fit to be released,
that's going to have a spillover effect,'' he said. ``Other judges
are going to be more reluctant to release patients if there's a
question as to their danger to the community. And juries may not
want to bother finding for patients if they figure their verdicts
are going to be set aside anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But William V. Grady, the Dutchess County district attorney,
said the jury verdict had been ``totally inconsistent'' and
commended the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   In written statements issued Thursday, Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer said Fentress ``still poses a very serious threat to the
public,'' and Gov. George Pataki said the judge's decision ``is a
victory for justice, common sense and the safety of New Yorkers;
simply put, Albert Fentress should not be on the streets of New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Spitzer said the case had highlighted the need to
change the laws governing insanity pleas and the confinement of
mentally ill people who have committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Masters, the father of Fentress' victim, said by telephone
from his home in San Jose, Calif., that he still believed that
Fentress was dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very relieved for the people in Long Island that they
don't have to worry about Fentress wandering around unsupervised,''
Masters said. ``It'd be a shame to let another tragedy happen when
it could be avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Masters, 69, added that he was ``quite positive'' that Fentress
would eventually be released. ``He's always made aware of just what
he has to do to satisfy all the psychiatrists,'' he said of
Fentress' repeated attempts to gain his freedom in recent years.
``Eventually, he's going to do all the right things and give all
the right answers. I just hope it doesn't happen real soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
