A1256 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-AZR &LR;      06-11 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WILL COMPETE IN ARIZONA PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the rumors began swirling that presidential front-runner
George W. Bush was planning to give up Arizona without a fight,
Arizona congressman Matt Salmon hopped a flight to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon wanted to get a &UR; feel for the candidate. But he also
wanted to know whether Bush was going to make a genuine push in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked both him and his campaign manager about it, and they
said, `You bet we are (going for Arizona),' '' said Salmon, who
hasn't committed to any candidate but clearly has an eye for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that he is going to invest as much here as he
will in New Hampshire, but I think he takes it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, an Arizona Bush campaign remains a wispy concept
issuing only from the Texas governor's private discourse with
would-be supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has no office or permanent staff members here, also
has promised to make only one personal visit to Arizona between now
and January, according to organizers and fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters acknowledge that his efforts in Arizona may
appear faint compared with those of publishing magnate Steve
Forbes, Arizona Sen. John McCain and former Vice President Dan
Quayle. Still, the latest state poll puts Bush ahead of all
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Forbes launched a multimillion-dollar campaign blitz
focused, in part, on Arizona. McCain has vowed to win his home
state and has vigorously pursued the endorsements of many in the
state's political establishment. And Quayle, who lives with his
wife, Marilyn, in Paradise Valley, has his nationwide headquarters
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he (Bush) was coming every week, but it just doesn't
make any sense,'' said Gordon James, a local public relations
executive who is among a handful of Phoenix residents laying the
groundwork for Bush in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they are going to want to concentrate on New
Hampshire and Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're not going to Alaska and Hawaii, either, and in
1992, President Bush didn't ever come to Arizona, though we wish he
had.''
</P>
<P>
   James noted that, unlike other presidential aspirants who have
been kicking up dust on the campaign trail for months, Bush has
remained focused on his duties as governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's front-porch campaign will come to an end this week, when
he will sweep through Iowa and New Hampshire to attend a series of
fund-raisers and campaign events. He will travel in a chartered
commercial-size jet with 150 members of the media in tow.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush's first appearance in Arizona could come in
August after he first stops in California, James said.
Nevertheless, James insisted that the candidate would make a
sincere stab at winning Arizona's Feb. 22 primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not ceding any states to anybody,'' James said. ``We
need all 50 states, and he'll fight just as hard here as he'll
fight anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Arizona's prominence as an early presidential primary, a
number of political observers are not surprised by Bush's decision
to direct his campaign elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly every poll taken in Arizona, Bush has walloped Quayle
and Forbes and also outdistanced McCain, the state's apparent
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The latest survey, a Rocky Mountain Poll, showed Bush edging out
McCain, 30 percent to 26 percent, among Maricopa County
Republicans. Former Red Cross director Elizabeth Dole received 12
percent, Quayle got 11 percent, and Forbes netted 8 percent.
However, the Texas governor's lead was well within the poll's 6.9
percentage-point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Given his early strength, which comes without the benefit of a
single campaign appearance, Bush has little incentive to make a
splash here, observed Arizona State University pollster Bruce
Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, in the broader scheme of things for him, this frankly
isn't a very important state, and it is for McCain because it's his
home state and it's just before California,'' Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is doing well in the polls, but there are only 8
electoral votes here, so he would be wise to start with the larger
states and ensure that he is very solid there and move down as he
has the time and resources to do so,'' Merrill addded.
</P>
<P>
   Bush officials have made contact with several rising activists
in the Hispanic community, signaling a desire to tap into the
state's large Hispanic vote and its growing fund-raising base.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Trujillo, a key fund-raiser for Gov. Jane Hull, said the
Bush campaign contacted him recently seeking support.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo said he and several associates will organize a
fund-raising event, yet to be scheduled. Other fund-raisers close
to Hull are expected to wade in for Bush, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when,'' he said of the fledgling effort to
organize for Bush. ``But it's fast materializing.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate was the beneficiary of a fund-raiser in March,
which netted more than $250,000, and a second event in Tucson,
which brought in $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin DeMenna, a Phoenix lobbyist who wrote a check for Bush in
March, said the Texas governor's tack may be to take a bye in
Arizona under the assumption that even a second- or third-place
showing would constitute victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bet is that Bush never makes it out of the airport in this
state,'' DeMenna said. ``Why pick a fight if you win by not doing
it?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
