A1257 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-SPI &LR;      06-11 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WORM' VIRUS MAKES FOR UNPRODUCTIVE DAYS IN MANY OFFICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At 10 a.m. Thursday, Gina Calabria had a hard drive
full of plans, spreadsheets and presentations.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, all of them _ every last Microsoft Office document _
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was `It must be in here somewhere,''' said
the public-relations account supervisor at Seattle's Imagio
Technology Marketing and Communications Inc. ``But it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Calabria was one of hundreds of thousands of computer users
around the world struck by a new virus called Worm.Explore-Zip.
</P>
<P>
   The new virus spread across the Internet Thursday, infecting
machines by e-mail like the recent Melissa virus _ but causing more
damage by ruining computer files.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately clear how many machines or networks had
been stricken.
</P>
<P>
   The virus _ transmitted as an e-mail attachment to users, and
activated when the attachment is opened _ hit even the world's
largest software maker, Microsoft. The company had to disconnect
its computers for two hours Thursday morning so Microsoft users
wouldn't infect customer computers.
</P>
<P>
   The list of victims in the Seattle area alone was staggering.
Along with Microsoft, The Boeing Co.'s corporate e-mail system was
struck down. MSNBC reported the Worm was wreaking havoc on its
systems. Eastside technology company Attachmate took its e-mail
server off-line by midmorning Thursday and didn't expect it to be
back up until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on the Eastside _ where technology companies have
clustered since the 1980s _ was especially heavy Thursday afternoon
as companies crippled by the loss of e-mail collectively threw up
their hands and let workers go home early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those people who gets to work early,'' said Tiffany
Allesina, Attachmate's spokeswoman. ``I pretty much lost my hard
drive, except for some stuff I backed up last week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The firsthand reports we've gotten come from everything on the
scale from a single user to a systems where hundreds of thousands
of people are affected,'' said Mark Zajicek, a staff member of the
Computer Emergency Response Team at Carnegie-Mellon University in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Calabria's files were backed up on other computers, she
said. But several documents that hadn't been finished are now gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get an accurate count,'' she said. ``I won't know
until I begin needing to work on those documents again.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagio's computer folks spent about an hour and a half doing
nothing but damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into our mail server and noticed 18 messages that were
going to go out with this attachment,'' said John Stewart, Imagio's
director of technical services. ``We believe it moved through the
network and even infected people who didn't open the e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The Worm is written so that after it is activated in a mailbox
for the Microsoft Outlook program, it goes through a person's
e-mail inbox, sending out infectious, innocuous e-mails to any
address in the box.
</P>
<P>
   The Worm arrives by e-mail with a friendly message: ``Hi
(Recipient Name)! I received your e-mail and I shall send you a
reply ASAP. Till then, take a look at the attached zipped docs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Worm then begins searching a computer's hard drive for files
created with programs in Microsoft's top-selling Office suite _
Word, Excel and PowerPoint.
</P>
<P>
   Then it destroys them, leaving the file names intact, but
vaporizing the contents. It will also snake through the network
that a computer is attached to, destroying documents on other
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was first noticed in Israel on Sunday night, said Eric
Chien, a senior researcher at the Cupertino, Calif.-based Symantec
Anti-Virus Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was during their business day Monday,'' Chien said. ``The
virus hit about five of their major corporations. Early Monday
morning we hadn't heard much. But Monday night we got several
reports of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-virus team at Symantec, one of several industry groups
doing anti-viral work, had a solution down in an hour _ the fix is
to two delete two lines in a computer's WIN.INI file.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a crucial junction in the virus world, now,'' Chien
said. ``Originally we saw'' viruses that a person needed to
physically move from computer to computer to infect others. ``Now,
we've got network-aware programs that get onto a computer and can
propagate themselves across the world in a matter of seconds by
e-mailing themselves, with no input from the user.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as systems administrators around the area realized what
was happening on their systems, they moved to shut mail access
down. Boeing upped system security. Computer users at Seattle's
Safeco Insurance Co. received a message from the company's help
desk telling them to be wary of e-mails with attachments. Microsoft
employees received a similar message from their company's main help
desk, telling them not to open e-mails with attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it had an attachment with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Killing the Worm
</P>
<P>
   The virus is transmitted as an e-mail attachment and activated
when the attachment is opened up. Don't open unfamiliar e-mail. If
you're hit by the virus, Worm.ExploreZip will go after files with
the extensions: .doc, .xls, .ppt, .h, .c, .cpp and .asm.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to remove it if you're running Windows 95 or Windows
98:
</P>
<P>
   Restart your computer in MS-DOS and enter the WIN.INI file.
Remove the line
``run &QC; C:(backslash)WINDOWS(backslash)SYSTEM(backslash)Explore.exe
</P>
<P>
   Then delete the file
C:(backslash)WINDOWS(backslash)SYSTEM(backslash)EXPLORE.EXE
</P>
<P>
   Source, Symantec Corp., Network Associates
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
