<HEADLINE>
KINGS' LIST GETS SHORTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ John Van Boxmeer has made it onto the Los
Angeles Kings' short list.
</P>
<P>
   So has former Canadian national team coach Andy Murray.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' search for coach Larry Robinson's replacement
narrowed Thursday as general manager Dave Taylor announced through
a spokesman that former Buffalo Sabres coach Ted Nolan and Detroit
Red Wings assistant Dave Lewis have been eliminated from contention
for the position.
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer, coach and general manager of the IHL's Long Beach
Ice Dogs, had a second interview for the job Wednesday with Taylor,
assistant general manager Kevin Gilmore and team president Tim
Leiweke. Murray had a second interview Thursday. A fifth candidate,
Montreal Canadiens assistant coach Dave King, has yet to be invited
back for a second interview but has not officially been eliminated
from contention, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back for a second interview and be considered as a
serious candidate is an excellent sign,'' Van Boxmeer said
Thursday. ``I'm flattered to be getting the consideration I'm
getting. I'm excited to be able to go back for a second interview.
Now, it's kind of wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer admitted the lengthy hiring process has him on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of nerve-wracking when it's getting this close,'' he
said. ``You're excited that you're close. You're certainly very
excited about the possibility. There are a lot of things about the
Kings' situation I like. They're going into a brand-new building
and a brand-new practice site, and they're a team that has the
ability to rise very quickly through the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're better than they were last year (when they
missed the playoffs for the fifth time in six years). I think they
can rise rapidly. And they have a general manager who I have a lot
of respect for and feel very comfortable being around. It would be
a wonderful opportunity for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ice Dogs owner Barry Kemp said he has compiled a list of
candidates to replace Van Boxmeer, and said he expects he'll have
to use it, though he has yet to contact anyone on the list. Kemp
said if Van Boxmeer is hired by the Kings, he will offer the job to
former Kings defenseman Mark Hardy, the Ice Dogs' assistant coach.
But there's a possibility Hardy would follow Van Boxmeer to the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Leiweke) has asked me about (Van Boxmeer),'' Kemp said. ``I
said the same thing I'd say to anybody: I can't imagine a better
candidate to take over the Kings. Here's a guy who's played at the
highest level, he was an All-Star as a player, he won a Stanley
Cup, he's been an assistant coach at the NHL level (with Buffalo),
he won a (championship) as a head coach in the AHL (at Rochester)
and he's kept us as one of the top two or three teams in the IHL
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's paid his dues. I can't imagine there's a candidate with
the variety of skills Boxy has who also has as much of an
understanding of the way an organization works. Granted, I'm a
little prejudiced, but put it this way: If I owned the Kings, I'd
hire him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
