A1259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACCUSED-NAZI-NYT &LR;      06-11 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCUSED-NAZI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ACCUSED IN NAZI CASE LEAVES COUNTRY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 74-year-old Sullivan County, N.Y., man accused of
concealing his wartime past as a guard at three Nazi death camps in
Poland renounced his American citizenship and is now living in
Germany, federal officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Dmytro Sawchuk of Glen Spey, appeared at the U.S.
Consulate in Frankfurt on March 23 to relinquish his American
citizenship, according to the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan,
which had been seeking to deport him.
</P>
<P>
   Sawchuk had been accused by the Justice Department last year of
having lied to the Immigration and Naturalization Service about his
past. Rather than face a trial that was set to begin on Sept. 30,
officials said, he fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed last June in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, prosecutors said that Sawchuk, an ethnic Ukrainian who
was born in Leski, Poland, joined the German military in 1943 and
served at three slave labor and extermination camps in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The first was an S.S. labor camp in Trawniki, where prosecutors
said Sawchuk was an armed guard. Later, the government said, he was
a guard at the Belzec death camp, where the complaint claimed
Sawchuk guarded Jewish prisoners who were forced to exhume and burn
the corpses of hundreds of thousands of Jews who were murdered in
1942.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Sawchuk immigrated to the United States in 1951
from Germany and, by lying about his past, became a naturalized
citizen in 1957 in Manhattan, said Eli M. Rosenbaum, the director
of the Justice Department's Office of Special Investigations, which
seeks out and prosecutes Nazi war criminals living illegally in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum called Sawchuk's flight from American soil ``an
outstanding resolution of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to achieve cancellation of their ill-gotten U.S.
citizenship,'' he said. ``That's exactly what we accomplished in
this case. And it took far less time than if this case had gone
through the litigation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawchuk's lawyer, Ivars Berzins, declined through his secretary
to discuss his case or his client's move to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weitzman, who directs a task force at the Simon Wiesenthal
Center that searches for Nazi-era war criminals, said that
Sawchuk's voluntary departure, while achieving the same goal as a
court trial would have, was less satisfying. ``On the one hand
you'd like to have a completed trial to show for the historical
record,'' he said Thursday. ``On the other hand, it's an admission
of clear guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Weitzman added that the Wiesenthal Center plans to formally ask
the German government to begin legal proceedings of its own against
Sawchuk. But that is not a likely prospect, said Rosenbaum in a
telephone interview from Washington. ``He would know that there are
many other people who have not been prosecuted, which is the case
generally in Europe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were not exactly surprised upon hearing in March
that Sawchuk, who lived a reclusive life in Glen Spey, N.Y., with
his wife, had fled and given up any chance of legally returning to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an increasingly common result in our cases because our
track record in court indicates to them the likely futility of
going to trial,'' Rosenbaum said. ``Defendants discover that their
wartime misdeeds are going to be documented in court to the
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
