<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALEDICTORIAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL GRAD AN INSPIRATION TO TULALIP TRIBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Most valedictorians can point to a handful of proud
relatives. Nicole Sieminski has around 3,400.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicole graduated from Marysville-Pilchuck High School in
Snohomish County on Thursday night, she drew accolades not only for
what she's done but for who she is: the first valedictorian from
the Tulalip Tribes.
</P>
<P>
   For Tulalip leaders, who have made a top priority of improving
poor graduation rates, Nicole's achievement was a cause for
celebration and an event they hope will inspire younger students
throughout the reservation near Marysville.
</P>
<P>
   The news was ``being bragged all around the tribes,'' said
Tribal Council Chairman Herman Williams Jr., with requests for
extra graduation tickets flooding the tribal office earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole was awarded a Pendleton blanket, a prized recognition for
tribal members of any age, particularly for one so young.
</P>
<P>
   Williams _ a former Marysville High student who regrets getting
an equivalency diploma rather than graduating _ said the gift of a
blanket will be a tradition for the future valedictorians he knows
the Tulalips will produce.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a day for celebration even without Nicole's
success.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two other Tulalip students are graduating, including 13
from the Tulalip Learning Center Alternative High School. This
represents roughly double the learning center's rate in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Tulalips have distributed a color poster with the names,
pictures and family heritage of each graduate, and they have bought
30-second TV commercials in Seattle and Bellingham with tribal
elder Raymond Moses reading the graduates' names.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a special day, a special night for all
Tulalip tribal members,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole, who graduated with a perfect 4.0 grade-point average,
had her pick of Ivy League schools, turning down Harvard and MIT in
favor of pre-med studies at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Verna James, the high school's liaison for Native American
students and mother of another 1999 graduate, called Nicole's
achievements inspirational.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to set our (goals) high and encourage kids to reach
them _ because it is possible,'' James said. ``We need to do
everything we can as adult people to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   A delighted James took Nicole to meet with tribal elders after
the school announced the names of the 560-student senior class's
co-valedictorians (senior Sabrina Habib shared the honor with
Nicole).
</P>
<P>
   ``We had her grandpa come with her, and her mom and dad and
aunts, to explain her family, and what branches she comes from, and
let them know the honor she was carrying,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   For Nicole, a math and science whiz who's taken college courses
the past few summers, the Tulalips' reaction has been a surprising
honor. A model student from elementary school onward, she's also
juggled participation in three sports and four school bands in
which she plays alto saxophone and vibraphone.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole set the goal of valedictorian in her freshman year and
said she did it for herself rather than to set an example for
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks it's so hard, but I haven't found it that hard
... if you just do your work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole said she's wanted to be a doctor as long as she can
remember, and she plans to return to the reservation after becoming
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need good doctors out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of commitment, the hope that tribal members will use
their education to benefit their people, is one of the reasons for
the financial and institutional support that the Tulalips provide
for students of all ages, partly fueled by the economic success of
their casino.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Tulalips pay tuition, books and a small living
stipend for the roughly 100 students a year who pursue higher
education, said John McCoy, the tribe's governmental affairs
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The Tulalips also pay for tutoring, night school, summer school
and other intervention programs as early as kindergarten, leaders
said.
</P>
<P>
   They've printed the ``Native American Graduating Class'' poster
for about 10 years _ it includes Marysville graduates from other
tribes as well as their own _ and hold an annual banquet honoring
the Tulalip graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Less visible but perhaps more significant, each school that
Tulalip children attend has a liaison to help Native American
students, from mentoring to addressing cultural clashes to alerting
parents of attendance problems.
</P>
<P>
   The graduation rate for tribal members has doubled from 25
percent to about 50 percent in five years, according to James.
</P>
<P>
   She attributes the improvement to the tribal support and to such
alternative programs as the Tulalip Learning Center, the
alternative high school that serves the area.
</P>
<P>
   School and tribal leaders said the alternative high school
provides flexibility and extra support for students who once would
have dropped out, overwhelmed by the size and strange faces of
Marysville's secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could work at your own pace (at the Tulalip Learning
Center),'' said Tashina Simpson, who graduated from the school last
night. ``The teachers are very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Tashina, who plans to attend Everett Community College, sought
out the alternative school after finding Marysville Junior High
crowded and alienating when she began eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   She was determined to graduate from high school even after she
had a baby 18 months ago, returning to class a week after her son
was born. Tashina said she hoped her diploma would prove something
to those who told her she would never be a success, that it would
show outsiders that ``native people can make it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor in her achievement, she said, was school liaison
Shonta Retasket-Truong, who helped with child care while she did
schoolwork, and often drove to Everett when Tashina moved there
three months ago and offered her rides to school. It made
attendance far easier than it had been when she took her son with
her on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Retasket-Truong, herself a graduate of the Learning Center, said
she's proud of all the students, but especially the handful of
young mothers who stuck with their schoolwork while meeting the
demands of caring for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Each student, Retasket-Truong said, overcame personal struggles
to become the newly minted graduates they are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all did a good job,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
