<SLUG> BC-TAGTEAM-FAMILIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONSTANDARD WORK SCHEDULES TAKING TOLL ON MARRIAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dan Fox begged off the swing shift at Rocketdyne
when his kids got in school so he could be around to help with
homework, soccer and Little League.
</P>
<P>
   When the Quartz Hill resident returned to the 1 p.m. to midnight
shift this year, his wife, Lynne, was a little more receptive than
when the kids were young.
</P>
<P>
   ``All else being equal, she'd probably prefer I'd still be
working days,'' said Fox, 52.
</P>
<P>
   More Americans than ever are working nights and weekends, and
the resulting conflicts are straining many relationships to the
breaking point, according to a study published in Science magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of separation or divorce are six times higher for
fathers who work at night, compared to those who work during the
day. The odds are three times higher than normal when the mothers
work nights, said the study by University of Maryland sociologist
Harriet B. Presser.
</P>
<P>
   The study found fewer than 30 percent of Americans work a
``standard'' schedule _ 35-40 hours a week, daytime hours, Monday
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great deal more diversity in the labor force than
people realize,'' said Presser, who derived her findings from a
1997 Labor Department study of 48,000 U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   She found only 42 percent of working couples with children have
fixed weekday, daytime schedules. Parents who work opposing shifts
often see it as a benefit, so they can split child care during the
course of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Such an arrangement might seem convenient but can be
``enormously difficult and stressful to balance,'' said Susan D.
Einbinder, assistant professor of social work at the University of
Southern California. ``Having a relationship in general is
difficult. And when you throw in a child, that multiplies the
stress exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Working night shifts can mess with the body's rhythms and cause
sleep and health disturbances and threaten family relationships,
Presser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people living their lives that way. It's an
unresearched area, and it's an area policy-makers have not
addressed,'' Presser said.
</P>
<P>
   Einbinder added: ``We do very, very little for parents.
Government views kids as the property of the parents who had them,
but we all benefit if today's kids grow up into healthy,
well-adjusted adults. How well kids grow up is a joint venture
between parents and society.''
</P>
<P>
   Single mothers also are more likely than married ones to work
long hours and nonstandard schedules, Presser said. Yet
policy-makers have been slow to recognize the shift in work
patterns and the need for off-hour child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, it would be heaven if they had really good day
care at night,'' said Sarah Straw, 21, of Canoga Park, a single
mother of a 2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   She works at the Saddle Peak Lodge restaurant in Calabasas as a
hostess until at least 10 p.m. Thursday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard. You have to find a sitter,'' she said.
``It's hard to find someone you trust who can come into your
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Presser said the shift toward night and weekend work comes from
a push toward a 24-hour global economy, dual-income couples
demanding after-hours entertainment and other services, and a boom
in service jobs. Those jobs _ in restaurants, malls, video stores,
etc. _ often involve nonstandard work hours.
</P>
<P>
   For Fox, now a swing shift manager at Rocketdyne Propulsion &AMP;
Power, working days meant a lot 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was about the time my children were hitting Little League
age,'' he said. ``I felt real strongly about being involved with my
kids and schools and sports.''
</P>
<P>
   But he realizes not everyone is lucky enough to adjust their
schedules to family needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so large, we have the flexibility to do a little
rotation'' of schedules, he said. ``But I'm sure a lot of small
businesses don't have that luxury. I've been real blessed, where
it's worked out real well.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
