<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-GAMER-TEX     06-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-GAMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS ROAR BACK TO EVEN SERIES ON HULL'S GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Statistically speaking, you could spin this one almost
any way you wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no statistic that could measure what the Stars put
on the ice last night in the third period: desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled hard, and we deserved to win,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said proudly after the Stars scored three third-period
goals to take a 4-2 victory against the Buffalo Sabres in Game 2 of
the Stanley Cup Finals. ``We were a little desperate out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull scored his first game-winning goal of the playoffs
with 2:50 remaining to allow the Stars to tie the best-of-seven
series at one game apiece. The Hull goal broke a series of
statistical trends, including the one that had the Stars 1-5 in
games in which Hull had scored playoff goals. The game also saw the
Sabres drop to 10-2 in playoff games in which they score first. But
maybe the most important statistic is the one that says teams that
win Game 2 of the Stanley Cup Finals have gone on to win 27 of the
past 31 series.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds a lot better to Stars fans than the statistic that
said teams that win Game 1 take the series 80 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now, it's time to throw the statistics out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a helluva series,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I
see every game coming down to the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   While Hull's goal, an empty-netter by Derian Hatcher and Craig
Ludwig's seeing-eye shot that was his first playoff goal since 1988
were ecstatic moments for the roaring crowd of 17,001 at Reunion
Arena, the Stars didn't escape without some scars. Stars center and
leading scorer Mike Modano hurt his left wrist on a third-period
hit by Jay McKee of the Sabres. Modano did not return to the game
and is ``probable'' for Game 3 tomorrow in Buffalo, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   If Modano can't go, expect Hitchcock to move Tony Hrkac to the
first line. Hrkac was exceptional in his first game back in the
lineup after missing more than a month with cracked ribs. He took
Modano's place after the injury and assisted Hull on the
game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Chambers won a puck battle to rim the puck around, and
Hrkac found Hull at the top of the right circle as the arena was
getting more and more intense in expectations of a second overtime
game. Hull unleashed his vicious one-timer _ the hardest shot the
Stars have on their team _ and the puck whistled past Hasek's
blocker, off the right post and into the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that from Hullie,'' Nieuwendyk said of the man who
was signed as the Stars' hired gun in the off-season. ``We need him
in situations like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull's shot was the culmination of a wild third period in which
the Stars bowed their necks and made a series of the Finals. After
running into a spider web of team defense and coming up with just
12 shots in the first two periods, the Stars unloaded 19 shots in
the third period and swarmed the Sabres' All-World goalie Dominik
Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig gave the Stars their first lead of the game at the 4:25
mark as he whistled a puck through a crowd after Brian Skrudland
won a faceoff to the right of the goal. It broke a 102-game playoff
goal drought for Ludwig dating back to March 9, 1988 _ the longest
in Stanley Cup playoffs history. It was also just the fourth goal
of his 172-game playoff career.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lead was short-lived as Buffalo stormed back to tie
the game on an Alexei Zhitnik power-play goal just 1:09 later.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when the Stars showed their desire. They outbattled
the Sabres for just about every loose puck and forced officials to
hand over a few power-play chances. Spurred by great opportunities,
particularly three big shots by Hull on a 5-on-3, the Stars finally
took momentum from their power play instead of losing it.
</P>
<P>
   That led to more aggression and more puck hunting, and it paid
off in Hull's game-winner. The Stars then had to kill a final
penalty to Hatcher at the 17:31 mark and capped off the victory
with a Hatcher empty-net goal.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, the Stars threw out a stunning 48 hits to the
Sabres' 38. But then again, we weren't going to talk statistics.
What the Stars did was go after Hasek and maul him for much of the
game. They never gave up against a fierce Sabres defense, and they
sent a message that they're not out of this quite yet. In short,
they reclaimed their desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we learned to hate Buffalo,'' Ludwig said. ``Because
we obviously didn't take them as seriously as we should have.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
