<SLUG> BC-BKL-STING-MYSTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMIQUE MYSTIQUE OVERCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yes, the New York Yankees were at the White House
Thursday to be honored by President Clinton. But this town had much
more on its mind; namely the arrival of No. 1 draft pick Chamique
Holdsclaw to the Mystics as the team made its season debut against
the Charlotte Sting.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras followed her out of the locker room and microphones
caught her every word, but ultimately she, the fans, and the media
knew that the only thing that mattered was how she delivered on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her 18 points, including two 3-pointers, everyone
came to realize that one player does not make a team. The Sting
handed the Mystics an 83-73 loss at the MCI Center. And aside from
the the star quality that Holdsclaw brought, the sellout crowd of
20,674 left the arena feeling like they did most of last year, when
the team had the worst record in the league (3-27).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I played a good game, but we didn't do enough as a
team to win tonight,'' Holdsclaw said.
</P>
<P>
   And the player who led her high school team to four
championships and Tennessee to three NCAA titles, acknowledged that
the feeling of defeat is not one she's familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when the last time she lost the first game of the season,
Holdsclaw just laughed and said, ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   When Holdsclaw scored the team's first field goal with a jumper
just over 2 minutes into the game, the crowd went crazy _ this is
what they had come to see. But it was another Tennessee grad, Nikki
McCray, who would light up the first half for the Mystics, as the
5-foot-11-inch guard drove for the next two baskets.
</P>
<P>
   She finished the half with 13 points and four rebounds, as the
Mystics took a 36-34 lead at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be their biggest lead of the game, as the Sting
kept up the pressure and pulled away to a 14-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team had spurts, and Chamique had spurts as well,'' said
Mystics coach Nancy Darsch. ``But Charlotte is the best team in the
East, I'm convinced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sting's zone defense befuddled the Mystics, and led
Washington to commit 15 turnovers. Not to mention the play of
new-kid-in-the league Dawn Staley, who scored a game-high 23
points, including three 3-pointers. Staley, a 5-6 guard who was on
the '96 Olympic gold-medal team, had played in the ABL for the past
two years, and was drafted by the Sting when the league folded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawn Staley is not one of the best point guards in the world
for no reason,'' Darsch said. ``She really ran that team and made
the plays in the second half when we were trying to make a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the offense was Sting guard Stephanie McCarty, from
NCAA champion Purdue, who scored all of her 11 points in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   After tying the score, 63-63, with less than 10 minutes to go,
the Sting went on an 18-4 run, and the Mystics could never recover.
</P>
<P>
   McCray led the Mystics with 22 points, followed by forward
Muriel Page (14), and forward Shalonda Enis (11).
</P>
<P>
   And even though Holdsclaw's team didn't win, she gave the fans a
taste of what they had seen during her four years at Tennessee _
her pull-up jumpers, her 3-pointers, and her drives to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, she said she was just as disappointed as the
fans were. ``I guess I'm a sore loser,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I like
to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
