<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADUATION-SPEAKER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL SPEAKER TESTS THE PRINCIPLES OF SCHOOL PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ During a two-decade career in higher education,
Jane Jervis learned well the principles of academic freedom,
including the freedoms of speech, thought and expression.
</P>
<P>
   But never have those principles been tested as fiercely as they
have over the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jervis, president of The Evergreen State College, is at the
center of a controversy over the school's decision to hear remarks
at Friday's graduation ceremonies from a convicted cop killer.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of the slain officer, police from across the nation,
even the attorney general of Pennsylvania have urged Jervis to
rescind the decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Jervis says she will allow the taped remarks of Mumia Abu
Jamal, who is awaiting execution in Pennsylvania, to be heard by
about 800 graduates, their family and friends during commencement
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal, convicted of killing Philadelphia police Officer Daniel
Faulkner in 1981, was chosen by students to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``They chose to include Mumia, not because he's the killer of a
police officer, ... but because he has created an international
conversation about the whole issue of poverty, the
(disproportionate) numbers of blacks in prison and the death
penalty,'' she said. ``The educational principle here is for
students to be confronted by the dissidence of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a graduation ceremony that highlights the real
issues in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   While Evergreen has never shied from controversy, the selection
of Abu Jamal as a commencement speaker has brought controversy to a
new level. Faulkner's widow, Maureen, will attend the ceremony,
with police officers and other supporters from across the state
joining her protest.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner's supporters are asking students who object to Jamal to
stage a silent protest, such as standing and turning their backs
when Jamal's remarks are played, or wearing blue ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., GOP Rep. Tom DeLay from Texas, the House
majority whip, will ask the House to observe a moment of silence to
protest Evergreen's decision to hear from Jamal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a symbol of cowardliness, lies, deceit and outright
murder,'' said Suzie Sawyer, executive director of Concerns of
Police Survivors, which represents families of slain officers. ``He
has never shown one bit of remorse. He absolutely has no respect
for any system of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamal, a Black Panther turned writer, journalist and activist,
claims he was framed by police and railroaded by a racist criminal
justice system. He has become a cause celebre among death penalty
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   His conviction _ by a mixed jury _ has been upheld by appeals
courts. His case in now before the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal's selection by Evergreen students has been controversial
from the beginning. Washington state troopers reacted angrily, and
their pressure led Gov. Gary Locke in April to withdraw as the
commencement's keynote speaker.
</P>
<P>
   On the Evergreen campus, his selection has sparked debate. On a
Web site set up by the college to air the issue, more than 150
students made their opinions known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry an officer lost his life,'' wrote one, ``but his
death has nothing to do with, nor is an intellectually defensible
argument against, their presentation of anyone's views about the
inherent and provable racism of our criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Another wrote, ``You ... insult not only the murder victim's
family and friends, but also the many honest and humane law
enforcement officers in this country who undertake impossible,
no-win task of protecting us.''
</P>
<P>
   Students involved in the efforts and decision to hear from Jamal
defended their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Koslen, 23, a member of the graduation committee that
selected Jamal, pointed to Evergreen's governing document, which
states: ``An essential condition for learning is the freedom and
right on the part of an individual or group to express minority,
unpopular or controversial points of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Jervis, a Radcliffe- and Yale-trained scholar, said Thursday she
has tried to meet that standard in defending the choice of Jamal.
At Evergreen, where she been president since 1992, every spring
seems to bring a contentious issue and new controversy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jervis said she's had doubts at times, but said principle
dictated her position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this is the right and decent thing to do,'' she said.
``I believe this is the right thing to do, and that belief is
important to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
