A1267 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-11 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' MONEY TALKS AS HULL SHOWS WHY HE WAS SIGNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He lurks. He scores.
</P>
<P>
   It is what Brett Hull does and, no matter what the head coach
says, what he was brought here to do.
</P>
<P>
   And so, money talked last night. It talked so loud, there are
17,001 cases of earache to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   In time, it might be easier to put a price tag on the
game-deciding goal that Hull scored last night. For now, it looms
as every bit worthy of the $17.5 million that owner Tom Hicks spent
to get him.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Stars lost this Game 2 of the Stanley Cup Finals, a Lake
Erie-sized hole would have awaited them in Buffalo. With the
Sabres' mitts firmly clutched around the Stars' necks, thanks to
the power play, the possibility of another stunning home loss
clearly existed.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull lurked _ as he has quietly done for all of his career _
and, with less than three minutes to play, Hull scored.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fable that yet exists, propagated this week by the
invading Northern media, that the reason the Stars fizzled in the
Western Conference finals last season was the mental unraveling of
goaltender Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the scoring, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the power play and the paucity of scoring depth
once center Joe Nieuwendyk was injured were far better reasons for
the Stars' demise. Oh, the Detroit Red Wings also had much to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of that defeat, the Stars needed a goal scorer _
not a straitjacket or a shrink for Belfour. Hicks, who has a thing
for fireworks, signed Hull on the day before the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   At last, a distinct difference in this final series. The Sabres
and Stars have been touted as cousins, reared from the same
defense-first trough.
</P>
<P>
   But let's talk money. While Buffalo was slashing payroll and
making the talented Michael Peca dance naked for his new contract,
the Stars were shamelessly adding a guy who had scored 554 career
goals.
</P>
<P>
   And they will every time. The difference is as broad as, well,
Dallas and Buffalo. Ferraris (leased, of course) and factories.
Chrome skyscrapers and chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks was able to issue the ``sign'' order for Hull in a deal
that could eventually cost $24 million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Last night he got to watch the Cadillac drive off the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Goals like this are why the Stars signed Hull. Nobody in the
Stars' locker room, despite that defensive mantra they chant, can
argue that point now.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the Stars' Nieuwendyk said of the game-winner, ``We
expect that from Hullie. He's a great shooter, a goal scorer. We
certainly need him in situations like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the playoffs started, you could replant a small forest
with the newsprint that has been wasted chronicling the ``new''
Brett Hull. The allegedly forechecking Hull. The
maintain-my-proper-positioning Hull. The ``team guy'' Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, puh-leese. A scorer has to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   He does not weave gentle figure eights through the ice, as a
Mike Modano will do. He doesn't jet from goal line to blue line the
way he once did.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he has always been the cocked pistol at the poker table.
Just floating. Waiting.
</P>
<P>
   When Tony Hrkac got him the puck high in the slot late in the
third period last night, Hull knew what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you give Brett a good luck from that range, he's going
to take advantage,'' teammate Craig Ludwig said. ``He's something
special to watch in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the game-winning goal, joining Hull on the ice were Ludwig,
Hrkac, Shawn Chambers and Jere Lehtinen. With Modano injured and
back in the dressing room, the Stars still were able to juggle to
find the right scoring combination.
</P>
<P>
   In time, it will be depth that decides this best-of-seven
series. The deep-pocketed Stars should have the edge in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither team is going to go away easily,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   No one would argue that _ not after the two tense nights at
Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the Cadillacs that lead the Stanley Cup parade, we were
reminded last night.
</P>
<P>
   They are expensive. But _ just ask the owner _ worth every
penny.  &LR; tagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lebreton &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
