<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MIRACLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES CAN'T PRODUCE MIRACLE VS. COMETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ No, it wasn't the storybook reunion of anyone's
imagination, and it wasn't the fairytale ending of anyone's dreams.
But the WNBA season is just beginning, so who knows what lies
around the next well-manicured corner? This is, after all, the city
of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it would have taken a miracle for the Orlando Miracle to
win Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, going up against the two-time WNBA champion
Houston Comets. There was none, unless you count Orlando pulling
within 4 points, 49-45, early in the second half, as Houston
triumphed, 77-63, in front of 15,422 nonetheless rocking fans in
Orlando Arena, thrilled to finally have women's professional
basketball in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   And no, none of the University of Connecticut alumni making
their WNBA debuts were the stars of the game, although from the way
things shaped up Thursday night, Nykesha Sales is going to get
plenty of opportunity to be just that for the fledgling Miracle,
while New England Blizzard expatriates Kara Wolters and Jennifer
Rizzotti are likely to be relegated to supporting roles as rookie
draftees on the talent-ridden Comets. Neither saw action Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really a role I've ever been in before,''
acknowledged an upbeat Rizzotti after the game. ``I'll do what I
can to help the team, and if that means playing hard in practice to
help the starting team, that's what I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales, meanwhile, started at shooting guard for the Miracle and
played 33 minutes, scoring 13 points and grabbing six rebounds.
Although acknowledging first-half jitters (``There was a lot of
hype about this game,'' she said. ``I'm pretty glad it's done'')
that induced her to go a dismal 3 for 15 from the floor as she
tried to do too much, she settled down in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Carolyn Peck, making her own WNBA debut after leading
Purdue to the NCAA title last season, isn't worried. ``There are
nights when your shot just doesn't fall,'' she said of Sales's
performance. ``I'm not going to handcuff her. She's always got the
green light.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales, the 6-foot, 160-pound guard/forward who is UConn's
all-time leading scorer, was the first player assigned to the
Miracle, Sept. 15, 1998. Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, she grabbed the first
defensive rebound in franchise history, and scored the first points
of her professional career when she hit a soaring 3-pointer with
12:27 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Taj McWilliams, most recently of the ABL's Philadelphia Rage,
will go down in history as the first Miracle scorer, however,
thanks to her 3-pointer 2:04 into the game. Unfortunately for
Orlando, they were the only points amid a 9-3 run by Houston to
open the game, with Comets forward Tina Thompson showing why she
was an All-WNBA first-teamer last season when she scored 7 of those
9. She would end a searing first half with 17 points, shooting 7
for 11 from the floor, and trailed only Cynthia Cooper's game-high
24 points with 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets led by as much as 18 in the first half, before
Orlando went on a late 14-6 run to cut it to 43-35 at the half.
With two-time league MVP Cooper hobbling on an ankle sprained
Wednesday in practice, the Miracle might have been hoping for just
that. But what to say about the mythic Cooper, who played every
minute of the second half and took over the game every time Orlando
started nibbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have known Cooper was going to make plays,'' said
Houston coach Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sales, long known for her electric play at UConn, she
took the loss and her role in it as a learning experience. ``I need
to slow down a little bit, let the game come to me,'' she assessed
afterward. After all, ``I'm a rookie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
