<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS &LR;      06-11 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL GOAL TOPPLES SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When the Stars went out and signed Brett Hull as a free
agent last July, their fervent hope was that paying Hull would pay
off in the form of a Stanley Cup for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, Hull showed exactly why they gave him a
three-year, $17.5 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hull drilled a near-perfect shot past Buffalo goalie Dominik
Hasek, beating him with a one-timer from the right circle with 2:50
left to lift the Stars to a 4-2 victory over the Sabres in Game 2
of the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought (Hull) got stronger as the game went on,'' said
Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock. ``I thought our veteran players played
with a lot of passion tonight and never quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The series is tied at one game apiece and switches back to
Buffalo for Games 3 and 4, beginning Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Craig Ludwig had given the Stars a 2-1 lead at 4:25
of the third period when Brian Skrudland beat Buffalo's Wayne
Primeau in the left faceoff circle. The puck went back to Ludwig
and he fired a shot that was deflected through Hasek's pads. It was
the 38-year-old Ludwig's first playoff goal since he scored for
Montreal in a game against Hartford back in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got one for the '90s,'' quipped Hitchcock. ``That's it.
He's done.''
</P>
<P>
   That lead only lasted 1:11, though, because the Sabres tied it
on their second power-play goal of the game. After Curtis Brown
fired a shot from the slot that goalie Ed Belfour saved, defenseman
Alexei Zhitnik blasted the rebound from the left circle past
Belfour's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres were able to stave off a 43-second five-on-three
disadvantage, but they couldn't prevent the surging Stars from
taking the game.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Derian Hatcher added an empty-netter with 25.8
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   As close and as intense as Game 1 ended, that's just how Game 2
began.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek faced some pressure of a different kind in that period.
Hitchcock vowed his team would put more heat on the netminder but
not to the point of running him. However, at 12:25, Skrudland ran
over Hasek in the left corner and received a charging penalty.
Players on the Buffalo bench stood and pointed to the other end at
Belfour, letting him know his turn was coming.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the period, all kinds of contact broke out,
starting with Mike Modano clipping Hasek, and then Hasek was jawing
with Jamie Langenbrunner. That caused Dallas's Joe Nieuwendyk and
Buffalo's Brian Holzinger to drop the gloves. Buffalo defenseman
Richard Smehlik then wrestled with Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   At the 20-minute mark, six players were assessed penalties,
three from each side, with Holzinger and Nieuwendyk getting five
minutes each for fighting while Modano got a tripping penalty,
Hatcher and Smehlik got roughing penalties, and Zhitnik earned two
minutes for cross-checking.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres came out strong in the second, taking a 1-0 lead on
the power play at 7:27. Defenseman Jason Woolley, who was the hero
in Game 1 when he scored at 15:30 of overtime, was positioned at
the right point. Michael Peca, who was left alone, skated from
right to left around the net and when he got near the left post, he
lifted his stick in the air and called for the puck. Woolley saw
the Buffalo captain and made a perfect pass, and Peca chipped the
puck past Belfour. At that point, the Sabres were outshooting
Dallas, 7-0. But that would change in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars then turned on the jets and started putting all kinds
of heat on Buffalo. Nieuwendyk had a shot from in tight that Hasek
had to handle. Later, it was Sergei Zubov who sailed a shot from
the right point that Hasek saved. The goalie could do nothing about
the Dallas goal at 18:26. Defenseman Richard Matvichuk teed up a
slapper from the left point that Langenbrunner redirected high into
the net to tie the game, 1-1, setting up a wild third period in
which the Stars outshot the Sabres, 19-4, and in which Hull was the
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you give Brett a good look from that range, he's going
to take advantage,'' said Ludwig. ``He's something special to watch
in that situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
