<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     06-11 1622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ As the long army convoy
roared out of Kosovo Thursday, beginning a defeated Serbia's
painful retreat from its historical heartland, a military policeman
in his black beret snapped a salute to each passing vehicle, tears
streaming down his face. Small knots of Serbs gathered quietly on
Podujevo's streetcorners in the wearying sun as the long column
moved past. Soldiers rode in military trucks and civilian busses,
and in passenger cars of every kind. Trucks full of stretchers
moved past, then portable kitchens and armored personnel carriers.
The Serbs stood shocked, pale and still, as if their blood was
draining into the gutter. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUTURE (Cologne, Germany) _ As the Clinton administration
turns toward the task of reviving life in Kosovo and what will
essentially be an international protectorate, officials envision an
entity that in theory remains a sovereign part of Yugoslavia but in
reality will be self-governing, and in the long run, probably
independent. Now that the war is over, the problem of the political
and economic status of Kosovo, a pocket of territory about the size
of Connecticut but now in ruins, will move to the forefront. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-PALESTINIANS (Sidon, Lebanon) _ No one yet knows exactly
who fired Kalashnikov rifles into a courtroom here two days ago in
a massacre that killed the chief judge and three other court
officials. But the attack has focused attention on a problem that
Lebanon has long done its best to ignore. A large and angry
population of Palestinian refugees now numbers more than 300,000,
most living in camps _ like Ain Hilwe, just outside Sidon _ that
are ruled by armed militias. It was to Ain Hilwe that the gunmen
are believed to have fled. But like all the camps, Ain Hilwe is a
place where the Lebanese police and soldiers do not dare to go. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MINISTERS (Sacramento) _ When leaders of the United
Methodist Church's Northern California and Nevada region meet here
in mid-June, they will begin grappling with the unusual decision of
whether to charge 68 ministers with violating church law for having
jointly blessed a same-sex union last January. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
