<P>
   SOC-HAMM-PROFILE (Undated) _ Mia Hamm is considered the world's
best female soccer player, a woman born in 1972, the year of Title
IX, the federal law aimed at prohibiting discrimination against
athletes on the basis of gender. And now, at 27, Hamm represents
for many the full realization of sports opportunity for women. At
15, she became the youngest player ever to join the national soccer
team, and in winning a world championship and an Olympic gold medal
in recent years, she has scored 109 career goals, more than any
other man or woman ever to play the game. She has, as well, reached
an uncommon level of celebrity and corporate appeal. By Jere
Longman.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the Knicks, who,
to everyone's surprise, now lead the Eastern Conference finals by 3
games to 2 and can vault right into the finals by beating the
Pacers at the Garden on Friday night. If these 12 characters in
search of an identity should get past Indiana, they would be New
York's most surprising finalists since the Jets won Super Bowl III
and before that the 1951 New York Giants. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-CAMBY (Undated) _ Feature on Marcus Camby, the tall, skinny
Knicks forward who started the season on the bench but has exploded
in the playoffs and has clearly become the one player that the
Pacers can't seem to cope with. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS (Undated) _ A look at coach Jeff Van Gundy's
situation _ despite all the rumors about his possible departure, a
victory on Friday puts him in the driver's seat for next season. By
Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-PACERS (Undated) _ An analytical look at the Pacers. All
told, they look like the Knicks of old: slow, plodding, lethargic.
By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ When the Mets traded for Bobby Bonilla
in the off-season a lot of people scratched their heads. He was
starting to get old, he had spent much of 1998 injured and it was
very unclear whether he could still cover enough ground to play in
the outfield. Now he has quickly become a big distraction in the
clubhouse and the Mets may now be forced to cut him and then pay
him all the money they still owe him. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES (undated) _ The Yankees are not the team they were a
year ago, although they are back in first place. With the trading
deadline six weeks away, a look at who the Yankees have in the
minor leagues and which of those players might form an attractive
package that would bring the Yankees some help in return. By Buster
Olney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CASSETT-EXHIBIT (Washington) _ ``Women should be someone and not
something,'' the American artist Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) once
wrote, emphatically underlining her words. And she dedicated a long
career to fleshing out this conviction through art. Her efforts
come across with a quiet, though sometimes surprisingly passionate
force in ``Mary Cassatt: Modern Woman,'' a succinct survey of her
paintings and prints at the National Gallery of Art in Washington.
The show, which has appeared in Chicago and Boston, is the first
comprehensive look at Cassatt's work in nearly 30 years. And it
marks yet another step in evaluating an artist who was herself a
someone _ indeed, several someones _ to be reckoned with. By
Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   PLANET-EARTH (New York) _ Over more than a century, scientists
and explorers from the American Museum of Natural History have
searched the world and returned with arresting examples of life in
all its diversity: dinosaurs from Montana to Mongolia, birds and
butterflies, artifacts of exotic cultures from here to the South
Sea. For the last four years, their quest has been to collect the
stuff of Earth itself and bring it back for a new exhibition
illustrating the planet's 4.5 billion-year history. Now the
collections have been studied, winnowed and arranged for display in
the museum's newest permanent exhibit, the Gottesman Hall of Planet
Earth, which opens Saturday. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT13,14) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TANGO-MANIA (New York) _ The Argentine tango is not unlike
chess. It is serious; it takes discipline; it must be studied hard
to be done well. It is elegant and formal, passionate and intimate.
It is about power and vulnerability. It is both a dance and a
metaphor. And to its captives, it can become a magnificent
obsession. By Janny Scott.
</P>
