<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-JOURNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STANLEY CUP POISED FOR A NEW SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich)  (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The essential goodness in hockey comes out on these soft summer
evenings during the Stanley Cup finals. The players dream of more
than money or personal glory or just plain winning. They dream of
taking the cup back home.
</P>
<P>
   New families, new friends will be sharing the Stanley Cup this
summer, with either the Buffalo Sabres or the Dallas Stars taking
home North America's greatest sports trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars tied the series at one game each Thursday night with a
4-2 victory over the Sabres in Dallas, delighting the NHL, which is
rooting for a long and tangled series rather than the yawning
sweeps of the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The league has a few problems, hemmed in by Knicks madness as
well as the continuing absence of Chicago, Los Angeles and New York
television markets, and stuck with bankrupt ownership in Pittsburgh
and callous ownership on Long Island. But in these post-Gretzky
days, the league still has the Stanley Cup, its great and
longstanding star.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer passion, consider the way the players love the Stanley
Cup. Like figures in some medieval morality play, they practically
shield their eyes from the cup until it is theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Woolley of the Sabres came close in 1996, when he played
for Florida but was swept by Colorado. The players went through
hockey's gracious ritual of the handshake line, and then Woolley
forced himself to watch the Avalanche players hoisting the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to be on the other end,'' Woolley recalled
Thursday. ``I think I watched for half a second and then I couldn't
stand it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of players will not even touch the cup until
they win it. When Shawn Chambers helped win the cup with the Devils
in 1995, he took it home with him to Sterling Heights, Mich. He
wanted his childhood friend, Derian Hatcher of the Stars, to drink
from the cup, but Hatcher declined, not out of superstition but out
of respect. Now they are teammates on Dallas, dreaming of drinking
together from it.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the cup to go home for the summer is one of the great
traditions of sport. Joe Juneau of the Sabres grew up in Quebec,
watching on the CBC as the Canadiens hoisted one of their four
straight cups at the end of the 1970s. Last June he played for
Washington and lost in four straight to the Red Wings, and now he
has another chance to take the cup to Pont-Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about how you got here,'' Juneau said Thursday.
``You think about your parents, you think about your grandparents,
how they laced up your skates for you, how they drove you to
practices. All kinds of people have made sacrifices, so you can get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in hockey knows the story of the old Canadiens'
temporarily leaving the cup by the side of the road. Everybody
knows about Clark Gillies letting his dog eat from the cup. (``He's
a nice dog,'' Gillies explained.)
</P>
<P>
   Woolley, who scored the overtime goal in the first game, was
dreaming out loud yesterday about taking the Stanley Cup to
Camborne Avenue in North York, Ontario, ``where my parents have
lived since Day 1.''
</P>
<P>
   He will set the cup on the curb, where he used to play street
hockey (``in running shoes'') with his pals down the block, Gino
and Paul Cavallini, both of whom would have long careers in the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best street-hockey team in history,'' Woolley said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cup no longer travels unattended, because the Hockey Hall of
Fame in Toronto sends out bodyguards to carry the cup to the great
cities and obscure hamlets that produce Stanley Cup players, now
expanded from Canada into the United States, Sweden, Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Oke, one of the chaperones, makes no predictions about who
will win this cup, but he looks at Jere Lehtinen of Dallas and
thinks, ``I've never been to Finland'' _ and neither has the cup.
He looks at Geoff Sanderson of Buffalo and he thinks of Pine Point,
Northwest Territories, a portion of his own country that he has
never visited.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of last summer was Kelvington, Saskatchewan, a
town of 900 residents where 30,000 people showed up to greet Joey
Kocur, bringing home his third Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had hundreds of friends and neighbors sitting around the
campfire, in tents and trailers in his back yard, a real
festival,'' Oke recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Stanley Cup is on public display, first in the
Dallas Museum of Art the past few days, now in the Walden Galleria
in Buffalo. Soon the cup will be taking off on this summer's
magical mystery tour, with copious amounts of beverages being
consumed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great rules of hockey is: On the Stanley Cup, all
germs are healthy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
