<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BATSIDE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY MOVES DEBATE CLOSE TO HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Something's not right with Andrew Sanchez. He
can't maintain his concentration through a 30-minute TV show. When
he travels in a car _ he can't drive _ he gets headaches. Just
sitting through a three-hour baseball game saps his energy.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez is 23. On April 2 he was a college athlete, finishing
out his baseball career as a relief pitcher for Cal State
Northridge. What happened that afternoon at USC changed his life. A
batted ball struck Sanchez in the forehead. He lay on the field for
an hour before he was taken to L.A. County USC Medical Center by
ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez would later find out the impact of the ball fractured
his skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, that's probably the scariest thing I've ever
seen,'' said Kevin Patrick, who was playing second base for CSUN
and was close to Sanchez when he was struck. ``He dropped to the
ground. His head was already swollen and turning blue.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a split-second for the line drive off the metal bat of
USC's Dominic Correa to strike Sanchez. Correa, primarily a second
baseman for the Trojans, has been used by USC as a reliever this
season. He never met Sanchez before the incident and he hasn't seen
him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no control over it, but I still felt bad,'' Correa said
recently. ``It seemed that it happened in slow motion. I was pretty
shook up.''
</P>
<P>
   Correa said he's in favor of stricter aluminum-bat rules. But he
was quick to point out his line drive would have struck Sanchez
even if he was using a wooden bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have made a difference,'' he said. ``I think it
would have hit him the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Correa's statement would probably fall upon deaf ears in the
NCAA office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we have a sport that doesn't put a
student-athlete at risk,'' said Dennis Poppe, the NCAA director of
championships. ``You're never going to make (college baseball)
completely safe. It's a part of the game. You just want to minimize
that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford head coach Mark Marquess said he's only seen one
pitcher seriously hurt by a batted ball in 28 years of coaching. He
said safety should not be an issue in the aluminum-bat debate.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, who took a medical withdrawal from his classes in
April, is consulting with a lawyer over a possible lawsuit against
Louisville Slugger, which made the aluminum bat used by Correa. He
said he couldn't be interviewed for this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
