<HEADLINE>
STREET STOCKS ENJOY BULL MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ The screeching of the tires is louder than
the engines. The driving is less than stellar.
</P>
<P>
   The older American-made cars look like they've been in too many
fender-benders; they do not have the perfect paint jobs and some
parts look mismatched. But in the low-budget world of Street
Stocks, it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   No 100 mph speeds. No obtaining a sponsorship from some
multimillion dollar corporation. Perhaps, a sponsor from the small
store down the street.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator for the drivers of these everyday
jalopies is to race, have fun, learn a little and do it as cheaply
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a race fan, but I never had the finances to
get started,'' said Covina resident Luis Del Real, who will race on
Irwindale Speedway's third-of-a-mile oval on Saturday night. ``I
would always go to Saugus before it closed, and then went to the
Orange Show in San Bernardino to watch races. I always wanted to be
involved; I just had to save my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Real, who says his favorite driver is Dale Earnhardt -- his
1972 Chevrolet Nova is painted black with the number 3 on the side
-- finally saved the funds necessary to begin racing this year. He
is in second place in the point standings, 12 points behind Michael
Pope. Del Real and Pope are the only drivers to have competed in
every Street Stock race at Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked long hours to get ready for this year,'' Del Real,
39, said. ``Seven days a week, every weekend and after getting off
work, I was in the garage getting it ready. My wife says it is my
second wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Romo had the same obsession as Del Real. The Covina
resident said running hot laps at the Orange Show convinced him to
try racing. He purchased a 1972 Monte Carlo and put it together in
his garage, just down the street from Del Real. Romo said it cost
about $3,500 to get his car race-ready and, in his first outing
three weeks ago at Irwindale, he finished third in a five-car
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I always wanted to do,'' Romo, 37, said.
``ln that (first) race, it was real exhilarating and very exciting.
It was awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
