<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWLS AND BRUISES AS STARS EVEN STANLEY CUP FINALS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stanley Cup finals surged into high gear Thursday
night with a dramatic Dallas victory amid a series of serious
developments. The Stars beat Buffalo by 4-2, the winning goal a
slap shot by Brett Hull past Dominik Hasek with 2 minutes and 50
seconds remaining to break a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Their victory evened the best-of-7-game series at one victory
apiece and guaranteed that the championship round would last more
than four games for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The evening featured a brief multiplayer fight that included two
major penalties, rare for post-season games in recent seasons. The
minibrawl broke out after several Dallas players spent the first
period colliding with Hasek. Although Hasek did not seem rattled by
the tactics, he gave up three goals, with the fourth going into an
empty net in the final minute after he was pulled for an extra
attacker during a Sabres power play.
</P>
<P>
   The player who fouled Hasek to trigger the brawl, Mike Modano,
was not in the game at the frantic finish, and his absence could be
the most significant event of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, a talented and high-scoring center, left the game in the
third period with what the Stars say was a wrist injury. He was
hurt after checked into the boards by Jay McKee, a Sabres
defenseman. Although the injury appeared to be higher up on his
body, possibly to his shoulder, Modano and his coach insisted that
it was a bruised and swollen left wrist and said Modano is probable
to play in Game 3 on Saturday night in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is traditional in the NHL for teams to be less than
candid during the playoffs when discussing injuries, particularly
to stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day to day,'' Modano said, when asked about the prognosis.
``It's pretty tender and sore.''
</P>
<P>
   No penalty was called on the play. Modano said he jammed his
elbow into the space between panes of glass above the boards.
Modano has 18 points in the playoffs, second on the team behind Joe
Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Modano's replacement, Tony Hrkac, set up the goal with a pass to
Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the goals everyone wants to get,'' said Hull, who
has two in this series and seven in the post-season. ``I just bury
the head and shoot it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars clinched it in the final minute when Derian Hatcher
came out of the penalty box to shoot the puck into the empty net.
It ended a rugged game of tight checking and tension, filled with
ties and lead changes.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock, the Dallas coach, said: ``For a low-scoring game,
it sure was exciting. Good win. We're back in the series. It's
going to be a hell of a series.''
</P>
<P>
   In the regular season, the Stars were 23 points better than
Buffalo, but the teams have appeared evenly matched. Dallas was the
first-seeded team in the West; Buffalo the seventh-seeded team in
the East. Michael Peca, the captain of the Sabres, said: ``We are
obviously disappointed with the outcome, but we are confident going
back to Buffalo with the split.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas took a 2-1 lead at 4:25 of the third period on a goal by
Craig Ludwig, a shot-blocking defenseman who rarely scores. After
Brian Skrudland of the Stars won a faceoff from Wayne Primeau, he
sent the puck back to Ludwig, who wristed a screened shot from high
in the left-wing circle that beat Hasek between the skates.
</P>
<P>
   But Buffalo soon tied it at 2-2 when Alexei Zhitnik intercepted
a clearing pass on a Sabres power play and whipped it past goalie
Ed Belfour on the glove side at 5:36.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Sabres took a 1-0 lead at 7:27 of the second period
on a power-play goal by Peca. Uncovered below the left-wing
face-off circle after coming from behind the net, Peca called for
the puck and got it from Jason Woolley. Peca's shot from a bad
angle got past Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the period, Dallas began to create more
scoring chances and the Stars forced the Sabres to take penalties.
They killed them off, but the Stars tied the score at even strength
at 18:29. Scoring it was Jamie Langenbrunner, who stood in front of
the crease and deflected a shot by Richard Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   The first period ended with a fight involving several players
that began when the Stars jostled Hasek for the second time.
Earlier, Skrudland was penalized for knocking over the Buffalo
goalie when they met in the corner in a chase for a loose puck at
12:25.
</P>
<P>
   At the buzzer, Modano's leg became entangled with Hasek's and
Hasek went down. As Modano was being penalized for tripping,
several players joined the fray, with the Dallas captain, Hatcher,
bloodying the face of Buffalo defenseman Richard Smehlik while
others paired off.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek and Belfour, the opposing goalies, stood near each other,
exchanging words, while the officials kept watch. The fighting
majors went to Brian Holzinger of Buffalo and Nieuwendyk. Smehlik
and Hatcher got roughing minors while Zhitnik was charged with
cross-checking.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
