r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SANDERS-COWBOYS-T     06-11 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS DECIDE TO OFFER EXTENSION TO SANDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Though a timetable for his return after ``rare''
toe surgery is uncertain, there is no longer any doubt about
cornerback Deion Sanders' future with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Thursday that he will ``take the
risk'' and work to sign the several-time All-Pro Sanders to a
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can tell me when he'll be back or when he'll be
healthy,'' Jones said. ``But it is my belief that Deion is going to
play this year. And if that's the case, I want to try to work
something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sanders nor his agent, Eugene Parker, was available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the team is negotiating with Parker. The Cowboys
probably will try to work out a multiyear deal that gives Sanders a
large signing bonus and a low base salary over the next few years
to clear salary-cap room.
</P>
<P>
   However, it won't be a low-budget contract. Sanders has said he
won't sign for less than market value, which could mean a contract
averaging more than $7 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has a base salary of $6.5 million for the 1999 season.
Jones had been planning to extend his deal since the end of the
season to free up salary-cap room.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery April 27, Sanders was given a best-case prognosis
of four to six months for his return. Doctors suggested the
possibility that Sanders might never play again.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said nothing has happened to change
the original prognosis, and said Sanders' rehabilitation is going
as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has progressed as we thought it would since the
surgery,'' Maurer said. ``We haven't had any setbacks, and that's
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   However, after the surgery, Jones became hesitant about signing
Sanders to a long-term extension.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk that the Cowboys possibly would waive Sanders to
save money, considering that they need more salary-cap room to sign
their rookie draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Thursday backed off any notion of releasing Sanders, and
said restructuring was in the best interest of the Cowboys and
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said I would waive him,'' Jones said. ``And I know
firsthand how much Deion wants to compete and help us win. Never
did I think that Deion can't dramatically help the team.''
Irvin expected at minicamp
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he expects wide receiver Michael
Irvin to take part in the team's three-day minicamp June 15-17.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who has a year remaining on his contract, has given the
Cowboys permission to trade him. At issue are his reduced role in
the Cowboys' offense, the fact that the Cowboys tried to trade him
before the draft and the team's decision not to give him a contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin did not participate in any of the team's voluntary
off-season coaching sessions, which ended Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who said he has not talked to Irvin in more than a week,
said ``everybody'' is required to be at minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to see everybody,'' Gailey said, when asked
specifically about Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones, however, said he was more concerned that Irvin is
at training camp, set for July 26, than minicamp. He said he hopes
to have the situation resolved one way or another by then.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
