<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-FINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS FINED FOR TREATING TRENT AND FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The NBA responded to Don Nelson's lavish treatment of
free-agent forward Gary Trent and his family by fining the
Mavericks $25,000 yesterday for violating the league's salary-cap
rules and other provisions of the collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Nelson provided an all-expenses-paid trip to
Maui, Hawaii, for Trent and Trent's son, mother, father, fiancee
and future mother-in-law. The league said because Trent is a free
agent, Nelson was in violation of league rules.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the Mavericks' coach and general manager, returned to
Dallas yesterday after a three-day stay in Chicago for the predraft
camp. He said he was unaware he had violated any rules when he gave
Trent and his family the red-carpet treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why I've been penalized, but I have, and we'll
accept it and go on,'' Nelson said. ``I thought I could take my own
player anywhere I wanted but evidently I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he spoke with NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik on
Wednesday in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him that I didn't know about the rules, and if
there were any rules, I've never seen any,'' Nelson said. ``I
explained my side, and that I was upfront and I wasn't trying to
hide anything. I was open and honest about us and what we did with
Gary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Well, we have to fine you to set a precedent.' I
said, `Well, if you do that, I'll understand.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Trent averaged 16 points and 7.8 rebounds per game last season
and is expected to be one of the NBA's top free agents when the
free-agency period starts July 1. The most the Mavericks can offer
the fourth-year power forward is a one-year, $2 million contract,
or a two-year deal for approximately $5 million, but he probably
will attract more-lucrative, long-term deals.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who admittedly never checked with the NBA before he
arranged for Trent's family to fly to Hawaii, owns a home in Maui.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still glad that I had that time together with Gary and his
mom and dad,'' Nelson said. ``We had them over for dinner the first
night, and we all got in my hot tub and sat around in my hot tub
for about half an hour talking and having a cold beer. That was
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get that opportunity very often. So, hopefully it'll
pay dividends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
