<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1292 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPELINE-EXPLOSION-SP     06-11 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-EXPLOSION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPELINE BLAST CREATED A RIVER OF FIRE, TOWER OF SMOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLINGHAM, Wash. _ A ruptured pipeline turned a creek cutting
through the heart of this city into a river of fire Thursdsay
afternoon, sending a plume of smoke 30,000 feet into the sky and
people fleeing for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a napalm drop,'' said Grant Stevens, who lives
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The gasoline-fed fire left one person dead and critically
injured two boys. The explosion, which occurred within a mile of
downtown, also temporarily closed Interstate 5 through the city.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,660 barrels, or 277,200 gallons of gasoline, spilled,
said Doug Beu, operations manager for Olympic Pipe Line Co. It was
the biggest fuel spill in the history of the pipeline, which
extends from near the Canadian Border to the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   The rupture occurred about 4:30 p.m.; fire crews already were
searching the creek after receiving reports of smells of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Pipe Line managed to shut the gasoline off, but not
until about 6 p.m., according to officials with the Whatcom County
Division of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   After the gasoline hit the rushing waters of Whatcom Creek, it
ignited near a city water-treatment plant sending flames through a
commercial area where many of Bellingham's car dealers are located.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a roar, like a 200-mile-an-hour gust of wind was
about to tear the roof off,'' said Mike Seymour, who was in his
shop at Windsor Plywood about 100 feet from the creek. ``We ran
outside, and the whole creek was going up. There was a series of
explosions, maybe five or six or seven, rolling down the creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like nothing you've ever seen, amazing, and then it was
just a wall of black smoke as high as you could see.''
</P>
<P>
   Two 10-year-old boys suffered deep burns over 90 percent of
their bodies, said Larry Zalin, a spokesman for Harborview Medical
Center in Seattle. The boys were flown to Harborview, where they
were in critical condition in the burn intensive-care unit.
</P>
<P>
   The boys were playing in the creek when the gasoline ignited,
Zalin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a chance, but it's going to be tough for them,''
Zalin said. ``These are pretty severe ... I'd have to say they're
both going to have a very tough battle.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph Hospital in Bellingham treated two other people for
respiratory problems related to the smoke plume. They were later
released.
</P>
<P>
   On nearby Iowa Street, people ran out on the busy street to
escape the flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I saw flames shooting up. It seemed like it started
like a forest fire catching on to old brush and then it shot up 30
or 40 feet to the tops of treelines and followed along the top of
the tree line and followed across the creek,'' said Roger Anderson,
a car salesman at a Chrysler dealership on Iowa Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole street was full of people running. They are
evacuating us right now. I have to hang up!''
</P>
<P>
   People blocks away heard explosions they mistook for thunder,
then saw their lights flicker as the power was temporarily
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   From her office at the town's main library, Jane Lowery looked
out her window to the east and Iowa Street and saw a bank of black
smoke looming above the creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a picture of smoke from Mount St. Helens,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   To Lane Older, who was driving home near Whatcom Creek when the
explosion occurred, the fire and smoke ``looked like the Gulf War
oilfields'' aflame.
</P>
<P>
   The flames ``went straight down the creek,'' said Rodger
Kenoyers, who owns Speedy Auto Glass near the explosion. ``There
must have been 200 feet of smoke and 100 feet of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   He drove on a road along the creek and the heat singed the hair
on his arms. ``My arms are still burned from driving down that
road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters managed to get most of the major blazes under
control by 6 p.m. and the smoke cloud had largely dissipated before
7 p.m., said Orman Darby, a spokesman for the Whatcom Cunty
Division of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``All civil authorities in the region have been mobilized,'' he
said. ``We don't know what caused a leak or rupture in the
pipeline. The fuel went all the way down the freeway before it
ignited, so there was quite a backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard closed Bellingham Bay for a one mile radius from
the mouth of Whatcom Creek out of concern that gas or fuel might
have gotten around dock pilings and boats, Darby said.
</P>
<P>
   A team of investigators from the state Ecology Department were
dispatched to the scene to review what happened and to clean up the
spill, said spokeswoman Sandy Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Pacific's pulp mill in Bellingham, where 850 people are
employed, remained shut down out of concern that more fuel could
come down the creek, said Darby, who also works for the mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It initially went down because the explosion caused a major
power dropout, and the mill's power plant has to be manually
restarted,'' Darby said. ``It's costly to shut down, but they did
so out of the interest of safety to personnel and equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Western Washington University will hold its graduation Saturday.
Parents and other family members were already starting to arrive
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The graduation is schedule to proceed, university officials
said. The campus is three miles from the site of the fire. The
smoke had little effect on the university.
</P>
<P>
   The fire did destroy one home near the creek on Valencia Street
and a water treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astounded that the damage is this incredibly light. If the
cloud cover weren't so high the smoke might have moved over the
city and that could have caused a lot of accidents and injuries,''
said Bill Quehrn, with the county's Emergency Management Division.
</P>
<P>
   In its wake, the explosion also blackened the creek's greenbelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creek looks like the face of the moon now,'' said Seymour,
whose shop is along Whatcom Creek. ``Trees are just skeletons, and
all the fish are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in there walking the creek bed and it was charred as
wide as this road on either side,'' added Bellingham police officer
Rob Brandland. The road is 28 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   Neither investigators nor officials with the pipeline company
could explain the rupture in the 16-inch line last night.
</P>
<P>
   But Quehrn, of the Emergency Management Division, said ``Police
say they have some leads but I don't know what that means.''
</P>
<P>
   Beu, the operations manager with Olympic Pipe Line, said he
didn't know what ignited the gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline is pretty volatile. It does ignite if it finds a
source of ignition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's spokeswoman Joann Hamick said the company's
control center in Renton noticed the problem when instruments
detected a drop in the line's pressure. The system shut the
pipeline down shortly before an Olympic crewman called in to report
seeing the leak.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the crew member called back again to say
``he was running from the scene and it (the line) was on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Beu said the company had had no troubles in that area recently
with the line, which moves gasoline, diesel and jet fuel from
northern Puget Sound oil refineries to shipment terminals in
Seattle and Portland.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second pipeline explosion in as many years in Whatcom
County. A natural gas pipeline _ not owned by Olympic _ ruptured
and exploded in Everson east of Bellingham in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporters Mike Barber, Ellis E. Conklin,
Heath Foster, Gordy Holt, Kimberly A.C. Wilson, Judd Slivka, Phuong
Le contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
