<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1293 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS &LR;      06-11 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ Brett Hull's center had gone to the locker room with a
wrist injury. His Dallas Stars were fighting for their Stanley Cup
Finals lives.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final minutes of regulation were ticking away, and the
always-dicey proposition of overtime seemed imminent.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Mike Modano think of Hull's game-winning goal
Thursday night at Reunion Arena?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he has to do it himself,'' Modano said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Hull did just that when his slap shot beat Buffalo's Dominik
Hasek at 17:10 of the third period, providing the difference in the
Stars' 4-2 win over the determined Sabres, an outcome that evened
the series at one game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the goals everyone wants to get,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was the biggest of his career, Hull said, ``So far,
I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll have a chance to seek a bigger one this postseason after
helping Dallas avoid a 2-0 deficit as the best-of-seven series
shifts to Buffalo for Game 3 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we're all disappointed after winning the first
game,'' Hasek said. ``Now, we're starting from the beginning, but I
like our chances because of home ice.''
</P>
<P>
   An empty-netter by Derian Hatcher with 25.8 seconds remaining
gave the Stars a bit of a cushion, but it came on the heels of a
scramble on the other end in which Ed Belfour, who stopped 19 of 21
shots, barely kept the Sabres from sending yet another game into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a series,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``It's going to be this way all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, said Hitchcock, is day-to-day with an injury the coach
termed not serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not out for the series, hopefully,'' Hitchcock said.
``The doctors want to see if it is something that settles down.''
</P>
<P>
   But the All-Star center wasn't quite ready to dismiss the
problem, which resulted from a collision with Sabres defenseman Jay
McKee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jammed it on the boards pretty good,'' he said. ``It's a
little bit tender and sore. It's playoff hockey, day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   A relatively uneventful first period ended on a livelier note as
emotions spilled over at the horn.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who earlier drew a charge from Brian Skrudland in the
corner, went down again when Modano flipped him near the crease in
the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a cheap shot by Modano,'' Sabres coach Lindy
Ruff said. ``There are ways to combat it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing mini-melee was much ado about nothing, because the
penalties canceled each other out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the emotional ante clearly had been raised after a
relatively civil Game 1 and an additional 20-minute standoff.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone responded to that early in the second period, it was
the Sabres, and Buffalo finally got tangible results.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Woolley, who scored the game-winner in overtime in Game 1,
found Michael Peca alone on the far side of Belfour, and Peca
wristed a quick shot over the late-arriving goalie to make it 1-0
at 7:27 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   That lead held up for more than 10 minutes, but the Stars
finally came alive as Jamie Langenbrunner evened the score at 1
when he deflected a Richard Matvichuk blast past Hasek at 18:26.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas got a rare goal from defenseman Craig Ludwig at 4:25 of
the third period to take a 2-1 lead, but it didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Within a minute, Daryl Sydor was in the penalty box for a high
stick, and Alexei Zhitnik made the Stars pay when he picked up the
rebound of a Curtis Brown slap shot and poked it past Belfour to
tie the score at 2 at 5:36.
</P>
<P>
   The game seemed headed into overtime as the Stars flailed away,
but Hull finally found a bit of open space just inside the post and
blasted a shot past Hasek to allow Dallas to leave home with a
split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept coming,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation, and a big slap shot, finally paid off, better late
than never.
</P>
</TEXT>
