<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1294 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX     06-11 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENYING FRESHMEN WOULD HURT THEIR CAREERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NCAA is considering a vote to make men's basketball players
sit out their freshman year. Not freshman women's basketball
players, mind you. Not freshman men's baseball players. Or freshman
men's lacrosse team players. Or freshman cheerleaders. Or freshman
swimmers. Or freshmen who want to be on the university debate team.
</P>
<P>
   Just freshman men's basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   It's an absurd measure.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's stated reason for doing this is in the name of
education _ too few male basketball players graduate compared with
other athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right!
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that a resolution to sideline freshman men's
basketball players is a shot at all of the underclassmen who leave
school early for a chance at the NBA. By keeping a blue-chip
recruit on the sidelines until he is a sophomore, you, in effect,
put his NBA future and earning power on hold while ensuring the
college he attends gets his services for at least two, maybe three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies two major problems.
</P>
<P>
   First, if men's college basketball players should not be allowed
to play as freshmen, then shouldn't the ruling apply to all
freshman athletes, male and female, in all sports? This is, to be
sure, a legal Pandora's box waiting to be opened.
</P>
<P>
   Second, and most important, why should athletes who are good
enough to jump to the NBA after their freshman or sophomore years
be penalized? If college is supposed to prepare you to make a
living, why legislate against those who have the potential to make
a very large living at a very young age?
</P>
<P>
   Because, say the proponents of the measure, a recent study
indicated that only 41 percent of male Division I basketball
players who entered college in 1991 achieved their degrees,
compared with 57 percent for all Division I athletes. The
graduation rate for black college basketball players was even
lower, 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   No one, not the athletes in question, nor their educators,
should be proud of this statistic.
</P>
<P>
   But who are we fooling? Legislation to ensure that a
student-athlete stays in school at least three or four years won't
ensure that student a college degree _ or a nonathletic occupation.
</P>
<P>
   If college presidents really cared about education, they would
pay closer attention to the student-athletes their basketball
coaches recruit in the first place. But that's too much to ask for.
</P>
<P>
   College presidents know that by limiting their talent base, they
might be sidelining the next Michael Jordan or Mike Bibby _ both of
whom led their schools to national championships as freshmen. This
would adversely impact a school's won-loss record, which in turn
would limit the amount of money coming into the school's coffers
from television exposure and shoe contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the college presidents mean well. But to me, the issue
that will be discussed in Chicago in two weeks by a 27-member NCAA
panel looks too much like a veiled approach to keep minority
athletes from quickly climbing the financial ladder.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a black athlete, how can you think anything else?
</P>
<P>
   First, the NCAA mandated college boards to regulate who is and
who isn't eligible to play college sports. Those tests are arguably
culturally biased and have closed the door for thousands of
minority students who dreamed of playing Division I college
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   (Interestingly enough, earlier this year a U.S. district judge
ordered the NCAA to stop using minimum standardized-test scores in
determining freshman eligibility. I wrote in March that there
should be a national standard on test scores, but that maybe the
NCAA should use tests that are more culturally diverse.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, the NCAA _ tired of all of their talented underclassmen
basketball players passing up their years of college eligibility
for a chance to play in the NBA _ wants to, in effect, tell a kid
how long he has to stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   I'd feel better if those whiners who complain about basketball
players going pro after their freshmen season voiced similar
complaints about athletes from other sports. Society does not raise
a big fuss about all of the tennis players who go pro as
teen-agers, or all of the hockey and baseball players who forgo
college to start pursuing their dreams on the minor-league levels.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have a big problem with basketball players _ or
shall we say more plainly ``black kids'' _ leaving early.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and squirm as you read this.
</P>
<P>
   But let it soak in a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: The NCAA should allow all student-athletes who
qualify academically to play any sport.
</P>
<P>
   And leave it to the NBA to worry about the influx of
underclassmen into the league.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
