<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1295 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-11 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BELIEVE whomever you want. Or believe no one. Believe everything.
Or believe nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Believe Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. bared his soul,
revealing his feelings toward Hispanics a week ago, and then tried
to backtrack out of the mess when he realized he got caught.
</P>
<P>
   Or believe McLane was an innocent victim entangled in the
ugliest of misunderstandings. He fell victim to an exaggerated
report about what was another run-of-the-mill marketing spiel.
</P>
<P>
   Demand an apology. Or ask for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But the inevitable truth about the words McLane shared with
Telemundo executives a week ago is this: No matter if reality lies
with McLane's version of the story, with the Telemundo executives'
version or somewhere in between, damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   This issue will not go away quietly. Ignore this, and it will
fester. Give it only lip service, and some in the community will
resent the token concern.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to what was said or wasn't said at the fateful
reception where McLane spoke with KTMD general manager Marco
Camacho, it all comes down to one's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Mine remains that something was said that caused Telemundo to
run with the story. Something inflammatory had to have been said.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine anyone would be so shallow, so
contemptible, to fabricate such a life-changing allegation for the
sake of attention and maybe some ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Your opinion might be different. Fine. People can disagree _
that's why we live in this country, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is the discussion in question was indeed
fateful. Now comes the damage repair. And repairing this might be
as big a personal test for McLane as the emotional test he has felt
in the past week. It will be a long and arduous time. For some,
maybe nothing the Astros do from this point forward will help.
That's their choice, too.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent talk with McLane in the aftermath of the
Telemundo report, he recognized the need to do something big,
something significant, in an attempt to make everyone realize that
no matter what happened, things will be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always tried to be tough on the issues, not tough on
people,'' McLane said. ``This is an issue. This has become a great,
huge issue, and it's painful to me that it has. I'm not mad; I'm
hurting. I don't want to argue about who said what. I want to
change what people think about the Astros for whatever reason they
think it.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend when the Astros open a homestand against the San
Diego Padres _ a team that has long and successfully marketed
to &UR;  &LR; its Hispanic community _ McLane said he will invite numerous
Hispanic leaders to suggest ideas about where the club should go in
its relationship with the Hispanic community. He says he personally
will look into the Astros' Spanish-language broadcast marketing
strategy and try to decide, ``Are we doing it the right way?''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a youth baseball clinic targeting Hispanics this
weekend, with first-base coach Jose Cruz and outfielder Richard
Hidalgo conducting.
</P>
<P>
   He says he will instruct vice president for marketing Pam
Gardner to pursue discussions with the Padres and Los Angeles
Dodgers, another team entrenched in its Hispanic community, in an
attempt to develop ideas about how to raise the Astros' presence
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job now is to put a bridge between all of this,'' McLane
said. ``We have to get the Hispanic community back.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be impossible. Resentment and questions remain
regarding the fateful words McLane spoke, how Major League Baseball
responded and how the Astros look in their aftermath. The moves
McLane has decided to make toward soothing feelings are but baby
steps.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the scarcity of Hispanics in upper-management
positions with the club, McLane pointed to numerous
lower-management minorities, saying, ``We have a high rating
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But is that enough for those who think McLane bared his soul?
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the way baseball commissioner Bud Selig glossed over
the issue by defending McLane without speaking to Camacho or
Telemundo, McLane said: ``I really was not involved in that. I just
told (Selig) what I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of people were there a week ago to hear what
McLane said. Looking back on that night, McLane was asked to try to
dissect the conversation. Was there anything he can remember that
might have been wrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were any mistakes, it's because I'm very open,'' he
said. ``Maybe it was just fanned by the way it was interpreted,
making it sound extreme. When you get into a group like that, it
can be inflamed and someone can jump to conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe what you want. But believe only one person can make it
better: Drayton McLane Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
