r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-PHYSICAL-TE     06-11 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PHYSICAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS TAKE PHYSICAL ROUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Buffalo Sabres played the part of the bully on the
beach in the first game of the Stanley Cup Finals, repeatedly
kicking sand in the faces of the meek Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Last night in Game 2, the Stars kicked back in their 4-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   After taking 16 more hits than they dished out in the series
opener, the Stars got physical. They delivered 48 hits while taking
38, including 30 in the first period when they set the tone for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our goal to be more physical,'' said Stars defenseman
Richard Matvichuk, who was credited with three hits.
</P>
<P>
   There was more to the game plan than revenge.
</P>
<P>
   By winning the physical battle in the first game, the Sabres got
the Stars on their heels. Buffalo took control in the third period,
finding open ice that wasn't there in the first two.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars began to change things in the first period last night.
Their 30 hits in the period were of the hard, bone-jarring variety,
and 18 of them were delivered by the forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get some hits on their defensemen,'' said Mike
Keane, who had five hits in the first period and a team-high six
for the game. ``I felt we gave them a day off in Game 1. No
defenseman likes to handle the puck when someone's bearing down on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the physical play flowed from the Stars' attitude. After
losing Game 1, they were in a must-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last game we were hoping to win,'' Keane said. ``Tonight we
were desperate to win. It's just a matter of playing hard. We had
to battle back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are walking a fine line with the physical play. They
want to slow down the Sabres while sending a message, but they
can't afford to take penalties and put the dangerous Buffalo power
play on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to play our aggressive style, but we're trying to
do it within the rules,'' Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   They took seven penalties last night, but most were for tripping
and high-sticking, not rough play.
</P>
<P>
   One of the penalties for rough stuff came after a hit on Sabres
goalie Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek strayed far from his goal to play a puck almost all the
way in the corner in the first period, and was hit from behind by
Brian Skrudland, who drew a charging penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Hasek plays the puck, he sticks his body out to shield
the player,'' Keane said. ``We're not trying to run him. That's not
part of our game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was hit later in the period by Joe Nieuwendyk, who slid
into the goalie while going after a rebound. He went down again in
the waning seconds when he was tripped from behind by Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars said they weren't going after Hasek, but were just
following their plan to get more traffic in front of him to try and
score on deflections and rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the game plan of every team to bother the goalie, but
I don't think we're trying to run him,'' forward Guy Carbonneau
said.
</P>
<P>
   The hits on Hasek led to the Stars' first fight of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner got in Hasek's face when the goalie went in
search of a referee to complain after being tripped by Modano.
Sabres defenseman Richard Smehlik flew after Langenbrunner and hit
him, and players paired off all over the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk and Sabres forward Brian Holzinger dropped the
gloves, and Nieuwendyk landed a couple of punches before it was
broken up.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the hits _ both legal and illegal _ and the
fight stirred up some bad blood between two teams that only played
each other twice in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play a couple of games to get that dislike for a
team, and I guess we've got that now,'' Keane said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
