<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTITUTION-RING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-PROFILE PROSTITUTION RING CRACKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cracking a high-priced prostitution ring that
catered to Hollywood's elite and Los Angeles business leaders,
police said that they have arrested Jody ``Baby Doll'' Gibson and
seized her client list.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, 41, described as a longtime associate of convicted
Hollywood madam Heidi Fleiss, was arrested Tuesday by male officers
posing as clients during a meeting at the Century Plaza Hotel near
Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the resident of Palo Verde on the
California-Arizona border ran her call-girl empire out of a San
Fernando Valley hotel when she was in Los Angeles and had mail
drops in Toluca Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Men arranged meetings with women on an Internet site or an 800
number, and they paid between $500 and $3,000 per night or more,
detectives said. Reams of paperwork, computer files and her ``black
book'' were confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation and the information we have at this point
shows that several Hollywood actors, CEOs of major Fortune 500
companies and one athlete, at least at this point, were on the
client list,'' said Lt. Mike Felix of the Los Angeles Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to the names were listed their ages, where they were
located and whether they had any fetishes or special requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said her driver's license stated her name as Jody Babydol
Diane Gibson. Detectives said Gibson, also known as ``Sasha'' and
``Baby Doll,'' ran the high-priced ring since at least the late
1980s and has an association with Fleiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to documents that we seized _ if what she wrote is
true _ Heidi applied for a job with her service before her troubles
began in the early '90s and was turned down. Heidi then began her
own endeavors as competition for Gibson,'' Felix said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson is among five operators of major prostitution rings in
Los Angeles, according to detectives. She is believed to have taken
in hundreds of thousands of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's big in Los Angeles, and very big on the East Coast,
too,'' said Detective Keith Haight. ``We know she is operating in
at least 16 states.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson is accused of employing 34 women in Los Angeles and at
least six in Europe, including well-known pornographic actresses,
detectives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interviewing the girls now, and it could very well lead
to the men who hired them,'' Haight said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get into her operation with undercover
officers,'' Haight said. ``An undercover female officer was hired,
then directed to have sex with her clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Three accused prostitutes were arrested and released on bail,
police said. Their names were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Gibson would send escorts from Los Angeles wherever
her clients wished. Clients would call an 800 number that would
ring at her home to place orders, Haight said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was done by phone. There are no offices,'' Haight
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her Web site, accessed only through a password, displayed
photographs of women who could be ordered over the phone, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the dates, the women kept 40 percent of the fee and sent
the rest to mail drops. Gibson would come to the Valley twice a
month to pick up her cash and interview prospective employees,
Haight said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was booked at the Van Nuys Jail on suspicion of pimping
and pandering and was released on $25,000 bail, police said.
Arraignment is scheduled for Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Officers in the LAPD's organized crime and vice divisions have
been watching Gibson since 1990, Haight said. In 1994, they
discovered she was an associate of Fleiss, but their involvement
with each other remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if they were in business together, or friends,
or traded trade secrets,'' Haight said. ``We have stacks of diaries
and paperwork that we're trying to piece through to figure out
their connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Their investigation began in earnest earlier this year when
detectives received an anonymous complaint from a woman that
Gibson's escorts were offering sex, Haight said. Investigators
believe the caller was a disgruntled prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the undercover female officer who worked for
Gibson, two male officers placed orders for escorts and were
offered sex, Haight said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   She is the first high-profile madam arrested since Fleiss, who
was sentenced to 37 months in federal prison in January 1997.
Fleiss was convicted of tax evasion, conspiracy and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Fleiss, 33, was accused of generating more than $600,000 by
running a call-girl ring in which the rich, famous and powerful
paid $1,500 to $7,500 for an evening with one of her prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
