<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MIRACLE-HN     06-11 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MIRACLE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ORLANDO, Fla. _ The relative health of the Comets came under
question in recent days as they approached their WNBA season opener
against the expansion Orlando Miracle.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper sprained her ankle in practice Wednesday, and
Sheryl Swoopes had expressed concern about a sick defense that had
not performed up to Comets standards in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard was a suspect position with starter Kim Perrot
sidelined because of her battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, before an enthusiastic crowd of 15,422 at
the Orlando Arena, the Comets, despite Cooper reinjuring her ankle
in the first half and two teammates getting banged up, recorded a
77-63 victory that indicated that perhaps the earlier concerns were
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little frustrated when I got hurt,'' said Cooper, who
had to leave the game briefly at 11:34 of the first half. ``I was
ready mentally to play, then I go and hurt my ankle. I was a little
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But tell you what, the team came out and played great. Tina
Thompson, wow. She shot the ball, did it all tonight. And that's
what it takes for us to win. When one person is down, that's why
we're so hard to stop. When someone is down, someone else steps
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping gingerly on her right ankle all night, Cooper went
4-for-6 from the 3-point line and led all scorers with 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   When she had trouble with her mobility and difficulty shooting
the ball, she found other ways to help. Cooper added a game-high
seven assists and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a gutsy effort by Cynthia,'' Comets coach Van
Chancellor said, ``playing on the ankle that she could not walk on
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, I was really concerned because she started
out with no hobble and then she went to a bad hobble. That worried
me to death. But I should have known Cooper was going to make
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also did a little of everything. She scored 22 points,
pulled down 12 rebounds and was 3-for-5 from beyond the arc in the
first half, picking up the slack for Cooper with 17 of her 22
points in the half.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Swoopes. With Orlando mounting a charge in
the second half after trailing by as many as 13 points in the
opening half, Swoopes scored six of her 18 points during a 12-0
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheryl just gives us so much,'' Cooper said. ``She shoots off
the dribble; she posts up. She's so quick. And in the tough moments
of the game, she just steps it up and really helps the team get
back on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Superlatives are usually expected from Cooper, Swoopes and
Thompson. But Sonja Henning, although scoring only two points,
teamed with Janeth Arcain to give Chancellor a strong showing from
the point position. Henning had four assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about Sonja for coming in and playing
hard,'' Chancellor said. ``You can't say enough about Arcain for
the game she had.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper started and was playing well until nine minutes into the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while scoring on a driving layup, she came down and
stepped on a cameraperson seated along the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cooper, who was fouled by rookie Nykesha Sales as she
made the basket, righted herself long enough to complete the
three-point play, she then was taken to the bench for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   She would return later, but Thompson stepped up to fill the
void, scoring 11 of the Comets' first 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   With Cooper on the sideline, Thompson dropped in back-to-back
3-pointers and Polina Tzekova (six points, four rebounds) followed
a miss by Arcain, Cooper's replacement, with a bucket that made it
32-19.
</P>
<P>
   That was part of a 10-0 Comets run that saw the lead grow to
37-19. But with Cooper back and limping noticeably, the Comets had
difficulty on defense and in solving the half-court pressure
defense of the Miracle.
</P>
<P>
   What proved to be the biggest hurdle for the Comets, however,
was three fouls on center Monica Lamb within the final 1:14 of the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the fouls were against Taj McWilliams, one of the many
former American Basketball League players who fill the lineup of
the Miracle.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams, who led the Miracle with 15 points, made four
consecutive free throws as Orlando trimmed the lead to 41-32.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer by McWilliams with 7.6 seconds left before
intermission brought the Miracle to within 41-34.
</P>
<P>
   But Tzekova, re-entering the game in place of Lamb, came up with
a monster follow shot.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer by Swoopes missed badly, but Tzekova, in one motion,
leaped to grab the carom and in midair connected to give the Comets
a 43-35 advantage at intermission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
