<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S ON RECORD PACE, BUT LONG BALLS A MIXED BLESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Monday night's 4-2 Mariners win over the Colorado
Rockies was perhaps the most incongruous outcome of the season, and
not just because it came at the ear-popping elevation of Coors
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Hit-and-run plays. Trickery on the base paths. Singles the
opposite way. For just the third time this season, Seattle won a
game without hitting a home run. Nice to play that kind of
baseball, isn't it, Lou Piniella?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners manager, who knows better, smiled and said,
``That'll change.''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, it did. Before they had made their first
out Tuesday, the Mariners were bashing again, off to a two-homer,
six-run first inning and their 14th game scoring 10 or more runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power's a good thing,'' Piniella said. ``The home-run ball,
when it comes, is a thing of beauty. But when it doesn't, and you
don't advance the runners, and you leave them in scoring position,
you get situations like the San Diego series, when we left about 25
men on base those first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team can strand baserunners, but when you make outs not
advancing people, they're not in position to score when the base
hits come. The secret is to have a combination of hitters in your
lineup to give you more opportunities to advance runners when you
make outs. And we really don't have that type of lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have more balance if you did, but certainly, you
wouldn't hit the home runs that we do.''
</P>
<P>
   And do they ever. In 1997, the Mariners set a major league
record with 264 home runs, getting 45 percent of their runs from
the long ball. Last year's team hit 234, tops in the majors, and
scored 43 percent of its runs on homers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the M's are on pace for 330 homers and have scored 51
percent of their runs on home runs. Seattle reached 100 homers
faster than any team in history, doing so in game No. 50, and has
118 homers for the season. That's more than the Florida Marlins,
Minnesota Twins, Pittsburgh Pirates and Tampa Bay Devil Rays had in
all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually with National League clubs, at least two or three guys
in your lineup are speed and defense guys. They may hit one out,
but not a lot,'' said Kevin Towers, San Diego Padres general
manager. ``But every guy in their lineup can hurt you with the long
ball. That's nice _ you could be down two or three runs, and with
that type of lineup, you could be up two or three in an inning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have one or two guys who can hit it out, you can be a
little extra careful with those guys and not give in to them,''
said Milt May, Colorado Rockies pitching coach. ``But when a team
has four or five guys in a row, like the Mariners, you have to
pitch to somebody. You can pitch around one. You can't pitch around
four or five.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lineup that's perfect if you enjoy anonymity. The
Mariners have six players with 10 or more home runs _ Ken Griffey
Jr. (23), David Bell (14), Russ Davis (14), Butch Huskey (11),
Edgar Martinez (10) and Alex Rodriguez (10). That's just what
Huskey was expecting when he was traded from the New York Mets to
Seattle last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what was exciting for me?'' Huskey said. ``What I
really thought of was that I could come over here and fit in and
almost be a guy that no one thinks is going to hit the ball,
because they already had Junior, Edgar, Jay (Buhner), Alex, Russ
and (David) Segui. Then you throw me in there, I can almost be a
sleeper in the lineup, and that's the way I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sleeper? That was more like a sleeper hold Huskey put on a Mark
Brownson pitch two batters after Griffey's blast on Tuesday. Huskey
hit the ball 458 feet, the longest homer for the M's this year
until Griffey hit one 20 feet deeper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Huskey, like most in the Mariners clubhouse, feels a need
almost to apologize for the home runs. Huskey said the Mets never
lost four dozen baseballs every batting practice, as his new team
does, but reliance on the homer can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll kill you,'' he said. ``But I think this team has the
capability of doing the little things when we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Dan Wilson is one of the most reliable hitters in
executing the hit-and-run, and he also has a team-high five
sacrifice hits. Wilson has hit just three homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be some periods where home runs aren't
going to be there,'' Wilson said. ``Any time you can get out of the
double-play situation or get a guy over to third base so a fly ball
can score him, that helps. When you have a team that can hit home
runs and win close games, too, that's the mark of a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Jesse Barfield has tried to stress those so-called
little things. Barfield's instructor in Toronto, Cito Gaston,
taught his hitters to make ``smart outs'' that advance runners or
make the pitcher work. Imparting that message to his hitters is now
Barfield's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not where we should be, but we're getting there,''
Barfield said. ``The tougher pitchers are going to slow down the
home run a little bit, and that's why you have to do the little
things. (Baltimore's) Mike Mussina, he owned this ballclub, and we
did the little things to beat him. We had to go the other way
against him, because he pitches that way. And it's not just
Mussina, but a lot of the better pitchers are like that. If you
make outs against them with smart at-bats, no one can say much.''
</P>
<P>
   As great as it is to hit home runs, Barfield points out that
homers also can stop momentum, clearing the bases and giving the
pitcher a break. That's why a merry-go-round of base-runners
becomes so important.
</P>
<P>
   And why, as staggering as the Mariners' home-run totals are, the
team always will be hamstrung unless the offense is well-rounded.
That won't happen easily, because home-run hitters naturally hit
more fly balls and strike out more often.
</P>
<P>
   But it must happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you keep constant pressure on a pitcher is (with) a
steady stream of baserunners,'' Piniella said. ``He's got to make
better pitches; he's going to work harder. Nothing's more
demoralizing to a pitcher than making a pitch down and away with
two runners on and seeing it sliced down the line for a two-run
double.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, there's a need for home runs. But the best type of
offense is one that's got a blend of both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 0202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
