<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-WITHOUT-HEROES-EDITORIAL-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR INHUMANE WAR FOR HUMANITY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial...Resending from June 9)   (This provocative 350-word ``separate buy'' commentary is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No war is to be revelled in, but the one that at last seems to
be drawing to a close in Kosovo leaves an especially bitter taste.
</P>
<P>
   Formally, we have won, since it is our leaders and our generals
who are dictating terms to those of the vanquished Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But historians will long argue whether this war should ever have
been fought; whether Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic made it
inevitable, or whether more skillful diplomacy might have avoided a
conflict that has compounded the tragedy it was supposed to
prevent.
</P>
<P>
   And, we are entitled to ask, was it a ``war'' at all? In a war,
do not two sides engage each other in battle, and both sides suffer
casualties?
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovo 1999 will feature on no regimental roll of honor.
This was among the very few wars fought not in pursuit of national
interests but for reasons of simple humanity. However, there is no
sense of triumph, or of virtue rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   There might have been, had NATO suffered some casualties or had
Milosevic _ architect of a decade of misery in the Balkans _ been
overthrown. But he has not been, despite a one-sided contest in
which the Allies have not lost a single life in battle.
</P>
<P>
   This has been war by remote control, carried out by deadly
machines _ one without heroes, only victims: the million or more
ethnic Albanian refugees (now to be followed, surely, by tens of
thousands of ethnic Serb refugees) and the dead and maimed
civilians who constitute the ``collateral damage'' of errant NATO
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   For all the wicked things they have done, one can feel even a
shred of sympathy for the Serb commanders in the tent at Kumanovo,
obliged to surrender to an enemy they have barely seen, let alone
laid a glove on.
</P>
<P>
   All of which only reinforces our own obligation to spare no cost
or energy so that the refugees in whose name we fought this ``war''
can return home safely and in peace. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this pithy 350-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 0537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 05:37 </DATE_TIME>
