<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     06-11 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, June 11, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SELENIUM-MUTATIONS (San Francisco) _ Kesterson National Wildlife
Refuge, already infamous as the place where selenium poisoned
thousands of birds, has just presented scientists with a startling
environmental puzzle: an outbreak of hermaphroditic rodents. By
ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   ARMADILLO-MEAT (San Francisco) _ As it turns out, armadillo meat
isn't so bad for you after all _ unless you eat it raw. San
Francisco Health Department officials told members of the Animal
Control and Welfare Commission that any risk of contracting leprosy
from armadillos would be nil as long as the animals were either
frozen or cooked. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   COUNSELING-HOMELESS (Houston) _ The Baylor/Star of Hope Family
Counseling Center is one of only a handful in the country that
offers intensive, individual and group counseling, psychological
testing and evaluations to the homeless. The program is helping an
abused woman understand the anger she's now free to feel. By
JANETTE RODRIGUES. (Filed Wendesday for release Sunday, June 13.
Photo available on the NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   LIVERMORE-LAYOFFS (San Francisco) _ Major layoffs may be ahead
at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, the nuclear weapons lab
east of San Francisco, as it ends a 26-year effort to use lasers to
develop nuclear fuel. The layoffs might affect as many as 500
employees of the lab and its contractors, lab officials announced.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT (San Antonio) _ Officials are urging people to
conserve water as lack of rain and heavy demand are causing Edwards
Aquifer levels to plunge almost a foot a day with the region in a
moderate drought. If the drought management plan is triggered this
summer, it would be the third time in four years. By JERRY NEEDHAM.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Aboard the Konkar Star, Panama) _ Here on the
Panama Canal, Robert Holden is part autocrat, part artist. His curt
instructions set off a chain reaction of bustle and fuss by the
captain and crew of a ship he is piloting through the waterway. We
look at Holden's life and work, both of which are fast disappearing
as Washington prepares to surrender one of the key engineering
marvels of the American Century _ the Panama Canal. By JOHN OTIS.
(Filed Wednesday for release Sunday, June. 13. Photo available on
NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL-WINDFALL (Balboa, Panama) _ What does the Panama
Canal mean to most Panamanians? Instant wealth for the country. By
JOHN OTIS. (Filed Wednesday for release Sunday, June 13.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you believe the conventional
wisdom, then the office suite war _ like the operating system war
and the browser war _ is over, and Microsoft has won. But a funny
thing happened while Bill Gates &AMP; Co. were celebrating another
victory. Corel Corp. has just released the slickest version yet of
its office suite. WordPerfect Office 2000 Professional nearly
matches Microsoft's latest entry, Office 2000, feature for feature,
and certainly beats it in one key area: the price. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``When I send
e-mail to someone on America Online, they tell me they get strange
markings and the sentences are broken up. `BSP' is at the end of
each sentence. Question: Do I have to do something different when
sending e-mail to someone on AOL? I use Netscape Communicator as my
browser and e-mail program.'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN, by L.M. Sixel, will return next week.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SHAGGED (Undated) _ An ``Austin Powers'' sequel
didn't have to be good. It could have let its hype do all its work
like that other sequel. It could've coasted on and basked in its
cultural-sleeper-phenomenon status. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BESIEGED (Undated) _ Told with the distorted
ambiguity and hypnotic poetry of a dream, ``Besieged'' is a jolt of
restless sleeping. But who's dreaming here? Is it the African woman
(Thandie Newton) and British man (David Thewlis) forced into a
tryst in order to make smooth beauty out of a sexual pairing of the
Third World and Imperialist England? Or is it Bernardo Bertolucci,
who's directing with a scaled-down litheness he rarely displays? By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ALONE (Undated) _ ``I Stand Alone'' has the ghastly
stink of a rotting corpse. You can smell the cess as clearly as you
can see the blood vessels striking like lightning around the pupils
of its malefactor's eyes. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CHIAPAS (Undated) _ Too sophisticated to be simply
wide-eyed, not nosy enough to be deeply probing, Nettie Wild's ``A
Place Called Chiapas'' makes a virtue of its filmmaker's innocence
as she slyly, almost manipulatively, ingratiates herself to the
major players in the notorious, ongoing Zapatista insurgence that
broke out in 1994 in southern Mexico. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
