<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN12-COX     06-11 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political analysis at home
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ I was at my end of the breakfast table
with the morning paper, trying to catch up on whose embassy and
what hospital had been bombed in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how people change,'' I remarked. ``Bill Clinton
certainly has done a 180.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's changed all that much,'' my wife objected.
``The only difference I can see is that, while he was a womanizer
in Arkansas, he's been more of a girlizer in Washington. Monica
Lewinsky is a lot younger than Gennifer Flowers and Paula Jones and
some of the others we know about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about his sex life,'' I explained. ``What
puzzles me is how he switched from being a Vietnam draft dodger and
war protester into a president who drops bombs and shoots missiles
all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because he's really an actor,'' she said. ``He
probably thinks he's George C. Scott playing General Patton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he'd rather go down in history as Bomber Bill than a
near child molester,'' I said. ``I just wish he'd be more like
Teddy Roosevelt. Ol' TR went straight up San Juan Hill with his
troops. Clinton could at least ride along on one of his Stealth
bomber missions. It would make a great photo op, and he'd be safer
than being home in bed with Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have guns we wouldn't have all these people being
killed,'' my wife protested.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may be right,'' I admitted, ``but there are constitutional
issues about individual rights to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do dogs have constitutional rights?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' I admitted. ``I wouldn't think so, but trees
and snail darters seem to, so I guess it's possible. Why are you
asking about dogs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you read the story about the Fayette County
Commission?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered. ``What have they done now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made it illegal to have more than three dogs. The
story says one lady is eight dogs over the limit. She hired a
lawyer to try to keep her dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So what happens if you have more than three dogs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you go to jail, unless you open a kennel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you open a kennel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It says here you have to have runs and shelters and be at
least 300 feet from neighboring residential property.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing Lassie didn't come from a big family and
live in Fayette County,'' I said. ``She'd have ended up in the
pound instead of in the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like a good law to me,'' she said. ``We shouldn't be
feeding so many dogs when children in Africa are starving to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good point,'' I admitted, ``but it sounds
unconstitutional. What if the commissioners decide we can have only
two dogs, or one dog, or no dogs? How about parakeets and goldfish?
There are some things the government just shouldn't control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it happens,'' she said. ``Don't you remember when we
were in China last year? The government won't let Chinese couples
have more than one child, unless they're farmers and need the
help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I agreed. ``But China is a communist dictatorship.
We're supposed to be a democracy. Besides, the Fayette County dog
law is obviously prejudicial, unfair, and discriminatory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you mean?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about cats? People can have as many cats as they want,
but only three dogs. That's discrimination if I ever heard of it.
It's ridiculous! Everybody knows a dog is man's best friend. Cats
hold humans in contempt, show no gratitude, don't recognize their
own names, bite and scratch benefactors, and sometimes smother
newborn babies. If we're going to have a limit on dogs we darn sure
need a limit on cats!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the commissioners will make up some new laws about
cats,'' she suggested.
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out that every time politicians and bureaucrats make
up new laws we lose individual rights. In Fayette County I don't
think you can build a birdhouse without several complicated
permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strange,'' she said. ``Aren't all the people in charge
Republicans? And don't Republicans stand for individual rights?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not any more,'' I said. ``Barry Goldwater's dead. Everybody
has switched roles. Bill Clinton acts like Teddy Roosevelt and
Republicans love Big Government as much as the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then maybe when they finish with dogs they'll do something
about cars,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do what about cars?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you read the newspapers?'' she said. ``We've got so many
cars nobody can get anywhere on time and we can't breathe because
of the pollution. Why can't the commissioners make people cut down
on cars while they're getting rid of their dogs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good idea,'' I agreed. ``Or, they could eliminate
drivers. Remember when we were in China they told us the government
makes people stop driving when they reach age 55?''
</P>
<P>
   ``China seems to have a lot of good ideas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.'' I agreed. ``And we've worked out a nice trade
arrangement. They steal our military secrets and we steal their
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
