<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1554 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD12-COX     06-11 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jointer vs. planer debate continues
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some folks feel they don't need a jointer if they have
a planer. I think they're wrong, and it was gratifying to encounter
this thread on the rec.woodworking newsgroup on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It started with a question:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting close to buying a jointer for my home workshop and
I need some advice. From a functional point of view how much more
useful is an 8-inch jointer than a 6-inch? I know that the 8-inch
usually has a longer bed and more horsepower, but for someone who
will be making cabinets from solid wood is there a significant
difference?''
</P>
<P>
   I'll inject part of an answer here: Someone making cabinets from
solid wood has the greatest need of all for a wide planer. Now,
I'll step aside and report what the folks in the news group told
him:
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself in the same dilemma two weeks ago. I got the
8-inch jointer for one reason: I just couldn't afford a 12-inch,''
said the first responder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought an 8-inch WoodTek last year,'' said the next reply.
``For the money, it can't be beat. The extra power is very
noticeable when you need to get through some seriously hard
maple.''
</P>
<P>
   Then another novice weighs in with a related question :
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the advice to go with 8-inch to handle wider boards still
apply if you are planing on a planer also?''
</P>
<P>
   A response, and I couldn't have put it better myself:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, because a jointer and a planer are extremely
complimentary tools. I use the jointer on every rough board I
plane, to give it one smooth or ``plane'' side. Plane it with a
jointed side down, and you won't believe the accurately milled
board you get.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
