   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Some folks feel they don't need a
jointer if they have a planer. I think they're wrong. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEHOUSE _ For 44 years, the Waffle House has been almost as
reliable as sunrise on the Southern landscape. It's doors stay
unlocked 24 hours a day, seven days a week, 52 weeks a year. Here's
a look at what happens inside. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-WILEY _ BUENA PARK, Calif. _ The Southern Baptist
minister who has introduced at least a third of all resolutions at
the last three or four conventions _ including the Disney boycott _
himself has a church near Disneyland. He also has a homeless
ministry and has defied local loitering ordinances by letting
people hang around his church. In advance of the Southern Baptist
Convention, meeting in Atlanta in June, we talk to Wiley Drake and
visit his church. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-HOLOCAUST _ Never forget. That has been the vow of many
Holocaust survivors who feel it is their duty to remind others of
the horrors of Nazi Germany. Andre Steiner never held such a
philosophy. But his story is destined to serve just such a purpose.
Steiner, an architect who emmigrated to Atlanta shortly after WWII,
is the subject of a new documentary, filmed by an Atlanta native
and to be shown at the Carter Center. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14. WITH PHOTO. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIOUS-MUSIC _ Reviews of two new Christian music
collaborations, ``Songs from The Book,'' and ``Streams in the
Desert.'' (Dayton Daily News). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CHICKENPOX _ ATLANTA _ It used to be that Dr. Karen Dewling had
to persuade parents to give the chickenpox vaccine a try. But in
the past six months, she's seen a dramatic turn-around, with moms
and dads asking for the shots for their kids. ``People have really
caught on to the fact that this is a good disease to prevent,''
said Dewling, a pediatrician at the Emory Clinic North in Duluth.
``A lot more parents are getting the message.'' To make sure the
trend continues, a Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
advisoroy committee has just issued new recommendations about the
chickenpox vaccine. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-REHAB _ SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ Janet Gray remembers what her
life was like after she was diagnosed with breast cancer. ``My life
was going down the tubes fast,'' the 50-year-old Springfield
resident said. ``I was tired all the time. I gained 90 pounds on
the tamoxifen they were giving me for chemotherapy.' But then she
discovered a fitness program specifically for breast cancer
survivors run by the Ohio State University Center for Wellness and
Prevention, The James Cancer Center, and Community Hospital. Gray,
a bus driver for the Clark-Shawnee District, attends the fitness
program twice a week at the Community Hospital Center for Coronary
Prevention and Rehabilitation. (Springfield News-Sun). 15. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   INFANT-BEDSHARING _ DAYTON, Ohio _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The baby
triplets clearly don't like being apart. When one of them is left
alone in the bed they all share, it won't be long before she'll
start moving around and fussing. She seems to be reaching out for
her sisters. ``They always have to be touching each other, and
they'll smile,'' says their mother, April Lenz. ``When you look at
them together, you can just see the peace that they have.'' The
limited research on premature babies who share a bed with their
siblings suggests it's more than just comforting to stay close with
their buddies from the womb as soon as practical after birth. They
also gain weight faster, begin maintaining body heat earlier and
nurse sooner on more nutritious breast milk, says Linda Lutes, an
infant-development specialist and the country's foremost advocate
of what she calls co-bedding. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
MONDAY FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   POOR-VISION _ Imagine. Waking up at night and making your way to
the bathroom without stumbling over the dog and banging into the
door. For people with poor vision, the idea of seeing clearly late
at night or first thing in the morning _ well, actually, seeing
clearly anytime _ comes close to fantasy. It's something they try
to imagine but can't quite visualize. (Scott, Austin
American-Statesman). 13. WITH GRAPHCIS, PHOTOS, TIMELINE. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCI-HEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
This layout will be available at 5 p.m. EDT.COXNET SCIHEALTH 0612
SNUGGLE INFANTS -- Research on premature babies who share a bed
with their siblings suggests it's more than just comforting to stay
close with their buddies from the womb as soon as practical after
birth. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) Art includes 3-column color photo
of babies in crib.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAUMA RESPONSE -- Paramedics arriving to the scene of
accidents in well-equipped vehicles and trained in up-to-date
techniques have improved the chances a victim of a traumatic
accident will survive. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
