<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1591 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTIC-CITY-ART-NYT     06-11 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTIC-CITY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: NEXT STOP -- ATLANTIC CITY 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Sales Executive DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available electronically by e-mail AT NO
EXTRA CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you
want the art when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Round-trip motorcoach tours to fun destinations give mature
travelers the opportunity to visit nearby gaming areas for a day or
two at almost no expense.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in Las Vegas or Laughlin, Nev., such motorcoach
tours, which are also called ``turn-arounds,'' arrive almost daily
from Arizona and California, while buses to Reno, Nev., come from
San Francisco and other Bay Area locations.
</P>
<P>
   Ludmilla Alexander of Saratoga, Calif., joined Matty Bagano of
Nutley, N.J., and Diane Bocchino of Hawthorne, N.J., on a Leisure
Line motorcoach (800-522-4187) heading to Atlantic City. Their
goal: Gamble a little, eat lunch, stroll along the Boardwalk and
watch the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Bugano, 81, says she takes the motorcoach for little getaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm retired and live with my daughter, so this gives me an
opportunity to see people and do something exciting,'' she says.
``It's not expensive at all. You pay $23 for the round-trip bus
from Nutley, then get back $16 in silver half-dollars at Trump
World's Fair Casino. I also look in the newspapers for coupons on
food and attractions. One time, I collected so many coupons, the
entire trip cost me $2.''
</P>
<P>
   Bocchino, who is in her mid-50s, echoes Bagano's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take care of an ailing mother and need to get a break
occasionally,'' she says. ``Twice a week, I take the bus to
Atlantic City to swim in the ocean and lie on the beach. It's very
relaxing, and you meet wonderful people.''
</P>
<P>
   During the three-hour trip from northern New Jersey, bus
passengers compare coupons they have clipped that week from
newspapers. Once in Atlantic City, they get off at their favorite
casino and head for cashier windows to claim their coins.
</P>
<P>
   Some use the money to buy themselves lunch, while others head
for their ``lucky'' slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander says Atlantic City, whose fame started in the first
half of this century, is experiencing a rebirth, thanks, in part,
to mature travelers arriving by the busloads.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors, she says, tend to favor Mondays through Thursdays
because of fewer crowds and lower accommodation prices should they
decide to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling is the key to Atlantic City's success: Bally's,
Caesars, Trump and Tropicana are just a few of the gaming
corporations that line the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wynn, who built the highly successful Mirage Resorts Inc.,
Treasure Island and Bellagio properties in Las Vegas, is planning a
new casino resort, tentatively called Le Jardin, that will be up
and running by mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd Gaming has formed a joint-venture with Mirage to build The
Borgata, a resort-casino with an Italian-village theme. It is
expected to open in mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlantic City differs from Las Vegas in that Atlantic City has
a beachfront location and a well-preserved history,'' Alexander
says. ``The resort was built in the 1880s to attract working- and
middle-class Americans who could finally afford to travel because
of mass transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Alexander says, ``Atlantic City is wonderful to visit,
whether gambling is for you or not.''
</P>
<P>
   For nostalgia buffs, the Atlantic City Historical Museum
(609-347-5839; free) on the old Garden Pier _ where silent-film
star Rudolph Valentino once taught dancing _ is a must-see
attraction. It has many displays from Atlantic City's early days,
like the origin of the Heinz 57 pickle pin and the history of the
Monopoly game. (All locations on the Monopoly board are named after
Atlantic City streets.)
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Chairs (609-347-7148), which became popular near the
turn of the century, are still pushed along the Boardwalk by hardy
walkers, many of whom are international students. Fees start at $5
for a push up to six blocks.
</P>
<P>
   For Alexander, the experience is unlike any other. ``It's so
nice to roll along in the wicker chairs past the various souvenir
shops, arcades and food stalls which sell everything from Italian
hoagies to funnel cakes,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Miss America Pageant, held annually on the second weekend
after Labor Day, welcomes the public to many activities, including
the preliminaries, the pageant itself, and the Boardwalk parade.
</P>
<P>
   The Friday night parade, Alexander says, ``is great fun for
onlookers as they shout `show us your shoes' to contestants, who
ride by in convertibles. The women smile, wave and ... display wild
footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition started in the early days when tired contestants
with sore feet used the opportunity to get out of their tall heels
and into comfy bedroom slippers. Now, decorations on their shoes
represent each contestant's state and can include sunglasses,
flowers and leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the year, some pageant memorabilia can be seen at the
Sheraton Hotel across the street from the Convention Center, where
displays of gowns worn by various Miss Americas over the years are
showcased in the lobby, as well as the Waterford crystal crown and
scepter the winner receives.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hotel is a statue of Bert Parks, longtime emcee for
the pageant. He holds a replica of the prized possession in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can resist standing underneath the crown to be Miss
America for a quick photo?'' Alexander asks.
</P>
<P>
   Discounts for mature travelers are posted at Ripley's Believe It
or Not! Museum (on the Boardwalk at New York Avenue, 609-347-2001),
where seniors ages 60 and older pay $6.95 vs. $8.95 for other
adults, and Atlantic City Cruises (609-347-7600) that leave from
Gardner's Basin. Discounts range from $5 to $10 off various
cruises.
</P>
<P>
   While lodging is not discounted specifically for seniors, summer
is prime time for hotels to offer lodging packages filled with
extras. Here is a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlantic City Hilton Casino Resort (800-257-8677) has a
Celebrate Summer package, available June 27 to Sept. 23, with room
rates starting at $72, double, Monday through Thursday. This summer
package includes $10 in coins and $10 in food vouchers per person
plus other discounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Caesars Atlantic City Hotel Casino (800-524-2867) has a spring
package until June 30 in which $130 gives two guests a room, Sunday
through Thursday nights, breakfast for two, and two passes to the
health spa. From July 1 to Aug. 30, the bed-and-breakfast package
costs $175 per night, double, on weekdays and includes breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comfort Inn North (800-233-4656) has a Home Run Package priced
at $79.95 for one or two guests and includes a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comfort Inn Victoria (609-646-8880) has a Sun-Sational Package
of $44.50, July 1 to Oct. 1, for $44.50 a person, double, Sunday
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Holiday Inn Express (800-447-6667) prices its rooms, Sundays
through Fridays, for $65 a night year round. In addition, $14 in
coins is given at the Hilton Casino to Holiday Inn guests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard Johnson (800-447-6667) offers rooms year round for $45,
single or double occupancy, with $14 in coins returned at the
Hilton Casino.
</P>
<P>
   For general information about Atlantic City, call (800)
262-7395.
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)
