<HEADER>
A1609 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     06-11 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OK, GET OUT ALL YOUR FINGERS, TOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: From reading your columns, it seems you favor
Windows 98 over 95. My local ``experts'' don't recommend using 98
yet. What advantages does it have?
</P>
<P>
   _Windows Watcher
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WATCHER: What advantages? Are you kidding? Don't you know
that 98 is at least three better than 95? That's why I can hardly
wait for Windows 2000, which promises to be at least five better.
</P>
<P>
   Tell your ``experts'' to pull their heads out of their
respective sandboxes. Their attitude might have been justified the
first couple of months Windows 98 was on the shelves, but it's
downright silly now that it has proved itself a big improvement
over 95. These people became ``experts'' because they got really
comfortable with 95. Giving up 95 for a new operating system
threatens that specious expertise. They probably had trouble giving
up their baby blankies, too.
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't even a new operating system. Win98 is just a
gussied-up Windows 95, minus a couple of thousand bugs. It's got
support for all sorts of new hardware, and it's chock-full of new
features and utilities, including stuff that repairs system errors
that would have been fatal to 95.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that 98 is bug-free or that your life
will be endlessly better because you upgraded or even that I've
sold out to Microsoft. The check wasn't big enough.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I bought an iMac even though I have no real
reason for a computer. I believed the Internet hype.
</P>
<P>
   _ Applesauced
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SAUCED: My editors are asking readers to please refrain
from providing me with such obvious straight lines. They are tired
of the ceaseless death threats we all receive here every time I say
something nasty like, ``But you didn't buy a computer. You bought
an iMac.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually iMacs, despite their unfortunate color schemes, are
fine machines, perfectly suited for Net surfing, gaming and most of
the stuff home users say they want to do. I hope you didn't really
believe their commercials about how easy they are to hook up to the
Internet, though.
</P>
<P>
   The ad agency sort of left out the part about establishing an
account with an Internet service provider and getting all those
software and modem settings right. It doesn't matter whether you
have a PC or a Mac, that stuff is confusing. A computer isn't a
toaster oven. You can't just turn it on and have everything working
without investing a little brainpower, although the suit that hired
Jeff Goldblum as a spokesman exhibited none of that. I bet he burns
his toast, too.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: You lost me! I've given up reading your column.
It disgusts me! Your sexist remarks and ``humor'' must be written
by and for the 15-24 age group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Apoplectic
</P>
<P>
   DEAR AP: I wish! The demographics dweezils have been after me
for years to go after that market since the only ads they've been
able to sell anywhere near my column have been for laxatives and
trusses.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am a dedicated fan. I always, always read
you. I'm only 16, but I relate with your attitude.
</P>
<P>
   _Biggest Fan
</P>
<P>
   DEAR FAN: Hey! Apoplectic was right! How totally kewl! The
Marketing doodz will be pumped. And that means next week we can
finally talk about that Ricky Martin/'N Sync fistfight over Lacey
Chabert. Wanna see my tongue ring?
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay rulez, dood! He can be
reached at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101, or fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, he is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1619 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     06-11 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of repair.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bathroom was found to be the most dangerous room. Two or
more hazards were found in 59 percent of bathrooms. More than 60
percent lacked grab bars in the tub or shower, about the only
hazard that was not found in housing for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Other common hazards included loose mats, slippery tubs and
showers lacking nonskid mats or abrasive strips, poor lighting and
toilets that were wobbly or too low to allow older people to rise
from them safely. The living room was second most dangerous, with
42 percent having two or more hazards, mostly trip hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens came next, with 40 percent having two or more hazards.
Light switches were hard to find in more than two-thirds of
kitchens, especially in the dark, and trip hazards were found on
nearly a third of kitchen floors.
</P>
<P>
   Other kitchen hazards included unstable step stools, poor
lighting and storage of frequently used objects in places that
required reaching up or bending over. Living rooms were next with
dim lighting, shadows or glare and chairs that were too low to get
out of easily, along with many floor hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of falls occur at home, and about a quarter of all
falls result from hazards like slippery or wet surfaces, poor
lighting, inadequate footwear and cluttered pathways in a home. To
help avoid these kinds of falls, Dr. Mary Tinette, director of
Yale's Program on Aging, suggests two proven measures.
</P>
<P>
   One involves exercises that increase physical strength and
balance. Strength training, like lifts with hand and leg weights,
has grown in popularity among older people. These exercises have
two benefits: they increase people's physical strength, thus
decreasing their chances of falling, and they increase bone mass so
that if a fall should occur, the risk of fracture is reduced.
Muscle strength is important to nearly every activity of daily
living, from getting out of the bed to climbing stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Tai chi has been demonstrated by osteoporosis researchers at the
Hospital for Special Surgery in New York to improve balance and
decrease the risk of falls in older people.
</P>
<P>
   Another important measure for maintaining balance is avoiding
side effects like dizziness and vision impairment caused by
medications. Those most at risk of falls take four or more
medications. Certain drugs, for example some drugs used to treat
high blood pressure or heart ailments, can cause dizziness, central
nervous system depression and movement disorders that increase the
risk of falls.
</P>
<P>
   Tinette suggests that people discuss with their physicians the
possibility of reducing the number of drugs taken and keeping
dosages to the minimum necessary to control the ailment. Effective
alternative medications can sometimes be prescribed to avoid the
side effects that make falls more likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish researchers also attributed the increase in falls
among the older people to an increase in alcohol consumption and
the use of psychotropic drugs. Older people are more susceptible to
the adverse effects of mind-altering chemicals; an amount of
alcohol that was handled well at 40 may become a serious hazard at
60.
</P>
<P>
   The fall-prevention program of the American Academy of
Orthopaedic Surgeons suggests a number of ways to help the elderly
stay on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Install sturdy hand rails on all stairways and grab bars in
the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cover stairs with tightly woven carpet or nonslip treads.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid climbing and reaching up to high shelves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a step stool with handrails
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not wax floors and always clean up spills as soon as they
happen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear low-heeled shoes with nonskid soles. Avoid thick, heavy
soles and keep laces tied so that the shoes fit snugly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try not to use a bed that is too high, and before getting out
of bed, sit on the edge for a few minutes to be sure you are not
dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   The academy offers a free brochure on fall prevention, available
by calling (800) 824-2663 or by sending a stamped, self-addressed
business-size envelope to Don't Let a Fall Be Your Last Trip,
American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons, P.O. Box 1998, Des
Plaines, Ill. 60017.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
