<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, CLINTON, BUSH, BUSH AND TORME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: Do you suppose that the president's claims of
victory in his Yugoslav military adventure will hold up under the
scrutiny of history? For that matter, do you suppose they'll hold
up for the 11 days that NATO has given the Serbs to clear out of
Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   There are those who suspect that Clinton went to war only for
the purpose of securing some sort of meaningful legacy for his
controversial presidency. Nothing is beneath this guy, but my guess
is that he intervened in Kosovo because he truly believed it was
the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, lots of us who believe that involving the
United States in a centuries-old ethnic conflict in Europe was the
wrong thing to do, no matter what the outcome. Right or wrong, the
United States is committed for the long haul _ which means that
questions about rightness or wrongness must be answered with that
always reliable cliche: Time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: Where do these people get their nerve?
Many Americans are counting the days until January 2001, when the
Clintons are required by law to vacate the White House. But the
first lady refuses to go away, gearing up instead for a U.S. Senate
race in New York.
</P>
<P>
   If she's seeking redemption by undertaking a political career of
her own, her efforts could turn out to be self-defeating. Her
opponent and the contentious New York media surely won't let her
stroll through a Senate campaign without reliving the various
Clinton scandals _ including a few in which she was a knee-deep
participant.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't Hillary do what's best for the country by taking a few
years off before jumping into the political fray? Must be because
the country always takes a back seat to the Clintons' ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE BUSH: The former president will be 75 years old Saturday,
and he's still jumping out of airplanes. If I'd known he had so
much fuel left in those Ivy League engines, I wouldn't have spent
so much time worrying about the hapless Dan Quayle being a
heartbeat away from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: While his dad was skydiving over College
Station, the Texas governor was getting ready to leap into the
treacherous crosswinds of the 2000 presidential campaign. The
all-but-declared candidate will be ``testing the waters'' of
national politics in the coming days and weeks in hopes of finding
out if voters are as enthused about his White House prospects as
pollsters are.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that once the just-plain-folks in remote locales
such as New Hampshire, Iowa and California get a close-up look at
Bush the Younger, his poll numbers will get even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   D. WAYNE LUKAS: The highly successful but always controversial
trainer of thoroughbred race horses is taking heat again _ this
time because one of his trainees broke a leg while trying to win
the Triple Crown in last week's Belmont Stakes in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The horse, Charismatic, had taken the world of racing _ the
whole world of sports, for that matter _ by storm when he won the
Kentucky Derby at odds of 31-1 and followed that with an impressive
win in the Preakness Stakes. A Belmont victory would have made him
just the 12th horse to win all three races _ and the first since
1978.
</P>
<P>
   It was not to be, but that wasn't the trainer's fault. There was
no indication that Charismatic was anything but sound and healthy
before the Belmont, ready to run the race of his life. Lukas can be
a headline-grabber, and his arrogance can be annoying, but he does
what he does better than anyone else who does it. Which might be
the reason he has so many critics.
</P>
<P>
   MEL TORME: He was never a bobby-sox idol or the king of rock 'n'
roll or the king of pop. He was never as famous as Sinatra or Elvis
or even Tony Bennett _ at least not until he became a recurring
character on the ``Night Court'' sitcom in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   But Torme, who died June 5, was one of the finest vocalists ever
to raise his voice in song _ and more. He was a composer, novelist,
instrumentalist and pretty darn good actor. Put him on the list of
show biz's all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
