A1684 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWTOWNHERD-TEX     06-11 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWTOWNHERD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-TIME DROVER RIDES HERD ON A LIFELONG DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When the Fort Worth cattle herd leaves
downtown for its ceremonial trek to the Stockyards on Saturday,
Cathy Cannon will be alongside the longhorns _ every nervous step
of the way.
</P>
<P>
   She changed careers to be part of this cattle drive. She took a
salary cut to work the steers daily, and now she labors nights and
weekends to supplement her income and recover her losses.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon is one of six full-time drovers who will push the newly
formed Fort Worth Herd down North Main Street toward Exchange
Avenue in celebration of the city's 150th birthday. On Monday, the
15-head herd will become a permanent tourist attraction in the
Stockyards.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon and the other drovers will drive them to the Trinity
River banks daily to let them graze.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a dream of mine,'' said the mother of
three from Weatherford, just west of Fort Worth. ``It's hard to
explain how someone like me, without a ranching background, would
want to do this, but I've always dreamed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Lubbock and raised in Midland, Cannon lived on the
periphery of the livestock business. Her family didn't ranch or
farm, but she participated in local FFA and 4-H projects.
</P>
<P>
   When she left high school to join the Army, she trained as a
veterinary assistant and was assigned to a small animal hospital on
a U.S. base in Germany. It was a good job, she said, and it kept
her involved with animals _ but, again, only on the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to join the civilian job force, she found she
needed more gainful employment. She became an X-ray technician and
was working at Harris Methodist Northwest hospital in Azle when a
friend told her about the drover jobs in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she is a full-time part of the livestock industry, of
Texas' ranching heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's drive will be the culmination of a lifelong fantasy,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 longhorns will be penned below the Chisholm Trail mural
at Main and Third streets at 9 a.m. A host of speakers will salute
the herd, the city and the city's western heritage. The Fort Worth
Symphony will provide the background.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony recalling cattle drive traditions, Anne Marion and
representatives of the Waggoner, Reynolds and Matthews families _
all legendary ranching families _ will present the herd tally to
Red Steagall, master of ceremonies for the morning event.
</P>
<P>
   The herd will be moved to Paddock Park at the top of the North
Main bridge, where Marion and riders from her 6666 Ranch will
exchange gifts with Ben Tahmahkera and a delegation of Native
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Marion is the great-great-granddaughter of cattleman and oilman
Samuel Burk Burnett; Tahmahkera is the great-great-grandson of
Comanche chief Quanah Parker. The two men were friends.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 10:30 a.m., the cattle will be herded across the
Main Street bridge for a 30-minute drive to the Stockyards.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 15 longhorn steers are massive, 1-ton animals with
horn spans wider than 6 feet, Cannon said she is certain the drive
will go well because she and her fellow drovers have done their
jobs in training them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is harder than I thought it would be,'' she confessed.
``There is a lot more mental work than people would think. You have
to learn the cattle, learn the horses, watch them work and
understand how to handle them. It's not just riding a horse all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year-old Cannon is the only woman among the Fort Worth
cowhands. She's also the most inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was intimidating at first,'' she said, ``but everyone
helped. They were all encouraging. They have all been very
supportive from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I don't have as much experience as they do, but I've
learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannon doesn't have to work her extra job this weekend. But next
week, she'll be back on her regular schedule _ Tuesday through
Saturday with the herd, and 16 hours straight, on Saturday night
and Sunday, as an X-ray technician at Harris Methodist. Then she
will work an additional four hours sometime during the week at a
temporary agency.
</P>
<P>
   She also sees to the care and feeding of her family and their
five horses. Daughters Christy and Melinda, son Bryan and husband
Gerry all help.
</P>
<P>
   It is a grueling agenda, but Cannon said she has never feared
hard work and long hours. She is doing it with the blessing and
support of her family, and she is loving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' she said, looking out over the herd, ``this is my
break job. This is like a vacation. I'm not like some of the guys
who grew up doing this kind of work. I don't take it for granted.
I'm just so pleased to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
