<SLUG> BC-LIVERMORE-LAYOFFS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYOFFS EXPECTED AT NUCLEAR LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hundreds of people are expected to lose their
jobs as a Cold War program to use lasers for developing nuclear
fuel is scrapped at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs could affect as many as 500 employees of the lab and
its contractors. A decision on layoffs is expected by the end of
summer at the federal facility that employs 8,000 people east of
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The doomed project is the Atomic Vapor Laser Isotope Separation
project, or AVLIS, that aimed to use lasers to find easier ways to
generate fissionable materials for nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   The company that operates the AVLIS facility at Livermore
concluded that the project is not an economically viable way to
generate nuclear fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the AVLIS project after 26 years or research means
that Livermore's future _ highly uncertain since the end of the
Cold War _ is increasingly dependent on one glamorous project, the
National Ignition Facility, planned to be the world's bigger laser.
</P>
<P>
   The mega-laser should be finished by 2003, lab officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the AVLIS program, scientists fire big lasers at vaporized
uranium in order to separate it into isotopes, forms of an element
with different weights but closely related chemical properties.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to figure out cost-effective ways to generate
enriched uranium, which has a high concentration of isotopes called
uranium-235, ideal for commercial nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Once an exciting frontier in nuclear research, AVLIS has fallen
on hard times because of the collapse of the Soviet Union and the
abundance of fissionable materials _ such as uranium _ from
dismantled nuclear weapons and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Also, sales of nuclear fuel have fallen short of early,
optimistic projections, because of strong public opposition to the
construction of new nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Livermore officials managed to corral the United States
Enrichment Corp., a private company established by the government,
into continuing the AVLIS project. With corporate offices in
Bethesda, Md., and a research site at Livermore, the company's goal
was to establish an AVLIS production plant by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, the company itself has made the decision to
can the AVLIS project, despite Livermore's desire to continue it,
said Livermore spokesman Jeff Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided it was not commercially viable to continue
research into AVLIS. ... They felt that even if all the science
succeeded, it would still not be commercially viable to produce
nuclear fuel with this technology,''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500 people working on AVLIS at Livermore, 200 are
Livermore employees. The rest work for private contractors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
