<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEOS FOR DADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Father's Day around the corner and the NBA
playoffs in full swing, there are a number of new videos that would
make fun gifts _ provided Dad likes sports.
</P>
<P>
   First up is ``Michael Jordan: His Airness'' (listed at $19.95).
Mike may be retired, but only from the court _ the promotional
bandwagon marches on. ``His Airness'' covers Jordan's life from
childhood to his final championship in 1998. The documentary
includes footage from his high school days to his time under
legendary coach Dean Smith at the University of North Carolina to
triumphs with the Chicago Bulls. What becomes evident through all
this is Jordan's undiminished desire to be the best. A number of
NBA greats, including Magic Johnson and Isiah Thomas, give
testimony to that, but former Celtic star Bill Russell may have
expressed it best, saying the reason Jordan sustained his level of
excellence was because ``he was determined to be Michael Jordan
every night.'' Despite what seems like undue adulation, it's hard
to argue with the man's accomplishments, and ``His Airness'' is a
fitting and entertaining tribute.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan and a few others like Johnson are models of
top-level consistency, the NBA is filled with players who _ despite
outlandish salaries _ do not show up to play every night. Yet at
any given moment, many of these well-conditioned and talented
athletes can perform jaw-dropping feats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA's 100 Greatest Plays'' ($14.95) compiles some of the
most spectacular plays in basketball history. The 100 plays are
broken down into 10 categories, including: buzzer beaters, dunks,
steals, hustle plays, alley-oops, blocks, moves, assists, clutch
and teamwork plays.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the players involved include Johnson, Larry Bird, Julius
(Dr. J) Erving, Russell, Wilt Chamberlain and a couple of current
Lakers _ Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a music video ``Slam Dunk (Da Funk)'' performed by
the recording group Five, featuring other great moments.
</P>
<P>
   The way Kobe and Shaq are playing, though, you won't see them in
the next version of ``Greatest NBA Finals Moments'' ($14.95). You
!ital!will!off! see plenty of former Lakers involved, however.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Johnson _ filling in at center for an injured Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar in the sixth game of the finals _ took L.A. to the
championship with a spectacular 42-point performance. On the other
hand, the Lakers of Jerry West, Elgin Baylor and Chamberlain (three
hall of famers) were upset in 1969 and 1970. In 1969, it was by an
old Boston Celtic team with Russell in his last hurrah, and the
next year it was by an undermanned New York Knicks team led by an
injured center, Willis Reed.
</P>
<P>
   If hoops isn't your thing, baseball season is also in full
swing. ``Major League Baseball: Generations of Heroes'' ($19.95)
compares seven groups of players such as power pitchers Nolan Ryan
and Roger Clemens and Giants Willie Mays and Barry Bonds or
home-run hitters Babe Ruth and Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   As any sports fan knows, it's difficult to compare athletes from
different eras, especially baseball with its long tradition. But
fans like to talk and speculate, and this video is fun in that it
can help fuel the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Dad prefers bruising checks and slap shots, you
can give him a rain check until July 16 when ``The Official 1999
NHL Stanley Cup Championship Video'' ($19.98) will be out. It's
already been a bruising and sensational playoffs. Now the finals
between the Buffalo Sabres and the Dallas Stars promise to be
spectacular. (Did I mention I'm from a certain upstate New York
city? Sabres in six.)
</P>
<P>
   If sports isn't your dad's thing, maybe space is. Originally
broadcast in April and May 1998, the epic miniseries ``From the
Earth to the Moon'' (six tapes, $89.92) cost HBO $68 million.
Hosted by executive producer Tom Hanks, the miniseries chronicles
the entire history of NASA's Apollo space program from 1961 to
1972. Each episode is devoted to a crucial aspect of the space
program.
</P>
<P>
   The production has a terrific cast, good writing and talented
directors, and Hanks' well-known enthusiasm for space exploration
is seen throughout every program. Though it is flat at times, the
series leaves you with a deep appreciation of NASA's monumental
exploits. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
