<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-WILEY-COX     06-11 1697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-WILEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Politicking for the Lord
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buena Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   First Southern Baptist Church on Western Avenue in this Orange
County town is a long way culturally and geographically from the
home country of the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But when its minister, the Rev. Wiley Drake, flies into Atlanta
tonight for next week's annual meeting of ``messengers'' of the
15.7 million-member denomination, he plans to make his mark.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, 55, a former rodeo cowboy, is armed with a briefcase full
of resolutions and motions to put before his fellow Southern
Baptists. He'll ask them to tell the president and Congress to quit
``violating people's Second Amendment right to bear arms'' by
supporting gun control. He wants to condemn a report published by
the American Psychological Association that he says is trying to
``water down pedophilia.'' And he'll try to get Baptists to demand
prayer and Bibles back in schools after shootings in Littleton,
Colo., and Conyers.
</P>
<P>
   There will be at least one more, but he's not saying what it
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want them to know it's coming,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For Drake, a steel-haired preacher known for his suspenders and
patriotic ties, the paperwork is just business as usual. In recent
conventions, Drake has been the man behind _ or in front of _ some
of the Southern Baptist Convention's most publicized votes.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, whose church is mere miles from Disneyland, introduced
the idea of a boycott of the Disney company in 1996. A year later,
when a convention committee recommended that Baptists not patronize
the company's theme parks or retail outlets, Drake moved from the
floor that the boycott be extended to all Disney outlets and
subsidiaries. His amendment passed overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Drake tried to go further by suggesting that the SBC
change plans for its 2000 meeting, scheduled for Orlando. The
convention's Executive Committee will recommend against a change at
the meeting next week. But Drake does not think the issue is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1998 _ while introducing resolutions on everything from
property control to abortion _ Drake tried to persuade the SBC to
call on Clinton's home church in Arkansas to discipline the
president for his stance on civil rights protection for homosexual
federal employees. The measure failed by only 66 votes of more than
2,000 cast.
</P>
<P>
   Drake _ who introduced five of 27 resolutions and two of 27
motions before the SBC convention last year, typical of the last
few years _ is a ``very active participant,'' said the Rev. Bill
Merrell, vice president for convention relations.
</P>
<P>
   Although he says he operates from his sincere convictions, Drake
admits enjoying the sport of politicking. ``There's nothing more
political than Southern Baptists,'' he says with relish. ``You've
got to go to Washington, D.C., to get more political than Southern
Baptists. But I'm glad we're the way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   'Made promise to God'
</P>
<P>
   Drake doesn't have to wait for his annual denominational meeting
for controversy. He has plenty of that on his home turf here in
Buena Park. In fact, he is a convicted criminal.
</P>
<P>
   This theological fundamentalist was found guilty in 1997 of four
counts of violating city ordinances for allowing homeless people to
sleep in a covered, screened patio behind the church and camp in
its parking lot. He is appealing the convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Drake's congregation of about 100 souls officially
dedicated a temporary building, made up of modular units, to serve
as a shelter until a more permanent facility can be constructed.
After making the makeshift building handicapped-accessible and
adding a sprinkler system and fire alarms, Drake was recently
granted an occupancy permit by the city of Buena Park. He is hoping
that now the local courts will remove an injunction that prohibits
use of the building for housing.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it wasn't already full to the brim of homeless men and
women. ``Up to this point, we were occupying the building
illegally,'' Drake freely admits.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he says he believes he was inspired by God to persuade
Baptists to boycott Disney, Drake thinks he was clearly shown by
his maker that he was supposed to take care of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   He tells a story he has told many times: Drake had come to Buena
Park in 1987 planning to build up a large congregation and
eventually run for the presidency of the Southern Baptist
Convention. On a crisp November morning in 1989, he walked onto the
grounds to find a dirty, drunken man curled up by the heat vent.
The man smelled of urine, and Drake was disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally grabbed him by his shoulders and shook him,'' said
Drake. ``How dare he come onto God's property drunk!''
</P>
<P>
   The man staggered away and Drake entered the church, where, he
says, he threw his Bible down in anger. It fell open to the book of
Matthew and Jesus' words, ``As you did it to one of the least of
these ... you did it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord seemed to be saying, `You've just kicked me off your
property,''' he says. ``I made a promise to God to never kick
anybody off this property as long as they were sincerely seeking
help. My second promise was to stop trying to build a church and do
my best to minister to the needs of the people he sent.''
</P>
<P>
   For Drake, the moment was one of a series of epiphanies that
have shaped his life.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam conversion
</P>
<P>
   Born between Hope and Magnolia, Ark., a few miles from Bill
Clinton, he was one of six children of an oil field worker and a
housewife who were casual churchgoers at best. After repeating the
ninth grade, he dropped out of high school to join a traveling
rodeo and circus. He joined the Navy at 17 and married at 18.
</P>
<P>
   He met God in Vietnam. He sat beside a fatally injured young
Marine who begged several times, ``Please don't let me die,'' and
then said his last words, ``I don't want to go to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That haunted me for several days,'' said Drake. He talked
about his feelings to a fellow enlistee who was a committed
Christian. ``That's how I really came to know the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake became part of a group of sailors who spent port time
doing mission work.
</P>
<P>
   After discharge in the late 1960s, with a wife and two children,
he enrolled in college and worked as a youth minister at a small
church in Huntington Beach, Calif. On the side, he spent time with
the young people crowding into Southern California as part of the
so-called Jesus Movement.
</P>
<P>
   With a degree in communications from California State University
at Long Beach in 1972, he headed for the largest seminary in the
Southern Baptist Convention, Southwestern in Fort Worth, Texas. But
after seminary, instead of becoming a full-time minister, he took a
higher-paying job marketing oil equipment to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   He was living high _ literally _ in New Jersey, ``strung out on
a little bit of everything,'' when he lost his job in 1979. He
parked his silver-gray Cadillac around the corner from the welfare
office to walk to pick up checks for his family, which now included
four children. After 14 months of unemployment, he found himself
lying drunk on the floor of a room at the Holiday Inn in Baton
Rouge, La., where he had gone for a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord seemed to say to me, `Either get your act together or
I'm going to end your life,''' he said. He caught the first flight
back to New Jersey, sold his five-bedroom house and moved his
family into a trailer in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   He took a job as a groundskeeper at Camp Canfield, a Southern
Baptist camp near the Louisiana border. When a 30-member church
nearby needed a preacher, he gave up the camp job and became a
minister, also driving a school bus, working as a stock boy in a
small store, and pumping gas to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, a bigger church called him to be pastor, and he moved
to Atlanta, Texas. He made friends with the new managing editor of
the local paper, The Atlanta Citizens Journal, and began writing a
weekly church roundup and commentary. He also began attending the
annual Southern Baptist Convention, writing articles for small
papers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, sitting in the office of his California church,
``our hearts were always out here,'' as was his wife's family. So
when he heard First Southern Baptist Church in Buena Park was
looking for a pastor, he moved to Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   'I had nowhere to go'
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of poor people are glad he did. His church's shelter
can house 52 people, with separate dormitory areas for men and
women. The church's clothes closet, furniture supply and food
pantry offer assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Core, 37, has stayed at the shelter for about six months.
Sitting in a folding chair on a walkway, she lifts a cigarette to
her mouth with a tattoo-covered hand. ``I wouldn't have a place.
I'd be in the street,'' she said matter-of-factly. Drake ``told me
when I came here he didn't turn anybody away.''
</P>
<P>
   Toby Chamness, 24, came about the same time. He admits to having
had a drug problem. ``I lost my job, got evicted and my truck got
stolen,'' he said. ``I had nowhere to go. I was living in a
Dumpster.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake, said Chamness, ``is a little too political for my taste,
but I have to admit he's doing a service.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Buena Park officials and Southern Baptist leaders would
probably agree.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Drake has been unnecessarily confrontational in an
effort to get attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel that the city was willing to work with him ... and
he just didn't want to follow any rules,'' Jim Miller, president
and CEO of another homeless shelter, told the Los Angeles Times
during Drake's criminal trial. ``Even the good Lord said you had to
obey civil authority, but maybe he didn't read that part.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Drake says the attention he gets is in the
interest of what's right, whether it's in a Southern California
courtroom or on the floor of the Southern Baptist Convention. And
he's just using the talent God gave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personality,'' he says, ``is as a scrapper and
rabble-rouser.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
