A1704 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-HOLOCAUST-CO     06-11 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-HOLOCAUST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Jewish Schindler' simply wants to forget
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Andre Steiner does not want to share his pain. He does
not want to relive his horror. He won't cry for you.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner simply wants to forget.
</P>
<P>
   And for 60 years, the courtly Atlanta architect did just that.
</P>
<P>
   He never told anyone that he was considered by many a ``Jewish
Oskar Schindler.'' He didn't even share his story with his two
sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to push my emotions as far back as possible,'' is
how Steiner, 89, described his post-Holocaust philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner's isolation changed when his two sons, George and Peter,
persuaded him to return to his homeland in Eastern Europe. The
result of their journey is captured in a fascinating documentary,
``Andre's Lives,'' scheduled to be shown at the Carter Center on
Wednesday as part of the 23rd Annual Atlanta International Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-day festival, which begins today, features experimental
films and documentaries, many by Atlanta filmmakers. Films will be
shown at several Atlanta venues, including the High Museum of Art,
the Carter Center, and various theaters in Midtown and Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre's Lives,'' produced and directed by Atlanta native Brad
Lichtenstein and funded in large measure by the Atlanta Jewish
Federation and dozens of local investors, is a 55-minute
documentary that explores a form of Holocaust denial _ the kind
that springs from the victims themselves. While many documentaries
are filled with anguished survivors pouring out their stories,
Steiner isn't interested in assuming that role.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner saved the lives of 7,000 Slovak Jews by arranging for
them to work in labor camps instead of being transported to death
camps.But Steiner doesn't want to be called a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his refusal to acknowledge the impact of the Holocaust
on his life provides the film's emotional center.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner's denial is captured most powerfully when he returns to
the mountain village where he last saw his parents. Too frail to
scramble across a looming mountain range, they were captured by
troops in league with the Nazis and later murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner nonchalantly scans the village, shrugs and tells his
sons that he recalls little of the last time he saw his parents
because he refuses to live in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Choked with emotion, Steiner's eldest son, Peter, asks,
``Doesn't it mean anything that you are here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it means to me that this was one of the reasons I
refused to come back,'' Steiner snaps. ``I'm a fool that I did it.
Should I start to cry 60 years after I left my parents?''
</P>
<P>
   Steiner storms off, leaving his sons staring silently at one
another.
</P>
<P>
   His actions may seem puzzling, but there are many Holocaust
survivors like Steiner who don't feel a moral obligation to
remember the past, Lichtenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there are a large number of survivors who keep it
inside, who don't want to talk it over,'' Lichtenstein said. ``This
has consequences for subsequent generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Those consequences are evident in the documentary. Through much
of the film, Steiner remains emotionally withdrawn from his two
sons.
</P>
<P>
   And at the film's end, he wonders if the homecoming was a good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was better to simply forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive images which I had are spoiled now,'' says
Steiner, sitting alone on a train traveling through his homeland.
``Now I have a lot of negative ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
