<HEADER>
A1713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN12-CO     06-11 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: In Virginia, I'm an expert on
Texas
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX STATION, Va. -- There's nothing like aristocratic
Virginia, land of huge country estates and narrow country roads,
where wealth and good breeding go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   But here I am, foot in mouth, engaged in cocktail conversation
at a weekend party where I was invited as a friend of a friend in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And all of a sudden everybody seems interested in what I have to
say.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is George W. Bush, of whom I am expected to possess
insight of an intellectual perspective.
</P>
<P>
   They don't know me very well, do they?
</P>
<P>
   No matter. They want to know what I think.
</P>
<P>
   The host has made that much clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be interested to hear what you think,'' he announced, and
everyone turned in my direction.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now, then there, I began, feeling very much like Dan
Quayle caught in the glare of headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, I think George W. Bush is his father's son, and
what you've already seen is what you'll get a second helping of --
a nice guy who can finish first, at least the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   I was about to add, Ahem, when, thank goodness, a proper lady
interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But how can he be against a hate crimes bill?'' she said, her
faced pained. ``And what about gun legislation in Texas?''
</P>
<P>
   Before I could answer, thank goodness, she continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you what my 9-year-old son said, just the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the car and the radio news was on. We don't let him
watch the news on television or read the newspapers. Even the
headlines are so dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is what he said, and keep in mind, this is coming
from a 9-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mother,' he said, `do you know what I would do if I had Bill
Gates's money? I would buy up all the guns in the world and all of
the gun factories, and then I would melt them down and use that to
build a cathedral to peace.'''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the proper lady had to pause in her account, such
was the emotion of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the mouths of babes ...'' she finally managed, her eyes
glistening.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I ask you,'' she said. ``Why can't we do exactly that? Why
can't we simply do away with all the guns? I ask you.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, she wasn't really asking me. It was more of a
question for the whole world.
</P>
<P>
   Better to let the whole world deal with it at some point in the
future, preferably after I had left the party.
</P>
<P>
   However ...
</P>
<P>
   If they had really wanted to know about the governor of Texas,
who well might be president of all these United States, as
pertaining to (1) hate crimes and (2) gun legislation, I would say
this:
</P>
<P>
   1. More voters disapprove of homosexuals than approve of them.
Politicians like George W. Bush will conduct themselves
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Gun legislation in places like Texas is most likely that
which would limit the liability of gun manufacturers. I don't
expect a whole lot more nationwide, once the gunsmoke has cleared
from our school yards.
</P>
<P>
   But I never got around to saying that. To do so under the
circumstances would have been dreadful, almost as much so as
exposing children to newspaper headlines.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
