<HEADER>
A1716 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-SHAGGED-H     06-11 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SHAGGED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND, STRANGELOVE MERGE IN `AP2' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought you were too gun shy to love again in the
long, lifeless shadow of ``The Phantom Menace,'' along comes the
exhaustingly jokey ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a special brand of excitement to mine giddy laughs just
from the New Line Cinema logo floating into place while techno diva
Goldie sings ``Dr. Evil'' on the soundtrack, then send you reeling
seconds later with a ``Long ago in a galaxy far, far away''
scroll-up that explains what Powers (Mike Myers) has been up to
since we saw him last.
</P>
<P>
   He's been doing the nasty with his ladylove Vanessa (Elizabeth
Hurley), who suddenly turns out to be a femmebot assassin sent by
his nemesis, Dr. Evil (Myers again). Her quick destruction frees
Austin to swing again, and allows Myers to do a supremely inspired
``Benny Hill'' remix of the Oscar streaker.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the film rollicks on a similar plane of winking verve,
unrelenting acuteness and observant shenanigans. We learn, for
instance, that the only entity cagey and determined enough to free
Dr. Evil from deep-freeze incarceration is ``The Jerry Springer
Show,'' on which the bald villain with his aquiline nose and
girly-man body language is reunited with his unloved son Scott
(Seth Green) in an episode titled ``My Father Wants to Take Over
the World.''
</P>
<P>
   In a jealous bid to foil Powers, Evil has a time machine built
and sends an obese Scotsman called Fat Bastard (Myers one more
time) back to 1969 to swipe Powers' ``mojo'' _ it's the essence of
sex that comes in a glittering, velvety liquid. Instantly rendered
impotent in mid-shag with a vamp called Ivana Humpalot (Kristen
``3rd Rock'' Johnson), Austin has to get on the groovy train to '69
London to stop him. There, he's reunited with his comely sidekick
Felicity Shagwell (Heather Graham, falling coif-first from the
Barbarella-Bardot beauty tree and hitting every Wonderbra on the
way down).
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the film sinks its teeth into mass-market,
industrial- strength consumerism without ignoring the fact that
``Austin Powers'' has willed itself into a commercial franchise
simply by high-profiling its return as if it were a Second Coming
of its own _ but a knowing one. ``AP2'' shares its audience's
cynicism and contempt of corporate capitalism, while remaining
self-conscious of the hypocrisy involved in skewering brand names _
particularly because AP officially is a market force in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Evil's lair is a Starbucks Space Needle, with actual
latte-slinging staff; a compartment in Austin's Shaguar announces,
``You've got mail!''; and when a soon-to-be-hilariously-abused
shagamuffin with the appellation Robin Swallows (Gia Carrides)
inquires about Austin's heinie, he whips out a Heine instead.
</P>
<P>
   Are these acts of damnation for the unavoidable omnipresence of
``stuff''? Or are they just smirking, snarling, but explicit
product placements? Both.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' _ directed by Jay
Roach with cagey sarcasm and precision pacing _ that much more
difficult to pin down is that in this virtual climate, it's
plugging real stuff with a heightened preoccupation with the fake.
The film (written by Myers and Michael McCullers), more
successfully than the first, is a collection of arbitrary sketches,
bits and improvs jammed into a locker room-style variety show
masquerading as some semblance of a narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's inherently real or original, from Mini Me (Verne
Troyer), Dr. Evil's bite-size clone, and Xerox soundtrack acts such
as the Monkees, the Guess Who and Lenny Kravitz right down to the
wrong, if ravishing, Graham, who seems so psyched to hang with
Myers that she can't wipe the smile from her lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``AP2'' has had to break down into a pastiche mess to weather
times in which an allusive, pop-reference-dependent text succeeds
better than none at all. ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' is Bond with
its tongue piercing its cheek. It's ``Blow-up'' with juice, ``Dr.
Strangelove'' hollowed out and colored in, ``Shaft'' with
whiteners, a one-man ``Hard Day's Night,'' you name it.
</P>
<P>
   But, to be sure, this is meaningless, feverish, paradoxical and
mostly smart sniping. Myers is its Peter Sellers-ish master of
ceremonies with a cantankerously funny Mel Brooks vision.
</P>
<P>
   There are large traces of fat around what Myers does _ he riffs
as if there were a bebop wing of screen comedy _ but he has
Sellers' genius for losing himself beneath unflattering get-ups
without compromising the exuberant sharpness of his lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   And only Frau, Mindy Sterling's delirious German frightmare,
threatens to make Myers behave. It'd be too much to bear if he had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
