<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, June 12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories on the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Some 150 to 500 Russian troops move
into Yugoslavia from Bosnia after U.S.-Russia talks break down.
Strobe Talbott, the U.S. envoy, flying from Moscow to Brussels,
turns around in mid-air and returns to Moscow for further talks. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Whiteman AFB, Mo.) _ President Clinton visits
the base where the B-2 bombers flew from during the air war in
Yugoslavia. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Madeleine K. Albright, who
had made the return of the ethnic Albanian refugees the major
mission of the Kosovo war, met face to face with them for the first
time Friday. She hugged some of them, shook hands, and as she
passed along a rope line holding back exuberant crowds, shouted:
``You'll be going home.'' By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ The scene from the Albanian
border where planning continues for what is expected to be the
chaotic re-entry of refugees to their homes and villages. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FORCE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Peacekeeping force
developments; convoys of Italian and British troops are on the move
and could enter Kosovo at any time. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Gniljane, Yugoslavia) _ A scene-stter from the
town where the U.S. peacekeeping forces will be based. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-POPE (Warsaw) _ Pope John Paul II pays tribute to Polish
Jews who died in the Holocaust and addresses Parliament. Earlier,
at a reception broadcast on Polish national television, the chief
rabbi of Poland refers to John Paul II as ``Mr. Pope'' and asks him
to take down the last cross at Auschwitz. By Alesandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-WARSHIPS (Tokyo) _ South Korean patrol boats bumped three
North Korean vessels Friday, forcing them out of disputed waters on
the fourth day of a tense armed standoff. After retreating, four
North Korean warships sailed back into the disputed zone,
confronting eight South Korean navy ships, South Korea's defense
ministry said. By Nicholas Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-LIBYA (United Nations) _ United States holds its first
meeting with Libya in more than a decade, but says sanctions are
not likely to be lifted for some time.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUKARNO (Jakarta) _ The ghost of Sukarno has hung
heavily over Indonesia this week, as the country held its first
democratic elections in more than four decades. The party of
Sukarno's 52-year-old daughter, Megawati Sukarnoputri, seems headed
for a clear victory in the parliamentary vote _ raising the
possibility another Sukarno may be the next leader of Indonesia. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANGELES-CALLGIRLS (Los Angeles) _ Police say they have busted
one of the most elaborate call girl rings since they cracked the
case of the ``Hollywood Madam,'' Heidi Fleiss, six years ago. Jody
Diane ``Babydoll'' Gibson, reported to be a former competitor of
Fleiss, was arrested Tuesday after a 10-month investigation. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-SCOTUS-REACT (Chicago) _ A day after the Supreme Court
struck down a Chicago law that banned loitering by suspected gang
members, people in the neighborhoods, where the law had been well
received, were angry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ Many amendments are offered to gun
control legislation by the noon deadline, illustrating the
divisiveness and confusion over the House effort to pass
legislation. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-TESTING (Washington) _ The Department of Education's draft
of recommendations on how schools can avoid discrimination suits if
standardized tests such as the SAT's, produce racially disparate
results has drawn the ire of conservatives. Critics claim that in
proferring the advice, the Department is telling schools not to use
such tests at all. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-VIRUS (San Francisco) _ Developments in the effort to
contain the venomous Explore.Zip computer worm.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY (Undated) _ The Labor Department reported that producer
prices rose just two-tenths of a percent in May, as predicted, down
sharply from the advance of five-tenths of a percent in April. In
another key measure, the Commerce Department reported that retail
sales jumped 1 percent in May, compared with a rise of four-tenths
in April, which was revised upward from only one-tenth of a
percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BANK-AMERICA-SHARE (Undated) _ Bank of America, one of the
country's largest banks, said it would not share customer
information _ particularly credit card account numbers _ with
telemarketers amid a growing crackdown by federal and state
regulators on potentially abusive practices. By Timothy J. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The Japanese Government unveiled a laundry
list of proposals to make the job market more dynamic, speed
corporate restructuring and create more than 700,000 jobs but did
not say how much it would spend on the program, leaving the plan's
potential power to spur the economy somewhat mysterious. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis column.
</P>
