<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-LESSONS-BOS &LR;      06-11 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-LESSONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIA IS TESTAMENT TO DIFFICULTY OF KOSOVO MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSTAR, Bosnia _ The old bridge across the River Neretva was one
of those places where history spoke for itself. At the bridge, as
at the Great Wall of China, the Pyramids, or the Western Wall in
Jerusalem, the very stones had a pulse. You could feel it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the graceful, white-limestone arch, erected by Ottoman Turks
in the mid-16th century and blasted from its foundations by Bosnian
Croats in the late 20th, lies in pieces on a platform, waiting to
be reconstructed by one of the scores of international governments
and donor agencies trying to put Bosnia back together again.
</P>
<P>
   Physical reconstruction almost certainly will succeed. Such
projects have flowered all over the country since 1995, when the
Dayton accords, a peace agreement brokered by the United States,
put an end to the most savage and destructive fighting Europe had
seen since World War II. But restoring the pulse of the place? That
is a different matter, and may not be possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia is full of cautionary tales and lessons for the Americans
and Europeans who, in the wake of the NATO bombing of Serbia, are
setting out to restore 1.4 million ethnic Albanians to their homes
in Kosovo, and to reconstruct their lives in Serbia's southernmost
province. Some lessons tend toward the philosophical, but most are
practical.
</P>
<P>
   Above all is the need for speed. Close behind that comes the
need for a competent civil administration, and the need for the
military to perform some vital civilian tasks to get the return and
reconstruction effort off on the right foot. None of these things
were given immediate high priority in Bosnia, and as a result the
recovery effort has struggled, at best, despite major international
investments of funds and personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international presence here is dysfunctional,'' said
Jacques Klein, a top-ranking official in the Office of the High
Representative, which administers the Dayton accords, in an
interview Thursday. ``We do not want to repeat in Kosovo what we
have done here.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein, a former US Air Force general and veteran diplomat, won
praise for overseeing the reversion of Eastern Slavonia from Serbia
to Croatia before taking on the number two job in Bosnia. What will
be most critically needed in Kosovo, he said, is ``a strong, single
chain of command, with a clearly defined mission, and with
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   A rule of thumb, supported by research by United Nations
agencies, is that no more than 50 percent of refugees can be
expected to return home once they have been away from their former
lives for a year. Crops are missed, social circles break down, and
children engage in new lives. With each additional year away, the
number likely to return falls again by half.
</P>
<P>
   Because this reality was not quickly taken to heart, ``we have
to work very hard in Bosnia for small results,'' said Andy
Bearpark, the chief official for refugee return and reconstruction
under Klein.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, while jealousies and turf wars are to be
expected in any major international relief effort, ``I have never
seen it as bad'' as in the Balkans, where many of the nations and
relief agencies involved have long histories and private agendas
with local political groups.
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to find the results of this situation.
</P>
<P>
   High on a dry eastern hillside in Mostar, just past the pile of
stones that used to be the Orthodox Cathedral, a large yellow van
is parked against the wall of a former parish building. From a
distance, it looks like a workmen's van, and suggests the church is
under reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth. The van contains the
worldly possessions of a middle-aged couple who had an apartment in
the neighborhood before the war. Family members made a gift of the
van when the couple was told to get out of Germany. They are
settling more and more deeply into the rubble, building a laundry
area here, a bathing area there, and becoming increasingly bitter
at the reconstruction work going on around them that they do not
understand and that will do nothing for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West gives all this money to Bosnia and Herzegovina, and
the people have none of it,'' the man said, spitting in the dust.
``We can't do anything. We just sit here.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in the valley, Jelka Kebo, director of the Mostar Culture
Center, which sponsors multiethnic programs for youth and women, is
facing problems of a bureaucratic nature.
</P>
<P>
   The center had some early triumphs, including a youth radio
station and educational programs, that won support from the
European Community and some foundations. But the support is spotty,
and can vanish when she needs it most.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the center is the lead local agency for the Mostar
Summer Festival, a 20-year-old event that has assumed heightened
importance since the war because it attracts the whole community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received a letter from the Council of Europe that they will
be donors,'' Kebo said. ``We have not received a penny, and the
festival is July 1 _ unless we cancel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mato Zovkic, the Roman Catholic vicar general of Sarajevo,
said that ``the foreign assistance is far too complicated, both
that which comes from foreign governments and that which comes from
NGOs,'' or nongovernmental organizations. ``They all look very
busy, but there is overlap, duplication, and not very much happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the need for their presence,'' Zovkic said. ``Without
them there would be war. But I wish there were more coordination,
more efficiency. Instead, they struggle for their own visions of
Bosnia. . . . You USA people can hardly grasp why we insist so much
on our ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe and the United States, people tend to speak of
repairing societies here which have been damaged by the bitter
years of war. But if the goal is to have democracy and market
economies, ``creating,'' rather than rebuilding, is the correct way
to describe the goal.
</P>
<P>
   There was never democracy, in Bosnia or in Kosovo, before the
onset of the wars in the early 1990s, and no free economy above the
level of local markets. Democracy and open economies, if that is
what there is to be, will have to built through education and
training efforts that easily could take decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of democracy and democratic traditions are the
biggest problems'' in the region, said Jakob Finci, director of the
Soros Foundation in Bosnia. ``You cannot bring democracy here by
NATO and OSCE,'' the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe. ``The historic memory is of the communist days, when the
decisions were all made in the central committee, and then everyone
in Parliament just raised their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Making democratic processes and an open economy priorities would
require steps that many who are preparing to launch the relief
operation in Kosovo would rather avoid.
</P>
<P>
   These include such sticky subjects as detaching Kosovo from
Yugoslavia until Yugoslavia becomes a democracy, and disarming the
Kosovo Liberation Army, which is not a democracy-friendly force nor
likely to surrender its weapons willingly. Western leaders will be
tempted to accept a few truckloads of weapons and declare the KLA
disarmed, knowing full well that it is not, rather than risk losing
soldiers disarming it forcibly.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting fuzzy thinking about these or other goals, said Albert
Rohan, secretary general of the Austrian Foreign Ministry, is a
formula for failure. ``Better for Kosovo to have the plans very
strictly and clearly defined.''
</P>
<P>
   A much more serious concern, according to a well-informed
diplomatic source in Bosnia, is whether some of the most important
players in the soon-to-begin Kosovo effort are willing to address
some of the highest priority needs.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, a lack of clarity between the United
Nations and the OSCE about who is to do what in Kosovo, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, military leaders have been told their troops will have
to perform some basic civilian functions, such as setting up water
supplies and electrical systems, and they are unhappy about it.
That leaves Western civilian leaders worried about whether the
military will be prepared to do those tasks within the next few
days, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the source said, the NATO alliance has put the European
Commission in charge of reconstruction, and many relief veterans in
Bosnia believe ``you could hardly find a less competent agency to
do a job of this magnitude with any speed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
