<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1739 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-BESIEGED-     06-11 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BESIEGED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTOLUCCI'S GORGEOUS LETDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Told with the distorted ambiguity and hypnotic poetry of a
dream, ``Besieged'' is a jolt of restless sleeping. But who's
dreaming here?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the African woman (Thandie Newton) and British man (David
Thewlis) forced into a tryst in order to make smooth beauty out of
a sexual pairing of the Third World and Imperialist England? Or is
it Bernardo Bertolucci, who's directing with a scaled-down
litheness he rarely displays?
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci always has fashioned political statements out of
coitus, but in ``Besieged'' he's working under a spell that has him
marginalizing the polemical circumstances at stake. His tendency to
half-explain characters isn't mystifying here, it's careless, and
offering the fair-skinned Newton as the symbol-delegate of central
African civil unrest, an emerging Third World and an object of love
situates the film perfectly in America's obsession with
light-skinned, mixed-race deities as the lone shade black women
come in.
</P>
<P>
   Every frame of ``Besieged,'' Bertolucci's 17th film, bleeds with
a gorgeousness and dire radiance that serves as a willful
distraction from the hulking, wanton fetishization and eerie
ignorance that Bertolucci distorts as subtle eroticism.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that after the tourism on display throughout ``The
Sheltering Sky'' (North Africa) and ``Stealing Beauty'' (Tuscany),
he'd have gotten the sightseeing-over-storytelling out of his
system. But the film blinks back and forth between an unspecified
(read: fictional) African country and Rome. It's also afflicted
with that dangerous, reckless, standard mythologizing of Africa as
a nameless monolith of political turmoil, symbolic home of an
emaciated nomadic troubadours and an indigenous people in perpetual
strife.
</P>
<P>
   How Shandurai (Newton) got from her African village _ where her
schoolteacher-political insurgent husband is jailed _ to the Roman
villa owned by Kinsky (Thewlis, clean-shaven, mostly sane, nearly
unrecognizable), a lonely English composer, is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   In order to obtain her permit to study medicine in Italy, she
cleans his home, dusts his statues, makes his bed, hems his pants.
She's haunted by bad sleeps and the uncertainty of her husband's
fate. In the hours when she's at school, he drifts into her
quarters, touching her Kente nightgown. When she's around, he
impales her with his gaze. Then, in a cumbersome, outlandish
confession, he declares that he's in love with her, promising that
if she reciprocates he'll take her back to Africa, the location of
her traumatized state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   What umbrage Shandurai takes at his declaration erodes as she
finds _ rather, the film finds for her _ a reason to begin to love
him back. Had Bertolucci, who co-adapted James Lasdun's short story
with partner Clare Peploe, given psychological gravity to this
narrative bouquet instead of fondling its petals, perhaps the fact
that Kinsky's drowning in a colonial obsession with his African
cleaning lady would exude more heat than consternation.
</P>
<P>
   That Shandurai loves him back is an act of sheer volition, not a
plausible decision of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't people; they're puppets, regardless of what Newton
and Thewlis' mannered performances say.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci is clearly out to have a good, lyric time,
accelerating the frame speed, slowing it down with complete
disregard to implications of his human subjects and how they
behave. ``Besieged'' is simply looking for love, and if there is no
rapture in his script, then the sensuous confluence of Jacopo
Quadri's cutting and Fabio Cianchetti's photography will have to
hypnotically do.
</P>
<P>
   There's the not-so-vague suggestion that Bertolucci might be
trying to pull off one last tango between two forlorn strangers
colliding unexpectedly in a foreign country. But ``Besieged'' has
none of the physical sensuality of ``Last Tango in Paris'' _ it
doesn't aspire to. After 93 minutes, these lovers have lived a
wispy, minor life with unmined consequences in the time it takes to
finish a novella.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
