<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1740 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-PUNDITS-BOS &LR;      06-11 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-PUNDITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PUNDITS ARE CASUALTIES OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a few short weeks ago, the buzz on the Balkans was all bad.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of London was spreading a story that the United States
was seriously considering committing 90,000 troops to a ground war.
The conventional military wisdom resonating with the media was that
no one ever surrendered to an airplane. Public opinion polls
revealed decreasing support for the US role in the NATO campaign
and President Clinton's approval ratings were on a similar
southbound trajectory. Commentators, from the Brahmins of Beltway
punditry to distinguished former generals, were predicting gloom
and doom.
</P>
<P>
   Then on June 4, news of a possible peace agreement surfaced.
Suddenly everything changed, and the pundits popped the champagne.
``I think it's an enormous victory for Bill Clinton,'' said ABC's
Sam Donaldson. Fox News Channel's Morton Kondracke, who had warned
of a US defeat at the hands of a ``tin-pot dictator,'' reversed
course and said that Clinton had taken ``the biggest risk ... maybe
in his whole presidency,'' and emerged victorious.
</P>
<P>
   While the debate over what the United States has actually
accomplished in Yugoslavia may rage for months, the end of
hostilities has already claimed one casualty: the credibility of
talking heads and columnists who advocated either suing for peace
or escalating to a ground war while ignoring the possibility that
the bombing could lead to a settlement without US casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that as we approach the millennium,'' the Balkans
war ``is one of the first-class failures of Washington punditry,''
said Craig Crawford, executive editor of the Hotline political
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   What went so wrong with the chattering class? According to
military and media observers, the errant punditry is a result of
everything from misleading Pentagon leaks to Clinton's polarizing
impact on public policy to the failure to understand the evolving
realities of post-Cold War warfare. Perhaps most significantly,
there are also the media's own insistent demands for imprudent and
impatient commentary.
</P>
<P>
   In these days of the 24-hour cable news network, the shouting
heads declared the war over Kosovo lost in a matter of weeks. ``Day
27 and no end in sight'' was the opening line of an April CNN
``Crossfire'' show practically conceding defeat. The battle lines
quickly hardened between those who wanted to cut our losses and go
home and those who wanted to get tougher with Milosevic, with both
sides converging only around the consensus that NATO's bombing
strategy was a loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disaster for President Clinton and the country,''
declared syndicated columnist and CNN pundit Bob Novak. ``It is
astonishing that those who spent decades recounting the `lessons of
Vietnam' have themselves failed to heed those lessons,'' wrote
former defense secretary James Schlesinger. On a typical day,
people could read Washington Post columns with headlines such as
``Three mistakes,'' ``Bombing empty buildings,'' and ``Bumbling in
Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that what former ABC diplomatic correspondent
Barrie Dunsmore called this ``negative drumbeat'' began to pierce
public consciousness. Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup
Poll, said surveys showed that the public ``was fairly
pessimistic'' about the conflict and ``strongly'' believed that
ground troops were going to be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to know exactly what spawned those views, said
Newport, but ``the public is totally at the mercy of everything
they read and see.'' In an era when the Fox News Channel can air a
debate between one ``expert'' arguing that we pulverize Serbia in a
ground war and another suggesting we disarm its soldiers with
college scholarships, analysts say that much of what passes for
sage commentary is deliberately provocative, extreme, and
oversimplified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern television and modern news don't honor hesitation or
qualification,'' said Pew Research Center director Andy Kohut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the way the media beast works, complexity
and uncertainty don't play well,'' said Rob Leavitt, associate
director of New York University's Center for War, Peace, and the
News Media, decrying the trend for ``punditry to get worse'' with
every passing crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that not only has foreign policy debate become
increasingly politicized, but that Clinton's role as a lightning
rod _ particularly after the impeachment episode _ has further
polarized public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this town has gotten so obsessed with Bill Clinton's
personal success and failure that everything is filtered through
that prism,'' said Crawford. ``People have this difficulty in
examining issues in any logical way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain amount of skepticism that Clinton could get
something like this right,'' said Kondracke, who is also executive
editor of the Capitol Hill paper Roll Call. ``Nobody had confidence
that bombing would work . . . because the Pentagon generals were
leaking it out that bombing wouldn't work. . . . I just know how I
formed my opinion and I formed it on the basis of talking to
presumptive experts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed unusual, essentially the Pentagon challenging the
administration,'' said Leavitt, noting that the military was
``really using the the media to question what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impressive parade of military brass who showed up on
our TV screens (the American Journalism Review noted that Kosovo
did for the media careers of military analysts what the O. J. trial
did for lawyers), many of them fell into into the trap of reliving
the lessons of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last-war phenomenon ... was at play,'' noted Thomas
Patterson, the Bradlee Professor of Government and the Press at
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government. Commentators, he
added, were too caught up in the apparent lessons learned in Bosnia
and in the post-Gulf War attacks on Iraq, ``where it took a couple
of days of heightened hostilities to get people to the bargaining
table. ... This is situationally different. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the pundits were quick to argue _ and I
certainly was right there with them _ that you aren't going to
succeed without ground forces,'' said Richard Shultz, the director
of International Security Studies at Tufts University's Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy, who is still wary about the situation
in the Balkans. ``I think it's hard to live on the past lessons.
... War always has a degree of uncertainty to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
