</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CHARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIAN SCORNED FOR GOD-LESS PLEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ One of Canada's most controversial
politicians has been hurled into parliamentary purgatory for
demanding that references to God be banished from Canada's Charter
of Rights and Freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Svend Robinson, a member of national Parliament, stunned leaders
of every political party, including his own, and ignited anger
across Canada this week when he rose in the House of Commons, after
making sure plenty of journalists would be on hand, and read a
petition urging removal of a passage stating that Canada is
``founded upon principles that recognize the supremacy of God and
the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Robinson told the booing lower chamber, Canada should
be ``founded upon principles of intellectual freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The petition generated big headlines and angry responses from
other political leaders. ``What do we stand for in this country?
What are the values? What are the morals?'' demanded Parliament
member Randy White, like Robinson representing British Columbia.
``Every time you turn around, you see government slipping lower and
lower into the gutters of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is one of the brightest stars of the leftist New
Democratic Party. He is known as well for his unabashed love of the
limelight as for his passionate advocacy of gay rights and other
not-always-popular causes.
</P>
<P>
   By throwing down the gauntlet to God, he unloosed an unholy
ruckus that has roiled the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse than poor political judgment, it's absolutely
stupid,'' said Nelson Riis, a close political ally of Robinson,
fellow New Democrat, and also from British Columbia. ``We find it
to be disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   So did party leader Alexa McDonough of Nova Scotia, who busted
Robinson from the party's prestigious front bench seats in
Parliament, the roost of party leaders empowered to speak during
debate, to the far back row, an especially severe punishment for
Robinson since it obliges him to silence.
</P>
<P>
   The Charter of Rights and Freedoms is Canada's equivalent of the
Bill of Rights. The allusion to God makes no mention of
Christianity or any other faith.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was at first unrepentant, arguing that references to
the supremacy of God are `` discriminatory'' and ``offensive to
Canadians who are nonreligious or non-Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the much-chastened politician, who earlier in the
decade became the first Canadian parliamentarian to openly proclaim
his homosexuality, was reading from a different hymnal. ``I deeply
regret the pain and difficulty that my decision . . . has caused,''
he stated in a letter to McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also suddenly insisted that the petition did not
represent his personal view, but had been presented on behalf of
constituents. It is not unusual for members of Parliament to enter
petitions from constituents into the official record, but it is
usually done without fanfare by simply submitting the paperwork to
the house clerk.
</P>
<P>
   In his attack on the charter reference to God, Robinson not only
read the petition in an open session of Parliament but had made
sure that journalists were tipped off.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the New Democratic Party's founders included
religious activists who believed Christian morality should be
applied to politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has always been to have God in the
constitution,'' Riis said. ``It's a free country and you are
entitled to be stupid. But what Mr. Robinson did goes beyond
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Parliament delivered its disciplinary blow to Robinson the same
day that the federal government backed away from a proposal that
would have abolished the practice of swearing on the Bible before
giving court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Atheists in the country were angered by both moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned by the immense and all-encompassing intolerance of
this country,'' said Ray Blessin, an activist with the Humanist
Association of Canada. ``There's a huge nonreligious community in
Canada, and we object to the intrusion of God into our lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-11 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGUMENTS AGAINST WAR DIDN'T HOLD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The successful conclusion of the Kosovo caper deserves a look
backward at some of the most oft-repeated arguments against it.
</P>
<P>
   --``This war is not worth fighting,'' ``This is the wrong war,
in the wrong place,'' or ``These people have been killing each
other since the year 1369; let them sort it out.'' There was only
one alternative to NATO's bombing campaign: Let Slobodan Milosevic
get away with it, ending the bloodiest century in history with the
ethnic purging for which Hitler and Stalin are infamous.
</P>
<P>
   --``The NATO bombing will only worsen, not alleviate, the plight
of the Kosovar Albanians.'' If that were true, why do virtually all
of the Kosovars emphatically support the NATO air war? What about
the 100,000 Albanians who fled before the bombing began? What about
the 2,000 to 3,000 murdered before the first NATO bomb fell?
</P>
<P>
   --``The NATO coalition will fall apart.'' The treaty alliance's
50th anniversary fell awkwardly in the beginning of the elaborately
calibrated air war. President Clinton said Thursday that the
alliance ``is now stronger and more unified than ever,'' while his
critics grind their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   --``Air power alone will never achieve the goal. It'll take
ground troops.'' No ground troops were sent into combat, not one
airman died except in two training accidents, and only two planes
were lost out of a NATO air arm that was 75 percent US.
</P>
<P>
   --``The Russians will turn against the West and resurrect the
Cold War.'' Variations of this theme had the Russians so exercised
on behalf of their fellow Slavs, the Serbs, that US critics of
administration policy ignored the virtual dependence of the Russian
economy on US-backed loans.
</P>
<P>
   --``The Chinese will break with the West over Kosovo.'' The
accidental bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade accelerated
this plaint. In fact, the Chinese dependence on US trade is a
hundred times more important than fears of some sort of trumped-up
US colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   --``Clinton lacks the moral authority to lead the United States
into war.'' This was a favorite of Republicans in Congress and on
the post-impeachment presidential trail. Having lost at Monica
Roulette, the Republicans scrambled for the moral high ground, even
refusing to go on record in support of the NATO bombing effort. The
GOP approach was as shortsighted as it was craven.
</P>
<P>
   --``America's fighting forces, taking their cue from a
conservative-leaning office corps, will refuse to accept combat
orders from a disgraced and nearly impeached president.'' This
theme was big on Bible Belt talk shows, and among Sun Belt
right-wingers who worry aloud over black helicopters, blue berets,
and red-faced impeachment predictors.
</P>
<P>
   --``Public opinion will never stand for it.'' In fact,
choreographing a military action, by definition a bloody business,
among 19 democracies with unfettered news media criticism and
political oppositions not above demagoguing against any policy, is
a ticklish chore. As recently as two weeks ago, public opinion in
the NATO countries was only 49-40 percent in favor of the bombing
campaign that has just succeeded so brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   --``We are playing into Milosevic's hands, by inviting Kosovars
to western sanctuaries and cementing him in place by extinguishing
domestic dissent.'' No and no. He was repeating in Kosovo what
worked for him in Croatia and Slovenia. His iron grip on
paramilitary storm troopers and the propaganda apparatus of Serbia
meant no opponents could get traction. He murdered his biggest
critics, exiled or rendered impotent the rest.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard all the complaints listed above, and the war was won
despite that chorus. There are many Americans, including many in
the media, sincerely convinced that this war was not worth
fighting, and there are some who seem to believe that no war is
worth fighting.
</P>
<P>
   While there were mistakes aplenty _ the tactical ones of using
outdated maps and intelligence to map bombing runs and the
strategic one of failing to comprehend Milosevic is a brutal
psychopath who operates outside the conventions of 20th century
civilized behavior _ the war ended in victory because NATO
persevered.
</P>
<P>
   In US politics, his Republican enemies are yet again humbled by
Clinton. They got it wrong again. When ideological bitter-enders
like Senator James Inhofe of Oklahoma prevent Senate confirmation
of people like Richard Holbrooke, the administration's most
experienced Balkan negotiator, or Lawrence Summers as Treasury
secretary, they trifle with important public policies that dwarf
their cheap political causes. Unlike Slobodan, Republicans like
these these don't know when to cut their losses.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
