   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-MAYORS _ NEW ORLEANS _ The U.S. Conference of Mayors opens
its gathering with a session on gun lawsuits. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-CARS _ ATLANTA _ EPA holds second of four national
public hearings on new pollution rules for automobiles. The agency
is proposing tougher standards for both cars and SUV's, but many
environmental and public interest groups say even more stringent
standards are needed, particularly for large SUV's. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   POGO _ WASHINGTON _ The Project on Government Oversight, a
little-known group that labors for low pay in search of fraud and
inefficiency in government, is being accused of bribing an Interior
Department employee. A POGO lawsuit recently forced Mobil Oil Co.
to pay the government $45 million in back royalties for oil pumped
from taxpayer-owned land. As part of the settlement, $1.2 million
went to POGO, which chose to make $350,000 ``grants'' to two
bureaucrats, one retired. The organization said the money was to
reward the bureaucrats for ``putting their jobs on the line'' by
pressing for action to force repaymenty of royalties. But House
Resources Committee Chairman Don Young says the ``grant'' to a
current federal employee was an illegal payoff. Cheered by oil
company lawyers, Young has launched an investigation.
(Nesmith/Malone, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
