<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV EVANGELISTS FIRMLY ROOTED IN DALLAS/FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest TV evangelist at the moment is Benny Hinn, a
spirit-filled crusader known for the practice of touching people on
the forehead with his palm, causing them to fall backward as if
``slain in the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   And his announcement that he will move his headquarters to Fort
Worth-Dallas from Orlando, Fla., was good news for both his
advocates and his naysayers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics such as Ole Anthony, president of a watchdog
organization in Dallas, won't have to go as far to investigate
Hinn's international evangelism operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will certainly lessen our travel expenses,'' said Anthony.
He and his associates have journeyed far and wide in recent years,
investigating Hinn and other nationally known TV preachers.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony's Trinity Foundation is best known for helping ABC's
``PrimeTime Live'' produce a 1991 documentary that helped unravel
the huge TV ministry of Robert Tilton, whose headquarters formerly
were in Farmers Branch. Among the claims against Tilton was that he
``trashed'' letters from supporters after he took out their checks.
</P>
<P>
   Tilton and his attorneys denied that accusation and sued ABC,
saying the network tried to destroy the ministry. The courts threw
out the suit. Negative publicity, several lawsuits against his
ministry and two marriage breakups have reduced Tilton's ministry
to a fraction of what it was.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony has also investigated Hinn, and reports from those
investigations have appeared on local and national expose-style TV
programs questioning Hinn's lifestyle and his claims of miraculous
healings.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't deter Hinn's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Metroplex should welcome the Benny Hinn Ministries with
open arms,'' Ruth D. Allen of Fort Worth, a Southern Baptist who
donates to Hinn's ministries, wrote to me. ``I guarantee they will
be an asset to the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Rodriguez of Fort Worth said she is proud to be one of
Hinn's ``partners,'' a term she said is given to people who donate
at least $1 a day to his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partners met in Houston and we were the first ones to
learn that Pastor Hinn would be moving from Orlando,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the partners were told that $5 million is being raised
to begin building a headquarters somewhere near the Dallas/Fort
Worth Airport.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't mind the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other evangelists have gone wrong,'' she said. ``If they do,
we just stop giving to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-Dallas has been a hotbed _ and a graveyard _ for
nationally known evangelists.
</P>
<P>
   One former high-profile evangelist, W.V. Grant Jr., who was
investigated by Anthony and others because of his healing claims,
spent a short time in prison for misuse of ministry funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant's church building, which he called the Eagle's Nest,
has risen from the ashes of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   It is now the Potter's House Church, one of the fastest-growing
congregations in the nation. The pastor, T.D. Jakes, has a national
TV ministry and he has baptized Deion Sanders, Emmitt Smith and
some other members of the Dallas Cowboys football team.
</P>
<P>
   Another evangelist who lives in the Fort Worth area, Kenneth
Copeland, has been a top 10 television preacher for years. He and
his wife, Gloria, have their headquarters on the banks of Eagle
Mountain Lake, northwest of Fort Worth. They teach that Christians
can be spiritually, physically and financially prosperous if they
follow God.
</P>
<P>
   The Copelands have their critics. One of them, author Hank
Hanegraaff, calls their prosperity theology a ``counterfeit''
gospel that ignores some core teachings of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known evangelist James Robison, who with his wife, Betty,
hosts a nationally televised Christian talk show, has his
headquarters in Euless. Paul and Jan Crouch, the leaders of the
Trinity Broadcasting Network, one of the largest Christian TV
networks, have a glittering facility in Irving that looks very much
like the nation's White House.
</P>
<P>
   So Benny Hinn will have a bit of company.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Hinn's followers, Tincy Burns of Fort Worth, said her
life has been changed since she began watching his television
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited he's coming to Texas,'' she said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Her philosophy is to ignore criticisms of Hinn and let his
ministry speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is doing something wrong, God will punish him,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
