<SLUG> BC-CARMAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARMAX MAKING A PLACE FOR ITSELF IN NO-HAGGLE AUTO SALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB COX 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANCASTER, Texas _ It's been an uphill battle, but CarMax Auto
Superstores is gradually carving out a slice of the retail auto
business _ and getting close to making money at it, too, says
Austin Ligon, president of the Richmond, Va.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   CarMax was built on the premise that consumers should be able to
buy new and used cars in much the same way they buy computers,
televisions and appliances from CarMax's parent company, Circuit
City Stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company hasn't been as financially successful as hoped,
Ligon acknowledged in an interview Thursday at the grand opening of
CarMax's newest Fort Worth-Dallas location, a
Chrysler-Plymouth-Jeep dealership in Lancaster. But he said that's
not because the company's concept of no-haggle pricing and
customer-friendly sales practices isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're behind the plan. We projected we'd lose money for the
first four years in business and break even in the fifth,'' Ligon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after opening its first store, CarMax finally turned a
small profit, 3 cents a share, in the first quarter that ended May
30. When the company's fiscal year ends in February, CarMax will
post a small loss or break even, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Selling cars hasn't been CarMax's problem, Ligon said. Almost
all of CarMax's 35 separate locations have high sales and are
solidly profitable, he said. But the costs of expansion, building
the company and implementing standardized systems has been greater
than projected.
</P>
<P>
   The Lancaster location is CarMax's first new-car outlet in the
Metroplex, joining the three used-car superstores, including one in
Fort Worth. CarMax acquired Hilltop Chrysler-Plymouth of Lancaster
and the Jeep franchise rights of Red Bird Jeep-Eagle in Duncanville
to form the new outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll more than double the size of this store,'' Ligon said.
``We should be able to have 300 to 400 new cars and 250 used cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is simply to become the biggest
Chrysler-Plymouth-Jeep dealer in the market and offer a very
successful used car superstore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lancaster store won't be CarMax's last in the area, either.
Ligon said the company plans to open a used car outlet in Plano
next year and could pursue a sixth Metroplex location, probably in
west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   CarMax's lack of profitability so far isn't a good indication of
the company's impact on automobile retailing, according to one
industry analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had a tremendous impact, but unfortunately they're not
benefiting,'' said Eric Noble of Auto Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them, it's a question of surviving long enough to reap the
benefits of the change. It's like the pioneers get the arrows,
settlers get the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Noble said that CarMax and AutoNation have been handicapped by
the high costs of entering the business. Existing dealerships, he
said, often have a huge advantage in that they own the land and
facilities on it.
</P>
<P>
   If CarMax or some other large chain ever puts together enough
buying clout to command price discounts from auto manufacturers,
much as Wal-Mart does with its merchandise, they will have a huge
competitive advantage, Noble said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Ligon said, he foresees about 250 new- and used-car
CarMax locations nationwide, although it may be years before that
goal is reached. One of the impediments to growth, he said, is in
state franchise laws and other legal obstacles in the path of large
companies like CarMax and AutoNation.
</P>
<P>
   Ligon likens his company's experience to that of Southwest
Airlines and says that if consumers like the way CarMax and other
companies try to simplify buying cars, the large chains will grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer is still in charge. The good ideas tend to win
out in the marketplace. ... It took years for Southwest Airlines to
get to the East Coast. That didn't mean it (Southwest) wasn't a
great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
