<HEADER>
A1754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-AFTERLIFE-BOS &LR;      06-11 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-AFTERLIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPPLING WITH MEMORY'S MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFTER LIFE &QL; 
Directed and written by: Hirokazu Kore-eda &QL; 
Starring: Arata, Erika Oda, Susumu Terajima, Takashi Naito, Kei
Tani, Taketoshi Naito, Kayoko Kagawa, Kisuku Shoda &QL; 
Running time: 118 minutes &QL; 
Rated: Unrated &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is memory? How ephemeral is it? What kind of meaning can it
give life? A heartfelt and ultimately poignant grappling with these
questions distinguishes Hirokazu Kore-eda's ``After Life'' from
most Western films that deal with the betwixt and between of life
and death.
</P>
<P>
   In this genre as we know it in the West from such films as
``Outward Bound,'' ``Stairway to Heaven,'' and ``Defending Your
Life,'' heaven can wait while it is decided to which afterlife this
or that character will go. This Japanese take on the imparting of
meaning to life before leaving it demands patience, but richly
repays it as the film leads us into a contemplation of human
experience few others even notice.
</P>
<P>
   Here there is no judgment made of the newcomers to the shabby
way station that suggests a run-down school or hospice run by civil
servants who blandly and formally process each week's new arrivals.
But the newcomers are by no means let off the hook. When they check
into the nondescript facility on a Monday they are told they have
until Wednesday to select a memory. It will then be filmed in a
makeshift studio, screened for them by the weekend, and given to
them to accompany them into the afterlife. Their other memories
will be erased. As the interviews proceed, with the camera standing
in for each interviewer, we realize that although everyone looks
earthy enough, they are in fact dead.
</P>
<P>
   By Japanese standards, the film is quite droll as we learn that
the ones doing the questioning are those who for one reason or
another could not choose a memory, and so remain in limbo in the
facility and put to work there. Not that the interviewers are
without passions. One young woman (Erika Oda) has fallen for a
colleague (Arata) who, although young-looking, has been there since
World War II. When the recollection of one old man jars the
interviewer into possibly selecting a memory of his own, the young
fellow staffer who has a crush on him is not happy. But it isn't
conventional drama or plot twists that make ``After Life'' moving.
Rather, it's the exquisitely tender memories that come floating to
the surface of this or that interviewee's mind.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if, having been jarred loose from an ocean floor, the
memory floats up to the surface to be reveled in, wondered at. One
old woman decides to take with her the memory of a dance lesson. An
old man talks big about sex, but in the end decides to carry with
him the memory of his daughter's wedding, at which she handed him
her bouquet. A teenage girl wants to take with her the memory of a
trip to Disneyland and is informed, with a more than detectable
trace of sadness by her interviewer, that 30 other girls have
chosen the same memory in the last year. A slightly punked-out
young man, who hasn't lived that long, says he can't possibly
choose. A 72-year-old man has the same problem and is handed 72
videocassettes, one covering each year of his life, to jog his
memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, memory itself becomes the star of the film,
precious, perishable, vivid, hooked to sense memories of mundane
and otherwise unremarkable events, such as one man's insistence
that he can recall the sun shining on his body when he was less
than a year old. ``After Life'' is governed by Kore-eda's
background as a documentarian. His style is spare and elegant and
subtly layered as the faces and the expressions on them (including
nonprofessionals) become the delivery system for a life-affirming
connection to a wide range of human experience. Kore-eda actually
went out and interviewed many people, then came back and distilled
their replies into this film. The interplay between the real
memories, their transformation into a screenplay and a film within
a film adds to the resonance of this exercise that goes beyond
documenting the life of postwar Japan to give us deeper truths that
go beyond mere fact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
