<HEADER>
A1760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BOWLES-BOS &LR;      06-11 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOWLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIVETING LOOK AT A LITERARY LION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETSY SHERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LET IT COME DOWN: THE LIFE OF PAUL BOWLES 
Directed by: Jennifer Baichwal 
Running time: 73 min. 
Rating: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canadian filmmaker Jennifer Baichwal has made a handsome,
fascinating portrait of Paul Bowles, the octagenarian who is best
known for his novels (``The Sheltering Sky'') and short stories,
his complicated marriage to writer Jane Bowles, and his longtime
status as an American expatriate in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Even newcomers to Bowles's work will be impressed by his stature
as a figure who touched the major arts movements of the 20th
century, from a period in his 20s as a protege of poet Gertrude
Stein in Paris, to a significant career as a composer who interwove
influences from Tin Pan Alley to Stravinsky, and as an elder
brother to the Beats, who joined him in drug-abundant Tangiers in
the 1950s. As a closeup look at an old lion, the film is riveting:
there are subtle ripples beneath Bowles's placid face as he mixes
confession and obvious denial, looking back on a full life that he
seems compelled to dismiss as not very special.
</P>
<P>
   Always present is the atmosphere of Bowles' adopted home,
Tangiers. Arabic chants bubble up on the soundtrack, and shots of
the desert landscape that Bowles loves are intercut with the
interviews. It was during the 1930s that Bowles was dispatched to
Tangiers by Stein to keep tabs on another protege. He made that
trip with Aaron Copland, who was horrified by the ``madhouse'' of
North Africa. Says Bowles in the film, his Yankee intonations
providing instant irony, ``I was completely overjoyed because I
thought that it was a madhouse, completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowles was born in Jamaica, N.Y., in 1910, into an ascetic _ and
anti-religious _ household. He discovered release (from boredom, he
says) in writing and music. He fled home for Paris, the stint in
the Stein household proving educational, if humiliating. His
subsequent work as a composer is explored in the film via a 1995
tribute performance by the Eos Orchestra at Lincoln Center (the
film also records a 1995 meeting at the Mayfair Hotel reuniting
Bowles, William Burroughs, and Allen Ginsberg). In the '40s,
Bowles' music and fiction careers overlapped. Bowles' prose, which
exhibits a violence that the writer says has never been present in
his life, is read by Tom McCamus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, Bowles wed Jane Sydney Auer, who shared his passion for
travel. He describes how they were opposites in temperament, she an
optimist and he a pessimist, but there's no doubt that they were
soul mates. But among the array of friends and commentators in the
film, there seems to be an agreement that the love of Bowles's life
was the Moroccan painter Ahmed Yacoubi. Bowles's sexuality is an
area around which he steps gingerly. Burroughs derisively redubbed
Bowles' 1972 autobiography ``Without Stopping,'' ``Without
Telling.''
</P>
<P>
   The talking-head sequences of Bowles are the movie's prize.
Baichwal shoots him in closeup against a black background, in a
chiaroscuro that makes his proudly etched face seem like a floating
bust of a Roman senator. Bowles' soft voice and formal manner of
speech understate his often startling pronouncements. For the
documentary camera, the artist does a veil dance between the poles
of monster and victim, but never lays himself bare. He proves to be
as unknowable as he himself has called the Muslim culture. Among
his parting words are these: ``I think people are planets, floating
spheres. So if they touch, they touch at one tiny point. ... In
general, they fly around, self-sufficient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BESIEGED-BOS &LR;      06-11 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BESIEGED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTOLUCCI CRAFTS A POLISHED BUT FLAWED GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the likelihood of bad dialogue swamping most love stories,
there's something to be said for a love story played out as a
string of mostly nonverbal convulsions. Bernardo Bertolucci's
``Besieged'' sets us up for one, but in the end doesn't deliver.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it sets us up for quite a lot. Racial and sexual
politics seem on track to converge provocatively in the film that
begins with Thandie Newton's Shandurai stunned at the imprisonment
of her schoolteacher husband by the repressive regime running their
African country. Cut to a side street in Rome, where Shandurai is
next seen working as a domestic for an eccentric British pianist,
David Thewlis's Kinsky, who inherited the house from his aunt.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in her own quarters downstairs and busily leads the
demanding life of a medical student when she isn't fetching and
carrying for the pianist, who doesn't do much of anything when he
isn't flailing away at his Steinway. Lack of occupation may be his
biggest problem. Idle mind and all that. At any rate, it doesn't
take Kinsky long to fall for Shandurai. Except for a handful of
students, he has no friends, and doesn't go out much. Given their
mutual confinement, it's only a matter of time until he follows up
leaving little presents for her by blurting out an agonized
declaration of love for her. When he says he'll do anything for
her, she suggests he try freeing her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Because both characters remain both superficial and opaque, we
never believe in the depths of feeling we're asked to buy into, or,
for that matter, the depths of character that must be present to
give rise to any feelings at all. We do get the sense that each is
a foreigner floating unanchored in the little Roman side street
they provisionally share. When an Italian medical school classmate
(Claudio Santamaria) comes on to Shandurai, Newton tempers
Shandurai's aversion to his advances with her own loneliness.
Similarly, isolation rather than emotion nudges her toward the
pianist.
</P>
<P>
   Because they don't speak much, and likely wouldn't have much to
say to each other if they did, Bertolucci lets music do the talking
for them. This proves a major miscalculation. It's one thing to
have Shandurai play African music to shore up her assaulted
identity while the pianist sits upstairs giving Western music a
heavy workout. But when he suddenly is rejuvenated and composes a
clangy new work borrowing heavily from African rhythms, the film's
master-servant, First World-Third World dialectics start crumbling
fast. Thewlis's Kinsky is an emotional loose cannon, and the script
can't seem to decide whether Shandurai is a competent modern woman
or a shy, subservient one. ``Besieged'' looks good. It even looks
raw and immediate. But it's ultimately about worlds in avoidance,
not collision. In ``Besieged,'' nobility does battle with a vacuum,
and the vacuum wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1427EDT &QL; 
