<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1765 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SALVATION-BOS &LR;      06-11 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SALVATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHARITABLE ARMY'S RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ubiquitous red kettles and bell ringers at Christmastime. A
convenient bin to receive donated clothes. A shelter for the
homeless. These are the familiar images most people have of the
Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But the army is not just a powerful and successful charity. It
is first and foremost an evangelical Christian church born in
England and exported to America in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   How a small band of fiery streetcorner evangelists _ in the
beginning derided as vulgar exhibitionists _ evolved into a
formidable charitable organization that raises more than $1 billion
annually is the focus of Diane Winston's superb new book.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Red Hot and Righteous: The Urban Religion of the Salvation
Army,'' Winston, a journalist and research fellow at New York
University, combines intelligent insights, rich anecdotes, and
telling facts to chart the remarkable ascent of the Salvation Army
from 1880, when it landed on US shores, to 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The book's finest and most compelling moments come when Winston
adroitly profiles the army's evolution into a mighty charitable
engine. As the army gained greater acceptance, church leaders
realized that before it could successfully promote personal
salvation it needed to deal with social salvation by addressing the
squalid conditions of society's downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   Winston provides one intriguing reason for the army's turn
toward social activism: its failure to win converts among the lower
classes. In the 1890s, she writes, the Salvation Army began
referring to itself as a religious and philanthropic organization.
``While the Army may have failed at saving slum dwellers' souls, it
was able to allay their physical needs,'' Winston notes.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at the end of the last century and continuing into
this one, the army rapidly expanded its social services. ``Between
1904 and 1913 the number of relief institutions grew from 195 to
413,'' writes Winston, who makes good use of primary sources to
buttress her arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army cemented its reputation for good works in
World War I when it mobilized ``sallies,'' groups of women who
served American soldiers in France. ``Salvationist work in World
War I wove together themes of action, gender and patriotism,''
Winston writes. ``Fashioned into a shining tapestry of God,
country, and motherhood, these themes hallowed the Salvation Army
as America's own nonsectarian faith, a religion of action.''
</P>
<P>
   As Winston skillfully shows, the Salvation Army was the first
American religion not only to embrace but to appropriate popular
culture to promote its message to a broad spectrum of society. The
parades, vaudeville acts, brass bands, and uniforms were all a
marked contrast to the reserved practices of more established
religions. The Salvation Army, Winston points out, was savvy when
it come to public relations. It got itself noticed.
</P>
<P>
   As much as anything, Winston shrewdly notes, the army needed
attention if it was to gain a foothold on the American religious
landscape. ``Unlike other faiths, the Army did not have a natural
constituency; during its formative years, no one was born a
Salvationist,'' Winston writes. ``People converted or contributed
because they saw the Army in action. That required the Army to go
where people worked and lived _ and to reach out in ways the public
could understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The army's successful marketing helped overcome the initial
suspicion that greeted church members and laid a solid foundation
for the future. Winston also gives us a vivid and absorbing glimpse
into how the Salvation Army opened doors to women and stoked
debates on feminism. For middle- and upper-class women, in
particular, the army provided opportunities for organizational
leadership and grass-roots activism. Even though the ability of
women Salvationists to progress was still limited, Winston writes
that the Army was the ``first Christian group in modern times to
treat women as men's equals.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston's fine book is a remarkable tale not just of the rise to
prominence of the Salvation Army but of the interplay between
religion and culture _ a dynamic that is still alive and well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1428EDT &QL; 
