<HEADER>
A1768 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-11 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHIFT FOR THUROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why have the US economy and stock market done so well?
</P>
<P>
   According to Massachusetts Institute of Technology economics
professor Lester Thurow, it is because the United States is
remarkably flexible. It is a country that is willing to embrace the
new and toss out the old.
</P>
<P>
   The same might be said about Thurow himself. In an interview
this week to promote his new book, ``Building Wealth,'' Thurow
seemed to have discarded most of the ideas he has been peddling for
the past 20 years in favor of some new and different ones.
Apparently economists can be flexible, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of books, beginning with ``The Zero-Sum Society'' in
1980, Thurow praised the government-directed economies of Europe
and Japan and criticized the United States' economy. A Washington
Post review of Thurow's 1992 book, ``Head to Head,'' summed up his
take on the US economy this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not kept up with our major competitors; we've let
manufacturing erode; we've allowed our schools to fail; we've
focused too much on short-term financial rewards; we haven't saved
enough; our deficits, at home and abroad, are shameless.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is something of a surprise to pick up Thurow's latest book
and read lines like ``America is back'' and ``all of Europe is an
also-ran.'' The new Thurow reminds you a bit of the movie character
Austin Powers, who after waking up from a 30-year sleep and
learning that the West has won the Cold War, shouts ``Groovy,
smashing, yeah capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurow concedes he got some things wrong in the past, but he has
a defense. ``It's not because I was dumb,'' he says. ``No one saw
the technological revolution coming.'' At 61, Thurow still looks
terrific and speaks incredibly fast.
</P>
<P>
   Technology changed the rules of the game, says Thurow. If the
1980s was about making old things a little better _ cars,
semiconductors _ the 1990s is about making brand new things. It is
a game that plays to the United States' strengths. We have the
right ``genetic material,'' is the way Thurow puts it.
</P>
<P>
   When Thurow's son studied engineering at Stanford University, he
took a course in creative thinking. ``That wouldn't happen in
Tokyo,'' he says. Thurow himself serves on the board of E-Trade,
one of the hottest of the Internet finance companies, so he has
seen the new economy up close.
</P>
<P>
   This ``third industrial revolution'' has created the opportunity
to make large fortunes, much the way earlier industrial revolutions
did. So why aren't the Europeans making these fortunes, too?
</P>
<P>
   They lack the entrepreneurs to take advantage of the new
opportunities. ``They've created a no-risk society in Europe,''
says Thurow. ``They're too conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Europeans shrink from the new and cling too tightly to the old.
Europe's refusal to accept food that has been biologically altered
``sounds an awful lot like the fears and restrictions imposed on
China five hundred years ago when it closed its doors to outside
influences,'' Thurow writes.
</P>
<P>
   He says that Europeans have to be willing to blow up their old
companies, arguing that the ``destructive'' side of ``creative
destruction'' is critical for success. The United States could not
have done as well, says Thurow, if big companies like AT&AMP;T and IBM
had not jettisoned thousands of workers in unprofitable lines of
business. Europe must do the same or be content to fall farther
behind in the race to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, another Thurow favorite in the past, has all the same
problems as Europe plus a terrible financial crisis. The latter
must be tackled before the country can get on the right track,
Thurow says.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier books, Thurow was a big advocate of government
intervention in the economy. He favored governments that picked
winners and losers, and governments that managed trade. He doesn't
say that any more.
</P>
<P>
   The only government policies he credits with boosting the US
economy are very old ones _ government-supported research for
medicine and defense, which helped create the modern biotechnology
and computer businesses. Thurow says President Clinton and Federal
Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan may have helped a little at
the margin, but both their efforts pale compared to the impact of
the technological revolution.
</P>
<P>
   How long can the revolution last? Thurow doesn't know. But he
points out that the revolutionary eventually becomes the
commonplace and that the huge profits earned by leading-edge firms
will eventually give way to more commonplace profits. Are you
listening, Mr. Gates?
</P>
<P>
   Thurow doesn't offer any specific advice for investors, but he
suggests that the United States will remain the world economic
leader for the forseeable future and that it will take some time
for Europe and Japan to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, given Thurow's track record on predictions, you might
want to buy some European and Japanese stocks just to be on the
safe side.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
