<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAMBERLAIN-COLUMN-BO     06-11 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMBERLAIN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A HARLEY HAVE-NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot spring nights remind me that for years it seemed inevitable
I would one day have my Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Like thinner hair and liver spots (``barnacles of age,'' my
dermatologist calls them), the time would arrive when, like any
natural progression, life's path would have crossed some
demarcation line and there it would be suddenly in my garage: a
1,200cc gleaming Harley-Davidson motorcycle with a custom burnished
leather saddle and just enough chrome to accent the subtle depth of
its British racing green paint job _ all to carry me back to my
youth.
</P>
<P>
   My concession to maturity would be to keep the factory baffles
in the pipes that create that strangely mellow Harley rumble, as
understated and sweet as a French horn. I'm older. None of that
ear-tearing gnash of straight pipes for me.
</P>
<P>
   I would nod to baffles and a conventional helmet (``brain
bucket,'' as my medical sister darkly calls them) rather than one
of those black plastic beanies riders wear to show they are rebels.
They would be wearing no helmet at all if only the bureaucratic
fuddy-duddies bent on taking our freedoms and Camels away let them
ride the range as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll look like an old fool,'' said a person in my life who
readily shares such opinions. ``Don't think you're getting me on a
motorcycle. I've paid those dues.''
</P>
<P>
   She meant that, as a young bride some 32 years ago, her mother
holding a Kleenex to her nose and her father looking on in grim,
helpless alarm, this woman climbed onto the back of a motorcycle
behind her new husband to ride eight hours to their newlywed bower
up in the north woods of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I'm not too old for it,'' she added, ``I've gotten too
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   I should have, too. In fact, I did own several motorcycles in
days past, spent most of a decade riding, off in the woods and on
long trips on highways and back roads. It should be out of my
system, right?
</P>
<P>
   But still every spring, skis put away, grass fertilized,
forsythia bursting, I hear that first sweet rumble on a spring
night and my ears tune in to the exact pitch, not duplicated by any
brand of motorcycle. The truth is, in all my riding days I never
had a Harley.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I'm into some retro Hell's Angels thing. As an
attendee of the last 20 or so Allman Brothers concerts at Great
Woods, I always go check out the Harleys and the guys riding them.
They roll in like those gangs of old, the Angels laying seige to
some little country town, Brando in the lead _ all a reenactment of
cowboy movies.
</P>
<P>
   These days their Harleys may still gleam and roar, but the
Senior Angels are a sad-looking lot: old, toothless lions who've
lost their roar. Biceps sagging out of sleeveless leather vests,
gray beards and guts hanging on the gas tanks, dated tatoos awash
in hoary fur, the old Angels have become almost pure comedy.
</P>
<P>
   I know this and, as an adult, I also know now that motorcycles
are dangerous, tiring, inconvenient, limited by weather, and not
sociable. I know that listening to Mozart in an air-conditioned car
is a hundred times more comfortable. And I also know that there are
probably a lot better motorcycles out there than Harleys, from BMWs
to Hondas to Ninjas.
</P>
<P>
   But for years I had been making a secret promise to myself that
after the domestic obligations of child raising and college tuition
were finally discharged, my middle-aged angst would be expressed in
the mellow rumbling of a Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Why a Harley I can't exactly say. Years back life couldn't offer
up much better than a Triumph or BSA. But somewhere along the line
Americans fell in love with Harley-Davidson, perhaps after the
Japanese taught them how to make a superior bike, and I fell, too.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a Springsteen ``Born in the USA'' kind of thing.
Whatever, the question is not technical but one of the heart.
Harley is summer. That insouciant rumble rings with the chords of
ancient rock 'n' roll _ Elvis, Buddy Holly, Chuck Berry . . .
</P>
<P>
   That rattling purr brings back hot nights and the arcade aroma
of dime store perfume mingling with fried clams and salt air.
</P>
<P>
   It is the promise of the open road, the next town and the next
state, the Rockies, the desert, the West Coast . . . that
peculiarly American optimism that if you want a better life just
get in the saddle and ride for it. Hail the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' she asked a couple of years after my first raving,
``where's your Harley?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' I told her. ``I'm afraid if I bought one
I'd ride it to the beach a couple of times and put it away in the
garage to collect dust.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't exactly that, though I suspect some truth there.
Nor is it the fear of being taken for a lapsed, paunchy,
white-bearded fallen Angel myself.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I still get misty about Harleys, and I stop to watch one go
by when I hear that unmistakable throaty rumble, but now I know I
won't get one and here's the real point:
</P>
<P>
   A sentimentalist mourns his innocence while a true romantic
misses the fun of losing it, knowing it can be lost only once.
After all, it is a rare summer indeed that delivers on the promise
of spring.
</P>
<P>
   Vroom. Vroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
