A1782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-11 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGING DR. GREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the difference between a shyster and an entrepreneur? In
the case of former surgeon general C. Everett Koop, about $41
million.
</P>
<P>
   Koop, who has been hanging his hat up at Dartmouth Medical
School, is the centerpiece of www.drkoop.com, the latest in a
series of medical Web sites that dole out information to a vast new
public of HMO-traumatized ``cyberchondriacs.'' Koop and his
business partners are betting that his hard-won reputation for
integrity as surgeon general during the Reagan years will lure
clients to the site to seek medical advice and to buy ``drkoop''
products.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, the venture has already made its investors rich.
Koop himself sewed up $41 million in Monday's initial public
offering. His fellow director, ``Good Morning America'' teledoc
Nancy Snyderman, took home about $6 million in the IPO. In addition
to his stock windfall, Koop has been pulling down lecture fees,
director's fees, and a six-figure annual consulting payment from
the company, according to its stock filing.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. In return for use of ``his image, name and
likeness in connection with healthcare-related services and
products,'' the company reports, ``we are obligated to pay Dr. C.
Everett Koop a royalty equal to 2 percent of our revenues derived
from sales of our current products and up to 4 percent of our
revenues derived from sales of new products during the term of the
(five-year) agreement.'' Why Koop is so anxious to attach his name
to a Web site that hosts support groups like Angel Power and Beyond
the Locker Room (whatever that means) is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   As surgeon general from 1981 until 1989, Koop made a huge splash
for supporting AIDS research and AIDS patients at a time when many
worried that the Republican administration might turn its back on
them. At the same time, he never backed off from his principled
stand against abortion, alienating the same liberal constituencies
who liked his activist AIDS and antismoking stands.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past decade, Koop seems to have lost his once-perfect
pitch for public politics. His name surfaced in the Clinton
administration's Arlington National Cemetery scandal. Apparently
confusing himself with a real general _ he never served in the
military _ Koop had obtained Clinton's permission in 1994 to be
buried at Arlington. The waiver of Arlington requirements was
especially unusual and was opposed by the Army, because Koop was
still living. After the scandal broke, Koop relinquished his claim
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Koop has tried once before to capitalize on his good name.
Working with television personality Linda Ellerbee, he accepted a
reported $750,000 fee from Time-Warner to roll out a series of $20
videos on consumer health issues. The videos were a bust. According
to The Wall Street Journal, the ill-fated venture burned through
$65 million before declaring bankruptcy in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Koop, who was traveling and could not be reached for comment,
has a list of professional honors longer than this column. So why
come between the good doctor and what many would regard as his
well-deserved payday? Perhaps just to warn that a reputation is
purchased dear and sold cheaply _ no matter what the price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
