<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-POWERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE VELVET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME 
Directed by: Jay Roach 
Screenplay by: Mike Myers, Michael McCullers 
Starring: Myers, Heather Graham, Michael York, Robert Wagner, Seth
Green, Mindy Sterling, Rob Lowe, Gia Carides, Verne Troyer,
Elizabeth Hurley, Kristen Johnston, Will Ferrell 
Playing at: Copley Place, suburbs 
Rated: PG-13 (sexual innuendo and crude humor) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for the silly season, here comes ``Austin Powers:
The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' It's bigger and slicker than the first
go-round. It's more confident, has more of a sense of what it wants
to be, but remembers never to take itself seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's pretty dumb and vacuous, but it wins you over
anyway. It's still able to seem a big joke, a screenful of bits and
poses sunnily trying to will itself into a movie, and knocking it
is like kicking styrofoam. Mike Myers's toothy airhead is back in
his velvet suit as the Carnaby Street James Bond wannabe, keeping
the world safe for psychedelia and other pop culture artifacts,
including, this time around, a few live artifacts quick to see that
rubbing shoulders with Austin Powers would nudge their coolness
quotients up a few notches.
</P>
<P>
   We're not just talking cameos from the likes of Woody Harrelson
and Willie Nelson. We're talking a duet of Burt Bacharach and Elvis
Costello singing Bacharach's ``I'll Never Fall in Love Again.''
We're talking Tim Robbins, ol' Bob Roberts himself, showing up as a
US president. We're talking about Myers and his colleagues using
the Jerry Springer Show's soul-baring mayhem as much as it uses
them. We're talking about places where casting and sight gags meet,
such as Rob Lowe materializing as the young Robert Wagner character
after Myers's Austin inevitably steps into a psychedelic VW Beetle
time machine and transports himself back to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The '90s sight gags aren't bad, either _ Starbucks's green
letters festooned like mold across Seattle's Space Needle, for
instance. But the '60s rule here, whether in the Playskool-colored
dazzle of Austin's swinging bachelor pad or the way Austin and his
nubile CIA counterpart, Heather Graham's Felicity Shagwell, go
after Myers's alter ego, Dr. Evil, in a yellow submarine. There's a
little too much Dr. Evil, and more than you probably will want from
a third character Myers plays, an obese Scottish hitman and prime
source of crude humor, sporting a name that can't be printed in
this newspaper. The joke is that Dr. Evil is a pussycat who may
talk about world domination, but has all he can do to maintain a
shaky hold on his own dysfunctional family, whose conflicts are
kept bubbling by Mindy Sterling, Seth Green, and the doc's little
clone, Verne Troyer.
</P>
<P>
   Myers and his colleagues know enough to avoid burdening the film
with plot. Nobody will ever accuse this one of being convoluted.
Dr. Evil steals Austin's mojo and Austin needs to get it back to
take advantage of Felicity's willingness to meet him on, so to
speak, equal terms. That's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a big plus, delivers a sly, on-the-money,
tongue-in-cheek take on the deadly macrame-clad CIA beach bunny who
drives a Corvette with a Stars &AMP; Stripes paint job to counterpoint
Austin's Shaguar, with its custom-painted Union Jack. But then the
whole film is as customized as the two sports cars are. It's
Day-Glo bright and kicky, it aims low, and it'll never make you
feel intellectually drained. For once, here's a sequel that hasn't
been buried underneath its increased budget, but has some fun with
it. Give your brain the night off, and Myers will make you smile,
too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1436EDT &QL; 
