A1792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TWICE-BOS &LR;      06-11 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TWICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROMANTIC EXCURSION IN LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maria Ripoll's ``Twice Upon a Yesterday'' is a spicy, beguiling
Anglo-Hispanic romantic fantasy that charmingly unfolds in London.
But not in the usual London. It's London transformed from a
battleground into a place of gentle enchantment. It begins on a
mundane level, as two lovers betray one another, part in order to
be with other partners, then experience the urge to reunite, but at
different times. Do they go back and try to regenerate old love? Or
push on to try for new love?
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that sets Ripoli's film apart from most other
romantic comedies, aside from its light touch, is its forgiving
nature. The couple we meet at the outset _ Douglas Henshall's Vic
and Lina Headey's Sylvia _ is mutually unhappy and mutually
unfaithful. Each is seeing somebody else on the side. But the film
isn't out to condemn either. It simply views them as people who
make mistakes. And when Vic gets lucky, it isn't because he's
deserving, but because the law of averages breaks in his favor in a
world that isn't out to get him, and includes a pub whose bartender
(Elizabeth McGovern) may be dispensing magic along with pints of
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   The film also includes a pair of seraphic garbagemen right out
of the pages of Cervantes. When Vic staggers into them one night,
they send him on his way with a gentle nudge and a page out of
``Romeo and Juliet.'' Soon he meets a Spanish muse named Louise
played by a softly radiant Penelope Cruz, who, in her words, helps
him get the rain out of his shoes. By the time the film has
finished making its way through a few alternative realities, which
involve Vic and Sylvia soon leaving the people they originally left
each other for, each must make a choice based on their new mutual
availability.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the film's way of blurring the harsh contours of
romantic breakup and believably offering a vision of emotional
fulfillment that sets it apart from most other couples-in-turmoil
movies. It unflinchingly follows its own romantic impulse toward a
generously humane overview, and while it could easily have landed
on its head, it lands instead on its feet, lightly and with a smile
through its tears. So simpatico and filled with finesse is ``Twice
Upon a Yesterday'' that it's hard to believe that it's a debut
film. But it is, and it casts a spell as Ripoll, with a big assist
from Cruz, brings off her warm and sparklingly inventive romantic
excursion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
