<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUBS AGAIN BECKON DEL FUEGOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Del Fuegos had a decade-plus run as the beloved crazies of
Boston's garage-rock scene. They eventually broke up in the early
'90s, not long after being nominated along with Aerosmith, New Kids
on the Block, Bonnie Raitt, and Bobby Brown for outstanding
pop-rock album at the Boston Music Awards. It was for an album
called ``Smoking in the Fields.'' And the band was not talking
about smoking tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the Del Fuegos went far in their day. They rose to
playing arena shows with Tom Petty, ZZ Top, and INXS, but the
Fuegos never felt totally comfortable there, preferring clubs
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those big shows were exciting on paper, but there's an
intimacy that takes place in a club that you can't capture on the
big stage,'' says Del Fuegos guitarist Warren Zanes.
</P>
<P>
   That club intimacy is beckoning again. The Fuegos play a reunion
show at the Middle East Downstairs in Cambridge on Friday night to
benefit a Concord, N.H., soup kitchen operated by the mother of
Warren and his brother, Dan, the lead singer of the Fuegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is for a good cause and we're eager to see some old
faces,'' says Zanes, whose other bandmates include bassist Tom
Lloyd and drummer Woody Giessmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also eager to get back because our final years were kind
of sloppy,'' says Zanes. ``But everyone gets along well and we're
leaving the ego baggage at the door. For all the moments of
turbulence we had, we still hold dear the moments that it went
right musically.''
</P>
<P>
   Those moments were many. The Fuegos, sporting a bristlingly raw,
garage-rock sound that dipped liberally into rhythm and blues, used
to record for Slash Records _ the label that had such bands as X,
the Blasters, Los Lobos, and the Gun Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``All were bands that we looked up to,'' says Zanes. ``When we
signed to Slash, suddenly we could go where we wanted to. But it's
pretty tricky to be under 25 and have things go your way too much.
That's a little scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fuegos upheld Boston's honor by naming one of their albums
``Boston, Ma.'' They also enjoyed a national hit with the song
``Don't Run Wild.'' But things started to unravel when they moved
to Hollywood to seek out new opportunities. In those days, it was a
move not appreciated by many ardent Boston rock fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet we still considered ourselves a Boston band,'' Zanes says.
``A lot of our good memories have to do with Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The last Del Fuegos reunion was five years ago at the wedding of
Lloyd's brother, Seth. But group members have generally pursued
separate lives. Now Lloyd has a PhD related to rocket science
(seriously). Dan has a solo career in New York. Giessmann continues
to drum around Boston. And Warren has been living in Los Angeles,
finishing up a PhD in Visual and Culture Studies begun at the
University of Rochester, in New York. He's also signed a record
deal with the Dust Brothers to make a CD that will come out on
Ideal Records, a division of Mammoth Records.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, he and the Fuegos are focused strictly on the
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to come back and say, `Hey, we're still just a
four-piece garage band.' That's what we do best,'' says Zanes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
