<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-MAMET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID   MAMET MAKE `MARRIAGE' OF CONVENIENCE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON MARRIAGE
</P>
<P>
   Play in three acts written and directed by David Mamet. &QL; 
Set, Sharon Kaitz and J. Michael Griggs. &QL; 
Lighting, John Ambrosone. Costumes, Harriet Voyt. &QL; 
Presented by the American Repertory Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   At: Hasty Pudding Theatre, through June 27.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you assigned students in a playwriting course to create a
drawing-room comedy connecting Oscar Wilde to Harold Pinter and you
got back ``Boston Marriage,'' you'd give it an A and tell all your
friends about the witty new writer you'd discovered in your class.
If, for extra credit, you asked the class to throw in some
playwriting tics from one of today's major American playwrights
you'd go up to an A+.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that the writer of ``Boston Marriage'' is David
Mamet, the expectation is more for a brilliant play than a
brilliant exercise and that expectation is not fully met. The play
is fun, it's smart, and it even adds some insights into Mamet's
work, and for all those reasons it's worth seeing. At Mamet's level
of playwriting, though, the grading curve is steeper and the play,
in its world premiere at the American Repertory Theatre, is closer
to a B-.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious from the start that Mamet is having a ball writing
his version of ``An Ideal Husband,'' or in this case, ``An Ideal
Lesbian Lover.'' A Boston marriage was in fact a term at the turn
of the century, when the play takes place, but the two women,
played by Rebecca Pidgeon and Felicity Huffman, are at each other's
throats with a wit akin to characters out of Wilde and a vengeance
not unlike those from Pinter, Edward Albee, or Mamet himself.
</P>
<P>
   The difference for Mamet is that these characters are females of
the species, whom Mamet has supposedly served poorly through his
career in favor of the machismo-laden. One of the more interesting
aspects of the play is Mamet's ability to dispel that annoying buzz
without writing a condescending play about how women are so much
more sensitive and soulful than his men.
</P>
<P>
   Quite the contrary. These women would give Teach in ``American
Buffalo'' a run for his macho money, considering the epithets they
hurl at each other and at the maid, played by Mary McCann. This
being the turn of the century and every bone of their body
stiffened and corseted, they do it with incredibly proper diction
and comportment, but there's still not that much psychological
distance between Mamet's louts and Mamet's lesbians. Nor should
their amusing man-hating asides be taken as what the playwright
thinks anymore than Teach's tirades at Ruthie be taken as what he
thinks about women. Mamet's characters are equal-opportunity
gratifiers.
</P>
<P>
   In each case it's what's said between the lines and around the
pauses that carry weight. Anna (Huffman) is the mistress of a
wealthy man who has set her up in very tasteful digs (nice, simple
set by Sharon Kaitz and J. Michael Griggs). It's for Claire
(Pidgeon), however, that Anna's knees go weak, so when Claire
declares her love for a younger woman, and asks that Anna provide
housing for them that the two go at it hammer and verbal tong, at
least within the parameters set by their class and gender and the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet's interest used to be in what his characters were left
with after they stopped swearing and screaming at each other. Here,
as with his film of ``The Winslow Boy,'' he's more interested in
what is going on underneath that British, or in ``Boston Marriage''
a faux British, reserve: ``I am sorry I was moved to speak with
enthusiasm.'' Their Wilde-isms betray an intellectual shallowness:
``I never could abide learning,'' says one. ``It's a mark of the
social climber,'' agrees the other. And their theater-of-cruelty
accusations and attitudes betray a moral torpor (``Where's the
slavey?'').
</P>
<P>
   One knows, though, where Wilde or Pinter is behind his
characters' bad behavior. Mamet is a bit too elusive here, despite
some well-placed anachronisms from time to time, such as ``Tell it
to the Marines'' or other phrases from his four-letter phrase book.
He also throws in some delicious, Wilde-like plot twists regarding
a necklace. But the play is still lacking a strong authorial point
of view, which is what makes it feel more like an exercise than the
typical Mamet play.
</P>
<P>
   There is a nice balance that Mamet strikes between the women's
prim and proper reserve and the anger and sexuality simmering
beneath it, but these characters are so beyond any redemption that,
unlike ``The Winslow Boy,'' who cares what that reserve is hiding?
Pidgeon and Huffman engage in a bizarre form of Mamet-speak, one
that allows for almost no facial expression. That's obviously what
he wanted, given that he's also the director. They're quite good at
the Thelma-and-Louise-with-parasols poses, and the earthiness and
emotionality of McCann's maid is a welcome counterpoint. I wonder,
though, if ``Boston Marriage'' wouldn't play better with a Wilde-r,
Maggie Smith-like approach to the parts.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, ``Boston Marriage'' continues the strong
relationship between Mamet and ART, although the first,
``Oleanna,'' is still the best. ``Boston Marriage'' is a curiously
entertaining addition to that collaboration, one we hope will
produce the next ``Glengarry Glen Ross.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
