<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-ALONE-HNS     06-11 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ALONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MONSTER IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his fist crashed through the window of our aesthetic
sensibilities, the French writer-director Gaspar Noe splits the
Earth to unleash the hounds of hell foaming at the mouth in one
man's mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he reframes, if not redefines the psychosis of
movie violence in timely apocalyptic fashion. ``I Stand Alone'' has
the ghastly stink of a rotting corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Said devil is actually a butcher (brave Philippe Nahon in an
unnerving double-fisted fit of internal combustion) _ unnamed but
not remotely anonymous and turned inward when the outside world
kisses him off. His misery festers into fuming depression explained
in a series of hard-knock events _ recapitulated in the film's
opening minutes with stills from the film's predecessor, ``Carne.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a comprehensive failure and unwitting societal victim whose
loser status has followed him into middle age. His depression
builds into a molten rage belied by his granite composure, but
elucidated in a bilious Uzi-speed voice-over narration.
</P>
<P>
   What elevates ``I Stand Alone'' from psycho-on-a-rampage
conventionality is the way it refuses to cut its umbilical tie with
the butcher. It doesn't grant him a subjectivity, it is his
subjectivity, hard-wired and jacked-in to the ugly erosion of his
perception, finally becoming a mind-blowing horror film. The
butcher's mental state has the caprice of a land mine: Check out
the gunshots that explode sporadically on the soundtrack when he
zeros in on an unwitting catalyst of his fury. The camera then
sprint-pans in for a jarring close-up on the victim.
</P>
<P>
   In a deft display of ideological craftsmanship, Noe never
reduces his butcher's contempt to the generic proportions of, say,
serial killing. When he pummels his pregnant girlfriend (Frankye
Pain) or uncorks his homophobia on some kid in a bar, something has
provoked him. But the important clarification Noe offers is that
insanity doesn't drive the butcher so much as his wallowing in his
pissed-off state.
</P>
<P>
   He's also middle-aged without having tasted so much as a leaf of
lettuce of his so-called salad days. French films grant much more
credence and respect to the nuance of aging than do American films.
The butcher's lost youth deglamorizes the film's violence,
depriving this man's behavior of the sexy nobility that an
18-year-old thug elicits.
</P>
<P>
   Every year the conversation on cruelty and violence seems to
swell around ``the year's most violent film.'' Last year, the
dogfight between the graphic and the simply gross yielded Todd
Solondz's misunderstood kitsch sitcom ``Happiness'' as the winner.
But year after year, the bar gets raised until violence is the
story, not the force that drives it. ``I Stand Alone'' plays like
Jean-Paul Sartre's ``Taxi Driver'' with the butcher as its Travis
Bickle _ a deranged loner on a self-redemptive quest to rescue a
girl.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the girl is not a hooker but his mentally ill
daughter (Blandine Lenoir, subdued, suggestive), whom he uses like
a holy, incestuous luffa to cleanse his scuzzy guilt. Their reunion
provides the film with its final trenchant sequence _ and Noe's
roiling assertion that monsters aren't born, they're made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0114 </DOCNO>
