<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-11 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFORD CALLS IT AS HE SEES IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's about time someone took a long, hard look at major league
umpires.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's Frank Deford talks with Richie Phillips, the umpires'
union leader, and Sandy Alderson, MLB senior vice president of
operations, and basically concludes that upcoming negotiations
between the sides will be nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips tells Deford the commissioner's office has not shown
the umpires ``any respect'' since the last contract. ``Let's see if
they can do without the unimportant people,'' Phillips threatens.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Umpires have become a powerful force. Their incomes and benefits
have increased dramatically since Phillips became union boss in
1978. Back then, an umpire couldn't make more than $40,000 a year.
Now, senior umpires can earn $250,000 a year with an astounding
five weeks of vacation during the 162-game season. More important,
Deford reports, it's virtually impossible to fire an umpire _
regardless of his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks that each umpire has their own strike zone,''
Alderson said. ``People have to believe there is accountability.
You know it's bad when hitters were telling me that they were more
concerned with which umpire was calling their game than the
opposing pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips doesn't want to hear any of it, blasting away at
broadcasters for pointing out badly called pitches and the
commissioner's office for trying to ``shove things down the
umpires' throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is not afraid to blast commissioner Bud Selig for
protecting the interests of the owners at the expense of the game's
overseers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selig walks like an owner,'' Phillips said. ``He talks like an
owner. He acts like an owner. He's slippery like an owner. In fact,
he is an owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's lead baseball analyst, Tim McCarver, was interviewed for
the piece. McCarver, a former catcher, told Deford the strike zone
has definitely changed, that umpires are not calling the high
strikes (the ones below the lettering and at the bellybutton) while
expanding the zone 2 inches off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is accountable,'' McCarver said. ``But whenever
anyone mentions accountability to the umpires, somehow it is
considered to be a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece airs Monday as a segment on ``Real Sports with Bryant
Gumbel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCarver likes what he sees &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of McCarver, he works the Red Sox-Mets game Friday
afternoon. It's still early, but McCarver likes what Jimy Williams
and pitching coach Joe Kerrigan have done with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was saying that trading away Mo Vaughn was a
mistake,'' McCarver said. ``People were saying that Jose Offerman
would never be able to replace Mo's offensive output. Well, they
have.'' He also praised Red Sox management for paying Pedro
Martinez the money. ``He is basically holding up the whole team,''
McCarver said. ``Dan Duquette and John Harrington are looking like
geniuses for hiring Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY's Childs has rebounded
</P>
<P>
   NBC has made a name for itself by producing interesting features
on athletes. One of the best aired during halftime of Game 5
Wednesday between the Knicks and Pacers, on Chris Childs. The
report detailed Childs's alcoholism and rehabilitation under John
Lucas. The former Boise State standout said he drank before and
after practices and games during his days in the Continental
Basketball Association. He was out of control until Lucas finally
convinced him that he was not only lying to his friends, but also
to himself. Childs has been sober for six years, and regardless of
his play, hats off to him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Buy this Rose by dozen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Olbermann hasn't exactly been red-hot since joining Fox
Sports Network. But he did have a funny bit on the possible
reinstatement of Pete Rose during his weekly commentary last week.
``So much Rose `stuff' had made its way into the hands of dealers:
game-used bats, baseballs, gloves, jerseys _ that by 1984 there was
a well-known joke at the card and autograph shows,'' Olbermann
said. ``Collector goes up to a dealer and says, `I want a Pete Rose
game-worn uniform.' Dealer answers, `Phillies, Reds, or Expos?'
Collector says, `Reds.' Dealer says, `Home or away?' Collector
says, `Home.' Dealer looks him in the eye and says, `What size
would you like?' We collectors knew Pete Rose needed money. For
what we did not know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Visual aid on `MNF' games &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABC will use the computer-generated first-down marker during
``Monday Night Football'' telecasts next season. The yellow line
was the most useful bit of gadgetry deployed in recent memory. ESPN
was the first to use the technology last year. WEEI (850) airs
``Monday Night Football'' games this season with Howard David and
Matt Millen working the booth. The deal includes the playoffs, the
Super Bowl, and Sunday night games, starting with the Sept. 12 game
between Cleveland and Pittsburgh at the new Cleveland Stadium. The
Racing Network, the first multichannel, satellite-delivered network
devoted to racing, launches a channel dedicated to greyhound
racing. The programming starts in July and features races from 12
tracks around the country . . . ABC airs the US men's soccer game
against Argentina Sunday, with Bob Ley and Ty Keough. Former
Toronto Blue Jays outfielder Joe Carter joins Sean McDonough to
call first-round action of the College World Series. Florida State
plays Texas A&AMP;M on Saturday at 1:30 p.m. CBS airs the championship
game June 19 at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
