<HEADER>
A1811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-DAUBACH-BO     06-11 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DAUBACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE BAT, WILL TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Brian Daubach's father, Dale, has been walking a
dozen miles a day for years as a letter carrier, delivering mail on
a route so close to home, he can stop in for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least that's how far he says he walks,'' Daubach said with
a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's driver's ed teacher, Jim Brueggeman, and his wife,
Gail, also a teacher, have organized family vacations around seeing
Daubach play baseball. That's how they've wound up spending time in
such exotic climes as Kingsport, Tenn., Pittsfield, Mass., and Port
St. Lucie, Fla., which is a beach town but not a place you'd want
to go in the dead of summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' Brueggeman said, ``you all have been calling him
DAW-back. It's DOW-bock. There are a lot of Germans around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? Call him whatever you want. Just put him in
the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something about going the extra mile that fits for Red
Sox rookie Brian Daubach. After a nine-year odyssey in the minors
that appeared to have run aground last winter, when he was about to
abandon his hopes of playing in the big leagues for a gig in Japan,
Daubach ranks as perhaps the most improbable story line in what
until recently has been a sweet spring for the Red Sox, who will be
trying to end a five-game losing streak when they meet the Mets
Friday night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach comes into the weekend with a .324 batting
average--three percentage points behind team leader Nomar
Garciaparra--six home runs and 20 RBIs in just 102 at-bats--and a
team-best slugging percentage of .637. Judge a hitter on a handful
of games at your own risk -- the game is littered with guys who've
carried a club for a month then faded from memory.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the Belleville Basher, who was the team's 25th man
coming out of camp and was demoted to the minors two weeks later
before being summoned back, has been a Dan Duquette blue-plate
special, a big bang for a cheap buck.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach is no stranger to the Mets, though their fans may be
only vaguely aware of the name. The Mets drafted Daubach nine years
ago, choosing him on the 19th round after being one of the only
teams that showed any interest in him coming out of high school.
Perhaps their scout was there the day Chuck Hasenstab, the baseball
coach at Belleville West High School for the last 33 years, saw
Daubach hit the longest home run he's ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one they still talk about,'' Hasenstab said.
``It's 325 feet down the right-field line here, 365 to the power
alley. Behind that is a huge stand of trees. They've been there for
ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Brian hit one over the trees. Nobody ever saw it come
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention it to Daubach, and he smiles. ``That's still probably
the longest home run I've ever hit,'' he said. ``I got it good. But
remember, I was using an aluminum bat.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in high school, Hasenstab encountered the same problem
that would dog Daubach later in his pro career. ``I really didn't
know where to play him,'' Hasenstab said. ``As a junior, I played
him in right field, but he's not very fast and he didn't have a
particularly strong arm. Then I thought maybe he could play first
base, and he wasn't bad there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Brian wound up choosing his own position. He
wanted to catch. He'd done a lot of catching when he was younger.
But there was never any doubt about his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about his future as a ballplayer, however, came as
quickly as the first winter after he received a $25,000 signing
bonus from the Mets, when he tore the anterior cruciate ligament in
his knee while playing a game of pickup basketball at home. There
would be three knee operations in the next five years, and after
all of that, Daubach was still in Class A ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to stay around the organization,'' said Daubach,
who was so desperate to retain his fragile hold on a job that he
agreed to be a replacement player in the spring of '95 during the
big-league work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, despite hitting 22 home runs for Double-A
Binghamton and earning a promotion to Triple-A for a cameo
appearance, the Mets let Daubach go. It was Steve Phillips, now the
team's general manager but then in charge of the farm system, who
informed Daubach the club was not putting him on the 40-man
major-league roster, and thus were making him a minor-league free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to give me a major-league invite and I would
sign,'' said Daubach, who had never made it to the Mets' big-league
camp during spring training. ``But they wouldn't give me a
major-league invite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weirdest thing is, the Mets always thought I was a better
player defensively. The Marlins thought I could hit, but they
didn't think I could play anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   All Daubach did, in two seasons at Triple-A Charlotte after
signing a minor-league contract with the Marlins, was hit. He
learned how to pull the ball and hit 21 home runs with 93 RBIs his
first season, then trumped that with numbers a Statman would love:
.316 average, 39 home runs, 124 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it took me by surprise when they released me,''
Daubach said. ``They'd seen a lot of me the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, in the eyes of one Marlins' official, was a 4-A
player--too good for Triple-A, not quite good enough for the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disillusioned when the Marlins released him,''
Brueggeman said. ``He was crushed. I think he was ready to go to
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's other options appeared limited. He'd taken a few
semesters of math classes at St. Louis University. And those
winters where he didn't go to Venezuela or the Dominican Republic
to play ball, he'd come back to Belleville, where he worked in the
Champs sporting goods store.
</P>
<P>
   But then I talked to Brian's dad,'' Brueggeman said, ``and he
told me the Red Sox had signed him. He was pretty excited about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, who had a booster in Sox coach Dave Jauss, his manager
in the Dominican Republic, had a good spring for the Sox in
Florida, hitting .313 with four home runs. That might not have made
any difference if Reggie Jefferson had been healthy, but Jefferson
had a bad back, and Daubach stuck as a left-handed hitter off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   It was with red eyes that Daubach came out of Jimy Williams'
office soon thereafter, told he was being demoted to the minors.
But when Williams moved Jose Offerman from first base to second and
benched Jeff Frye, Daubach was back, and in the lineup, either as
DH or alternating at first with Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   He's played so well, the Brueggemans are already planning their
next summer trip. Baltimore, perhaps, Atlanta or maybe even Tampa.
Big-league destinations, all.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many other people would have given up sooner?'' Brueggeman
asked. ``Brian just believed he could do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
