</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'M ON THE `100 MOST PUZZLED' LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aren't we all pleased as a puppy with two tails to be among the
living in the late 20th century? Otherwise we beings of fortuitous
timing would not have the opportunity to review the last 100 years
of history through the constant stream of ``100 best'' lists that
are pouring forth from erudite and eclectic minds everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 best movies, the 100 best works of English literature,
the 100 best stocks, the 100 best songs, the 100 best Internet Web
sites, the 100 best companies, the 100 best recipes for Spam. ...
It appears that any and every special-interest group and trade
association feels compelled to concoct a 100 best list. No harm in
it; they make for interesting, if often trivial, reading.
</P>
<P>
   One person's best list, of course, is going to contain another
person's losers. Everyone has his or her own standard for
determining what's ``the best.'' After the Modern Library, a
division of Random House, came out with the century's best
English-language novels, it was a sucker's bet that another group
of literati would counter with a different list because the first
wasn't inclusive/discriminating/wide-reaching/focused enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library's selections may be just dandy for people
devoted to the writings of dead white guys, but it didn't appeal to
readers whose tastes in literature run farther afield. No surprise,
then, when the Publishing Triangle this week released its 100
greatest gay and lesbian novels of all time. Publishing Triangle is
an organization of 250 gay and lesbian writers, editors, agents and
publishers, based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   So why should they be denied their nanosecond in the
end-of-the-century spotlight?
</P>
<P>
   I've never heard of, much less read, about 80 percent of the
books cataloged by Publishing Triangle. But I have read Nos. 13,
43, 64 and 67, and their inclusion on the list made me wonder if
I'd missed an important discussion period in my high school English
Lit class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Budd,'' ``Little Women,'' ``Moby Dick'' and ``To Kill A
Mockingbird'' rated among the best homosexual novels. Had my
school's library contained doctored copies of these literary
classics? Did I miss something in the relationship between Marmee
and Hannah in Louisa May Alcott's tale of a family's triumphs and
tragedies? Was there more to the mysterious Arthur ``Boo'' Radley
in Harper Lee's masterpiece on racism in the South than his
propensity to hide from public view?
</P>
<P>
   Moby Dick ``is'' a gay bar in Dallas, but who knew the
homosexual connection went beyond a wicked double entendre?
</P>
<P>
   ```Moby Dick' is very much about the survival of the
different,'' novelist Dorothy Allison, one of the judges compiling
the Publishing Triangle list, told The Associated Press. ``And
that's pretty much the situation for gay and lesbian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so books could make the list without the story actually
being about homosexuality?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, according to the AP.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criteria for what constitutes a `gay novel' were hazy,''
the story said. ``Titles apparently could make the list if the
author was gay, if the book had gay subject matter, or the text was
simply open to gay interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, what an interesting way to classify books.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa May Alcott, Herman Melville and Harper Lee _ possibly
homosexual? I had no idea _ probably because the sexuality of these
important American authors didn't matter one iota to the
generations of teachers who placed their works on the must-read
list.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just hope that their inclusion on the Publishing Triangle
list won't lead some narrow-minded homophobe to decide that it's
grounds enough to sweep these classics from the shelves of some
school library in the Bible Belt. Should that occur, one hopes that
the school board will give such a request as much consideration as
it deserves: absolutely none.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
