A1815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBUM-OF-WEEK-NYT &LR;      06-11 0251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICK COREA and ORIGIN: `CHANGE'  
(pr) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no question that Chick Corea's recently formed band,
Origin, has invigorated him; there's so much and so many different
kinds of jazz writing on ``Change,'' his new album, that it sounds
like a competitive young band leader angling for his first precious
shot of attention, rather than a figure who has been well known for
30 years and weathered one conceptual overhaul after another.
</P>
<P>
   His band, Origin _ a New York crew including the saxophonists
Steve Wilson and Bob Sheppard, the bassist Avishai Cohen, the
trombonist Steve Davis and the drummer Jeff Ballard _ is precise,
relentlessly playful with melody and rhythmically alert as it
negotiates the tango, flamenco, blues and splintered-melody mazes.
(One of them, ``L.A. Scenes,'' sounds like a cross between Eric
Dolphy and particularly evocative crime-film soundtrack music.)
</P>
<P>
   The structure of many of the arrangements is staggered: a quiet
pedaled solo piano passage segues into a saxophone-trombone duet
that leads to a line for double-bass and bass clarinet.
</P>
<P>
   A result is that the tunes create their own forward motion,
never stalling in the round-robin soloing that bedevils so much
mainstream jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Corea gets his say, though, especially in the trio ballad
``Compassion,'' and in uptempo pieces his fluid, skating lines skid
to a shuddering stop on dark chords. It is smart, exacting music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
