u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     06-11 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE REPLACEMENT WINDOWS REALLY BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. You have written in the past that regular single-glazed (one
layer of glass) windows with quality storm windows are as good as
double-glazed (two layers of glass) replacement. My son-in-law
feels replacements are better, and wants to replace the windows in
my three-decker at $275 each. I am not convinced. Are replacements
really better?
</P>
<P>
   H. M., Cambridge, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, no, replacements are not (necessarily) better, do not
insulate better than tight, single-glazed inner windows and quality
storms. That has been the handyman's position for some time: If
your doube-hung windows (those that slide up and down) are in good
shape, not rotted or broken, they don't need replacing.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two caveats: Old windows must be well
weather-stripped to make them weatherproof and tight in their
frames. The second caveat is that storms should be virtually
airtight, and if storms are old and rickety, they should be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   There is more. You said your windows have weights and pulleys
and ropes. That is good, but there is one drawback: You get a
certain loss of heat through the weight pockets because they are
uninsulated and it is not practical to insulate them. The handyman
feels that this heat loss is minor, and is worth tolerating because
such windows never get out of adjustment and are easily fixed if a
rope breaks. They are nothing like a spring-loaded window
(contemporary and replacement double-hung windows are
spring-loaded) which is miserable, sometimes impossible to adjust
or repair if the springs lose tension or break.
</P>
<P>
   So the key is quality. Cheap never works.
</P>
<P>
   The only windows the handyman feels should be replaced are metal
casements because they are impossible to insulate.
</P>
<P>
   Incidently, while replacement windows may save you some heat,
don't expect that savings to pay back the cost of the windows.
Suppose you have 36 windows; at $275 each that comes to $9,900. If
each unit costs $1,000 per season to heat, and the windows save you
10 percent, that is $100 per year per unit, or $300. At that rate,
it would take 33 years to pay for the windows. T'aint worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The air coming out of one of the hot air grates is smudging
the ceiling. I tried washing it with Spic and Span and water, but
it smeared. Am I doing something wrong, or is there another product
I can use to clean it?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE OLENIK, North Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You are doing nothing wrong, but your technique in cleaning
with the Spic and Span may need improving. Apply the solution to
the stain, and wait one or two minutes, without allowing the
solution to evaporte. This will give the solution time to do its
work in dissolving the dirt. Wipe with a clean, damp sponge.
</P>
<P>
   Then again this might not work anyway. Washing latex ceiling and
wall paint is iffy because the paint is naturally soft. In the good
old days, oil paints, even the flat oil, was hard and easily
washed. My father washed the oil-finished walls and ceilings with
something called Crystal cleaner, and everything came out
beautifully clean; no streaks, smudges.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is another product you can try: a dry sponge called
Wonder Sponge, made by Gonzo, and sold in hardware and building
stores and maybe supermarkets. It is used dry, and should work,
especially against soot and other oily dirt. Another dry sponge is
Professional Soot &AMP; Dirt Remover, made by Bloch/New England,
Worcester, MA 01603. Sold in hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce further staining, have your air ducts cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to put outdoor window caps over my windows, pediments
of some kind to dress up the house. Where can I find them, or a
catalog showing ones I could order?
</P>
<P>
   DOTTY HOGAN, Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Try Fypon of Stewartstown, Pa., makers of plastic foam
components, which look good, stand up to the weather and can be
painted. The choice of caps and pediments is very large. For a
catalog, call Fypon at 717-993-2593.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In my son's new house, the previous owner coated the driveway
to ``Make it look nice.'' It may look OK, but the sealer stuff gets
sticky when it gets warm outdoors. Can he cover it again, or must
he get rid of it?
</P>
<P>
   CAROL MASALSKY, Stoughton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I hear it more and more: the ``improvements'' people put slap
dash on their houses before selling, which don't work for long. The
stuff the man used may be motor oil or similar product, not
ncessariy designed as a driveway sealer, which promises to stay
sticky forever. He did you no favors.
</P>
<P>
   I think your son has two choices, other than getting after the
previous owner like ugly on an ape. This first is chancy: Apply a
proper sealer (tar emulsion, Jennite is one brand) over the old and
hope this works. If it doesn't, the driveway is in worse shape than
before. The second choice, more likely to succeed but more work, is
to scrape off that sticky sealer and remove residue, then reseal
with a tar emulsion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
