<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1835 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV13     06-11 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIXED-INCOME EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I understand that the value of fixed-income securities moves
inversely to interest rate changes. As a result, the value of
fixed-income securities has increased sharply over the past few
years, due to the effect of declining interest rates. The trend in
interest rates could very well reverse itself and begin increasing,
causing the value of fixed-income securities to decline. Under
these circumstances, can you explain the rationale to justify
investing in bonds or bond funds at this time to balance an
investment portfolio. Wouldn't it be better to leave the portfolio
unbalanced and take advantage of the rising stock price trend,
rather than move some of the portfolio into fixed-income
investments.
</P>
<P>
   C.A., Needham, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It would be silly to invest in fixed-income instruments and
funds if you KNEW that interest rates will advance and fixed-income
holdings will lose value. But the fact that nobody does know for
certain what will happen in the markets is the reason that people
seek a balanced portfolio, one designed to make the best of any
likely sequence of markets.
</P>
<P>
   The same lack of assurance applies on the stock side. Bear in
mind that when the stock markets take a slide, it can be very deep
and very painful for investors, but when bond markets go sour, it's
usually a matter of 12 to 24 months at most, and the slide is
frequently followed by a substantial recovery. In the last decade,
1994 was the worst year for the fixed-income markets. That year,
the average intermediate-term bond fund showed a 3.78 percent loss
(and it recovered with a 17.37 percent recovery in 1995). Compare
this with what many observers sometimes discuss as a healthy
stock-market correction -- bringing losses in excess of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I think it's problematic to project that the
fixed-income markets will go into a long slide. Consider the fact
that most economists say we are nearing the end of one of the
longest economic booms in recent history. Once this expansion comes
to an end, it will bring the normal side effects -- lower
employment, a sour stock market, etc. And when the economy is
fading, what do the politicians do in efforts to revive it, or at
least to slow the slide? Why, they cut interest rates, effectively
pumping money into the economy in efforts to create more jobs. For
the owner of bonds, this means rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, consider why most people buy bonds and bond funds. They
buy them first for the yield, which is typically considerably
better than they can do with banks and other absolutely secure
investments. They do it, secondly, because bonds are likely to
supply a steady stream of income, regardless of what the markets
are doing. And, thirdly, they buy bonds because they are convinced
that over the long haul they will be less volatile than stocks,
opting for the relatively steady principal value and the handsome
income stream rather than the prospect for higher but riskier
returns of the stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a single man, 41, with all of my money _ approximately
$25,000 _ in a regular savings account. I make $35,000 a year and I
would like to retire at age 62. My friends give their advice
freely, such as buying income property, mutual funds and so forth.
What is your advice as to how to make my money grow to its best
potential?
</P>
<P>
   A.D., Watertown &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A key question is what you view as the purpose of this money.
It appears to be for general savings, kept in the bank to provide a
financial buffer against emergencies, and later to help you to
finance your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   What I suggest you do is determine how much of the money
represents emergency savings, and how much might have been put
aside for a short-term goal, such as buying a car in the next
couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the purposes are, I suggest that you put the emergency
money and savings that you expect to draw upon during the course of
the next five years in a mutual fund company's money market fund.
While these funds are not insured, they invest in extremely safe
assets, such as government notes, loans to banks, and commercial
paper, which is short-term loans to corporations. A typical money
market fund has an average portfolio duration of about 50 days.
With these funds, the value of your investment normally doesn't
change -- shares are always valued at $1 each. But the interest
rate being earned changes daily, very closely tracking interest
rates in general.
</P>
<P>
   While in theory, bad investments might make a money market fund
break the buck, in historical experience none offering shares to
the public ever has, and I view the likelihood of it happening as
minuscule. Almost every major mutual fund family offers one or more
money market funds, and you can expect to get between 4.5 percent
and 5 percent on average in the current markets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's suppose you put $5,000 in a money fund. What about
the rest? The big question here is how much risk you can stand.
Most people save for retirement using mutual funds invested in
common stocks, and over a long haul such as the 21 years you have
until your anticipated retirement, it's reasonable to expect that a
diversified stock portfolio will deliver about 10 percent average
annual returns. If that happened in your case, that $20,000 would
grow to $148,023 over the course of the next 21 years, even if you
made no additional contributions. But as it grew, it would also
bring you tax bills based on that growth. For that reason, I
suggest that this year you move $2,000 of that money to a Roth IRA
account, where its will have a tax-free status. Each year, move
another $2,000 to the Roth, and by the time you retire, almost all
of the funds will have tax-free status.
</P>
<P>
   The final big question is how much risk you want to assume. For
people with a normal appetite for risk, I'd suggest all-stock index
funds. If you follow this reasoning, you might put $14,000 into
Vanguard Index 500, a fund which tracks the Standard and Poor's
Index of the nation's 500 leading companies, another $3,000 in
Vanguard Mid-Cap Index fund, which tracks an index of medium-sized
funds, and a similar amount in Vanguard Small-Cap Index fund, which
seeks to track an index of the country's smaller stocks. But before
you make such moves, telephone the company (1-800-662-6273) and ask
for prospectuses for the funds. These will spell out the risks, and
hive you charts showing historical performances; here you can study
what happened in the sour years as well as the sweet ones.
</P>
<P>
   If those sour years make you nervous, you might consider looking
at some more tame fodder -- mutual funds which divide their
investments between stocks and bonds and cash. Solid entries among
the major fund families in these categories are Fidelity Asset
Manager and Fidelity Puritan (my favorite among the four funds
mentioned here), Vanguard Asset Allocation and Vanguard Balanced
Index. A careful study of the prospectuses of these funds should
show you that the risks are lower, but the potential rewards are
lower as well. You'll have to decide what level of risk suits you
and act accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, unless you have a strong pension program that you can
rely on in retirement, you should step up your savings level as
much as you can. Remember, the first dollars that go into
retirement savings are the ones which are going to produce the
highest long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
