<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-COKE-$ADV13-COX     06-11 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-COKE-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CASTRO FUMES IN BATTLE OVER TRADEMARK FOR CUBA'S POPULAR RUM
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Despite a U.S. trade embargo, ``Coke Is It!'' in
communist Cuba, which imports the popular soft drink from third
countries. But, in the future, will Coke be the real thing?
</P>
<P>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro has threatened to manufacture fake
Coca-Cola in retaliation for a recent New York court ruling against
Havana in a fight over the trademark for Havana Club rum, Cuba's
most-prized liquor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should complain if we start using any North American
brand to produce and commercialize products. Maybe there are some
who say, 'Caramba! Let's taste Cuban Coca-Cola','' Castro pondered
in a recent speech.
</P>
<P>
   The tug-of-war pits Cuba and its French partner, Pernod Ricard,
against the Bermuda-based liquor giant, Bacardi, both of whom hope
to sell Havana Club rum in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least, Bacardi's hanging on to the most rope.
</P>
<P>
   Pernod Ricard, which markets the Havana Club brand outside the
United States, sued Bacardi in 1996 after it introduced its own
Havana Club rum here.
</P>
<P>
   But the April court ruling agreed that Bacardi _ and not the
Cuban-French partnership _ should be allowed to market rum under
the Havana Club name because Bacardi had purchased it from the
original owners, a Cuban rum-making family whose properties were
confiscated by Castro's government.
</P>
<P>
   And that has Castro seething with anger, and threatening to
limit protection of U.S. trademarks such as Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Baskin, a spokesman for the Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co.,
said only that he ``hopes Cuba will abide by trademark rules as we
have always abided by trademark rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. embargo prevents Cuban-made Havana Club rum
from being sold in the United States, it's clear the Cuban-French
partnership is jockeying for a position in a post-embargo era.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba and Pernod Ricard, which formed their partnership in 1993,
already hold trademark rights to the Havana Club name in 170 other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Bacardi officials say they formally bought the rights to the
Havana Club name from the Arechabala family in 1997, although ``an
agreement in principle'' was reached as early as 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cuban-French partnership claims the name was abandoned
by the family, which fled the country after Castro nationalized the
rum industry in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government did legally register the name at the United
States Patent and Trademark Office in 1976 after the family failed
to renew the trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family clearly relinquished its rights to the trademark,''
said Pierre-Marie Chateauneuf, Pernod Ricard's attorney in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   He said the judge might have agreed if not for a controversial
law pushed through Congress last year banning U.S. courts from
upholding trademarks that were confiscated, unless the original
holders, or their successors, agree to the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was sponsored by Sen. Bob Graham, a Democrat, and
Sen. Connie Mack, a Republican, both from Florida, at the behest of
Bacardi, which enjoys a major presence in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the measure because it is important to prevent the
illegal confiscation of trademarks,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pernod Ricard, which plans to appeal the New York court
ruling, argues that the law is illegal and prejudiced, and has
urged the European Union to file a complaint with the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Such a complaint would fan the flames of an even bigger showdown
between Europe and the United States, already embroiled in a trade
war over bananas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this law was a piece of self-interest legislation
conceived by Bacardi's attorneys,'' Chateauneuf said.
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Gibson, vice president and general counsel for Bacardi,
said the law simply codifies the principles of international law
that say foreign confiscations can't be recognized.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, many U.S. companies are worried that Havana may
stop honoring their trademarks, meaning a Cuban or any foreign
company could take the names of U.S. products and make them their
own in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 U.S. companies have registered trademarks in Cuba,
which include Coca-Cola, PepsiCo, Calvin Klein, and the Hard Rock
Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically Cuba has been protective of intellectual
property, but now I believe that companies, especially those that
have yet to register their trademarks, may have reason to be
concerned,'' said John Kavulich, president of the U.S.-Cuba Trade
and Economic Council, a New York-based research group.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech, Castro chastised the United States for its
``bald-faced violation of international law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope no one complains if one day we begin to produce
Coca-Cola,'' he said. ``We might be able to make it better, and on
the can we'll put: Cuban Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
