<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICKENPOX-COX     06-11 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKENPOX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chickenpox vaccine message gets through
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It used to be that Dr. Karen Dewling had to persuade
parents to give the chickenpox vaccine a try. But in the past six
months she has seen a dramatic turnaround, with mothers and fathers
asking for the shots for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have really caught on to the fact that this is a good
disease to prevent,'' said Dewling, a pediatrician at the Emory
Clinic North in Duluth, Ga.. ``A lot more parents are getting the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   To make sure the trend continues, a Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention advisory committee has just issued new
recommendations about the chickenpox vaccine. The Committee on
Immunization Practices wants all children entering day care centers
or elementary school to receive immunization against chickenpox,
officially known as varicella, along with polio and measles
vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, only about one in every four children is vaccinated
against the disease, a figure that puts the state just below the
national average for chickenpox shots, according to the CDC. But
that number could increase dramatically by the 2000-2001 school
year. That's because several groups, including the state's
pediatricians, are pushing the Georgia Department of Human
Resources to change the state's guidelines and be in compliance
with the federal recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   It would take several steps, however, to make the chickenpox
vaccine mandatory in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Department of Human Resources board would have to
propose new regulations and air them at a public hearing, according
to Barbara Joy, a spokeswoman for the agency. If no revisions were
suggested, the board would have to take a vote. If the measure
passed, the guidelines could become a reality. But the process of
getting doctors' offices, public health departments and schools
ready for the new guidelines could take at least four months.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 10 states and the cities of Washington and San
Antonio require that children receive chickenpox vaccinations. Five
other states are considering similar regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The new interest in making the vaccine mandatory arises because
scientists are more comfortable with the safety of chickenpox
immunization. Since 1995, more than 16 million doses have been
administered, according to Merck &AMP; Co., which manufactures the
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``School and child care requirements are an effective strategy
in increasing vaccine coverage,'' said Jane Seward, chief of
varicella activity at the CDC's national immunization program.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations could also help the government meet its
Healthy People 2010 chickenpox goals of vaccinating more than 90
percent of children by age 2 and more than 95 percent of children
entering school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implementing (such) requirements will be the most effective
way to achieve these goals _ as it has been for other childhood
vaccines,'' Seward said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, between 50 and 100 children die of chickenpox every
year, and more than 5,000 hospital admissions are attributed to the
illness. One in every 49 people who contracts it experiences
serious complications, such as skin infections, pneumonia or
central nervous system infections.
</P>
<P>
   But Dewling said that when the vaccine was first released in
1995, many people were suspicious of its benefits and concerned
about possible side effects. Some parents worried that the immunity
will decrease over time, making adults more vulnerable to
chickenpox than they would have been as children. Adults have a
much higher risk of complications if they contract chickenpox,
although Japanese studies have indicated that the vaccine is
protective for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dewling said many of those fears have been allayed by more solid
data about the shots' safety. ``I think you'll find gradual
acceptance as many of these issues are put to rest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, doctors say, the vaccine should be administered to
children between 12 and 18 months old and again when they are 13
years old. The immunization has been shown to prevent 95 percent of
serious chickenpox cases, although some children will still get the
disease _ in a much milder form.
</P>
<P>
   Chickenpox is a virus spread through the air and by direct
contact with skin lesions. The incubation time is 11 to 21 days,
and the disease is contagious from one to two days before a rash
appears until four days after a rash occurs. The majority of cases
happen in the winter and spring, with 90 percent of those affected
being younger than 10.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
