<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-11 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW GENDER MAY INFLUENCE OUR RELATIONS WITH ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Does your dog keep better track of your hormonal
cycles than you do? Why do women outnumber men at animal rights
gatherings by a ratio of 3 or 4 to 1? Why is it usually men who are
responsible for violent animal cruelty? Is the woman in a household
closer emotionally to the family pet than the man is? Do the health
benefits of owning a pet apply equally to men and women? And do
canine characters hold the key to understanding ``Wuthering
Heights''?
</P>
<P>
   These were a few of the eclectic questions asked and discussed
at a conference last week at the Veterinary Hospital of the
University of Pennsylvania, a gathering run by James Serpell,
director of the Center for the Interactions for Animals and
Society, and author of ``In the Company of Animals'' (Cambridge
University Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``Men, Women, and Animals: The Influence of Gender on Our
Relations with Animals and Nature'' may not have answered all the
questions posed, but it pointed out how much we have to learn about
how gender affects our relationships with wildlife and pets.
</P>
<P>
   Academics, scholars, animal welfare experts, social workers, and
veterinarians gathered to hash out notions of how men and women see
the natural world in different ways, and further how animals
perceive us differently according to gender.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing talks came from Dr. Myrna Milani of
Charlestown, N.H. A veterinarian specializing in behavioral issues,
she says 98 percent of her practice is dedicated to problems of
aggression. She has been sniffing out the influence of biochemical
signals and body language, and has paid attention to phenomena that
other behaviorists have observed: Some dogs grow protective of
female owners at the onset of pregnancy; and certain dogs will
become aggressive toward boys who are going through puberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Female owners of aggressive male dogs,'' Milani says, ``report
that their pets appear more aggressive toward them during the
period preceding their menses and during the menses itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Milani believes that humans often unintentionally give off
biochemical cues (such as through natural pheromones) and
behavioral signals (for instance, sitting on the floor while your
dog is on the couch cedes status to the animal) that may make an
aggressive dog moreso.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of scientific inquiry is required to puzzle and
plot this all out, but Milani believes that leadership qualities
can be conveyed in the wild _ and at home _ through chemical
signals. ``Certainly, observations of leader dogs and studies of
successful men strongly suggest that testosterone or, more likely,
some pheromonal component of it, communicates leadership,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict and harmony between man or woman and beast dominated
other presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Lockwood of the Humane Society of the United States
discussed animal cruelty. He pointed out that 90 percent of
homicides in this country are committed by men, so it was no
surprise that men are responsible for the vast majority of animal
cruelty cases. In his study of newspaper clippings over two years,
males accounted for all cases of mutilations, draggings, and
poisonings.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockwood doesn't think that harming animals is an
exclusively male occupation. He points to the strange phenomenon of
``animal collecting,'' in which a person hoards animals in filthy
and unhealthy conditions. Women accounted for slightly more than
half of these kinds of abuse cases in his study. And furthermore,
Lockwood discussed a rare but odd disorder that is the pet owner's
version of Munchausen by Proxy, in which an owner will
intentionally make a pet sick in order to nurture it back to
health.
</P>
<P>
   Well, how about looking for a little harmony between owners and
pets? Susan Phillips Cohen conducted a survey to sort out how men
and women differ in their intimacy with pets. She found from
working at the huge Animal Medical Center in New York City that
just about all clients coming in described their pets as ``a member
of the family.'' But what do they mean by that? Cohen randomly
selected 201 clients to fill out questionnaires, which measured
intimacy, psychological kinship, and bond with pets.
</P>
<P>
   She found big differences between men and women. Women felt
``significantly'' more intimacy with the closest pet than the
closest person in their lives. And they had fewer problems with
pets than men did. Responding to questions about how animals are
different from us, men tended to point out things pets cannot do,
like talk. Women tended to concentrate on how pets are better than
people, as in ``my dog never needs his space.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Herzog, a professor at Western Carolina University in
North Carolina, studied why women dominate the scenes at animal
rights demonstrations. Looking over various studies, Herzog pointed
out that women are more likely than men to attribute mental states
to other species, to feel that animal research is morally wrong,
and to believe that animals should have rights. ``Indeed,'' he
says, ``gender has consistently been found to be the single most
important factor in predicting attitudes toward animal welfare
issues.'' Just why is open to debate: Is it socialization?
Differing approaches to relationships? A feeling of shared
oppression? Is Darwinian psychology at work?
</P>
<P>
   Another big mystery is whether men and women differ in the
health benefits of pet ownership. Though there have been studies
over the years tracking how pet ownership can help decrease blood
pressure and anxiety and increase longevity in certain patients,
none indicates gender differences. Erika Friedmann, a professor at
Brooklyn College of City University of New York, discovered that
many of the long-term studies focused on men, and many of the
short-term studies involved premenopausal women. Many studies do
not even identify the sex of the subjects. All people do not
benefit equally from pets, Friedmann concludes, and future studies
should take care to identify gender, race, and ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Emily Bronte and dogs? Many of us in the audience had
forgotten just how central dogs are to the action in ``Wuthering
Heights.'' From nursing curs to pampered spaniels, dogs illuminate
Bronte's thoughts about human nature and wild impulses versus the
comfort of the hearth. Dogs are a ``threshold species,'' according
to Maureen Adams of the University of San Francisco, standing
between two worlds in a book that crosses many boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, it seems right that there were more questions than
answers at the conference. We are ourselves at the threshold of
exploring our own nature in relation to animals. For now, maybe all
we can say is that men are from Mars, women are from Venus _ and
dogs are from Pluto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
