<SLUG> BC-ARMADILLO-MEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMADILLOS NOT SEEN AS FOOD THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ People who eat armadillos are unlikely to
contract leprosy as long as the meat had been either frozen or
cooked, the San Francisco Health Department officials told members
of the Animal Control and Welfare Commission in response to
concerns about the animals and the disfiguring disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless somebody's scarfing up road kill, they shouldn't come
upon that problem,'' said Ben Gale, the department's director of
Environmental Health.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, armadillos could be removed from the list of
animals that are legally sold in the city as food, commission
chairman Richard Schulke said.
</P>
<P>
   Gale told commissioners that his health inspectors were able to
identify one Oklahoma company that supplies armadillos to Chinatown
merchants and discovered that the company did not have permits to
sell them. The Health Department has asked the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration to look into sanctions against the company, Sooner
Aquatics, Gale said.
</P>
<P>
   Gale said health inspectors recently found four armadillos in
two stores in Chinatown, but employees at the stores were unable to
identify from whom they received the shipment. The frozen
armadillos were impounded and will be disposed of unless the
dealers are properly licensed, Gale said.
</P>
<P>
   Gale emphasized that it is legal to sell armadillos for
consumption, but they must be supplied by businesses with permits.
</P>
<P>
   Gale said that even though as many as 15 percent of armadillos
found in the South have leprosy, humans do not run the risk of
contracting the disease if the animal has been frozen or cooked
properly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
