<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-POWERS-HN     06-11 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-POWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IRREVERENT `AUSTIN POWERS' STRIKES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' insults fat people. It
insults little people. It insults Scots, Arabs, Germans, lesbians
and the LPGA tour. It is sophomoric, scatological, brazenly
derivative, anatomically obsessed and contributes no major insights
into the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   But it's funny. Extremely funny. Funny in a relentless, cheesy,
bonks you-over-the-head with-stupid-jokes sort of way, like
spending an afternoon with a geeky cousin who won't stop cracking
puns.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jay Roach with the same cartoon splashiness that
marked the first film, ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' is both puerile
and charming, a terrifically amusing follow-up to what has become a
cult hit.
</P>
<P>
   The original, for those of you who don't have a teen-age boy
lurking somewhere, starred Mike Myers as a vintage-1960s,
cryogenically preserved British agent with cruddy teeth, groovy
velvet suits and a taste for shagging. The sequel marks the
reappearance of both Austin Powers and his world-dominating
archnemesis, the nefarious Dr. Evil (also Myers), last seen
floating through space in a Big Boy statue.
</P>
<P>
   The new film begins with Dr. Evil's return to Earth, where he
reconvenes with his yes-men the loyal Number Two (Robert Wagner),
the stern Frau Farbissina (Mindy Sterling), the cat Mr.
Bigglesworth and meets his new clone, Mini-Me (Verne J. Troyer),
who is one-eighth the size of the original. He also reunites with
his slacker son, Scott (Seth Green) popping up for a surprise visit
on ``Jerry Springer'' (an episode titled ``My Father Is Evil and
Wants to Take Over the World!'').
</P>
<P>
   So fortified, Dr. Evil hatches a plan to go back to the late
1960s via a time machine and steal Austin Powers' mojo (i.e., ``the
libido, the life force, the essence'') from his cryogenic chamber
the idea being, of course, that if Austin is minus his mojo, he
won't be able to defeat Dr. Evil's latest plan for world
domination.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is robbed of his mojo, which turns out to be red Jell-O
streaked with small squiggly objects. Doing the ugly deed is Fat
Bastard, with Myers again, in prosthetic flab _ an obese Scottish
operative who weighs a metric ton and provides 99.9 percent of the
movie's bathroom humor. Austin immediately senses his mojo is
missing. So he hops into his own time machine (actually a New
Beetle with a snazzy paint job) and zooms back to the era of lava
lamps, where the plot goes off in ever more convoluted directions.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that Austin's escapades bring him into contact
with a variety of femmes, among them a looming Russian named Ivana
Humpalot (Kristen Johnston) and a CIA agent in hot pants named
Felicity Shagwell (Heather Graham). If the cast has a weak point,
it's Graham: Someone forgot to tell her to ham it up. The wide-eyed
fawn routine is no substitute for campy overacting, which everyone
else in the film seems to grasp. Otherwise, ``The Spy Who Shagged
Me'' is good, dopey fun.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``Austin Powers'' spoofed James Bond flicks, but this
one spoofs everything _ Will Smith videos, prog rock,
``Independence Day.'' ``Star Wars'' gets hit repeatedly, from its
pre-credits opening scroll to the Death Star. Even Robert Wagner
himself gets tweaked, in a freakishly accurate imitation by Rob
Lowe as a young Number Two. The film is stuffed with cameos,
including Burt Bacharach, Elvis Costello and Tim Robbins, a few of
them strung together in a marvelous pastiche of bad-taste genitalia
humor that cannot be described here.
</P>
<P>
   What can be described is the movie's opening credits, in which
Austin cavorts nude through a chi-chi hotel, his unmentionables
hidden by props. If nothing else, ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who
Shagged Me'' features some of the giddiest product placements ever
committed to film.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, we get shots of Dr. Evil wiping cappuccino foam from
his nose at his HQ in Seattle. It seems to be the Space Needle.
And, like everything else in Western civilization, it has been
converted to a Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
