<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-GRIEF-BOMBS-NYTS     06-11 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-GRIEF-BOMBS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 BENEATH the FALLING BOMBS  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By STEVEN ERLANGER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    In a moral universe full of shadows and grief, I have been an
American correspondent working in a country at war with America.
 &HT;    Of course, it is the NATO alliance that has been formally
attacking Yugoslavia, but no one, Serb or Albanian, believed that
this was anything but Washington's war.
 &HT;    My most searing memory is not of physical horror _ of the
charred corpses from a bombed passenger train, or the severed head
near a rocketed column of Albanian refugees. All that comes with
war in the Balkans, when history and high explosives collide.
 &HT;    What will stay with me longest is the memory of two large
bearded Serbian men, hours apart, weeping uncontrollably in my
arms, the arms of the aggressor, over the deaths of their friends
from an American missile. Their friends, a technician and a makeup
artist, died in the April 23 attack on Radio Television Serbia
headquarters in Belgrade. They were not even the people who made
the programs, which NATO had decided, in its infinite capacity for
misunderstanding this country, were the propaganda that fed Serbian
resistance and which remained on the air in any case.
 &HT;    Neither man expected me to apologize for the attack, which I
would not and could not do. In a sense, I think, they were weeping
not only for their friends, but also for the death of their own
misconceptions of America. What began as a campaign against the
Yugoslav military, to get Slobodan Milosevic to capitulate quickly
over Kosovo, veered, perhaps out of frustration, into a psy-ops war
aimed also at civilians, at their electricity and their water and
their heating plants. A month into the war, no Serb believed that
the bombs were not aimed at them, or that NATO hit anything _ even
hospitals or the Chinese Embassy _ by error.
 &HT;    So I have been slapped by an old lady and hit by a man, both
offended at hearing English, and I have simply walked away. I have
heard Serbian policemen, at a scene of bombing devastation in
Aleksinac, when Western reporters joked to inure themselves to the
bloody human remains on which they were unavoidably stepping, say,
``Listen to the bastards, speaking English and laughing.''
 &HT;    I have been yelled at by drunks and waylaid at parties, with
normally polite people lecturing me about the tortured history of
Kosovo and demanding that I defend the half-truths uttered by the
NATO spokesman, Jamie P. Shea.
 &HT;    Sometimes, full of resentment, I did defend Shea, even when I
knew from my reporting that some of what he said was wrong. Because
not to do so was to accept the grotesque moral equivalency _ both
sides lie, we're victims just as much as the Albanians _ in which
too many Serbs want to wallow. And sometimes, also full of
resentment, I've taken pleasure at telling particularly smug Serbs
just what their forces have done, in their name, to the ethnic
Albanians of Kosovo.
 &HT;    We journalists think we are all so charming and self-evidently
objective. But even the waitresses who have brought me coffee for
weeks, when there was electricity to make it, could barely disguise
their disgust with us, the vultures of war, whom they have served
in a hotel that got priority for electricity as if it were a
hospital. I could tell the mornings when NATO's bombs have kept
their kids up all night, with only a flashlight to keep away the
dark, and the mornings when there was no running water. They would
tell me that they were angry with me as an American, another odd
form of trust, and yet they wanted to know what I'd discovered,
whether it reflected well on their country or not.
 &HT;    As for what I think, well, that's a different matter. I do not
tell them or anyone, not completely. My job is to find out what
they think, and how they live and manage, and to try to present
them as real, and not as caricatures from some movie about American
good and Nazi evil.
 &HT;    Of course from Washington's point of view, and in sharp contrast
to its rhetoric about the Balkan Hitler, this has scarcely been a
war at all; it has been more like a police action from the sky.
Here I feel some shame. Looked at from beneath the bombs, NATO's
conduct can seem cowardly. The Serbs knew they were powerless to
prevent NATO from doing what it pleased, but they have been
insulted by the invisibility of the enemy. They sense that it is a
way of pretending that their lives are expendable, the ``collateral
damage'' of NATO's desperate effort to retain credibility in a
mismanaged war. But many Serbs also know that what their forces
have done to the Albanians of Kosovo is horrible, and few have much
love for Milosevic. Many would be happy to see him gone, or on
trial, or hanged.
 &HT;    Perhaps soon, some will try again to depose him.
 &HT;    But I think the Serbs, however misled, have a right to their
patriotism, and to their own national myths, and to their grief.
All this must be reported; their grief, at least, I have shared.
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Steven Erlanger is The New York Times bureau chief for Central
Europe and the Balkans.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
