<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JOY-RIDE (Austin, Texas) _ A 16-year-old Round Rock, Texas, boy
with four hours of flight training sneaked out of a juvenile group
home with a friend and took his flight instructor's Piper Cherokee
for an overnight joy ride. After a trip in which they landed,
refueled, took off and landed again, the two boys boy were picked
up eight hours later and 110 miles away. They could have driven
there faster, but the boy didn't have a driver's license. By JOHN
GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush takes his
yet-to-be-announced presidential campaign on the road for the first
time, beginning with stops in Iowa on Saturday. Leading in the
polls and in raising money, the Republican governor's four-day trip
also will include visits to New Hampshire and Massachusetts. By
LAURA TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   MALPRACTICE-TEXAS (Houston) _ In what must be one of the state's
biggest medical malpractice verdicts, a Beaumont jury awards nearly
$27 million to the family of a woman whose brain ailment was
misdiagnosed. The resulting operation and complications caused her
to suffer brain damage and a chemical imbalance that causes her to
eat constantly. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NBA-EAST (New York) _ The New York Knicks need one more
victory to become the first No. 8 seed to advance to the NBA
Finals. Tonight, in the NBA Eastern Conference Finals, the Knicks
take on the Indiana Pacers. (Game time is 9 p.m. EDT.) By JONATHAN
FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ For the first time since last year's
National League playoffs, the Houston Astros face the San Diego
Padres at the Astrodome in the opener of a three-weekend series.
(Game time is 8 p.m. EDT.) By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Washington) _ President Clinton leaves Tuesday
for a seven-day trip to Europe for meetings with world leaders,
including a summit with Russian President Boris Yeltsin that may be
the last rendezvous of the chummy ``Bill and Boris'' partnership
before the United States and Russia plunge into presidential
campaigns to choose their successors. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-TRUSTS (Washington) _ Elouise Cobell won a ``genius
grant'' from the MacArthur Foundation for her savvy banking skills,
but even she can't figure out how much money the government owes
her and hundreds of thousands of other Indians. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore formally opens
his presidential bid next week on the steps of the Smith County
courthouse in Carthage, Tenn., his ancestral home. Gore supporters
hope the announcement jump starts a campaign beset by a lack of
focus and voter perception that Gore himself is kind of a bore.
Republicans are heartened by polls showing Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Elizabeth Dole both leading Gore, but they do not see Gore
as a pushover. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITY-EXAMS (Moundsville, W.Va.) _ Bradley Miller lost his
bid for Social Security disability insurance after what he
describes as a 10-minute quickie medical examination that yielded a
detailed six-page doctor's report concluding he was fit to work.
Miller's case and dozens of others like it nationwide illustrate
what lawyers and advocates describe as a tendency of states and
Washington to rely on mass-production medical practices that do an
inadequate job of determining whether claimants are actually
disabled. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Let it be recorded that Bill
Clinton is a human Phoenix, rising repeatedly with renewed life
from the ashes of doom and destruction, like the colorful bird of
Egyptian religious legend. The latest example of his ability to
ride to triumph when disaster was predicted is the tenuous peace
agreement in Yugoslavia. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
