<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-11 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY TO WATCH PIRATED `BUFFY' EVEN SCARIER THAN THE SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're sitting in a dimly lit guest house overlooking a hilly
street in a tree-lined neighborhood, and the fact that I can't say
which guest house along what hilly street in which tree-lined
neighborhood is a bit unnerving. This deal of silence was struck
before my trip here, and at one point my host wonders aloud if a
blindfold might have been necessary, delivering this comment in
complete and utter seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike'' is 16 years old and quite aware of the consequences
that come with standing up for your principles. Like going to jail,
which is a long shot; being hit with a stiff fine, which is a
remote possibility; or having Dad confiscate the shiny black
Toshiba laptop, which is highly likely.
</P>
<P>
   He talks of being able to go anywhere and do anything when
plugged in and fired up, and that's why this crowd has been
assembled here, circling him like believers around a messiah.
</P>
<P>
   The season finale of the teen drama ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
_ the one the WB network pulled because its violent story line
seemed insensitive to the families of slain Colorado students _ is
the spiritual connection. Here, it's being played out on Mike's
laptop. Small, grainy, jerky, and sounding like a transistor radio
in the middle of nowhere, the video shows Sarah Michelle Gellar's
Buffy leading the charge against a 60-foot demon who has vowed to
massacre the entire senior graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   Ooohs and aaaahs echo around me, but all I see are shadowy
figures and crackling voices.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, out of respect for a network that spent $1 million to
produce this one-hour episode, that's all you'll get out of me.
</P>
<P>
   I'd come here at Mike's request, partly to satisfy my curiosity
(like everyone else, I saw Part 1 and am experiencing Buffy
withdrawal) and also figuring it might at least make an interesting
column.
</P>
<P>
   You be the judge on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Mike is one of many savvy Internet wizards who downloaded
bootleg copies of the episode when the series aired in Canada. This
clearly constitutes copyright piracy, but because this is the
Internet, where policing is still in its infancy, who knows what
the rules are?
</P>
<P>
   Still, he declines to tell exactly how or where he got it. The
episode had been copied on Canadian television and plastered on Web
sites. Those who knew where to find it merely copied and
downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   In this two-level house, a dozen others scamper around us,
munching on doughnuts and sipping what looks like punch. All are
teen-agers, except for a guy lodged quietly on the floor in the
corner, furiously knocking down cups of coffee and tossing a Nerf
ball at a cat, which doesn't move. The guy is dressed in black
pants, shirt and baseball cap, and looks no younger than 30.
</P>
<P>
   Most are fans of ``Buffy,'' although one 16-year-old high school
girl in jeans and halter top merely claims to be a proponent of the
public's right to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's censorship,'' she says. ``You can't control what we see.
It's our decision to either watch something or not watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Halter-top girl leaves as soon as the show starts, saying,
``I've made my point.'' (There's a bizarre round of applause.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a marketing scheme,'' claims a boy in a Nike T-shirt.
``This wasn't done because they (the WB network) are responsible or
whatever. They play the first (of a two-part) episode, right? You
think people won't want to see it if they can't? ... Man, people
who ain't even seen Buffy will watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads again nod in unison at this information, and that's when I
began to move toward the door.
</P>
<P>
   I'd either stumbled into ``The Twilight Zone'' or was being
taped for ``Candid Camera.'' Either would be a humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   We do talk intelligently about the WB's decision to run the
episode over the summer, and how the Nike T-shirt guy is right
about how the audience will be far greater than what the show would
have gotten had it aired May 25.
</P>
<P>
   I leave with home phone numbers and cell-phone numbers and
beeper numbers so I can ``stay in touch with the truth,'' as one
boy, in shorts and holding a soccer ball, puts it. I get in my car
and head down this hilly street, getting the distinct feeling that
my car will explode.
</P>
<P>
   Back home safe and sound, I wonder if something deeper and more
meaningful came out of my meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Like teens and the Internet. Teens and their rebellion against
authority. Teens and their hatred for censorship. Teens and their
love for ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is it.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from sharing doughnuts with a bunch of, um, interesting
conspiracy theorists, the only revelation was that the guy in the
corner was indeed older than 30. And that cat was dead.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
