<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHIAPAS-H     06-11 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHIAPAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM EXPLORES THE UNEXPECTED FACETS OF CHIAPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too sophisticated to be simply wide-eyed, not nosy enough to be
deeply probing, Nettie Wild's ``A Place Called Chiapas'' makes a
virtue of its filmmaker's innocence as she slyly, almost
manipulatively, ingratiates herself to the major players in the
notorious, ongoing Zapatista insurgence that broke out in 1994 in
southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Wild, a Canadian documentarian, trekked south of the border to
have a look at the ensuing political chaos and carnage. Her manner
is that of a high school social studies teacher on an excursion
with her class in a troubled country that she falls in love with.
Her grasp of the politics and danger swelling around her ranges
from advanced placement to remedial, but ``Chiapas'' is largely
free of the didactic, discursive academics that relegate lots of
uprising documentaries to History Channel pomposity: It's electric,
alive and commendably, coincidentally surreal.
</P>
<P>
   What seems potentially fraught with condescension _ a white lady
lugging her cameras and crew to Mexico to capture the truth about
Mexico's showdown between its indigenous people and its government
_ is actually a humorous, awkward, imperiled cat's cradle of
history, fury and injustice made occasionally lucid.
</P>
<P>
   What Wild manages to do is check hard-boiled journalistic
chutzpah at the border and just be a terribly concerned filmmaker,
crew in tow. Without feigning empathy or deigning to be ``one of
you,'' Wild films intimate moments with the major players in a
battle for the loss of property control.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary's handling of the Zapatista uprising also
happens to have the uncanny literariness of a sign-laden novella,
with Wild as its sort of Alice _ shrinking, shrinking, shrinking
into the tense, occasionally, bizarrely magic- kissed landscape of
this incensing wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas themselves are a band of ambiguous, approachable
men who quote Brecht and sport wool pull-over facemasks and whose
leader is a figure called Subcommander Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   A post-industrial, ultra-liberal political organization, the
Zapatistas exist in large part on the Web, publishing manifestoes,
essays, photos and news briefs, hoping to educate the world about
the contradictions mounting since 1994 when the Mexican government
complied with the ominous tenets of the North American Free Trade
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But what the film reveals is that the Zapatistas are also a
one-size-fits-all outfit of post-modern superheroes, for whom
individual identity is irrelevant and their agenda is their power
because, beyond the Internet, they have no agency.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Marcos exudes a dangerous charisma from behind his mask
that manages to capture the world's attention, as he becomes the
faceless, generic model for his cause. In one throwaway hilarious
scene, Marie Claire sends a writer and a crew to the South Mexico
jungle for a must-have story and photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Marcos is hot and the Zapatista movement is a
cumbersome cause celebre in the international media, which are
willing to whore for Marcos if for no other reason than that Marcos
doesn't mind pimping Zapatista concerns and his anonymous image for
them.
</P>
<P>
   His media saturation rankles and worries some of his supporters,
who fear, and suffer at the hands of, an irate Mexican government.
He and Wild forge a fascinating, dare-I-say romantic rapport as she
is told stories of his legendary status and he risks credibility to
speak with her. Though she remains off-camera for most of the film,
the two have a question-and-answer relationship predicated upon her
roughing-it outsider status and his suave, elusive stardom.
</P>
<P>
   If a major studio ever chooses to fictionalize ``Chiapas,''
their love would be a concoction heaving between ``Mahogany'' and
``Doctor Zhivago.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Wild goes astray is in her eloquent, poetic narration of
people, circumstances and events. Her words have the lugubrious
richness and edifying tactility of NPR reportage _ descriptive in a
way that, were you to close your eyes, you could see, and feel, the
world she was conjuring through her airwave microphones. As the
supplementary component of ``Chiapas,'' her voice-over needlessly
reiterates what unfolds before her cameras, which are handled with
alert attention to beautiful inertia and capricious action by Wild
and Kirk Tougas.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the film, Wild finds stirring, bold ways of
showing unexpected sides of a story that sometimes has the
transcendent urgency of a luscious and troubled agitprop fable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
