<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-GREEN-TEX     06-11 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-GREEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS FLASH: ANCHORWOMAN WAS A PLAYER ON THE PAGEANT CIRCUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first and last time Lauren Green would play piano
on national television, something was missing _ something very
close to her.
</P>
<P>
   It was during the final round of the 1985 Miss America Pageant.
Green had just zipped off the runway in her swimsuit and had
moments to dress for the talent competition. Too few moments,
unfortunately: When she took a seat at the piano bench, there was
nothing between Green and several layers of scratchy tulle.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Green, Miss Minnesota, was named third runner-up,
and her final-round performance actually came off much better than
the preliminary round, when nerves sabotaged her Chopin. That
experience shook the pianist to the core, and Green, now a New York
City television news anchor, still approaches public performances
with a bit of dread.
</P>
<P>
   So why put herself through it again by playing, as she did
Thursday night, in the Cliburn-sponsored International Piano
Competition for Outstanding Amateurs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pride, I think,'' said Green, 40. ``For all of us (in the
competition), we're very hard workers, very tenacious, and you just
don't fool around at anything. You achieve a certain level of
excellence in a certain area and you transfer that to every other
endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has been with Fox News in New York since 1996, where she
anchors a dozen news updates between 9 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. weekdays.
As an arts and entertainment correspondent, she has interviewed,
among others, Placido Domingo and Denyce Graves, whose picture
hangs above her almost empty desk. (Green swears her office was far
messier before a recent major cleanup.)
</P>
<P>
   In a bright red suit and black pumps, Green is undeniably
striking and intimidatingly tall. As she talks, she pulls off the
heels and replaces them with a pair of hot pink socks and worn
sneakers. Her exercise routine consists of the 40-minute walk she
takes each weekday to her West End apartment from work. It's about
all she can fit into a day that has recently required up to four
hours in front of the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Green grew up in Minneapolis, the youngest of five
children. Her oldest sibling, a sister who is also an accomplished
pianist, is 17 years her senior. On a recent weekday, her brother
Ken, a Minneapolis-based painter, was waiting at the Fox News
studios on 46th Street to take her to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Green took her first piano lessons at age 6 and began studying
in earnest at 10. Her mother played; their upright piano had
belonged to her grandmother. ``I didn't know anything different
than having a piano in the house,'' Green said. ``I thought it was
standard furniture, like having a couch.''
</P>
<P>
   After her junior year in high school, Green was one of four
pianists invited to the High School Musicians Project at the
University of Minnesota. She eventually majored in music there, but
had set her sights on acting. She headed for Los Angeles
immediately after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I soon found out that I really just cannot act,'' she admitted
recently. But modeling was another story. Green, who had entered
pageants as a teen, began doing so again. She won Miss Bloomington
(Minn.). She won Miss Twin Cities. She won Miss Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Green's success in the Miss America Pageant led to an internship
at a news station in Minneapolis _ which led to graduate school in
journalism at Northwestern University, which led to jobs in Chicago
and then New York.
</P>
<P>
   Piano has remained a part of her life throughout, though at
times she regrets taking to heart the opinion of a college piano
teacher who told her she didn't have the talent to pursue music
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Green played a duet with Daniel Barenboim of the
Chicago Symphony Orchestra for a school project. Barenboim
complimented her playing, and Green says she realized then just how
much damage one negative comment can do.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks back, Green called another competitor in New York in
a slight panic. ``I don't know if I can do this,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   But the paralyzing doubts have passed. ``It's not about
winning,'' Green told herself, and still believes. No matter what
happens in Fort Worth, ``I still have a life, a job, an apartment,
a future.''
</P>
<P>
   And time to dress completely before each round.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
