at a reception broadcast on Polish national television, the chief
rabbi of Poland refers to John Paul II as ``Mr. Pope'' and asks him
to take down the last cross at Auschwitz. By Alesandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-WARSHIPS (Tokyo) _ South Korean patrol boats bumped three
North Korean vessels Friday, forcing them out of disputed waters on
the fourth day of a tense armed standoff. After retreating, four
North Korean warships sailed back into the disputed zone,
confronting eight South Korean navy ships, South Korea's defense
ministry said. By Nicholas Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-LIBYA (United Nations) _ United States holds its first
meeting with Libya in more than a decade, but says sanctions are
not likely to be lifted for some time.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUKARNO (Jakarta) _ The ghost of Sukarno has hung
heavily over Indonesia this week, as the country held its first
democratic elections in more than four decades. The party of
Sukarno's 52-year-old daughter, Megawati Sukarnoputri, seems headed
for a clear victory in the parliamentary vote _ raising the
possibility another Sukarno may be the next leader of Indonesia. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANGELES-CALLGIRLS (Los Angeles) _ Police say they have busted
one of the most elaborate call girl rings since they cracked the
case of the ``Hollywood Madam,'' Heidi Fleiss, six years ago. Jody
Diane ``Babydoll'' Gibson, reported to be a former competitor of
Fleiss, was arrested Tuesday after a 10-month investigation. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-SCOTUS-REACT (Chicago) _ A day after the Supreme Court
struck down a Chicago law that banned loitering by suspected gang
members, people in the neighborhoods, where the law had been well
received, were angry.
</P>
