<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COREL'S OFFICE SUITE A TOUGH COMPETITOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you believe the conventional wisdom, then the office suite
war _ like the operating system war and the browser war _ is over,
and Microsoft has won. But a funny thing happened while Bill Gates
&AMP; Co. were celebrating another victory.
</P>
<P>
   Corel Corp. has just released the slickest version yet of its
office suite. WordPerfect Office 2000 Professional nearly matches
Microsoft's latest entry, Office 2000, feature for feature, and
certainly beats it in one key area: the price.
</P>
<P>
   While WordPerfect may never dominate the office productivity
market like its DOS-based word processor once did, this new version
will do a lot to hold the line against the Microsoft onslaught, and
may win back some who've strayed from the fold.
</P>
<P>
   First, the obligatory caveat: My name is Dwight, and I am a
WordPerfect user. I've used it since DOS version 4.2, and I still
find it to be easier to use and more intuitive than Word. However,
I prefer the other components of Microsoft Office, particularly
PowerPoint and Excel, to the other applications in Corel's suite.
</P>
<P>
   Previous versions of the WordPerfect suite suffered from a
varied lineage. The Quattro Pro spreadsheet and Paradox database,
for example, came from Borland. As a result, the look and feel of
the programs were not always homogeneous.
</P>
<P>
   That's been dramatically fixed with the 2000 version. The
primary applications finally feel like they are part of a cohesive
package.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A SLEW OF APPLICATIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along with WordPerfect, Quattro Pro and Paradox, Office 2000
Professional comes with a slew of other applications. They include
Trellix 2.0, a program designed for creating documents to be used
online; Corel Print Office, for specialized printing and graphics
projects; NetPerfect, an HTML conversion program; and Dragon
NaturallySpeaking 3.0, for voice recognition.
</P>
<P>
   That last component is a key differentiator difference between
the Corel and Microsoft products. Corel is aggressively touting
voice recognition as a key part of its top-of-the-line office
suite. Yet, even though Microsoft has a close relationship with
Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, one of the premier makers of voice-recognition
software, that feature is nowhere to be found in its Office 2000
suite.
</P>
<P>
   WordPerfect Office 2000 Professional, as with the Microsoft
product, has a handy feature that lets you install only the options
you need for each application. This is good, because the
``typical'' installation is almost 300 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   With this feature, called Install-As-You-Go, only the most-used
options are placed on your hard drive. However, all the possible
options are available via the menus. If you try to use a feature
that's not installed, you're prompted for the CD. Or, if
WordPerfect Office is installed via a network, the component can be
pulled off a server.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that the main programs in this suite are lean
and mean. WordPerfect in particular remains a hog of memory and
Windows resources _ but it's better.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the program launches faster, loads documents faster,
saves files faster and converts between formats faster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CONVERSIONS IMPROVED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It also does a much better job of converting to Microsoft Office
file formats. Previous versions of WordPerfect and Quattro Pro did
a less-than-stellar job of converting to Word and Excel, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   I tried converting a variety of spreadsheet, word processing and
presentation documents. The spreadsheet and word processing files
converted flawlessly every time, and I found only minor, easily
corrected animation glitches with the presentation documents.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new features I like the best in the WordPerfect Suite
is called the Real Time Preview. As you make various changes _ font
types, margins, backgrounds, etc. _ you're shown how the document
will look before you lock in the formatting. For folks who don't
consider themselves whizzes at document design, it's a godsend. You
can see what works and what doesn't in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Corel got its start as a graphics application company, and that
strength has finally shown up in the suite. Yes, the Professional
edition comes with the aforementioned Corel Print Office, but more
importantly the built-in graphics components of the applications
have been beefed up.
</P>
<P>
   For example, WordPerfect, Quattro Pro and Presentations all come
with the ability to search through an on-disk library for specific
images, displaying the results as thumbnails in a feature called
the Scrapbook. If you work with a lot of clip art, it eliminates
the need for a separate media-management program.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that both the Microsoft and Corel suites do is try to
make it easier to save documents as HTML files for use on the Web.
Microsoft has the edge here; it's built into each component
program. While the Corel programs will save as HTML, it's not a
perfect conversion. The NetPerfect program that comes with
WordPerfect Suite 2000 is designed for just-right conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and Corel have several different configurations for
their suites, and doing an apples-to-apples price comparison of the
two up and down the line can be tough. But if you look at the
high-end versions _ Microsoft Office 2000 Premium and WordPerfect
Office 2000 Professional _ you'll see that the WordPerfect package
is a better buy. First-time users pay $499 for WordPerfect,
compared to $799 for the Microsoft product. Those who are upgrading
from a previous version pay $209 for WordPerfect vs. $449 for
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, I'll take a detailed look at Microsoft Office 2000
Premium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
