A2063 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     06-11 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS AN INCREASE IN INTEREST RATES NECESSARILY BAD FOR STOCKS?  
  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (jt)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bombs stopped falling on Kosovo last week. Japan's economy
recorded its first growth in 18 months in the first quarter.
Germany's industrial output is quickening, and its unemployment
rate is falling. Yet the markets persist in brooding about the
prospect of a modest hike in interest rates by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Recent price moves suggest that the bond market is convinced the
Fed will raise rates. Partly in sympathy, stock measures like the
Dow Jones industrial average have slipped 5 percent or more from
their peaks.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, however, that an increase in interest rates
would be unremittingly bad for stocks. Robert Heisterberg, a senior
vice president and chairman of the asset allocation committee of
Alliance Capital Management, took some time last week to discuss
that proposition. Here are some excerpts: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Market interest rates have risen much more sharply
from their troughs than they did in 1994 and 1997, the last two
periods when the Fed tightened monetary policy. Has the increase
been justified?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The bond market overshot by about 50 basis points on the
downside last fall, because everything conspired to create a set of
expectations that, in a medium-term sense, led people to believe we
were about to enter a recession, if not a depression.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of cyclical factors, I would trace the rise we have
seen from a level of about 5 percent or 5.25 percent on the 30-year
Treasury bond. That backup has been warranted. The American economy
has continued to grow, and now we are seeing signs of growth
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The news out of Japan is important. If they can sustain positive
economic growth, it will do a lot for the Asian region and for the
world economy. If others pitch in, it means America doesn't have to
as much. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)In response to the crisis last year, the Fed cut
short-term interest rates by three-quarters of a percentage point
in a matter of weeks. Will it take back all of those cuts?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would be surprised if they will be required to take back
all of the 75 basis points they eased last year. However, I am
quite confident they will take back one-quarter of a percentage
point. At this point, it's a 50-50 proposition they will raise
rates by another one-quarter of a point after that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Why do you think they will stop short of taking more
dramatic action?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The fundamentals of inflation are still performing quite
well. Inflation becomes a problem when it begins to influence
decisions. When I start to see companies and consumers making
decisions based on concern over rising prices, that is when I start
to get concerned. I haven't seen that. Also, I think we will get
some slowing in the economy during the second half of the year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Does the increase in interest rates we have seen,
and may yet see, pose a significant threat to stocks?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Valuation levels right now are fairly lofty, and that makes
stocks more vulnerable. But to say that interest rates are going to
unglue this market is probably an overstatement. To make a strong
negative case for stocks relative to interest rates, you would have
to see rates go up considerably more than they have. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Money is getting drained out of stocks that are
viewed to be vulnerable to rising interest rates, like technology
and financial services. But some of these companies performed quite
nicely when rates were higher than they are now. What is your
view?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A resumption of growth outside the United States has to be
good news for multinationals and a number of technology companies,
as well as some less exotic machinery manufacturers and capital
goods makers. A good number of these companies were hurt by
contraction in consumption spending in Latin America and Asia, and
some were just shut off by the recession outside the United States,
especially in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional view is that rising interest rates hurt banks
and financial stocks. But most of these companies, if you study
them closely, have been hell-bent on generating fee income, which
is not sensitive to interest rates at all. Generally speaking, we
think the valuations in this area reflect the old view about their
vulnerability to interest rates, and not the new reality. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Has the rise in interest rates caused you to alter
your model portfolio?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In terms of allocation, we are closer to our long-term
benchmarks now than we were a few months ago, but that is because,
due to superior performance, we took some money out of the equity
market.
</P>
<P>
   Our allocation for growth-investor accounts is about 70 percent
in equities, about 24 percent in bonds and the remainder in cash.
We are modestly overweighted internationally, and our domestic
equity positions are skewed toward a somewhat broader list of
stocks than the large-cap growth stocks that have been driving the
market. The market has broadened dramatically, and we have had to
respond to that.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
