<HEADER>
A2081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      06-11 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH HEADS TO THE HEARTLAND TO TEST HIS CAMPAIGN METTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush plans to leave Texas
Saturday to attend a couple of barbecues, shake some hands and meet
a few people. No big deal really.
</P>
<P>
   Only the nation will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   After months of staying home tending to legislative business and
boning up on world and national affairs, the son of former
President George Bush will hit the campaign trail on a whirlwind,
four-day trip to Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he was eager to go ``look people in the eye
and hear what they have to say,'' even though he has done amazingly
well so far running his race from the ``Yellow Rose Garden'' in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, both in the polls and in raising money.
</P>
<P>
   His first stops are in states that can make or break a would-be
president. Iowa hosts the first caucuses, and New Hampshire is home
to the first primary. Voters in both states are used to attention
from presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of holding cozy meet-and-greet sessions, Bush will
make a grand debut under the harsh glare of the national news
media.
</P>
<P>
   A crowded field of GOP opponents, struggling to raise money and
get attention, are anticipating Bush's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the candidates are ready for the sphinx finally to
speak,'' said Dennis Goldford, a political science professor at
Drake University in Des Moines. ``They'll be glad to try and scuff
him up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign trip has all the elements of a Cinderella story or
the voyage of the Titanic, depending on how they're mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolutely clear slate with the guy at this point,''
said New Hampshire pollster Dick Bennett. ``But you can't come here
and please all the people. It will be interesting to see what
things bother certain people. It will be interesting to see how he
does here, to see if he gets it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tremendous expectations,'' Bennett added.
</P>
<P>
   Goldford noted that being on top is a mixed blessing. It's not
news if you do well, it's expected. It's big news if you stumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations could get out of control,'' Goldford said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was under a self-imposed moratorium on traveling until the
Texas legislative session ended May 31. During the session, he
stayed in Austin, but advisers and contributors came to him to talk
strategy and develop an agenda that he has yet to lay out.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush insists he is only ``testing the waters'' for a
possible White House bid, there is little doubt he will run for the
GOP nomination. An announcement is expected later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Goldford said Bush needs to do several things on his first trip
to the nation's heartland: Give Iowans a clear reason he wants to
run and tell them what he would do as president. And, he said, the
Texas governor needs to shore up support among social
conservatives, the best-organized group in the Republican caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to come in here and energize his supporters,''
Goldford said.
</P>
<P>
   Oftentimes, people want a candidate to win because they support
him. But Goldford said that in Bush's case, many people back him
because they think he's the one who can win back the White House
for the Republicans after an eight-year shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has got to get people who'll be ready to walk through
fire for him,'' Goldford said, adding that other candidates already
have stalwarts in their Iowa organizations. ``A lot of people are
with him because things are thick, but he's got to be sure they'll
be with him when things are thin.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Bennett already sees a potential problem with
Bush's agenda because many of the events are closed to the public.
And in that state, people pay great attention to such slights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inability to meet with real voters is a problem
sometimes,'' Bennett said. ``It's truly retail campaigning here.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, with a population of 1.2 million, thrives on
representative government. The state House has 400 members, and
local governmental decisions are hashed out in small, town hall
meetings. Voters and presidential candidates often meet in livings
rooms. Residents ask hard questions and expect honest answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates have to be accessible,'' Bennett said. Those who
don't risk a poor showing in the first presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stumping in Iowa and New Hampshire, Bush and his
wife Laura will visit his father and mother at the family vacation
home in Kennebunkport, Maine, and the Texas governor will meet with
Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci, a friend and supporter, in Boston
on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
