<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIANS-TRUST-$ADV13-     06-11 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANS-TRUST-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS' LAWSUIT ACCUSES U.S. OF MISPLACING BILLIONS OF DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elouise Cobell won a $310,000 ``genius grant'' from
the MacArthur Foundation for her savvy banking skills, but even she
can't figure out how much money the U.S. government owes her and
hundreds of thousands of other Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at least in the billions, possibly in the tens of
billions,'' says Cobell, who looks like a banker with her dark blue
suit and glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Cobell, 53, a member of the Blackfeet tribe in Montana, is suing
the federal government for alleged mishandling of Indian trust
funds. The class-action lawsuit filed on behalf of more than
300,000 Indians and 2,000 tribes wants the government to repair the
trust system and make up for what the plaintiffs claim are billions
of dollars in underpayments.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to trial last week with the government
acknowledging that it had made a mess of the trust accounts and had
inadequately controlled receipts and disbursements and failed to
provide regular reports to account holders.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyer Tom Clark said the government was
``doing what it could'' to solve the problem and that it was not
guilty of breaking its trust relationship with the Indians and the
tribes.
</P>
<P>
   But Thaddeus Hold, attorney for the Indian plaintiffs, told the
court that the mismanagement of the accounts was ``one more example
of the breaches of faith with the original inhabitants of this
land.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust funds were created in the 19th century when it was
national policy to break up reservations and parcel out tracts of
80 or 160 acres to individual Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those lands were rich in oil, timber, minerals or
agricultural products. The government, acting as a trustee for
individual Indians, negotiated the sale of oil, trees, ore or
crops, and then collected the money on behalf of the property
owner. The government was supposed to manage this task like a trust
officer at a local bank, always acting on behalf of the landholder.
</P>
<P>
   But for Cobell and other Indians, the government has proved less
than trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the government's mismanagement, thousands of Indians
who literally need the money from their trust accounts to feed
their families are not seeing a dime,'' says the soft-spoken
Cobell, who was awarded the MacArthur grant for her work in helping
to create the Blackfeet National Bank in Browning, Mont., in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 Interior Department report showed that more than 123,000
of the 340,000 individual Indian trust fund accounts lack a Social
Security number or taxpayer ID number. At least 46,000 accounts are
being held for Indians whose whereabouts are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   In tens of thousands of cases, trust fund documents were shoved
into unmarked boxes and stored in barns or sheds, according to the
Interior Department.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, many of the documents were lost or
destroyed. One neglected warehouse in Albuquerque, N.M., eventually
became so rat-infested that officials entering the building in
search of trust documents needed to wear astronaut-style suits to
protect them from rat-borne diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several billion dollars may have been lost over the
years in undervalued and uncollected lease payments and in
destroyed or lost checks for Indian beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person working in a bank had done even a fraction of what
the government has done, they would be in jail,'' says Cobell.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 report for Interior Department by the consulting firm
Arthur Andersen said the Bureau of Indian Affairs, a branch of the
Interior Department that oversees the trust accounts, couldn't
document $2.4 billion in tribal trust fund transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, another report for the department by the
consulting firm Griffin &AMP; Associates warned that trust fund
problems and the Cobell lawsuit ``may result in a potential
liability to the federal government so large that it is not
reasonably estimable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Gingold, a lawyer for Cobell and four other plaintiffs,
said his clients' own preliminary estimate by the Price Waterhouse
accounting firm shows that the Indians are owed at least $10
billion _ far exceeding the Interior Department's entire annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the Interior Department say they are trying to
straighten out the trust fund problems, which they say go back 100
years, and to recover all missing documents.
</P>
<P>
   However, last February, the judge presiding over Cobell's case
disagreed and found Secretary of Interior Bruce Babbitt and
Secretary of Treasury Robert E. Rubin in contempt for failing to
provide required materials to lawyers for the Indians in what he
called a ``campaign of stonewalling and strained interpretations''
of court orders. U.S. District Judge Royce C. Lamberth has set a
hearing on the contempt charges for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The government ``engaged in a shocking pattern of deception of
the court,'' Lamberth said. ``I have never seen more egregious
misconduct by the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobell points to her own case as an example of the difficulties
Indians face in trying to determine what land they own and how much
it is worth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Cobell's father died. Sixteen years passed before the
BIA finished her father's probate _ a delay that Cobell only
discovered after she filed her lawsuit against the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy as it sounds, I still don't know completely the types of
land I own,'' she says. ``It's frightening to think how much money
has been lost and how much damage it has done to people who are
struggling just to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
