A2125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-OFFICES-$ADV     06-11 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-OFFICES-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE BACKS DOWN ON BIGGER ALLOWANCES FOR MEMBERS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 13.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For a few hours late Thursday night, the House of
Representatives nearly erupted over one of the touchiest issues in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Congress prepared to trim back education, veterans, and
housing programs, the House was considering a bill that would have
raised the allowances for running members' offices by 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the shouting was over, rebel conservatives led by
Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., had prevailed. The House agreed by voice
vote to roll back the raise and keep the allowance at its current
$385 million total.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell the public how we can increase the spending
for running our house and then ask everybody else to take a cut,''
Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote averted certain lambasting by watchdog groups.
``Frugality begins at home, and so members of Congress ought to
spend the public dollar wisely,'' said Gary Ruskin, director of the
Congressional Accountability Project, part of Ralph Nader's
consumer advocacy network.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, members have difficulty hiding their expenses, since
most of them are required to be listed on quarterly reports, which
in the coming months are scheduled to be posted on the Internet for
anyone to examine.
</P>
<P>
   An average of 70 percent of the funds go for paying staff in
both their Washington and district offices.
</P>
<P>
   Here are illustrations of how members spend the rest of their
allotments:
</P>
<P>
   _ From his 24-county district including Augusta, Ga., Rep.
Charlie Norwood, R, urges less government, but he uses every penny
allotted him for his office operations. His top aide, John Walker,
said the aim is to deploy aides to help constituents fight the
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood ranked as the seventh biggest spender on his office in a
study released this spring by the National Taxpayers Union. Norwood
also is among the most frequent users of ``franked'' mail,
newsletters that carry the member's signature in place of a stamp
and a popular way to keep in touch with the folks at home. During
the election year of 1998, he spent nearly $124,000 on mailings,
13.9 percent of his office cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, uses part of his funds in pursuit of
his intense interest in famines worldwide. Two of his 17 aides are
assigned fulltime to researching hunger. An examination of his
mundane office purchases of supplies, computers and other items
turns up another indicator: a $108 payment for trinkets with the
House of Representatives insignia to hand out to hosts on his trips
abroad to check out famine-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, reinforces his image as a
penny-pincher in his disbursement records. Among the recent
listings: five Pilot pens for $5.10 and an imitation leather desk
pad for $7.99. Doggett last year spent only 86.5 percent of his
allowance, according to a study by the National Taxpayers Union.
</P>
<P>
   _ With one of the fastest-growing districts in the country, Rep.
Mark Foley, R-Fla., has three offices back home and one of the
biggest House allowances, just under $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Every second year he uses part of his taxpayer funds to help
host a ``fly-in'' of Florida community leaders, which last year
cost his office $1,408 for a meal for the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of expenditure that raises questions, Ruskin
said last week. ``Why is the member spending money on meals for
constituents?'' he asked. ``That's not an appropriate use of
taxpayer funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials say they are not concerned. ``If you
aren't spending anything you shouldn't, you shouldn't worry,'' said
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
