soldiers quicker off the mark than we were. A commander screams at
us to take cover in a ditch. I follow two soldiers scrambling up a
hill that suddenly seems impossibly steep. More bombs follow as we
run.
 &HT;    I wipe a soldier's mangled leg, plainly visible through his
tattered trousers. He is about 18. In shock, he keeps offering me
cigarettes from his package of L&AMP;Ms, repeatedly taking them out of
his camouflage jacket, which is also torn up. When I rub his head
to comfort him, it is burning hot. The young medic from Switzerland
curses and rips the wrapping off a bandage. Someone offers a bottle
of mercurochrome.
 &HT;    ``Be prepared for anything,'' shouts a commander, who appears
halfway through the ordeal to distribute helmets to those, like me,
who lack them. ``Be prepared for everything.''
 &HT;    Around me are soldiers of all kinds: some veterans of the
Yugoslav National Army, others who had fought in Bosnia, Croatia,
Morocco and the Persian Gulf war. Then there are the young ones,
the raw recruits who signed up in Vancouver, New York, London or
Geneva with no clear idea where they were going. No one admits to
fear, but you can see it in their faces and in their eyes.
 &HT;    ``Turn your watch back 400 years before coming to Albania,'' a
friend of mine, an experienced aid worker, told me before I
arrived.
 &HT;    She is a veteran of missions in Bosnia, Serbia, Rwanda and
Zaire. She does not exaggerate. The Albanian port of Durres, an
hour's drive from Tirana, is where it starts for most of the KLA
volunteers. Like most things Albanian, Durres is dusty, grimy,
cheap and dirty. White prefabricated houses dot the shoreline
overlooking the polluted Adriatic Sea, where wealthy Kosovars once
spent their summers.
 &HT;    For the past two months, Durres has been invaded by young
volunteers who want to fight for the KLA. Fresh-faced, they are
usually under 35 and have paid their own way.
 &HT;    They have bought their own equipment _ army fatigues,
olive-green T-shirts, guns that are routinely confiscated by
Italian police. Some of them hook up with groups like the Atlantic
Brigade, composed of Kosovar emigres from America and Canada.
Others simply arrive at the port and look for the bus station.
There, several minibuses a day will take them north to a KLA base
in the vicinity of Kukes, the refugee camp, for their first round
of training.
 &HT;    You can spot them a mile away, with their freshly shorn hair and
their earnest expressions. Nearly all the young recruits I meet had
been working in ``the restaurant business'' _ as waiters.
 &HT;    At the Cafe Drenica, a two-story white building overlooking a
stretch of shore where teen-agers play soccer, the KLA has opened
up a recruitment center. The place is decorated with posters of
Adem Jashari, the rebel fighter now elevated to the status of
national hero since he was brutally murdered along with most of his
family at Prekaz in March 1998 by the Serbs. Jashari is holding a
Kalashnikov and sporting an ammunition belt and a lot of facial
hair. Underneath his picture, touched up by soft-focus painting, is
the inscription: Homeland is calling.
 &HT;    Taf Tafa (``Tough Tougher'' in Albanian, but this is his real
name _ he produces a German driver's license to prove the point) is
one of the commanders at the Cafe Drenica.
 &HT;    Uniforms are piled in the corner, along with a rifle and a stack
of helmets. He reaches down, opens a drawer and produces a sack of
passports from recruits who registered there before being moved
north: Swiss, German, Swedish, Norwegian, American and British
passports, all in a jumble. ``It's like the European Union,'' he
says sardonically. ``It's a real international army.''
 &HT;    ``The KLA is a collection of various groups of Albanian
patriots,'' Billal Sherifi, the KLA political representative, tells
me later at the KLA's Tirana office, a crowded flat in an
all-concrete building that is difficult to find. Sherifi represents
one side of the KLA: the intellectuals who are ``outside'' Kosovo,
presenting a kinder, gentler face to the world.
 &HT;    At this point, I am not yet aware of the many factions within
the movement. I am simply trying to gain information. Later, I will
find out that one faction, still headed by Ibrahim Rugova, the
former political leader of the Kosovar Albanians, and his ally, a
German-based physician named Bujar Bukoshi, is locked in a power
struggle with a group led by Hashim Thaci, the Kosovar
representative to the ill-fated Rambouillet negotiations, the
failure of which precipitated the war. Many feel Thaci is the major
force in the KLA _ for now, at least.
 &HT;    When I meet the KLA contacts, it is in secrecy _ understandably,
as the Serbian paramilitaries have singled out intellectuals and
political leaders for execution. Our conversations take place in a
linguistic melange of French, Italian, English and Albanian.
 &HT;    Most KLA commanders appear to be bi- or trilingual, typically
having German, French or Italian as a third language along with
English, and are usually highly educated. (Most also speak
Serbo-Croatian, but they don't like to admit it.) The men I meet,
who will eventually arrange my passage to the front lines, usually
have noms de guerre and, sometimes, beefy bodyguards.
 &HT;    One of these is Visar Reka, a former filmmaker who learned
English so he could study the work of Martin Scorsese and Robert
Altman. (``Nashville'' is his favorite.) Now a KLA spokesman, he
sits with me in a backstreet cafe in Tirana, where we are served
lukewarm cappuccino while he chain-smokes.
 &HT;    The KLA's claim of 8,000 recruits in its training camps is
impossible to verify, but my own informal survey of the volunteer
pipeline from Durres to the Kosovo border lends it some credence.
Albania is crawling with volunteers. ``We have many more than we
have the capacity to train,'' Reka says. ``We don't have enough
uniforms. We are scavenging for guns.''
 &HT;    And a throng of raw, poorly armed recruits led by a few
experienced commanders was never going to be a match for Serbian
armor, artillery and air power. They wanted American tanks to go
with the air power.
 &HT;    ``We need help,'' one commander admitted a little woefully.
``We're not ashamed to admit it.'' Another young soldier put it
simply: ``When are those damned Apaches going to get off the
ground?''
 &HT;    On the 11th of May, I reach the border camp 15 miles up the
road. Living among the soldiers is like living in another world.
They sing, they eat, they wash with stream water from a rusty pipe.
But once again, there is the pervasive sense of fear and waiting,
punctuated by the sight of bodies brought on stretchers from the
front. The hospital is full of wounded and bloody soldiers. Bombs
fall sporadically. It isn't just that the camp is dangerous; some
days, it feels like the end of the earth.
 &HT;    The next morning, the Serbian bombardment starts, and I'm forced
to lie in that squalid trench for four or five hours. At
midafternoon, after the bombing and shelling has stopped, we hike
into the hills and find the wing and tail lights of a Serbian
plane. We cross a stream, trudge over some hills and scamper across
a field, running to avoid snipers.
 &HT;    Finally, the commander says: ``OK, stop. Lie here.'' We stop,
panting, in a heavily wooded area. When I turn, I see soldiers
everywhere: young guys dug in, sitting with Kalashnikovs, machine
guns and khaki uniforms. They lie back in their positions, smoking
cigarettes and looking at us in amazement.
 &HT;    Suddenly, I see my interpreter from Pristina, staring at
someone. Her face drops. Her mouth opens. She is staring at a
handsome young soldier who is crouching in a foxhole. He calls her
name. As if in a dream, she walks over and looks down. Her
expression softens, and they speak quietly in Albanian for a bit,
and then we are called away.
 &HT;    Within five minutes, we are in the midst of a firefight and we
lie on our stomachs underneath a bush until it is safe to run to an
abandoned stone house filled with soldiers.
 &HT;    ``That was my first boyfriend in Pristina,'' my interpreter
says, still stunned. ``I haven't seen him in three years.'' She
pauses. ``I wanted to give him a hug. He was waiting for me to give
him a hug. But I couldn't do it. There were too many other soldiers
around and there was no one to hug them. It wouldn't have been
fair, would it?''
 &HT;    This is what has happened to her since she fell in love with the
young fighter a million years ago in Pristina: Her best friend, the
most beautiful girl in the city, died in her arms in a Pristina
cafe; she herself was shot in the neck and the arms; in Albania, a
month later, she was raped by local men who told her they were
policemen.
 &HT;    Once, she confided, she dreamed of falling in love with someone
and becoming a famous actress. Now she says things to me like, ``I
don't want anyone to touch me.'' Or, ``Do you think I will go
mad?''
 &HT;    At 3 a.m. the following morning, we are awakened by a heavy
thud; more bombs. After our experience the day before, we are
prepared, sleeping in clothes and boots, ready to run for cover
outside our tents. The Serbs, the soldiers believe, can detect body
heat in the tents. So we move quickly in the dark, to the cover of
a trench.
 &HT;    For hours, we lie there, on a steep, muddy slope. The Bosnian
commander, with his handsome, craggy face, stands next to me
smoking cigarette after cigarette. He tells my interpreter that he
lost his entire family in the war. Later he goes into a tent and
brings us back a blanket to cover us. ``I am used to the cold,'' he
says.
 &HT;    We leave the camp in the afternoon, hitching a ride on a
military van. Twelve hours later, I am sleeping in a real bed in
Kukes, which doesn't seem quite so grimy and godforsaken as it did
just three days before.
 &HT;    What will become of this army? By the first days of June, the
young fighters already seem distant. They got the world's
attention, but that attention is now shifting to reconstruction and
resettlement. So far, KLA leaders have expressed a willingness to
accept the peace plan, though they remain deeply skeptical of
Milosevic's true intentions and strongly committed to achieving
their goal of independence; autonomy within Yugoslavia, as called
for in the peace settlement, is not in their plans.
 &HT;    The rebels are supposed to lay down their arms, and they
probably will _ but will they abandon their cause? I doubt it. They
have tasted power. They have watched their friends die in their
arms _ but for what? They have been clear from the start that they
want to escape Serbian repression. And they are the Kosovo
Liberation Army, not the Kosovo Autonomy Army. But now the world is
impatient; the world wants to move on.
 &HT;     c.1999 Janine di Giovanni  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Janine di Giovanni is a correspondent with The Times of
London. She has covered the Balkans for seven years, and is the
author of ``The Quick and the Dead: Under Siege in Sarajevo.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
