<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-HAWLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCIENCE CAREER, PIANO TALENT AND REEL GENIUS, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Among its 92 competitors, the International
Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs has several geniuses _
including Michael Hawley, professor of media technology at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   And, though he's not a professional musician, he says that
playing the piano has been an important part of his development in
other fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most productive and creative times in my life have been
when I've been practicing the piano,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley, 37, has applied his genius in both popular and esoteric
areas: He may well be the only contestant who has worked for both
George Lucas (you know, the guy who came up with those ``Star
Wars'' movies) and composer Pierre Boulez. The latter occurred at
the Institut de Recherche et de Coordination Acoustique/Musique
(IRCAM), a center for development of electronic music in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Genius hasn't stifled Hawley's whimsical nature, however;
there's a stack of yo-yos on his desk, and he's apt to practice his
competition repertoire on the hotel-bar piano when he travels to
lecture. We caught him by phone in Fort Lauderdale last week, where
he was scheduled to present a lecture for IBM. He's been so busy,
he said, that he started practicing seriously for the competition
only a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Born in California and reared in New Jersey, Hawley played by
ear as a youngster and got serious about piano in high school _
serious enough to apply to the renowned Curtis Institute of Music
in Philadelphia, but not serious enough to be accepted there.
Instead, he entered Yale, where he simultaneously earned bachelor's
degrees in music and science _ while financing his education by
working at Bell Laboratories in New Jersey, a 2 1/2-hour commute
from Yale.
</P>
<P>
   The double major served him well when he went to work for
Lucasfilm, where from 1984 to 1986, he helped invent technology for
the burgeoning digital film industry.
</P>
<P>
   But he continued his devotion to the piano, too. While working
on his doctorate at MIT from 1986 to '93, he continued to study
piano. He played concerts and chamber music performances regularly
_ and worked up tricks like programing a pair of Bosendorfer pianos
to play Liszt's Totentanz, hooking up a computer interface to the
player-piano mechanism that had previously been attached to the
acoustic pianos.
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn Foundation executive director Richard Rodzinski met
Hawley at the Jack Kilby Awards in Dallas in 1987, when Hawley was
being honored for innovation in science and music; Rodzinski
encouraged Hawley to enter the amateur competition, which is
sponsored by the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fallen out of practice,'' Hawley says. ``Richard gave me
the kick in the pants. And I've had a marvelous time getting
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawley made his first bid for advancement yesterday with Liszt's
transcription of J.S. Bach's Fantasy and Fugue in G minor, hoping
to move to today's second round with a pair of ragtime pieces by
William Bolcom and Liszt's ``Mephisto Waltz No. 1.'' If he makes
the finals tomorrow, he'll perform Faure's Nocturne No. 13 in B
minor and Chopin's Sonata in B minor _ proving that, even though
he's a high-tech genius, he's a romantic at heart.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
