<HEADER>
A2180 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-$ADV13     06-11 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-YELTSIN SUMMIT DESIGNED TO COOL ANTI-WEST BACKLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, departing Tuesday for
consultations in Europe on post-war Kosovo, may need to cash in on
his chummy ``Bill and Boris'' partnership with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin to ease strains stemming from NATO'S victorious
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Yeltsin plan a separate summit in Cologne, Germany,
next Saturday during the annual gathering of leaders from the Group
of Eight nations that brings together officials from the United
States, Russia, Canada, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also will consult with French President Jacques Chirac
in Paris, address the International Labor Organization in Geneva,
meet with leaders of the 15-nation European Union and visit
Slovenia, a former republic of Yugoslavia, during a seven-day trip
to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president also may visit a refugee
camp in the Balkans before returning to the United States on June
22.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said allied leaders are planning to salute
Yeltsin at the Cologne summit for helping the western alliance
persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw Yugoslav
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin repeatedly dispatched former Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin to Belgrade during the allied air offensive to
seek an agreement with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Their meeting comes amid a deepening anti-western backlash
across Russia. Opinion polls show ordinary Russians regard the
U.S.-led air campaign against Yugoslavia as the latest in a string
of humiliations inflicted upon Russia by an encroaching western
alliance bent on exploiting the weakness of the former Cold War-era
superpower.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Goldgeier, former director of Russian affairs at the
National Security Council earlier in the Clinton presidency, says
Clinton must allay Russian concerns during his summit with Yeltsin
or face the risk that Russians will turn to nationalistic,
anti-western candidates in next year's Russian presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin is likely to insist on a wider Russian role in Kosovo,
guaranteed Yugoslav sovereignty over Kosovo and suspension of
western efforts to encourage the ouster of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, whose Slavic homeland enjoys long-standing ties with
Yugoslavia, is expected to challenge NATO plans to cede virtual
independence to the predominantly ethnic Albanian Muslim province
of Kosovo in order to persuade the secessionist Kosovo Liberation
Army to surrender weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues between the United States and Russia include
differences over future allied intervention in humanitarian crises,
repayment of Soviet-era debt and the Kremlin's preference for the
Group of Eight nations to deal with future European security
disputes rather than the 19-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. Russia is a member of the G-8 but not of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivity of the U.S.-Russian relationship in Kosovo was
underscored late last week when the Kremlin surprised senior U.S.
officials by moving a convoy of Russian troops from Bosnia across
Serbia and toward Kosovo before military command-and-control
arrangements had been worked out with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The southbound column of more than 50 Russian armored vehicles
and trucks flying Russian flags prompted Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to order Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott to return to Moscow immediately to negotiate arrangements
for up to 10,000 Russian troops to join the international
peacekeeping force moving into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials insist that the 50,000-strong peacekeeping force,
commanded in the field by a Briton, be under the direct command of
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has rejected having Russian troops serve under NATO
command. But U.S. officials are hopeful that Russia will agree to
have Russian troops serve under a Russian commander based at NATO
headquarters in Belgium _ an arrangement used for Russian troops
serving in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton and Yeltsin work out differences and cooperate
as they have on other issues in the past, Yeltsin's successor is
likely to win next year's Russian presidential election on promises
to ``rebuild military strength (and) to play the nuclear hand a
little more riskily,'' Goldgeier said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution and a former National Security Council
official in the Bush administration, says Yeltsin may press Clinton
for additional international financial assistance to reward Kremlin
cooperation in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin seeks immediate payment of $4.5 billion in promised
assistance from the International Monetary Fund even though he has
not been able to win approval of IMF-sought legislation by the
Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could well be a growing gap between Russian expectations
and western preparedness to act,'' Haass said. ``The Russians feel
now that they're owed something.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Yeltsin also must ``begin to try to bridge some of
the differences on humanitarian intervention which is a fundamental
disagreement between the United States and Russia,'' Haass said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia opposes international intervention in sovereign nations,
even in the face of humanitarian crises, in part because the
Kremlin fears European intervention in many of the nasty ethnic
disputes that smoulder in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is banking once again on payoffs from a so-called
``Clinton-Yeltsin bargain'' that provides Russia a prominent role
at European summits in return for the Kremlin's cooperation on
issues of vital western interest, Goldgeier said.
</P>
<P>
   But these experts said there was little hope that Clinton could
parlay U.S.-Russia cooperation to end the war in Kosovo into fresh
energy to ratify a stalled seven-year-old nuclear weapons reduction
treaty or to win Russian compliance with U.S. demands for the
Kremlin to end nuclear technology cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   With a parliamentary election in Russia in December and
presidential elections looming next year in both the United States
and Russia, there is little prospect for ``any big cooperative
steps,'' Goldgeier said, adding: ``We're likely to see a holding
pattern until after both presidents are elected next year.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
