<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2184 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ALLIED-DOME-AR     06-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ALLIED-DOME-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STIRRING NEW INTEREST IN A DISTILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When it comes to sure bets, nothing seems quite as
predictable as the idea that, in Britain at least, people will go
to the pub and enjoy a tipple.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few weeks, Allied Domecq PLC, the staid
distiller and pub chain that so exemplifies that notion, has seen
some surprising events that should serve notice to investors that
little in the world of commerce is ever predictable. In short
order, Allied Domecq has received an investment from a famed
billionaire, shed its chain of pubs, announced the replacement of
its chief executive and become the subject of takeover rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The question for investors, naturally, is whether these
developments, and the accompanying rise in Allied's stock price,
make the company more or less attractive than it was.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of events began on May 18, when a British newspaper
reported that Berkshire Hathaway, the holding company controlled by
Warren E. Buffett, had taken a 2.2 percent stake in Allied.
Presumably, the purchase reflected Buffett's liking for name brands
like Coca-Cola and Gillette; Allied's spirits portfolio includes
barroom staples like Beefeater gin, Ballantine's and Canadian Club
whiskies, Sauza tequila and Kahlua liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, Allied struck a $3.8 billion deal to sell its more
than 3,500 pubs to Whitbread PLC, a brewing and leisure business.
Analysts noted that the deal leaves Allied free to concentrate on
spirits _ and that is where investors see money.
</P>
<P>
   Also on May 25, Allied announced that Tony Hales, its chief
executive the last eight years, would resign after the completion
of the deal to make way for the finance director, Phillip Bowman _
a move praised by investors. ``Bowman is a highly competent chief
executive and the appointment is good news,'' said Mark Puleikas, a
beverages analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   There remains, however, the issue of how much upside is left in
the stock, which have risen from a 1998 low of 451 pounds ($7.23)
in February to close at 6.005 pounds ($9.62) in London last week,
and how best to get it. (Allied's American depository receipts
closed at $9.625, with each ADR representing one ordinary share.)
</P>
<P>
   Some say that a deal _ either a merger, sale or acquisition _ is
necessary to bolster Allied's share price. Others think not.
</P>
<P>
   Puleikas, for example, rates Allied neutral at a pre-deal fair
value price of 5.50 pounds ($8.80). But, he added, ``the 5.50 pound
price is based on the presumption that nothing happens'' to change
Allied's status as a stand-alone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are of the view that to move forward, Allied Domecq needs
to undertake the long-awaited spirits merger,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Allied's divestitures inspired a crop of merger rumors,
all reflecting the belief that the company will have to merge to
fend off its rival Diageo PLC, which has twice the spirits volume
of Allied. Diageo, itself the product of a 1997 merger of Grand
Metropolitan and Guinness, owns popular brands like Johnnie Walker
whisky and Smirnoff vodka. British newspapers said Bacardi of
Bermuda, Brown-Forman of Louisville, Ky., and Pernod Ricard of
France were interested in a deal. Seagram of Montreal was also
mentioned as a possible suitor. Allied has denied the reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal with Whitbread seems to be selling a poor business to
keep a good business, and that good business has the potential to
do further deals,'' said a British money manager whose firm holds
Allied shares. Depending on the outcome of any such negotiations,
the manager said, Allied's price in a year could be between 50 and
100 pence higher.
</P>
<P>
   But others think Allied can reward shareholders handsomely
without putting itself up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Charles A. Winston, a beverage analyst at HSBC Securities in
London, is impressed with the managers of Allied's European spirits
business, saying they have proved themselves to be adept marketers.
As the company stands now, Winston puts its fair value at 6.50
pounds a share ($10.42). But with the right managers chosen from
the ranks of its European business, he thinks the stock is worth 7
pounds ($11.23). And Robert G. Cumming, an analyst at Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson, has a ``buy'' rating on the stock, with a
12-month target of 7 pounds as well.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jennings, manager of the Oppenheimer Global Growth and
Income fund, has held Allied stock for more than three years. He
reckons that by shedding its pubs, the company has positioned
itself to advance. ``They can take that cash and either buy brands
or buy back stock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said Allied has underlying growth potential of about 10
percent. After spinning off the pubs, he said, ``it becomes one of
those little money machines as opposed to something that loses
everything it makes in the pubs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
