<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO HOPES TO AVOID `NIGHTMARE SCENARIO' WITH REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ A few eager refugees came back to the border
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   No one tried to go home, and it was not hard to see why: bombs
are no longer falling, but smoke rose from two villages on the
Kosovo side. Photographers with long lenses said two corpses
floated on the far side of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Destruction aside, however, there was no sign of what aid
officials here have begun calling the ``nightmare scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the possibility that huge numbers of refugees pick up
and move back to Kosovo before NATO has made sure Serbian forces
are gone, villages are de-mined and houses are freed from booby
traps.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that refugees could return before power is restord
or there is enough food or water. Tractors putting along could clog
the main road, already rutted and barely passable.
</P>
<P>
   In short, aid officials say they are trying to head off what
could become the Kosovo refugee crisis in reverse, with the added
danger that the refugees would be resettling on a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic message is: If possible, don't go home on your
own,'' said Rupert Colville, a spokesman for the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees in Kukes. ``But it's going to be
tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Aid groups say, for the moment, that they believe signs point
away from a mad rush to the border once NATO troops arrive Kosovo.
And while many refugees said several days ago they would return as
soon as they could, interviews Friday suggested more caution now
that going home has become more than a theory.
</P>
<P>
   Friday evening, for example, the first real sign of the NATO
force that will go into Kosovo was expected to arrive here: the
advance party for the 1,500 German troops that will enter from
Albania as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are mines, you know, and it's dangerous,'' Jashar
Rrahmonaj, a 27-year-old farmer, said at the border, looking up to
the clouds of smoke above the Kosovar towns of Gorozhupe and Zhur.
``You can see them burning the villages up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rrahmonaj whizzed up in a white van with eight friends and
relatives to the border post, which only days ago rumbled with NATO
bombs and exploded mortars from fighting between Serbian forces and
the Kosovo Liberation Army. But they did not cross: They came to
get exit cards from Albanian customs officers, which many refugees
believe, mistakenly, will be required for their return.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the refugees' apparent hesitation to leave now, aid
officials say they are preparing for chaos. Radio messages and
posters are warning of the danger of mines, pleading with people to
wait until NATO has declared Kosovo safe.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans to distribute leaflets, conduct mine awareness
classes and work with women and youth groups to urge participation
in the ``ordered'' return _ which will probably not start for
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. World Food Program is preparing monthly rations to
distribute at the border, though that creates problems of its own:
The food package for one person _ 38 pounds of flour, rice, beans,
canned foods _ will be very hard to carry.
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR has also begun testing a system for re-creating the
official identity of the Kosovar refugees _ most of them stripped
by the Serbs of passports, drivers licenses and other documents _
by issuing cards with the refugees' photos. The cards will be
required for receiving aid once they get home.
</P>
<P>
   But the process takes 20 minutes per family because the system
tries to get as much information as possible, including how much
schooling each refugee has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be labor-intensive,'' Colville said.
</P>
<P>
   In the event refugees flood back home, Colville said that there
is a backup plan to simply issue papers at the border naming the
head of household. Those papers would be traded in later for the
more permanent card.
</P>
</TEXT>
