<HEADER>
A2189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-CONNECTION-NY     06-11 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CONNECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE CULTURE THE CAUSE OF ALL OF SOCIETY'S ILLS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a villain at large in the land. What led to the
horrendous behavior of the convicted policemen in the Abner Louima
torture case? What caused the killings of high school students in
Littleton, Colo.? Why did welfare often fail to change the
underclass into the working poor? Why has Microsoft been so
ruthless? And why do so many American students perform so poorly on
standardized tests?
</P>
<P>
   Culture.
</P>
<P>
   A culture of police conduct; a culture of racism; a culture of
violence; a culture of video games; a culture of poverty; a culture
of corporate aggression; a culture of permissiveness; a culture of
capitalism; a culture of multiculturalism.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the relatively new academic field of cultural
studies also treats culture as the villain: a con artist that must
be subverted, unmasked and contested.
</P>
<P>
   This roster might lead us to suspect that the word culture has
been denatured to the point of meaninglessness, but the reverse is
true. Apparently culture now provides the foundation of all
meanings. Culture has become the prime mover, the first cause. As
Adam Gopnik recently wrote in The New Yorker: ``Every age has a
term to explain things that resist explanation. The Elizabethans
had Fate; the Victorians had History; we have Culture.'' Culture
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Culture has been consolidating that power for decades. In 1952
two leading American anthropologists, Clyde Kluckhohn and Alfred
Kroeber, argued that culture is ``one of the key notions in
contemporary American thought.'' They compared it to the concepts
of gravity in physics and disease in medicine. But by treating it
as a part of American thought, they acknowledged something else:
culture, unlike gravity and disease, is itself a cultural creation.
It developed out of particular ways of thinking about the world.
And the more power culture accumulates, the more urgent it is to
understand just what it is, how it came to be and how it affects
the way we think.
</P>
<P>
   Some hints can be found in an elegant historical survey in the
opening chapters of a new book by anthropologist Adam Kuper:
``Culture: The Anthropologists' Account'' (Harvard). The modern
idea of culture, he suggests (drawing on the work of German
sociologist Norbert Elias), began as an 18th-century German
response to the French notion of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Civilization, the French asserted, was a progressive human
accomplishment, evolving over centuries. It was a supreme
achievement of Reason, culminating in the Enlightenment. But for
German intellectuals, civilization was a danger to Kultur. For
them, culture was everything civilization was not. It developed out
of spiritual values rather than reason; it was particular rather
than universal; it was reflective rather than progressive. Culture,
not civilization, was the touchstone of the Romantic
Counterenlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition between civilization and culture helped define
two centuries of French-German intellectual rivalry. It also
influenced the conflict between the 19th-century European left,
with its universalist vision of humanity guided by rational
scientific principles, and the European right, with its
particularist vision of a nation and its spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the celebration of cultural primacy is now associated
with the left in doctrines of multiculturalism, but the basic
tension between the universal and particular remains.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of culture did not develop only from opposition to a
universal human order. As anthropologists have suggested, culture
also arises out of a challenge to a binding natural order. Nature
might declare that humans are inherently acquisitive or polygamous
or rebellious; culture says it can shape human material as it
wishes. Nature is immutable; culture is constructed. Nature is the
domain of science; culture is the domain of art.
</P>
<P>
   These two declarations of independence, from Enlightenment
civilization and from nature, may have been crucial to forming the
dominant American idea of culture. Here culture becomes insistently
democratic. No culture can claim priority over any other because
there is no universal principle that might limit a culture's
authority, not even natural law. Thus culture becomes thoroughly
malleable, a free-floating set of beliefs, preferences, life
styles.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch is that because no other authority is recognized,
culture is given absolute authority over its adherents; it is
thought to mold their every act and thought.
</P>
<P>
   This is a strange situation. We know that culture has a
tremendous influence: it affects our tastes, manners, assumptions
and actions. But if we assert that culture is both absolute and
arbitrary, then culture becomes at once everything and nothing. To
a certain extent, this is the complaint of Frances Fukuyama in his
new book, ``The Great Disruption'' (Free Press). He is disturbed by
the ``problem of cultural relativism'' and its effects on social
life. He searches for a higher authority, arguing, unconvincingly,
I think, that human nature is in itself so powerful that culture
will eventually acknowledge its presence, accommodate its limits
and devise arrangements that might reconstitute what he sees as a
disrupted social order.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the modern idea of culture reigns both
powerless and supreme. Diverse and ancient ways of thinking about
human action _ notions of will, freedom, responsibility, virtue _
fade away, becoming mere flickers of cultural preference.
</P>
<P>
   And if something goes awry, culture is so arbitrary that it is
also thought to be easily altered.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers kill? Check ID at movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers smoke? Eliminate tobacco advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Cultures conflict? Teach tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural solutions are as simple as the cultural causes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the real villain is the culture of culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
