<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIKE-MYERS-$ADV13-NYT     06-11 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIKE-MYERS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY CANADIAN CONNECTION WITH `AUSTIN POWERS'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the credits for ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,''
the sequel to the inspired 1997 spy spoof, Mike Myers mugs through
another elaborately choreographed dance number. The first time I
heard this swinging instrumental by the Quincy Jones Orchestra, I
could have sworn it was the theme music from ``Definition,'' a
Canadian game show from the 1970s, whose idea of a grand prize was
a Brother typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course! I figured Myers must have chosen it as an inside
joke. After all, he grew up in Toronto. So did I, and every time I
see a Myers movie or ``Saturday Night Live'' sketch, I get pangs of
proprietary recognition and envy. We're roughly the same age. We
both watched the same bad television shows, obsessed over hockey,
hung out at doughnut shops. The difference is, he has parlayed all
these cultural reference points into a career as an acclaimed funny
man and coiner of catch phrases. I'm reduced to interviewing him
and going to his movies.
</P>
<P>
   This is my pain.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graham's big entrance in the new ``Powers'' is
accompanied by a Lenny Kravitz cover of ``American Woman,'' the
1970 anthem by Canada's own Guess Who. I used to worship the Guess
Who. Myers has Ms. Graham go-go dancing to them.
</P>
<P>
   It started with ``Wayne's World,'' the sketch about two
basement-bound teen-agers Myers and Dana Carvey originated on
``SNL'' and continued in two hit movies. These guys suit up for
street hockey in full padding and goalie masks, for a game played
with a tennis ball.
</P>
<P>
   I did that.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wayne and Garth, we'd have to yell ``Car!'' every few
minutes and drag the net onto the sidewalk. If you called another
kid on high sticking, he'd say, ``No way.'' To which you'd respond,
``Way!'' _ another Wayne-and-Garthism.
</P>
<P>
   They supposedly lived in the Chicago suburb of Aurora, Ill., but
I knew better. Myers grew up in ``Scar-beria,'' as the remote
Toronto suburb of Scarborough was known to those of us who lived
inside dynamic metro Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne's crazy ex-girlfriend gave him a gun rack. I know the
real-life ex-girlfriend who gave Myers a gun rack (it was a joke,
and she's not really crazy). Wayne and Garth went to a bar called
the Gasworks. A friend of mine bit chunks out of beer glasses at a
biker bar with the same name. I used to go to Tim Horton Donuts, a
chain serving the city's voracious doughnut needs. Myers
Americanized the name, replacing a retired Toronto Maple Leaf with
a Chicago Blackhawk, to come up with Stan Mikita Donuts.
</P>
<P>
   Garth drives a Pacer. We had a Chevette.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just ``Wayne World.'' Dieter, the pretentious German
talk-show host Myers played on ``SNL,'' was based on a waiter he
knew at a restaurant on Queen Street, in the East Village of
Toronto. Hey, I knew pretentious waiters on Queen Street! Sure,
that's a bit of a reach. But what about the crazed kilted Scotsman
_ another of his favorite characters? He plays one in his 1993
romantic comedy, ``So I Married an Axe Murderer,'' and in the new
``Austin Powers'' (a grotesque villain named Fat Bastard). On
``SNL'' he did sketches set in a store called All Things Scottish,
based, I suspect, on a Toronto landmark called Richardson's Tartan
Shop, just up the street from the Gasworks. My grandmother was
Scottish.
</P>
<P>
   He also has an affection for all things Jewish (see his ``I'm
far-klemt'' Linda Richman routine), even though he's not. Same
here.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Wieseltier, the literary editor of The New Republic, once
wrote ``I am Rushdie'' in an article protesting the fatwa against
Salman Rushdie. To express my own brand of deep identification,
I've thought of getting a button made that says, ``I am Myers.''
</P>
<P>
   I've talked to him twice, for an article on funny Canadians and
at the time of the original ``Powers.'' At the risk of seeming
stalkerish, I brought up a couple of these connections. Over lunch
two years ago at the Four Seasons Hotel in Los Angeles, I told him
I'd just met his brother Paul, who had done a funny song at the
wedding of a mutual friend in Toronto. Myers muttered something
like, ``Oh, great.'' It was as if I'd violated some rule by
bringing up a personal connection. He looked thrown off his script,
confused about how to respond.
</P>
<P>
   I've gotten this reaction before from movie stars. In the
theater of the celebrity interview, breaking the fourth wall is not
done. You could be telling the star that you both shared the same
birth mother, and he or she would stare blankly at you and keep
talking about how great it was shooting on location in Kuala
Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps me from getting weird or resentful about Myers' fame
and my comparative lack thereof is that I find almost everything he
does extremely funny. Maybe because we were weaned on the same
uniquely Canadian hybrid of British and American humor. In Rolling
Stone's June 10 cover story on Myers, he talks touchingly about his
late father, who used to wake little Mike up in the middle of the
night to watch Peter Sellers movies.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say Myers is the next Sellers. I merely look a
little like Sellers. Then again, my father never woke me up in the
middle of the night to watch ``The Pink Panther,'' although I do
remember lying in bed hearing my parents giggling at a similar
strain of silly British wit, ``Monty Python's Flying Circus.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more you know about people, the less you covet their
lives. Reading Chris Heath's excellent Rolling Stone profile, I
realized that whatever gave Myers his talent also made him _ how to
put this gently? _ unenviably odd. He spends much of his spare time
collecting and painting plastic army men. He hates to be touched.
His co-star, Ms. Graham, attested to their lack of off-screen
chemistry, calling him ``the least flirtatious person I ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   No way.
</P>
<P>
   Way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
