<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ISRAEL-MANAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VENTURES: BORN IN ISRAEL, RAISED IN THE U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(jt) 
 By JESSICA STEINBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel is called the Silicon Valley of the Middle
East because so many new technology companies get started there.
But the country differs from the California original in one crucial
respect: Fledgling companies must leave the nest to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Long on trained technologists, thanks to universal military
service, Israel also has always abounded in entrepreneurial spirit.
But turning a bright idea into a thriving business requires three
more ingredients _ capital, customers and experienced managers _
that are scarcer here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis are strong on innovation and technology but weak on
business models and strategy,'' said Samuel Rockman, managing
director of Isratec, a Jerusalem company that provides marketing
and financial advisory services for high-technology business. He
added that executive training and graduate schools of business had
appeared only recently in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   So ambitious Israeli companies are looking abroad for money,
markets and especially management, and the search usually leads
directly to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. marketplace is where the de facto leaders are
defined,'' said Nir Barkat, managing director at BRM, an investment
banking and consulting firm here specializing in high technology
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Some 82 Israeli companies, mainly technology firms, have tapped
American capital markets by listing their stocks on the New York
Stock Exchange or Nasdaq, far more than from any other country of
similar size.
</P>
<P>
   At least 150 Israeli technology companies have set up executive
or marketing offices in Boston, Washington or California, and
scores more dispatch senior executives to America for months at a
time. Barkat's firm, which teams up with entrepreneurs to turn seed
ideas into companies, often recommends establishing research and
development centers in Israel while sending company entrepreneurs
to the United States to test the business concept.
</P>
<P>
   Ely Razin, a Canadian lawyer, took that approach when he started
Expert Ease, a company that develops legal software, in Israel in
1995. He found himself shuttling between research headquarters in
Jerusalem and a marketing office in New York for the first two
years. ``If we had been started by some stellar engineer, we would
have been run aground years ago,'' Razin said. ``An engineer type
wouldn't know how to raise money, wouldn't have known how to push
to get something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkat of BRM said: ``The challenges aren't trivial. Israelis
and Americans both speak English, but they come from very different
cultures.'' A tendency toward secretiveness and reluctance to
relinquish control are more common among Israeli business people
than Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Maxwell, president of Commtouch, an Israeli-conceived and
San Francisco-based developer of consumer e-mail applications,
agreed that cultural barriers can be major issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we bring is an American face to the company,'' explained
Ms. Maxwell, who is British and is the daughter of Robert Maxwell,
the late media baron. ``Americans are funny that way; it helps to
have less of an accent when working with them.'' And the work gets
done because of the Israeli military culture and its work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're able to accomplish is highly complementary to one
another,'' Ms. Maxwell said. ``The Israelis have the prescience to
choose the market well and a lack of ego to allow someone else in
to help achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Commtouch, which was established in 1991 and counts Business
Week, Excite and Nippon Telephone and Telegraph among its clients,
is the quintessential Israeli start-up. The company's chief
executive, chief financial officer and marketing operation are in
San Francisco, while research and development are based in an old
egg warehouse in Ein Vered, an Israeli farming cooperative.
Analysts value the company, which has filed plans to go public, at
$150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maxwell, co-founder of the Magellan online guide acquired by
Excite in 1996, considered other California-based Internet
start-ups, but felt a pull toward Commtouch and the Israeli
connection. ``The people and the product seemed great, but it was
an affair of the heart,'' said Ms. Maxwell, whose father is buried
in Jerusalem.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
