<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV13-B     06-11 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET THE NEW BIG GUY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are, as nearly as I can tell, three Big Guys in
present-day American magazine journalism, as distinct from
newspapering. They are James Fallows, Michael Kinsley and, now,
Andrew Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter to readers of a business page who and how many
are in a tiny circle at the top of the opinion-making trade? Of
course it does, because such skirmishers have disproportionate
influence on taste. They become journalistic avatars associated
with the presidencies in which they came of age: Carter, Reagan,
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows is 49, Kinsley 48, Sullivan 35.
</P>
<P>
   Each served for a time as editor of a highly visible magazine _
US News and World Report (Fallows), The New Republic (Kinsley and
Sullivan), Slate (Kinsley) at the pleasure of an
intellectual/financial impressario: the Washington Monthly's
Charles Peters, The New Republic's Martin Peretz and Mortimer
Zuckerman, owner of The Atlantic Monthly and US News.?
</P>
<P>
   Each has written widely, taking sufficently strong positions on
a wide array of leading issues of the day. (Kurt Andersen, an
influential editor who co-founded Spy magazine in the mid-1980s,
might otherwise be a Big Guy, except that characteristically he has
written a hilarious novel, ``Turn of the Century,'' instead of a
tract, and keeps up a weekly column in the New Yorker.)
</P>
<P>
   It also happens that each of the three has made a splash _
Sullivan most recently _ by taking a strong position on global
business' favorite magazine, the London Economist. Surely there is
some information in that.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1988 that Kinsley quit his job as editor of The New
Republic to edit from London the magazine's American Survey _ a few
pages near the front of the book each week. ``An export item, like
Crabtree and Evelyn soap,'' he later described it. ``Americans buy
it because they assume it is an important institution in Britain.''
Yet he brought more than a little of his economic sophistication
back home.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The Washington Post three years later, the famously
dirigiste Fallows asserted that The Economist ``unwholesomely
purveys smarty-pants English attitudes on our shores.'' It had
become a sacred cow among America's professional class by asserting
its preference for markets over management in a tart English
accent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Its circulation had risen from 40,000 when Ronald Reagan took
office to 183,000 in 1991, he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Today its American circulation tops 300,000, and earlier this
month Andrew Sullivan wrote in The New Republic that ``Apart from
Austin Powers, there can be few British institutions as groovy
right now as The Economist.'' Everybody agrees, he said: Der
Spiegel, Vanity Fair, London's Sunday Telegraph, Anthony Lewis,
Bill Gates and Larry Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the closer you look at the magazine, according to Sullivan,
the more ordinary it seems.
</P>
<P>
   The Economist is drifting, he wrote. Its American Survey is out
of touch and unoriginal (except for variations on the theme of
whimsical condescension), its coverage of business and finance
overshadowed by the more original reporting of others, its market
intelligence lacking (we're still waiting for $5 oil) and its world
historical compass spinning (Kosovo? its prescriptions have been
``remarkably slithery'').
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to its vaunted analysis, (The Economist) has
shown a remarkable capacity over the past couple of years to be
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Now The Economist been publishing for 156 years, and by any
standard, it is among the most successful of all magazines. Time
and Newsweek, which also aim to furnish readers with a certain
Weltanschauung by the device of summarizing the news, are still
vital, but forever trembling on the brink of metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   The Economist, however, was founded in the aftermath of the
Napoleonic Wars to expressly espouse basic principles of free trade
and political economy. And by steering a steady course ever since,
and by concentrating on top end of the world market, it has
furnished an extremely comfortable niche.
</P>
<P>
   It rode to its current prominence in the '70s and '80s on the
strength of four broad insights propounded again and again: that
the world was not running out of oil, that the command economies of
the Soviet Union and China were falling behind, that among the
industrial democracies America was in the van, and that Japan was
not going to take over the world.
</P>
<P>
   In this program it embedded enough hard-headed original
reporting of politics, culture and science that it became, for a
time at least, a sort of de facto agenda among those who take
seriously modern management and economics.
</P>
<P>
   It is true there is a widespread feeling that The Economist is
off its recent peak, that it has ceased to be the straw that stirs
the drink. It is this feeling to which Sullivan gave vent. Indeed,
it is hard to credit the omniscience of any voice that so
frequently and completely failed to understand the significance of
events surrounding the impeachment of Bill Clinton. ``Just go,''
thundered the cover at a certain point, demanding Clinton's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan offered two reasons why ``the paper'' (as its staffers
know it) may find itself adrift. The first reason boils down to too
much Magdalen. The Oxford college (``probably the finest academic
institution in the world'') certainly has produced a huge
proportion of current staffers. The editor, his deputy and the New
York bureau chief are graduates, as were three of the four
runners-up for the top job. So is Andrew Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Such clannishness is fine for producing a distinctive voice, he
says, but it's not much on generating the necessary negative
feedback. (He doesn't mention the American executive, Marjorie
Scardino, who oversees the conglomerate that owns the magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is in the nature of things that these curious pockets of
excellence should crop up in colleges and in the papers to which
their graduates flock after graduation. The Harvard Crimson is like
this, too, to mention another obvious example, a self-selecting
group of peers who may be prone to excess in any given year. (Both
Fallows and Kinsley are former Crimson editors.)
</P>
<P>
   Precisely because some members of each new cohort want to be
what their predecessors were not, there is a kind of
self-correcting cycle built into organizations of this sort,
sufficient to provide renewal over a relatively short period of
time. The wheel within the wheel turns, thanks to the competition
among generations. Meanwhile, just as the Crimson goes on being
Cambridge's only breakfast daily, no matter where the in the cycle
it?, so The Economist remains the world's business weekly,
regardless of its editors' blind spots. Business schools teach from
it; a huge user group is involved in maintaining its relevance. The
Financial Times provides salutary competition as well.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to mark is Sullivan's second explanation of the funk,
that perhaps The Economist is another victim of the peace. ``Until
the 1990s, it had a definite role in promoting the free-market
revolution, pioneering such concepts as deregulation, privatization
and globalization.'' The magazine's liberal bent on social issues
attracted a wider following than simply market professionals. But
then the Cold War ended. ``With the end of such an ideology, the
magazine has wandered,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Has the era of market liberalism in fact ended? That's where
Sullivan comes in. Until recently, he was best known as a writer on
gay issues. There have been a pair of books: ``Virtually Normal'' a
strong brief for same-sex marriage; and ``Love Undetectable'' about
the effect of AIDS on homosexual culture. (Sullivan is gay.)
</P>
<P>
   But a remarkable piece on American conservatism in The New York
Times Sunday Magazine at exactly the right moment last autumn _
``Going Down Screaming'' _ drove home Sullivan's reputation as a
political analyst. (He writes a weekly column on American politics
for the Sunday Times of London.) Sullivan has become the newest of
the Big Guys. His decent, conservative, Catholic views, which
routinely go far beyond the measuring rod of money, illuminate the
temper of his times. The political future increasingly belongs to
those born after 1968.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
