<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO PROTECT THE EGGS? USE MORE BASKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MARK HULBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unfortunate consequence of the long bull market in stocks is
that investors are paying precious little attention to asset
allocation _ the division of their holdings between various asset
classes like stocks, bonds and real estate. They have been lured by
stocks' huge returns into thinking that equities are the only game
in town.
</P>
<P>
   That assumption is costly, and not just because the run-up in
stocks won't last forever. By focusing only on equities, investors
are also paying too high a price whenever they want to reduce risk.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you are invested only in stocks, but want to reduce
your risk by one-half. One way to do that, of course, is to
withdraw half your assets from the stock market and put them in
cash instead.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, your new portfolio will indeed be only half as risky
as the stock market, but your returns will be only be half as much
(plus the interest earned by the cash). Over the last 10 years
through April 30, the returns of a portfolio that was 50 percent
invested in the Wilshire 5000, a broad stock index, and 50 percent
in cash would have been 11.5 percent, annualized, or 6.2 percentage
points less than a pure equity portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   By expanding your allocation focus beyond stocks and cash,
however, you could improve returns without incurring any more risk.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, a fixed-allocation portfolio that was 41
percent in stocks and 59 percent in United States government bonds,
for example, would have been no more risky than the half
stocks-half cash portfolio. Yet it would have returned 12.5 percent
annualized, or one percentage point more.
</P>
<P>
   That extra percentage point is the payoff of effective asset
allocation.
</P>
<P>
   Asset allocation works because the various asset classes don't
move in lock step. When one is declining, at least one of the
others will usually be rising. The right combination can reduce
overall volatility _ and risk _ by flattening the peaks and troughs
of each class' performance. And because stocks, bonds and other
classes historically outperform cash, a good asset allocation
portfolio should outperform one that uses cash alone to reduce
risk.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of asset allocation can be seen in the
performance of investment newsletters that focus on it explicitly.
Though none of the 10 such newsletters tracked by The Hulbert
Financial Digest over the last decade through April 30 have beaten
the overall stock market through that period, six of them have
outperformed the market on a risk-adjusted basis. That is
significant, because the vast majority of newsletters that use
other strategies for beating the market _ like market timing or
stock selection _ have failed to keep pace with the stock market
when adjusted for risk.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that advisers who focus on asset allocation are smarter
than the others. When these same advisers have tried their hands at
market timing or stock selection, most of them have also failed to
beat the market. The lesson to draw is that it's easier to beat the
stock market when you expand your focus beyond equities to include
several asset classes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're not interested in reducing risk, asset allocation
is still worthwhile. Using an example that may not be altogether
realistic for all investors, let's reconsider that portfolio
containing 41 percent stocks and 59 percent bonds. How would it
have performed over the last decade if you had doubled the original
amount invested, say by borrowing the additional money?
</P>
<P>
   Your risk would have been the same as that of the stock market
itself, but you would have realized a greater return, even after
paying interest on the amounts borrowed. You would have made a 19.8
percent annualized profit over the 10 years through April 30, or
2.2 percentage points more than the 17.7 percent return of stocks
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
