<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-SPOT12-BJT-1STLED     06-11 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SPOT12-BJT-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1STLEDE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, June 12,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDs: Adds: KOSOVO-MAIN, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, WORM, VIRUS,
FLA-ABORTION, ALABAMA-LIQUOR.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ ABLE SENTRY BASE _ NATO forces, led by British
paratroopers camped along Macedonia's border, prepared to go into
to Kosovo Saturday as Serb troops continued their pullout.
Meanwhile, a Russian convoy stationed in Bosnia headed toward
Kosovo, intensifying the debate about Moscow's role in the
peacekeeping force. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
visited refugees and troops in Macedonia. As President Clinton
greeted military personnel and their families during a visit to
Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo., he was asked: ``What about the
Russians?'' ``We?ll work it out,'' the president replied.
Developing. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Alabania _ As refugees prepare to head
back, there are still threats in the form of landmines, boobie
traps and Serb paramilitary gangs continuing to loot and burn
homes. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to begin moving at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CARE _ ATLANTA _ CARE officials discuss their plans for
going back into Kosovo and say they expect three CARE staffers
imprisoned in Yugoslavia to be released. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IOWA _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the last candidate,
declared or not, to arrive in Iowa. But, when does on Saturday he
will touch down with a press entourage worthy of a president: close
to 200 reporters, major and minor network crews, the works. A
preview of the trip. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
15-18. WITH SCHEDULE.
</P>
<P>
   ETA: 8 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ABORTION _ TALLAHASSEE _ Gov. Jeb Bush on Friday signed into
law a bill that marks the first restrictions on a woman's right to
an abortion in Florida since Roe v. Wade. The law, sure to be
challenged in court, requires that the parents of a girl under 18
to be notified if she is going to have an abortion. Civil
libertarians and privacy advocates vow to challenge the law.
(Elmore, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WORM _ ATLANTA _ Even as the FBI was trying to trace the source
of the Explorer worm that infected computers worldwide Thursday and
Friday, most organizations and companies that had been hit by it
purged the infection after a few hours. Observers say the worm's
impact was lessened by the fact that it came just a few weeks after
the less-harmful Meliss virus, which prompted many computer
networks to strengthen their protection systems. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-LIQUOR _ Alabama state attorneys say the Legislature
approved a bill that would make Sunday liquor sales legal statewide
in wet communities _ apparently without knowing what they were
approving, and Gov. Don Siegelman has not decided if he will sign
it. Sen. Tom Butler, D-Madison, said Friday that Siegelman told him
he would not approve the bill. Butler said the measure contains
some ``crafty wording'' by an attorney who apparently wrote it. But
the governor's press secretary, Kristin Carvell, said several hours
later that Siegelman has not decided whether to sign the bill.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-MAYORS _ NEW ORLEANS _ The U.S. Conference of Mayors opens
its gathering with a session on gun lawsuits. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION-CARS _ ATLANTA _ EPA holds second of four national
public hearings on new pollution rules for automobiles. The agency
is proposing tougher standards for both cars and SUV's, but many
environmental and public interest groups say even more stringent
standards are needed, particularly for large SUV's. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS _ WASHINGTON _ As the world becomes more interconnected by
computers, viruses like this week's data-destroying ``worm'' will
become more common, experts warned Friday. Malicious people will
always be able to infect software, they said, but consumers can
protect themselves if they are diligent. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in Washington (w) and financial (f) categories.
</P>
<P>
   POGO _ WASHINGTON _ The Project on Government Oversight, a
little-known group that labors for low pay in search of fraud and
inefficiency in government, is being accused of bribing an Interior
Department employee. A POGO lawsuit recently forced Mobil Oil Co.
to pay the government $45 million in back royalties for oil pumped
from taxpayer-owned land. As part of the settlement, $1.2 million
went to POGO, which chose to make $350,000 ``grants'' to two
bureaucrats, one retired. The organization said the money was to
reward the bureaucrats for ``putting their jobs on the line'' by
pressing for action to force repaymenty of royalties. But House
Resources Committee Chairman Don Young says the ``grant'' to a
current federal employee was an illegal payoff. Cheered by oil
company lawyers, Young has launched an investigation.
(Nesmith/Malone, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
