</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in Washington (w) and financial (f) categories.
</P>
<P>
   COX-MP3 _ We take a detailed look at MP3 technology and what it
says about the future of music distribution. As many details of Cox
deal as can get. Feeds from Sonia Murray on artist reax and fan
relationship. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECHNO-BUDDY12 _ A look at technologies that have changed the
way we live - an attempt to put MP3 in perspective. (Husted,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CINNABON _ Cinnabon, a subsidiary of Atlanta-based AFC
Enterprises, is embarking upon a major expansion both domestically
and internationally. The company said it plans its first entrance
into the Asian market with 42 units and to expand its reach in the
Middle East with another 42 units. Then, to top it off, the
company, which sells cinnamon rolls, has inked a deal with Host
Marriott to open 52 stores in various airports. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-ASIA _ Coca-Cola Co. announced a $275 million equity deal
Friday to acquire Fraser and Neave Ltd., and a majority of its
bottling operations in Asia. Coca-Cola said the deal is consistent
with its strategy of investing in bottling operations to maximize
efficiency in production, distribution and marketing. It will gain
bottling operations in Brunei, Cambodia, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri
Lanka, Singapore and Vietnam. In exchange, Fraser and Neave will
get Coca-Cola's 5.6 percent stake in Australia-based Coca-Cola
Amatil, a stake valued at $275 million. Coca-Cola Co. now has a 43
percent stake in Amatil, which will be reduced to 37 percent.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-BOEING _ Delta Air Lines annouces today it will defer its
remaining Boeing 777 orders because of a stalemate over pilot pay.
The move is expected to delay for months or years the Atlanta-based
carrier's plans to make the giant jet a significant part of its
international fleet. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SOCOM-BRITAIN _ Southern Co. announced the sale today of the
marketing segment of its British electricity distributor for $256
million in a wave of mergers and acquisitions that is sweeping
across Britain's newly deregulated utility industry. (Quinn,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   THOMASTON-MILLS _ Thomaston Mills announces a reorganization and
downsizing beginning in September. THe company will exit the
industrial, sales yarn and denim markets, eliminating 700 of its
2,350 jobs. A plant in Zebulon, GA will lose 145 jobs, the rest
will come out of Thomaston and sales offices in New York and Los
Angeles. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
