<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVESTING-WITH-ARMSTR     06-11 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-WITH-ARMSTRONG-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH ARDEN ARMSTRONG: MAS MID-CAP GROWTH FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., Okla.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arden Armstrong, lead manager of the $887.6 million MAS Mid-Cap
Growth fund, cheerfully acknowledges the growth-oriented nature of
her investing discipline. She asks only that her style not be
confused with the methods of other growth-fund managers. ``We like
to find quality growth,'' she explained from her office in West
Conshohocken, Pa. ``We're not momentum or
growth-at-a-reasonable-price investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Three elements characterize what she calls ``quality growth''
companies: projected annual earnings growth of more than 15 percent
over the next one to three years, expanding profit margins over the
same period and consistency in the profit growth _ to rule out
companies benefiting from unusual conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The fund seems to have benefited from the formula. MAS Mid-Cap
returned 25.9 percent, annualized, for the three years ended June
4, compared with 12.3 percent for its peer group of mid-cap growth
funds, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher, and 27.6 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, individuals have been able to buy fund shares
through through financial advisers; the fund was previously
available only to institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Armstrong, 38, begins the stock-selection process with a
computer program that looks at the 2,500 or so companies traded on
United States exchanges that have market capitalizations of $500
million to $5 billion. About 40 percent of them have the quality
earnings characteristics she seeks and become candidates for
further research, which she does with the help of two co-managers
and eight analysts. They whittle down their list to the 90 or so
stocks in the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The research focuses on whether Wall Street earnings estimates
are sustainable. On company balance sheets, she looks for lean
inventories and low totals in accounts receivable and in working
capital _ a sign of a company that operates efficiently, producing
excess cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   She also reviews companies' market position. ``In small-cap and
mid-cap investing,'' she said, ``you can end up with little
companies that compete with big companies.'' She avoids those small
companies because they risk being overwhelmed and looks instead for
those that are industry leaders in fragmented industries or that
dominate in narrow market niches.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly one-third of the portfolio is always allocated to
aggressive-growth stocks _ with rates of earnings growth above 25
percent _ and another third to more stable growth companies. The
remainder shifts between those two categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've trimmed our holdings in the stable growers because we're
trying to get more economically sensitive stocks that are poised to
benefit from a better global economy, like semiconductor or energy
stocks,'' she said. ``These are a little more cyclical, but I think
we're in the right point in the cycle for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The price she will pay varies. If a company has a very stable
growth rate, she's willing to pay a price-to earnings multiple that
is higher than the comparable earnings growth rate. For cyclical
growth companies with low profit margins and no excess cash flow,
she is likely to pay a multiple that is only 60 percent to 80
percent of the comparable growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   She bought CNF Transportation, a Palo Alto, Calif., air carrier
and trucking company, for $44 a share in January. ``Merchandise
bought over the Internet is generally shipped by the U.S. post
office, and CNF has a contract with the post office for providing
transportation for priority mail on the East Coast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   CNF owns Emery Worldwide, a shipping company that has suffered
over the last two years as many foreign economies stumbled. But CNF
has cut costs and improved service, she said, and its earnings
should improve as economic activity picks up abroad. Analysts
expect earnings to grow 14.3 percent annually over the next three
years. The stock now trades at $39.25, or 11.7 times the earnings
of $3.36 a share that analysts estimate for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Armstrong began buying General Instrument, which makes
analog cable set-top boxes, at $20 a share in April 1998, hoping to
profit from the cable TV boom. The company has been introducing
digital cable versions of its boxes, she said, and is upgrading its
equipment to provide modem and telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   General Instrument had a 1998 net profit margin of 10.9 percent.
Wall Street expects earnings to grow 23.5 percent a year over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The stock now trades at $38.25, or 32.7 times expected 2000
earnings of $1.17 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The fund recently added to its position in Premier Parks, which
it originally bought in 1997 at $16 a share. The company, based in
Oklahoma City, acquired the Six Flags theme parks and name from
Time Warner last year and has been rechristening the larger parks
it already owned with the Six Flags name.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Armstrong says the company is likely to see steady growth
because its parks are used by day-trippers and are not as sensitive
to the economy as parks requiring longer stays.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is an acquisition-driven company, Ms. Armstrong looks
at Premier Parks' earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and
amortization which she expects to grow 22 percent a year over the
next three years. The stock now trades at $37.50.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2242 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGIOUS-MUSIC-COX     06-11 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-MUSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Songs of devotion
 &HT;    (Eds: Moving in lifestyle and entertainment categories.)
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, Word Records and Myrrh Records released the
first of a series of recordings called ``My Utmost for His
Highest,'' original songs by some of the top voices in contemporary
Christian music that were inspired by the classic devotional of the
same name by Oswald Chambers. At the same time, an updated edition
of the book was published.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad strategy: Use music, a main medium of communication
for the rock-'n'-roll-and-beyond generations, to entice listeners
to check out the written word.
</P>
<P>
   The record was well-received, earning the Gospel Music
Association's Dove Award for special event of the year in 1996, the
book sold and the marketing idea caught on so well that Word
recently released two similar projects. They take slightly
different approaches, but both are worthy, and one stands out among
the best music of 1999. Word introduced them to the press and
Christian music industry in April at a concert during Gospel Music
Week in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs From The Book,'' which came out May 18, is the more
obvious promotional tool. ``The Book'' is a special edition of the
New Living Translation of the Bible, which was published by Tyndale
House in 1996. Citing polls by Gallup and Barna that almost 90
million Americans have not read the Bible, Word and Tyndale House
are partnering with the Christian Broadcasting Network on a $7
million media blitz to try to add more than 10 million readers for
``The Book'' _ and sell a bunch of Bibles. Part of the marketing
drive will include ads featuring Kathie Lee Gifford, Roma Downing,
Reggie White, Tara Lipinski and others.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the 14 ``Songs From The Book'' are written for the
project. Michael Card gets things off to a rousing start with ``The
Book.'' Jerry McPherson's bouzouki tosses in a little Greek
seasoning to this otherwise Celtic-flavored cut. The harmonies and
cool urban stylings of Anointed are featured in ``The Word,'' which
speaks of the comfort and practical counsel offered in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Two modern classics, however, have been reworked by different
artists. The first radio single is ``El Shaddai,'' the CCM hymn
written by Card and John Thompson in 1981 that became a signature
song for Amy Grant. However, signaling that the song has been
handed off to a new generation, the song is performed here by
Winans Phase 2, cousins who are the sons of the Winans brothers.
Their slightly R&AMP;B interpretation is smooth and every bit as
reverent as previous ones, and Grant offers her stamp of approval
by singing backing vocals. In the Nashville concert during GMA
Week, she joined the group on stage for a duet that was among the
night's highlights. That night, Grant also shared a nostalgic duet
with Michael W. Smith on a song they co-wrote, ``Thy Word.'' Here
that song is performed by Ginny Owens, a recent addition to Smith's
Rocketown label, who is able to capture some of the same innocence
and earnestness that made Grant's 1984 recording so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Sixpence None the Richer, which has caused major mainstream buzz
with its little love song ``Kiss Me,'' offers a remake of its own
song, ``Trust,'' a confession of childlike faith with a chorus that
etches itself in the mind and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The other songs are previously released material such as Crystal
Lewis' duet with Ron Kenoly, ``Beauty for Ashes,'' Jaci Velasquez's
hit from last year, ``God So Loved,'' and this year's Dove winner
for song of the year, ``My Deliverer,'' by The Ragamuffins. While
all are good songs well done, they've received so much exposure
that their inclusion here seems almost overkill. Not so with two
songs that were part of the first ``My Utmost for His Highest:
Sometimes He Comes in the Clouds,'' by Steven Curtis Chapman, and
``You Are Holy,'' by 4Him, are worth reviving.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Songs From The Book'' plays like a collection of
disparate if well-crafted songs, the other Word project,
``Streams,'' is remarkable for its continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Released June 1, ``Streams'' is connected with an updated 1997
edition of the ``Streams in the Desert'' devotional by L.B. Cowman
that was edited by James Reimann for Zondervan Publishing. While
dollar figures weren't announced for the publicity push, Christian
retailers have had promotional material for a month, and floor
displays contain both the CD and a newly released edition of the
devotional, with a blue cover to match the disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Streams,'' too, has connections with ``My Utmost for His
Highest.'' Word Entertainment President Loren Balman, who was
executive producer of ``My Utmost,'' has the same task here. He and
producer Brent Bourgeois have created a wonderful, unified work by
repeatedly using complementary songwriters, such as Cindy Morgan
and Michelle Tumes; collaborating on some of the songs themselves;
having singers do vocals on numbers they didn't write; and using
the musicians, including the Irish Film Orchestra, to even things
out where needed.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its goal of providing ``songs of hope, healing and
restoration,'' this is no rock album, and its slower tempo might
take awhile to appreciate. But it is well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job,'' written by Morgan and Balman and sung by Morgan, sets
the pace with a melancholy rendering of the Old Testament character
beset by problems he doesn't understand, full of questions and
doubts but determined not to give up on God. Morgan's passionate,
plaintive rendering of the chorus (``All I have is Yours/All these
ashes and these sores/All that I am living for/I will follow you to
shore'') is possibly the best vocal performance of her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Streams'' also manages to group singers in unusual
combinations successfully. Remember Peter Gabriel's ``Don't Give
Up'' from the '80s? Here the song is reworked slightly to make God,
with the voice of the Doobie Brothers' Michael McDonald, the one
who comforts Maire Brennan, the Irish singer from Clannad.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois' ``The Only Thing I Need,'' one of the more upbeat
cuts, features 4Him and Jon Anderson of Yes. With vocals starting
out like the pealing of bells, 4Him, sans Anderson, carried this
off without a hitch at the GMA concert.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most unexpected pairing is British rockers Delirious
with Grant on ``Find Me in the River.'' The original version of the
song appeared on the group's ``Cutting Edge'' disc on Sparrow.
Here, however, Grant's harmony, which takes advantage of her
constantly-improving lower register, gives the song added
grounding. ``Find Me in the River'' becomes a song of determination
in the midst of pain; its soulful electric guitar becomes almost
another vocalist, and the loops by Tedd T. add an ethereal edge
that implies perseverance is not in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Also appearing are Jaci Velasquez, Tumes, Sixpence None the
Richer again, Chris Rodriguez, Point of Grace and, perhaps the
oddest fit, Burlap to Cashmere. The trademark acoustic guitarwork
of Johnny Philippides and vocal of Steve Delopoulos make this cut
stick out a little stylistically, but Uileann pipes and low whistle
keep it from veering too far off course.
</P>
<P>
   In one last twist, ``Streams'' wraps up with a four-song
orchestral suite. Typically, instrumentals are interspersed
throughout a project, but by grouping them, ``Streams'' leaves the
listener feeling rested and restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Streams'' will set the standard for any like-minded project in
the future, and judging from how well several numbers worked live
in Nashville, don't be surprised if a ``Streams'' tour flows into a
venue near you.
</P>
<P>
   James Lloyd writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
