</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP FRONT-RUNNER BUSH BRACES FOR NATIONAL PRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has had a down and up
relationship with the media.
</P>
<P>
   He snarled at reporters about their coverage of his father's
1992 presidential campaign. &UR;  &LR; He said journalists investigated his
personal life back then because they had been ''stirred up`` by
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after years of reaping ``good press'' as Texas governor, he
says the Texas media respect him. He is downright chummy with
reporters. He says he is jealous of their freedom to be
smart-alecks.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bush starts campaigning for president with the status of
front-runner for the Republican nomination, he may go back to
square one. Longtime observers of presidential campaign coverage
say the national press is ready to pounce on the Texas governor _
and that his powers of self-defense will be limited.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of things perhaps to come, the Wall Street Journal in
May ran a front-page story detailing unsavory rumors about Bush's
personal past that it acknowledged it could not verify.
</P>
<P>
   University of Virginia professor Larry Sabato wrote the book
that applied the term ``feeding frenzy'' to the fierce
concentration of media attention to political scandal, and he says
Bush is ripe for one or more such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can expect a classic feeding frenzy,'' Sabato said. ``You
cannot get 250 journalists together, representing every major news
organizations in the world, without an attempt by at least some of
these organizations to find fault and generate controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The press entourage on Bush's first campaign trip, which starts
Saturday, indeed may reach 250 people and includes news crews from
foreign publications. Bush spent Friday at fund-raisers in Chicago
and St. Louis before returning to Austin, Texas, to pick up the
traveling media and fly to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters will try to bait Bush into making misguided or
embarrassing comments, Sabato said, and knowing about the ``gaffe
watch'' ahead of time will not necessarily protect Bush from making
such a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he watched his father go through it and even
though he has been elected (governor) twice, it will still be like
nothing he has ever imagined,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has recruited a campaign communications staff that is
experienced in trying to limit gaffes and the reaction to them. His
chief campaign spokesman is David Beckwith, who worked for Dan
Quayle during Quayle's gaffe-prone vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is also telling himself to exercise verbal self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to quip,'' he said. ``I am mindful though, I have to be
careful what I say. Otherwise it gets totally blown out of
proportion. It's going to take some discipline on my part not to
quip back when the quippers quip.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, what's a governor to do in the face of a media
onslaught?
</P>
<P>
   ``You do your homework,'' said University of Houston political
scientist Richard Murray. ``You sure don't want to play into the
suspicions of the national press that you are not well prepared. He
needs to be well prepared, and he needs to be well informed;
comfortable in discussing a wide range of topics beyond what a
governor has to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has hosted intense, lengthy meetings with foreign policy
experts, many hailing from his father's and Ronald Reagan's White
House administration, to bone up on presidential issues.
</P>
<P>
   It would also help, Murray said, if ``you know how to pronounce
Kosovars, and that it's `Greeks,' not `Grecians,' and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, hardly an experienced hand at foreign policy, did once
describe the residents of war-ravaged Kosovo as ``Kosovians'' _ the
kind of verbal mishap that can plague a candidate under intense
media scrutiny. He also recently referred to natives of Greece as
``Grecians.''
</P>
<P>
   In an April interview, Bush said he respects the media's role in
the political process. But, he added, he already senses the
hostility that comes with his position as the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain sense of, `We'll show this guy,''' the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was miffed at reporters' attempts to portray his
inner thoughts and the essence of his personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the profiles, and all the people trying to figure out what
I am all about and stuff, makes me a little uncomfortable,'' he
said. ``I think people trying to figure out my psyche, and
psychoanalysis _ I am not very good about that, and I know if I'm
not very good about it, they aren't either.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bush maintains friendly relations with individual reporters
in and out of Texas, to an unusual degree for a candidate from the
Republican Party, which often views the press as biased in favor of
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   During his father's presidential campaign, he forged friendships
with national political columnists who, one-by-one, have
interviewed the governor in Austin this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
He addresses some Houston Chronicle reporters by nicknames he has
coined. He sent a get-well card to a Chronicle reporter who
developed a a serious illness. On the other hand, he also did not
hesitate to call a midlevel Chronicle editor at home in the evening
this year to express misgivings about an article that was about to
be published.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The experts say Bush's media friendships might help him fend off
some of the hair-trigger news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to milk the symbiotic relationship, recognizing that
everything down the road is going to be adversarial,'' Murray said.
``You hope you build a pretty good foundation that will help you
ride out the rough spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said Republican presidential candidate Pat Buchanan, a TV
commentator, showed in previous contests that having friends in the
right studios and newsrooms can help a campaign that theoretically
is covered on the same basis as the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buchanan has gotten almost a free ride in some campaigns
because of his close association with CNN and many in the print
media,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sabato said Bush's pleasant media encounters in the past
will not help in any long-lasting way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (reporters) will turn on you the third day rather than
the first day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the Chronicle he doesn't consider ``the media'' a
monolith that takes a constant approach to his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between someone who takes time to
thoughtfully write a story and somebody who just slops stuff from
the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's professed tolerance of media criticism also appears
to have its limits.
</P>
<P>
   In a May interview on ABC, he said that as part of the national
political system, the media plays ``a game to destroy somebody's
reputation.'' He has explained that he does not plan to go into
detail about his ``young and irresponsible'' days, and he has
refused to say whether he used marijuana or cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   When an Internet prankster created a Web site that lampoons
Bush's official Web site, Bush called him a ``garbage man'' and
added, ``There ought to be limits to freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
