A2262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOLETO-FESTIVAL-NYT &LR;      06-11 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: ARTISTIC NOVELTY STILL NOVEL AT SPOLETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The elderly theatergoer was eager for
enlightenment. ``Why do you have that masking tape on your back?''
she asked an actor sporting a black strip on his costume, between
the shoulder blades. ``It represents our skin color,'' replied the
actor, whose job it was to mingle with the audience just before the
curtain.
</P>
<P>
   She looked puzzled by the redundancy _ the actor was black _ but
it was a wonderful exchange all the same, this brief colloquy
between the older Southern woman and the young emissary from the
experimental wing of New York theater. The production for which
they had traveled to Spoleto Festival U.S.A. was a quirky,
modernist reworking of the 1939 low-country melodrama ``Mamba's
Daughters,'' by Target Margin Theater, a small downtown company
known as much for its curious visual flourishes (blue faux tattoos
on ear lobes and chins, for instance) as for its eclectic
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pleasant shock, arriving and finding a lack of
resistance to the director David Herskovits' quasi-radical ideas
about performance; Heather Gillespie, the lead actress of
``Mamba's,'' captivating here as in New York, received a thunderous
curtain call for her portrayal of an illiterate laborer with a
tender heart in Dorothy and DuBose Heyward's clunky drama.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, one could sense open-mindedness in the theaters of
Charleston toward the radical notions promulgated night after night
in Spoleto's offerings. Audiences were revved up for challenges,
whether they came by way of Laurie Anderson's synthesized worship
service in honor of the whale (in ``Songs and Stories From Moby
Dick'') or in the American debut of a political SOS in operatic
form by Kurt Weill (``Die Buergschaft'') or even in the
intellectual idiosyncrasies of a group of New York actors
performing a stodgy old play with pieces of masking tape on their
backs. (The tape being Herskovits' comment on the play's racial
hierarchies.)
</P>
<P>
   The festival has been throwing open this dewy city of antebellum
refinement and she-crab soup to artistic novelty for 22 years now.
And of course in an enterprise of this scope _ more than 100 dance,
opera, chamber music, jazz and theater performances take place over
17 days each spring _ the results are bound to vary. That is why
the forbearance of the Charleston audience is a decided blessing; a
little patience is in order in approaching the festival and
especially for its theatrical ventures, in all of their messy and
adventurous aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Though much of Spoleto's theater is imported _ the visiting
productions included the sleight-of-hand of ``Ricky Jay and his 52
Assistants'' and the puppetry of Ping Chong in ``Kwaidan'' _ the
festival itself produced the American premiere of ``Die
Buergschaft'' (``The Pledge''). The caustic and prophetic 1932
opera, composed by Weill and with a libretto by Weill and Caspar
Neher, takes a figurative machete to the politics of the Nazi power
grab in Germany, the country that the Jewish Weill was soon to flee
and renounce.
</P>
<P>
   Weill, whose collaboration with Bertolt Brecht had all but ended
by the time of ``Die Buergschaft,'' straddled the worlds of opera
and theater. This was a circumstance vividly illustrated by the
director Jonathan Eaton's brooding, menacing Spoleto production.
The work's epic nature, its reliance on the power of parable, its
formalized emotions and its polemical call to arms all carry strong
echoes of Brecht. All these elements are vibrantly incorporated
into Eaton's staging of the opera, which plays as a three-hour
descent into an ever more dehumanized and mercenary version of
hell.
</P>
<P>
   Sung in German with English surtitles and conducted by Julius
Rudel, the tale unfolds in the land of Urb, a storybook nation of
inbred cynicism. ``People don't change; it's circumstances that
change the way they act,'' sings the chorus, perched throughout the
opera on double-decker platforms on each side of the Sottile
Theater stage. ``Die Buergschaft'' reiterates this sentiment again
and again in the story of the friendship of David Orth (Dale
Travis), a grain merchant, and Johann Mattes (Frederick Burchinal),
a cattleman, men of vastly different temperaments who degrade
themselves equally in the deprivation and profiteering that follows
Urb's occupation by a Gestapo-like ruling body.
</P>
<P>
   Danila Korogodsky's flimsy cardboard sets stand in contrast to
the opera's assertion of the immutability of man's character. Even
the placard the chorus flashes as a symbol of Orth's and Mattes'
bond, a spray-painted silhouette of their handshake, plays with the
idea of impermanence; theirs is a shadow of a friendship, easily
obscured.
</P>
<P>
   In its own time, ``Die Buergschaft'' must have seemed
terrifyingly potent: imagine an opera set today, say, in the
complicated killing fields of Rwanda or Chechnya. Weill's and
Neher's evocations of the Fascist threat, the opportunism of the
collaborators (embodied splendidly by the production's three
henchmen, played by Peter Lurie, Lawrence Craig and Herbert Perry)
and the struggles of the oppressed masses are both prescient and
almost journalistically precise.
</P>
<P>
   But the work lacks a galvanizing presence. There's no equivalent
of Macheath of ``Threepenny Opera''; neither Orth nor Mattes
emerges as a compelling figure in his own right. It is left to
Anna, Mattes' wife, portrayed to heart-rending effect by the
mezzo-soprano Margaret Thompson, to lay claim to an audience's
hopes and sympathies. (Ann Panagulias is nearly as haunting in the
role of the Mattes' daughter Luise, who turns to a life of
prostitution.) In the treatment by Eaton and Rudel, ``Die
Buergschaft'' is a fascinating if protracted piece of agitprop.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson, the performance artist, is preoccupied by the epic
form as well. Her ``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick,'' which is to
be presented by the Brooklyn Academy of Music later this season,
amounts to her own alternative telling of Melville's classic
American novel. One senses that Ms. Anderson is still in pursuit of
the elusive core of her multi-media spectacle. What she presented
at Spoleto was a digressive series of intriguing songs and scenes
that combine her personal response to the novel with bits of
extraneous whale trivia that may not have been known to Melville.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal, it appears, is to elucidate what is relevant to a
modern audience in ``Moby-Dick.'' It must be for this reason that
Ms. Anderson includes a passage of her own devising that would
probably do Greenpeace proud, a lecture on how sperm whales
communicate and how they got that unusual name. (It dates back, Ms.
Anderson explains, to a misunderstanding over the consistency of
the whale's brain.) Several of Ms. Anderson's conceits are
inspired: a heavy-handed sea chantey from a florid early film
adaptation of the novel is funny. But many of the other musical
interludes merely repeated themselves. Given that Spoleto so
wholeheartedly embraces experiment, it was only fitting that this
should be considered a tryout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
