u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-PLANS-NYT &LR;      06-11 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-PLANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT EXECUTIVE MOVING TO NISSAN SKETCHES SOME OF HIS IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Carlos Ghosn, the former Renault SA executive who will
soon be helping manage Nissan Motor Co., on Friday gave reporters a
peek at where he hopes to help steer the troubled Japanese
automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn is an important part of the complex, cross-border alliance
that began in March, when Renault bought a 36.8 percent piece of
Nissan in hopes of improving its long-term chances of survival. As
such, Ghosn has spent much of the time since the deal was announced
trying to get to know the company he will officially join later
this month. He is also taking a crash course in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of informal press briefings Friday, he made it clear
that he had not finished his research but had some ideas about
where he will be heading when he becomes chief operating officer of
Japan's second-largest car company. ``Even if it's not complete,
there are a lot of chapters of this diagnosis already written,''
Ghosn said.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Ghosn said, Nissan's suppliers are on notice that
if they hope to work with the company going forward, they must
prove they can provide the best technical innovation, quality and
price.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn also said that the dealership networks that Nissan owns
are less profitable than their independently owned cousins. He
hinted that Nissan should increase the number of independent
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   He even foreshadowed what may become the first friction between
Nissan and its new partner, the potential purchase by Nissan of a
stake in Renault that would mirror Renault's stake in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of such a reciprocal purchase was a significant
part of the agreement between the two companies. It allowed Nissan
to save face and it underscored the notion that the two companies
were equal partners, not knight and vanquished. Nissan president
Yoshikazu Hanawa, soon to be Ghosn's boss, said this week at a
meeting in Paris that he hoped to consummate that part of the deal
as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn, however, sounded less eager, perhaps because it will be
his job to make sure Nissan pays down a big chunk of the billions
of dollars of debt that drove it to seek a partnership with
Renault. ``I really don't know,'' he said when asked whether Nissan
would purchase shares in Renault. ``The most important thing is
putting Nissan back to profitability, and then we can decide what
to do with the cash.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that that decision should be based on whether the
purchase of Renault's shares would be the best use of the company's
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Any potential conflict on this issue, however, will not happen
soon. Ghosn said Nissan's losses would widen in the fiscal year
that ends March 31, although he said Nissan might recover
profitability in the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it will happen; I'm saying it's possible,'' he
said. ``We'll need a little luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian-born executive has spent his time meeting as many
Nissan employees as possible, using interpreters who specialize in
both French and English, as well as a trusted assistant to help him
along. ``Unfortunately, I don't speak Japanese well enough to
conduct a business conversation, but it will come, it will come,''
he said. ``It's part of the cost saving.''
</P>
<P>
   Light-hearted as he may be, Ghosn seems to clearly understand
the challenges he will face in trying to turn around one of Japan's
most conservative and traditional companies. ``What I'd like to do
is probably different from what I'll be doing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1830EDT &QL; 
