</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service news budget for Sunday, June 13, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-G8 _ WASHINGTON _ As the Group of Seven industrial
nations, plus Russia, prepare to meet in cologne Germany later this
week, foremost on their minds will be how to knit the war-torn
Balkans back into the fabric of Europe. Developing. (Deans, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ We take a look at ethnic
relations, the bottom line reason for NATO bombing campaign of the
last 2 1/2 months, and how this will be dealt with in upcoming
months. The Serbs and ethnic Albanians don't like or trust one
another any more than they did 11 weeks ago. We will get into some
of the bad stuff happening over the last months (years) as
</P>
<P>
   well as have a bit of a forward spin. (Kunstel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Fri., June 11, in International and Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS PAGE EDs: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the
current week. This layout is now available.Art includes five color
photos
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0612 KOSOVO AIR _ There has never been an air
campaign quite like it. Over 78 days, NATO warplanes flew 35,000
sorties, dropped 23,000 bombs, destroyed 1,500 targets and
shattered the backbone of a central European military force, all
without losing a single U.S. or allied pilot in combat. But the
campaign has raised questions and sparked debate whether air power
alone can win a war without the use of ground troops. (Deans, Cox
Washington Bureau). Art includes 3-column color photo of a jet
fighter leaving the flight deck of a carrier; a 2-column photo of
soldiers aiming guns out of a helicopter; a 12-pica photo of a B-2
bomber; a 6-pica photo of a helictoper delivering goods to troops.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO FUTURE -- Although the political future of Kosovo is left
vague in the settlement that ended the war, American and NATO
officials say they envision an international protectorate that will
in theory be part of Yugoslavia but that may well, after a few
years, become independent. (Perlez, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes 2-column color photo of worried Albanian refugee.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush makes his first out-of-state
trip as a presedential explorer. Iowa and New Hampshire are eager
to meet him in person. We pose the questions of how much his
delayed campaigning has hurt him and whether there's any backlash
for Bush not announcing he's a candidate. After all, he's raised
more money and is higher in the polls than any other GOP candidate.
How much more exploring does Bush need to do? When does he simply
appear indecisive? (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Spot sidebar may be filed.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story will be filed by 8 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Al Gore sits down with a few regional
reporters in advance of his formnal announcement for president next
week (Wednesday). (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FAULDER-ADVANCE _ GLADEWATER, Texas _ Joseph Stanley Faulder,
61, is scheduled for execution after 7 p.m. EDT Thursday for the
July 8, 1975 slaying of Inez Phillips in her Gladewater, Texas,
home. Faulder is a native of Canada, and if the Thursday death
penalty is carried out he will become the first Canadian executed
in the United States since 1952. Gladewater residents talk about
Inez Phillips _ ``It really shook up the whole town, because she
was so beloved and so innocent'' _ in a story that advances the
Faulder execution. (Graham, Longview News-Journal). 24. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-PREVIEW _ Olympic organizers in Salt Lake and Sydney
have told IOC members not to expect to be treated royally at their
Games, as the members are accustomed to. Several candidates to host
the 2006 Winter Games fear that they haven't had a chance to
``sell'' their cities because of a travel restriction for members.
In many small ways, the Salt Lake City scandal has changed the way
the Olympics does business. Advancing big IOC meetings in Seoul.
(Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: List of agenda at the IOC meetings.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (s) Sports and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-ADVANCE _ Spending some time with Southern Baptists, in
Atlanta for next week's annual meeting of the Soutern Baptist
Convention, as they go door-to-door Saturday, spreading the gospel
and trying to save souls. Story also focuses on evening concert at
Centennial Park where parents of of some of the victims of the
Columbine, Colo. shooting are scheduled to appear. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   TROPICAL- DISEASES _ Every year, 3 million people die from
malaria, most of them children. Of the 90 million people living in
Latin America, 20 million of them are infected with Chagas Disease,
a fatal condition created by a parasite that damages the heart.
Millions more suffer from African Sleeping Sickness and River
blindness. Researchers at the University of Georgia are hoping to
help remedy these situations. The newly formed Center for Tropical
and Emerging Global Diseases will focus on finding vaccines for
these and other devestating conditions. We talk with director Rick
Tarleton about the center, its scope, purpose and future. 18.
(McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ As communities _ from Littleton, Colo., to Conyers,
Ga. _ reel from violence among their children, a host of
anti-violence programs like Family Solutions are flooding the
schools, churches and counseling centers. But researchers are
hesitant to declare victory. Too many programs are
well-intentioned, but don't have either the data or the history to
show they can live up to their promises, scientists say. (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICCOSUKEES _ For more than 100 years, they lived a rugged,
primitive life deep in the harsh but beautiful Everglades, isolated
from the white settlers who pushed them off more hospitable coastal
lands. But this week, the once-isolated Miccosukee Indians enter a
new era with the official June 14 opening of their 302-room luxury
gambling resort perched on the border of the vast swamp. The tribe
has already prospered with a popular bingo operation on the site,
but the new resort will feature video gambling machines and
top-flight entertainers like Hootie and the Blowfish and Bill
Cosby. Environmentalists worry about the tribe's growing
developments in and around the troubled Everglades, but tribe
officials say they have done more to save the swamp than anybody
else. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SEGREGATION _ WASHINGTON _ Even as the nation becomes more
racially diverse, the public education system is consolidating a
trend toward racial resegregation that began in the late 1980s,
according to a new study by the Civil Rights Project and
researchers at the Harvard Graduate School of Education. (Mollison)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move Saturday.
