</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SCHOOL _ BAGHDAD, Iraq _ With their sneakers, cartoon
backpacks and pony tails, these girls could fit in at any school.
But, when visitors enter classes at the Hidayeh (Enlightenment)
Elementary School in Baghdad, the students rise together with
smiles and shout, ``Welcome and long live the leader, Saddam
Hussein!'' There's something else different about schools in Iraq.
This one, with about 1,200 girls, has one telephone and no copying
machine, lights are often out and many students sit on the floors
for lack even a broken-down desk. Each year, the girls start their
studies by erasing the penciled-in work in last-year's workbooks so
they can be reused. Serious Samar Khatab, a 13-year-old in fifth
grade, sums up the problem saying, ``It is because of the
sanctions. The enemy countries want to take everything from us
because we were rich.'' (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 15. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Tuesday.
