<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-GRASS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOKEY HIPNESS OF WHEAT GRASS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PENELOPE GREEN  (DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I've got a tiny lawn in my house, as goofy and bright
as a Chia Pet and darn near as useful. I couldn't be happier.
Feeling like Mrs. Dalloway on her errand to pick up flowers, I
brought the thing home with me last week _ a fresh June morning on
10th Street _ a 4-by-7-inch box with sprouted wheat grass, wrapped
in pale blue tissue paper from Spruce on Greenwich Avenue. Spruce
is a flower store with a motto _ ``Our grass is greener!'' _ and it
specializes in witty and ironic items like a pickle jar with
daisies floating in three inches of water and boxes of wheat grass
like mine, which sell for $25 each.
</P>
<P>
   The box of grass is a decorating flourish that seems to make an
appearance every 10 years or so, like Donna Summer. I've been
seeing a lot of potted grass sprouting up, so to speak, lately: on
the tables at Palladin, the restaurant at the new boutique hotel
called Time; in the rooms at the W hotel, complete with a
galvanized metal watering can and a little sign saying ``Water
Me!''; in Asian-inspired department stores like Felissimo and
Takashimaya. These sightings amused and tempted me. Take a trend
home! Why not?
</P>
<P>
   This one's as furry as a shag rug, but I can throw it out if it
gets on my nerves. Perhaps you've seen a box of grass yourself.
Perhaps you've wondered, why wheat grass, why now?
</P>
<P>
   Wheat grass is hokey, and therefore modern. ``I like hokey, and
so I like wheat grass,'' said David Stark, a painter, who with his
partner, Avi Adler, another painter, makes extravagant and mod
floral installations for the best parties these days, like the
Brite Nite shindig at the Whitney Museum in March. ``It's all about
context,'' Stark said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat grass is sort of a signature for these guys, who made
wheat grass candelabras for the New York City Opera (``very Emerald
City,'' Stark said), wheat grass walls for a party for the Greg
Norman clothing collection and steps upholstered in wheat grass
leading into the 69th Regiment Armory for the American fashion
awards two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not using it as a little Zen tribute,'' Stark said. ``I'm
more interested in the maximalism of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat grass is interactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were excited about the W because it seemed like an
opportunity to make progress in what a hotel looked and felt
like,'' said David Rockwell, the architect of the midtown hotel and
creator of other giddy theme places like Planet Hollywood and the
Mohegan Sun casino in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he continued, ``we wanted to move beyond this
impersonal anonymous thing. So the box of grass was something
alive, something you could interact with, i.e. you could water it,
and maybe feel a little bit rejuvenated. There's a Secret Garden
thing going on, and `Water Me,' of course, is sort of Alice in
Wonderland. There are nurturing implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat grass is ironic.
</P>
<P>
   A lawn in a box makes a nice reference to the suburbs or an
idealized childhood, and so is the perfect coffee table fixture for
urban adults. You can display it alongside a new book, ``A Man's
Turf: The Perfect Lawn'' (Clarkson Potter) by Warren Schulz, out
last month. Here's Schulz, a turf specialist, writing about the
sweet smell of mown grass: ``It's the scent of growth, interrupted
by sharp circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   But wheat grass isn't really grass, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Nope, it's just sprouted wheat. It gets leggy and weird and
yellow in about two weeks. ``People think it's like a house plant,
but it's not, it's more like cut flowers,'' said Ken Druse, author
of ``The Collector's Garden'' (Clarkson Potter, 1996). ``You have
to throw it out.''
</P>
<P>
   So who started the trend?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, me?'' Druse suggested. ``I know I put it in a shoot for GQ
in 1979, on a table with some sand. It always amuses me when it
comes around again.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother said: ``The Swedish Ambassador's wife? It was in
Washington, in the early 70s, and she gave a party for some tennis
player, and there were grass centerpieces, with a little net strung
over each one. I was very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   What Swedish ambassador's wife, Mom? ``I don't know. Maybe I
didn't go to the dinner party. Maybe I just heard about it. Ask
Renny.''
</P>
<P>
   Renny Reynolds of New York, who has been making parties fabulous
with his flowers since 1972, said: ``Maybe it was Tony Di Pace. He
was Halston's companion, a brilliant grower, and he was all about
overkill in a pot, like masses of narcissus. Ask Ronaldo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo is Ronaldo Maia, a Madison Avenue florist, who says he
personally has planted wheat grass in boxes with living flowers for
25 years, but he wasn't the first. ``Oh, it would be nice if it
were Tony,'' he said. ``He was a gorgeous person. No longer with
us. A fantastic artist who brought beautiful things to the city.
Mountains of moss, pots of moss! Maybe grass flats. People would
say, `What is this mud on my table?' Life then, it was all
Champagne. Now, it's just Alka-Seltzer.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought the box of grass was a Zona creation, introduced in
those throbbing yuppie years in the mid- to late 80s, when the
lines to get into Zona at Christmas stretched down Greene Street.
Do you remember Zona, one of the first ``life style'' stores, with
its Windham Hill soundtrack and its preciously displayed objects _
Soleri bells and Smith &AMP; Hawken gardening tools and Taos furniture
_ each presented with a tiny printed index card? I can imagine the
little printed card that would have accompanied the wheat grass:
``Remember grass? This is the real thing. Run your fingers through
it. Wiggle your toes in it. Or leave it around the house as a
textural accent.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Sagar, Zona's founder, told me: ``I don't remember what we
wrote, but I was one of the first to show it as something you could
do indoors. It had a few inspirations, like always wishing to have
the grass of suburbia, even though we know it's a trap, and also
the experience of seeing something natural grow and change is a
wonderful thing to bring into the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat grass is still soulful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole first floor is called Dream Ground,'' said Mitria
Digiacomo, vice president of corporate marketing and creative
services at Felissimo, the Asian-themed housewares store on West
56th Street. ``It's a place where you come and contemplate and are
inspired. I wanted grass for that. It's this very natural thing
that's not designed and goes back to our philosophy here of being
an urban oasis.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat grass isn't a look, it's a life style.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its role as table-top lawn, wheat grass is a 70s-era
cure-all _ for cancer, bad breath, gray hair, blood poisoning,
dirty aquariums and more. One-ounce shots of wheat grass juice _
still turning stomachs after all these years _ are sold at most
health food stores and juice bars. I tossed one back recently, at
Karen's on Astor Place. It was acid green and frothy and utterly
disgusting. The juicer man cheered, ``Knock it back, baby, knock it
back!'' and then handed me a chaser of water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
