<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLMEC-SCULPTURES-NYT &LR;      06-11 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLMEC-SCULPTURES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT MESOAMERICAN SCULPTURES MAY BE EARLIEST RENDERINGS OF HUMAN
FETUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico, Central America, Ill., Pa., Texas)   (bl)  
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was it Roe vs. Wade, circa 900 B.C? The breaking of an ancient
taboo or an expression of spiritual transformation? Or some other
yet-to-be-explained convergence of art, science and religion?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, two scholars writing in a bio-medical journal say
they have identified the earliest known naturalistic renderings of
the human fetus, carved by various stone sculptors in Mexico more
than 2,000 years before Leonardo da Vinci made the first anatomical
drawing of the unborn child in the early 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures, from the ancient Olmec civilization, have long
been classified by museums and collectors as dwarfs, dancers,
acrobats and jesters. The Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York,
which displays one of the sculptures cited in the article _ a
10{-inch-high stone statuette with bent knees and hands at the ears
of its large helmeted head _ calls it a ``crouching figure.''
</P>
<P>
   But the authors, citing supporting evidence from obstetricians,
neonatologists and other medical specialists, say the effigies with
their distinctive oversize heads and sharply bent knees portray
fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   If so, they would be extraordinarily rare in the history of art.
Most societies until Leonardo's time shunned depictions of the
unborn, say the article's authors, art historian Carolyn Tate and
cardiologist Gordon Bendersky. They suggest that humans regard
gestating life as ``too sacred for scrutiny'' and may be
uncomfortable contemplating its strange changes in form.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures studied, 21 figures carved between 900 and 600
B.C., are described as individualized portraits showing such finely
rendered prenatal details as incompletely formed ears, swellings
and folds around the eyes, the bony protrusion of the clavicle and
even the translucence of the skin as portrayed by the choice of
stone incised with lines reddened with cinnabar to simulate veins.
They are, moreover, in dynamic poses as they might be in the womb,
arms crossed, or hands to head, or in one case, one hand cocked at
the ear ``as if intently listening.''
</P>
<P>
   The article was published this week in the spring issue of
Perspectives in Biology and Medicine, a quarterly journal of the
Division of Biological Sciences of the University of Chicago.
Editors said it would be posted shortly on the University of
Chicago Press' Web site (www.journals.uchicago. edu).
</P>
<P>
   Bendersky, a cardiologoist at MCP-Hahnemann University School of
Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania and a visiting art
scholar, is an avid art sleuth who has proposed medical solutions
to other art mysteries. In 1977 he identified a 3,000-year-old
Olmec vessel as the earliest known anatomically correct image of
the human heart.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tate, a Mesoamerican specialist at Texas Tech University in
Lubbock, is the author of the book ``Yaxchilan: The Design of a
Maya Ceremonial City'' (University of Texas Press, 1992).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tate first thought that the figures' poses suggested
epileptic seizures and asked Bendersky for an opinion. She also
broached the fetus theory and, after initial skepticism, he
obtained medical opinions that supported her growing conviction
that the sculptures were fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Since the article has just been published, most experts in the
field have not yet read the findings. But Brian Stross, a professor
of anthropology at the University of Texas in Austin, who reviewed
the article before it appeared, said, ``I find it quite credible.''
He said that because of the lack of written records, ``there isn't
going to be any better evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Grieder, another University of Texas specialist in
pre-Colombian art and archaeology who also reviewed the findings,
said: ``I don't know a lot about fetuses but I know about art.'' He
said he had studied the same sculptures himself, had known Ms. Tate
as a graduate student and trusted her conclusions. ``I think she's
right on the button,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Olmecs appeared along the Gulf Coast of what is now Mexico,
Guatemala and Belize about 1200 B.C. and vanished about 400 B.C.,
leaving behind monumental helmeted stone heads with flat eyes and
noses and thickly carved, downturned lips, and glyphs hinting of a
written language.
</P>
<P>
   In their article, Bendersky and Ms. Tate say that some of the
small figures show congenital deformities, including an undersize
jaw or lack of a jaw altogether, conditions called micronathia and
agnathia, or a disproportionate enlargement of the head,
macrocephaly, which may have led to premature birth and death.
While deliberate abortions were performed in Mesoamerica, as in
many other ancient societies worldwide, the Olmec fetuses were most
likely spontaneously aborted, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The feet of the sculptures are uncommonly large, but for
practical reasons of stability rather than symbolic ones, the
authors say.
</P>
<P>
   The Olmecs did produce some images of dwarfs, they write, but
they do not show the same distinctive 1-to-3 or 1-to-4 head-to-body
ratio of the figures identified as fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Excavations at an early Olmec site at El Manati, Veracruz,
Mexico, they say, uncovered the skulls of several newborns or
fetuses, some bearing evidence of cuts suggesting they might have
been sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   Why the veneration of the fetuses? Bendersky and Ms. Tate say
the Olmecs may have known enough about the progression of reptile
forms that a human fetus passes through to relate the process to
the mystical transformation of their shaman, or spiritual leader,
into jaguar and other animal incarnations. In a similar vein, the
authors say, Mesoamerican people related human beings to the maize
plant with its growing cycles and some of the fetus sculptures bear
maize iconography.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tate credited the Olmecs with scientific courage in focusing
on the fetus, probably observed from stillbirths. ``Instead of
saying, `Oooo, this is yucky' and throwing it away,'' she said,
``they studied it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
