<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     06-11 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW TIPS FOR NEWCOMERS TO FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota, Fla., Herald Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newcomers to an area don't always know what they're getting
into, which is why I think the ``Code of the West'' booklet
published by rural Spokane County, Wash., is an especially good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet gives city folk transplanted from California and
other pickup-truck-deprived areas some pointers on living in
Spokane and deals with issues that seldom come up in La-la Land.
</P>
<P>
   For those who might not be aware, the booklet explains that
``unpaved roads generate dust'' and that ``animals and their manure
can cause objectionable odors.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks who have never lived in anything but an apartment or
condominium might also be grateful for this useful tip on lawn
maintenance: ``Without irrigation, grass does not grow very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of people who relocate to Florida every year would
certainly benefit from a similar tip sheet tailored to our area.
Life in Florida takes some getting used to and not everyone is up
to the challenge. Indeed, some people are so traumatized by their
first few weeks in Florida that they become mentally unbalanced and
spend the remainder of their days swatting at invisible bugs and
organizing architectural review committees.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of invisible bugs, newcomers need to be warned
immediately about Florida's abundant insect life. The way things
are now, people don't learn what a palmetto bug is until one gets
them in a sleeper hold, and then it's too late. It might help calm
new residents if we told them that a palmetto bug is the unofficial
state bird rather than a filthy, disgusting insect that resembles a
penny loafer with wings. We should also advise new residents that
the palmetto bug, being the unofficial state bird, is protected by
law and is not to be shot, stabbed or attacked with a
flame-thrower. It doesn't do any good and just makes them mad.
</P>
<P>
   Like newcomers, palmetto bugs are part of the food chain and are
gleefully consumed by Florida's abundant lizards, iguanas, giant
toads, poisonous snakes, killer bees, stinging ants and surly,
disaffected manatees. (Most of these species find newcomers
distasteful and spit them out after a brief but purposeful gumming.
I would not, after all, want this booklet to seem alarmist.)
</P>
<P>
   When a newcomer encounters any creature with which he is not
familiar (that would be most of them), he should avoid making eye
contact or any threatening gestures. Sometimes a wan smile and a
feeble shrug of the shoulders will defuse the situation, but take
care at all times to avoid presenting any part of your body that
you do not wish to be pierced, probed or lacerated by cruel fangs
or bloodsucking mandibles.
</P>
<P>
   While you're outside enjoying Florida's abundant insect life,
you may notice your flesh melting or your hair spontaneously
bursting into flames. This is because Florida is located in the
``semi-tropics,'' meaning that we're like the tropics, only with
more trucks. But don't despair: The hot weather in Florida lasts
only part of the year, usually from early December to late
November. During the rest of the year the tourists are here and you
won't be able to move.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of not moving, you will probably need time to adjust to
Florida's system of roads and highways. Unlike other parts of the
country, Florida's roads were not built for the purpose of
transporting traffic from one point to another. Rather, their
purpose is to provide work for Florida's dedicated
road-construction crews, some of whom have been tearing up and
replacing the same stretch of pavement continuously for more than
50 years.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few of the topics that we could cover for
newcomers in our Florida orientation booklet. I have intentionally
omitted any mention of hurricanes, sinkholes, red tide, alligators
or real-estate developers for fear of scaring everyone off to
Spokane County, which I understand doesn't smell all that good.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
