</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 13, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   EAST-WEST-VALUES-REVIEW (Moscow) _ Americans think their values
are the world's _ and in economics, that often is true. But to some
nations, the Kosovo atrocities were just the broken eggs of yet
another national omelet and the West is a self-righteous, ever-more
meddlesome cook. This anti-West club is not so much motivated by
love for Milosevic as a conviction that bloodlettings like Kosovo
are internal matters; that it's arrogant and foolish to thrust
yourself into someone else's war; that the safe and even humane
course usually is to let the two sides duke it out. By Michael
Wines. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOWERCLASS-PROSPERITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ The U.S. economic boom
is finally starting to trickle down to affect the poorest
Americans, challenging the conventional wisdom that government had
a crucial role in helping the poor. But now there's reason to
wonder if maybe prosperity can do the job alone. Or to put it
another way, how far down the economic ladder can prosperity be
expected to reach? Economists aren't sure, but job statistics give
some interesting clues. By Michael Weinstein. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-SWITCH-REVIEW (Washington) _ With more drugs available and
more prescriptions being written each year, the FDA is concerned
about deaths and injuries caused by medications. Much attention is
given to medication mix-ups and other pharmaceutical errors. But
many people don't realize that pharmacists, at the behest of
insurance companies and HMOs, intentionally switch medications all
the time, with potentially harmful consequences. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-LOSERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Whether they are
well-known faces or ordinary people who run for Congress, losing
candidates find that just because the election is over doesn't mean
the fund-raising stops. But if it was tough raising money in the
heat of a campaign, try fund-raising after Election Day, as the
bills from pollsters, the telephone company and poster makers keep
rolling in. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   JUDAISM-PROSELYTIZE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Unlike Christianity,
Judaism emphatically shuns prosyletizing. But even if many
modern-day rabbis are not so discouraging as all that, what would
happen if they took a really different tack and encouraged
spiritual seekers to embrace Judaism? That idea is gaining
attention _ and some hot criticism. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-APPOINT-REVIEW (Washington) _ President Clinton's recess
appointment of a homosexual as ambassador to Luxembourg has
provoked a clash between two of the most venerable _ and arguably
most anachronistic _ traditions of the federal government. At issue
is the right of the president to make appointments during
congressional recesses without Senate confirmation vs. the right of
individual senators to block any nomination that comes before them.
By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-TITUS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Movie audiences will
see a different side of Shakespeare in the upcoming film version of
`Titus Andronicus.' It is Shakespeare's bloodiest play and, many
critics feel, his worst. Some examples of critical reaction over
the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   WILDE-HUSBAND-REVIEW (Undated) _ A century after the debut of
Oscar Wilde's ``An Ideal Husband,'' the portrait of a successful
politician trying to slip out of humiliation retains a certain
currency, while the portrait of his wife seems like a classy
photograph that has faded from fashion. By Waklter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-MONITORS-REVIEW (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ One of the
founders of the National Movement for Free Elections, or Namfrel,
Jose Concepcion helped end the 20-year rule of Fredinand Marcos and
pioneer a new weapon in the spread of democracy around the world:
independent, citizen-led election-watch groups. He was in Jakarta
last week with a Namfrel delegation keeping an eye on the world's
latest democratic experiment, Indonesia's first free election in 44
years. Also here were scores of men and women from other nations
who are in effect his students. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COMPUTERS-REVIEW (Washington) The U.S. has determined that
the new Sony Playstation II, available later this year, is powered
by a chip so powerful that Washington would have to be notified
before it could be shipped to China. But a Chinese military officer
determined to play out his fantasies on state-of-the-art Sony _
perhaps simulate an attack on Taiwan _ can simply send his kids to
any of the five Toys `R' Us stores in Hong Kong, which is still
considered a safe place to send advanced technology even though it
has reverted to Chinese rule. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TEACH-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ Serbia's leaders have cast the
Kosovo air war as great patriotic trial even as the West has cast
it as a great moral crusade, and so it is reasonable to wonder just
what the next generation of Serbs will be taught about the war,
particularly since the nationalist government remains in power. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: (888) 603-1036  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
