<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CINNABON-12-COX     06-11 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINNABON-12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cinnabon Bakeries expanding overseas
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cinnabon Bakeries is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based cinnamon roll retailer Friday announced
several major international and domestic deals that will
significantly broaden its market.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the company has signed agreements for 134 new units in
Asia, the Middle East and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabon, which is owned by Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises, will
make its entry into the Asian market in a franchise deal to open 42
bakeries in Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   William Van Epps, president of AFC's international division,
called the Asian deal the first of many. He said more deals could
be announced over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia, even with the recent economic problems, is starting to
turn around and a lot of companies are looking now at expansion for
the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cinnabon also has reached a franchise agreement with Mohammed
Qusai Assad &AMP; Sons for an 42 units in the Middle East, which
includes 25 units in Egypt, 12 in Kuwait and five in Jordan. The
bakeries will be opened during a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the United States, Cinnabon and Host Marriott Services
extended their current partnership with plans to open 50 sites over
the next eight years. The partnership has units in various airports
and travel plazas, which contain gas stations and food courts.
</P>
<P>
   Franchising is a major growth vehicle for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Under its previous owners, Cinnabon had suspended its
franchising efforts, but they were revived when it was acquired by
AFC last October.
</P>
<P>
   Van Epps said the international markets have a lot of potential
for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international arena will probably double or triple that of
the domestic market in the foreseeable future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Cinnabon has 16 bakeries outside the United States.
Those are located in Canada, Saudi Arabia and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, over the years they have had a good reputation and
apparently with the right controls in place, AFC felt this was the
proper time to step up their expansion,'' said Bill Carlino,
managing editor of Nation's Restaurant News, a New York-based trade
publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``To expand you obviously need capital and AFC certainly has
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlino said it's hard for U.S. food concepts to go wrong
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the international consumer has always had a kind
of fascination with American concepts,'' he said. ``There have been
a lot of companies that have had good success in overseas
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabon has 375 bakeries in 39 states. Systemwide sales in 1998
were $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   AFC also owns Churchs Chicken, Popeyes Chicken &AMP; Biscuits,
Seattle's Best Coffee, Torrefazione Italia Coffee and Chesapeake
Bagel Bakery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
