<SLUG> BC-COKE-ASIA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola acquires Asian bottling operations
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. said it will acquire the Asian bottling
operations of Fraser and Neave Ltd. of Singapore in a $271 million
equity deal.
</P>
<P>
   The move is unusual for the Atlanta-based beverage company,
which seldom acquires a controlling stake in bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola said Friday that buying the F&AMP;N Coca-Cola Pte Ltd
subsidiary reflects its belief that emerging markets in the region
offer an opportunity to put its drinks in the hands of 260 million
more consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola currently owns 25 percent of F&AMP;N Coca-Cola, which has
bottling operations in Brunei, Cambodia, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri
Lanka, Singapore and Vietnam. The company also has operations in
Malaysia, but those are not part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of Coca-Cola's business in Asia has slowed over the
last year because of economic problems that have made consumers
less eager, and able, to buy its products. For the first quarter of
1999, Coca-Cola estimated its unit case volume, a way of measuring
beverage consumption, dropped 1 to 2 percent, compared with an
increase of 11 percent in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser and Neave, which has interests in dairy products,
breweries and commercial real estate, also has lost money trying to
quench thirsts in the region. The company reported Friday that it
lost $48 million in Singapore dollars ($28 million in U.S.) in the
six months ended March 31 on its beverage operations. Soft drink
sales were down in Indochina, Singapore, Malaysia and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulty in growing the business, Coca-Cola has
said that owning a majority stake in a bottler allows it to better
control sales and marketing programs, and strengthen business and
information systems. It also allows the company to put capital
where it's needed to build a bottler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our confidence in the long-term growth prospects in this
region of the world is strong,'' said Douglas N. Daft, president of
the company's Middle and Far East Group. ``We are fully committed
to having the right capital and management structure in place to
capture profitable growth over the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Caroline Levy at Schroder &AMP; Co. told Bloomberg News that
Coca-Cola is getting the F&AMP;N bottling operations at ``a very good
price.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for its controlling stake in F&AMP;N Coca-Cola, Fraser
and Neave will gain the Atlanta company's 5.6 percent stake in the
Australian anchor bottler Coca-Cola Amatil. As an anchor, Amatil is
one of Coke system's largest bottlers, and the stake is valued at
$271 million. After the deal, Coca-Cola's stake in Amatil will drop
to 37 percent, from 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction comes on the heels of a failed attempt by
Coca-Cola to salvage a deal with Cadbury-Schweppes to acquire that
London-based beverage maker's operations in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite revising their original agreement, Coca-Cola failed to
convince Australian antitrust regulators that it would not end up
having too much control of the local soft drink market.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the revision called for Amatil to handle the production,
sale and distribution of Cadbury's products, but Amatil would sell
some of its second-tier products to Cadbury.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Coca-Cola's stock lost 2 percent of its value
Friday, closing at $64.44, down $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
