<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHNOBUDDY: Remember MP3 _ it's a pioneer
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year or so before Apple introduced its palm-sized Newton you
were told that almost everyone would want to own one of those
little gadgets that let you write on the screen instead of type on
a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make a person go out and buy stock in Apple.
Those who did were soon sorry.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton is literally history. It had a few flaws: Most
notable was the fact that its handwriting recognition technology
didn't work any more often than your laziest uncle.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when it seems I work in the hysteria industry
covering a world that changes too fast to follow. When an arguably
important technology comes along, the press is tempted to scream
loud and fast rather than take the chance of missing something.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that we were wrong about the Newton, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   It truly did make history. It was a pioneer, the first breeze
that told us a storm was coming. The news wasn't that Newton was
the product of the century. Instead it was tangible proof that
smart people at a big technology company were trying to satisfy the
public desire for computing on the go.
</P>
<P>
   The itch was a real one and you won't have to look hard today to
find the successor to the Newton. Sooner or later, a company really
did make palm-sized computing practical and nowadays the Palm Pilot
scatches that itch nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Smart people at big companies are making the same sort of bets
on a technology called MP3 right now. MP3 is being touted as a
technology that will replace CDs as the way you buy music. Instead
of dropping in at the music store, you'll download your music from
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it, or against it. Instead, learn from the history
of technology. You'll find dozens of pioneering products that were
important as predictors of a basic change. In many cases, the
products fell by the wayside ... that's always been the risk that
pioneers take.
</P>
<P>
   Odds are that you don't know Mosiac from monosodium glutamate.
It was one of the earliest computer programs used to browse the
Internet's World Wide Web, introduced back in the days before most
of you knew or cared what the Web was.
</P>
<P>
   It got rave reviews and _ unlike the Newton _ it actually
worked. But nowadays Microsoft and Netscape own the market for
browsers. Mosiac's place was as a pioneer. Just as the Conastoga
wagons paved the way for Interstate highways to the West, Mosiac
made it possible for you to show off your kids on your own personal
Web page. It wasn't the wagon that ended up being a big deal, the
important thing was in opening up a way to move West.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes we forget that when working in the hysteria
industry. When a Newton or a Mosiac comes along, the temptation _
both in the public and in the press _ is to focus on the product
itself and not on the need that it was created to fill. Important
products _ and Newton and Mosiac fit that definition _ are created
to solve a problem.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about MP3 _ a technology with a name so unwieldly
that we must call it by its initials instead of Motion Picture
Coding Experts Group-1, audio layer-3 _ it would be a mistake to
focus on today's technology or even on MP3.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 may end up being the best thing since sliced bread. But, it
is not that yet. Try this experiment, even now after it has been
written about extensively. Stand in the mall and ask the next 10
people what MP3 is. My guess is that two of them will think it's a
new Army tank and at least one person thinks you're trying to get
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Then take another survey, this time among your friends who have
a computer and access to the Internet. Ask them if they regularly
download files _ and that's what you must do if people are to make
money peddling music on the Net using MP3.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 may some day represent a technology as simple and as
all-pervasive as the telephone. But _ other than to the companies
that are betting big bucks on it _ that's almost immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   What is important is that the wind is blowing again. Now that
we've sampled how easy it is to order merchandise using the
Internet, there is a growing desire to be pampered even more. We
want the Net to deliver that merchandise ... in this case music.
And, by MP3 or some technology that you've never heard of, it will
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted covers technology issues for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
