<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORM12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    System administrators battle Explorer worm
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thursday morning, an e-mail landed in Brent Fowler's
in-box at Socket Public Relations in suburban Tucker, Ga. The
e-mail was from one of Socket's clients, a technology firm in
Raleigh. Normal stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler clicked to open the note, then clicked to open the
attached document files.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the attached file, which contained a software
infection called a worm, entered Fowler's address book and sent
copies of itself to everyone in it. It might also have erased the
files on his hard drive. The same scenario played out on the PC of
every recipient of Fowler's e-mail: co-workers, clients, friends,
family.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, the 30-PC system at Socket was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday they were back up and running. But Peter Baron, Socket
principal, estimates the lost time and data will cost his firm
about $10,000; $5,000 per click.
</P>
<P>
   ``It slammed us pretty good,'' Baron said. ``This is the most
wicked one I've seen. And I think it's going to get worse now that
they've figured out the social aspect to make it seem like it came
from friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Worm.Explore.Zip bug, the third major computer infection in
three months, hit sometime this week but landed in e-mail in-boxes
in full force Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was socially engineered in a sense, designed to
address itself to its recipients in a friendly fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi (recipient name)'' the initial message reads, ``I received
your e-mail and I shall send you a reply ASAP. Till then, take a
look at the attached zipped docs.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is harmless unless a person opens the ``zipped
docs,'' a term referring to a compressed file sent with the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   By opening that file, a person unknowingly activates the bug.
</P>
<P>
   The virus attacked computers at Compaq Computer, Motorola, AT&AMP;T,
Boeing, General Electric and Southern Co. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The messages contain an attached file that, when opened,
releases a software program that can destroy any files created by
Microsoft programs, including spreadsheets, documents and
presentations. The bug is only known to hit PCs running Microsoft
operating systems, including Windows 95 and Windows 98 and Windows
NT.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Melissa and Chernobyl viruses this year, computer
systems administrators were able to react more quickly to the worm,
possibly reducing the extent of the damage, said IBM's Dave Chess.
</P>
<P>
   He said for the short-term, computer owners should avoid opening
any e-mail that bears an attachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a file attached to an e-mail, don't open it, even
if it appears to be from someone you know,'' said Chess, a member
of IBM's anti-virus research team in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get one, call the person who sent it and ask if they
meant to. If they did, you're probably OK,'' he said. ``That's
probably the hardest thing to understand. It's tough to realize how
insidious e-mail can be. ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
