u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0612-     06-11 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS REFUGEES GROW ANXIOUS TO RETURN, PERILS OF KOSOVO STILL CLEAR
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0612.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ Beyond the turquoise waters of the White Drin
River and over a grassy ridge that obscured their source, two
plumes of white smoke towered above the Kosovo side of this border
crossing Friday and served as a warning that the province is still
not safe.
</P>
<P>
   For the third day in a row since the signing of the peace deal
requiring withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo, no refugees
crossed into Albania from the province.
</P>
<P>
   But none had tried to return, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one dares to go in there until the Serb military and police
withdraw,'' said an Albanian policeman, giving his name only as
Teki, as he lounged with a machine-gun on a hill near the border.
He speculated that the smoke was from Serbs burning homes, as they
have done throughout Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the nearly half a million ethnic Albanian refugees in
Albania waited to learn when they can go home, reasons seemed to
multiply for why returning might be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Aid groups spoke of the land mines, booby traps and unexploded
ordnance suspected on the other side. United Nations workers
worried that there could be an uncontrollable crush of refugees if
they begin coming from camps far away in central and southern
Albania. And, officials with the pro-independence Kosovo Liberation
Army warned of Serb forces just inside Kosovo who have yet to begin
withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   They are not required to leave the area near Albania for another
few days and the KLA claimed that the Serbs were still engaged in
the kind of activity that drove nearly 800,000 ethnic Albanians
from Kosovo to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have observed a few units withdrawing but not the big ones.
On their way withdrawing, they have been looting and burning
houses,'' said KLA representative Kadri Kryeziu (cq).
</P>
<P>
   The KLA says its forces are frozen in position and will not try
to pursue the Serbs during their withdrawal. But, the group's
leaders say their fighters will attack if they see Serbs looting
homes.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs Friday of the shaky security situation in
Kosovo. The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
reported that two northern Albanian towns, Pogaj and Qafa Prushit,
came under light shelling from Serb troops Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees, eager to go back to their land if only to find the
charred rubble of their homes, seemed to understand the risks of
return but not the time it will take for peacekeeping forces to
secure Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vjollcas Nebiu(cq), a 17-year-old refugee living in the back of
a flat-bed truck with 15 relatives, said she is worried about land
mines but, ``just a week would be enough for NATO to go in and then
tell us that it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials say it will take months, likely into next summer,
until all the refugees can return. About half the homes in Kosovo
are estimated to be damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about security in Kosovo will start being answered as
early as Saturday, when the first NATO troops may enter southern
Kosovo from Macedonia. On Sunday or Monday, more than 2,000 German
troops will lead a convoy that includes aid workers and journalists
into southwestern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Seven mine removal teams are being imported from abroad and the
United Nations is expected to send several hundred aid workers into
the province in the beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
