<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-WINSTAR-$ADV13     06-11 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WINSTAR-$ADV13-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALS FOCUS ATTENTION ON WINSTAR COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 13)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHELLE LEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, the world seems smitten by the prospects of
fixed-wireless technology _ the fast-growing industry niche that
links users to high-speed telecommunications networks through
disk-shaped antennae instead of expensive fiber optic or T-1 lines.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, Liberty Media Group _ the AT&AMP;T affiliate controlled
by John Malone _ signed a deal worth around $3 billion that will
give it, among other things, a 41 percent position in Teligent
Inc., a fixed-wireless provider based in Vienna, Va. The same day,
Qwest Communications International, a long-distance provider, said
it and other investors planned to pay $251 million for a 48 percent
stake in Advanced Radio Telecom of Bellevue, Wash., another
fixed-wireless concern.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals have focused increased attention on Winstar
Communications of New York, the nation's largest fixed-wireless
company, operating in 33 markets.
</P>
<P>
   Winstar's shares have climbed 38.8 percent this year, to $54.125
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The question for prospective investors is whether to buy the
recently marked-up shares of Winstar or to wait, and possibly miss
a further climb, especially given that Winstar is often rumored to
be in the sights of an acquirer. (A spokesman for Winstar declined
to comment on a possible acquisition.)
</P>
<P>
   Winstar, which is spending heavily to build its network, has
posted losses since 1993, when it went public. Last year, it lost
$444.7 million, or $11.96 a share, on sales of $244.4 million. But
it has told analysts that it expects earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization to be positive by the first
quarter of 2001 and that it will turn a profit by year-end 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem like a long time. But the payoff could be big: The
fixed-wireless industry, which had sales of $103 million in 1998,
should grow to $8.5 billion in 2007, according to Pioneer
Consulting of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   John Hodulik, an analyst at Paine Webber, agrees that the market
for these services is just beginning to take off. ``The real value
is going to emerge over the next 12 to 24 months,'' Hodulik said.
</P>
<P>
   By at least one measure, Winstar is cheap. Hodulik puts its
enterprise value, the amount that an acquirer could be expected to
pay for the company, at $5.6 billion, versus $4.3 billion for
Teligent, Winstar's major rival. Yet Winstar's market
capitalization is $2.6 billion, while Teligent's is $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts are concerned about Winstar's ability to keep
pace. ``There are a lot of execution risks if the business doesn't
grow as aggressively as planned,'' said David Heger of A.G. Edwards
in St. Louis, who thinks Winstar will not post a profit until 2004.
In April, Heger downgraded the stock from ``buy'' to
``accumulate.'' He has a 12-month target of $64 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Also of concern to some analysts is Winstar's heavy debt load _
$1.44 billion at the end of 1998, up from $789.8 million at the end
of 1997 _ much of it spent on building the network. To help defray
costs, Winstar has signed several partners, including Lucent
Technologies, which agreed in October to provide up to $2 billion
in financing over five years for purchases of Lucent equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Winstar's recent run-up has encouraged short-sellers. In May,
there were 9.78 million open short positions, equal to about
one-fifth of the shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerald Unterman, president of GEM Capital Management, a New
York money manager that is a large holder of Winstar stock, said
the short-sellers were being taught a lesson as Winstar's stock
continued to rise. He thinks it will hit $150 a share in three
years. ``This company's just beginning to come into its own,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
