<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCOM-BRITAIN12-COX     06-11 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCOM-BRITAIN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. selling British concern
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co. is selling off a large chunk of its
British electric power distributor just as the country's utility
industry becomes competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Southern announced Friday the sale of the supply business of
South Western Electricity (Sweb) to London Electricity, a
French-owned power distributor, for $256 million. The proceeds will
be split with Southern's partner in Sweb, the Pennsylvania-based
utility PP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale is completed, which is expected within six months,
Southern will be left as operator of a distribution system that
carries electricity to Sweb's 1.4 million customers in southwestern
England. London Electricity takes over the newly competitive supply
and marketing of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Southern was first in a wave of U.S. utilities to move into
Britain's power sector when it acquired Sweb in 1995 for $1.8
billion. Regulators blocked Southern's attempt a few months later
to take over National Power, a leading British power generator.
</P>
<P>
   Southern has since sold off 51 percent of Sweb to PP&AMP;L for $359
million but retains operational control.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bowers, a Southern executive assigned to Sweb as chief
executive, said Southern was approached in recent months by several
suitors interested in acquiring all of Sweb, but decided to retain
the distribution business.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's utility industry, which became fully open to
competition last month, is seeing a new wave of mergers and
acquisitions. That included New Orleans-based Entergy Corp.'s sale
of London Electricity to Electricitie de France for $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweb has found its role in the deregulated U.K. market, and
that role is one of a distributor,'' said Rick Pershing, executive
vice president of Southern Energy Inc., Southern's international
subsidiary. ``It's inevitable that the U.K. market will see
consolidation of energy suppliers, and it made more sense to sell
our supply business now than try to grow it to the size suppliers
will need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bowers, Southern retains 900 of Sweb's 1,700
employees and most of the utility's revenues. The supply business
accounts for $19 million in annual net income, while the
distribution end brings in $64 million, which Southern splits with
PP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said London Electricity plans to fold its supply business
into the Sweb operation, creating a base of 4 million customers
that will make it a national player. Because of its French
ownership, the company can receive power from an underground cable
from France.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
