<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMASTON-MILLS12-COX     06-11 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMASTON-MILLS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thomaston Mills announces layoffs
 &HT;    (Attn: New York, Los Angeles)
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of Georgia's few remaining family-controlled
textile manufacturers plans to discharge 700 employees and close
two divisions by fall. The move by 100-year-old Thomaston Mills of
Thomaston comes on the heels of several unprofitable quarters,
suspended dividends and an expected loss for the fiscal year that
will end this month.
</P>
<P>
   The downsizing represents one company's effort to overcome the
effects of too much denim and yarn in the American market and too
little export potential. Thomaston will cease production of denim,
industrial fabrics such as beltings, and yarns manufactured for
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is going through a difficult period, and yarn and
denim segments have been hard hit,'' said Neil H. Hightower Sr.,
president and chief executive officer. The Asian export market
dried up at the same time a spate of imported fabrics and yarns
created an oversupply, causing prices to drop.
</P>
<P>
   The downsizing, which will start in September, will shrink
Thomaston's 2,350-person work force by 30 percent. The company's
denim plant in Zebulon, Ga., which employs 145 people, will be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   This is the facility where Thomaston invested heavily earlier in
the decade in the hope that the then-vibrant market for
American-made denim would grow.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the remaining 555 jobs will come from Thomaston
operations and sales offices in New York and Los Angeles, Hightower
said.
</P>
<P>
   What will remain will be the new core businesses of dyed khaki
and twill fabrics, plus beddings and comforters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be highly automated and very competitive, aimed at
expanding the comforter business and the piece-dyed apparel
business,'' Hightower said, while adding that sales for the year
ending June 2000 will probably be down again.
</P>
<P>
   Since reaching $19 a share in 1994, Thomaston Mills' stock has
been on a downward trend. After trading was briefly halted Friday,
shares closed at $2.75, down 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
