A2306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-NYT     06-11 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB FIGHTER PLANES SURVIVE NATO ONSLAUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO had few more important targets during its air
strikes against Yugoslavia than the airfield at Pristina, the
capital of Kosovo, which was pounded by tons of NATO bombs meant to
destroy the Yugoslav MIG fighters and other deadly hardware based
there.
</P>
<P>
   So how did at least 11 MiG-21 fighters at the base manage to
survive, not only intact but ready to fly? The Pentagon released
aerial surveillance photographs showing the fighters taking off
from Pristina on Friday and flying to safety in Serbia. They had
been stored in a hillside bunker near the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a hardened bunker,'' said Maj. Gen. Charles Wald
of the Air Force, explaining why the jets had survived the nightly
assaults. ``It's actually dug into the side of a mountain that
obviously is made out of granite or something.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesmen said that both ends of the bunker were hit by
bombs or missiles during the air campaign. But Wald suggested that
NATO had held back from using its largest ``bunker-busting'' bombs
against the hillside bunker for fear that it might damage the
runway, which NATO hoped to use eventually to help Albanian
refugees return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This runway has never been struck; we wanted to keep that open
for KFOR, when they went in,'' he said, referring to the
international security force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      06-11 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID SHUNS LAWLESS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAJRAM CURRI, Albania _ Imagine sticking thousands of sick
people, feeble elderly, and children in the middle of the OK Corral
at high noon _ with two feuding and heavily armed cowboys at either
end of the town.
</P>
<P>
   This is the situation in the lawless, northern Albanian mountain
town of Bajram Curri, where the risk of getting shot or robbed is
so high that no humanitarian aid organization, save one, has the
courage to go there to feed the 3,200 Kosovar Albanian refugees who
are virtually imprisoned by the local banditry.
</P>
<P>
   No one goes out at night, when the only sounds from the street
are a cacophony of gunfire and barking dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Shootings? ``Ah, a couple last night, but that's just like
having coffee in Brussels,'' shrugged an international observer
stationed here for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, a human rights monitoring agency.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as Serb shells fell on Bajram Curri, two Albanians
in a car clearly marked as an OSCE vehicle were shot dead, and one
was injured, as they drove out of town.
</P>
<P>
   No one bothers calling the police. The nephew of the police
chief, regional aid workers say, is head of one of the local gangs.
Many journalists have been robbed by masked bandits, and at least
one news organization was the victim of a carjacking despite having
two local police bodyguards with them.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to deliver food to the refugees, police who
were escorting workers for Concern, an Irish aid organization,
refused to go beyond a certain point in the road, saying they were
too scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police don't do anything. They'd get killed'' if they
intervened, said Langis Langois, one of seven OSCE staff in the
town. ``And they won't get killed for $200 a month,'' the average
salary here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE has agreed to distribute food if anyone can get it to
Bajram Curri _ a task only Concern has undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get nervous, apprehensive. But you get used to'' the
danger, said Michael Hilton, Concern's project coordinator, who
with his colleague, David Fraser, recently went on an aid run to
Bajram Curri.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law here, no order, no civil justice system. There
is only the Code of Lek, an old common law observed in northern
Albania. The code is clear: If someone is slain, the victim's
family must murder a member of the killer's family.
</P>
<P>
   The brutality is typical of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have a reputation for ``ethnic cleansing,'' the forced
expulsion or killing of an ethnic group, but the northern Albanians
have blood feuds that can go on for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees staying in Bajram Curri have been battered by both
worlds: In Kosovo, they were burned out of their homes and forced
over the border; in Bajram Curri, feuds and bandit violence keep
them huddled inside collection centers and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come out only to get some bread,'' said Raz Shabani, 73.
``I'm an old woman, and the strong ones are taking the food.
There's not enough for the refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   A 17-year-old boy also hoping to get a first crack at the aid
delivery agreed. ``There's no security here,'' Shemsedim Sutaj
said. ``We are afraid to go out even during the day,'' and so they
rely heavily on Concern's twice-monthly deliveries of flour, sugar,
beans, milk, and peas.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is getting especially dire, said OSCE staff member
Gaston Back, because of several cases of tuberculosis in one of the
collection centers _ illness that threatens to spread quickly.
Still, many refugees are afraid to move, or reluctant to venture
further from the border, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to deliver food in the midst of a Hatfields-and-McCoys
environment is a dicey proposition for Concern and for the OSCE
staff, who have volunteered to help with distribution. The
organizations normally directed to hand out food _ such as the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees _ pulled out of
Bajram Curri last year because of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Wild West,'' Back said. He gestured toward the main
street in town. ``See that white car? That's ours.'' It was stolen
last year, he said. ``There's nothing we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern workers expressed surprise to see vans and
four-wheel-drive vehicles carrying the logos of other aid agencies
cruising around town. Then they realized that the vehicles had been
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   To get along in this hellish environment, international aid
organizations have to make deals with the devil.
</P>
<P>
   The town is basically run by two clans, and much of the violence
is between the two, aid workers in Albania said.
</P>
<P>
   OSCE is ``protected by (one of) the big families,'' Back said.
``They know that if OSCE gets out, they have a big problem. They'd
have to feed 3,200 mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern workers calculate their risk very carefully. They take
only old aid trucks and bring little money, no satellite phones, no
computers, and no radios.
</P>
<P>
   They arrange for an armed escort along the winding border road,
and travel only by daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there are refugees there, we will keep bringing
food,'' Fraser said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
