<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POGO12-COX     06-11 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POGO12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WASTE GROUP UNDER FIRE FOR AWARD TO GOVERNMENT LAWYER
 &HT;    640&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH and JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of laboring with low budgets and little
recognition, a small organization of government waste-chasers is
suddenly wealthy _ and under fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Project on Government Oversight (POGO), was the chief
plaintiff in a lawsuit that forced Mobil Oil Co. to pay nearly $40
million last year for allegedly defrauding the federal government
out of royalties on oil pumped from public land.
</P>
<P>
   For bringing the matter to light, POGO received $1.2 million as
part of the court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But the organization's decision to share $350,000 of its reward
with a federal government whistle-blower and another $350,000 with
a retired federal employee is now under investigation by a House
committee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Justice Department's Criminal Division has
opened a preliminary investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The House Resources Committee last week approved a request by
its chairman, Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, for authority to subpoena
records from POGO and the two ``grant'' recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should a federal employee be able to take that amount of
money related
</P>
<P>
   to things that they worked on?'' said Duane Gibson, an
investigator for the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were another organization making the payment, people
would be
</P>
<P>
   incensed,'' he said. ``Well, we're incensed that this
organization made that
</P>
<P>
   payment.''
</P>
<P>
   A POGO spokeswoman said the organization was ``very proud'' that
it shared its proceeds from the settlements with Interior
Department economist Robert Berman and retired Energy Department
employee Robert Speir. The two men had for years worked
unsuccessfully to get the oil company royalty payments increased,
said Beth Daley.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that POGO had not made the grants public,
adding that ``in hindsight,'' that was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Young, likening the grants to ``government-by-auction at the
Department of the Interior or the Department of Energy,'' said the
committee had a responsibility to ``understand how such payments
were allowed to be made and how they affected our legislative
proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Young and other oil state lawmakers have blocked rules that
would close loopholes that groups like POGO say allowed the
companies to shirk paying the full royalty obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, although Mobil has settled its suit, billions of
dollars are riding on similar POGO suits against other oil
companies. A lawyer who represents some of those companies says he
thinks POGO, Spier and Berman may have violated criminal laws with
the $350,000 payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``A federal employee cannot serve two masters,'' said the
lawyer, Poe Leggette. ``These two employees were either working for
the public or working for POGO. If they were working for the
public, then it was clearly improper for POGO to pay them a
so-called 'award.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Leggette represents Phillips Petroleum Corp., Comoco Inc., Shell
Oil Co. and other defendants in the fraud suits brought by POGO. He
also is a former lawyer at the Interior Department _ where he
helped write the regulations that led to the allegedly fraudulent
company conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing about his activities violates government ethics
regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Tabackman, Berman's lawyer, said neither he nor his
client believes there was anything wrong with Berman accepting the
POGO money.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Berman has no authority or influence over any
change in government regulations sought by POGO and has not
promised to do anything in return for the money.
</P>
<P>
   He compared the grants to monetary awards such as Nobel prizes
that are sometimes won by government officials for their work.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations allow government employees to accept awards
in excess of $200 ``upon a written determination by an agency
ethics official that the award is made as part of an established
program of recognition.'' No such determination was issued.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Tabackman said Berman has been writing memos at the Interior
Department since 1986 objecting to a formula under which oil and
gas companies that drill on government lands or offshore waters
were being allowed to pay only a fraction of the royalties he
believed they owed.
</P>
<P>
   The memos did not result in any changes, Tabackman said.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1995, POGO issued a report in which it said that some of
the largest oil companies in the world _ companies such as Mobil,
Shell, Exxon and Texaco _ were using accounting tricks and
subsidiaries to understate the amount they owned the government.
</P>
<P>
   Still there was no change.
</P>
<P>
   Then POGO filed a series of lawsuits under the False Claims Act,
a law that permits private organizations and individuals to sue in
behalf of the government and to share in the proceeds if the legal
action succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil was one the defendants in one of POGO's suits, Daly said.
Additional suits, claiming the government has been defrauded of
more than $5 billion in royalties, are pending against 16 other
companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Six other public interest groups wrote to Young this week,
charging that the POGO investigation is ``simply intended to divert
attention from the real issue _ that major oil companies have
underpaid royalties owed the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who are lining up against POGO are also among the
largest recipients of campaign donations from the oil and gas
industry, according to a study by the Center for Responsive
Politics. Young received more than $118,000 in donations from that
industry for his last re-election campaign. Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., who has also joined in criticizing POGO, collected
$306,000 from oil and gas interests for his 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, Young's aide denied that oil companies were playing a
role in the House committee investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one from big oil came in here and asked us to do this,''
Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merely because there's campaign donations by certain PACs,
that doesn't mean there's influence. This is not about oil. This is
about true and proper decisions that have not been influenced by
outside groups.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
