<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LONGBALL12-COX     06-11 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LONGBALL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves pitchers battle for long-ball title
 &HT;    (Eds: Note time reference in 4th graf.)
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The commercial is hilarious, the Cy Young of TV spots,
and yet it cries out for a revised ending. Yes, Greg Maddux and Tom
Glavine still would belt batting practice bullets. Heather Locklear
still would approach the cage and come-hitherly coo, ``Hi, Tom.''
Maddux would bash forearms with Glavine and declare, ``Chicks dig
the long ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the remake, Heather then would ask, ''Hey, have you guys
seen Smoltzie?''
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't happen, right? Maddux and Glavine are Nike guys. John
Smoltz wears Reeboks. Big deal. As Braves pitching coach Leo
Mazzone knows, ``If John stays at this pace, he could have a
commercial all by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   If chicks do dig the long ball, dig this: Here it is, mid-June,
and Smoltz, who pitches tonight against Baltimore, is hitting an
even .400. Not since 1941, when Ted Williams finished at .406, has
a big-leaguer hit .400. It has been 19 years since George Brett's
.390 flirtation in 1980, five years since Tony Gwynn's
strike-shortened bid ended at .394 in '94. Yet in the last season
of the '90s, baseball holds its breath and wonders, ``Can Smoltzie
do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go out on a limb,'' Glavine dead-panned, ``and say he's
not going to hit .400.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What else do you want to talk about?'' Maddux asked, feeling
bigger. ``Me having twice as many homers as Smoltzie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the season's going to go on and I'm going to have about
80 at-bats,'' Smoltz said resignedly, ``I won't hit .400.''
</P>
<P>
   Even by their lofty standards, these are heady hitting times for
Smoltz, Maddux and Glavine. Baseball's winningest pitchers of the
'90s are also its hittingest pitchers. Yes, Glavine, who last year
won his fourth Silver Slugger as the NL's top-hitting pitcher, has
staggered out of the gate this season. A single Wednesday was just
his third hit of the year, but it improved his average to .120 (3
for 25). In the good-natured, highly competitive batting race among
the three Cy Young winners, Glavine has miles to go before he
sweeps past them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glavine's still the reigning king, the defending champion,''
Mazzone cautioned. ``Don't count Glav out yet. He's always laying
in the weeds. Glav sneaks up on everybody in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, yes. But how to explain his .083 start before
Wednesday's 1-for-2 eruption? ``You know, we play a lot of golf,
and John always gives me strokes in golf,'' Glavine said. ``So I
figured I'd handicap this and let John get off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, there's a lot of carryover from the commercial. I think
I'm going out there trying to hit the ball out.'' This from a guy
with one career dinger. ``I'm going back to the old way, go
inside-out and hit to left field.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Maddux, a lifetime .178 hitter before this season
with two career homers _ none since joining the Braves in '93. But
in his first start on April 6, Maddux took Chad Ogea deep to left
field for his first homer in seven years. Estimated distance: 380
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a good wind,'' Maddux said, ``and the ball carries
and the barometric pressure is just right, yeah, I can go about
380.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the afternoon of May 30, though, that truly astounded.
Maddux reached out and homered to right off _ Kevin Brown?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the first time I ever got a hit off him,''
Maddux said. ``You just want to put it in play. I'm hoping, 'Maybe
I can just get a grounder that won't go at anybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Long ball. His second in less than two months, after two
in 12 seasons. ``I'm in a tree,'' explained Maddux. A tree? ``In
over my head. I'm like the guy who won playing Lotto. You've got to
be in a tree, over your head, to win Lotto.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, then Smoltz has won the Big Game. A Silver Slugger winner
in '97 with 18 hits and a .228 average, he is 10 for 25 this
season, with three doubles, six RBIs and his fifth career homer.
That three-run, opposite-field blast on Monday overshadowed
Smoltz's 2,000th career strikeout an inning earlier and rallied the
Braves from a 3-0 deficit to a 9-5 victory. And it came after
Smoltz heard a familiar mantra in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all you hear when you're at the plate: 'Chicks dig the
long ball,''' Smoltz said.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Maddux, like Glavine, takes partial credit for
Smoltz's success. ``I think the commercial fired him up,'' Maddux
said. ``I think it gave him the extra push he's needed. If you can
find ways to motivate yourself to be a little better, you do it. I
think it gave Smoltzie that little extra push to lock in up there:
'No way somebody from Vegas hits higher than somebody from
Michigan.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough that he has to live with me being a better
golfer than him. It would crush him if I was a better hitter,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add below.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad Dog's showing more power this year,'' Mazzone said. ``But
Smoltzie's showing more power and base-hit ability. The ball's
exploding off his bat.'' Pause. ``Of course, the ball's exploding
off everybody's bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Juiced-up ball notwithstanding, what in the names of Hillerich &AMP;
Bradsby is going on here? Is Smoltz using a titanium-shaft
Louisville Slugger? ``Everyone else's bat but my own,'' he said.
``I haven't gotten the greatest lumber. Bats to me are like
putters: Whatever feels good, looks good, works for that moment.
When it runs out, it's time to change.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Smoltz used Kevin Millwood's bat _ the longest and
heaviest of the pitchers' bats _ to smack his homer and then a
single. In his previous start, his first since coming off the
disabled list, Smoltz used Glavine's bat _ the lightest among the
pitchers' bats, with the most barrel _ to drill a double, and then
he used Maddux's for a single.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not just good wood. It's also a swing thing,
Daddy-O, that differentiates the hitting pitchers. ``My swing's
limited in a lot of ways but produces a lot more power than
Maddux's ever could,'' Smoltz said. ``He pretty much gets ugly
hacks, ugly hits. Glav's more of a (Punch and) Judy hitter with a
good swing. If I had to pick somebody from among the three of us to
not strike out and put it in play, it'd be Glav. The luckiest
hitter would be Maddux.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, dude,'' Maddux said. ``Gotta be Millwood.''
</P>
<P>
   The most dangerous, at the moment, is Smoltz, who recalls his
even better start in '97. ``I think I got as high as .450,'' he
said. ''But then I went 1 for my last 22, hit .228. Fortunately,
they voted (for the Silver Slugger) before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit in eight straight games I pitched in, which I equate to
a 40-game hitting streak: Eight games times five (days for each
pitching start) equals 40,'' Smoltz said, smiling. ``So I figure I
was pushing DiMaggio's hitting streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's pushing the .400 envelope _ in mid-June. ``It's all
about matchups,'' Smoltz said. For example, Maddux attributes
Glavine's hitting slump to pitching at the top of the rotation and
batting against the opposing No. 1 starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certain things I don't want to give away that I can't
do,'' Smoltz said. ``I try to use my strengths and not worry about
the weaknesses. Once the weaknesses get exposed, you're done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Smoltzie's got a chance to hit .300,'' Glavine conceded.
``He's given himself a little cushion here. When you hit that good,
though, word gets out, and he's going to get a steady diet of
breaking balls. So, don't count me out yet. Smoltzie's got how many
hits, 10? I just need some two-hit games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be tough to catch me,'' Smoltz said. ``But when Glav
gets his hits, they come in bunches, and I'm capable of a 1-for-20
(streak). If anyone can catch me, he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, though, and .400 appear safe.''Most definitely,''
Smoltz said. ``Unless I go through a tremendous bunting spree,
where I get my (sacrifice) bunts down. I'd love to have 20 hits, 10
RBIs, 15 to 20 sacrifices. Thennnnnnn . . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I'm already leading the team in batting average with
runners in scoring position.'' He's 4 for 5, .800.
</P>
<P>
   ``How 'bout forehead?'' Maddux asked, referring to Smoltz's
hairline, receding so rapidly that it could be timed with a JUGS
gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in batting average with bases loaded,'' Smoltz continued.
``I'm 1-for-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltzie, Mr. .400, paused. ``This is all going to jinx me,
isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
