<HEADLINE>
INVESTING NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most Popular, Yes, but Most Likely to Succeed?
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to stocks, popularity seems to be inversely
related to future performance. That is the gist of a study by H.
Bradlee Perry, a consultant at David L. Babson &AMP; Company, a money
manager in Cambridge, Mass., with $20 billion in assets under
management.
</P>
<P>
   In his study, Perry equated ``popularity'' with a high
price-to-earnings multiple. He tracked the performance of the New
York Stock Exchange stock with the highest P/E as of April in each
year since 1982, totaling their returns through May 27, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The results: The high P/E stocks have returned less than a third
as much as the S&AMP;P 500-stock index, measured from when they won the
P/E popularity contest through last month. The winning stocks
returned 121 percent, on average, compared with 366 percent for the
S&AMP;P 500, averaged the same way. (The stocks had a P/E of 52 in
their winning years, on average, compared with 16 for the S&AMP;P in
those years.)
</P>
<P>
   Perry pointed to two factors in the underperformance of the
popular stocks. First, they were often in new industries that
piqued investors' interest for a while but then lost their sizzle.
As evidence, he pointed to the performance of Rollins
Environmental, a hazardous-waste disposal company, which won the
high P/E award in 1988. It benefited from stricter environmental
regulations, fueling investor excitement. But the cost of its
services encouraged companies to reduce the volume of toxic waste
they produced. (Rollins, which merged with Safety-Kleen last year,
had a P/E of 34 in 1988 versus just 15 for the S&AMP;P 500; its stock
then lost 78 percent, versus a gain of 406 percent for the index.)
</P>
<P>
   Even when a company is in an industry with staying power, the
very promise of the market attracts keen competition. Advanced
Micro Devices, a pioneer in microprocessor chips, was the high P/E
company in 1984. But then Intel and others moved in. The results:
Advanced Micro, with a P/E of 35 in 1984 versus 12 for the S&AMP;P 500,
is down 32 percent since then, versus a gain of 724 percent for the
index.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the popularity kings have underperformed. Home Depot won
in 1993 with a P/E of 58, versus 18 for the market, and has since
gained 239 percent, versus 196 percent for the index.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's winner, Coca-Cola Enterprises, was down 5 percent
from April 1998 though May of this year, while the index is up 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
<P>
   How Much Will They Buy When Trading on Line?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some investors are obsessed with trading on line. But how
much are Americans willing to bet in a single online trade without
asking a financial adviser? The answer, according to a poll by
Louis Harris &AMP; Associates, is $4,500, on average.
</P>
<P>
   Men seem to be more aggressive. They are willing to invest up to
$6,800 in one online trade, on average, versus just $1,900 for
women.
</P>
<P>
   And younger investors seem to be more aggressive than older
ones. Those who are 18 to 24 years old were willing to make a
$9,300 trade, versus a limit of just under $6,000 for those aged 50
to 64.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, commissioned by Alliance Capital Management, whose
funds are mostly sold through brokers and advisers, surveyed 1,010
adults in May.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Betting on a Cancer Cure
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds are becoming increasingly specialized. Kinetics
Holdings, a money manager in North Babylon, N.Y., has filed a
statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission to offer a
new fund, called the Medical Fund and the Cure for Cancer Inc.,
that will invest in companies involved in cancer treatment and
research.
</P>
<P>
   An impossibly narrow field for a fund? Many people thought so of
Kinetics' last offering, the Internet Fund, started in 1996. It
returned 196 percent in 1998, and has $670 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   _RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
