<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEVENTIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITCOM SHINES DESPITE LAUGH RIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THAT 70s Show 
Starring: Topher Grace, Kurtwood Smith, Debra Jo Rupp, Ashton
Kutcher, Mila Kunis, Danny Masterson, Wilmer Valderrama, Laura
Prepon 
On: Fox network 
Time: Monday at 8 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do the creators of ``That 70s Show'' feel they need to blast
viewers with a cacophonous, libidinous, and vacuous laugh track
that sounds like a hyena on amphetamines? Guys, your amusing show
brings on smiles regardless of all the force-fed happiness and
manipulative, metallic mirth. Furthermore, it's funny in a sly,
self-conscious, and pot-clouded way, one that calls for snickers,
and definitely not peels of thunderous laughter.
</P>
<P>
   If you can ignore the laugh riot, ``That 70s Show'' is actually
a neat little teen sitcom. It's a sort of TV-series equivalent of
Eddie Haskell from ``Leave It to Beaver'': On one level, it's a
friendly half hour filled with sweet nostagia for the 1970s, for
high school, for bad haircuts and sneaking around with friends in
paneled basements. Set in Wisconsin, it could be ``Happy Days''
with lava lamps and 8-track tapes. But look behind its Farrah
posters and beneath its shag carpeting and you'll find a fairly
warped sense of humor at play _ the sort of giddiness that made the
``Wayne's World'' movies so much twisted fun. Just watch actor
Topher Grace's deadpan face, as he gives his teen everyman Eric
Foreman layers upon layers of 1990s-style slacker irony. He's no
Richie Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though Fox wants to provide ``That '70s Show'' with
a good chance to catch on with viewers. Last season, the series
aired on Sunday nights before ``The X-Files,'' a plum timeslot that
made ``King of the Hill'' into a hit the year before. It begins a
Monday summer run, with new episodes at 8 p.m. paired with repeats
at 8:30. And in the fall, it's set to move to Tuesdays after
``Ally,'' the half hour of outtakes from the popular ``Ally
McBeal.'' But ``That '70s Show'' may never become a mainstream hit
for Fox, simply because it relies on material that could be too
subversive for many viewers. In Monday's episode, for instance,
Eric's mom worriedly compares his zombie-like behavior to the
checklist in a ``Is Johnny High'' pamphlet. What Mom doesn't know
is that he's a zombie because he accidentally saw her and Dad
making love. Meanwhile, he and his friends have painted a giant pot
leaf on the local water tower that looks suspiciously like an
obscene hand gesture.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the show, which was going to be called ``Teenage
Wasteland'' until Pete Townshend said no, is pretty upfront and
nonjudgmental in its references to marijuana. The smoking itself
takes place off camera, but the kids can be exceedingly giggly and
spacey in some scenes, and the Steve Hyde character is predicated
on the sort of government paranoia (the ``phony'' gas crisis'')
that is comically identified with longtime pot use. Every week the
show gives us its trademark 360-degree camera pan, sometimes with
the kids around a table riffing off one another's comments in a
flow of tangents, the bong seemingly one step ahead of the camera.
While ``That '70s Show'' has touches of ``American Graffiti''
innocence, its big-screen analogy would be accurately be ``Dazed
and Confused.''
</P>
<P>
   The young ensemble is appealing, particularly Topher Grace and
Danny Masterson, whose frizzy-haired Hyde is both a burnt-out
radical and an eager kid. Laura Prepon, who resembles Claire Danes,
makes her Donna into more than just the mature girl nextdoor and
the object of Eric's desire; she's also his friend. It's too bad
Prepon looks distractingly older than the rest of the gang.
</P>
<P>
   As Fez, the foreign-exchange student, Wilmer Valderrama milks
more laughs than ever seemed possible from a few malapropisms and a
Latin accent. The kids parents _ particularly Debra Jo Rupp as
Eric's protective Mom _ are also a hoot, as silly as their children
in their attempts at self-realization in the Me Decade. They, too,
are coming of age on ``That '70s Show,'' and you never know what
those crazy parents will do next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
