<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-LA-SUBWAY-ART-2     06-11 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-LA-SUBWAY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES' FIRST SUBWAY SYSTEM LIKELY TO BE ITS LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map of the Los
Angeles subway line is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For a brief moment Friday morning, the cream of
the Los Angeles political establishment could be found deep
underground, doing something that residents of this sprawling,
car-crazed city hardly ever do: riding the subway. And not just any
subway, but the spanking new stops under Hollywood that, after two
decades of striving, setbacks and billions of dollars spent, have
finally brought the system to just over 11 miles of subterranean
track.
</P>
<P>
   As he dedicated the new terminus of the Metro Red Line at the
fabled intersection of Hollywood and Vine, where old film reels
line the arched ceilings like pale blue stars and cast concrete
columns are shaped like giant palm trees with bright green metal
fronds, Mayor Richard Riordan pronounced it ``truly a great day.''
But the grand beginning was also an ending of sorts, because Los
Angeles' first subway line will almost certainly be its last.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, an extension is scheduled to open through the
Hollywood hills to Universal Studios and North Hollywood, bringing
the total subway to 17.4 miles, from Union Station downtown to the
southern edge of the San Fernando Valley, at a cost of about $4.5
billion, with some stretches costing $500 million a mile. But
further plans for underground lines have been suspended
indefinitely, and last fall voters in Los Angeles County
overwhelmingly passed a ballot measure barring further use of the
county sales tax surcharge that has financed the project for subway
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The fond dream of the late Mayor Tom Bradley, begun in the early
1980s with a self-conscious desire to give Los Angeles the
trappings of a world-class city, the subway opened its first short
downtown stretch in 1993. But from the beginning, it has been
plagued by cost overruns, political infighting, unexpected
difficulties in tunneling and doubts about its usefulness. Even if
ridership reaches the expected level of 125,000 weekday passengers
next year, it will serve only a tiny fraction of the city's
residents who depend on public transportation, and nothing like the
3.4 million passengers who use New York City's subways daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should get out of the subway business,'' Riordan said in a
less celebratory moment earlier this week. ``We never should've
started in the first place, and the only reason we're celebrating
opening these stations this week, and the only reason why we're
completing it to North Hollywood, is that the Red Line would be
virtually useless without completing it.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, planners hope that tourists in downtown hotels will
use the five new Hollywood stations, which cover 4.6 miles and open
to the public on Saturday, to take in venerable attractions like
Mann's Chinese Theater and the Hollywood Walk of Fame, and that
commuters from the San Fernando Valley will use the North Hollywood
stop next year as an alternative to the freeway to downtown. Los
Angeles' low-rise sprawl makes comparisons difficult, but the net
effect will still be roughly akin to a line that ran only from New
York's City Hall to Shea Stadium, by way of the Lower East Side and
Bellevue Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, weekday ridership for the Red Line is about
35,000 boardings, compared to more than 1 million on the city's
overcrowded fleet of buses. The stations are spotless and nearly
empty, the rubber-wheeled trains almost silent and the whole
experience such a comparative novelty that the $1.35 fare still
works on a honor system, in which passengers are expected to buy
tickets (and can be fined if they do not have them) but face no
turnstiles or other barriers before boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Another 60,000 passengers are carried on an interlinked system
of about 40 miles of light rail lines that run from downtown to the
harbor at Long Beach, and along the city's southern fringe near Los
Angeles International Airport, and total ridership of the combined
system is projected to reach 200,000 next year. But in a city where
residents live and work in a hopelessly criss-crossed pattern,
without a single central core, hub-and-spoke rail lines have
limited use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flawed thinking on all of our collective parts was that we
could build a mass rapid transit system that was principally
underground in time to make a difference, time for when it was
needed, and be able to afford it,'' said Zev Yaroslavksy, a Los
Angeles County supervisor who, like Riordan, sits on the 13-member
board of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, which runs the
system, and who sponsored last year's ballot measure cutting off
further funds for the subway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible,'' Yaroslavksy added. ``What became clear
years ago was that the subway project was on a collision course
with the other transit needs of Los Angeles, first and foremost
buses.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, since 1996, the transportation authority has been
operating under a federal consent decree in a civil rights lawsuit
brought by bus riders in an effort to force it to improve service.
It is currently fighting the demand of a court-appointed special
master that it buy 481 new buses to replenish its aging fleet,
arguing that the master has no such authority and that it is
working as fast as it can, with plans to deploy another 115 buses
in the coming fiscal year, bringing its fleet to over 2,000 buses
at peak hours.
</P>
<P>
   Over much of the decade until the suit was filed, bus service
was cut, fares increased and ridership fell as money was diverted
to pay for the subway, and bus riders argue that the system still
slights the poor riders who need service the most. On Friday
morning, a knot of protesters marched up and down Hollywood
Boulevard in front of the new Vine Street station carrying placards
that mocked the MTA's slogan, ``Downtown to Tinseltown in 15
Minutes,'' with an alternative reading: ``From Downtown to
Tinseltown in 13 Scandal-Plagued Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the rail's configured now, some of it will be serving
minority and low-income riders,'' said Erica Teasley, a lawyer with
the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, which represents the
bus riders in the suit. ``But it is ironic that politicians
continue to fight for subways. Buses can work well when there are
enough on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the subway has been driven by pork-barrel
politicking that helped determine its proposed route in an effort
to spread the spoils of construction jobs. Despite some outspoken
criticism of the system by Yaroslavksy and Riordan, who is
finishing up a two-year term as chairman of the MTA board, other
local politicians, especially those representing the heavily
Hispanic area of East Los Angeles, have continued to press for
extending the subway _ or at least a light rail line _ to their
neighborhoods as originally planned, perhaps with state money.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that railways make sense as part of a broader
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buses will always be the backbone'' of the transit system
here, Yvonne Brathwaite Burke, another county supervisor and MTA
board member who assumes the chairmanship this summer, said at the
dedication ceremonies Friday morning. ``But we cannot afford to put
all our transportation eggs in one basket. There's no single
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has picked up about half the cost of the
subway project and in the past it has been harshly critical of the
MTA's budget and management practices, several times rejecting its
proposed spending plans as unrealistic. But over the last two
years, under pressure from Riordan and the chief executive he
recommended, Julian Burke, the agency has much improved its
relations with Washington, and on Friday the federal transit
administrator, Gordon Linton, was among the dignitaries at
Hollywood and Vine.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the ceremonies if the government would be inclined
to support further subway construction after next year, Linton
replied: ``That's truly a local decision.'' But, he added, ``I do
think they have learned that you have to build within your
available budget.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, as cast members from a touring production of
``The Wizard of Oz'' scampered through the station to the strains
of ``Over the Rainbow,'' even skeptics like Yaroslavksy could not
resist an air of celebration. The new stations are each designed to
reflect their local flavor, so Hollywood and Vine pays homage to
the movies, with a yellow brick road rising out of the red floor
and upstairs to the street, while the Vermont and Sunset station,
which adjoins a handful of leading hospitals, has a space-age motif
containing medical symbols and an elevator that echoes the dome of
Griffith Park Observatory in the hills above it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a tremendous boon,'' said Leron Gubler, the
executive director of the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce, whose
members endured years of construction debris and mishaps, including
a giant sinkhole that swallowed up part of Hollywood Boulevard and
forced the closing of some stores in an area that is struggling to
reclaim its former glamour after years of hard times. ``I think the
new stations are going to be a tourist attraction in and of
themselves. We might even get a few Angelenos to go down and check
it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
