<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL BUSINESS NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raising Air Fares And Slashing Them, Too
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines raised leisure fares 4 percent on June 2. But
less than a week later, the increase was effectively rescinded when
the airlines trimmed those fares by as much as 25 percent for
off-peak summer travel and capped fares for round-trip travel on
peak days at $498.
</P>
<P>
   David Swierenga, an economist with the Air Transport
Association, a trade group, said that only about 6 or 7 percent of
passengers pay full fare _ ``almost everyone travels on some kind
of discount.''
</P>
<P>
   So do small fare increases make much difference? Terry Trippler,
the airline writer for 1Travel.com, thinks so, and not only because
they are likely to remain after the fare sales end. While raising
overall fares, he said, airlines often eliminate an entire tier of
bargain fares _ though they haven't done so this time around.
</P>
<P>
   _EDWIN McDOWELL
</P>
<P>
   Rewarding Wall Street Careers
</P>
<P>
   Workers may have grown accustomed to tiny pay raises in recent
years, but not so the chief executives of eight big Wall Street
investment houses. Last year, their median total compensation was
$13.9 million, up 27 percent from $10.9 million in 1996, according
to Pearl Meyer &AMP; Partners, a consulting firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures count only salaries, bonuses, restricted stock,
long-term performance payouts and the value of options on the date
they were granted. Add in profits from exercising stock options
issued in the past, and the numbers really soar. Sanford I. Weill,
co-chief executive of Citigroup, made $156.6 million exercising
options last year, and Philip J. Purcell, chairman and chief
executive of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, made $40 million. Of
course, profits from options reflect rising stock prices, which
benefit shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies in the analysis were Bear Stearns; Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette; Lehman Brothers; Merrill Lynch; J.P. Morgan, and
Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   _DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
