<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Fallen Bridge, A Raised Hurdle
</P>
<P>
   What could the collapse of a highway bridge in Connecticut 16
years ago have to do with up-to-date bookkeeping standards? Quite a
bit, when it comes to some controversial new rules that were
approved last week by the governmental Accounting Standards Board.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of government officials say they resent the board's
approval of a plan that will force states and cities to begin
including monetary values of their roads and bridges in their
financial statements. The government officials say it will be too
costly to gather decades-old files of information on bridges built
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the new rules will also force many governments to assess the
condition of their bridges systematically, a requirement that, for
some members of the accounting board, hits close to home.
</P>
<P>
   The board is based in Norwalk, Conn., and some members and
employees frequently cross a new bridge over the nearby Mianus
River, where the old one fell apart in June 1983, killing three
people and severing busy Interstate 95 for months. Federal safety
officials said the cause was rusty parts and poor inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive over that bridge quite often,'' said Tom L. Allen, the
board's chairman. In board meetings on the new rules, Allen said,
at least one board member made the point, ``Well, look what
happened on that bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   _MELODY PETERSEN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
