<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONGRATULATES AIR CREWS IN MISSOURI 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITEMAN AIR FORCE BASE, Mo. _ President Clinton applauded U.S.
air crews Friday for a job well done a day after U.S.-led NATO
bombers forced Yugoslav troops to retreat from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton congratulated the troops not only for besting Yugoslav
forces in the field but for being an example of ethnic diversity
that gives lie to Slobodan Milosevic's policy of ethnic division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all came down from Washington today on behalf of your
fellow Americans to salute the men and women of Whiteman Air Force
Base, to thank you for a job well done, to honor you for the way
you honor America,'' Clinton told several hundred crew members and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hastily arranged appearance at Whiteman Air Force Base
also gave the military a chance to highlight the first successful
operation of the B-2 stealth bomber, the $1.3 billion bat-shaped
radar evader that proved so controversial throughout much of its
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an I-told-you-so day,'' crowed Rep. Ike Skelton of
Missouri, the ranking Democrat on the House National Security
Committee and a supporter of the B-2 development. Many members of
Congress opposed the B-2 because of its costs and questions about
its mission after the demise of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The dual-pilot crews here flew 50 missions, each a 30-hour
roundtrip between the Missouri base and the Balkans. Although the
crews flew only a small number of the 30,000 sorties over
Yugoslavia, the B-2 dropped 11 percent of all the bombs that fell
during the 79-day air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   B-2 pilots told reporters that their 30-hour flights began with
some apprehension but turned into a routine. A pilot called Sunny
told of crews purchasing aluminum lawn chairs that they turned into
makeshift beds in their cramped cockpit quarters. Pilots took turns
sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Each plane carries 16 2,000-pound precision-guided bombs.
Whiteman currently has 10 B-2s. Six were used in the sorties. The
Air Force has 11 more B-2s under contract.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the goals of the United States and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization to force Serbs to withdraw from
Kosovo, to deploy an international force with NATO at its core and
to return the hundreds of thousand ethnic Albanians to their homes
have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic accepted these conditions for one reason _ you
made him do it,'' Clinton said. ``Thanks to you and the others who
flew and supported our air mission and those of our NATO allies; he
ran out of room, and he ran out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president also warned that much was left to be done in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to win the peace,'' Clinton said. ``Those folks
have to go home, and they've got to have a roof over their head
before it gets too cold to be outside. We've got land mines to take
up, and businesses to rebuild, and a future to make. That work,
too, can be dangerous for those who follow in your footsteps in the
peacekeeping missions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pointed to the varied ethnicity of the crews in
contrast to Milosevic's vision of an ethnically pure Greater Serbia
without the Bosnian Muslims, the Croatian Catholics or the Kosovar
Albania Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, look around here. You put the lie to that by the power
of your example. And make no mistake about it, it is even more
powerful than the power of our bombs,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the effort to stop Milosevic's ouster of ethnic
Albanians from Kosovo a ``defining moment'' for the Western
alliance because Milosevic thought its diversity would break its
unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought open societies with free dissent _ where, as you
know, everybody in America was free to tell me I was wrong about
this from the get-go _ he thought that made us weak. But he turned
out to be wrong,'' Clinton said, allowing himself a bit of
boasting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
