<SLUG> BC-KOREA-WARSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREAN NAVY RAMS SHIPS FROM NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ South Korean patrol boats rammed at least three North
Korean vessels Friday, raising tensions in the five-day standoff in
the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently responding to political concerns that it was dealing
with North Korean intrusions too gently, South Korea's Defense
Ministry also ordered more of its warships to the area. It said
that it had asked the United States to put some of its forces on
alert and said that U.S. troops would help in any crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States did not put any of its 37,000 troops in
South Korea on alert, and the U.S.-led United Nations Command
called for talks between generals on the two sides to help ease the
dispute. North Korea has not responded to the call for talks.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's actions Friday were a surprise, because generally
the South has been relatively patient and conciliatory toward the
North. But the government of President Kim Dae-jung has been
strongly criticized by the opposition party for being soft on the
North, and the government may have decided as a result to be more
forceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation came close to an armed clash,'' The Associated
Press quoted a member of the National Assembly, Han Young-soo, as
telling reporters after he received a briefing by navy officials.
``After the collision, the North Korean ships trained their guns at
us, and we responded in kind. It was a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   No shots were fired, and the six North Korean naval vessels in
the area initially retreated after the ramming. At least one had a
hole in its hull and was taking on water and had to be towed,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the afternoon, several North Korean vessels returned to
the area, and the standoff continued.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the confrontation has been sketchy and often
contradictory, but it seems to have begun Monday when several North
Korean patrol boats escorted fishing vessels into rich crab-fishing
grounds that South Korea regards as its own. The fishing grounds
are in a buffer zone south of the ``northern limit line,'' which
the South treats as the demarcation line between North and South in
the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The North has never acknowledged the line as the boundary, and
its ships venture south of it about 30 times a year, particularly
in the crab season. But while North Korean vessels normally back
off in the face of South Korean warships, this time they stood
their ground.
</P>
<P>
   There are various theories about what North Korea was up to. One
is that it was simply after crabs because food is so scarce in the
North. Another is that it was testing the South's will. A third is
that the North is preparing to negotiate with the West and has
found that it always gets more in negotiations if it reminds
everyone that war remains a real possibility on the Korean
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of confrontation as a bargaining tactic arises
because the Clinton administration is proposing to lift sanctions
against North Korea if it is willing to give up its long-range
missiles and take other measures to reduce tensions. North Korea
and Japan are also edging toward a resumption of talks on
normalizing relations.
</P>
<P>
   As for the South, Capt. Shin Han-Woo, a Defense Ministry
spokesman, explained its tough actions as a show of force to teach
the North a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep them out of the buffer zone and we wanted to
display our firm will that we will not hesitate to deal with
violations,'' Capt. Shin said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Defense Minister Cho Seong-tae had met the top U.S.
military commander in South Korea, Gen. John Tilelli, on Thursday
morning and asked him to put some U.S. troops on alert in case the
situation deteriorated. ``We do not intend to take military action,
but if such incidents happened, the U.S. Command would help us,''
said Shin, in what appeared to be a warning to the North.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Carl Kropf, a spokesman for the U.N. Command, said that the
command regarded the North Korean intrusion as a provocative act
but that no forces had been placed on alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching the situation very closely and are in dialogue
with the South Koreans,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
