<SLUG> BC-VOLKSWAGEN-ADVERTISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BEETLE ADS POINT TO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to be in the forefront of a trend in cross-marketing, a
television ad invites viewers to check out the new turbocharged
version of Volkswagen's updated Beetle on a Web site called
turbonium.com.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the TV ad introduces a story line, and the story
line is continued and reinforced on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying this is the wave of the future, but it could
be,'' said chief creative officer Ron Lawner of Arnold
Communications, the Boston agency that created both the ad and the
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have used traditional advertising to drive
traffic to their Web site. Remember the Super Bowl ad that
stampeded eyeballs to a Victoria's Secret Internet fashion show?
But these efforts are often for products that cost under $200.
</P>
<P>
   Now cross-marketing techniques are pitching cars. While most car
manufacturers have informational Web sites that contain echoes of
their ads, it is believed that the new VW spot is one of the first
examples of a car maker directly tying together a TV ad, a car
model, and special Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The VW ad is a spoof of a newscast. There's been a scientific
breakthrough, an announcer says. Turbonium has been discovered. Put
it in a Beetle, and the Beetle can attain warp speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Images in the TV ad were carefully selected so they would be
equally effective when viewed on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integration of Web marketing and traditional advertising
is increasing rapidly,'' noted Larry Weber, chief executive of
Weber Public Relations Worldwide, a firm that has done a lot of
Internet marketing. ``The Web could become the largest showroom in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the not too distant future, ``you're going to see a lot of
ads that say, `Come to our Web site and take a virtual test drive,'
'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For companies that want to sell products to young adults, the
Web has special appeal. Many young adults are turned off by the
hard sell of conventional advertising but seem more receptive to
marketing on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the inspiration for the turbonium campaign came from an
earlier VW ad created by Arnold. That ad showed a couple driving a
VW through New Orleans, all the street scenes in time with the
music of an original sound track.
</P>
<P>
   The VW Web site received so many inquiries about the ad that
Arnold decided to marry a future TV ad to a special Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you'll see a fun TV ad, but when you go to the
company's Web site, it's all business,'' said Arnold creative
director Alan Pafenbach. ``We felt if we could continue the fun of
the TV experience on the Internet, people will come and stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the turbonium.com site to be regularly upgraded
with fresh content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
