<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: GRAND MUFTI OF KOSOVO: AT HOME IN A ZONE OF GOD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Turkey)   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Rexhep Boja, the Grand Mufti of Kosovo, left New York last
Sunday for Istanbul. As of Friday, he was heading for the refugee
camps in Albania and Macedonia so that he could be with people as
they faced the joys and terrors of returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Home for Boja himself is what it is for many other Kosovars: a
burned-out dwelling, in Pristina in his case, from which he and his
family were driven at gunpoint shortly after the NATO bombing
began.
</P>
<P>
   But home for Boja (pronounced BOY-ah) also seems to be a
remarkable zone of faith in God, in the future and in human nature
_ a zone where sorrow nests, but no discernible trace of animosity.
</P>
<P>
   The Mufti was a marked man. As the elected religious leader of
Kosovo's Muslims, he had long been harassed, arrested and
interrogated by Yugoslav officials. Then he led the funeral prayers
for Bajram Kelmendi, a neighbor and prominent human rights
advocate. Kelmendi and two sons were seized on the first night of
the bombing; their corpses were found two days later.
</P>
<P>
   It was lunchtime not long afterward when armed men arrived at
Boja's home. Forced entrance, orders to lie on the floor, demands
for money, seizure of documents, house set aflame, the march to the
train, people shoved into the cars through open windows _ the
sequence is by now all too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 miles to the Macedonian border took eight hours. At each
prolonged halt, the huddled passengers feared they were about to be
shot, or used as shields against NATO bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was praying and depending on God,'' Boja said, ``and
many people were saying, `Pray for us.' Everyone was scared.''
Sitting in a Manhattan hotel restaurant next to a translator, he
raised his eyes to heaven and threw up his hands in a manner
expressing a state of both helplessness and supplication.
</P>
<P>
   It was an expansive gesture for this grave, neatly bearded man
in a dark suit who most often bent forward as he spoke and made
small, graceful circles with his cupped hands, like a potter
rounding, shaping and smoothing his words into reality. It was
typical that he concluded his story of flight with a plea: Please
don't sensationalize it so as merely to stir up more passion.
</P>
<P>
   Boja was in the United States under the auspices of the World
Conference on Religion and Peace, a worldwide coalition of
religious leaders addressing issues of conflict resolution, human
rights and economic development. The organization is convinced that
cooperation among Balkan religious leaders will be an essential
component of any future reconstruction and reconciliation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Boja expressed deep disappointment that Kosovo's Serbian
Orthodox leaders had never condemned the ethnic cleansing and
anti-Albanian terror. Then he quickly qualified his remarks.
``Maybe myself I would try to find some excuse for the Orthodox
leadership,'' he said, ``because we know the mentality of the
Communist regime: if any priests said a single word, they could pay
with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For Boja, there was clear continuity between the anti-religious
attitudes of the earlier ``communist regime'' and the current
Belgrade Government's efforts to inflame and manipulate religious
feelings. As a youth, he was spurned by Communist organizations and
condemned by Communist publications for his devotion to Islam. To
study his faith, he had to go abroad, earning a doctorate in Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Today's government, he said, ``tried to play the religious
card,'' deliberately offending Muslim sensibilities in hope of
provoking reactions that would substantiate government ``slogans
about `jihad.'''
</P>
<P>
   He challenged the widespread impression that Balkan history is
nothing but a chronicle of religious warfare. In Kosovo, it is
quite the contrary, he said: three religious communities _ Muslim,
Orthodox and Roman Catholic _ long coexisted peacefully. There are
sacred sites of the Serbian Orthodox in Kosovo, he said, that for
many years have been in the safekeeping of Albanian Muslim
Kosovars, who consider them part of a national heritage and spared
them damage even as ethnic conflict grew acute. In earlier years,
imams and priests were often jailed by communist officials in the
same cells, and emerged friends.
</P>
<P>
   Boja's hopes for the future brightened even while he was in New
York. The conversation in the restaurant took place before the
Yugoslav President, Slobodan Milosevic, accepted NATO's terms; it
continued, four days later, after that initial acceptance, over tea
at the home of William F. Vendley, secretary general of the World
Conference on Religion and Peace.
</P>
<P>
   What appeared to remain constant, however, was his conviction
that, with the aid of ``civilized nations'' _ first among them the
United States, in his eyes a model of religious pluralism _
reconstruction and tolerance could overcome bitterness and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   At moments during the talk at Vendley's home, it was hard not to
think the Mufti naive. Yet only that morning he had been visiting
refugee families at Fort Dix, N.J., and he knew that he would soon
be counseling families learning not only of destroyed homes and
livelihoods but also of murdered sons and raped daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to visit, advise, encourage and guide the families,
psychologically and spiritually,'' he said, ``and help them look to
the future, not be caught in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Boja discouraged by the fact that the Islamic center in
Pristina, which had also functioned as a civic and educational
center with newly installed computer technology, was now gutted:
``Even the spoons were taken and everything shot up with machine
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Vendley recalled having been welcomed there in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will come again,'' the Mufti said softly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
