<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS PEOPLE IN THE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jordan Shows His Hand
</P>
<P>
   Having dealt his way out of a job by turning Westinghouse, the
appliance maker, into CBS, the network, Michael H. Jordan has dealt
his way back into another job, and in a manner characteristic of
the times. Last week, the Clarant Worldwide Corp., which aims to
help major corporations and new Internet ventures do business on
line, filed for a $150-million-plus public offering, for 30.7
percent of the company, with Jordan as chairman. Clarant, based in
Dallas, will be formed from eight companies that it has agreed to
acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan yielded the top CBS job to Mel Karmazin, a far more
experienced broadcasting executive, on Jan. 1. Turns out, however,
that Jordan has learned a thing or two about matters digital. He
has been on the Dell Computer board since 1992 and the
Marketwatch.com board since last June. He is also involved in
ventures range from webcasting to Internet document encryption.
Jordan will leave the company's operations in the hands of
Clarant's chief executive and founder, Guillermo G. Marmol.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity Celebrations
</P>
<P>
   From women's fashion to general interest, magazines hardly let a
month pass without putting more actresses and pop stars on their
covers. Weightier publications compete for contributions by
renowned writers. And the celebrities are used to being treated
like, well, celebrities. While a model might be happy with a few
celery sticks, a celebrity requires some public prandial pampering.
</P>
<P>
   In October, when Vogue's editor in chief, Anna Wintour, featured
Oprah Winfrey on a cover, Ms. Winfrey got a grand cocktail party
for a few hundred friends at the restaurant Pravda. This spring,
Tina Brown threw a lavish dinner for Martin Amis, the British
writer, at her apartment and invited Harrison Ford and David Bowie.
Ms. Brown announced last week that her Talk Media group had signed
Amis for three books, a screenplay and several magazine articles.
Last month, when The New Yorker published a story by Salman
Rushdie, David Remnick, the editor, threw a dinner party for a
hundred and fifty at Il Cantinori.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, Elle magazine hosted an eight-course dinner at
Bond St., an upscale Japanese restaurant, to celebrate Jennifer
Lopez's cover. Sony music? chairman Tommy Mottola and Robert DeNiro
mingled with executives from L'Oreal and the advertising agency
McCann-Erickson. The cost? For about 40 diners, anywhere from
$5,000 to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not a contest to see whose dinner party is bigger or
more expensive, said Keith Estabrook, a publicist for Hachette
Filipacchi Magazines, which publishes Elle. ``It brings the product
to life,'' Estabrook said. ``It's the people who are in the
magazine, who read the magazine or that should be in the
magazine.'' All that, and everyone got a free tube of L'Oreal
mascara.
</P>
<P>
   _ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Brimming With Wealth
</P>
<P>
   C. Everett Koop, 82, the bearded apostle of well-informed
patients, critic of managed care, and battler against health
hazards from Big Tobacco to big bellies, once spoke disdainfully of
big bucks. He was already a reknowned pediatric surgeon when he
joined the Reagan Administration, and as a crusading Surgeon
General, he valued candor over political discretion. ``I did not
come here having to prove anything to myself,'' he said in 1987,
``and I was not looking for a six-figure job afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Koop became an eight-figure lord of the Internet
last week. Drkoop.com, his consumer-health startup, went public on
Tuesday at $9, soared to $20.25, and closed Friday at $15.8125,
valuing his 2.5 million shares at $39.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Koop Web site faces what David Restrepo, an analyst at
Jupiter Communication, calls ``a ton of competition.'' An estimated
15,000 Internet health sites range from cyberquacks to pillars of
science like mayohealth.org. Still, Chick Koop, as some medical
colleagues call him, is arguably the best-known doc since Benjamin
Spock. ``He has the persona to nudge patients and physicians
towards better health care,'' said Dr. Nancy Dickey, president of
the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Koop himself was understandably euphoric last week, but he cited
improved public health rather than his improved private wealth as
the reason. ``My special delight about this,'' he said, ``is it
provides me with an opportunity to get my message out to people _
that they have to take care of their own health.'' _MILT
FREUDENHEIM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
