<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANTS THAT MAKE LIFE EASIER FOR WATER CARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 13)  
(DW) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If house lots were all designed by efficient gardeners, there
might never be a need to carry water in a bucket to a thirsty
plant. All ornamental beds would be within easy reach of a
sprinkler.
</P>
<P>
   But every dwelling I've inhabited that had a yard also had a
little patch of flowers or shrubbery in a sun-baked spot that was
inconvenient or difficult to water. One was at the far end of the
driveway, the maximum distance possible from the outdoor faucet.
One was on a slope where most of the water ran onto the sidewalk.
One was adjacent to the neighbor's rose garden, which resented
having its foliage dampened by sprinkler drift. I watered by hand
to save the neighbor's roses from mildew.
</P>
<P>
   My current abode has a plethora of hard-to-water ornamental beds
in full sun, for which my inefficient nature is entirely to blame.
I didn't design or place them with the garden hose in mind. But I
did choose plants for those beds with a thought to minimizing the
number of times I'd need to water.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mediterranean natives like lavender and thyme are
content in sunny beds that seldom or never see a sprinkler or
soaker hose. They're far more likely to die in constantly moist
soil, or soil that stays soggy for days after a downpour.
</P>
<P>
   Domesticated versions of prairie flowers like Kansas gayfeather
(Liatris spicata) and meadowsweet (Filipendula purpurea) will grow
and bloom reliably without the gardener standing over them with a
watering can. Yucca and German iris are both great, and almost any
kind of dianthus or artemisia will thrive on natural rainfall
unless you live in a desert or semidesert area.
</P>
<P>
   Two personal favorites are butterfly weed (Asclepias tuberosa)
and cushion spurge (Euphorbia epithymoides, sometimes sold as E.
-poly-chroma). It stands to reason that these plants would do well
in dry areas. Butterfly weed is cousin to milkweed (A. syriaca),
and cushion spurge is kin to flowering spurge (E. corollata), both
common weeds throughout most of the eastern United States. I've not
yet seen the drought that milkweed and flowering spurge couldn't
survive.
</P>
<P>
   The most commonly available butterfly weed has orange or yellow
flowers, but there are white- and pink-flowered varieties as well.
All varieties take a very long time to emerge in the spring. Be
sure to mark where you've planted them so you don't accidentally
dig them up.
</P>
<P>
   Cushion spurge makes a neat mound of foliage, about a foot tall
and two feet in diameter. Like most euphorbias, it doesn't flower
in the usual sense but has colored bracts or terminal leaves. (The
family includes Christmas poinsettias, whose ``flowers'' are really
colored leaves.)
</P>
<P>
   The bracts on cushion spurge are a vivid sulfur yellow,
appearing in the early spring after the crocuses have finished
blooming and lasting for several weeks. For most of the year, the
plant is solid green, and in the autumn it turns scarlet. It's
extremely drought-tolerant, hasn't been bothered by any insects in
my garden, and looks good three seasons out of four. I can't find
much fault with it.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing annuals for seldom-watered spots is a little tricker
than choosing perennials. Annuals are expected to produce flowers
and foliage all summer long, which takes water, and they don't have
the deep roots that can tide perennials over in a dry spell.
</P>
<P>
   Annual vinca (Vinca rosea) or Mexican heather are good choices
if watering is mildly inconvenient but can be done if necessary.
Both will take hot weather and dry soil, but don't expect them to
survive without water for weeks on end.
</P>
<P>
   Vinca is a low-growing, spreading plant with small, shiny leaves
and flowers that resemble those of impatiens. The flowers are white
or shades of pink, lavender and rose. Mexican heather (Cuphea
hyssopifolia), also called false heather and elfin herb, looks
almost like a small boxwood shrub, except that it's covered with
tiny purple flowers. It is perennial in mild climates. It won't
survive winters much north of Georgia, but it grows so quickly that
it's well worth enjoying as an annual.
</P>
<P>
   If you're desperate for seasonlong color in a sunny spot where
watering is nearly impossible, the hands-down choice is portulaca,
also called moss rose. Like butterfly weed and cushion spurge,
portulaca has all the survival skills of its weedy relatives. It's
a cultivated version of common purslane, called pusley in the
South, which thrives in hot, dry areas.
</P>
<P>
   Portulaca is easy to grow from seed, and there are several good
varieties available that have been bred to keep their flowers open
longer during the day. (Portulaca tends to open its flowers only
when the sun is shining brightly, and to close them in the morning,
evening and on overcast days.) Seed-grown varieties have slender,
needlelike leaves and a habit of flopping over, which makes them
look untidy close up, but they are not stingy with their flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Even better is the vegetatively propagated variety called Yubi.
Yubi has a spreading growth habit. Each plant will cover an area
about two feet in diameter, which makes it useful as a ground
cover. Its succulent leaves look like a jade plant's, its flowers
are twice the size of those on seed-grown portulacas, and it grows
fast.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a terrific plant for tubs and baskets on sunny decks
and porches, especially those with no convenient source of water.
If decks and porches were all designed by efficient gardeners,
they'd all have built-in water taps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
