<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES FALL; FED EXPECTED TO RAISE INTEREST RATES  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   American consumers, the backbone of the second longest economic
expansion ever, are not showing any signs of pinching pennies. And
their spending spree is putting continued upward pressure on market
interest rates, with long-term yields jumping to a 19-month high
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Automobile and furniture buying helped push retail sales up one
percent in May, the government reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A separate economic report showed that prices paid to producers
of finished goods rose 0.2 percent last month, suggesting that
inflation was still in check.
</P>
<P>
   But price increases outside the oil sector in crude goods, like
wheat, and intermediate goods, like flour, could signal a
turnaround in the global economy. Such a turnaround would mean more
demand for credit and would put even more upward pressure on
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a rebound in Asia gained credibility last week
after Japan reported that its economy grew at a surprisingly strong
1.9 percent in the first three months of the year. Economists found
reason for optimism even after the government rushed to play down
the size of the increase, suggesting the growth rate would not be
sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree with everyone that first-quarter GDP overstates the
rate of revival in Japan,'' said Robert J. Barbera, the chief
economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. ``But we buy the notion that Japan is now
rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   All three reports strengthened the view of many analysts that
the Federal Reserve will raise its short-term interest rate to slow
economic growth and prevent any surge in prices. Economists now
expect a quarter of a percentage point increase when Fed
policy-makers meet at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Like many economists, Richard Berner, chief U.S. economist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, expects the central bank to push rates
up yet another quarter point later in the year. ``The question
now,'' he said, ``is what will the Fed do after that'' second rate
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The new data and growing concern about how far the Fed might
have to go to slow the economy helped send interest rates higher
again Friday in a very jittery market. The yield on the 30-year
bond jumped to 6.16 percent, its highest since November 1997, as
the price, which moves in the opposite direction, fell 1 point and
7/32 to 87 22/32.
</P>
<P>
   This sell-off capped the worst week for bonds in 3 1/2 months as
the yield on the 30-year-bond jumped from 5.96 percent last Friday.
The yield has now risen nearly 1.5 percentage points since a
30-year low for long-term interest rates last October.
</P>
<P>
   And as interest rates moved higher Friday, the stock market
tumbled. The Dow Jones Industrial average fell 130.76 points, or
1.2 percent, to finish at 10,490.51.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Talk of bond sales by big investors, which was not confirmed,
and other rumors about hedge-fund troubles pushed the bond market
sharply lower in the afternoon. Some traders said the Japanese were
selling, while others said that big money managers who had waited
too long to sell were jumping in to stop their losses.
</P>
<P>
   And the market volatility is expected to continue as investors
await this week's report on May consumer prices, scheduled for
release on Wednesday, and the appearance of Alan Greenspan, the
chairman of the Federal Reserve, before Congress the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of nervousness about that,'' said Thomas
Connor, head government trader at J.P. Morgan Securities. The
consumer price index jumped seven-tenths of one percent in April,
and analysts now believe that even a more moderate increase for May
will guarantee a Fed interest rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   Based on various market monitors, investors seem to be expecting
at least a half a percentage point increase in the Fed's short-term
target for Federal Funds, which is the amount banks charge each
other for overnight loans. But one barometer is leaning toward a
bigger move.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Friday the yield on the two-year Treasury note jumped to 5.69
percent, which leaves it almost a full percentage point above the
central bank's current Federal Funds target of 4.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If that yield moves just a little higher, it will indicate that
some investors are expecting a total move of three-quarters of a
percentage point in a series of steps. Such a move by the central
bank would erase all three of the quarter-point rate cuts made last
fall in a successful effort to calm global financial markets after
the Russian currency devaluation and the near-collapse of a major
hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera of Hoenig &AMP; Co.contends that long-term rates could edge
toward 6.50 percent, rather then the 6.25 percent peak many
analysts are discussing. He argues that much of the rise in market
rates this year reflects increasing demand for credit as the
economy grows, not just concerns about inflation.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the case, he said, a revival of the global economy
will put much more pressure on interest rates than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The 1 percent increase in retail sales in May came after what
had appeared to be two anemic months. But with Friday's report, the
Commerce Department revised April sales upward to an increase of
0.4 percent from the initial report of a 0.1 percent. Retail sales
rose 0.1 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   The May increase was led by a 2.7 percent jump in automobile
sales, a 1.1 percent climb in sales of furniture and other home
furnishings, and an 0.8 percent rise in department store sales,
adjusted for seasonal, holiday and trading day differences. Over
the last 12 months, retail sales have risen 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On producer prices, the increase of 0.2 percent on finished
goods in May followed gains of 0.5 percent in April and 0.2 percent
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between May and April was the price of
energy. In April, when the price of oil shot up to over $18 a
barrel, prices for finished energy goods, like gasoline, jumped 5.1
percent. But last month, when crude oil prices dropped back to $17
a barrel, finished goods energy prices were unchanged. The gasoline
index dropped 2.7 percent after a record 29.1 percent increase, on
a seasonally adjusted basis, in April.
</P>
<P>
   The core PPI index for finished goods, which excludes energy and
food, shows a more restrained picture. It has risen 0.1 percent in
each of the last two months and through the first five months of
the year is unchanged at an annual rate. In the same period the
overall finished goods index is up at a 2 percent annual rate after
being unchanged in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lift in commodity prices and the revival in early stage
of processing does reflect that the global economy is on the
mend,'' said Berner of Morgan Stanley, ``and that is consistent
with inflation moving higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
