<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS &LR;      06-11 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO BLASTS GOP LEADERSHIP OVER GUN CONTROL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno accused House
Republican leaders Friday of undermining a Senate-passed
gun-control bill by shortening the time required for background
checks and changing the definition of a ``gun show'' to make it
easier for criminals and minors to buy weapons without checks.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual attack directly at the GOP leadership, Reno said
the House version of the bill scheduled for consideration Wednesday
would continue to allow guns to be sold without regulation at small
gun shows, flea markets and other venues. She said those outlets
traditionally have been prime shopping spots for criminals and some
teen-agers looking for no-hassle access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current House bill will not require background checks at
lots of events where large numbers of guns are sold, such as flea
markets,'' Reno told reporters at her weekly Justice Department
briefing. ``It doesn't matter to criminals if the event is called a
gun show or a flea market. If they can buy guns without a Brady
(background) check, they will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno also complained that the House measure would gut the Brady
law, which is due to expire this year, by replacing its
three-business day limit on checks with a 72-hour limit. Since most
gun show events are usually held on Fridays or weekends, she said,
the 72-hour proposal would hamper the ability of law enforcement
officials to access court and other government documents used to
determine if an individual has a prior record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting the amount of time won't really benefit law-abiding
buyers,'' Reno said. ``The vast majority ... are already able to
buy their guns almost immediately. But the House bill is sure going
to make it easier for criminals to buy guns on weekends when their
state court records are inaccessible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a gun-control measure last month that broadly
defined gun shows as events where large numbers of guns are sold by
licensed and unlicensed dealers, collectors and individuals. The
bill also extended the Brady law, which is due to expire this year,
to gun shows, applying the same three-business day approach to
completing background checks that is now required for store and
dealer purchases
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also required that safety locks or other devices
be sold with all guns, but that provision has been altered in the
House bill to allow sales without locks.
</P>
<P>
   Reno called the Senate legislation ``the common-sense'' approach
to strengthen current gun control laws. But she said the House
changes had ``undermined'' the intent of the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last month, the American people spoke and the Senate listened.
They heard the American people say they wanted to keep guns out of
the hands of criminals and kids,'' Renot said. ``I'm hopeful that
the House will also listen to the people of this country and pass a
bill that makes all Americans, and particularly our children,
safer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill passed with a small measure of bipartisan
support last month on a vote of 51-50, with Vice President Al Gore
casting the deciding vote.
</P>
<P>
   Its passage, in the wake of the tragic school shooting and
bombing incident in Littleton, Colo., followed a contentious and
embarrassing debate on the Senate floor in which Republicans were
roundly criticized by Democrats and the public for not taking a
tougher stand on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Senate bill reached the House, members on the
Judiciary Committee drew up their own version of the bill with
significant changes recommended by the National Rifle Association.
Although they denied that the NRA, which opposes the Senate bill,
had been allowed to write the House version, they later
acknowledged that its lobbyists did confer with members who were
drafting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of embracing the bill, a number of Republican
conservatives and moderates _ who hate it for different reasons _
have all vowed to vote against it, making it doubtful that
gun-control supporters will be able to muster enough votes to pass
any measure designed to make access to guns tougher.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill, also has announced that he
will not use his leadership position to help pass any gun-control
measure this year, although he supports the idea of strengthening
existing laws and raising the age limit for purchasing a gun from
18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's announcement stunned not only Democrats but many
members of his own party who had looked to him for support,
especially in light of comments he made only two weeks promising to
forge a common position among Republicans on the gun-control issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert got a letter Friday from the U.S. Conference of Mayors,
which urged him to work for swift passage of measures raising the
age limit for gun buyers and requiring background checks for buyers
at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
