<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-RUSSIA-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS RUMBLE INTO YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Repeats to correct slug . )   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Throughout the Balkans war, unpredictable,
nuclear-armed Russia has always been the X-factor, and Friday was
no different.
</P>
<P>
   By becoming the first foreign power to send in troops in
Yugoslavia since a peace deal suspended 79 days of NATO airstrikes,
Russia has rattled the alliance's long-awaited entrance into the
southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow's unexpected move to transfer several hundred
peacekeepers from Bosnia into adjacent Yugoslavia means much more
than being first. It is a signal that the Russians are determined
to play their own game in the resolution of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders have sought to portray Russia's diplomatic
backing for a peace plan approved by NATO as a sign that Moscow had
joined in the opposition to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian officials still say that NATO, not Milosevic, was
the aggressor. They say that NATO, as the guilty party in the war,
should not be allowed to command peacekeepers in Kosovo. Russia
wants its troops to take control of a sector in northeast Kosovo
where most of the ethnic Serbs in the region live. NATO rejects
that and says Russia can be part of a unified force under a NATO
commander.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after US and Russian officials in Moscow were unable to
hammer out an agreement on Russia's role in the peacekeepers'
command structure, Friday's move to send in troops looks like a
challenge to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders reacted with palpable surprise. British troops
near Kosovo were put on alert and US Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott turned his plane around to return to Moscow for
urgent talks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO later appeared to publicly accept assurances from Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov that the troops were not going into Kosovo
under a deal could be worked out. But a senior military official,
General Leonid Ivashov, said Russia reserved the right to make a
separate deal with Belgrade on where its troops will be stationed.
Russian news agencies reported that more troops were ready to
arrive in Yugoslavia soon.
</P>
<P>
   Splits and confusion are nothing new to Russian policy on the
Balkans. Most political parties have distanced themselves from the
peace plan, which was helped along greatly by Russia's own envoy,
Viktor Chernomyrdin. Parliament this week passed a resolution
accusing Chernomyrdin of betraying Russia's geopolitical interests.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris N. Yeltsin's comments Friday did not make clear
whether Ivanov or Ivashov was right, only that the Russian leader
still rejects putting his troops under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on television with Ivanov and a Russian general,
Yeltsin growled: ``We have done all we needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing NATO wants is Russian troops staking out their
own territory in Kosovo. But even if the Russians plan to
coordinate their movements with NATO, their presence in Yugoslavia
puts another crimp in the alliance's overall strategy.
</P>
<P>
   NATO merely suspended its airstrikes after Yugoslavia accepted a
peace plan that provides for Serbian troops and police to withdraw
from Kosovo. The alliance has held out the threat of resuming the
bombing if the Serbs play any tricks. The presence of even a small
contingent of Russian troops complicates that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Yugoslav troops do not complete the pullout from Kosovo,
will NATO be able to resume bombing with Russian troops in
Yugoslavia?,'' a commentator for NTV television asked.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Russia's move Friday may have caught Washington by
surprise, but it appeared to have been planned with the Serbs, who
gave the Russian troops a police escort.
</P>
<P>
   The troops came from among the 1,300 Russian peacekeepers have
been serving under the NATO-commanded SFOR force, a parallel NATO
officials frequently bring up when trying to convince the Russians
of their need to command KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian politicians and military officials are suspicious
about NATO's motives. Despite the assurances of the alliance
leaders, many Russians believe NATO will be unable, or unwilling,
to prevent the takeover of Kosovo by the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we even talk about Russian troops, we should ask what
the goal of these peacekeepers is,'' said Russian lawmaker Alexei
Arbatov, an expert on defense issues. ``If the goal is to keep
Kosovo a part of Serbia, to stop the violence and allow refugees to
return, then we do not need a heavily armed force like the one NATO
is putting in place. We need 50,000 lightly armed troops under the
United Nations to act as police.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the goal is to divide Serbia and allow the KLA to take
power, we should not be involved in this contingent,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
