<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELES-CALLGIRL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CLAIM TO NAB MAIN RIVAL OF `HOLLYWOOD MADAM'
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Six years after police here titillated the country
with the arrest of Heidi Fleiss, who became known as the Hollywood
Madam, the Los Angeles Police Department said Friday it had
arrested one of her main rivals, Jody Diane Gibson, known as
Babydol, and charged her with running a high-level international
prostitution ring.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Ms. Gibson had been running one of the largest
call-girl operations in Los Angeles since 1990, catering to
well-known Hollywood figures as well as the head of a major
corporation and a professional athlete, but they refused to release
names or say how many clients Ms. Gibson had.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Mike Felix said that Ms. Gibson, 41, was arrested on Tuesday
night at a hotel after she stepped into a trap set by undercover
officers. He added that she had been under investigation for about
10 months after the police received a tip from a woman who
complained she had been cheated out of some money after working for
Ms. Gibson. Ms. Gibson is free on $25,000 bail, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that Ms. Gibson had been charging fees of $500 to
$3,000 for the services of her prostitutes and that her clients
included men from Arizona, New York and Europe, among other places.
They said she employed 34 women. She operated a Web site, called
California Dreamin', which displayed photographs of more than 25
women, often scantily clad, some nude, from which clients could
choose.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gibson was charged with one count of pimping and pandering,
police said, but added that they expected to charge her with a
number of felony counts once the investigation was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Felix said that a search of her bags, her car and her home, in
the remote town of Palo Verde, Calif., near the Arizona border, had
turned up detailed log books with the names of her clients and
their particular interests, offering the prospect of a scandal on
the scale of Ms. Fleiss'.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gibson's mother and her public relations representative
expressed shock at the news of the arrest. A person in the office
of her publicity agent, Edward Lozzi, said Ms. Gibson had recently
recorded an album of dance songs and was about to release it and
begin a tour of Europe to promote it. A previous album of hers was
called ``Good Girls Go to Heaven, Bad Girls Go Everywhere.'' Her
new album was to have been called ``Right on Track.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gibson's mother, Tobe Gibson, reached at the talent agency
she operates in New York City, said that as far as she knew her
daughter was a singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter's never really told me what she does,'' Mrs.
Gibson said. ``She's been singing for quite a while. This all hit
me like a ton of bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her daughter called on Wednesday and they spoke
briefly. ``She said, `Don't worry,' '' Mrs. Gibson said. ``It never
dawned on me she would do something like this. She didn't tell me
anything more and I don't want to know more at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gibson said that her daughter was divorced and had been
living in Los Angeles for some time, trying to succeed in the
entertainment industry. Ms. Gibson grew up near Scarsdale, N.Y. The
person in the office of Lozzi, her publicity agent, refused to give
his name but said that Ms. Gibson had also done some acting. He
added that the fate of her second album was now unclear.
</P>
<P>
   People who knew her said Ms. Gibson cut quite a figure. Her
driver's license lists her as 5 foot 5 inches, with blond hair and
brown eyes. She drives a blue 1994 Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Felix, the police lieutenant, said she had moved her primary
residence to the distant desert community of Palo Verde, in a
modest home on a canal off the Colorado River, in an effort to
avoid detection by the police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
