<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-FOLK-FASHIONS-A     06-11 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-FOLK-FASHIONS-ART-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING TO INDIA FOR THE JOURNEY AND THE JEWELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 13)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virginia Witbeck did a mannequin spin to show off her coat, a
luminous garment of quartz-pink silk that she designed in India.
Part of a collection she was showing at the Upper East Side
apartment of a banker friend, it looked fit for a Mogul prince. And
why not? It was, after all, cut from the cloth of her fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, drawn by the image of a mythologized East and
spurred by wanderlust, Ms. Witbeck embarked on a personal passage
to India. The grail she sought, and ultimately found: the
semiprecious stones and vibrant textiles that now find their way
into the lavish coats, caftans, evening wear and jewelry she sells
to private clients and a few upscale stores like Linda Dresner in
New York. She spends as much as six months each year hopscotching
around India, from Jaipur to New Delhi to Bombay, stopping at small
villages in between. Along the way she shops and collaborates with
local tailors and gem cutters to fashion her wares. ``You can't
have a real job and do what I do _ it takes too much time,'' said
Ms. Witbeck, a former creative director for Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   But then, why would she want to? A lawyer's daughter who grew up
on a horse farm in upstate New York, Ms. Witbeck would be the first
to acknowledge that she is living a dream. She lodges in palaces
and tents across the subcontinent, ruled by a passion for work that
she calls ``a lifelong research project.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sentiments, and her vagabond way of life, are shared by a
small band of international quasi-bohemian elite who Ping-Pong from
Paris, New York or London to Bombay and New Delhi and back,
thirsting for adventure and fashion inspiration. Mostly in their
30s and holding arty inclinations, they tend to be the daughters of
affluent professionals who led quasi-nomadic lives themselves. Many
have abandoned conventional careers as fashion stylists, editors
and decorators to follow their bliss and dabble in fashion design.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Isabelle Fraysse, 36, is a contributing editor at
French Vogue whose father was a banker and whose mother, a
perfumer, routinely wore couture. Another, Muriel Brandolini, 39, a
French-Vietnamese stylist-turned-decorator who is married to an
Italian banker, shows her diaphanous hand-printed caftans and coats
in the elegant drawing room of her Upper East Side town house. A
third, Marie-Helene de Taillac, grew up in Lebanon _ her father
worked for Elf, the French oil company _ and now travels by jet
half a dozen times a year between Paris, her home, and Jaipur, the
source of the semiprecious stones in her jewelry designs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Taillac, 33, sold an apartment in London three years ago
and used the proceeds and a small inheritance from her godmother to
finance her first trip to Jaipur. ``When you travel as much as I
do,'' she said, ``you can adapt to almost anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-confessed dilettantes, these jet-set fashion wayfarers are
unfamiliar with cutting boards and pinking shears. Not that they
care. ``I'm not a fashion designer at all,'' Christina Gitti said
blithely. ``I studied industrial design,'' The head of her own
Milan-based company, Malatesta, Ms. Gitti, 31, now sells
block-printed sarongs and pashmina shawls to Bergdorf Goodman and
Calypso, a trend-setting purveyor of exotic trinkets and clothing
in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fraysse likewise makes no excuses for her lack of fashion
expertise. ``My education is in traveling,'' she said. But her
gadabout background, sophisticated eye and instinct for color and
line gained her entree into the rarefied world of style. It wasn't
long before vanguard London boutiques like the Cross began asking
her for the colorful bags and blanket-size shawls she got in Jaipur
and New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few of these women are actually designers,'' said Nicole
Fischelis, the fashion director of Saks Fifth Avenue, which carries
Mrs. Brandolini's caftans and exotic housewares. ``But sometimes
they are social, and they have good taste. They're exposed to a lot
of travel, and they often sell to women like themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They tend to run their businesses with an airy disregard for the
bottom line. ``I have no idea what I'm earning,'' confided Ms. de
Taillac, who designs about 100 pieces a year. At Barneys New York,
her designs fetch from $250 for a pair of fragile earrings to more
than $9,000 for a necklace. ``At the end of the day, I do this
because I enjoy it,'' she said. ``As long as the orders keep coming
in, I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   She and the others could not have chosen a more propitious
moment. Fashion has embraced exoticism, ornamentation and
high-voltage color as part of a continuing enthrallment with the
East, India in particular. That country seeped into fashion
consciousness several years ago, when designers like Dries van
Noten began spicing their collections with sari fabrics. But the
raj rage also stems in part from a nostalgia for the festive,
free-spirited 1960s, when Jacqueline Kennedy returned from India
laden with shimmering saris, sparking a new Mogul mania.
</P>
<P>
   A decade or so later, the designer and socialite Mary McFadden
ventured to Bombay to have extraordinary beadwork done. ``In those
days we saw a swelling of craftsmanship, creativity and
self-expression,'' recalled Jade Hobson Charnin, who visited Jaipur
and New Delhi more than 20 years ago as a fashion editor for Vogue.
Designers today have retraced the steps of a past generation partly
out of ``a yearning to restore to fashion its soul and
individualism,'' Ms. Charnin said.
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the force driving Ms. Fraysse, who
commissions her raw silk and linen caftans and dresses, glass
beads, hand-dyed leather albums and canvas bags in India, and sells
them under the ISI label to Barneys and Kirna Zabete, a
high-bohemian outpost that is to open on Greene Street next month.
``My designs are imperfect, but that is part of their beauty,'' she
said. ``These things have nothing to do with a mass market
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   India is once again, as it has been on and off for four decades,
a magnet for spiritually thirsty Westerners in search of the latest
yogi. But for most of these well-bred fashion gypsies, India is
less a spiritual Mecca than a giant bazaar, and a place to act out
their most colorful fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these women may be in love with the myth of India,''
suggested Sandy Dalal, a New York designer whose family is from
Bombay but whose own work refers only obliquely to his roots.
``They are romanced about the place, and they go. Most of them are
genuinely devoted to their craft, but a few just want a joy ride.''
Not that he begrudges them that. ``Hey, if you can afford a joy
ride through all of India, do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
