<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-JUDGMENT-TEXAS     06-11 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JUDGMENT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FAMILY MAY NOT BE ABLE TO COLLECT $234 MILLION JUDGMENT
AGAINST RUSSIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ED ASHER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ International protocol might prevent a Texas family
from collecting a $234 million judgment it won against the Russian
Federation, an attorney who represented the Russians said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government could appeal and claim it was never
properly served with a lawsuit filed by Houston attorney Lee
Alexander Magness and his mother and aunt, Houston attorney Brendan
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Or Russia might simply ignore the judgment and wait to see what
happens, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with what is really a technical area of the law
and there is some fine hair splitting,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the threshold issue, since you're dealing in the
international realm, is whether they (the family) have followed
proper procedures and protocol to serve the lawsuit on the
defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of proper service could force another hearing on the
matter, either in federal district court in Houston or the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who no longer represents the Russian government, said he
did not know what hoops the Magnesses would have had to jump
through to properly serve Russia with notice of their lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly don't know,'' he said. ``The complication is whenever
you're dealing in the international arena, as we are here, where
you have parties who are truly foreign citizens, there are various
treaties and conventions and specific statutes, all of which
complicate the equation that dictates how, when and where these
parties are to be served.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what was done'' in the Magness case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Hittner this week awarded the
multimillion-dollar judgment in compensation for the Russian
government's seizure of Magness family ancestral property in St.
Petersburg, Russia, in 1917 and again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Magness' mother, Nina Schroder Magness, and aunt, Agnes Schroder
Atkins, are daughters of Johann Schroder, who in 1917 owned three
valuable properties in St. Petersburg: the K.M. Schroder Piano
Factory, now known as the Red October Factory; a retail shopping
center; and a 30-room downtown mansion, Hittner said in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   All were seized by the communists after the Bolshevik revolution
in 1917, he said. The family claimed the property then was worth
more than 16 million gold rubles, or about $162 million.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of communism, the Russian government initiated
reforms, including laws that prohibited the nationalization or
expropriation of foreign investments, Hittner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Magnesses traveled to St. Petersburg in 1994 to reclaim the
family fortune. After presenting historic documents showing they
were Schroder's heirs, the family was assured by Russian
authorities that they would receive titles to the property,
Hittner's ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Magness also purchased two antique Schroder pianos, one
built in 1889 and the other in 1910, according to the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Later in 1994, the Russian Federation claimed that all of the
properties were ``national treasures'' or ``historical'' in nature
and expropriated them, Hittner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Magness family sued in 1997 to stop the Russian Ministry of
Culture from removing a touring $100 million Romanov jewel exhibit
from Houston. The family asked the judge to hold the jewels as
collateral, which he refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   The jewels belonged to Russia's ruling Romanov family,
overthrown by the communists.
</P>
<P>
   After Hittner refused to stop the tour, the Magness family
pressed on with its lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Embassy spokesman Mikhail A. Shurgalin and Tim
Dickinson, a Washington, D.C., attorney who also represented
Russia, could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The award increases by an estimated $31,000 in interest per day,
and Magness family attorney Daniel B. Nelson believes there is a
way for his clients to collect.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has declined to say what his strategy will be.
</P>
<P>
   Hittner also awarded Lee Magness $400,000 for the two pianos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
