<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-FOLK-FASHIONS-$     06-11 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-FOLK-FASHIONS-$ADV13-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Charnin compares the current generation of entrepreneurs to
an earlier wave of young plutocrats, including Ms. McFadden, who
journeyed to India in the 70s and also brought back clothes and
goods for their friends and select stores. ``Those women had the
finances and the wherewithal to get around,'' she said. ``If you
were just some hippie girl, you might have been swallowed up by the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   No such fate is likely to befall Ms. Fraysse, who is nothing if
not resourceful. She travels from village to village in a beat-up
Ambassador, swathed to the ankles in traditional Indian garb and
wearing a scarf ``to cover the parts that shouldn't be seen,'' she
said. She spends about $12 nightly on lodging. She works with
village craftsmen, sitting side by side with them in sweltering
tin-roofed sheds. She communicates, when all else fails, by waving
her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I want the men to loosen up a certain pattern, I trace
the shape of a mountain or some other soft image,'' she said. ``I
just try to be as visually expressive as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Her dedication is fed partly by the noblesse oblige that dates
to colonial times. ``Designing in India traditionally has been a
lady's occupation,'' said Richard Martin, curator of the Costume
Institute at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. ``It has a certain
do-goodism about it: the ability to serve a social purpose and
esthetic commerce at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fraysse works with Datskar, an association of self-employed
women whom she commissions to do embroidery. She said that the
organization enables women to earn good wages and gain self-esteem.
``I'm given so much on a human level every day that I'm in India
that I find it only normal to put something back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Francesca Amfitheatrof, a London-based designer who works in
India, said, ``Setting up a workshop and teaching people what I do
_ I think about doing that at some point.'' But Ms. Amfitheatrof,
who designed the jewelry for Fendi's fall 1999 collection and sells
her gold rings and pastel-colored beads to about 25 stores
worldwide, isn't entirely an altruist. As a girl, she lived like a
nomad, following her father, Erik Amfitheatrof, a foreign
correspondent for Time magazine, to such far-flung destinations as
Moscow and Rome. ``My upbringing was so adventurous, I would like
my adulthood to be as incredible, but in a different way,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Amfitheatrof, 30, travels to Jaipur three or four times a
year, subsidizing her expeditions with her earnings _ a sum that
she put, somewhat vaguely, at under $1 million a year. But she said
that profits are secondary to the thrill she gets from working with
gem cutters at the fabled Gem Palace in Jaipur, India's largest
gemstone workshop and market, which has drawn shoppers like Goldie
Hawn and Diana, the Princess of Wales. Sitting on the floor at the
workmen's elbow, Ms. Amfitheatrof oversees the execution of her
designs, including gold rings and unfaceted tourmaline, citrine and
smoky topaz stones that she turns into luminous beads.
</P>
<P>
   The work tends to be improvised. ``There are about 20 cutters,
and they have this huge chest of drawers full of rocks,'' she said.
``The head of the workshop will pull one out, hold it to the light
and say, `You can get this or that shape out of it,' and the cutter
starts cutting it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a little man comes and takes the stones away. He cycles
20 kilometers to his workshop and drills them, and brings them
back. Some have been drilled properly, and some haven't. That's
part of the charm, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Taillac, another Gem Palace devotee, works with peridot,
bright turquoise and other pastel stones. ``I might spend an entire
day making nothing but pink necklaces,'' she said. ``I think I'm
quite eccentric at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Westerners would think of running a business as casually and
erratically as Ms. de Taillac and her fellow travelers. Nor would
most willingly subsist on an income that scarcely covers their
expenses. Ms. Fraysse said she put all her earnings back into her
business. ``Everything I have and own is in what I make,'' she
said. ``This bank account of mine, sometimes it's full, sometimes
it's empty. I guess I'm running at a risk, but I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   When monsoons, unreliable transportation and an unpredictable
labor force threaten to make hash of production and delivery
schedules, these entrepreneurs cultivate a kind of balmy fatalism.
Ms. de Taillac laughed at the memory of the day she charged into
work, desperate to meet a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``My craftsmen had already arrived, but not one of them lifted a
finger,'' she recalled. ``They just sat there all day long, saying
prayers for their tools. I had learned too late that it was a
special holiday. Patience is key _ that, and a readiness for the
unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``In India, everything is possible. I could have my samples made
in two days, or not at all. That's what makes this life so
interesting and challenging. What doesn't get made doesn't get
made. I don't get upset anymore. Why should I? I have only myself
to look after.''
</P>
</TEXT>
