<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-LIQUOR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lax liquor law slips by Alabama legislators
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alabama's got a tempest in a beer can.
</P>
<P>
   Putting its trust in a lobbyist at the 11th hour of its annual
session, the Alabama Legislature passed a bill that would permit
statewide Sunday alcohol sales in wet counties.
</P>
<P>
   Advocating Sunday sales wasn't his intent, said state Rep. J.E.
Turner, a Republican who represents Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Tom Butler (D-Madison) says Turner
apparently was duped by a lobbyist. Turner wanted to allow
19-year-old restaurant servers to be able to deliver alcoholic
drinks when ordered with a meal.
</P>
<P>
   But a subtle change in another part of the bill opened the door
for Sunday sales in counties that already permit alcohol sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the existing law, if you don't have a local law
authorizing the sale, you can't sell it'' on Sunday, said Jerry
Bassett, director of legal reference for the Alabama Legislature.
``Under the bill as it's currently before the governor, you can
sell it unless it's prohibited by local law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just changed it 180 degrees. The language is very clear.
It doesn't take an attorney to read it to see the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he ``didn't intend for it to do that. I take the
position that it doesn't do that. I guess it does but I had no
intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama _ like Georgia and many other Deep South states _ lets
counties and cities determine their Sunday alcohol policies.
Mississippi prohibits Sunday sales except at resorts.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, only the largest metropolitan areas _ Montgomery,
Birmingham, Mobile and Huntsville _ permit Sunday sales.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
