<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father's Day comes early for Earnhardts
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Father's Day came early for the Earnhardts
Friday at Michigan Speedway. Dale Earnhardt and his son, Dale Jr.,
raced side-by-side on the final lap, bumping fenders twice, before
dad pulled away to win his third straight IROC (International Race
of Champions) event.
</P>
<P>
   Twice before they'd been on the same track, but the race in
Japan last winter was an exhibition and three weeks ago at
Charlotte, Little E quickly fell a lap down in his Winston Cup
debut.
</P>
<P>
   This one was for real, even if it was in a 50-lap race matching
12 drivers from different types of racing in similarly-prepared
cars. Father beat son by .007 seconds. Or by a gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the most unique, neatest, exciting, fun and
just everything-rolled-into-one best times I've ever had in
racing,'' papa Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Was there a chance you might let the kid win, someone asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Earnhardt said. ``He's going to have to earn
everything just like dad did. And I don't think he would want me to
let him win. If he went home and everybody said, `well, your dad
let you win,' that wouldn't be cool. Of course, they're going to
say, `well, your son let you win.' Bull. Look at the side of that
race car.''
</P>
<P>
   They bumped fenders at the finish. ``I came off the (fourth)
corner and he hit me pretty hard, like `you ain't gonna win it,' ''
Little E said. ``I knew if I tried to pass him and didn't make it,
I was going to get a chewing out.''
</P>
<P>
   No IRL for Petty
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be just a little fun ride in an Indy Racing
League car but Friday Kyle Petty had to do some rumor control. He
denied he was ever going to drive one of the open-wheel cars in the
July IRL race at Atlanta Motor Speedway as has been rumored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were set up to test at Road Atlanta with the No. 43 car
(John Andretti's) and, ifwe can get it read to go, the No. 44 car
(Petty's) this coming Monday preparing for Sears Point,'' Petty
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry Lingner, who's a friend of mine, is a part owner of that
Panter Racing (IRL team) and they were going to test at Atlanta
Motor Speedway on Tuesday. He asked me if I'd be interested in
staying over and driving the Indy car for a few laps. I was going
to do a few laps for fun, see what it was like, tell them thanks
and head back home. It was just a fun deal, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
