<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-BOEING12-COX     06-11 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BOEING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta postpones deliveries of Boeing 777s
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Blaming excessive pilot pay demands, Delta Air Lines
said Friday it is postponing all further deliveries of Boeing 777
widebodies and will sell or lease the two it's already flying after
the summer season.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows five months of fruitless negotiations over pay
rates for the giant jet, considered the industry's premier
international aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unfortunate development for our company,'' Chief
Executive Leo Mullin said in an employee memo. ``The 777 is a
prestigious aircraft flown by our competitors and popular with the
traveling public.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Delta, currently offering to pay 777 captains $239 an
hour, will continue talks with the pilot union, which is seeking
$319 an hour. The airline will renegotiate delivery dates with
Boeing ``if and when an agreement is ratified,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Under its original plan, Delta would have had 11 of the jets by
next summer, adding them to an international fleet now consisting
of smaller MD-11s and 767s. It was scheduled to get another two
777s in 2002, with options to buy 20 more after that.
</P>
<P>
   Even if deliveries are rescheduled, Mullin said, it would be
``at a substantially reduced pace than we had anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Line Pilots Association, which represents Delta's 9,000
pilots, suggested the real motive for Friday's action is concern
over slowing traffic growth on trans-Atlantic routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Delta pilots may be a convenient scapegoat for
management's fleet decisions, there are marketplace realities that
must be considered,'' the union said, adding ``airline analysts
have been noting for months that traffic is softening over the
North Atlantic while capacity is increasing and revenues are
down.''
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman rebutted that claim, saying, ``Airlines don't
make decisions about aircraft of this magnitude on short-term
market demand.''
</P>
<P>
   ALPA also said the airline ``has shown little interest in or
commitment to reaching an agreement with pilots.'' It said Delta
``has spent the majority of the negotiating period issuing
ultimatums about the 777 fleet'' rather than bargaining in good
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it was forced to take the action now because of
scheduling issues. The pilot union has vowed to invoke its
contractual right to stop flying 777s on Nov. 1, six months after
the first plane entered use, unless a ratified pay rate is in
place.
</P>
<P>
   That creates too much uncertainty for the airline to add the
plane to fall and winter schedules, now being formulated, Delta
said. If the airline continued to take 777 deliveries, it said,
such a grounding would cause service disruptions and cost millions
as the planes sat unused.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side argues that 777 pilots should be the best-paid at
Delta, owing to the plane's newness and size.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said its offer would pay 777 captains $223,385 in base
salary, based on a typical 78-hour month. That's 5 percent above
the existing rate at American and 25 percent above the rate at
United. The pilot union's demand equates to $298,546, or nearly 40
percent above American's rates, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   ALPA has said its pay demand is calculated on the 777's
``productivity and efficiency.'' But Delta contends it wouldn't get
an adequate return on investment in the $108 million jets at the
rates ALPA is demanding.
</P>
<P>
   While only a few dozen pilots would be assigned to the planes
over the next several months, the ripple effect from their
promotions would have pushed many others into higher-paying
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ALPA cut its demand about 8 percent last month, while Delta has
raised its initial offer only 1 percent since February. It also had
announced a first wave of order deferrals in April, when it
indefinitely postponed four deliveries scheduled for early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side had made any new proposals in the last two
negotiating sessions. Another session is scheduled Tuesday, and a
breakthrough might yet allow Delta to salvage the purchase
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But if the impasse continues through the summer, 777 pay could
be incorporated into new contract talks that start in September. In
addition, the airline faces impending talks on another new
airplane, the 767-400, scheduled for delivery about a year from
now.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber analyst Samuel Buttrick said the lack of 777s hurts
Delta's service reputation, especially among frequent
trans-Atlantic fliers with a choice between carriers that fly the
plane and those that don't.
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted a deal will eventually be reached and the
orders will be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta wants to fly the triple-seven,'' Buttrick said. ``Pilots
want to fly it. Customers want to fly it. It will be flown. It's a
matter of when.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta's stock closed down 25 cents Friday at $57.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
