<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     06-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMS CRY FOUL OVER DELAY IN SENATE ACTION ON JUDICIAL NOMINATIONS 
BEST BUDDIES? 
NOW HEAR THIS 
ERODING COASTAL LAW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) (rk) 
 By CARL HULSE AND SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With 24 high-priority vacancies on the federal
bench, Senate Democrats say Republicans are playing politics with
judicial nominations, holding them hostage to score some points or
move their own picks forward.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, there are four so-called judicial emergencies,
vacancies that have existed for at least 18 months. The Southern
District of Alabama, the Middle District of Florida, the Northern
District of Georgia and the Eastern District of North Carolina each
have one such vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Another 18 judicial nominations are also pending before the
Senate Judiciary Committee, but those are for more recent
vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of North Carolina are entitled to a federal court
system that isn't clogged with backlogs that delay justice in
criminal and civil cases,'' said Sen. John Edwards, a freshman
Democrat from North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   While Edwards did not criticize his Republican colleagues, other
Democrats are angry with Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, saying the GOP
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee is stalling judicial
nominations because the White House won't nominate a conservative
Republican friend to the federal bench in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans counter that in many cases, the White House has been
slow to nominate candidates to the bench. A spokeswoman for the
Judiciary Committee said that a hearing has been set for Wednesday
to consider some nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina vacancy has a unique wrinkle. By tradition,
both senators must sign off on a home-state nominee before the
Judiciary Committee will act on the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Jesse Helms is, so far, withholding his support
for Judge J. Rich Leonard of Raleigh, nominated in March to served
on the Eastern District. An aide to Helms said the senator has
``nothing against'' Leonard, but Helms wants to shift a federal
judgeship from eastern North Carolina to the Western District in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Said Edwards: ``That would simply be robbing Peter to pay
Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST BUDDIES?
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Louisiana's Republican leaders were campaigning
against him. Now, they're throwing parties for him on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The newest member of Congress, Republican David Vitter of
Louisiana, found out that there's nothing like victory to foster
friendships. Vitter just won election to Louisiana's 1st
Congressional District, which was vacated by the retirement of Bob
Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Billy Tauzin, dean of the Louisiana delegation,
threw a reception for Vitter his first day in office despite the
fact that Tauzin and most of the state's Republican establishment
supported Vitter's Republican opponent, David Treen, in Louisiana's
unique open primary.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin laughed off the irony. ``That's our history,'' Tauzin
said with a smile. ``When the election's over, it's over. Now we
close ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW HEAR THIS
</P>
<P>
   With a meager six-vote margin in the House, Republicans simply
can't afford too much dissension within their ranks if they expect
to accomplish much this year.
</P>
<P>
   So House Speaker Dennis Hastert met with GOP members recently to
tell them that while debate is welcome and healthy, they better
fall in line once it's time to vote. Many conservatives had been
blocking appropriations bills, complaining that Republicans are
violating their own once-sacred spending limits. Moderates,
meanwhile, are unhappy with their party leaders for weakening
proposed gun safety legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who is close to Hastert, applauded the
speaker's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members of our conference understand that to get anything
done, we need to stick together as a team,'' Goss said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sue Myrick, R-N.C., who sided with conservatives during the
recent budget dispute, agreed. But she warned that Republicans must
not sacrifice their fiscal principles for the sake of expediency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, we're just like everybody else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ERODING COASTAL LAW
</P>
<P>
   An environmental group that monitors coastal issues accused
House Republicans of watering down a measure intended to slow
beachfront development.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of strengthening the coastal barrier resources system,
critics said an emerging measure that renews the program removes
property from the system, making the land eligible for federal
flood insurance and other government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers intent on turning coastlines into condos are lining
up to strip acres from the system,'' said Steve Ellis of Coast
Alliance, who complained Congress has been steadily eroding the
system's holdings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal adopted by the House Resources Committee would
remove parcels on Cape Hatteras, N.C., and Upper Captiva Island,
Fla., from the system. Backers of the bill said the land is already
developed and should never have been included in the program in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse report from the Washington Bureau
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 1941EDT &QL; 
