<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meeting in New Orleans, mayors push tough gun laws
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Congress should pass legislation requiring much
tighter restrictions on guns, including raising the age for
possession of a gun from 18 to 21 and requiring background checks
for buyers at gun shows, the U.S. Conference of Mayors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors proposed the legislation _ which goes further than
any bills being considered by Congress _ in a letter to U.S. House
Speaker Dennis Hastert. The letter will be signed by the 300 mayors
attending the conference here and sent to Washington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying to Republicans and Democrats that we want a
meaningful bill with teeth,'' said New Orleans Mayor Marc Morial.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been debating bills designed to restrict access to
guns and increase gun safety in response to the fatal shootings at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., in April.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed by the Senate is stuck in the House because it is
seen by many legislators as too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors' letter asks Congress to approve legislation that:
</P>
<P>
   _ allows a maximum of one gun purchase a month;
</P>
<P>
   _ reinstates the ``cooling-off'' period between the time of
purchase and possession of a gun;
</P>
<P>
   _ provides ``substantial'' funding for the development of
personalized ``smart'' guns, which only the owner can use;
</P>
<P>
   _ requires a background check for purchases at gun shows;
</P>
<P>
   _ raises the age for purchasing and owning a gun to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Pressuring Congress is one part of what Morial called a
``multi-front movement'' to reduce the incidence of gun-related
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Another important element is litigation: Twenty cities,
including Atlanta and New Orleans, have filed lawsuits against the
gun manufacturers and sellers. The suits allege that the industry
failed to make a safe product by not putting locks and other safety
devices on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Several states, including Georgia and Louisiana, have passed
laws making such lawsuits illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Morial said he is not worried about his city's suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bill that seeks to nullify an already-filed lawsuit is
headed for a swift constitutional death in the courts,'' he said.
``We will not be deterred.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayors _ some Republicans, some Democrats _ expressed
frustration and even outrage at the Republican-controlled Congress
for hesitating to pass stricter gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ridiculous,'' said Mayor Scott King of Gary, Ind. ``I
have buried a 2-year-old and I have buried a police officer and I
watch maimed and crippled people every day. Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
