<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CARE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE workers prepare to enter Kosovo
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A five-person team of CARE workers may enter Kosovo as
early as Sunday to assess the needs and dangers in the bombed and
burned-out Yugoslav province, and to determine the best way to help
refugees returning from other countries as well as Kosovars who
have been hiding in the hills with little to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Many challenges await relief workers entering the province _ the
danger of land mines and unexploded bombs, a lack of knowledge
about the number and the condition of internally displaced
Kosovars, and uncertainty over whether Kosovars now in refugee
camps will return in an organized fashion or a mad rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rapidly unfolding situation that will undoubtedly
take unexpected twists and turns,'' said Peter Bell, the president
of Atlanta-based CARE USA.
</P>
<P>
   CARE expects to be providing aid to 150,000 people in its first
month of operation in Kosovo, and the number may swell to 250,000
within a couple of months after that, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   For the purpose of organizing the delivery of humanitarian aid,
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees has divided Kosovo into
seven sectors. CARE will operate in the Urosevac area in the
southeastern part of the province, adjacent to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Glocker, a spokesman for CARE USA, said six different
CARE organizations will participate in the effort _ those from
Canada, Austria, the United Kingdom, Australia, Germany, and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of the different organizations are coordinated by
Brussels-based CARE International, a confederation of all 10
national CARE organizations. CARE International has named Marge
Tsitouris, a CARE USA official based in Atlanta, Balkans
coordinator for the international effort; the different national
CARE operations will report to her in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   CARE's immediate priority, Bell said, is to acquire the
necessary equipment _ trucks, fork lifts, computers, and the like _
to run what he called ``a fairly complex logistical operation.''
Aid workers' initial efforts will be to provide the refugees with
food, sanitation, temporary shelter such as tents, and building
materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE's preference will be to house people in tents next to their
damaged houses rather than to create new camps inside the province,
though anything is possible once the situation is assessed, said
Robert Macpherson, a CARE USA official.
</P>
<P>
   Macpherson, a retired colonel with 25 years service in the
Marines, plans to leave Atlanta Monday for Macedonia. He will lead
a team of about 25 people into Kosovo next week to further assess
the dangers _ and to begin setting up the relief operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to assess this thing to death,'' Macpherson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Macpherson said he is worried not only about land mines, but
about unexploded bombs, thousands of which he assumes are lying
about, and the possibility of numerous wells having been poisoned
as part of the campaign against the Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Macpherson was in Kosovo before the bombing began, and he said
the province's infrastructure then was very good. But his team will
have to assess how badly roads and bridges have been damaged, and
how difficult it is now to move equipment and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said that CARE estimates it will need $2.5 million to pay
for the first two months of the operation, excluding food and
supplies. So far the organization has designated $700,000 of the
$3.8 million it received for the Balkan crisis from the American
public _ individuals, foundations, and corporations _ for
operations in Kosovo itself. And the CARE board has approved using
and additional $800,000 from an emergency fund. But that still
leaves the organization $1 million short for the moment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
