<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-WELLS-$ADV13-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIRTHDAY PARTY GOES INTO EXTRA INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 13)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as a birthday party for the former Yankee pitcher David
Wells and his best friend, the restaurateur Noel Ashman, was coming
into full swing at Veruka on Wednesday night, the guests of honor
were nowhere near the SoHo nightspot. They were stuck in Flushing,
Queens, awaiting the outcome of a deadlocked baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, pitching for the Toronto Blue Jays, was a strike away
from closing out a 3-0 victory against the New York Mets when his
birthday went south. The home team rallied, sending the game into
extra innings. Ashman, Veruka's owner, grew more frantic in his
field-level seat at Shea Stadium. He phoned Wass, his doorman, and
went over the guest list, making sure that VIP's who had RSVP'd,
like Penny Marshall and Sarah Jessica Parker, would get in and
dictating the names of those who would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wanted to torture me, this would be a good way to
do it,'' he said. ``You're having this great birthday party and you
can't even get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The party marked a return to New York nightlife for Wells, who
during his Yankee years was known for his 91-mile-an-hour pitching
heat and faster barroom-brawling social life. They look like
unlikely buddies. Wells, a towering, 250-pounder from San Diego, is
a hard drinker with a passion for Harleys, Babe Ruth memorabilia
and tattoos of his children's faces. Ashman is a soft-spoken,
boyish 5-foot-9 Upper East Sider. He played a Henry Higgins role,
fine-tuning the rambunctious athlete's taste for the high life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to all the wrong places,'' said Ashman, who
turned Wells from stripper bars to the club demimonde of models,
rock stars and Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   By 11:15, Ashman was pacing the Diamond Club bar in his black
suede Adidas, keeping an eye on the game and his ear to his Nokia.
``Lorne Michaels is there,'' he said with frustration. ``Ione Skye,
Alex Von Furstenberg, Shoshanna Lonstein, Donovan Leitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaning on the bar, he relayed the play-by-play of his agonizing
split-screen night. At Veruka, on Broome Street, Samantha Ronson's
band was making its rocking debut in the downstairs room. At Shea,
neither team could buy a hit. Fashion models were blowing
over-the-phone kisses to Ashman. In the cheesy Mets bar, the
televisions were on the fritz.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:15 a.m., when the Mets scored at last in the bottom of the
14th, breaking the tie, Blue Jay wives and friends traded relieved
high-fives. ``Kato Kaelin's there?'' Ashman said into the phone.
They cheered when Wells, having skipped his press interviews,
arrived at the Diamond Club in a black T-shirt and khakis, his
short, thinning hair gelled into a spiky crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pitched a great game, Dave,'' Ashman said consolingly in
the stretch limo speeding toward Manhattan. Wells grimaced, upset
about his blown shutout and about being a straggler at his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the last of the Mohicans,'' he grumbled. Crossing the
Williamsburg Bridge, Ashman gave instructions via Nokia to have a
bottle of Ketel One vodka and Wells' favorite heavy metal ready.
``Play AC/DC,'' he instructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, play Bob Marley,'' Wells said unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the crush at Veruka after 1 a.m., the birthday boys
squeezed into their VIP booth, greeting Michaels and other friends
who had waited to say hello before saying goodbye. Von Furstenberg
rushed over for a hug before heading home. By all accounts, the
party had peaked an hour earlier, but Wells helped keep it alive
until dawn.
</P>
<P>
   A yardlong white birthday cake floated into view. Wells, who has
turned 36, and Ashman, soon to be 29, leaned forward to blow out
the candles. Then Wells took a swig of his screwdriver and started
playing air drums to ``Highway to Hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
