<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon wins pole in Michigan
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ A ``trying year'' for Jeff Gordon got a little
bit better Friday at Michigan Speedway. He won the pole for
Sunday's KMart 400 with a track-record lap of 186.945 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It's Gordon's 27th career Winston Cup pole, fourth this season
and second straight at the two-mile track. He'll start up front
with some surprising running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan had a season-best qualifying run, 186.712 mph, and
will start on the outside pole. Mark Martin and Ken Schrader were
third and fourth, respectively, and Bill Elliott ripped off his
best qualifying effort of the year (186.543 mph) to start fifth.
</P>
<P>
   What Gordon considers a trying year would delight the majority
of Cup drivers: three wins, seven top fives, sixth in the points
race and a $1 million bonus for winning one of the Winston No Bull
5 events.
</P>
<P>
   But the standards of a three-time Winston Cup champion are
understandably higher than the majority. He's also experienced some
un-Gordonlike calamaties: four DNFs (did not finish), five finishes
of 31st or worse, the first injury crash of his career at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely been a trying year for us a little bit,''
Gordon said. ``When you have the type of success we've had the last
few years there's a lot of pressure on you to live up to those
expectations. We came out of the box in Daytona with an awesome win
and said, man, we're going to start off where we left off. Well,
that quickly turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned around with a succession of what Gordon calls ``kind
of crazy things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A blown motor, cut tires, power steering pump seal go out,
things that rarely happened to us the last few years are happening
to us this year,'' Gordon said. ``It's just the way racing goes.
When you have the type of year we had last year, when it seemed
like we couldn't do anything wrong, you know that those times are
going to come back and they certainly have.''
</P>
<P>
   Another crazy thing happened last week at Dover. Gordon was
leading with six laps to go but had to pit for fuel and lost to
Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   And while Gordon believes that things happen for a reason (``If
it's our year to win the championship, then things will start going
our way'') he also realizes his team probably can't afford another
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically have no more opportunities left to have problems
and the other guys will have to have a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When: 1 p.m. EDT, Sunday
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Michigan Speedway
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending champion: Mark Martin
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: CBS
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
