<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stanley Cup finals: 'It's a war'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ What was expected to be a Stanley Cup final
short on goals and long on yawns at the blue line has been
saturated with threats, mudslinging and injury reports seemingly
put out by the secret service.
</P>
<P>
   Well. Couldn't hurt the TV ratings.
</P>
<P>
   When Dallas and Buffalo resume the Stanley Cup finals this
evening, with the series tied at one game each, the Stars may be
without their best player, center Mike Modano. It's also possible
Modano will start. It's also possible his next game will be in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Modano either did or didn't suffer a fractured left wrist when
he was crunched into the boards by the Sabres' Jay McKee in the
third period of Dallas's 4-2 win Thursday night. Dallas coach Ken
Hitchcock said only that his player's wrist was ``jammed,'' and
that his status was day-to-day. He would not comment when asked if
there was a fracture, as reported by ESPN, and NHL spokesman Frank
Brown said Hitchcock, ``has fulfilled his obligation'' in
disclosing the injury, even if the disclosure was somewhat vague.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the worst-case scenario has Modano out for seven
to 10 days, which could be the duration of the finals, but added,
``We think he's a player'' tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Now it gets interesting. The Sabres, upset because they beleive
the Stars have been taking intentional runs at goalie Dominik
Hasek, declared ``open season'' (coach Lindy Ruff's words) on
Dallas goalie Ed Belfour. At least one Buffalo player also
indicated Modano _ specifically, his left wrist _ would be targeted
if he does play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd be foolish not to,'' center Michael Peca said.
``I don't think we'd have anybody take a two-hand chop. But you
want to make sure you're physical with him. Maybe you bump him.
Certainly if there's a weakness, you want to exploit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano's response: ``Whether I'm hurt or not, I'm still
targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's threat: ``Mike's our best player. If they go after
our best player, we'll go after their best player. Tit for tat.
Their best player is Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where Ruff picks it up. He said he ``wouldn't want'' his
players taking an intentional run at Belfour, then made a U-turn:
``We're talking about the big prize. You do what you have to do to
win. Hitch is going to be the same way. What's fair? Fair is the
weather in Buffalo in March or April.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Our team will protect our goaltender in the same way
they're going to protect theirs. But if they take liberties, I
won't be able to control my players. Right now it's an eye for an
eye. It's a war. You do anything to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock returns: ``That's good. Eddie can take care of
himself. He's a tough guy. And if we get going exchanging
goaltenders, we've got lots of good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   McKee chimes in: ``We're going to drive the net hard. If we feel
guys are intentionally running over Dominic, I guess we'll drive
the net harder and if we get hauled down we'll end up going through
Belfour.''
</P>
<P>
   If Modano doesn't play, he likely will be replaced on the Stars'
top line by Tony Hrkac, who would center Brett Hull and Jere
Lehtenin. ``The thing we can't do is let down if Modano's not
there,'' Peca said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   STANLEY CUP FINALS SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO 1, DALLAS 1
</P>
<P>
   Game 1: Sabres 3, Stars 2 OT
</P>
<P>
   Game 2: Stars 4, Sabres 2
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: at Buffalo, 8 p.m., ESPN
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: at Buffalo, 8 p.m., ESPN
</P>
<P>
   Game 5: June 17, at Dallas, 8 p.m. , Fox
</P>
<P>
   Game 6: June 19: at Buffalo, 8 p.m. , ESPN
</P>
<P>
   Game 7: June 22: at Dallas, 8 p.m. , Fox
</P>
<P>
   - if necessary
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
