<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ALL-STAR TICKET SCAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buyer beware. That's the message coming from those people who
think they have deals to get tickets for the Major League All-Star
Game at Fenway Park in July.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people around here were scammed on tickets when the
Patriots made their last Super Bowl trip, and more will get skunked
on the All-Star Game. A friend told me Friday that a business
associate just paid $10,000 for four tickets. I told him that was
interesting, since the tickets haven't been issued yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been told that tickets are selling on the Internet for
$3,000 and $4,000 each,'' said Kevin Shea of the Red Sox. ``We want
to point out that it is illegal to re-sell an All-Star Game ticket.
The only tickets around here are going to season ticket-holders,
and they are not supposed to be resold.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is: Don't give anyone money in advance for the
tickets, or you may never see the money again. There has never been
a ticket as hard to get as this All-Star ticket. Imagine, the face
value of the ticket is $150 for a box seat, $100 for the
grandstand, and $50 for the bleachers, and people are ready to
spend at least 25 times that much.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, a Boston businessman called and said he and some
friends had a chance to by six tickets to the Super Bowl for $1,500
from a contact in Ohio. The Ohio seller claimed to have a
connection to an NFL assistant coach. I called the team, and the
coach said he had never heard of the seller and certainly wasn't
going to get him Super Bowl tickets. The whole thing was a sting.
The Ohio guy wanted the check in November, but the tickets weren't
even going to be distributed until January. No one has All-Star
Game tickets yet. Not even the Red Sox. And no one can guarantee
anything until the tickets are in hand. Last year, the Red Sox
pulled the season tickets of some fans when it was discovered they
were selling some of their tickets. They will do the same to any
ticket-holder who is found selling the All-Star Game tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino has been appointed to a new committee
to study point scoring in the NBA by commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stern is very concerned and upset by what is happening,'' said
Pitino, who will serve with a dozen other league coaches, general
managers, and owners to find a way to get the game back to higher
scoring levels. ``He wants the games to go back to both teams
scoring more than 100 points each. To get that, I think we have to
develop some defensive guidelines. Players are getting away with
murder on defense, and this is detroying the flow of the offense
and the ability to score points. The game has become too physical.
Even on the most simple play, like a pick and roll, the defensive
player is just using his forearm to push the offensive player
around. This has all slowed the game down and made it a halfcourt
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as fast, or exciting to watch, as a game with more
speed and plays in the open court. When I coached the Knicks, we
averaged 117 points a game, and 28 or 29 (fast-break
opportunities). This year with the Celtics, we averaged about 18.
We've got to take away some of the things the defense is doing.
Some guys are averaging 40 percent (shooting) from the floor. It
should be up around 48. When McHale and Parish were playing, they
both averaged 55 percent, and Bird was just under 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino feels the clutch-and-grab tactics that are being
permitted don't allow for big offensive explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grabbing and holding throws the timing of the offense
away,'' he said. ``It takes eight seconds to get the ball over
halfcourt, on average. Then it takes another 12 seconds to run the
play and try to set up the shot you want. If the timing is
destroyed, you run out of time, someone has to go one on one and
try to get off a shot before the buzzer. We've got to get the game
back to where these players can make plays in the open court and
make the game more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``maul-ball'' type of play dates back to the Detroit Pistons
of Isiah Thomas, Bill Laimbeer, Dennis Rodman, etc., who won two
titles by getting away with murder on the defensive end. This was
the start of the so-called ``Jordan Rules,'' in which the Pistons
found the best way to stop Michael was to hold him and never let
him use the screen to get away the shot. The problem is that the
Jordan rules are still in effect for anyone who has any kind of
offensive game: Clutch and grab him so he can't get free to get
some space. The Knicks have done it to Reggie Miller throughout the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This from a Toronto publication earlier this season: ``Roger
(Clemens) didn't want to be here, didn't think we could contend,''
said Blue Jay pitcher Pat Hentgen. ``And there are 24 Blue Jay
players here who didn't want him to stay.'' ... Credit Patriots
coach Pete Carroll for pushing Chris Canty out the door and helping
the Patriots cut their losses. Carroll didn't want Canty in the
first place. Canty's agent is calling other teams, who are calling
around to find out why a team would waive its first-round draft
choice after just two years
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I wish Connecticut would stop whining about suing the Patriots
and the NFL. The state officials are the ones to blame. When you
offer someone the greatest deal in the history of sports to move
and don't make it binding, and leave him five different ways to get
out, then you lose. It's your fault. But Connecticut left the
loopholes in and is now crying about the Patriots using them to
come back to Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
