A2380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TROPICAL-DISEASES13-C     06-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROPICAL-DISEASES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia researchers target tropical diseases
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ They resemble stink bugs, but instead of eating
plants, Reduviid bugs suck the blood of humans and animals, then
leave behind a plop of feces.
</P>
<P>
   They can also leave a lifetime of problems _ their waste can
contain a protozoan parasite that causes a fatal heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the estimated 20 million people, mostly in Latin
America, already infected with the parasiteTrypanosoma cruzi will
die of complications from an enlarged heart produced by Chagas
disease. Charles Darwin was said to have suffered from the
debilitating, incurable illness.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular biologists at the University of Georgia are hoping to
find a cure for Chagas disease and other parasitic infections that
are major sources of plant, animal and human illness and deaths.
Parasitic infections account for millions of lost dollars and lives
_ malaria, associated with mosquitoes, alone accounts for 3 million
deaths annually, mostly of children.
</P>
<P>
   Formed last fall, the UGA Center for Tropical and Emerging
Global Diseases draws its researchers from UGA's College of
Agriculture and Environmental Sciences, College of Veterinary
Medicine and Franklin College of Arts and Sciences. The UGA College
of Pharmacy is also expected to become involved, and two other
faculty positions will be filled by scientists associated with the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Adjunct faculty are scattered at Emory University's Vaccine
Center in Atlanta, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta, and the Medical College of Georgia in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Research Alliance is helping with the start-up of
the associated Laboratory for Technology Development, which will
bring to the commercial market any developments from the center's
research, such as vaccines. UGA officials hope to work with the
Georgia Research Alliance to build facilities for the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We developed the center to strengthen UGA's strong program in
parasitology,'' said director Rick Tarleton, a cellular biologist
who has been studying T. cruzi since he was an undergraduate at
Wake Forest. ``Also, we wanted to become more competitive for
program project grants, which are given to collaborative efforts
instead of individual researchers.''
</P>
<P>
   One scientist is exploring ways to manipulate the genes of
Reduviid bugs to make them incapable of carrying T. cruzi , while
another is analyzing the bug's saliva, which prevents blood from
clotting.
</P>
<P>
   Tarleton and his graduate students are trying to understand the
response of the immune system to the parasite and to determine how
that response can be amplified by vaccination to increase the odds
against the development of Chagas disease. He is also trying to
understand why the disease occurs in only 30 to 40 percent of
infected individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Although infectious diseases occur primarily in less developed
countries, they are on the rise in the United States, Tarleton
said. Witness in the last few years the outbreak of diarrhea and
death in Milwaukee, caused by cryptosporidia in the water system,
and 21 clusters of cases reported to the CDC in 1997, most of them
linked to cyclospora -contaminated raspberries imported from
Guatemala. With more international travel, immigrants and imports,
the number of such occurrences is likely to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Chagas disease isn't the only parasitic infection under study.
Center faculty are researching the causes and carriers of malaria,
African sleeping sickness, river blindness and leishmaniasis, which
can cause fever, weight loss, enlargement of the spleen and anemia
_ and which, if left untreated, is fatal.
</P>
<P>
   The center has received a $3.4 million grant from the National
Insitutes of Health. Over the next five years, the money will fund
four separate projects, all related to developing a vaccine for
Chagas disease.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the grant will fund collaborative work with scientists
in Argentina. Tarleton has traveled three times to Buenos Aires
with graduate students to do research, and Argentinian scientists
from there have come to Athens for training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, we study infected mice. There, we study infected
people,'' said Tarleton. ``It's different when a human face is
attached to the disease. What's an interesting biological question
here becomes in Argentina a human, personal tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
