<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-AMERICA-SHARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK OF AMERICA WILL STOP GIVING CUSTOMER DATA TO OUTSIDE
MARKETERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn.)   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid heightened concern about consumer privacy issues, Bank of
America, one of the nation's largest banks, said Friday that it
would no longer share any customer information _ including
addresses, telephone numbers and credit card account numbers _ with
outside vendors such as telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   The move came a day after U.S. Bancorp, a large Minneapolis
bank, ended relationships with several telemarketing companies that
solicit its customers to buy a variety of nonfinancial products.
Earlier in the week, the Minnesota attorney general's office sued
U.S. Bancorp, contending that the bank illegally sold credit
histories and other customer information to a large telemarketer,
even though it told customers it did not engage in such practices.
U.S. Bancorp disputes that its practices were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   As personal information continues to flow loosely across
telephone lines and through the vast reaches of the Internet, and
has become a lucrative trade for companies like banks with ready
access to the data, federal and state regulators have begun to
crack down on abuses tied to information trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Banks frequently provide birth dates, Social Security numbers,
checking and credit card account information, addresses and
telephone numbers to outside companies for hefty fees or
commissions. But there has been a proliferation of complaints from
consumers recently about telemarketing practices that include
charging a customer's credit card or withdrawing money from a
checking account when consumers believe they have not given
approval to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, consumer discontent about violations of financial
privacy have grown so strong that Congress took a step late
Thursday night toward circumscribing how banks do business. The
House Commerce Committee, in a bipartisan alliance, approved a
rider to financial services reform legislation that would give
consumers the right to prevent banks from sharing financial
information with their own insurance and securities affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   If the rider remains and the legislation passes it would be a
big setback for newly merged companies like Citigroup that are an
amalgam of banking, insurance and securities operations designed to
cross-sell a variety of products to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   John Hawke, U.S. Comptroller of the Currency, one of the main
federal banking regulators, has repeatedly spoken out about
incursions of financial privacy and has labeled information
trafficking as ``seamy.'' Friday, the Comptroller's office said it
welcomed Bank of America's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank of America had previously advised us that it was
reconsidering its policies and we commend the bank for announcing
these changes,'' said Julie Williams, the comptroller's chief
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America and U.S. Bancorp will not be insulating their
customers from every form of telemarketing. Both companies will
allow vendors of financial products, like insurance companies, to
keep contacting their customers, but will no longer maintain
relationships with vendors of nonfinancial products, such as
vacation packages and dining club memberships.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America is going one step further, saying that it will
not allow financial products vendors to contact customers directly.
Instead, the bank will require those companies to use Bank of
America as a middleman when pitching their products. Bank of
America said a curtailed relationship with telemarketers would harm
the bank's profitability.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bancorp said its move came in response to the Minnesota
attorney general's suit and to more than 800 complaints it received
from customers about its relationships with telemarketers. The bank
said it ended its relationship with four telemarketing companies:
Branddirect, Damark, Health Benefits Services and Memberworks.
Memberworks, cited for abusive practices in the Minnesota attorney
general's suit, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Corp. of Chicago said it only shared customer phone
numbers and addresses with outside vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Corp. and Citigroup declined to comment on
exactly what customer information they shared with outside vendors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
