u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-530&AMP;ADD-N     06-11 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS TO `HOLD KOSOVO TOGETHER,' GENERAL PROMISES
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, told
allied ambassadors Friday that the peacekeepers who would soon
begin moving into Kosovo would try to ``hold Kosovo together''
until international aid agencies could set up relief operations
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to recognize that at first we're the only
organization that's in there,'' he said in an interview summing up
NATO's 11-week bombing campaign, which ended Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have special responsibilities in gripping the situation,''
Clark said. NATO peacekeeping troops under the command of British
Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson are ready to provide first aid and food to
any refugees they find when they go in, he said, and to prevent
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there'll be hotheads on both sides who don't want to
let bygones be bygones,'' he said, not ruling out more organized
resistance to the peacekeeping force from Serbs or ethnic Albanian
rebels. ``We'll have to work those problems if we run into them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Clark said, the withdrawing Yugoslav forces had been
``pretty cooperative.'' The peacekeeping force delayed plans to
start moving in Friday, he said, because Yugoslav commanders had
asked for more time to get some of their heavy equipment together
and clear obstacles from the roads close to Kosovo's southern and
western borders.
</P>
<P>
   French, German and British peacekeeping troops plan to begin a
synchronized entry into Kosovo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 Yugoslav soldiers did pull out from the northern
part of Kosovo on the first day, allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the allied command said that some fighting between Serb
forces and Albanian rebels continued near the Albanian border
Friday and a Yugoslav anti-aircraft missile radar had ``locked on''
to an allied plane, Clark said he had not been notified of any
other violations of the military withdrawal agreement by late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Like other allied officials, he said he was relaxed about
Friday's diplomatic and military maneuvering by Russia over its
possible participation in the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there'll be Russians there,'' he said. ``From a
military standpoint, I think Russia has military capacities that
could provide some significant assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and other allied leaders credited Russian
diplomatic pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for
helping isolate Serbia. Clark, who negotiated with Milosevic on the
military aspects of the peace agreement in Bosnia in 1995, agreed
that, on that level, the Russians did help.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really wasn't a war,'' he said. ``It was diplomacy backed
by force. The destruction was only a consequence of his not
complying with international will. It wasn't a sense that we were
going to move in and occupy the country.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Clark said, his first priority had been to
attack the 40,000 Yugoslav soldiers and Serbian police and
paramilitary units that were systematically driving the Kosovo
Albanians from their homes and have now finally begun to pull out
of the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it took a while without a ground force to develop a
capability to go after them,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An essential part of the system that was developed, Clark said,
was Task Force Hawk, the 4,000 American troops who moved into
Albania in April with Black Hawk anti-tank helicopters that
famously never went into combat.
</P>
<P>
   The artillery-locating radar system that came with the
helicopters did go into action, he said, and was used to help
allied pilots and their targeting specialists develop new tactics
that eventually destroyed half the Yugoslav artillery and tank
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he brought it in and fired it, we took it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had not gathered all the helicopters and planes he
needed before the bombing started last March 24, Clark said, ``We
could not have gotten all those assets at the outset. There wasn't
a consensus position that that kind of power and destruction was
going to be required.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects the value of alliance cohesion was greater
than the value of any specific target. When we started, there were
many who from a variety of motives felt it wasn't going to be that
difficult to achieve what we wanted. Some who said we should do as
little as possible because Yugoslavia was a European country, and
every bit of infrastructure we tear up, one of us will have to pay
for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As we went in,'' Clark added, ``and it became clear it wasn't
going to be over in a few days or a few weeks, accelerating the
tempo became more attractive.At first, we wanted to work mostly at
night to minimize the effect of missiles and anti-aircraft fire. As
we got experience, as we took them out, we were eventually able to
fly 24 hours a day, but to do that we were going to need more
aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign ended, he said, with more than 900 allied planes,
three times as many as he had at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   By the time bombing was suspended, he said, these warplanes had
done tremendous damage to Milosevic's strategic military assets all
over Serbia. The allies lost not a single pilot in combat
operations in this campaign. ``A big part of our success was the
mystique of invulnerability,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   While they made their share of mistakes, causing unintended
civilian casualties in both Yugoslavia and Kosovo, Clark said they
were few, given the 23,000 bombs and missiles that were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final standard,'' he said, ``is, did it work? Did it
provide crucial leverage to diplomacy? I think yes, it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
