<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-MP3     06-11 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MP3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You say you want a revolution? Music industry faces one with MP3
technology
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The way you buy recorded music is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   One day in the not too distant future, you will be able to sit
down at your computer and download music from your favorite artists
at competitive prices and put it on a music CD you'll make
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a just a vision from a William Gibson cyberspace
fantasy novel, but reality brought even closer to consumers by an
audio technology called MP3 and two deals made by major media
companies this week.
</P>
<P>
   This week's rollout of digital music downloads from Amazon.com
and the announcement of Cox Interactive Media's $45 million
investment in the extremely popular Web site MP3.com are the first
steps toward making music on the Web a legitimate enterprise and
easing the tension between the recording industry and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive Media, a unit of Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises,
which owns Cox Newspapers and the Cox News Service, bought a 10
percent stake in MP3.com Wednesday, betting that the idea of
distributing music via the Internet, if not the technology itself,
will be a good way to make money in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Cox and MP3.com have agreed to develop Web sites incorporating
the MP3 technology. Cox Enterprises president and chief operating
officer David Easterly will join the board of MP3.com as part of
the deal. Neither MP3.com nor Cox Interacitve Media will comment on
the deal (MP3.com is in a quiet period because it has filed for an
initial public offering), but analysts believe it's a good move for
both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is a company known for placing its bets all across the
table. Cox also has a string of media interests including radio
stations and cable TV companies. Cable and radio could both gain a
great deal should MP3 technology blossom as Internet research firm
Jupiter Communications predicts it will by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about who is who in that investment relationship,'' says
Forrester Research analyst Mark Hardie. ``Cox is big in broadcast
radio, which is moving slowly to integrate interactivity into its
business and for good reason. They have yet to prove they can make
money from it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you see Cox saying is that the technology and the
distribtuion capabilities are imporant to the future of the
business. Digital music and the future of the business is critical
for radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio has always been a promotional tool for the music industy,
and in the past, even the most wildly popular radio station makes
no profit from any of the music it plays. At the same time, the
broadcast industry has demonstrated that if you put Web addresses
on the TV screen, viewers will go to their computers and visit that
site.
</P>
<P>
   The radio industry is slowly realizing the potential of Web
music downloads. They can play a song, then direct listeners to a
Web site to download music and eventually buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What radio stations want to do is prove that after they play a
song, it sells,'' Hardie says.
</P>
<P>
   Other industry watchers believe that Cox will have a calming
effect on the record industry, which has been hostile to MP3
technology, as well as mellowing MP3.com, which has often taken
shots at the major labels for not jumping on the download
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3.com has excellent traffic right now,'' says Jupiter
Communications analyst Mark Mooridian.
</P>
<P>
   However, the success of MP3.com as a Web site and a profitable
business venture depends on the company's willingness to work with
major labels to bring the big names online.
</P>
<P>
   ``When MP3.com gets a big artist like Tom Petty, they get
tremendous traffic, but so far their relationships with major
labels have been strained at best,'' Mooradian says. ``They've got
great growth potential that hasn't been realized. And the record
companies are starting to realize that MP3 is not going to go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Amazon.com rolled out the music downloads area of its
Web site Tuesday with largely positive results from both customers
and the record labels. Its success using music downloads to promote
artists and drive CD sales is showing the record industry just what
MP3 can do for business.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's product manager for music, Greg Hart, says Amazon
decided to offer free digital downloads after a trial run featuring
Sarah McLachlan in April sent advance sales of the album soaring to
the top of Amazon's music list. ``People liked to hear music they
couldn't hear anywhere else,'' Hart says, ``and it was a great way
to spur sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon worked hard to provide the ``positive user experience''
that analysts say is mandatory for the growth of the music download
industry. Currently, Amazon offers downloads for promotional
purposes only, because there are too many copyright and industry
standardization issues that haven't been resolved yet. ``We don't
think it's quite a sales format yet,'' Hart says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to focus on consumers and media experiences,'' warns
Hardie. ``It's not about a page on the Web, it's about an
environment and an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   These first forays of major media companies like Cox and Amazon
into the world of music downloads may establish a kind of detente
between MP3.com and the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 isn't necessarily a blasphemous word in the music industry,
but for some it's still a foreign one. ``I don't really know what
it is, other than, supposedly, everybody in this business is afraid
of it,'' says teen R&AMP;B singer Monica, a correspondent on the web
site for the Grammy Awards this year who lives in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, I only hear people outside of the business
talking about it,'' she adds. ``As an artist, it hasn't become a
part of my day-to-day concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based LaFace Records co-president Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid
is also familiar with the talk, but less so the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't downloaded anything, or tried,'' he says. ``But I
know it's out there. And I have to tell you, I don't necessarily
feel it is as much a threat as other people. At the same time, it's
not something that I can say that I like.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's not because Reid thinks the technology might be a way
for someone to set up shop and compete with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an option,'' he contends. ``When it becomes more of
an organized and familiar business, I can see it being more of a
complement to the business. Rather than one cannibalizing the
other, I think we'll just see a tremendous growth in our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a lot of work to be done before MP3, artists and
Web developers can live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Hardie believes MP3 isn't ready for prime time just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3 is just a format for downloading music,'' he says. ``It is
just an algorithm. It's a way to compress music, and it's not even
the best way. MP3 is really just the poster child for evoloution in
the distribution of music, but it's not ripe yet. It has no mass
market polish.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jupiter Communications analyst Lucas Graves says it's
time music companies learn to stop worrying and learn to love MP3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, the industry focus was on how to eliminate MP3,''
he said. ``Now, like it or not, the industry has to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that the record companies could stem the rampant piracy
of their product if they would embrace the new technology and use
the Internet as a marketing tool the way it uses MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every Alanis Morrisette CD that goes platinum in the
record stores, there's a massive promotion and marketing effort,''
he points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the music industry is one of the savviest
industries in the world, but they haven't spent any money in this
area. They are worried about priacy and they should be. However, if
the music industry plays its cards right, the piracy will be a
small part of the digital landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   The record companies' refusal to take advantage of MP3
technology has fostered the proliferation of underground and
pirated music on the Internet, Graves believes. ``People's own
personal music collections replaced actual music product,'' he
says. ``Ironically, if the record companies had moved faster, they
might have nipped MP3 piracy in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, like Amazon.com, has relationships with record labels it
needs to protect. Amazon's careful courting of record labels and
Cox's alliance with MP3.com are indicators the recording industry
is slowly accepting the idea that music downloads are here to stay,
that major media companies are going to want to use them and there
could be a potential pot of gold at the end of this virtual
rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Sonia Murray
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
