<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STANLEY CUP NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFAL0, N.Y. _ By whiffing on six power play attempts in Game
2, Dallas now has gone 15 straight power plays without scoring.
``The Sabres scored both of their goals on the power play and we
didn't score any on our six,'' said Stars forward Pat Verbeek. ``If
there's one area we need to improve on, it's special teams.'' . . .
The Sabres are 7-0 at home in the playoffs, the Stars are 5-3 on
the road. . . . The Sabres are a hot ticket in town. After
season-ticket holders and other officials were taken care of, there
were approximately only 2,000 tickets per game (or 6,000 total for
three potential home games) that went on sale to the general public
for the finals. They sold out in eight minutes. As a result,
tickets are being scalped for anywhere from $250 to $1,000. . . .
Dallas defenseman Craig Ludwig set a record for the most years (11)
between playoff goals when he scored in Game 2. The old record was
10 years, held by Johnny Bucyk (1959-69), Gordie Howe (1970-80) and
Harry Howell (1958-68).
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers interview Fraser
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Atlanta Thrashers have yet to stock their
minor-league system with players, but general manager Don Waddell
already has recalled a coach. For an interview, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Fraser, whom Waddell hired three years ago to coach the
IHL's Orlando Solar Bears, now the the Thrashers' top affiliate,
interviewed for the NHL team's head coaching vacancy Friday. Fraser
is only the third coach to have a formal interview in Atlanta,
joining former Phoenix coach Don Hay and former Edmonton coach Ron
Low. Waddell also has had informal interviews with Ted Nolan and
Mike Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell has spoken highly of Fraser before, although it was
believed he would he more in line for an assistant's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to hire an assistant right now I'm looking for
a head coach,'' Waddell said. ``Curt's a good guy, I know him well
and he's one of the bright young hockey coaches today. He's
obviously never been a head coach in the NHL before but he was an
NHL player and he's been in pro hockey for 20 years. He's down a
great job down there, so why not look at some of the better young
guys around who can grow with the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview with Fraser is the strongest indication yet that
Waddell has broadened his search from his original intention of
hiring only someone with NHL head coaching experience. It's also
further evidence that he is not close to reaching a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Solar Bears reached the IHL's Turner Cup finals this year
before losing to the Houston Aeros. Waddell also denied speculation
that Aeros coach Dave Tippett was a Thrashers candidate or had been
interviewed for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
