A2393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-SUSPECT-TEXAS-     06-11 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-SUSPECT-TEXAS-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY SHROUDS SUSPECT IN STRING OF KILLINGS IN TEXAS, KENTUCKY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 13) 
 
(Attn: Calif., Ky., N.M., Texas) 
 
By MIKE SNYDER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Aug. 19, 1995, a Santa Fe Railway police officer observed a
man climbing a chain-link fence onto railroad property in San
Bernardino, Calif. At the time, the area was known as a gathering
place for transients looking for a free ride on a freight car.
</P>
<P>
   The officer found a loaded pistol in a gym bag the man was
carrying. He was quick to come up with a story, telling the
skeptical officer he had found the bag in some nearby bushes. Local
police charged him with trespassing and having a loaded weapon in
public.
</P>
<P>
   The episode would become one entry on a growing list of
relatively minor crimes allegedly committed by this itinerant
Mexican national, who identified himself to authorities in
California as Pedro Angel Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is known as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, suspected in the
slayings of six people in Texas and one in Kentucky since the
summer of 1997. Hundreds of law-enforcement officers are trying to
find him.
</P>
<P>
   As FBI experts develop a psychological profile of
Resendez-Ramirez, their task is complicated by contradictions and
informational gaps: a history of nonviolent crime followed, police
say, by a series of savage attacks in which victims were bludgeoned
to death. A confusing tangle of aliases and disguises. An
incomplete criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real mystery man,'' said Devon Anderson, the Harris
County (Texas) prosecutor assigned to the December slaying of a
West University Place physician who authorities say is one of
Resendez-Ramirez's victims. West University Place is an enclave of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Evans, director of social psychology at the
University of Houston, said the emerging picture of
Resendez-Ramirez is of an intelligent but ``deeply disturbed'' man
who seems to feel no guilt about his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, Evans said, what might have triggered a
transformation from wandering illegal immigrant and burglar to
vicious serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's not uncommon in these situations is a kind of lurking
rage that develops in people over time,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   The limited information released publicly about Resendez-Ramirez
suggests a man who rides freight cars alone, committing sporadic
crimes of opportunity. Thus, Evans speculated that he may have ``no
family support system, no support system from friends _ an
itinerant person who probably has difficulty in relating to people,
is constantly rejected, and may have a terrible rage because of
something that happened in his personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Resendez-Ramirez has used at least nine
different names and four birthdates, and that he is adept at
changing his appearance. This has made it difficult for them to
track his background.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI says Resendez-Ramirez is a native of Puebla, a city of
about 835,000 people 65 miles southeast of Mexico City. The various
birthdates he has provided make him either 38 or 39.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prison system records show that on Sept. 18, 1986, a
federal judge in Laredo, Texas, sentenced Jose Reyes-Resendez _ the
alias Resendez-Ramirez was using at the time _ to 18 months in
prison for falsely representing himself as a U.S. citizen. He spent
time in various federal detention centers until his release on Aug.
14, 1987, when he was turned over to immigration authorities and
deported.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, still known as Jose Reyes-Resendez, he was back
before a federal judge, this time in Missouri. He was sentenced to
30 months for illegally re-entering the country and making false
statements. Upon his release on Feb. 1, 1991, he was deported
again.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, according to prosecutor Anderson's records, he
resurfaced in Santa Fe, N.M., using the name Antonio Martinez. In
March 1992, he was convicted of residential burglary and sentenced
to three years in prison. It could not be determined how much time
he served.
</P>
<P>
   On July 8, 1993, in the tiny town of Panhandle, Texas, near
Amarillo, a drifter identified as Carlos Rodriguez _ yet another
alias _ was sentenced to 29 days in jail for evading arrest.
Authorities in Carson County could not provide details of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the 1995 San Bernadino incident.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said fingerprints filed with records of each of these
cases matched those of Resendez-Ramirez. She said it is likely,
however, that there are other crimes in his past that authorities
don't yet know about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll ever have his complete criminal history,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, the UH psychologist, said Resendez-Ramirez's use of
aliases and disguises indicates ``a certain amount of guile or
cleverness. Even though he is a lowly itinerant worker, he is not
unintelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of his alleged crimes, Evans said, also could yield
some clues about him.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have linked Resendez-Ramirez, through physical
evidence or descriptions and circumstances, to the slayings of
seven people, ranging from a Kentucky college student to a central
Texas minister and his wife. Three of the victims' cars were
stolen, and at least two of the attacks included sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   All of the crimes occurred near railroad tracks, and several
victims were attacked at night. Evans said a professional thief
would be leery of operating at night because of the likelihood of
someone being home.
</P>
<P>
   The apparently random pattern of the attacks and the killer's
choice of small, quiet communities, such as West University Place
and the little town of Weimar, Texas, may have heightened the level
of fear he is inspiring in the public, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   This anxiety was evident after 73-year-old Josephine Konvicka
was found bludgeoned to death in her bed on June 4 in Fayette
County, a month after the slayings of a minister and his wife in
nearby Weimar. Authorities said they found Resendez-Ramirez's
fingerprints in Konvicka's home and unspecified physical evidence
tying him to the slayings in Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a relatively major crime-free county,'' Fayette County
Sheriff Rick Vandel said the day after Konvicka's body was found.
``These are good, honest, God-fearing Czech and German folk who
obey the law. Naturally, because this crime has some similarities
to (the) one in Weimar, we're getting a lot of paranoid folks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
