<HEADLINE>
IN RARE TALKS WITH LIBYANS, U.S. OUTLINES SANCTION VIEW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In their first official meeting in 18 years,
the United States told Libya Friday that it would not support the
complete lifting of sanctions until Libya stopped supporting
international terrorism and met other conditions required by U.N.
resolutions, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The message was delivered by A. Peter Burleigh, the U.S.
representative, to Libya's representative, Abuzed Omar Dorda, in a
meeting with Secretary-General Kofi Annan. Also present was Sir
Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's representative, whose government holds
views similar to the Americans, and other senior U.N. officials,
the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had called the meeting to discuss what the Security
Council requires to end the sanctions against Tripoli, which were
first imposed in 1992 and strengthened the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions were intended to force Libya to hand over two
suspects charged with carrying out the bombing of Pan American
Flight 103, which exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December
1988, killing 270 people, mostly Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Libya turned over the two suspects this spring to stand trial in
a Scottish court in the Netherlands, and sanctions were suspended
on April 5. But Libya has been pressing for them to be permanently
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have maintained that Libya must
comply with other requirements imposed by the resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony on Capitol Hill this week, Martin Indyk, an
assistant secretary of state, said Libya must ``end and renounce
support for all forms of terrorism, pay appropriate compensation''
to the families of victims in the crash, ``acknowledge
responsibility for the actions of its officials'' and ``cooperate
with the investigation and the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   While Libya, in handing over the suspects, had moved ``a
critical step closer'' to achieving the justice that would enable
sanctions to be ended, Indyk said, Libya had to fulfill the other
conditions as well. The United States is prepared to veto any
resolution to end the sanctions, he added, ``if it is presented
before we are satisfied with the Libyan actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary General Annan is supposed to offer his views on
whether Tripoli has fulfilled the Security Council's requirements
in a report next month. But the trial of the two suspects has been
delayed until next February at the earliest, which will complicate
Annan's ability to judge whether Libya is cooperating fully with
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat described the meeting Friday as ``very
professional'' and the atmosphere as cordial. Burleigh did not talk
to reporters after the session, but Dorda called the meeting a
``special day'' for Libyan-American relations. ``It will lead us
all to turn over the last page of the past and then we will open a
new one,'' he told reporters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that Libya has benefited handsomely from the
suspension of sanctions. Since April, Europeans in particular have
flocked to Tripoli in hope of securing lucrative contracts for the
development of Libya's estimated reserves _ 30 billion barrels of
oil and 55 trillion cubic feet of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Takeyh, a research fellow at the Washington Institute for
Near East Policy, said, for example, that five European consortiums
are competing for a $5.5 billion contract to develop Libyan gas.
Even without a permanent lifting of sanctions, he said, ``Libya has
effectively escaped its isolation and re-entered the international
arena.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
