<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-LOBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C. )  
 TEAR IN REBECCA LOBO'S KNEE IS COMPLETE , BUT SHE WILL PLAY AGAIN,
DOCTORS SAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news on Rebecca Lobo was bad and good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Craig Scott, the Liberty's team physician, said the injury
Lobo sustained Thursday night in an 87-60 season-opening victory
over the Cleveland Rockers was a complete tear of the anterior
cruciate ligament in the left knee. She said Lobo also tore the
meniscus, which is fibrous cartilage in the knee joint.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Lobo, one of the marquee players in the Women's
National Basketball Association, would undergo reconstructive
surgery in two or three weeks, when the swelling goes down and the
range of motion is normal. She said Lobo would miss the rest of the
three-month season, but should regain full strength after at least
six months of rehabilitation and be able to play next season with
no loss of movement.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the inflammation, Lobo began therapy Friday morning at
Beth Israel Hospital, North Division. The therapy will continue
until the surgery. Then Lobo will stay in New York for
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   After an emotional night, Lobo was positive during a
teleconference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first injury I've ever had that's taken me out of
commission for a long time,'' she said. ``I've had a scope on the
other knee, but this is the first thing of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Lobo, a 6-foot-4-inch power forward, led the
University of Connecticut to the national championship in 1995,
when she was voted the player of the year. She has started all 59
games in the Liberty's two-plus seasons. She was injured only 42
seconds into the game in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a real sweet offensive rebound,'' she said. ``When I
came down, my thought was that somebody hit me on the side of my
knee because it buckled. I knew as soon as it happened that it was
torn. I never felt anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   For 20 seconds, while Lobo clutched her leg and screamed in
pain, no one called a timeout. Finally, the officials did. Lobo was
helped to the locker room and later taken to the hospital, where a
magnetic resonance imaging test disclosed the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Lobo's mother and grandmother were in the Garden and rushed to
the locker room after the injury. Lobo's mother, RuthAnn, is in
remission from breast cancer, and mother and daughter wrote a book
telling how they had confronted the illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night was a roller coaster of emotions,'' Lobo said of
the post-injury scene. ``I finally felt OK, spoke to my mom and the
tears came. Then I was OK. Then I spoke to my dad and the tears
came. I'm disappointed this happened, but at the same time I'm
upbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said torn anterior cruciate ligaments were five to eight
times more common among female basketball players than male. She
cited three reasons:
</P>
<P>
   Anatomical _ the narrowness of the notch where the ligament is
attached prevents more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Hormonal _ female ligaments are looser.
</P>
<P>
   Muscle mass _ a woman's muscle mass is not the size of a man's,
so when a woman's knee is injured with force, the muscles do not
protect her as well as they protect a man.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Jones Young, drafted by the Liberty last month after a
highly successful career in the defunct American Basketball League,
tore the anterior cruciate and medial collateral ligaments in her
right knee in January. Scott said Young was making good progress.
</P>
<P>
   With Lobo out, 32-year-old Sue Wicks, who is 6-3, will start
against the Sting Saturday night in Charlotte. There will be more
playing time for two rookies _ 6-2 Tamika Whitmore and 6-6 Michele
VanGorp. Whitmore is comfortable offensively in the low post. The
slender VanGorp is a solid outside shooter but is not strong.
Whitmore played 21 minutes and VanGorp 6 against the Rockers, and
while both had good offensive moments, they also had defensive
problems in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to learn from Sue,'' Lobo said. `They'll
have to learn under fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lobo will try to get ready for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is diminished,'' Scott said of her
patient. ``We'll let her play when the strength is equal from one
side to the other and the stability is equal. That's the end point
of the therapy and then we turn her loose. She'll make a full
recovery. She's a tough kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobo left no doubt that she would be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday,'' she said, ``the tears flowed. Today, I'm starting
to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
