<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-PRISTINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB CIVILIANS JOIN TROOPS LEAVING KOSOVO CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Waving their guns and their traditional
three-finger salutes, thousands of Yugoslav soldiers rolled through
the Kosovo capital Friday on their way north, triumphant in
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   But more telling than the departing military vehicles were the
cars, tractors, and flatbed trucks interspersed among them. Serb
civilians were fleeing Kosovo, unmoved by NATO's pledge to protect
them from the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army and the soon-to-return
ethnic Albanian refugees who were expelled by Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   The cars carried families, clothing, and sticks of furniture,
and bore license plates indicating they came from the areas like
Djakovica and Prizren, where ethnic hatred was intense and where
the KLA could soon fill the vacuum created by withdrawing Serb
forces. Near Prizren, there was a convoy stretching more than 2
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Kosovo border, one car inched along, a mother and
father in the front seat, their school-age son crammed into the
back seat with bags of clothes, pillows and a Kalashnikov rifle.
The boy stared wide-eyed, his head resting on a rifle barrel
against the window.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of similar scenes on the border with the
republic of Montenegro, where local police told a UN refugee
official in Rozaje that about 250 Serbs and Montenegrins from
Kosovo had crossed the border in the previous two days.
</P>
<P>
   There were believed to be about 200,000 Serbs in Kosovo before
the war, about 10 percent of the province's population. Estimates
now put that number at 100,000, because many moved out when the
NATO bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, where the pre-war population of 250,000 has shrunk
to about 100,000, ethnic Albanians and Serbs always got along
better than in the more segregated, more bitterly divided
countryside. But the sight of their army, their police, and their
frightened compatriots leaving has got even fair-minded Serbs in
Pristina asking: Why are we staying?
</P>
<P>
   Alexander ``Simi'' Milosavljevic, 25, has thought about that a
lot lately. Most of his neighbors, Serbs and Albanians, have left.
His brother fled to Belgrade with his wife and three children. But
Milosavljevic needs only to take five exams to finish law school.
Despite the destruction throughout his country, he thinks there is
a future for him in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stay,'' he said. ``I don't have anywhere else to go. I am
not a rich man. Besides, I didn't do anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that some of his countrymen did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people must be frightened about their destiny,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he doesn't believe most Albanians will come back looking
for revenge. His nickname _ Simi _ is Albanian, and although he is
Serbian, he had many Albanian friends before most of them fled.
</P>
<P>
   Like others here, he believes that most Serbs in the countryside
will flee, because they feel vulnerable to attack by the KLA and
because they don't believe that the American or other NATO soldiers
about to enter Kosovo are neutral when it comes to the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Milosavljevic worked for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, which had been monitoring the escalating
violence between the KLA and Serb forces before the OSCE left
Kosovo right before the bombing began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Americans talking to Albanians in front of me. They
helped the KLA. They weren't so independent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, several hundred people gathered in Pristina's
center after rumors circulated that a contingent of Russian
soldiers was on the way to Pristina. It was a raucous crowd, and
their enthusiasm for the Russians underscored how little faith they
put in the word of the Western allies that they will be treated no
differently than the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Milosavljevic, who had served in the army, was called up again
to defend Kosovo. He wanted to serve, but his association with OSCE
made him suspect, ``so they discharged me.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of his best friends were drafted and were killed by NATO
bombs. Several other friends also were killed. Their pictures and
death notices adorn mail boxes and storefronts here, a local
custom.
</P>
<P>
   Milosavljevic, however, remains free of bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be angry,'' he said. ``I can't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosavljevic is unusual among Serbs here. Despite his anger at
NATO, he has a fondness for things from the West and doesn't hate
Westerners for things their governments have done. Friday, fellow
Serbs refused to serve him at three cafes when he tried to sit down
with Americans. The last man to refuse to serve the group was
Milosavljevic's brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out!'' his brother barked.
</P>
<P>
   Milosavljevic, who wore a University of Michigan basketball
T-shirt, said his father worked for Texas Instruments in the United
States for several years before returning here in 1991, incensed by
what he saw as anti-Serb bias in the US news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is a super patriot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosavljevic said he will express his patriotism ``by staying,
by not running away.''
</P>
<P>
   Others here seem less sure of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Stojanka Mitrovic, 46, who like so many other people here is
unemployed, said she is terrified about what may happen in the next
few days as Serb forces pull out. Her uncertainty is shared by
many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, I'm afraid for the children,'' she said. ``I will try
to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said she will base her decision on the way NATO forces
behave when they get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO should protect us. We have the same rights as
Albanians,'' she said. ``The way NATO protects us will decide how
many Serbs stay.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a dirty war. Most shops and businesses have had
their windows smashed and their interiors trashed. The few that
survived unscathed had on their doorways a painted logo with four
C's and a cross, a symbol that means ``Only unity saves the
Serbs.'' Like lamb's blood to a newborn in the Old Testament story,
the symbol spared the Serb-owned shops.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs' sense of abandonment, meanwhile, grew with each
passing convoy of soldiers. After low-flying NATO jets terrorized
this city for 78 days, the deafening roar of two formations of
seven Yugoslav MIGs flying over on the way to Belgrade was hardly
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   Bursts of gunfire sounded as often and as routinely as church
bells. A few miles outside the city, some Albanian homes, notable
for the brick walls that surround them, were on fire as retreating
Serb soldiers left a calling card.
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs here denounce such behavior, some because they
genuinely oppose it, others because they say they'll have to answer
for it when the Albanians return.
</P>
<P>
   Milenko Savovic was philosophical as the fleeing refugees and
the retreating soldiers passed through the city he has called home
for all his 63 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not afraid, because I'm old,'' he said. ``They can kill
me if there's any cause to kill me. I was born here and I expect to
die here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believed NATO troops would protect Serbs, the old
man replied, ``If they're human, they'll protect us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
