u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-INVEST-2TAKES-     06-11 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-INVEST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN BUSINESSWOMAN CHALLENGES POLAND'S TELEPHONE MONOPOLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Poland, France)   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ The lobby of the Sheraton Hotel here was packed
with dark-suited bankers last Wednesday, when Barbara J. Lundberg
blazed in.
</P>
<P>
   Her strawberry-red hair, bright enough to spot across the huge
room, had once again begun to rebel against her efforts to tame it.
But her freckled face scrunched up in easy laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a picture of me that I liked,'' she remarked
as she begged to avoid being photographed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet like it or not, Mrs. Lundberg is the center of a lot of
attention here.
</P>
<P>
   A former Wall Street executive who set up a venture capital fund
in Warsaw nine years ago, Mrs. Lundberg is suddenly in charge of
one of Poland's biggest and messiest conglomerates. Her goal?
Engineering a billion-dollar bet on telecommunications to compete
against Poland's former state telephone monopoly in both wireless
and traditional telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities and the risks are enormous. Poland, with its
population of 42 million and its remarkably strong growth, has
become Central Europe's hottest target for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors, mostly banks, own 50 percent of the shares in
Poland's banks. Foreign phone companies, including SBC
Communications of the United States and Deutsche Telekom AG of
Germany, are circling with interest around the government's plan to
sell off a big chunk of the national phone company.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to match the audacity of Mrs. Lundberg's plan. If
she succeeds, analysts predict Elektrim's debt will double to about
$1 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, Mrs. Lundberg became the chief executive of
Elektrim SA, a sprawling post-communist behemoth that had alienated
shareholders by buying up businesses from cable manufacturing to
chicken farms.
</P>
<P>
   Recruited by rebellious shareholders, many of them American
investment firms, Mrs. Lundberg has dismissed Elektrim's top
management and moved to sell off stakes in more than 80 companies.
</P>
<P>
   But far more important, she has plunged into the
telecommunications business with a string of acquisition totaling
more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she cemented a key part of her plan by teaming with
Vivendi SA, the French media and telecommunications conglomerate.
Vivendi will invest about $750 million to acquire 30 percent of
Elektrim's telecommunications ventures, which will be pooled into a
new joint-venture company.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Mrs. Lundberg plans to up the ante once again. In
need of big money to build high-speed networks around Poland, she
will try to raise about $500 million through a global convertible
bond offering.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the financial risks a huge challenge; so are the
political ones. Elektrim's strategy assumes in large part that the
Polish government will allow only one rival in each city to TPSA,
the former Polish telephone monopoly. But political leaders have
vacillated under strong lobbying pressure from a Swedish-backed
rival, Netia Holdings, and suggested Friday that they might change
the game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about violating Securities and Exchange Commission
restrictions about promoting stocks before a public securities
offering, Mrs. Lundgren refused to talk about her plans with
American publications this week.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she has long been one of Warsaw's most visible
foreigners, and the broad elements of her plan are clear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many expatriate American entrepreneurs here, Mrs.
Lundberg did not come to Warsaw because of her Polish ancestry. Now
47, she had worked as a venture capitalist in California and later
as vice president for corporate finance at Kidder Peabody &AMP;
Company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, less than a year after the collapse of Poland's last
communist regime, she organized the Polish American Enterprise
Fund, a venture capital fund financed initially by the American
government to encourage the development of Poland's private sector.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was successful enough that she subsequently began
several other investment outfits, which together managed about $500
million at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Elektrim, by contrast, was a direct holdover from the communist
era. Based around several of Poland's formerly state-owned
industrial companies, it was privatized as the country's biggest
producer of power-generation equipment, electrical cable and a
provider of engineering services.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other privatized companies in Eastern Europe, it
remained largely under control of the same managers as it had
during the old regime. The key player was Andrzej Skowronski, its
chairman, who took the company public on the Warsaw Stock Exchange
and then used its cash flow to buy up a treasure trove of smaller
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Poland's steady economic ascent under governments
that consistently pushed the country toward private enterprise,
many soured investors came to view Elektrim as a bad example of
Russian-style crony capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Elektrim's strategy was opaque, and its financial disclosure was
even worse. Dozens of companies and stakes in other companies were
hived off into separate entities, with the result that few people
had any idea what its true assets really were.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last year, Elektrim reported sales of $182 million
and a loss of $94 million. But those numbers did not include many
of the company's biggest properties, like its big cable-producing
business or its 34 percent stake in one of Poland's two nationwide
cellular telephone carriers, Polska Telefonia Cyfrowa.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to shareholders, Mrs. Lundberg estimated that
Elektrim's core equipment and engineering businesses were worth
about $886 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the real revolt came after revelations last year that
Elektrim had secretly agreed to sell part of its stake in the
wireless company _ the one business that enjoyed rocketing sales
and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by dissident shareholders, believed to include investment
funds run by Merrill Lynch among others, Mrs. Lundberg took over as
chief executive in early February.
</P>
<P>
   With an uncanny knack to charm almost anybody, people who know
her say Mrs. Lundberg, a twice-divorced mother with a ten-year-old
son, is tough and shrewd as well. She knows the key players in
Warsaw's elite and she has mapped out the political minefields.
</P>
<P>
   She has not been shy about imposing her ideas. Besides ensuring
the departure of Skowronski, Mrs. Lundberg got rid of Elektrim's
vice chairman and chief accountant. Then she recruited two top
executives from ABB Asea Brown Boveri's Poland subsidiary to map
out a clean-up effort.
</P>
<P>
   Under the scheme they devised, Elektrim will jettison stakes in
more than 80 ``non-core'' businesses and re-focus on power
generation equipment, power engineering and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
