<HEADER>
A2406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-INVEST-2NDTAKE     06-11 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-INVEST-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WARSAW, Poland: and telecommunications.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the three, telecom is to be the main event. Mrs. Lundberg
quickly scrapped the deal to sell off the stake in the wireless
company, agreeing to pay the aspiring buyer $25 million to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she negotiated to acquire a controlling stake of 51
percent in the wireless venture, for which Elektrim will pay about
$700 million. On top of that, she reached a deal to buy up Bresnan
International Partners, a cable television operator, for $325
million. Bresnan operates cable systems in northwest Poland as well
as a fiber optic network in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lundberg is also negotiating to buy a consortium of local
telephone operators in other cities around Poland, a deal that is
expected to cost several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, Elektrim will need to invest hundreds of millions
of dollars in new networks and in launching new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing she needed strategic partners, Mrs. Lundberg began talks
with Deutsche Telekom. But those talks bogged down over disputes
over control.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lundberg had much better luck with Vivendi, a one-time
water company that owns stakes in media companies and competes
against France Telecom in both wireless and wired phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors have generally applauded the new
strategy, but the political risks are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk is regulatory risk,'' said Pajak Sobek, an
analyst at Wood &AMP; Co. in Warsaw. ``No one knows, including
Elektrim, what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland is taking a relatively slow path toward allowing
competition in the telephone market. It has begun issuing licenses
allowing a single rival in each of Poland's major cities to the
state system. Long-distance and international service, which are
far more lucrative, will be off-limits for another few years.
</P>
<P>
   But even that modest plan has been wobbly and politically messy.
Elektrim waged a long and bitter battle against Netia Holdings,
whose biggest shareholder is the Swedish telephone company Telia
AB, just to acquire a local license in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   After months of lobbying and acrimony, Elektrim announced this
week that the government had guaranteed it the exclusive license
for Warsaw. But then, days later, Polish newspapers quoted
government officials saying they might allow another rival into the
Warsaw market.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very bad for Elektrim, because of their
assumption that they would be the sole rival for the next five
years,'' said Sobek. It would also raise deeper fears about future
decisions to change the rules of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lundberg seems determined to stay. Poland, she said, ``is
my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she still speaks Polish only haltingly, she quickly won
over many Elektrim workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may speak Polish and I may speak English,'' she told
workers shortly after arriving. ``But in business we are all
speaking the same language.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
