<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEIRUT-BEACHES-NYT &LR;      06-11 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEIRUT-BEACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BEIRUT'S BEACHES, MEN AND WOMEN ARE SEGREGATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Ah, summertime, and Beirut is flocking to the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   All along the dazzling shore, the people frolic. They dive from
splendid rocks into the swirling sea. They swim in sheltered coves,
and whack balls back and forth with wooden paddles. They sprawl
languidly in the Mediterranean sun.
</P>
<P>
   But something is missing from this picture-postcard-perfect
scene. The women seem to have been airbrushed out. So where are
Beirut's women on this dazzling day? At home _ or, sometimes, just
a few yards away, behind walls that let them frolic, too, but away
from the looks and talk that could destroy a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be so bad in Lebanon,'' Ghada Faour, a 25-year-old
secretary, said as she and a friend basked in string bikinis at
Ajram, a private women's-only beach just around the corner from the
all-male scene. ``Here we're more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, before the 1975-1991 civil war, Beirut was
sometimes known as the Paris of the Middle East. It is still,
undeniably, a cosmopolitan capital, with elegant restaurants,
dance-till-you drop nightclubs and a dress-to-kill fashion sense.
It still deserves its slightly libertine reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But, particularly in mostly Muslim West Beirut, that culture has
always been overlaid by more conservative strands, including very
specific ideas about what should and not be seen when it comes to
female flesh. The combination can be volatile, and one solution, in
summertime, is segregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't bring my fiancee here because if someone said
something, like what a beautiful girl, there'd have to be a
fight,'' said Hassan Karaki, 25, who sat wearing stylish
sunglasses, sipping beer and smoking a water pipe on a public
beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to have men and women on the beach together,
but there are advantages to being apart,'' he said. ``The guys
don't have to watch their language, and if the girls go to the
women's beaches, they can wear anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the weather, in the high 70s, was ideal, and the
beach was packed _ bronzed male bodies everywhere. Only a handful
of women could be seen, and most were fully clothed, and sheltered
by tents or beach umbrellas. Those who swam simply strolled into
the water, until their baggy dresses began to float along beside
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we were brought up,'' Mohammed Tayid, 23, said
with a shrug when asked whether he enjoyed the all-male scene. For
company, he and his friends had sculptured a buxom woman out of
sand.
</P>
<P>
   Randa Harb, 27, wore a modest pair of shorts and a tank top as
she sat under an umbrella with her bare-chested husband and young
son. ``If you wear a bathing suit, you're going to attract more
attention,'' Mrs. Harb said. ``So my husband won't let me, because
he doesn't want people to look and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the whirl that is Beirut, neither the segregation
nor the modesty are universal. Among the mobile-phone set, whose
conversations switch seamlessly from Arabic to English to French,
summertime means a membership at a club like the Summerland or the
Riviera. There, the sexes mix freely, and some women dress
daringly, in itsy-bitsy bikinis with matching platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the St. George's Yacht Club, renowned before
Lebanon's civil war by journalists and spies as a place to admire
the beauty of the women lolling by the pool. And up and down
Lebanon's coast are smaller, private beaches where middle-class
families might pay about $6 a person to spend a weekend day.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to public places, where anyone might pass,
women are always scarce. Mohammed Suhel, 26, a tailor who regularly
spends his late afternoons at the beach, said he always leaves his
fiancee behind. ``If she did come, I wouldn't let her wear a
bathing suit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon is not alone, of course, as home to a culture averse to
women showing too much skin. In Iran, a strict Islamic republic,
the insistence on female modesty means that women may not even
enter hotel pools. In most Arab countries, except among elites, a
standard woman's bathing costume is a dress.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebanon is different. Its substantial Christian population
has always contributed to a relatively libertine air, and its
geography means that most people live in close proximity to its
140-mile coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Ras Beirut, the heart of the capital, is a nob of land that
stretches into the sea, so the breeze is always salty. By 9 on any
weekend morning, the rocks below the seafront corniche are already
full of groups of boys and men, often in nothing more than bikini
bottoms as they begin a day of sunning, rough-housing, fishing and
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Beirut women, if allowed to go out at all, head to places like
Ajram and Costa Brava, where for $6 or so they can buy privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The last man they see is the one who takes their tickets, a
female journalist said. Even male children are barred once they
turn 7. Female lifeguards whistle away boats that stray near ogling
range. And women unwind enough to dance to the Arabic music that a
female disk jockey blares from the loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to dance where there are men, but here, we can
dance,'' said Ms. Faour, the young woman sunning herself at Ajram.
Her friend, Lina Abdo, 24, said her fiance preferred that she stick
to the women's beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Ms. Abdo said, ``he's a man, and this is the
Middle East.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
