<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2410 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-G8-$ADV13-COX     06-11 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-G8-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    G-8 SUMMIT TO FOCUS COST OF PEACE FOR KOSOVO, RECONSTRUCTION FOR
BALKANS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV13.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every day for nearly three months, the Pentagon has
displayed footage detailing the damage NATO bombs have done to
Yugoslavia -- bridges dropped, railroads crippled, buildings left
in smoldering ruins.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton boards Air Force One on Tuesday for a
week-long victory lap through Europe, the lead agenda item will be
deciding who will pick up the multi-billion-dollar tab to rebuild
many of those very assets so efficiently targeted by U.S. and
allied pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Having borne the risks of war, the United States and Europe must
now pony up the price of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're going to have to do, as we go forward, is to figure
out (how) to appropriately apportion, the cost of this,'' Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin told reporters on Thursday. ``We should do
what's appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   As the United States and its NATO allies embark on their
high-stakes peacekeeping role in Kosovo, Clinton journeys this week
to Europe to take up the longer-term mission of Balkans recovery
and reintegration into Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He's scheduled to spend Wednesday and Thursday in Switzerland
and France, then travel to Cologne, Germany, to meet with his
counterparts from the so-called Group of Seven, G-7, industrial
democracies (Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the
United States) on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin is scheduled to join the club on
Saturday and Sunday, for what has come to be known as the G-8.
Clinton will spend the following Monday in the tiny Balkan country
of Slovenia -- the first of four republics to break away from the
former Yugoslavia -- and he's hinted at a possible visit to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his fellow G-7 leaders plan to issue a statement
Friday on moving forward with immediate peacemaking and
reconstruction in Kosovo, and the longer-term, and far broader,
goal of helping to knit the entire Balkans region back into the
rapidly modernizing fabric of central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want the conflict now ending in Kosovo to be the
prelude to others,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Thursday, following a meeting with her G-8 counterparts in Cologne.
``We want to build the true basis for a new era of peace; so that
the future wars are prevented, economies grow, democratic
institutions attain their potential and the rights of all are
preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing that will take time - decades perhaps. It will
also take a great deal of money -- as much as $30 billion in public
money alone over the next five years, according to estimates that
came out of Cologne last week, where the top diplomats from the G-8
countries initialed a pact on Balkans reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The pact is likely to frame the outlines of Friday's G-7
dialogue, and a starting point, at least, for divvying up the costs
of securing long-term stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Having shouldered the lion's share of the costs of the NATO air
campaign, the United States plans to send Europe the bill for
patching up its southern doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect that most of the money would come through
Europe, because most of the costs of this campaign, the air
campaign, have been borne by the United States,'' Clinton said
Thursday. ``I don't want us to get into a haggling situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivo Daalder, a Balkans analyst with the Brookings Institution, a
Washington think tank, said the European Union expects Americans
will pay no more than a dime on the dollar for what amounts to a
Balkans Marshal Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any European government which believes
that the United States will even come up with 10 percent of the $30
billion,'' Daalder said Friday. ``We had a tremendous difficulty
coming up with $600 million for Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   After NATO air strikes and American diplomacy ended the war in
Bosnia in 1995, the World Bank estimated emergency reconstruction
needs there at $5.1 billion over four years. As of May, the United
States and five dozen other donor nations had pledged $4.6 billion,
and some $3.5 billion had been spent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer haul, Bosnia will need $20 billion worth of
public and private investment, however, to rebuild the homes,
telephone lines, water systems, roads and other major facilities
lost to the 3 1/2 year-long war.
</P>
<P>
   The European Community and the World Bank have already set up an
office in Brussels to coordinate reconstruction aid for Southeast
Europe. As of Saturday, it's even got its own web site
(HTTP://www.seerecon.org) and will soon announce a donor's
conference to try to raise international funding for repairing the
damage inflicted in recent months on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no good estimates on the destruction there, NATO
pilots have confirmed some 500 communities burned to ash and ember
over the past 11 weeks. Entire parts of the provincial capital of
Pristina have been looted by Serb soldiers -- one group of which
pulled into town after Belgrade agreed to peace and made off with
two truckloads of booty.
</P>
<P>
   And NATO bombs have destroyed dozens of bridges, railroads and
intersections across the province, in an effort to grind the Serb
forces there to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Serbia proper, NATO bombs took a far larger toll,
destroying two huge refineries, dozens of bridges and scores of
factories, airfields, radio and television facilities and telephone
and electricity systems. Long-term recovery costs in Serbia proper
could well top Bosnia's $20 billion estimate, though no one in the
G-8 capitals is talking about those costs quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair
have publicly ruled out providing reconstruction money for Serbia
so long as Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic, is in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he remains in power, as long as your nation is
ruled by an indicted war criminal, we will provide no support for
the reconstruction of Serbia,'' Clinton vowed to Serbs in his
televised Oval Office address Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to Balkans reconstruction than clearing the rubble
of war. Nearly a decade of conflict throughout much of the former
Yugoslavia has forced neighboring front-line states like Hungary
and Bulgaria to pay dearly in lost jobs and trade.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank has concluded that those countries and their
neighbors will fall into the equivalent of a recession this year --
with economic output shrinking an estimated 1.7 percent , on
average -- strictly due to the trade losses associated with the
NATO air war. The World Bank estimates that propping up the
economies of the front-line states will require $1.3 billion in
humanitarian aid and budget relief over the coming months to avert
dire consequences in the countries rimming Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are boats sitting in Hungary right now that would like
to get to Ukraine that can't get there,'' said World Bank spokesman
David Theis. Blocking their route are a half dozen bridges NATO
bombs dropped into the Danube river, the major transport link
between the Balkans and the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Romania estimates its economic losses from the last three months
at $800 million -- 2 percent of its annual output. Those trade
losses don't count, by the way, the house that was destroyed when a
U.S. missile flew 60 miles wide of its target and slammed into a
residential suburb of Sofia.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the poorest countries in Europe -- Albania and Macedonia
-- have between them shared the burden of accommodating nearly
800,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who fled neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``These countries have suffered enough,'' Daalder said during a
Brookings briefing on Friday. ``They have proven that they want to
be part of the European mainstream, and we owe them our
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is certain to use his trip through Europe this week to
echo Daalder's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be real. It's not only $30 billion just to deal with the
region; we're going to be there for many, many, many years, if not
decades,'' said Daalder. ``The challenge for the first decade of
the 21st century will be for Europe and the United States to
cooperate together to bring
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern Europe into the continent's mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
