<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2411 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV1     06-11 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUFFERING OF KOSOVAR ALBANIANS STOKES LONGTIME ETHNIC HATREDS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-G8-$ADV13.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Kosovar Serbs are loading up their families
and fleeing Kosovo in fear of facing down their old neighbors, the
Kosovar Albanians who are about to return from here wrapped in
righteous anger and the road dust of NATO tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs may be wise to leave. The Balkan ethnic pendulum is
beginning its inevitable backward swing.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians of Kosovo are in no mood to be forgiving,
not after the weeks and months of terror they passed, not after the
degrading, violent treatment so many suffered, or after losses like
the feeble grandfathers shot and babies expired on the tear-stained
roadways of exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our neighbors are Serbian police and paramilitary,'' said Isof
Ibrahimi, a 20-year-old refugee here speaking of his village near
Pristina, the provincial capital of Kosovo. ``They came to us
masked, but we know their names. We know where they live.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ibrahimis are in no hurry to leave their tent camp and get
home to what they believe is only a shell of a house -- if they are
lucky -- and to the memories of the burning bodies they said they
saw from the window of the train that took them away.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever they do get back, they don't want those Serb neighbors
to be in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did very bad things. There is no place for them any
more,'' said Ibrahimi. ``In our neighborhood, no. Maybe in another
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians and Serbs, peoples with different language,
different religion, different customs, have been mangling each
other since about the 7th Century, when the first Serbs arrived and
began jostling for dominance throughout the Balkans with the people
already in place -- including the ancestors of today's ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Killings and rapes have haunted families on both sides of this
ethnic divide for centuries. More recently, the Kosovo Liberation
Army hardly had been fighting a dainty battle for independence
before the Serb hammer came down on the province to crush it.
</P>
<P>
   That is when today's ethnic Albanians became the latest and
perhaps most profoundly injured of the victims in this long-playing
conflict. In any event, their injury under the Serbs' fierce ethnic
cleansing campaign has been the most widely recorded.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign began several days before NATO bombs fell on
Yugoslavia and continued in an erratic, inexplicable pattern that
sent tens of thousand of refugees flooding out of the country one
day, then none the next. Of about 1.8 million ethnic Albanians --
who made up 90 percent of Kosovo's population -- at least 800,000
now are refugees and an estimated
</P>
<P>
   500,00 are internally displaced.
</P>
<P>
   Early stories of simple expulsion gave way to tales of terror.
</P>
<P>
   Then satellite photos showed fresh, mass graves, and air
reconnaissance films documented scores of burned out villages. The
most eloquent images were the distraught faces and haggard bodies
of the refugees themselves as they crossed the borders of Kosovo
into Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Many who came out had been on the run for days or for weeks,
living in mountains on what they carried along or could scavenge
from houses they would raid under cover of darkness. They saw their
homes destroyed by Serb grenades, cattle slaughtered and even their
children put to death.
</P>
<P>
   How can Hodit Aslemi forget the sight he described of a Serb
shooting his son, not 15 feet from where the 59-year-old sat in the
tractor that would carry the survivors of his family to safety?
</P>
<P>
   How will Ferhat Halimi look at his hand and fail to remember the
last touch of his daughter-in-law, who ran to him for help when a
Serb soldier ordered her down from her tractor cart, everyone
assumed to be raped? She was clutching Halimi's hand when the
angered soldier ran a line of bullets down her spine.
</P>
<P>
   How will Ahmed Byqmeti even be able to face going home? At the
urging of his elderly parents, he left them, his brother and
sister-in-law at home, and now he has had no word for two months.
His perpetually twisted face signals the anguish his words express.
He expects the worst, blames himself for surviving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little hope,'' he said. ``I am sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   How will the children of Haqif and Ilmija Alili grow up? The
oldest is seven and the baby four months, so none will remember
much about the harrowing four-day journey out of Kosovo, walking
and riding and walking some more, to escape the Serb shooting in
their village and threats of harm. They won't remember much of the
harsh life in a tent, where Ilmija, 27, bemoans her inability to
keep her children clean or clear up her baby's vivid heat rash.
</P>
<P>
   They never will know the father's cousin who was killed by
Serbs, but surely they will hear about him. And not for a long time
are these beautiful Kosovar Albanian children likely to rub
shoulders with any Serbs, not, said their mother, if she can help
it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
