<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-IOWA12-COX     06-11 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush faces presidential campaign realities this weekend
 &HT;    (Eds: Trip begins Saturday.)
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Gov. George W. Bush embarks today on his
first presidential campaign trip, he'll ride on a jet his aides
have christened ``Great Expectations.'' It will be packed with more
than 100 reporters poised to deflate them.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 100 reporters will be on the ground when he lands
in Cedar Rapids, Iowa. Bush's Republican rivals, and advocacy
groups eager to pin him down on controversial issues, are also
lying in wait.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bush far ahead of his rivals in the race for the
Republican nomination, and he has secured so many major GOP
endorsements and raised so much money that his nomination has taken
on an air of inevitability. But the governor stuck to his pledge to
remain in Austin until the legislative session ended on May 31, and
he hasn't yet faced the withering scrutiny of a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon ends today.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, his wife, Laura, about 20 aides and security personnel and
a media horde from around the country will leave Austin at 7:30
a.m. for Iowa, where caucuses in February will kick off the
presidential campaign season. After a full day of campaigning
there, Bush will head to Maine for a quiet Sunday with his parents
in Kennebunkport. He'll hit the campaign trail again Monday and
Tuesday in New Hampshire, which hosts the nation's first primary,
and then go to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bush traveled to Chicago and St. Louis for his first
out-of-state fundraisers, and he'll wrap up this weekend's trip
with another one in Greenwich, Conn., on Tuesday. Despite a late
start in personal fund-raising appearances, Bush's campaign war
chest may contain as much as $20 million by the end of the month,
far more than his rivals have collected. Bush has tapped so many
Republican donors that his opponents are falling short of their
fund-raising goals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor flew
back to Texas after Friday's Midwest fund-raising swing because he
wanted the chance to schmooze with reporters on the plane trip from
Austin to Iowa. Bush is adept at such personal encounters, but the
rules of the media game are about to change. The governor said he
was concentrating on the Texas Legislature while it was in session,
and he declined to detail his views on many national issues. On
others, such as the war in Kosovo, Bush weighed in after his GOP
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   After months of what The New York Times dubbed the ``Yellow Rose
Garden'' strategy, reporters are eager to press Bush for specifics.
So are Iowa voters, according to Russell Ross, a retired University
of Iowa political scientist who has been following Iowa politics
for almost half a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expect the candidate to state what he believes on the
major issues. If he does not do that, he's going to probably turn
off the people who are planning to go the polls,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tucker said Bush won't be emphasizing specific policy
proposals on this first foray out-of-state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it's really important for people to get to know him
and his philosophy and his heart and why he's running for
president,'' Tucker said. ``There will be plenty of time in the
next several months to talk specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two advocacy groups aren't waiting. In anticipation of
Bush's arrival, the Washington-based National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League (NARAL) has been publicizing
Bush's anti-abortion rights statements on billboards and in radio
spots in Iowa. NARAL spokesman Stephen Gaskill said Bush muddied
his stance on the issue several months ago when he said he was
anti-abortion rights, but wouldn't push for a constitutional
amendment banning abortion if he were elected president because
most Americans wouldn't support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is creating the impression that he wouldn't bother trying
to change where we are with choice in America today, that he
wouldn't be a hindrance to choice, or try to change access to
choice, because America's not ready for that,'' Gaskill said. ``But
we know he has a record that he will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   NARAL this week sent packets of information to reporters around
the country, Gaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition to Stop Gun Violence also blanketed the nation's
news media this week with a press release titled, ``George W. Bush
Cozies Up to Gun Industry.'' That group is highlighting Bush's
support for Texas' concealed handgun law, and a bill passed this
session that would bar Texas cities from filing lawsuits against
gun makers. Several cities have sued gun manufacturers for damages
resulting from crimes committed with their products, and gun
control advocates are betting on court action as an effective way
to curb access to guns nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one candidate who has not spelled out his position in
any detail on the gun issue,'' said group president Michael Beard.
Bush's Republican rival Elizabeth Dole recently distinguished
herself from the GOP pack by expressing support for some gun
control measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to understand that his decision on this bill in
his state is going to have national repercussions _ and we'll see
that it does,'' Beard added.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor ``believes
that the best way to deter violence is to severely punish those who
commit crimes with guns,'' and that he supports the gun liability
bill because it will curb frivolous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's rivals for the Republican nomination, several of whom
will be in Iowa this weekend, also are eager to engage him
directly. This week, several of them cautioned Iowa voters against
a rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any idea that he's ready to be president,''
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander said during a campaign
appearance in Des Moines. ``Most voters in Iowa couldn't pick him
out of a lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Commentator Pat Buchanan, publisher Steve Forbes and former Vice
President Dan Quayle also urged Iowa Republicans to keep an open
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be darned if we're going to have a nomination that's
inherited,'' Quayle said. ``That's not the way Republicans act.
They want somebody to go in there and fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's schedule (all times local)
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Rapids, Iowa , 9:45 a.m. _ Welcoming ceremony at Cedar
Rapids airport
</P>
<P>
   Des Moines, Iowa, 5 p.m. _ Reception for Iowa supporters
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   Kennebunkport, Maine, Spending the day with parents George and
Barbara Bush
</P>
<P>
   Monday
</P>
<P>
   New Castle, New Hampshire, 8 a.m. _ Community breakfast at New
Castle Recreation Center
</P>
<P>
   Manchester, New Hampshire, Noon _ New Hampshire Federation of
Republican Women Lilac Luncheon
</P>
<P>
   Bow, New Hampshire, 3:50 p.m. _ Visit to Bow Fire Station
</P>
<P>
   Goffstown, New Hampshire, 7:15 p.m. _ Reception for New
Hampshire supporters at St. Anselm's College
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Derry, New Hampshire, 7:25 a.m. _ Meet-and-greet with workers at
Hadco Industries
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, Massachusetts, 10:30 a.m. _ Visit charter school with
Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci
</P>
<P>
   Boston, Massachusetts, 12:15 _ Fundraising luncheon at Park
Plaza Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
