<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2416 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-REEL-LADN     06-11 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-REEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH HAS HAD REEL IMPACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vince Reel was such a fast runner that in one year, 1936, he
out-raced three Olympic medalists, Frank Wykoff, Mack Robinson and
Foy Draper. Once, he even beat Jesse Owens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the track hardly was the only place where people had a hard
time keeping up with Reel.
</P>
<P>
   He was an innovative coach, a pioneering author, a quick wit and
such a talented singer that his voice was heard around the country
on CBS and NBC radio shows during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   These many talents are what his friends, colleagues and former
pupils are remembering as Reel, 85, is dying of prostate cancer. In
the last few weeks, they've phoned, written and visited with Reel,
who is at a hospice in Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man of tremendous talents a man for all seasons,''
said USC track coach Ron Allice, who met Reel in the 1950s when
Reel coached at Wilson and Allice ran for Poly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a big kick out of a story in the L.A. Times a few years
ago that he was coming back to coach (at Webb High in Claremont) at
80 years of age. When I first saw the story I thought it was an
obit. I told him if it wasn't, then going back into coaching would
kill him. There's nothing like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reel grew up in Long Beach, attending Jefferson Junior High and
then Wilson High, but through track and field he saw the world. He
coached at Wilson for 20 years before making his mark on the
international scene, coaching India in the 1960 Olympics and China
at the 1972 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes he's coached have represented five countries in the
Olympics and he's been inducted into five Halls of Fame, including
the Century Club and the Mount San Antonio College Relays.
</P>
<P>
   Also through track, Reel met his second wife, Chi Cheng, a
Taiwanese sprinter who set seven world records during the 1960s
when Reel coached her.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time Reel picked a good set of legs out of a
crowd. When he coached at Wilson, he pulled John Barnes out of a
physical education class to run on the track team. Just more than
five years later, Barnes was running the 800 meters for the United
States at the 1952 Olympics in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   Once he identified talented athletes, Reel knew just which
buttons to push for them to excel.
</P>
<P>
   Dick McDonald, a pole vaulter at Wilson who tied for the state
championship in 1950, remembers striving to reach the national high
school record of 13 feet, 7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Reel gave McDonald, whose best jump at the time was 13 feet, a
seven-inch strip of cardboard for McDonald to carry in his wallet.
Each time McDonald got closer to the national record, Reel would
trim that number of inches off the piece of cardboard until he
reached the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very demanding, but he had that sense of humor,'' said
John Dixon, a former Press-Telegram sports editor who covered
Reel's teams at Wilson. ``I think when people have his ability as
an athlete, perhaps they're more demanding because they know what a
human athlete is capable of doing. He didn't like to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a point that was driven home to his athletes each
spring. Reel, while he coached at Wilson from 1938 to 1957, made a
point of taking on his top sprinters and hurdlers, even when he was
in his 40s. Reel never lost, which confounded his runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they didn't know is that Vince would get out there early
and close up the spaces between the hurdles,'' said Tom Stewart,
who ran at Wilson, Long Beach City College and USC. ``He knew how
to handle it, but everyone else would get to the first hurdle and
crash into it or be off step.''
</P>
<P>
   This determination to win
</P>
<P>
   that pushed Reel to creative, and sometimes
not-so-sportsmanlike, methods.
</P>
<P>
   In a race against rival Poly, he knew the Jackrabbits would have
two runners chase Stewart in the 880-yard race. So he had another
Wilson runner announced as ``Tom Stewart'' and instructed him to
sprint as long as he could. With half a lap to go, the pseudo
Stewart dropped out and with the two Poly runners spent, the real
Stewart raced to a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince was smart,'' said former Poly coach Leon Forman, who
coached against Reel for 10 years. ``I always admired him because
of his attitude with the kids and how he studied the game and
planned his training exercises. I thought he really knew the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Reel developed a scoring table in the decathlon that soon became
commonplace, according to Allice, and he often handicapped meets
right down to the final point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before a meet he could put the points together and know
exactly where we'd be by the time the relay (the final race) would
start,'' Stewart said. ``In all the meets I participated in, he was
right on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Reel published a book, ``3471 Tips on Track,'' in 1962 and
founded ``Women's Track and Field World'' magazine in 1968. It
folded in 1985 after other track magazines began devoting more
space to women athletes. The magazine was far ahead of his time,
according to Allice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Track and Field News adopted women's track, (Women's
Track and Field World) was the only voice in the dark for women's
track and field, not just domestically, but internationally,''
Allice said. ``He had guys who were in it for the love of it as
correspondents feeding him stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Reel left Wilson in 1957 to accept a Fulbright Fellowship at the
University of Baghdad in Iraq. He returned the next year to coach
at Claremont-Mudd, the rival of his alma mater, Occidental, for the
next 14 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he came out of retirement to coach Rim of the World
High in Lake Arrowhead to a CIF championship and, at age
</P>
<P>
   81, served as an assistant at Claremont-Mudd three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, in a letter to Dixon, Reel congratulated him on
his jogging regimen. The letter meticulously typed with equal parts
</P>
<P>
   humor and advice was all too Reel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started coaching at Redlands (at age 59), I decided I
should start running, too,'' Reel wrote. ``After months, really
months, I got so I could run a mile but it took me 11 minutes or
more. Finally I said to myself, `Reel you moron, you couldn't run a
mile when you were 20, why are you trying to run one now.' So I
stopped and have felt better ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   To contact Vince Reel, write him at the Sunrise Palomares
Nursing Home, 250 West Artesia Street, Pomona, 91768. Phone: (909)
623-3564.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
