<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOY-RIDE-HNS &LR;      06-11 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOY-RIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE END BOYS' JOY RIDE IN STOLEN PLANE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A 16-year-old boy with fewer than four hours of
flying experience sneaked out of a foster home with a friend and
took his mentor's Piper Cherokee on a midnight joyride over Central
Texas, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After a perilous pre-dawn landing in Temple, the runaway boys
refueled, took off and landed again in Brownwood, more than 100
miles from where their trip began. But the boys, including the
``amazing'' unlicensed pilot, were arrested there and now face
possible prison terms for their escapade.
</P>
<P>
   They might have gotten even farther if they had driver's
licenses, credit cards or cash for more aviation fuel, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently starting in the wee hours Thursday, the boys flew in
the fixed-wing, four-seat airplane from Georgetown to Temple, where
they landed at 5:15 a.m. CDT and mixed naturally with other
lounging flyers. About 8 a.m., they were aloft again, flying around
sprawling Fort Hood to Brownwood to rendezvous with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The ``pilot,'' who had impressed adults with quick learning
skills and a photographic memory, and his 16-year-old companion
were returned by police car from Brownwood to a Williamson County
lockup. Both youths are charged with felony theft of an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a religious person, you'll give God all the credit
in this,'' said Michael Moore, the airplane's co-owner who was the
youth's volunteer mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a night solo cross country (flight) without any
formal instructions. This is amazing,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the youth in the pilot seat previously spent only 3.5
hours in the aircraft's co-pilot seat on two flights and fewer than
90 minutes on Moore's desktop flight simulator.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he got to do was watch me from the right seat and
occasionally put his hands on the controls,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   The youths were discovered missing about 8 a.m. Thursday from
the Texas Baptist Children's Home in Round Rock, which is just
outside of Austin. Officials weren't sure how they traveled about
12 miles from the open-campus home to the Georgetown Municipal
Airport. But once there, the would-be pilot easily gained access to
the locked-up airplane. He apparently had memorized a lock
combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be the greatest flight instructor that ever lived,''
said Moore, a 56-year-old insurance agent in Round Rock, ``but I
doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore isn't a certified flight instructor but trained Air Force
pilots 30 years ago. He has been mentor to two other Baptist home
residents interested in flight.
</P>
<P>
   The youth who stole his plane had been Moore's acquaintance
since February, when they took the first flight. The second flight
was exactly two weeks ago Saturday, June 12.
</P>
<P>
   The boy wasn't just fascinated by flying, Moore said. He seemed
to pick up on the technical nuances as well or better than adult
trainees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore supplied the boy with reading material, maps and audio
tapes to get him started. The boy probably didn't study the
materials, but he understood the 1964-vintage aircraft's controls
and its new-fangled equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``On both controls are yoke-mounted GPS (geographic positioning
system) units. I showed him how to use that thing and snap, he had
it,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, on the entire flight (May 29), this kid was
really focused. He had this in his mind, he was going to do this,''
Moore speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Moore got a call from the Baptist home when the ``cottage mom''
noticed the boys missing along with an aviation map.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were afraid that he might try something with the
airplane,'' Moore said. A call to the airport confirmed his plane
was missing.
</P>
<P>
   He described the youth as ``a socially underprivileged kid'' who
had just completed his sophomore year at Round Rock High School. A
disappointing report card threatened to stall the boy's aviation
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only going to do this if he gave me good grades. He did
not give me good grades,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   The realistic simulator training may have saved the boys' lives,
Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled that simulator like a pro the first time I ever saw
him on it,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just drowning in the flush of relief that it turned out
the way it did. There's no way I can be angry at the kid,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Temple airport manager Sharon Rostovich holds no grudge, either,
even though she was duped into thinking the boys _ dressed in
Desert Storm-style military fatigues _ were soldiers from nearby
Fort Hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bought 10 gallons of fuel, but they had to scrape
together enough money to pay for it. They didn't have a credit card
or anything, but sometimes that happens,'' Rostovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, aware that free ``courtesy cars'' are sometimes
available at airports, inquired about using one, but dropped the
request when they were asked to provide a driver's license,
Rostovich said. Apparently neither had one, she said.
</P>
<P>
   While in the Temple airport, the boys visited extensively with
another youth, dressed in civilian clothes, she said. Observing
them, Rostovich was convinced they were friends and might have been
traveling together. But airport workers said only two boys arrived
on the plane and only two left on it, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured they were just soldiers waiting to be picked up,''
Rostovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They landed and took off like they knew what they were doing.
They intercomed in. They followed all the procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials also aren't sure where the boys' flight path took them
after leaving Temple, but it is known they landed more than three
hours later in Brownwood, which is less than an hour's flight away.
</P>
<P>
   Brownwood Regional Airport assistant manager Mike Wilson said
the boys landed without incident about 11:15 a.m. He said they
called an acquaintance in Brownwood and asked him for a ride into
town, but the friend had no vehicle. The boys then hopped a ride
into Early, just outside Brownwood, to rendezvous with the friend
at a convenience store, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything looked perfectly normal until (Brownwood police)
showed up with a teletype looking for a stolen airplane,'' Wilson
said. Brownwood and Early police collaborated in arresting the two
juveniles who were still at the store.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Baptist home, officials were worried about their
missing charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked the floors as we agonized over the potential,'' said
the home's manager, Jerry Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just grateful that everything's OK, with no crash, no
death, no extensive damage or anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only power we had was to say `God, watch over those boys.
We hope you'll set them down safely somewhere,''' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's going to be up to a district attorney and a judge as
to where these boys go and what happens,'' he said, adding, ``we'll
look for the good that can come out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he did what he did is amazing. It looks like to
me there was a potential for a wonderful aviation career, but I
don't know whether that's going to be now,'' Bradley lamented.
</P>
<P>
   If tried as adults and convicted, the youths face from two to 10
years in prison and up to a $10,000 fine for the third-degree
felony theft charges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
