<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOP MOVEMENTS RAISE CONCERNS OVER RUSSIA'S INTENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian troops began to move into Yugoslavia on Friday,
prompting fears among NATO leaders that the Kremlin was preparing
to seize its own peacekeeping sector in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After a flurry of urgent phone calls, the Russian foreign
minister, Igor Ivanov, assured the United States that Russia did
not plan to send troops into Kosovo before reaching an
understanding with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. concern about a potential political, and perhaps even
military, confrontation with the Russians was so great that U.S.
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, en route to Brussels,
Belgium, by plane, was instructed to turn around in mid-flight and
rush back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's mini-crisis began without warning when about 175
Russian soldiers suddenly left their peacekeeping posts in Bosnia
and drove into Yugoslavia in a column that included 20 to 30
armored vehicles. The troops had painted ``KFOR'' on their
vehicles, the name of the peacekeeping force designated for Kosovo,
indicating they eventually intended to take up positions there.
</P>
<P>
   Another 1,000 paratroopers were on alert, waiting to be flown to
Yugoslavia, the Russian defense ministry said. A senior Russian
official denied Friday night that any of the paratroopers had yet
been sent.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said Washington anticipated that additional
Russian troops would be sent to Yugoslavia because Hungary had
granted a Russian request for overflight rights for its troop
transport planes. The official added that the United States had
received conflicting reports that a Russian IL-76 troop transport
plane might have already landed in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety over the Russian troops underscores the deep
distrust between the two sides following NATO's 78-day bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia, the most divisive event in Russia's
relations with the West since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   It also points to the Russian military's increasing tendency to
openly challenge the Kosovo peace settlement, which Moscow's own
diplomats helped negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO leaders worried, Kosovo Serbs celebrated. In
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, about 3,000 local Serbs, fired by a
message on local television that Russian peacekeeping forces would
arrive there at 10 p.m. Friday, gathered in the main square, in
front of the Grand Hotel, to greet them. The crowd, boisterous and
noisy, waved Serbian and Yugoslav flags and burned an American one.
Hundreds of rounds of ammunition were shot into the air from
balconies, rooftops and the street.
</P>
<P>
   When midnight came, hundreds of people still remained waiting
for the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the alarm among NATO leaders was generated when a senior
Russian defense ministry official, Col. Gen. Leonid Ivashov,
publicly warned that Moscow might unilaterally send troops to
Kosovo if NATO did not drop its insistence that it command all the
peacekeeping forces there.
</P>
<P>
   It was the abruptness of the Russian troop movements and the
fact that they followed a deadlock about the role of Russian
peacekeepers in Kosovo that alarmed NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have insisted that all the peacekeeping troops in
Kosovo must be under a unified command led by a NATO general.
Russia, however, has adamantly refused to put its troops under NATO
control and has insisted that it be given a sector of its own to
control.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was dealt with indirectly in the resolution the U.N.
Security Council adopted. An annex to the resolution refers to the
need for ``unified command and control'' but does not say
explicitly that NATO must lead the force.
</P>
<P>
   After generals from the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff and the
Russian defense ministry failed to agree in talks here Friday on a
solution to the question of command, the chief Russian negotiator
issued a blunt warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this agreement is not reached, Russia has the same right as
NATO,'' Ivashov said. ``We shall announce a sector that will be
agreed with the Yugoslav side and which will meet our interests.''
</P>
<P>
   His words, coupled with reports of Russian troop movements, set
off alarm bells at NATO's military headquarters in Belgium and at
the Skopje, Macedonia, headquarters of the allied peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military leaders were worried that the Russians might
simply drive into Kosovo, claim a sector in the northern and
heavily Serbian part of the province and, in the words of one
ranking allied official, ``create facts on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is vehemently opposed to the establishment of a
Russian sector, fearing that ethnic Albanians would be afraid to
return there. This could create a de facto partitioning of Kosovo,
with ethnic Albanians in some areas and Serbs in others, an
arrangement NATO has said it would never allow.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that NATO might have won its war with Yugoslavia only to
lose control of the peace, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who was visiting Macedonia, made an urgent phone call to her
counterpart, Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially repudiating Gen. Ivashov, the Russian foreign
minister assured Albright that Russian troops would not enter
Kosovo without an understanding with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, Ivanov added, is simply doing what NATO has been doing
for months: assembling peacekeeping forces outside Kosovo in the
anticipation that they will soon be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreign minister said he understands that there was to be
a unified command,'' Albright said. ``He also said this was a
preliminary step so that if and when they become part of the
international security presence today, they will be in a position
to deploy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, Albright was so concerned about the confusion within the
Russian ranks that she asked Talbott, who had just completed
several days of talks here, to return to Moscow for urgent
consultations on the command issue. Talbott remains in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ivanov's assurance, Russia remains deeply unhappy over
NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and the way the alliance is managing
the peace.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin said Friday that relations with NATO
would remain frozen. And the Russian foreign minister said Friday
night that Moscow would never agree to a command arrangement in
which its troops are ``subordinated'' to NATO officers.
</P>
<P>
   One fear, a Russian official said Friday night, is that NATO
peacekeepers will enter Kosovo and spread out through the province.
By the time a solution for the command problem is found, the
Russian peacekeepers would be superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are concerns that if NATO enters Kosovo first there
might be no place left for other forces,'' the Russian official
said. ``We will be begging for some place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated at NATO's stance, Ivanov hinted in a television
interview Friday night that Russian troops might not participate in
the peacekeeping force if the command issue is not worked out.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a major setback for the Clinton administration's
efforts to involve Moscow in a Balkan settlement and restore
American-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov's comment may have been intended to increase the pressure
on NATO to work out a compromise. Still, it was a less worrisome
form of pressure than Ivashov's brinksmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was not the first time that the Russian military appeared
to have chartered its own foreign policy on Kosovo. After the
Russian special envoy, Victor Chernomyrdin, returned from his
mission to Belgrade with the Finnish president, Ivashov assailed
the accord as a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin later intervened to support a settlement. Ivashov,
however, not only kept his position; he led the Russian delegation
in the talks Friday on command arrangements for peacekeepers in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration sought to put the best
face on the surprising Russian troop movements and the seemingly
intractable issue of command.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work it out,'' President Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
