<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2423 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV1     06-11 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC VIEW: A MARSHALL PLAN, ON THE CHEAP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 13)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When George Marshall died in 1959 he left strict
instructions: No eulogies. But getting politicians to follow
commands, even those issued by former generals, is tricky business.
And these days nearly everyone is paying homage to the Marshall
Plan, which rebuilt Europe and Japan after World War II and became
the gold standard for reconstructing some very deconstructed
corners of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the foreign
ministers of Europe were talking about a ``Marshall Plan for the
Balkans.'' It will be a main subject of discussion at the annual
summit meeting of industrialized nations later this week in
Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   At the same meeting, an agreement is expected on whether and how
to forgive the debts of some of the world's poorest nations, which
owe upwards of $130 billion in loans that they can probably never
repay. Lifting that burden, advocates say, amounts to a Marshall
Plan for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the term is no surprise: Congress despises foreign
aid almost as much as it loves phantom tax cuts. But call it a
Marshall Plan, and suddenly it's not a handout, but a noble effort
to turn beaten, bombed-out, or broke nations into models of
democratic capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one real difference: The politicians who invoke the
terminology these days are not really interested in paying
Marshall-sized money.
</P>
<P>
   By most estimates, the Marshall Plan cost about 2 percent of
America's gross national product each year from 1947 to 1951. If
the same ratio were used today, after the biggest run-up in
national wealth in a century, the United States would spend $160
billion a year on modern Marshall Plans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the talk is of spending only a tiny fraction of that
figure, perhaps forgiving a bit more than $600 million for the
poorest nations, assuming they meet a number of reform conditions
that many have resisted.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that true Marshall Plans are not big sellers
these days. During the Cold War they carried a strategic logic of
their own, shoring up economies so that nations would not be
tempted to spread communism. They also helped American industry by
creating export markets. But in the post-Cold War era, there is far
less enthusiasm for spending money to encourage countries to adopt
Western-style capitalism, much less to become customers.
</P>
<P>
   So the same countries that are enthusiastic about new Marshall
Plans talk even more enthusiastically about how to make others pay
for them.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs barely stopped dropping on Belgrade last week before
the NATO allies began jockeying about who would pick up the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows it's going to be expensive, but it has to be
done,'' Ms. Albright said. Then, in background briefings, U.S.
officials said that the United States had borne most of the cost of
prosecuting the war, so Europe ought to pay to rebuild Kosovo and
aid Albania and Macedonia. The price tag gyrates from $5 billion to
$100 billion, depending on whether people are talking just about
rebuilding roads and power lines and the like or about a wholesale
economic upgrade for the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the real arm-wrestling is taking place over debt forgiveness
for the poorest nations, chiefly in Africa. It's one of those ideas
that everyone agrees on in general but almost no one can agree on
in specific.
</P>
<P>
   No one thinks debt service should be allowed to keep gobbling 60
percent or more of destitute countries' budgets. But neither is
there much support for 100 percent debt forgiveness, no strings
attached. The International Monetary Fund and others fear that
simply writing off debts creates a serious ``moral hazard'' _ the
expectation that future borrowing need not be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, describing the
American position last week, talked about step-by-step debt relief
in return for real economic reforms _ more openness, enforceable
property rights, revamped banking systems _ akin to those asked of
South Korea, Indonesia, Russia and others in return for IMF
bailouts.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is figuring out who pays. The French and the
Japanese, who have done the most country-to-country lending, like
the idea that Western nations would contribute in proportion to the
size of their economies _ meaning the United States would pay the
most. Washington, not surprisingly, has a different formula in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Aid groups fear that debt forgiveness will cannibalize other
aid. ``We want to see as much debt relief as possible,'' said Lydia
Williams, a policy adviser at Oxfam America, who has been lobbying
Congress for a bigger package, but ``it has to be additional, new
resources to do much good.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jeffrey D. Sachs of Harvard points out, after an astounding
boom, the West could afford to solve the problem ``without
resorting to the kinds of huge numbers'' involved in the Marshall
Plan. ``It's just a matter of political will,'' he said _ which
Marshall had less trouble gathering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
