<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2424 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NRA-WOES-ART-2TAKES-N     06-11 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-WOES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA REGAINS LOST VIGOR AS NEW GUN MEASURES ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Colo., N.Y., Mo., Va., Pa., Okla., Tenn., Idaho, Ga., Ark.,
Mich., Texas, N.C.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JAMES DAO and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of drift and disarray, the National
Rifle Association finds itself right where many of its leaders want
it to be: under attack.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has found new life, members and money through
mass mailings that portray gun owners and sportsmen as being under
siege. Two weeks after the last funeral for a victim in the high
school shootings at Littleton, Colo., the NRA sent letters to its
2.6 million members, warning that President Clinton would ``demand
that you pay the price for the insanity of the killers.''
</P>
<P>
   With the threat of new gun control measures being voted next
week by the House of Representatives, checks are flowing into the
organization, which for decades had been one of the most
influential and feared single-issue advocacy groups. Its members
have hit congressional offices with a blizzard of e-mail messages
and phone calls opposing new gun restrictions. At the state level,
the rifle association is pushing legislation to prohibit municipal
lawsuits against the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, the NRA has been struggling with a heavy
debt, rebellions within its ranks and declining membership and
revenues. Its image was battered after the Oklahoma City bombing,
when the group was accused of being a bastion for right-wing
extremists, and again after a recent series of school shootings
that have helped transform the gun-control debate into a children's
safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   Its vaunted ability to win elections and oust enemies came into
question when several of its closest congressional allies lost
races last year. And in April, the NRA failed to persuade Missouri
voters to approve a pro-gun ballot referendum, despite spending
$3.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the two months since Littleton, the 127-year-old association
asserts that its membership has grown by tens of thousands and that
its contributions have increased sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The new money will bolster a $20 million lobbying and political
fund that the group uses to lavish campaign contributions on its
loyal supporters, and to punish its enemies in state and federal
elections across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Since Memorial Day, the group, through its sophisticated
direct-mail and phone banks operations, has mobilized its members
to call and write their congressional representatives, who are
considering the most comprehensive set of gun-control initiatives
since the assault-weapons ban in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The barrage seems to be working. In recent days, many members of
the House have stiffened their resolve to oppose any new
gun-control measures. And some of the precise provisions that the
NRA has demanded _ provisions that would weaken the bills _ have
already appeared in House Republican versions of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adversity is not our worst enemy,'' said James Jay Baker, the
organization's chief lobbyist. ``Our obituary has been published
before.''
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, the NRA will face a crucial test of its
influence in Washington as the House votes on several gun-control
measures like requiring background checks of gun buyers at gun
shows and raising the minimum age for buying a gun to 21 from 18.
</P>
<P>
   But Capitol Hill is just one of several battlefronts for the NRA
It is working in state legislatures across the country against new
gun restrictions and for bills that would prohibit cities from
suing gun manufacturers (to date, more than a dozen cities have
filed such suits). Its leadership is struggling to balance between
conservatives who think the group has been too conciliatory and gun
company executives who think that it has been too uncompromising.
</P>
<P>
   And, as always, the organization is trying to counter what it
considers unfairly negative portrayals of it in the national media
_ like Rosie O'Donnell's recent criticism of one of her guests,
actor Tom Selleck, for supporting the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the group can juggle so many
conflicts at a time when its resources are already spread thin and
its membership has dipped precariously close to a 20-year low
point. To its loyal members, the answer is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rallying cause,'' said former Rep. Gerald Solomon, a
lifetime NRA member from New York. ``They rally together just like
the Serbs support Milosevic, because they think their country is
being attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the association needs to fight many political and
legal battles, its resources are strained. In the 1990s, the
association spent more than it took in every year except two,
according to a review of the group's tax returns from 1990 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has also suffered steadily declining
membership, from a high of 3.5 million in 1995 to 2.6 million now.
Some dissatisfied members attribute the membership decline to the
group's moderation of some of its positions.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, the lobbyist, defended the group's decision to accept
some modest gun-control measures in the House bill to be voted on
next week. ``I just think that the political realities of the
situation that we find ourselves in, between the Congress and the
media, has dictated that we have to roll up our sleeves and come up
with a responsive proposal or there are going to be no gun shows,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite its numerous internal problems, the NRA still commands
respect among legislators all over the country. As almost any
member of Congress can attest, the association's power derives from
its large campaign war chest, its sophisticated lobbying and its
national network of organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the NRA contributed more than $4 million to
congressional campaigns and spent an additional $1.5 million
lobbying Congress. Its political action committee ranked with trial
lawyers and doctors as one of the most generous special interest
groups. In October 1998, the NRA's Political Victory Fund spent
more than $1.6 million for radio advertisements in 42 closely
contested House and Senate races. Just since last month's Senate
vote, the group has spent more than $1 million on phone banks and
mailings. And in the last week, it has been running radio ads in
the districts of conservative Democrats, urging them to vote
against new gun restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   At its headquarters in Fairfax, Va., the group employs 75 people
in its political division, the Institute for Legislative Action.
And through its Web site, mailings, three magazines and
affiliations with more than 100 gun-rights groups, the organization
keeps in close touch with hundreds of thousands of gun owners
beyond its own membership.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate approved gun control measures last month,
the vote still offered clear evidence of the NRA's influence. All
of the top recipients of its campaign contributions over the last
five years voted against the restrictions, says a study by the
Center for Responsive Politics. Those senators included Rick
Santorum, R-Pa., $19,700; James Inhofe, R-Okla., $17,350; John
Ashcroft, R-Mo., $14,850, and Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., $11,450.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the NRA maintains strong institutional links to
Congress. Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, and Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., sit
on the group's 76-member board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, many incumbents say they fear the rifle association
because it has a long record of turning against lawmakers who buck
it just once, and has a long memory for perceived transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., who retired in 1997, said he
infuriated the NRA in 1961 by proposing a bill in the state
Legislature that would have made it illegal to leave a loaded rifle
or shotgun in an unattended, unlocked vehicle. The NRA killed the
bill and then opposed him _ unsuccessfully _ every time he ran for
office in the next three decades, Pryor said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich., an NRA ally who is
considering voting for some new gun restrictions, found his
district flooded with letters from the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep taking our heads off, don't count on us to be
there,'' Stupak said he told the NRA officials. ``But,'' he added,
``the fear factor is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a perception in Congress that the association can
defeat even entrenched incumbents, and members often cite the case
of former Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas. A staunch NRA supporter for 40
years, Brooks lost its support in 1994 when he voted for a crime
bill that included an assault weapons ban. Later that year, he lost
his race for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not reliable,'' Brooks said. ``If you are not 110
percent for them, then they are against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Baker, the association's chief lobbyist, said that the
group would continue to single out pro-gun control legislators by
giving tens of thousands of dollars to their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But that record is mixed. Last year, two of its strongest
allies, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Sen. Lauch Faircloth,
R-N.C., were defeated, even though the group pumped more than
$400,000 into the two campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the NRA's fearsome reputation rests on its aggressive
lobbying presence in all 50 state capitals and its ability to
mobilize gun owners to vote in even minor state and local
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In its major effort of the past year, the NRA has also succeeded
in getting 10 states to enact laws prohibiting cities from filing
lawsuits against the gun industry. Similar bills are awaiting
governors' signatures in Texas, Oklahoma and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But the group has clearly lost ground in some states, even as it
increases its spending. Earlier this year, it had a big setback in
Missouri, where it spent $3.7 million in support of a referendum to
allow legal gun owners to carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   More than defeats at the ballot box, the anti-gun oratory after
the Littleton shootings has enraged, and activated, NRA members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun owners tend to respond when they feel threatened,'' said
Alan Gottlieb, founder of the Second Amendment Foundation. ``And
they feel more threatened right now than ever.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
