<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-BOS &LR;      06-11 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA'S INFLUENCE SEEPS INTO GUN DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House prepares to vote next week on the
politically explosive issue of gun control, congressional aides say
the National Rifle Association remains potent enough to doom the
modest measures passed by the Senate, despite the public's embrace
of restrictions since the Colorado school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, in fact, continues to enjoy so much clout that House
Republican aides agreed to work privately with its lobbyists this
week to accommodate some of their concerns as the legislation was
drafted, according to GOP aides and the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   While the NRA did not get exactly what it wanted, the lobby's
influence during the early stages of House discussions on gun
control has reversed the prevailing opinion that pronounced the gun
lobby weakened after last month's defeats in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our epitaph has been written many times,'' said Jim Manown, an
NRA spokesman, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers say the NRA's power, in the form of campaign
contributions as well as a voting bank of 2.9 million members, has
hampered the Republican Party's attempt to remake its pro-gun image
as the presidential election approaches. And though no one is sure
how the House vote will go, the partisan fight could sink the
overall $1.5 billion juvenile violence bill that contains the gun
provisions, congressional aides say.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert announced this week that he will
not pressure GOP lawmakers on the gun-control measures and will let
the House ``work its will'' on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think even within our conference there are two or three
different points of view, and legitimately so,'' said Hastert, an
Illinois Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Friday by the US Conference of Mayors, Hastert
was urged to pass tougher legislation raising the legal age of gun
buyers from 18 to 21, and requiring higher age restrictions for all
firearms buyers and background checks for all customers at gun
shows. Hastert favors such background checks and other measures
aimed at keeping guns out of the hands of children.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's two-pronged lobbying strategy, which was advertised on
the Internet, in mainstream newspapers, and all over Capitol Hill,
began two months ago with a campaign that questioned the wisdom of
passing new gun-control laws when the Clinton administration is not
enforcing existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   In one advertisement in The Wall Street Journal, the NRA wrote
that the government prosecuted only 37 cases where felons bought
firearms through straw purchases, 11 cases where individuals
provided guns to juveniles, and 11 cases of juveniles caught with
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``More firearms legislation, like previous legislation, that is
passed with no intention of enforcement is a dangerous fraud,'' the
ad said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said it could not comment on particular
prosecutions but defended its record, pointing out that combined
state-federal prosecutions of gun crimes were up 22 percent since
1992. The number of federal cases in which an offender is sentenced
to more than five years also rose 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many Republicans took up these arguments to defeat
stronger gun-control provisions and to add measures to their
gun-control proposal, such as requiring the attorney general to
assign federal prosecutors specifically to enforce gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure of the Clinton administration to prosecute federal gun
crimes is unconscionable at this critical time,'' said Oklahoma
Representative J.C. Watts, in a statement for the House Republican
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the NRA's strategy has been promoting the
idea that the Senate's gun-control measures would hamstring gun
sellers and buyers in a maze of red tape.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would ``impose a cradle-to-grave massive federal
regulatory scheme on gunowners throughout America,'' read a letter
the NRA encouraged its members to send to their representatives.
</P>
<P>
   These arguments showed up as House GOP members drafted a bill
that would ease record-keeping requirements by gun sellers and
gun-show promoters, make tracing of guns more difficult, and narrow
the definition of a gun show, so that vendors at small gatherings
and flea markets would be able buy and sell guns without conducting
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and congressional Democrats immediately
denounced the House proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their legislation is a total joke that effectively does
nothing for gun control,'' said Julian Epstein, the Democratic
counsel on the House Judiciary Committee. ``It is the NRA version
of the bill, and there's absolutely no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates such as Kristen Rand, director of federal
policy for the Violence Policy Center, a Washington gun-control
research group, argued that the Republican proposal would gut the
Senate bill, which would mandate background checks on the
purchasers of all firearms sold at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Republican bill you could have individuals offering
thousands of guns for sale by nine vendors, and no background
checks,'' Rand said about the House proposal. The measure would
change the Senate definition of a gun show from a place where 50 or
more guns are sold to a place where 10 or more vendors gather,
regardless of the number of guns sold.
</P>
<P>
   But Repubicans dismissed the notion that they are beholden to
the NRA, and they accused Democrats of threatening the entire
juvenile justice bill to create a political issue for the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Representative Henry Hyde, chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee charged with drafting the Republican
leadership's measure, said he is seeking legislation with a
realistic chance of passing the House, where pro-gun forces have
traditionally been strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegation that the NRA wrote this legislation is
nonsense,'' said Hyde, who said he never met with NRA
representatives though his staff did. Hyde said that most of the
four provisions in the new bill mirror the Senate's proposal, which
the NRA opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the NRA's involvement so far, it is far from clear how
the gun-control issue will be decided in the House. Between 160 and
180 members firmly oppose gun control, and that includes about 40
conservative Democrats from states such as Michigan and Texas,
according to congressional aides. There are a similar number of
swing Republicans who support tougher restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to assuage party conservatives, some Republicans
are trying to write a weaker version of Hyde's proposal, but
moderate Republicans and Democrats are unlikely to support that.
Meanwhile, a vote on the Senate's version is expected to be
extremely close. At the end of the day, congressional aides say,
both proposals could fail.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has spent $750,000 on a mailing campaign and $300,000 on
a phone bank operation to generate opposition since the Senate's
action, according to the NRA's Manown. He said that once the NRA
illustrated that its clout had not diminished, the group began
working with the Republican aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ability to influence the legislative process comes from
the strength of our members,'' Manown said. ``We urge them to
contact their elected representatives and voice their opinions,
which is something they do outstandingly well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
