<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI TEAM GOING TO KOSOVO THIS WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Great Britain, France)  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An advance team of FBI agents will go to Kosovo
this weekend to assess the forensic needs of the international
authorities who are about to start the most thorough inquiry into
war crimes since World War II, federal law-enforcement officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This week, an administration official recounted, the chief
prosecutor for the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia, Louise Arbour, asked the United States to contribute
crime-scene experts; videotape, photographic and mapping
specialists; explosives and ballistics experts, and forensic
pathologists.
</P>
<P>
   At The Hague, Netherlands, on Friday, Ms. Arbour's deputy,
Graham Blewitt, said that the first investigators would enter
Kosovo early next week, one step behind the first wave of
international security forces.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, Secretary-General Kofi Annan said the
tribunal would ask countries to lend 300 forensic specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the findings of the advance team, officials here
said, the FBI will probably send more than 25 people to the region.
The initial goal will be to conduct preliminary investigations and
recommend which crimes should be investigated further.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here said U.S. intelligence information like satellite
photographs would be extensively used to guide investigators to the
sites of presumed atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The initial focus will be guided by photographic intelligence
and interviews with refugees, officials said. They added that early
attention would be given to the seven locations identified as the
scenes of mass executions in the indictment on May 27 of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and four political and military
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here and in Europe said speed was essential to seal
off the sites where mass murder, torture and other crimes were
suspected before evidence could be destroyed or tampered with, and
to interview witnesses while incidents were fresh in their minds.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Pentagon, Kenneth Bacon, showed photographs
this week that he said indicated that Yugoslav forces had bulldozed
a mass grave in Izbica in western Kosovo in an attempt to destroy
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A team of eight forensic experts from the Royal Canadian Mounted
Police has been assigned to work for a month gathering evidence in
Kosovo for the tribunal, Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy of Canada
said.
</P>
<P>
   In London, a spokesman for the government said Britain would
provide a team of 15 forensic specialists. France will contribute
at least 12 ballistics experts, forensic doctors and police
photographers, a spokesman for the foreign ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, government officials and refugee and relief
organizations have been conducting interviews and passing out
questionnaires at the Kosovo borders to glean information about
possible war crimes and to prepare lists of witnesses who might
testify in trials in The Hague. Refugees who have relocated to
Western Europe have also been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   In France and the Netherlands, special attention is being paid
to cases of sexual attacks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a few months, the United States and its allies will have to
decide how much money they are prepared to pay to finance the
inquiries. The tribunal budget for the calendar year 1999 was
prepared last fall, before the Kosovo conflict began. With the
support of Congress, the Clinton administration has sent an
additional $9 million to the voluntary trust fund of the tribunal
to help meet expenses for the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has not prepared its budget for 2000. Officials
said the United States would obviously be asked to pay millions
more than it did this year.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the investigations in Kosovo would be
much more thorough and extensive than they were in Bosnia in 1995.
In part, that is because NATO forces will be in control in Kosovo,
and investigators will be free to go where their searches take
them. Another reason is that most atrocities in Kosovo were
committed in the last three months, making evidence and testimony
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, investigators met strong resistance in the regions
under Bosnian Serb control. Some atrocities in Bosnia were
committed as 1992. And even later crimes, like the massacre at
Srebrenica, were not explored until months after they had been
committed, leaving considerable time for tampering with evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
