<HEADER>
A2435 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACUZZI-JACUZZI_SFCHR     06-11 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACUZZI-JACUZZI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Hot Water, Cold Cash _ How Roy Jacuzzi turned family business 
 into global bath empire 
 &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
For a guy whose name is associated with bubbles, steam and nudity,
Roy Jacuzzi is surprisingly unassuming.
<P>
   The suit-clad, gray-templed Jacuzzi lives quietly in a
91/2-bathroom house in Contra Costa County. Every morning the
55-year-old executive watches the news in his $10,000 J-Allure
shower/steam bath with a built-in television set. Then he drives to
the headquarters of Jacuzzi Inc. in Walnut Creek, where he runs a
global bath empire founded decades ago by his immigrant forebears.
</P>
<P>
   The whirlpool bath business, far from drying up with the
encounter-group culture of the 1970s, has never been better. And
Roy Jacuzzi _ who was the first to sell whirlpools for purposes of
leisure, rather than therapy _ has been riding the wave for more
than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacuzzis have been engineering innovators since the turn of
the century, when Roy Jacuzzi's grandfather, Joseph, and Joseph's
six brothers immigrated to the East Bay from Pomone, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers had little formal education, but their Albany
company, Jacuzzi Bros., revolutionized aeronautics. Frank,
Valeriano, Rachele, Candido, Giocondo, Gelindo and Joseph Jacuzzi
are honored in the Smithsonian's National Air and Space Museum for
building the first enclosed monoplane.
</P>
<P>
   After a tragic plane accident in 1918, which killed Gelindo and
forced the company into bankruptcy, the brothers redirected their
engineering skills to agricultural irrigation systems, a business
that remains a small part of Jacuzzi Inc. today. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  By the time young Roy joined the company in the mid-1960s,
fresh from the University of California at Berkeley, Jacuzzi Bros.
had begun diversifying into swimming pool pumps and a mobile
hydrotherapy pump that could be used in a bathtub. (The latter was
developed to treat a family member with rheumatoid arthritis.) But
agriculture was still its focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather and his brothers thought I was a little
unusual'' when presented with the idea of installing hydraulic jets
in bathtubs, recalls Jacuzzi, who studied industrial design and
engineering in college.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the project got the go-ahead. In 1968, Jacuzzi began
peddling his first model, the Roman Bath, at home builder and
plumbing trade shows. (Actress Suzanne Somers posed for early
advertisements.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, Jacuzzi Inc. is a subsidiary of U.S. Industries, a
publicly held consumer-products conglomerate in Iselin, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Jacuzzi, whose goods are sold in more than 100 countries, is
expected to rack up more than $650 million in sales this year and
is aggressively acquiring competitors in the United States and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy is a very smart marketer who certainly understood that the
market was turning in the direction of leisure and fitness and
style and all the stuff that whirlpools are associated with,'' said
Eliot Sefrin, publisher of Kitchen and Bath Design News, a trade
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the most admirable thing is that he just went out
there and pushed the thing like heck at every trade show he
could,'' said Sefrin. ``It was very entrepreneurial. He really
believed in it.''
</P>
<P>
   To prime the pump for a product that was considered somewhat
bizarre, Jacuzzi gave home builders a great deal: For every $700
whirlpool tub they bought, contractors kept $350. That compared to
a $20 profit on each $100 conventional tub they installed.
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi took home 50 or 60 orders from his first trade show. At
the time, the whirlpool bath ``was a selling feature that made a
home unique and different,'' said Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   Today _ whether most homeowners actually use them or not _
whirlpool bathtubs are a standard feature in high-end homes. But
the fastest-growing category is under-$1,000 tubs sold at big-box
stores like Lowe's and Home Depot, a segment Jacuzzi entered just
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just stuck to the luxury market and sold through
distributors, you'd be talking flat growth to about 5 percent,''
said Brian Langenberg, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston.
``Home centers are pulling in a lot of that business.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for whirlpool tubs at Home Depot, where they sell for
$350 to $1,000, ``outpaces other (bathroom) fixtures by far,'' said
Gene Boiseau, the retailer's West Coast plumbing merchant.
</P>
<P>
   In total, Americans will install 427,000 whirlpool bathtubs in
new homes and 405,000 in remodelled bathrooms this year, estimates
the National Kitchen and Bath Association.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor whirlpools, known as ``spas,'' are a smaller part of
Jacuzzi's business than the indoor variety. At Home Depot, however,
the sales growth of its spas outpaces that of indoor whirlpools,
according to Boiseau.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast, an area where spas are just catching on, sales
rose 700 percent in the first four months of the year. A stunning
$9 million dollars worth of spas were sold in a Memorial Day
promotion at Home Depot, said Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jacuzzi Inc.'s biggest problem these days is keeping up
with demand. Just this week, it acquired Gatsby Spa, a $24
million-a-year company, and plans to immediately use Gatsby's
excess plant capacity to fill back orders, Jacuzzi said.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Gatsby and the 1998 purchase of Sundance
Spas, which had been the second-largest spa-maker, Jacuzzi now
accounts for about half of U.S. spa sales, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi Inc. is able to dramatically reduce costs among its
acquired companies because it can buy raw materials like acrylic
more cheaply as it grows. The company also installs Jacuzzi pump
systems in its new tub lines, many of which had used pumps made by
Jacuzzi rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacuzzi doesn't want to dominate only the whirlpool
business. Fueled by cash from its parent company, it is plotting a
takeover of the whole bathroom _ and the yard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Jacuzzi acquired a Canadian swimming pool company,
Haugh Products, maker of Atlantic-brand pools. That purchase
instantly made Jacuzzi the country's biggest manufacturer of
above-ground pools.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Jacuzzi spent $745 million buying Zurn
Industries, the maker of Zurn- and Elger-brand toilets, kitchen and
bathroom sinks, faucets and drains, items that Jacuzzi had never
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Since the average upscale home is being built with 21/2 baths,
``if you're only selling them a whirlpool for the master suite,
you've got another bath and a half you're not really working
with,'' Jacuzzi explained.
</P>
<P>
   Showers are another important area, since most people prefer
showers to baths for their morning ablutions.
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi is spending hefty development dollars on high-end
shower/bath combo systems. For example, the two-person J-Allure
comes with two shower heads, six side jets that shoot water at body
level, steam, a whirlpool bath, a TV, a VCR, a CD player, an AM/FM
radio and four speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The $8,000-to-$10,000 unit is for people with a lot of
``disposable, and I do mean disposable, income,'' observed
Langenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the United States, Jacuzzi operates plants in Europe and
South America, and it opened its first Asian factory in Singapore
last year. Jacuzzi will be well positioned when the economies of
those areas improve, said Jeanette Daly, an analyst with First
Honolulu Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Jacuzzi's major acquisitions have been funded by its
parent, U.S. Industries, which was spun off of Hanson, a British
industrial conglomerate, in 1995. ``The capital from U.S.
Industries has really been a godsend,'' said Jacuzzi. ``I've got
some pretty aggressive objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi said his company's 1999 revenues would be higher than a
$650 million forecast by Langenberg. He declined to be more
specific, but said that with various acquisitions, ``We're well on
our way to being a billion-dollar company.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the billion-dollar goal would put Jacuzzi in the same
league as industry leader Kohler, a privately owned Wisconsin
manufacturer that industry sources estimate sells $1.2 billion of
toilets, sinks and the like each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see Kohler as good competition, and getting into toilets
and sinks is a definite opportunity for us to rival Kohler some
more,'' Jacuzzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone is convinced that Jacuzzi is home free.
``Even though they are No.1 in the world, they are not the most
innovative,'' said Jeffrey Burton, owner of San Francisco's Bath
and Beyond showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Rival manufacturers have begun making tubs that create thousands
of tiny bubbles instead of ``slapping you around with jets,''
Burton said. The bubble tubs are also quieter than Jacuzzi's jet
tubs. Other innovations include underwater lights that change color
and sound-wave therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi said his company has plenty of innovations on the
drawing board, including aroma therapy, ultraviolet tanning, and a
feature that will use warm air to ``dry you like a desert wind''
following a bath or shower.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company makes a small line of bubbling tubs, Roy
doesn't foresee a big future in them. ``It's sort of like getting a
Ferrari with a two-horsepower engine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi has no current  &LR; plans to leave his post as Jacuzzi
Inc.'s chairman, president and chief executive. When he does, there
is no fourth-generation heir apparent. Roy Jacuzzi was the only one
of 257 family stockholders to stay with the company after it was
sold 25 years ago to Walter Kidde &AMP; Co. (which was acquired by
Hanson in 1987).
</P>
<P>
   Jacuzzi's two grown sons, Joseph and Jason, have gone into other
fields. It's too early to tell about Lincoln, 11, or Giordano, 5,
but Giordano is showing good instincts _ he watches cartoons every
morning in the J-Allure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
