<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Computer Glitch Halts EBay's Auction Service 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A computer glitch caused an all-day outage on eBay's popular
auction service yesterday, disrupting bidding on millions of Beanie
Babies, Barbie dolls, autographed photos of Mother Teresa and other
items.
<P>
   It was one of the largest Internet outages yet in terms of time
out and revenues lost.
</P>
<P>
   EBay is one of the top 10 Internet sites in terms of &LR; 
 &LR; transactions and one of the few that is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose company lets people in 50 countries buy and sell
almost anything online. Ebay gets a commission on every item sold.
It lists up to 2 million items at a time, and claims to get 500
bids per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Even among competing auction sites, which reported increased
business yesterday, there was fear that the eBay hiatus will scare
people away from doing business online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned what effects this might have on the entire
e-commerce community,'' said Sharon Greenspan, a spokeswoman for
Seattle-based Amazon.com, the online bookseller that recently added
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Some intermittent problems first cropped up Wednesday on eBay,
after the company reorganized its Web site to make it easier to
use.
</P>
<P>
   It shut down entirely at 8 p.m. Thursday and was still
inoperable early last &LR; yesterday evening. During the outage, a team
of 50 engineers struggled to repair corrupted data files.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry, but the eBay system is temporarily unavailable,''
the company said in an online message after service went out
Thursday night. ``We extend our utmost apologies for this
inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   By yesterday morning, though, that message was replaced with a
more cryptic note: ``Damage to the system is more extensive than
expected.'' The company emphasized that no data was lost, and the
outage was unrelated to the ExploreZip.worm virus which spread via
e-mail worldwide this week.
</P>
<P>
   Auctions that were scheduled to end yesterday &UR;  &LR; will be extended
by 48 hours after service is restored, eBay said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet glitches happen all the time, but the eBay blackout is
probably the biggest since America Online was off-line for 19 hours
in August 1996. AOL came under intense fire, but the company made a
concerted effort to improve its reliability and eventually came out
stronger than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can rebound from this the way AOL did a few
years ago,'' eBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove said. ``We've got to
make this up to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers who make all or some of their living selling items on
eBay were especially hard hit.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ostrowski of Cincinnati, who made $6,000 last month selling
used books and magazines, said the outage is ``killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   MarGee Charlier, a small-business owner in Kewaunee, Wisc., who
supplements her income by selling antiques on eBay, told the
Associated Press the daylong crash was a ``disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers warned that consumers who are still leery
about the reliability of shopping online may be scared off by
problems at eBay, which handles about 80 percent of online
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sellers have their inventories locked in eBay, which not only
hurts them but the entire e-commerce market,'' said Larry Schwartz,
president of AuctionUniverse.com, a competing online auction house
based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   AuctionUniverse.com reported an 80 percent in transactions and a
30-percent jump in new memberships the past few days. But in the
long run, Schwartz said, Ebay's problem ``is not good news for any
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly for eBay. In a recent survey by Jupiter
Communications, 46 percent of consumers polled said they will
abandon an e-commerce site with technical or performance problems
and go to a competing site. Of those, about half will eventually go
back to the site they left if the problems are solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auction sites, by nature, have loyal users. But at some point,
people are going to lose their loyalty to eBay and look at other
options like Amazon.com and Yahoo,'' said Fiona Swerdlow, senior
analyst of Jupiter Communications in New York. ``This is a huge
concern to eBay, yet they can't seem to get their arms around it.
They've got to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   EBay has suffered four outages in the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A six-hour shutdown on June 9 prevented the company from hosting
auctions of merchandise from the latest ``Star Wars'' movie.
Customers instead flocked to Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Last month eBay stopped auctions on two occasions, for about
seven hours on May 20 and four hours on May 3, because of technical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   EBay's earned $7 million in profits on revenues of $34 million
in the first quarter of this year. The company, which only went
public in September, has a market value of $20 billion and 3.8
million registered users _ almost twice the membership it had at
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The outage caused eBay's high-flying stock to plunge $16.81, or
9 percent, to $165.88 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   At least one EBay customer was heartened by yesterday's debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This outage is much like a fire drill or power outage during
normal business activity,'' said Roger Rymer of Dallas. ``It brings
you down to Earth and causes you to take a calm look at what you
are really in the midst of. In my mind, it is healthy for all of
us. But when the lights come back on, I'm getting cranked up to
really burn again.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
