<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS ENTER KOSOVO CAPITAL; SERBS CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to move ASAP.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Breaking assurances given to Washington,
a long column of Russian peacekeeping troops entered Kosovo and its
capital early Saturday morning amid scenes of wild celebration by
local Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people packed the streets to welcome the Russian
troops, firing pistols and automatic weapons into the air and
throwing flowers on Russian armored personnel carriers and jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians arrived in a column of some 50 military vehicles
and trucks as NATO peacekeeping forces on the border with Macedonia
prepared to move into kosovo later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The unilateral Russian entry into kosovo is sure to cause a new
crisis with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It came despite promises on Friday from the Russian foreign
minister, Igor Ivanov, that Russian troops would not enter the
southern Serb province before NATO did.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had been shocked by reports that Russian troops from
Russia's peacekeeping mission in Bosnia had moved earlier Friday
through Yugoslavia and Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, and might be
heading south to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore publicly said the Russians would not move
before NATO did, and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
turned his airplane around and headed back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials, while seeking to have the
Russians help solve the diplomatic crisis, had failed to negotiate
a serious peacekeeping role for the Russians under the U.N. mandate
authorizing foreign troops to move into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had refused to serve directly under NATO command
and had backed Belgrade in insisting that the peacekeepers serve
under a U.N. flag, and not simply as a NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd in Pristina fired hundreds of rounds of ammunition
into the air, kissed the Russian soldiers and jumped upon their
armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   They shouted slogans like ``Serbia Russia,'' ''Yeltsin, Yeltsin,
Yeltsin,'' and ``We and the Russians, we are 300 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the crowd shouted insults aimed at the United States
and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Russian soldiers displayed the three-fingered Serb salute before
the column moved off to the south, either toward Pristina's airport
or the Gratanica Monastery, one of the Serbian Orthodox Churches'
holiest sites.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
