<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-DEUTSCHE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Deutsche Bank Planning Big Area Buildup  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Aiming to wrest a spot as a Silicon Valley financial power,
Germany's Deutsche Bank, the world's biggest bank, plans a
large-scale buildup of its Northern California investment banking
operations, the bank's top official said.
<P>
   Rolf-E. Breuer, head of the company's spokesman of the  &LR; board of
managing directors, said Deutsche could increase its 260-person Bay
Area securities unit by as many as 90 new employees in the months
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion follows Deutsche's takeover earlier this month of
New York's Bankers Trust, the parent company of BT Alex. Brown, a
midsize investment bank that specializes in raising capital for
technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of Alex. Brown's Silicon Valley business ``can't
be overstated,'' Breuer said in an interview in San Francisco.
``It's one of the reasons why we thought Bankers Trust was such a
perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche is already one of the world's leading securities firms.
In Europe, where banking and securities operations haven't been
separated as they were until recently in the United States, the
bank is sort of a combination of Chase Manhattan and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   After mergers in the United States, the buttoned-down world of
banking has often clashed with the more-wide-open investment
banking culture. Alex. Brown staff members have reportedly had a
hard time adjusting after Bankers Trust bought the firm two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some of them were not happy in the past,'' Breuer said
of Alex. Brown's staff. ``But I met with enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Deutsche's first foray into Silicon Valley. Earlier
in the decade, it recruited virtually the entire Morgan Stanley
technology team, headed by superstar investment banker Frank
Quattrone.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche soured on the relationship, claiming that  &LR; saying most
of the profits went to Quattrone's team. Last year, the group
jumped ship for a rival firm, Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
