<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND OPENS MINICAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The sun was bright, the air clear. Drew Bledsoe was
throwing passes as well as, if not better than, ever. Terry Glenn
was catching them. Patriots owner Bob Kraft was there, smiling, no
politicians or business writers in sight, and Kraft eyeing a
product that can sell and fill any luxury suite _ his football
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' most important season of football since Bill
Parcells arrived in 1993 began, in a fashion, Friday with the first
day of minicamp. Once again, the Patriots may take a step to the
top of the NFL or they may spiral; many a future depends on which
direction the Patriots go in.
</P>
<P>
   But for two rookies, center Damien Woody and linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer, this first day of minicamp was a true welcome to
professional football. Woody learned a lesson on how pro football
will be different from college football, courtesy of canny and
tricky defensive lineman Chad Eaton, while Katzenmoyer was peppered
with questions about his academic past, questions that the
linebacker obligingly answered. Past and future mixed and swirled
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked for this day all my life,'' said Katzenmoyer, the
quick linebacker from Ohio State, eager to learn his trade as a
professional. ``I'm here now, and what's done is done. The whole
thing, for me and Ohio State, is over and done with, and it's old
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of the past is that Sports Illustrated's current
issue details apparent preferential treatment given to Katzenmoyer
so he could retain his collegiate eligibility. This, of course,
came as shocking news to no one, as having one rigorous standard
for all students at a university is a relic of an American past
long gone. Some athletes, of course, have been among those students
so favored over the years, from Harvard to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Still in all, appearances must be maintained. So Katzenmoyer was
asked whether the courses he took, courses open to all students,
were easy, and whether he had had his grade changed in one of them,
a spring semester course called Introduction to the Computer and
Visual Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about that is the classes I took weren't easy,''
said Katzenmoyer, who readily acknowledged his priority at Ohio
State was to play football. In fact, he said, his classes ``started
at 7 a.m. and went to 2 p.m.,'' and then ``from 2 to 8, I had
practice or I was working out. So it wasn't like it was blow-off
classes. Then, after working out, I had to go home and do homework
or write papers.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the grade change, he said it is a common practice among
many students to approach professors to change grades. ``The grade
change? Everybody has a grade change; it's a part of college,''
said Katzenmoyer. ``Any student can get going and talk to a
teacher, and if they feel a grade change is necessary, it's
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, said Katzenmoyer, he should have worked harder at Ohio
State. He said he hoped ``students who are trying to remain
eligible should work harder and learn from my mistakes.'' The
linebacker said he did not feel singled out for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that I'm picked on,'' he said. ``I guess it's an
example of what kids shouldn't do when they're in college. I mean,
I'll be the first one to take the hit for it.'' In his opinion, he
went on, ``the whole thing was over and done with last summer. I
guess it was something they felt they could use to sell magazines,
and that's fine by me. But to me and my family's opinion, it's over
and done with.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Katzenmoyer said no matter what the New
England coaches or fans expect him to do, ``I'm going to expect
even more of myself.'' He said he was neither frustrated nor hurt
by being taken 28th in the draft ``because I like the situation I'm
in now here.'' The Patriots play an aggressive defense, he said,
``and I'm an aggressive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woody, the rookie center from Boston College and the
Patriots' top draft choice, found himself playing the role of Max
Lane to Reggie White as Eaton quickly taught him how his future
must be: He will have to have his wits about him. Eaton easily
manhandled the rookie on a pass rush with a move ``I never saw
before in college,'' said Woody; namely, grabbing the center's hand
during the rush.
</P>
<P>
   A welcome to the future. For both Damien Woody and Andy
Katzenmoyer. The past is past as of Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
