<HEADER>
A2446 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOFA-BOFA_SFCHRON &LR;      06-11 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-BOFA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   3 Banks Slow Flow Of Data to Marketers 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
California's three largest banks said yesterday they would stop
giving confidential information about customers to outside
telemarketing firms in some cases, a practice industry critics have
called abusive and possibly illegal.
<P>
   In the most sweeping ban, Bank of America, the state's largest
bank, said it will stop providing any customer information to
third-party marketers. The bank, which is now headquartered in
North Carolina, said it was responding to customer concerns about
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, the largest bank still based in California,
announced a more limited cutback. The San Francisco bank said it
will only sell financial products such as insurance through outside
telemarketers and discontinue third-party sales of nonfinancial
products.
</P>
<P>
   And in a rapid about-face, San Francisco's Union Bank of
California said it is suspending a telemarketing program set up
just two weeks ago through an outside vendor, pending a review.
</P>
<P>
   The moves come as customer privacy and telemarketing abuse have
exploded as public-policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a San Francisco speech earlier this week, Comptroller of the
Currency John Hawke, a top federal bank regulator, characterized
some agreements between banks and telemarketers as ``seamy.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he slammed arrangements in which banks give
account information to high-pressure telemarketers in exchange for
a cut of sales. He said customers frequently wind up being charged
for products without giving out account information or agreeing to
buy anything.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the Minnesota attorney general sued
Minneapolis' U.S. Bancorp, one of the nation's largest banks, for
providing customer data to a vendor selling health program
memberships. The vendor levied ``bogus, unauthorized charges,'' the
state charged.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bancorp denied any wrongdoing but said it would end its
relationship with outside telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   Under typical telemarketing arrangements, banks provide a range
of personal, financial and account data to outside vendors. The
banks get a commission on sales but may have little control over
the vendor's sales tactics.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Bank of America described its ban on providing
customer information to outside marketers as ``industry leading.''
The ban will allow the bank to continue its own telemarketing
activities and sell third-party products by having its own
employees make the pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The bank doesn't know how long it will take to put the ban in
place, spokesman John Cleghorn said. The bank has contracts with
vendors selling products such as travel packages that will take
some time to unwind, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleghorn declined to say how much revenue the bank got from such
sales, but described the cost of the ban as ``not insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank has been talking with the Office of the Comptroller of
the Currency (OCC)  &LR; for about a month about ending its third-party
telemarketing programs, Cleghorn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We commend the bank for announcing these changes,`` said Julie
Williams, the comptroller's OCC's  &LR; top legal officer, in a release.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Mierzwinski, a financial services specialist with U.S. Public
Interest Research Group, called BofA's move a good step but said he
was concerned about loopholes. ``I can't get a straight answer
about whether there are going to be a bunch of exceptions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In a press release, Wells Fargo described its arrangements
with outside telemarketers as ``limited'' and said it doesn't
provide them confidential customer information ``for their
independent use.''
</P>
<P>
   Union Bank of California, the state's third-largest bank, said
it is halting telemarketing by its vendor, Member Works, while it
reviews the relationship. Member Works is the Connecticut firm
named in Minnesota's suit against U.S. Bancorp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is being made in light of the allegations in
Minnesota, and in view of the discomfort of our customers regarding
their expectations of confidentiality and privacy,'' the bank
explained in a memo circulated to employees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
