<HEADLINE>
MORE BOOK PUBLISHERS TALK OF MERGER
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The News Corp.'s HarperCollins is in discussions to acquire the
Hearst Corp.'s Avon Books and William Morrow &AMP; Co., a person close
to the talks confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A merger would bring together the publisher of ``Men Are From
Mars, Women Are From Venus,'' ``Up Island'' and ``The Dilbert
Principle'' _ all from HarperCollins _ with Morrow, the publisher
of ``We are Our Mothers' Daughters,'' by Cokie Roberts, and Avon
titles like ``Dr. Atkins' New Diet Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Mergers have swept the publishing business in the last several
years, fueled by cost-cutting and the desire for more leverage in
dealing with both writers and bookstores. But even if the News
Corp. acquires Avon and Morrow, it would still trail Bertelsmann's
Random House, with 1998 estimated sales of $1.9 billion.
HarperCollins had 1998 sales of $760 million, while Avon and Morrow
had sales of about $180 million combined, according to Subtext, an
industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were reported in The Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, which had been going through hard times as
recently as 1997, has experienced a turnaround under its new
president and chief executive, Jane Friedman, who was lured from
Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp. took a $270 million charge for HarperCollins in
1997, and there were rumors that it might try to sell the
publishing company. Instead, HarperCollins chose to revamp by
slashing staff and canceling many books for which authors had
missed their contractual deadlines. The decision to cancel the
books created a furor in the industry because it was such an
unusual move.
</P>
<P>
   The company also changed its publishing strategy by reducing the
number of books it would publish so that it could focus its
marketing. The strategy worked, and last year HarperCollins had 34
titles on The New York Times best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Avon and Morrow have also been having some tough times. Some
industry experts believe that the problems started in 1993 when
Hearst put the publishers up for sale and nearly struck a deal with
MCA's Putnam Berkeley Group. But Hearst eventually took them off
the market. Shortly after negotiations with Putnam Berkeley
collapsed, Howard Kaminsky, then president of Hearst's trade book
division, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the two units have published such well-known authors
as Sidney Sheldon and Faye Kellerman. But there have also been
debacles, including the decision to pay Whoopi Goldberg a rumored
$6 million advance for ``Book,'' which did poorly, as did Paul
Reiser's ``Babyhood.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hearst executive did not return phone calls and a spokesman
for Rupert Murdoch, chairman and chief executive of the News Corp.,
declined to comment on the talks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
