<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-PIANO-AMATEURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DOCTORS TO DIPLOMATS, THEY CHASE PIANO DREAMS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, N.M., Mass., N.Y., Fla., Brazil)  (jw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Juanita Madland, a schoolteacher from Los
Alamos, N.M., walked purposefully across the brightly lighted stage
of the Ed Landreth Auditorium at Texas Christian University,
smiling a little sheepishly at the audience, and approached the
great black hulk of the Steinway concert piano dominating the
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous,'' she said later, still flushed from
the performance. ``But once I got out there, I was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-proclaimed amateur pianists from around the world are here
for the first International Piano Competition for Outstanding
Amateurs. It is presented by the Van Cliburn Foundation, longtime
sponsor of the famous Van Cliburn International Piano Competition,
a quadrennial event first held in 1962 that includes professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 150 people sent in applications from 23 states and nine
foreign countries and just under 100 were chosen to compete. Among
them are two ambassadors, three homemakers, four journalists, two
ophthalmologists, two eye, ear, nose and throat specialists, a
dermatologist, two flight attendants, a director of table games for
a Nevada casino, an automobile glass installer and assorted
authors, professors, business executives, consultants, jurists and
computer specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just heard a blackjack dealer play Chopin's G minor Ballade
and you know what, he did a really nice job,'' said Michael Hawley,
37, a media technology professor at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology who is planning to play Liszt's ``Mephisto'' in the
semifinals, if he makes it there.
</P>
<P>
   Like many here, Ms. Madland, 57, had once seriously considered a
performing career. ``But that was B.C.,'' she said. ``Before
children. I really hadn't performed in 36 years until I picked it
up again a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   She gingerly worked her way through Brahms' Intermezzo in A
major, smiling sheepishly again as she rose to acknowledge the
applause at the end of her 10-minute performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intellectually, I knew I could do it, but emotionally, that is
something else,'' she said. ``I lost a lot of confidence in 37
years. Now I think perhaps I got some of it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Modeled on the Councours des Grands Amateurs de Piano, a
competition for amateur classical pianists held in Paris every year
since 1989, the competition is the first of its kind to be held in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people want to have a change of life back to
music, while another group has music as a central part of their
lives, but not central to their earning a living,'' said one
competitor, Marcus Raskin, 64, a member of the National Security
Council during the Kennedy administration and author and editor of
17 books on public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodzinski, executive director of the Cliburn Foundation,
said the love of music at the Paris event, which he attended at the
suggestion of Nela Rubinstein, wife of pianist Arthur Rubinstein,
persuaded him to move ahead in Fort Worth. The foundation's goal,
he said, is to attract ``not just amateurs or dabblers, but really
outstanding amateurs.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition's first prize, the jury prize, includes a cash
award of $2,000, a promise to be allowed to perform with an
orchestra in Paris, an invitation to visit the next Van Cliburn
competition and an assortment of piano CDs: all told one-thousandth
of the total package that goes to the winner of the professional
Van Cliburn competitions.
</P>
<P>
   But these contestants were not here for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Ms. Madland or Michael Kimmelman, chief art critic of
The New York Times, had once seriously considered a music career
and were now revisiting that desire, perhaps to retaste its
pleasures and perhaps to help silence that niggling inner voice
asking about what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had considered making music my career,'' said Hawley of
M.I.T. ``But I also always thought that I didn't want to be in a
position of waking up jet-lagged and thinking: `Where am I? Oh,
yes. It's Tuesday; it must be Beethoven.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many contestants said they had played very little except for
their own amusement in recent years. But many others had somehow
managed to keep up their training, often with the help of a coach
who continued to guide them. (Hawley called his ``my private
Yoda.'') Both flight attendants in the competition said they chose
their career, in part, because it gave them significant chunks of
time in which to practice and perform.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid confusion with the long-standing Van Cliburn
competition, contestants were limited to those over the age of 30
who were amateurs and making their living in some other field.
</P>
<P>
   In the preliminary round, each contestant performed for 10
minutes, beginning on Wednesday and ending Friday night, with the
announcement of the dozen or so asked to perform a 20-minute
repertory in the semifinals on Saturday. Then, six are to be chosen
to take part in the finals on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were overwhelmed with the response we got,'' Rodzinski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Raskin said he had not performed before an audience, or even
practiced seriously, in ``more than a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, performing here was, in part, a way of putting certain
things to rest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was struck by the way people from so many varied
backgrounds so easily found a common language in their passion for
the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Luiz Benedini, Brazil's ambassador and consul general in Miami,
said he had the same sense of communion with the other performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all seemed to me very interesting people and from such a
tremendous broadness of activities,'' he said. ``But everyone is
very relaxed, enjoying themselves, taking the whole thing as a new
experience.'' If the competition succeeds, Rodzinski said, there
may well be a move to hold future amateur competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether it will be every four years, maybe every
two years,'' he said. ``It depends on how it turns out, how much
effort is involved and, financially, how things are going to work
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
