<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-TESTING-NYT &LR;      06-11 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-TESTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION PAMPHLET RISES IRE OF CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.) (rk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Department of Education recently drafted a
pamphlet advising school districts and colleges how to avoid being
sued for discrimination if a standardized test they use produces a
wide racial disparity in scores.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that advice, the department now finds itself
under attack by conservatives who charge it is trying to do away
with tests all together.
</P>
<P>
   Writing op-ed articles and columns and planting news stories in
educational journals, a group of anti-affirmative action
conservatives in recent weeks has alleged that the Department of
Education's advice represents an attack on the concept of merit as
measured by tests like as the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Such an attack, these critics charge, is a way to help
minorities, especially blacks and Hispanics, who tend not to score
as well on these exams as do whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Department of Education has created a novel policy to
close the racial performance gap on the Scholastic Assessment Test
and the American College Testing exams: make it illegal for
colleges to use the results if minority students perform below
white students,'' wrote Edward Blum and Marc Levin, two opponents
of affirmative action in a recent column published in The Wall
Street Journal. The article was headlined, ``Washington's War on
Standardized Tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Such criticism has exasperated Education officials who say they
are merely describing the current state of the law as a way to help
school administrators who are under intense political pressure to
have pupils pass standardized tests to be promoted. The draft
booklet, which was circulated last month to educators and testing
companies, barely mentions the SAT and ACT examinations, the
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to capture existing, long-standing
anti-discrimination principles and to discuss test measurement
standards in a way to help educators and policy-makers devise and
craft appropriate test-use policy,'' said Arthur Coleman, deputy
assistant secretary for civil rights at the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a highly complex area of civil rights law known as
disparate impact theory. The theory is based on a number of Supreme
Court decisions stating that if minorities or women score
significantly lower on a given test, then using that test for
decisions like admitting students to college, promoting pupils to
the next grade or assigning them to gifted programs or special
education may be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Once a racial or gender disparity in a test results is shown,
courts have held that schools or colleges must then show whether
there is an ``educational necessity'' for the test and whether
there are alternative means of evaluating students.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Heubert, an expert on testing and disparate impact law at
Columbia University Teachers College, said that while the burden
sounds onerous, courts have said that schools and colleges can meet
it if they show that the test is being used for the purpose for
which its producers say it should be used.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Educational Testing Service, which produces the
SAT, says it should not be used as the sole criterion for college
admissions. Rather, the ETS recommends using tests in combination
with an applicant's grade point average and teacher
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very well established principle in the law and in
the standards adopted by testing professionals,'' said Heubert, an
associate professor of education at Teachers College and an adjunct
professor of law at Columbia law school. ``That is to say that no
important decision about an individual should be made on the basis
solely on the basis of a single test score.''
</P>
<P>
   When the draft of the pamphlet first was presented to
representatives of school public school administrators, colleges
and test makers at a meeting with Education officials on May 14,
officials at the Educational Testing Service ``panicked,'' said
Anthony Carnavale, a vice president at ETS. According to Carnavale,
test makers feared that the Clinton administration was trying to
get colleges to use an alternative to the SAT or ACT examinations.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting a second time with officials with the Department
of Education, Carnavale said many of his organization's fears were
allayed. But he said he was concerned that the publicity
surrounding the pamphlet may have given fodder to conservatives who
are against affirmative action in college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Rep. Peter Hoekstra, R-Mich., who opposes affirmative
action programs that provide breaks to minorities and women, has
scheduled hearings on the department's draft pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of screwed up,'' Carnavale said. ``It's a juicy story.
It's race. It's affirmative action and the power of the federal
government. It all kind of plays into the politics of the moment.
The irony is, all of us in the testing community who are being
portrayed as antagonists, really want this document. And we have
set forces in motion who want to kill it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
