<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES SCRAMBLE TO KILL COMPUTER `WORM'
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash., Pa., Texas, Calif., Germany, France, Britain)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Large corporations worldwide scrambled Friday to halt the spread
of a malicious computer program that began infecting computers in
Israel on Monday and spread rapidly to Europe and the United
States, carried by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The program, a computer attack known as a worm, destroys
documents created by several widely used Microsoft programs,
including Word and Excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still receiving new reports, although they are tapering
off from what we were receiving yesterday,'' Jeff Havrilla, a
member of the Computer Emergency Response Team at Carnegie Mellon
University, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co.'s e-mail system remained down most of Friday as
teams worked to clean up after the attack. As of Friday night,
Boeing workers still had not determined how many files were lost, a
spokesman, David Suffia, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel Corp. reported minimal damage, most of it confined to
its Israel offices.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the Electronic Data Systems Corp. in Dallas, which
has sites in 47 countries, said only six of them had been infected
and that the company began inoculating all its computers an hour
after the first report Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Chien, a researcher at the Symantec Anti-Virus Research
Center in Santa Monica, Calif., said he had first heard reports
from Israel of worm attacks late Sunday night, Pacific time, and
that reports from the United States began to arrive late Tuesday.
The company also got reports of infections from Germany, France and
Britain. He said it took just 10 minutes to adjust the company's
Norton anti-virus software to detect and destroy the worm and
another 10 minutes to write up a description and a warning.
</P>
<P>
   But it took much longer for companies around the world to apply
the updated anti-virus software and assess damages.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly harmful aspect of this worm is that a single
infection can affect an entire network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disastrous in that you lose not just your data but
everything on your file server,'' Chien said.
</P>
<P>
   File servers are computers that store files and programs shared
by a network. Often data from an entire corporation is backed up on
file servers. A typical large company has 20,000 to 40,000
computers connected to four or five file servers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The program initially infects a computer when a user receives an
e-mail message, ostensibly from an acquaintance, stating: ``I
received your e-mail and I shall send you a reply ASAP. Till then,
take a look at the attached zipped docs. Bye.'' When the recipient
attempts to open the attachment, a program is executed that deletes
files. It then sends the same e-mail message as a reply to all
unread mail in the recipient's in box as well as to all subsequent
e-mail messages sent to the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   The worm only infects machines running Microsoft Windows or
operating systems that emulate Windows, but it can delete files on
other computers in the network regardless of what operating system
they use. The program can be sent only via Microsoft e-mail
programs and other e-mail programs that use the Windows support
software for e-mail, known as MAPI.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients of the e-mail who use the popular Eudora program, in
its default setting, will lose files but will not spread the worm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2472 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DEFENSE-ADS-$ADV1     06-11 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DEFENSE-ADS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE GROUP ATTACKS MILITARY EXCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 13)  
(DW) 
 By ERIC QUINONES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why must Bell Industries, a computer services company in El
Segundo, Calif., go all the way to India to hire programmers? The
company's co-chairman, Theodore Williams, thinks it is because
America doesn't have its priorities straight.
</P>
<P>
   Williams says his frustration at being unable to find enough
qualified Americans for the jobs is why he believes the goals of
Business Leaders for Sensible Priorities are so important. The
organization is a group of business people campaigning for
fundamental changes in the way the government uses its resources,
and Williams is one of the founders.
</P>
<P>
   To Williams and others in the group, the shortage of programmers
is symptomatic of an education system that is starved of money and
hurting America's competitiveness, all while billions of dollars
are lavished on unproductive military spending. The group wants a
higher budget priority for schools, health care for children and
other programs to insure America's future economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Led by an unabashed liberal activist, Ben Cohen, co-founder of
Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, the group has attracted members like Paul
Newman and Ted Turner _ names that are decidedly not part of the
business mainstream. But most of the group's members are
lesser-known executives and business owners who hope their
practical business background will give them credibility with
lawmakers and voters.
</P>
<P>
   The group steers away from the usual ideological and partisan
camps. It does not ask its members about their party affiliations,
and several members said in interviews that encouraging wiser
spending was a goal that fit a conservative agenda as well as a
liberal one.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Conservative' means prudence, and `conservative' means not
spending money indiscriminately without a return,'' said Arnold
Hiatt, chairman of the Stride Rite Foundation and another of the
group's founders. ``I think an awful lot of money is being spent,
particularly in the Defense Department, not for the right
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   But pacifism isn't on the group's agenda, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in favor of a strong military,'' said Bruce Klatsky,
the chairman and chief executive of the Philips-Van Heusen Corp., a
clothing and shoe manufacturer, and also a founder of the group.
``What we are against is the waste in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's profile rose considerably late last year when it
began an advertising campaign arguing that, with the Cold War over,
billions of dollars could safely be cut from nuclear weapons
programs and from new generations of fighter aircraft and attack
submarines meant to replace models that are already the world's
best.
</P>
<P>
   In expressing these views, the business group relies on several
military advisers, including Lawrence Korb, assistant defense
secretary in the Reagan administration, and Paul C. Warnke, chief
arms negotiator in the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the group's message is anathema to the
military industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spent $44 billion on weapons last year, the least
in more than a decade, said John W. Douglass, president and chief
executive of the Aerospace Industries Association of America. Over
all, he said, arms spending has fallen by 70 percent since the end
of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to try to say that Americans have two choices, education
or Pentagon waste, is just an outrageous oversimplification and
unfair statement,'' Douglass said.
</P>
<P>
   The business group counters that military spending is already
rebounding. Even before NATO began bombing Yugoslavia in late
March, the Clinton administration was asking Congress for the
biggest increase in military spending since the 1980s, an
additional $112 billion over the next five years, raising the
Pentagon budget to $319 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're in a warlike state creates a climate for
larger budget increases and less examination of the wastefulness
that already exists,'' Newman said in an interview conducted before
the Kosovo peace agreement was concluded late last week.
</P>
<P>
   The business leaders' group has grown from 5 members in 1996 _
Messrs. Cohen, Williams, Hiatt and Klatsky, as well as Alan
Hassenfeld, chairman and chief executive of Hasbro _ to 450 today.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the advertising campaign, the group is also paying for a
bus tour called ``U Slice the Pie.'' It began in April in
Washington and is to run through November, spending a lot of time
in Iowa, an early stop in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At events like county fairs and church picnics, three young
actors present the group's message using huge inflatable displays
with statistics on budget allocations, military industry lobbying
and job creation. The bus is painted to look like piles of cash;
some of the executives have spoken at the stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue of federal budget priorities is kind of dry,''
Cohen said. ``It's kind of off-putting to people. The object of the
`U Slice the Pie' performance is to make it fun and exciting.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
