<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-SCOTUS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO EXPRESSES ANNOYANCE BUT UNDERSTANDING OVER DECISION ON
LOITERING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif.)  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For more than 20 years, Bennie Meeks watched out his
apartment window as gang members routinely occupied the nearby
street corner. Sometimes they sold drugs. Sometimes they merely
intimidated, by their very presence.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Meeks, a community leader in the Austin section, on
Chicago's West Side, wanted them out of there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, his Southwest Austin Council and other community groups
finally persuaded the city to enact a law that sought to sweep the
gangs from Meeks' corner and hundreds of others like it. The law,
which ultimately made some difference in his neighborhood and
resulted in more than 42,000 arrests around the city, authorized
police officers to break up groups congregating ``with no apparent
purpose'' and to charge anyone who refused to move on with a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   But the Illinois courts suspended enforcement of the law in
1995, and on Thursday the U.S. Supreme Court agreed with them that
it was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-to-3 decision, written by Justice John Paul Stevens, said
the ordinance was too vague, affording the police too much
discretion and failing to tell potential offenders precisely which
activities were unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, a 65-year-old retired phone company worker, said Friday
that he understood why the court had ruled as it did and that he
hoped a law could be drafted that would resolve the justices'
objections but satisfy the needs of Chicagoans terrified by gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be careful,'' he said. ``We don't want to give the
police too much power, because I've seen it abused. But if we don't
use this law as a tool, how are we going to get these guys off the
corner? What about the constitutional rights of my neighbors whose
kids have to walk by that corner every day on their way to
school?''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks' concerns were voiced by his neighbors as well and by city
officials who had lobbied hard for the ordinance, saying the rights
of law-abiding people outweighed those of gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the law's fiercest advocate, Mayor Richard M. Daley,
said after learning of the court's decision that ``we have to ask
ourselves if it is constitutional for gang-bangers and drug dealers
to own a corner'' and that ``everybody knows that they aren't out
there cooking hot dogs and studying Sunday-school lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People in neighborhoods all over the country,'' the mayor
added, ``are tired of feeling intimidated where they live.''
</P>
<P>
   But like Meeks, Daley said he understood the constitutional
objections, and he vowed that the city would rewrite the law to
meet them. Municipal lawyers said they hoped to have the new
version ready within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much in this decision that we find very
encouraging,'' said Brian Crowe, the Corporation Counsel, who noted
that unlike the Illinois Supreme Court, none of the justices had
found that the ordinance infringed on the First Amendment rights of
freedom of speech and assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court felt the ordinance gave too much discretion to
police officers,'' Crowe said, ``and we're confident we can sit
down and write a new ordinance to meet those parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they gave no details of their approach, city lawyers
said they were particularly encouraged by Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor's concurring opinion, which suggested that such laws could
be rewritten through addition of a more specific definition of
proscribed activity.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities, including San Jose, Calif., have been able to
reduce gang crime by taking the novel approach of suing gang
members as a public nuisance. But the Chicago law, too, was
considered a bold and innovative tool with which to combat urban
violence, and as a result the court's decision was eagerly awaited
by municipalities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of that decision, Phil Gordon, who as a city
councilman in Phoenix has led a push for an anti-loitering law
there, said discussions would resume on legislation that was tabled
pending the outcome of the Chicago case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing to see the decision,'' Gordon said, ``but
we'll have to talk with our attorneys and see if there isn't a way
to narrow the scope and see if we can go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling comes at a time when relations with the police are at
best strained in many Chicago communities. Two recent fatal
shootings by police officers have drawn protests, and many here
approved of the court's objection to a law that gave officers such
broad power.
</P>
<P>
   Among the law's critics was the Chicago office of the American
Civil Liberties Union, which challenged it on behalf of 66
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Supreme Court said is really what political leaders
in this city should have been saying all along: that you can't
allow the police to determine who is allowed on the street,'' said
Ed Yohnka, director of communications for the Illinois ACLU.
``There are better ways to fight crime than just sweeping people
off of the street, and the court affirmed that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
