u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-NYT &LR;      06-11 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ADVANCE CONFOUNDS NATO'S PLANS FOR ENTERING KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-RUSSIA-TROOPS) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER with KEITH MEYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ NATO's plans for a dawn entry into Kosovo
were confounded early Saturday morning by Russia's unexpected
advance into Pristina, the Kosovo capital and Western forces' goal
as their headquarters for a peacekeeping force to return more than
a million ethnic Albanians to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   British paratroopers were poised to lift off by helicopter at
three o'clock Saturday morning to secure strategic hills
overlooking the highway to Pristina, about 90 kilometers from the
border. The main advance elements of the NATO forces, led by a
British armored force, were to pass the border post at Blace at 5
o'clock .
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian appearance in Pristina, joyously greeted by the
remaining Serbs there, threw the operation into doubt. The Russians
came from the U.N. peacekeeping contingent in Bosnia. Some of their
armored vehicles had the Bosnia peacekeepers insignia, SFOR,
hastily painted over by one letter to read KFOR, the name of the
new Kosovo deployment, while others still bore the old SFOR
designation.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 a.m. when the stunning news of the Russian operation _
which had seemed to be defused by diplomatic maneuvers during the
day _ reached here, so there was no immediate reaction from NATO
military officials.
</P>
<P>
   But it had been a jittery day, as paratroopers and other troops
stood on alert to go into Kosovo to block the Russians, then stood
down as it appeared the threat had passed, and senior Russian
officials gave their word their troops would not move in.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Russian surprise, NATO tanks rumbled through the
dark, and long columns of armored personnel carriers, ambulances
and other military vehicles snaked through the streets here into
assembly points as British, French, Italian, American and other
NATO contingents gathered to launch their peacekeeping effort.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan called for the advance party of British paratroopers
to take off in helicopters at 3 a.m. to seize the high ground on
the hills overlooking the main road to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   At five o'clock, if all went well, a British officer involved in
the operation said, the main convoy was to pass through the border
crossing here, its advance element led by British troops of the
Fourth Armored Corps, including the Irish Guards and a unit of
tough Ghurka infantrymen. They were to be followed by the other
European and American units, which were to spread across specific
zones in Kosovo as the Serbs withdrew on an 11-day timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's preparations followed a confusing day, in which
Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, the commander here, after already putting
off a dawn paratroop movement for 24 hours _ ostensibly because the
Yugoslavs were having difficulty moving out for lack of gas _ was
confounded by the sudden appearance of Russian peacekeeping troops
from Bosnia moving through Yugoslavia toward Kosovo. They were in
armored vehicles whose SFOR insignia, the initials of the U.N.
deployment there, had been crudely painted over to read KFOR, the
acronym for the peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Paratroopers and other units were stood up on-one hour alerts
late Friday afternoon, but diplomatic efforts then appeared to ease
the crisis, at least for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   This border-crossing point, where hundreds of thousands of
weeping refugees had been dumped off the trains from Pristina, was
so quiet Friday night, a refugee transit camp just down the hill
all but shut down, that the noisy singing of the birds in the
surrounding bushes and woods seemed almost overwhelming. But, just
a few hundred yards back, the KFOR's olive drab military vehicles
were already assembling in the parking lot and cleared spaces
around the Europa `93 Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   A little farther back, thousands of refugees in long lines along
the road, kept more or less in order by self-appointed monitors,
cheered the passing NATO military vehicles and anyone that appeared
even vaguely associated with them.
</P>
<P>
   `'NATO, NATO,'' the crowds chanted, quickly following up with
`'UCK, UCK,'' the Albanian initials for the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But when the blue and white cars of the Macedonian police, many
of whom have abused the refugees, passed by, there were high
pitched hoots and jeers.
</P>
<P>
   `'We have waited for this day,'' said 20-year old Bekim
Mustapha, in sentiments echoed by others in the crush around him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-0612-CO     06-11 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN TROOPS ARRIVE IN KOSOVO AHEAD OF NATO, KFOR DEPLOYMENT
UNAFFECTED
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0612.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ NATO forces kept up their plans for some
British and French paratroopers to enter Kosovo by daybreak
Saturday, despite Russian troops' surprising arrival in the
provincial capital Pristina overnight.
</P>
<P>
   To a celebratory crowd of thousands of jubilant ethnic Serbs,
troop transports and tanks carrying hundreds of Russian troops from
SFOR in Bosnia paraded through downtown Pristina, reassuring the
war-ravaged province's ethnic Serb population that they would be
secure during the NATO peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Russian Prime Minister Igor Ivanov gave
assurances to the Clinton White House that the convoy of some 50
vehicles, which left their peacekeeping mission in Bosnia
unexpectedly to head into Yugoslavia -- but not yet into Kosovo --
would not enter the southern Serb province before NATO did.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on CNN about an hour after their entry, Ivanov said
the troops had arrived ``unfortunately'' and that they had been
ordered to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons for this are being determined. They have been
ordered to leave Kosovo immediately and to await further orders,''
Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Though clearly embarrassing on a diplomatic level, the movement
by the Russian troops -- traditional allies of the Serbs -- did not
immediately appear to force any change in NATO's schedule for
British and French troops waiting in Macedonia on Kosovo's southern
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why our plans to go in a little bit later will be
affected,'' said a NATO spokesman said after begin told of the news
about 2 a.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Able Sentry, where more than 3,000 U.S. peacekeepers
have gathered to go into Kosovo as part of the United Nations
authorized force, Army spokesman Capt. Mark Ballasteros, said ``I
don't know about all of NATO, but I can tell you that the Americans
aren't moving tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   German television monitored from here showed thousands of
Kosovar Serbs cheering in the streets and waving the Yugoslav flag
and shouting, ``Russia! Russia!'' in anticipation of the arrival of
the Russian troops. The ethnic Serbs also burned an American flag
to show their dissatisfaction with the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians arrived shortly after midnight aboard trucks, tanks
and armored personnel carriers. As they crept through an avenue
jammed with people, the crowd whipped into a frenzy with fireworks
and shots being fired into the air, and people reaching out to
touch the hands of the Russian troops, and showering them with
flowers and chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials said they had been reassured by Russia
that its troops would not be deployed in Kosovo ahead of the
international peacekeeping force, known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're currently trying to get clarification about the facts,''
said White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, NATO commanders gave emergency orders for 2,000
British paratroopers to prepare for an immediate airlift deep into
Kosovo to block Russian peacekeepers that were feared heading for
the Kosovo capital.
</P>
<P>
   For three hours, members of the crack British First Paratroop
Regiment sat sweltering in 95-degree heat beside troop-carrying
helicopters, waiting to jump aboard with their machine guns and
anti-tank rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   This followed reports from Moscow's Interfax news agency that
1,000 Russian troops would leave Moscow Friday afternoon and fly to
cities in Kosovo, including the capital Pristina. Interfax claimed
the Russians were at a military airfield waiting for orders to take
off.
</P>
<P>
   Another report by the Yugoslav news agency Beta said a convoy of
Russian troops had crossed into Serbia from Bosnia on their way to
peacekeeping assignments in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving in Macedonia to visit Kosovar refugees and NATO
troops, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was surprised
when she learned from British Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, commander
of KFOR, of the Russian troop movements.
</P>
<P>
   She ordered Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who had
just left Moscow, to return to try and revive his talks with
Russian counterparts about the status of a force of up to 10,000
Russian troops within the 50,000-strong peacekeeping force that is
essentially run by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians oppose putting their troops under unified NATO
command, and had backed Belgrade in insisting that the peacekeepers
serve under a United Nations flag, and not simply as a NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
