<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2489 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-RUSSIA-PEACE-BOS     06-11 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-RUSSIA-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS TROOPS RUMBLE INTO KOSOVO CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates with Russians in Pristina.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Throughout the Balkan war, unpredictable, nuclear-armed
Russia has always been the X-factor, and Saturday was no different.
</P>
<P>
   By becoming the first foreign power to send troops to Kosovo
since a peace deal suspended 79 days of NATO airstrikes, Russia
trumped the alliance's long-awaited entrance into the southern
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow's unexpected move to transfer several hundred
peacekeepers from Bosnia into Kosovo's capital, Pristina, means
much more than being first. It may be a signal that the Russians
are determined to play their own game in the resolution of the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders have sought to portray Russia's diplomatic
backing for a peace plan approved by NATO as a sign that Moscow had
joined in the opposition to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian officials still say that NATO, not Milosevic, was
the aggressor. They say that NATO, as the guilty party in the war,
should not be allowed to command peacekeepers in Kosovo. Russia
wants its troops to take control of a sector in northeast Kosovo
where most of the ethnic Serbs in the region live. NATO rejects
that and says Russia can be part of a unified force under a NATO
commander.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after US and Russian officials in Moscow were unable to
hammer out an agreement on Russia's role in the peacekeepers'
command structure, Friday's move to send in troops looks like a
challenge to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the troops arrived in Pristina, Western leaders
reacted with surprise. British troops near Kosovo were put on alert
and US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott was ordered to turn
his plane around and return to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   NATO later appeared to accept assurances from Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov that the troops were not going into Kosovo until a deal
could be worked out. But a senior military official, General Leonid
Ivashov, said Russia reserved the right to make a separate deal
with Belgrade on where its troops will be stationed. Russian news
agencies reported that more troops were ready to arrive in
Yugoslavia soon.
</P>
<P>
   After the troops' arrival, Ivanov, adding to the confusion over
who wields power in Moscow, made a statement calling this ``an
unfortunate incident'' and urging the troops to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic splits and confusion are nothing new to Russian policy
on the Balkans. Most political parties have distanced themselves
from the peace plan, which was helped along greatly by Russia's
envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin. Parliament this week passed a
resolution accusing Chernomyrdin of betraying Russia's geopolitical
interests.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris N. Yeltsin's comments Friday did not make clear
whether Ivanov or Ivashov was right, only that the Russian leader
still rejects putting his troops under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on television with Ivanov and a Russian general,
Yeltsin growled: ``We have done all we needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing NATO wants is Russian troops staking out
territory in Kosovo. But even if the Russians plan to coordinate
their movements with NATO, their presence in Yugoslavia puts
another crimp in the alliance's overall strategy.
</P>
<P>
   NATO merely suspended its airstrikes after Yugoslavia accepted a
peace plan that provides for Serbian troops and police to withdraw
from Kosovo. The alliance has held out the threat of resuming the
bombing if the Serbs play any tricks. The presence of even a small
contingent of Russian troops complicates that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Yugoslav troops do not complete the pullout from Kosovo,
will NATO be able to resume bombing with Russian troops in
Yugoslavia?'' a commentator for NTV television asked.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's move may have caught Washington by surprise, but it
appeared to have been planned with the Serbs, who gave the Russian
troops a police escort.
</P>
<P>
   The troops came from among the 1,300 Russian peacekeepers who
have been serving under the NATO-commanded SFOR force, a parallel
NATO officials frequently bring up when trying to persuade the
Russians of their need to command KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian politicians and military officials are suspicious
about NATO's motives. Despite the assurances of the alliance
leaders, many Russians say NATO will be unable, or unwilling, to
prevent the takeover of Kosovo by the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we even talk about Russian troops, we should ask what
the goal of these peacekeepers is,'' said Russian lawmaker Alexei
Arbatov, a specialist on defense issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the goal is to keep Kosovo a part of Serbia, to stop the
violence and allow refugees to return, then we do not need a
heavily armed force like the one NATO is putting in place. We need
50,000 lightly armed troops under the United Nations to act as
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the goal is to divide Serbia and allow the KLA to take
power, we should not be involved in this contingent,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
