<SLUG> BC-DELTA-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNABLE TO REACH PILOT PAY AGREEMENT, DELTA CANCELS ORDER FOR 777S  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines said Friday that it would defer an order for 11
Boeing 777 aircraft and that it would put two 777's that it already
owns on the market because it could not reach an agreement on pay
scales for flying the airplanes with its pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Delta announced a similar deferral of four 777's in April
because of the dispute. Instead, it took delivery of four 767's.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots have asked for $319 an hour to fly the 777, while
Delta has offered them $239 an hour. Delta said the pilots' figure
was 5 percent above what AMR's American Airlines pays pilots to fly
777's, 25 percent higher than UAL's United Airlines pays and 26
percent higher than Continental Airline's rate.
</P>
<P>
   Karen McGuffey, a spokeswoman for the Air Line Pilots
Association, said the pilots deserved more because the 777's were
moneymakers. The planes carry more cargo than other planes, and
their twin-engine design makes the aircraft cheaper to operate than
four-engine aircraft like the Boeing 747.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeking a pay rate commensurate to that productivity,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides, which have met several times since February to
discuss the issue, said they would meet again on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing contract terms, Delta has six months to work out
a pay scale with pilots once a new aircraft is introduced. Because
Delta has been flying 777's since May, pilots could decide to stop
flying the new planes after Nov. 1. Ms. McGuffey said the provision
meant the two sides had months to come up with an agreement. But
Delta said that including the planes in its schedule now only to
see them grounded in November could leave thousands of passengers
stranded. In addition, it could cost the company millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, Delta has not canceled its order with Boeing.
Under the terms of its broad, 20-year contract to purchase planes
exclusively from Boeing, Delta has certain options available, such
as substituting orders for other planes.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute comes at a particularly delicate time for Delta and
its pilots, because the two sides are scheduled to begin
negotiations in September on a full-scale contract. But both sides
said Friday that they saw the disagreement about the 777's as a
separate issue from the coming contract negotiations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
