<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-350&AMP;ADD-N     06-11 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TASK FORCE CHIEF, U.N.'S NO. 2 OFFICIAL IS PUT TO TEST
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ It is midafternoon in Kosovo when Louise
Frechette's forces assemble here each morning at 9 sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Around a mahogany conference table in the U.N. situation room
sit the generals of the world organization's peacekeeping army:
heads of U.N. departments and of key relief, refugee, human rights
and peacekeeping agencies that make up an informal group known as
the Kosovo Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   At the head of the table is Ms. Frechette, a Canadian diplomat
who 18 months ago became the first deputy secretary-general,
filling a post created by Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frechette quietly set up this group three weeks ago to
coordinate efforts in the Balkans and to begin ``post-conflict''
planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that all the agencies and departments
involved in such a crisis have been brought together, in person and
by video conferencing,'' said Ms. Frechette. ``There's tremendous
team spirit now.''
</P>
<P>
   This management system will soon be put to its ultimate test.
Under the peace agreement for Yugoslavia hammered out in Cologne,
Germany, 50,000 peacekeepers are to enter Kosovo and the United
Nations is in charge of creating an interim administration for the
war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   Policing the province, establishing a judicial system, tackling
human rights abuses, institution building, organizing elections and
making possible the return of more than a million refugees are some
of the daunting tasks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much bigger role for the United Nations than
Bosnia,'' said one senior official. ``And thanks in large part to
Louise's planning, I think we're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and U.N. officials also credit Ms. Frechette with
bringing greater discipline and efficiency not only to the
organization's ambitious relief efforts in the Balkans, but to many
of its wide-ranging activities. The United Nations has 5,000
international civil servants in New York alone, from 185 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's become the United Nations' chief operating officer,''
said John Ruggie, who is an assistant secretary-general and a
special adviser to Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frechette's position grew out of efforts to reform the U.N.
system, which was widely criticized on Capitol Hill and elsewhere
for waste, inefficiency and duplication.
</P>
<P>
   She has taken significant steps, reducing nonessential costs,
streamlining reform-resistant bureaucracies and demanding
accountability from U. N. fiefs that are often entrenched and
unresponsive. In three years, some 900 U.N. posts have been
eliminated, partly as a result of Ms. Frechette's hard-nosed
management style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good, strong record of reform,'' said Peter Burliegh,
the acting U.S. representative here.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Frechette is a seasoned diplomat who was based in New
York twice before, she says it was her experience as deputy defense
minister that best prepared her for redefining the U.N.
administration from the top down.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Frechette, 52, runs the morning meetings, which are
normally closed to the press, with almost military precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, Human Rights,'' she barks, welcoming the
representative of the Human Rights commissioner's office, who
arrived a few minutes late to a recent meeting via video from
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Also present on television monitors were representatives of the
World Food Program from Rome and senior officials of other U.N.
agencies based in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent morning Ms. Frechette led a brisk debate over
whether agencies could drop food to people starving in mountain
hideouts in Kosovo, a risky mission in a war zone. The
International Rescue Committee, a private agency, has since made
such airdrops with two leased aircraft from the Italian city of
Pescara and with American government financial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task force meetings are crucial, because that is where we
all share information,'' said Kofi Asomani, the director of the
liaison office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   That agency alone has more than 350 international relief workers
on the ground in Yugoslavia and neighboring countries, plus
hundreds of local staff members working in refugee camps. They in
turn coordinate their activities with hundreds of private relief
groups and their workers.
</P>
<P>
   The coming weeks are likely to be even more intense for Ms.
Frechette as the U.N. scrambles to prepare for the role of civil
administrator and relief coordinator for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the World Food Program has been preparing to get food
into Kosovo as quickly as possible by providing more than a million
daily rations in Macedonia, Greece and Italy, where more than 30
trucks are ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   The food program has also set up mobile warehouses for food and
has identified five sites in Kosovo where it will set up offices,
with headquarters in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The food program now has enough food in the region to feed some
800,000 refugees for two months and expects to have, within two
weeks, a three-month supply of food for some 600,000 additional
people inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Ms. Frechette helps prepare for the task of assuming the
civil administration of the province, she urged the world not to
forget the crises in other parts of the world addressed by the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the world won't forget the 1.2 million people
desperately short of food in drought-stricken regions of
Ethiopia,'' she said, ``or the long-suffering people of Sudan,
where we also have had a mission for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things that only the United Nations can
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2501 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-NYT     06-11 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUVENILE-CRIME BILL SAGS UNDER 200 PIGGYBACKERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill., Mass., Ga., Texas)  (jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans and Democrats began to file more
than 200 amendments Friday to a juvenile crime bill that has become
a vehicle for the kind of modest but bitterly divisive gun-control
measures that the Senate approved last month.
</P>
<P>
   The number and variety of these amendments, which will be
winnowed to a manageable few before the bill comes to the House
floor next week, provided a glimpse into the gaping range of House
opinion and hinted at the difficulty that lawmakers may have in
passing legislation on such a politically charged issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Friday that the stakes of getting something
through the House were high, with the very credibility of Speaker
Dennis Hastert's leadership on the line.
</P>
<P>
   In many instances over the last few months, Hastert has been
unable to forge a consensus among House Republicans, breeding
protracted debate, intermittent inertia and fears among House
Republicans that they could find themselves lurching into the 2000
elections with the tag of a do-nothing majority.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Hastert has his own promises to keep. He made a
speech on the House floor three weeks ago in which he forecast that
the House would pass some of the kinds of gun-control measures that
succeeded in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   By late this week, however, Hastert sounded less certain as he
announced that he would not press party members to vote in any
particular way and held many of his own opinions in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could make or break him in terms of the legitimacy
of the rest of his tenure,'' one senior Republican aide said of a
juvenile crime bill with gun-control measures. ``He can't escape
the fact that he went to the floor and said what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendments filed Friday with the House Rules Committee went
far beyond gun control. They included one Republican measure that
would give federal permission to post the Ten Commandments in
classrooms and another that would create a new category of
``violently obscene'' entertainment and impose criminal sanctions
on adults who let children have access to the material.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, the variations in rival amendments brought the
battle lines between advocates and opponents into sharper focus. It
became clearer, for example, that the most spirited fight would
come over the terms and language governing mandatory background
checks of buyers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pushing for an amendment on shows that replicates
the Senate legislation, which defines those events broadly and
gives vendors three business days to complete checks.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, unveiled an alternative that
narrowed the definition of the events and shortened the maximum
time for checks to three calendar days.
</P>
<P>
   But while Democrats denounced that measure as too lenient, many
Republicans found it too harsh. One amendment sent to the House
Rules Committee with the blessing of Republican leaders proposed a
24-hour limit on checks at gun shows. This position dovetailed with
the desires of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   In other instances, Republican leaders were less concerned that
Senate gun-control legislation be watered down than that
Republicans get to vote on each measure, not a package. That way,
Republicans and conservative Democrats would not be forced to vote
against a measure they found palatable because it was coupled with
an unacceptable one.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Republican aide said that Republican leaders wanted
some of these measures to pass not because the leaders felt pressed
by public opinion but because the certain consequence of failure
was that Democrats would try to attach gun-control proposals to any
tangentially relevant spending bill from now on. That disruption
could help shackle Republicans, stopping them from accomplishing
other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also fresh reminders Friday that Democrats were a
long way from unified on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Clinton administration had been pushing for stricter
measures than those the Senate adopted, senior Democratic aides
said Friday that party leaders were aiming simply to replicate the
other chamber's efforts. That decision partly reflected leaders'
fear that some Democrats in rural districts could be hurt in the
elections if the party was too aggressive on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   House members and political analysts also raised concerns Friday
that the potential breadth of the legislation could alienate
lawmakers on the left and the right and leave a center too narrow
for the bill to pass.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many liberal Democrats, including members of the
Congressional Black Caucus, are so opposed to measures that
severely toughen penalties for juvenile crime that they could wind
up voting against a bill that embraced these provisions, even if it
included gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The repulsion outweighs the attraction,'' said Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some conservative Republicans are likely to
try to kill the bill if it contains any significant gun control at
all. ``I think its prospects are very gloomy right now,'' said Rep.
Bob Barr, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno both spoke out
again Friday in favor of Democratic gun-control proposals,
continuing to use their bully pulpits to pressure lawmakers in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   The volatility of the issue was also evident on the presidential
campaign trail. More than 100 demonstrators gathered outside a
Chicago hotel, the site of a fund-raising reception for Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, urging him to take a stronger stand on gun
control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2502 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-11 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAN'T LET JACKSON GET AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers can think of 20 million
reasons not to hire Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can they give us one good reason?
</P>
<P>
   The news is out, and it comes as a shock to nobody with the
possible exception of Kurt Rambis, who might have been under the
impression he's the Lakers' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The team's front office has been talking to Jackson's agent
about a contract.
</P>
<P>
   This makes it more than wistful speculation that the man who
coached the Chicago Bulls' volatile mix of Michael Jordan, Scottie
Pippen and Dennis Rodman to a handful of NBA championship rings
will try to do the same with the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe
Bryant and Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Good news for Lakers fans. But keep the champagne on ice.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unanswered questions in this week's reports is whether
Jerry Buss, the owner, and Jerry West, the executive vice
president, are serious about hiring the best available coach for
their talented players.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know how long the two sides have been talking. Days?
Weeks?
</P>
<P>
   We don't know exactly what changed since last week, when it
sounded as if Rambis was about to have the ``interim'' label
removed from his coaching suit. Did Jackson watch the New York
Knicks save Jeff Van Gundy and figure his best chance for a
big-city job lay in Los Angeles? Did Buss and West note the
lukewarm support for Rambis among the players and the public and
wave a bigger check book at Jackson?
</P>
<P>
   And we don't know where the Lakers-Jackson negotiations stand _
that's for them to know and for us to find out _ let alone where
they go from here. What does Jackson want from the Lakers other
than more money? What do the Lakers want from Jackson other than a
vow of poverty?
</P>
<P>
   Which is where those 20 million reasons come in.
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about a salary in the $5 million to $6 million
range. That's $20 million to $24 million for four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of money, especially to the Lakers, who were paying
Del Harris about $1.2 million a year and Rambis much less than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it a lot of money? I mean, compared to what?
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the $120 million they've committed to O'Neal?
Compared to the $70 million they're paying to Bryant? Compared to
the $40 million-plus it would take to make Rice happy?
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of money, especially if all you're getting for it
is swept out of the playoffs year after year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' stated goal is nothing short of a championship.
Their fans expect nothing less. And now, as they move into the
downtown Staples Center, with more seats to fill, creating optimism
after 11 title-less seasons is wiser than ever.
</P>
<P>
   What the Lakers need is a coach with a record of turning talent
into a title. If that coach can be theirs for $24 million, he looks
like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   What's the alternative?
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Daly? No. He just walked away from coaching the Orlando
Magic to earn his paychecks in the consulting racket.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Daly will be 69 years old next month. Some jobs are
just right for a man that age. President of the United States, for
example. But coaching the Lakers? Too stressful.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy? No. After looking like the NBA's leading candidate to
be fired, he's the toast of New York during the Knicks' unlikely
playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you don't have to, you don't trust your $200 million
roster to a coach who's never actually won anything.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Rambis, who's coached a grand total of 28 NBA
victories. If Jackson is a bargain, Rambis is the bargain basement.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the old Lakers forward say it would be unfair to pull
the coaching chair out from under him after a 46-game trial in
which he had to deal with the arrival of Rodman, the two-for-three
Rice trade and the scarcity of practice time in the
lockout-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   It's innocent-until-proven-guilty applied to basketball: Rambis
did nothing wrong, you can't fire him.
</P>
<P>
   But in his first head-coaching job at any level of the sport,
Rambis also did nothing to prove he'll be as clever a coach as the
Lakers evidently need.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping Rambis, Buss and West would risk enduring another
season of on-the-job training for the coach and another season of
missed opportunity for the players.
</P>
<P>
   And that mistake couldn't be corrected a year from now. Jackson
probably won't be available then. And other than Pat Riley, who is
not coming back to Los Angeles, there isn't a more attractive
coaching candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's credentials improved, if anything, during his season
out of the game. The Bulls broke up, with Jackson and Jordan first
out the door, and the rest of them struggled with their new teams.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen averaged 14 points a game with the Houston Rockets, five
less than he scored while sharing the ball with Michael. Rodman _
need I say?
</P>
<P>
   Blame the loss of Jordan for some of that. Blame the loss of
Jackson for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Buss has spent tens of millions of dollars trying to build a
roster of players as talented as the Bulls'. Now, for a few million
more, he can have the coach to match.
</P>
<P>
   It's no time to be cheap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
