<DOCNO> NYT19990611.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WICCA-BOYCOTT12-COX     06-11 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WICCA-BOYCOTT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian Coalition skips Wicca boycott
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Conservative religious groups calling for
Christians to join a nationwide recruiting boycott against the Army
lost some of their ammunition Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.1 million-member Christian Coalition announced that the
organization will not tell its members to participate in the Army
boycott, which was called to protest the Army's policy of allowing
Wiccans to practice their rituals on posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Coalition doesn't tell its members what to do on
personal issues of faith,'' spokeswoman Molly Clatworthy said. ``As
individuals, Christian Coalition members may support the boycott.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the American Family Association _ listed as one of
13 groups that originally called for the boycott _ withdrew its
support.
</P>
<P>
   Paul M. Weyrich, president of the Free Congress Foundation, said
Friday he was disappointed in the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Washington-based representatives for both groups signed onto the
boycott earlier in the week, Weyrich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held a coalition meeting, laid out our game plan and asked
people to sign on,'' Weyrich said. ``A couple of these groups
either misunderstood what was being advocated or got cold feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The call for a boycott came after publicity stemming from an
Austin American-Statesman story last month about Wiccans at Fort
Hood in Killeen. The Army installation for three years has
sanctioned a Wicca group by providing on-post space for rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Wiccans, who call themselves witches, celebrate cycles of the
sun and moon and believe in the dual deity of god and goddess.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
