<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Wash., D.C., Mich., Japan)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW JONES AVERAGE DROPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average declined for a fourth
consecutive day after economic reports deepened investors' concerns
that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates later this
month. The Dow average fell 130.76 points, or 1.23 percent, to
10,490.51.
</P>
<P>
   Other market gauges also dropped. The Nasdaq composite index,
which includes many computer issues, declined 36.74 points, or 1.48
percent, to 2,447.88, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
decreased 9.18 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,293.64.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES FIGHT COMPUTER ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and other big companies worldwide scrambled to halt the
spread of a malicious computer program that began infecting
computers in Israel on Monday and spread rapidly into Europe and
the United States, carried by e-mail. It destroys files created by
Microsoft programs, including Word and Excel, and infects entire
networks.
</P>
<P>
   SERVICE DISRUPTED ON EBAY WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   The popular online auction service eBay experienced one of the
worst service disruptions in recent Internet memory, as technical
problems crashed the site.
</P>
<P>
   HECHINGER SET TO CLOSE 89 STORES
</P>
<P>
   The home improvement chain Hechinger filed for bankruptcy
protection and plans to close 89 stores to focus on its healthier
117 outlets. Separately, Kmart said it would reduce its earnings by
about $230 million because it had guaranteed the leases on the
Builders Square chain, which it sold to a venture that was combined
with Hechinger two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN TO CREATE 700,000 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment at a postwar high of 4.8 percent, the Japanese
government announced a plan to create more than 700,000 jobs. The
measures would include offering subsidies to emerging industries
like biotechnology and telecommunications. But the government did
not say how much it intended to spend, making it difficult to
assess the plan's potential for stimulating the economy.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA DELAYS AIRCRAFT ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines said that it would defer an order for 11 Boeing
777 aircraft and that it would put two 777s that it already owned
on the market because it could not reach an agreement with its
pilots on pay scales for flying the airplanes. The pilots, calling
the 777s moneymakers, have asked for $319 an hour to fly the 777,
while Delta has offered them $239 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   NEW NISSAN CHIEF PLANS CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Ghosn, the former Renault executive who will soon be
helping manage Nissan Motor, gave reporters a peek at where he
hoped to help steer the Japanese car maker.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE VICTORY FOR AMERICAN STEEL
</P>
<P>
   The International Trade Commission, a federal agency, handed
U.S. steel producers an important victory, approving punitive
tariffs to combat low-priced Japanese shipments. Tariffs ranging
from 18 percent to 67 percent will be ordered by the Clinton
administration within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   GM IS BUYING ARRIVA FLEET UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Arriva has agreed to sell its automotive fleet-management
business to the finance subsidiary of General Motors for 235
million pounds ($376 million).
</P>
<P>
   TRACKING PETS BY MICROCHIPS
</P>
<P>
   Microchips are reuniting lost pets with their owners. At least
1.6 million American dogs and cats now have identifying chips the
size of a grain of rice implanted in their shoulders, and three
manufacturers _ Home Again, Infopet and Avid _ are working to
develop an industry standard. Now, some people suggest, the same
technology could be used at hospitals to be sure babies are not
switched and later to help find children who are lost or kidnapped.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
