A2509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-INDONESIA-NYT &LR;      06-11 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INDONESIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INDONESIA'S TENTATIVE DEMOCRACY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 12:
</P>
<P>
   After 44 years of scripted elections and stultifying military
rule, the people of the world's fourth-largest country, Indonesia,
got their chance at real democracy this week. They grasped it
enthusiastically. Fears of violence proved unfounded. Press
coverage was admirably free. On Monday more than 100 million
Indonesians, 90 percent of those eligible, cast ballots for
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, delays in the vote count have now raised fears of
possible manipulation. Any such tampering would have disastrous
consequences, undermining Indonesia's prospects for political
stability and economic recovery. There are, however, other
plausible explanations for the slowdown, and international monitors
and opposition parties have so far refrained from condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   With some 20 percent of the vote now tallied, the front-runner
is the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle, or PDIP, led by
Megawati Sukarnoputri, the daughter of Indonesia's first president,
Sukarno, and a leading presidential candidate herself. President
B.J. Habibie's military-backed Golkar party is hovering between
second and third, well behind Mrs. Megawati's party. Projections
suggest that the PDIP will probably end up ith the largest
parliamentary delegation. With 48 parties fielding candidates, no
one group is likely to win a clear majority.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's next president will be chosen this fall by a special
assembly made up of the 462 newly elected members of Parliament, 38
delegates nominated by the armed forces and 200 others chosen by
local assemblies and designated interest groups. In this assembly
the military and its Golkar allies may try to use bribery, backroom
dealing or intimidation to impose their own favorite candidate
despite the opposition parties' strong showing this week. General
Wiranto, the armed forces commander who last year played a helpful
role in easing Indonesia's long-serving dictator, Suharto, from
power must make sure that his fellow officers do not try to
overturn the voters' choice.
</P>
<P>
   The next president's priority task will be to lead Indonesia out
of the economic crisis that has thrown 20 million of its people
into poverty since 1997. That will require rebuilding a shattered
banking system, cleaning up the crony business empires set up
during the long Suharto dictatorship and regaining the trust of
international investors. The next president must also spark enough
growth to rebuild drastically reduced tax revenues so that the
government can resume paying its bills. It will help if some of the
illicit billions allegedly amassed by the Suharto family can be
recovered. The Clinton administration is rightly looking into
whether any such money is now being held in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Megawati has been vague about her economic plans beyond
rejecting the Socialism favored by her father and embracing the
market. Habibie, her likely rival, has long been associated with
Suharto and his business cronies. Indonesians deserve to have the
hope and enthusiasm they showed during this election vindicated.
There must be a clean break from the electoral manipulations of the
past and from the failed economic policies of both the Sukarno and
the Suharto eras.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2207EDT &QL; 
