<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2512 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-TROOPS-     06-11 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-TROOPS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS ENTER KOSOVO CAPITAL; SERBS CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update and rewrite material sent earlier and to add a 2nd
take of new material.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Breaking assurances given to Washington,
a long column of Russian peacekeeping troops entered Kosovo and its
capital early Saturday morning amid scenes of wild celebration by
local Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said that the
movement of the troops into the Kosovo capital, hours before NATO
peacekeepers were to have entered the Serbian province, was a
mistake and that the soldiers would be ordered to leave. In
Washington, Clinton administration officials went into an emergency
meeting to try to find out what had happened and how they had been
left unaware of the movement.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian solder, Yevgeny Sadovsky, said: ``We came from Bosnia,
from Tuzla, and Ugljevik, and we are supposed to stay here for two
weeks, and then go back to Bosnia. We just came to prepare the
airport for our troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people packed the streets of Pristina to welcome
the Russian troops, firing pistols and automatic weapons into the
air and throwing flowers on Russian armored personnel carriers and
jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic,'' said Yvonne Stankovic, one of the Serbs
celebrating here. ``It may not be victory, but it shows NATO we are
not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ilija Karalic: ``The United States is not the only country
in the world. Our Russian brothers are here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians arrived in a column of some 50 military vehicles
and trucks as NATO peacekeeping forces on the border with Macedonia
prepared to move into Kosovo later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The unilateral Russian entry into Kosovo is sure to cause a new
crisis with Washington. It came despite promises on Friday from
Ivanov, the foreign minister, that Russia's troops would not enter
the province before NATO did.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov told CNN Saturday morning: ``The reasons for this are
being determined. They have been ordered to leave Kosovo
immediately and to await further orders.''
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman in Brussels, Belgium, said Saturday morning
that he had no details about the Russian action.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had been shocked earlier by reports that Russian
troops from Russia's peacekeeping mission in Bosnia had moved on
Friday through Yugoslavia and Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, and
might be heading south to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore had publicly said Friday that the
Russians would not move before NATO did. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott, who was flying from Moscow to Brussels after talks
broke down on how NATO and Russian forces would interact in Kosovo,
turned his airplane around and headed back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials, while seeking to have Russians
help solve the diplomatic crisis, had failed to negotiate a serious
peacekeeping role for the Russians under the U.N. mandate on
Thursday authorizing foreign troops to move into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had refused to serve directly under NATO command
and had backed Belgrade in insisting that the peacekeepers serve
under a U.N. flag, and not simply as a NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials stressed on Friday that 30 nations wanted to
participate in the Kosovo force, known as KFOR, a more
representative grouping than the 19 nations of NATO that waged a
78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, the crowd in Pristina fired hundreds of rounds
of ammunition into the air, kissed the Russian soldiers and jumped
upon their armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   They shouted slogans like, ``Serbia, Russia,'' ``Yeltsin,
Yeltsin, Yeltsin'' and ``We and the Russians, we are 300 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the crowd shouted insults aimed at the United States
and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Russian soldiers displayed the three-fingered Serbian salute
before the column moved off to the south, either toward Pristina's
airport or the Gratanica Monastery, one of the Serbian Orthodox
Church's holiest sites.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Russian troops had painted over the SFOR on their vehicles _
the acronym for the peacekeeping forces in Bosnia _ with KFOR, the
name of the Kosovo peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians and the Serbs, both Slavic peoples, also share
similar Orthodox faiths. While Yugoslav officials feel Moscow is
pursuing its own interests here, they are nonetheless glad to have
public support from Moscow and to embarrass the NATO alliance,
which had negotiated a peace that felt to Yugoslavs like a
capitulation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, during the war with NATO, Russia refused to provide
Belgrade with significant aid or even to lift sanctions. There is
no great love between Russia's president, Boris Yeltsin, and the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic. Russia's special envoy for
the Balkans, Victor Chernomyrdin, was an important factor in
getting Milosevic to agree to the bulk of NATO's terms.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, inspired by a message on local television
here that Russian forces would arrive at 10 p.m., about 3,000 local
Serbian residents gathered in the main square here to greet the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, boisterous and noisy, waved Serbian and Yugoslav
flags and burned an American one. The sound of gunfire, from shots
fired into the air from balconies and the streets, sounded like an
infantry invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, however, did not arrive until about 1:30 a.m.,
when there were still nearly 2,000 people in the street.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian move is not likely to comfort the ethnic Albanians
who have remained in Pristina or the nearly 1 million who were
pushed out of their homes by the Serbs. They are likely to be less
eager to return quickly to Kosovo from the refugee camps, and that
may have been one of Belgrade's ideas when it allowed the Russians
to move in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
