<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GUN GAMES IN THE HOUSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 12:
</P>
<P>
   With the gun control issue careening toward a probable showdown
on the House floor next week, Republicans need to decide whether
their fealty to the gun lobby will lead them to ignore the public's
demand for strong Congressional action to keep guns away from
children and criminals. Americans will not be fooled by halfway
measures, some of them watered-down versions of the provisions
approved last month by the Senate. The gun package introduced by
Rep.s Henry J. Hyde and Bill McCollum requires significant
strengthening if the House speaker, Dennis Hastert, is to fulfill
his promise of last month to make meaningful progress on gun
control. Yet Hastert seems reluctant to confront Republicans trying
to further weaken the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The hand of the National Rifle Association is most evident in
the watering down of a provision in the Senate bill that would
require mandatory background checks for all buyers at gun shows.
Under the House proposal, the definition of gun shows has been
altered to exempt shows with fewer than 10 vendors, even if
thousands of guns are sold. The House language also weakens the
Senate's record-keeping requirements, making tracing of firearms
sold at gun shows all but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The language also eases present restrictions in current law on
interstate gun shipments, gives vendors new protection from civil
liability and exempts gun-show vendors who sell their wares from
rolling carts from conducting any criminal background checks at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP proposal at least gives law enforcement 72 hours to
complete the background check for gun-show purchases, which is
better than the 24-hour limit the NRA aggressively lobbied for. But
that is less than the three business days provided in the Senate
bill _ a critical difference since most gun shows take place on
weekends, when court files needed to confirm convictions are
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the Republican House proposal would increase
the legal minimum age for all handgun purchases to 21 from 18 _ a
provision opposed by the NRA and absent from the Senate bill. But
for some reason, the proposal stops short of also raising the age
for handgun possession. In addition, House Republicans managed to
come up with an even weaker child safety lock requirement than the
one that passed the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there is still a chance to improve upon the flawed
proposals now on the table. The open question is whether Hastert
and his colleagues will allow that to happen. The public deserves a
full debate on the provisions in the bill and Democratic and
Republican proposals to strengthen them. Hastert should promptly
instruct the Rules Committee, which will meet early next week to
decide the debate's format, that he means to allow a thorough
airing and recorded votes on the full range of gun control issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
