<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VALENTINE ISSUED A FOOLISH CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Pa., Toronto, Mass.)  (jw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to Friday's National League edict, Bobby Valentine,
the Mets' manager, has been suspended for two games for ``the
violation of rule 5.1'' during Wednesday night's 4-3 victory over
the Toronto Blue Jays in 14 innings _ not remaining in the
clubhouse until the game ended after having been ejected. He also
was fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Valentine was suspended and fined for brazen
stupidity _ appearing briefly on the steps below the dugout in a
disguise: mustache, sunglasses, a black cap and a black Mets
T-shirt, after having been ejected in the 12th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday night's game with the Red Sox, Valentine explained
that he had been trying to ``lighten'' the mood on the Mets with
his disguise. And as the Mets did their stretching exercises at
Shea Stadium, some wore eyeblack strips as mustaches.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine has appealed his ban ``just to discuss it'' early next
week with Leonard Coleman Jr., the NL president, who lightened the
manager's wallet. But what's there to discuss? Through the years,
other ejected managers remained hidden in the runway and issued
instructions without being disciplined, but with his disguise
Valentine foolishly challenged Coleman's authority, especially
after a television cameraman spotted him. Coleman couldn't ignore
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Piazza told me, `I think that camera's got you,' ''
Valentine recalled.
</P>
<P>
   At the far end of the Blue Jays' dugout, the cameraman focused
on Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I was,'' Valentine was saying now, as if
describing a crime scene, as he stood on the steps below the Mets'
dugout. ``On this step, that's as far as I went and then I leaned
back against the wall for a few seconds. How long was I there?
Seconds. It might have been a little more than seconds, but I never
saw a play. I never saw a pitch. I don't know how the camera seemed
to have me sitting in the dugout. I never went up into the
dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine acknowledged, ``It was a mistake'' that would cost him
a few dollars. And unless Coleman shortens the suspension, it will
cost the Mets their manager for two games.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets make a run for the wild-card berth in the NL
playoffs, Valentine's disguise caper will quickly be forgotten. But
if they remain on a treadmill to another disappointing season
without a playoff berth, it will be remembered as another bizarre
incident that could contribute to his dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, tightly wound and sensitive to criticism, has a habit
of creating more controversies than he defuses, notably his stormy
relationship with Todd Hundley, now with the Dodgers, and this
week's squabble with Bobby Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his fourth season as the Mets' manager after eight with
the Texas Rangers, he should know better than to try to stand on
the edge of the dugout in a laughable disguise. The smiles he got
from his players weren't worth a two-game ban.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Valentine, like every other manager, has
stood in the runway below the dugout after being ejected. ``I've
heard of managers coming back as part of the ground crew, or
sitting in a front-row seat and giving signs,'' he said. ``Or
sitting in the bleachers with binoculars, or standing behind a
photographer or a TV cameraman.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda, the former Dodgers manager, remembered being
ejected, then putting on a trench coat, a hat and glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on the bench for three innings and none of my players
realized I was there,'' Lasorda said. ``But that was an exhibition
game with the Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Other managers have been more subtle, or more secretive, about
issuing instructions after an ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Leo Durocher, then managing the New York Giants, was
ejected from a game in Pittsburgh, then dressed, went up to the
Forbes Field press box and sat behind Barney Kremenko of The New
York Journal-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're giving the signs,'' Durocher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the signs,'' Kremenko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just do what I tell you,'' Durocher said.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the clubhouse, Durocher had got word to his
third-base coach to watch Kremenko in the press box. As the game
progressed, Durocher told Kremenko, for example, to touch his right
shoulder or his left shoulder, to raise his right arm or his left
arm. But to ease an itch, Kremenko suddenly scratched his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barney, what did you do?'' Durocher yelled. ``That's the steal
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a Giant was caught stealing. Kremenko did not
scratch his nose again. And if Bobby Valentine is as smart as he
thinks he is, he won't wear a disguise again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
