<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEGREGATION-0612-COX     06-11 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGREGATION-0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SCHOOLS ARE RESEGREGATING, SAYS CIVIL RIGHTS REPORT
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The separation of whites from African Americans and
Latinos in public schools has increased in the 1990's, according to
a new report from the Civil Rights Project at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this century nears its end, we are a decade into the
resegregation of our nation's schools,'' said the report released
Friday by Gary Orfield and John T. Yun.
</P>
<P>
   They reported that in 1970 the typical African-American student
attended a school in which 32 percent of the students were
non-Latino whites. That white percentage peaked at 36 percent in
1986, and fell steadily to 32.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For the typical Latino student, the proportion of non-Latino
whites in the same school dropped steadily from nearly 44 percent
in 1970 to 33 percent in 1980 and fell to 29.9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The result: While the average white student goes to a school
where fewer than 20 percent of the students are minorities, the
average student of African, Latino, Asian or Native American
heritage goes to a school where most students are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said the racial gap grew due to the faster
growth of the student population among racial minorities, and the
tendency of Americans to live near people of their own race and
income level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the Clinton administration has seen the largest
increases in segregation in the last half century, it has proposed
no policies to offset the trend and has not included the issue
among its priorities for education policy,'' said the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to look at is broader than that,'' responded
Julie Green, chief spokeswoman for the U.S. Department of
Education. ``We want to help parents get choices in where they send
their children to have an education, and make sure our resources
are targeted to the most disadvantaged students to level the
playing field, so all children can learn to high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Yun said programs that allow children to transfer to
magnet schools or charter schools within or even outside of their
districts have failed to break the racial patterns in which large
numbers of racial minorities end up in the same schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're concentrating poverty and its consequences into a
single school, and attempts to counter all those influences at once
is extremely difficult,'' Yun said in an interview. ``It's most
intense in the inner cities, but it's spreading now into the
suburbs, especially in large metropolitan areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He said schools with lots of poor children often perform below
par because they tend to have fewer parents with higher education,
a smaller selection of advanced courses, fewer teachers with
credentials in the subject they are teaching, more dropouts and
more untreated health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also miss out on the enriching social and cultural
exchanges that could take place if you put more students from
different races and income levels into the same schools,'' Yun
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
