<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS MIGHT HAVE A COACH WITH THEIR OFFER TO JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though an agreement has yet to be signed, Phil Jackson appears
to be honing in on taking over the Los Angeles Lakers for a deal
believed to be worth nearly $30 million over five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the team nor Jackson's agent, Todd Musburger, has
confirmed the two sides have reached a deal. Jackson, who coached
the Chicago Bulls to six championships, is fishing for king salmon
with family members in Alaska over the weekend. But Lakers
president Jerry West confirmed the Lakers had made contact with
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to deny the fact that we've talked to Phil
Jackson about coaching the Lakers next season,'' West said in a
prepared statement. ``With the success he's had in the NBA, he's
definitely an attractive candidate. However, we're exploring
several possibilities with different individuals and no decision
has been made yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential hiring of Jackson, who has not coached since
guiding the Bulls to their third straight title last season, is
expected to create a domino effect among the league's coaching
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   With the most-sought-after candidate nearing a deal, the
possibility that the Nets' interim coach, Don Casey, will remain in
New Jersey as the head coach increases. Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy, who dealt with the specter of Jackson looming as a possible
replacement for him for much of the season, would also gain a good
measure of job security.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Lakers' owner, Jerry Buss, nor West has met face to
face with Jackson, but the two parties are scheduled to meet early
next week. Jackson is planning to be in Los Angeles on Wednesday
with Bill Bradley, his friend and former teammate who is running
for president. They will be in town for a campaign fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Eastern Conference team official with knowledge
of Jackson's plans, the former Bulls coach was genuinely interested
in coaching the Lakers, the Nets and the Knicks, but firmly
believed the Laker job had more upside based solely on talent.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 10 days ago, persons close to Jackson believed that
he would not return to the game next season and instead take one
more year off.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment seemed to grow as Jackson's leverage with New
York seemed to decline; the Knicks turned their season around,
qualified for the playoffs and made a stunning run to the Eastern
Conference finals, with Van Gundy earning widespread support among
the team's fans.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson spurned a lucrative offer from the Nets, believed
to be in the neighborhood of $20 million over three seasons, it
became apparent his only viable option would be with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   If the two sides agree in principle over the next few days, the
decision by the club to dole out such a lucrative contract to a
coach is a major shift in management style for the Lakers. Less
than three weeks ago, team officials were privately discounting
Jackson as a candidate, based on the fact that Buss rarely spends a
fortune for coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kurt Rambis, the interim coach who has been a loyal team
employee since he retired as a player, was thought to have a fair
shot of returning _ if for no other reason than he only had three
months with the underachieving team after he replaced Del Harris at
midseason.
</P>
<P>
   A year after they were swept in four games by the Utah Jazz in
the Western Conference finals, the Lakers were swept in the
conference semifinals this season by the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond on-court chemistry problems and an off-floor feud between
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, the Lakers' acquisition of Dennis
Rodman turned into a disaster, with the unreliable rebounder
finally released by the team after a chaotic two months.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Rambis would return with the team and in
what capacity he might serve.
</P>
<P>
   En route to six championships in eight seasons, Jackson
assembled a regular-season winning percentage of .738 (545-193) in
his nine seasons as the Bulls' head coach. Named coach of the year
in 1996, he holds the National Basketball Association playoff
record for best winning percentage (.730).
</P>
<P>
   He was also a backup forward of the Knicks' last championship
team, in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's informal meeting with Madison Square Garden president
Dave Checketts in mid-April seemed to indicate a sincere interest
by the Knicks in bringing Jackson back to the franchise for which
he had played 11 seasons. But Checketts and Jackson never spoke
again about the possibility of becoming the Knicks' coach after
that meeting.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
