<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHESTRA-PERILS-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIONAL ORCHESTRAS FACE PERILOUS EXISTENCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Va.)  (jw) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Although they make no claims that their
orchestra rivals the New York Philharmonic or the Boston Symphony
Orchestra, the musicians and patrons of the Hudson Valley
Philharmonic can dream as gaudily as anyone. A year ago, they
dreamed of creating a summer home for the orchestra that might
become another Tanglewood.
</P>
<P>
   It was a vision as idyllic as Beethoven's ``Pastoral'' Symphony,
with concerts on the verdant lawn of a country club in Dutchess
County where lovers and families could picnic to the strains of
Tchaikovsky while fireworks illuminated the night.
</P>
<P>
   But the execution turned into something closer to Wagner's
``Gotterdammerung.'' At the opening concert on the evening of July
4, a rainstorm struck, flooding the stage, forcing the musicians to
flee, dimming the outdoor lights and sending thousands of soaked
spectators scurrying for cover. In the pandemonium, shuttle buses
filled with concertgoers trying to escape slid into one another on
the muddy field, while someone fired off the fireworks in an
incongruous effort to light up the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse. Publicity about the debacle was blamed for
hurting the box-office take of the subsequent concerts. The
orchestra found itself grappling with an entrepreneur who had
promised to pay all the bills and was now stalling, just as
creditors said he had done in a history of sour deals that seemed
to have escaped the attention of the orchestra's board.
</P>
<P>
   The swamp of debt soon reached $617,189, forcing the orchestra
to dismiss most of its administrative staff and, in April, to file
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, the Bardavon 1869 Opera House in Poughkeepsie, the
orchestra's principal home, had taken over the orchestra's assets
and administration. In the process, the philharmonic had to
surrender its 40-year-old independence as an institution and
eliminate concerts in Kingston and Newburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the lush, rolling hills, tranquil dairy farms and weathered
cities where its audience resides, the orchestra has pained and
bitterly divided its devotees with its near-death experience.
Musicians and a few board members are angry not only at Francis
Zarro Jr., the sometimes grandiose entrepreneur, but also at board
leaders _ including a bank executive _ for not exercising common
prudence and rejecting a deal that eventually compelled the
orchestra to put up money for the production costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable that people who are conservative would have
allowed themselves to be sweet-talked into something like this,''
said Susan Seligman, the orchestra's principal cellist.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley's summer fiasco has drawn attention to the
hand-to-mouth existence of the nation's regional orchestras. These
ensembles play the live classical music most Americans hear, but
they walk a much more perilous tightrope than do orchestras in
large cities where money, musicians and music lovers are more
plentiful. There are at least 600 classical orchestras in the
United States, and all but 50 are on the scale of the Hudson
Valley, with limited seasons and annual budgets of less than $2
million, according to the American Symphony Orchestra League.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley Philharmonic has 65 musicians, usually
performs about 15 concerts a season and has a budget of $1 million.
The New York Philharmonic has 107 full-time musicians, a season of
126 performances and a budget of $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley's musicians are the next rung down on the
professional ladder, conservatory-trained musicians who spend their
days scrambling to stitch together their livelihoods. Blair
Tindall, the orchestra's principal oboist, has been known to play
at a Saturday matinee of ``Les Miserables'' on Broadway, then drive
up the Taconic Parkway and arrive in Poughkeepsie in time for the
philharmonic's evening concert. She earns $100 a performance and
$25 a rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has substituted in the New York Philharmonic, she
knows she will probably never work there full time, since it has
only four oboists and a slot may open up once a decade. Like many
of her colleagues, she has idealistic notions about the importance
of regional orchestras in small cities and whistle-stops where
their concerts may provide a rare chance for aspiring musicians to
hear the classical canon live or for residents to savor an elegant
night out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like virtually all regional orchestras, the Hudson Valley
Philharmonic has always struggled to balance its books. But its
current troubles began with an enticing proposition. In 1997,
Zarro, 48, a Bronx-bred lawyer who had just bought the Island Green
Country Club in Amenia, N.Y., proposed a summer concert series at
the club to the orchestra's administrative director, RoseMarie
Freni. He said concerts on the club's bowl-shaped lawn would
enhance the visibility of his property and the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the orchestra's board say he burnished his
credibility by mentioning that he represented a group bidding on
the Washington Redskins football team and that he was buying casino
properties in Las Vegas. He also sponsored three philharmonic
concerts inside the country club, and these came off without a
hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the orchestra's 20 or so board members were beguiled by
the idea of six summer concerts that would provide extra work for
musicians, create a new revenue source and cultivate larger
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped in time to see this whole project turn into another
Wolf Trap or Tanglewood,'' said Joseph Tockarshewsky, who at the
time was president of the orchestra's board and chief executive of
Poughkeepsie Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Others were skeptical, particularly since there was talk that
Zarro had left a trail of sour financial deals. The doubting
Thomases like Frank Meyer, former managing editor of Variety, and
Richard Sampson, a Bell Atlantic executive, were reassured,
however, by executives of the orchestra board who said that Zarro
would provide the production money up front.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, bothered to check Zarro's background. Zarro,
who lives in Stanfordville, N.Y., has said that he filed for
personal bankruptcy in 1994. After the summer disaster, The
Poughkeepsie Journal published a list of 11 lawsuits, tax liens and
default judgments against Zarro and his enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Zarro's financial history, his lawyer, David Sall,
disputed the validity of individual legal actions, then added:
``I'm not trying to paint pictures of sainthood. Frank Zarro is an
entrepreneur. He makes a fortune; he loses a fortune. Anybody who
wants to know the story of Frank Zarro can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Florida, where he was exploring
some fresh real estate deals, Zarro said his financial troubles
were widely known.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Freni, the orchestra's administrative director, said the
watershed moment came in April 1998 when Tockarshewsky signed a
contract for the summer series. She said that Tockarshewsky should
have required Zarro to agree to an explicit payment schedule that
was drawn up to ensure that the orchestra had money to pay its
vendors for portable toilets, generators, playbills and
advertising. Zarro, she said, had apparently balked, citing
uncertainty about his cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You supposedly have professional men, including a bank
president, who should have said, `No, let's not do it,' '' said Ms.
Freni, who lost her job in November.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense, Tockarshewsky said he had believed that the box
office income would be sufficient to cover the bills even if Zarro
stalled on paying them. Associates of Tockarshewsky added that he
also believed the overall contract obligated Zarro to meet the
payment schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Had the July 4 concert been a success, events might have turned
out differently.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ray Charles, the headliner for the final concert, could not
turn things around. As the shortfall deepened, Zarro repeatedly
promised to repay money, but he never fully came through, board
members said.
</P>
<P>
   Zarro contends he lost $750,000, accuses the orchestra's
management of overspending and building a shoddy stage, and blames
it for giving away tickets. When the Hudson Valley Philharmonic
sued him to recover its losses, he countered with his own lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told people I had the money up front to pay for
this,'' he said. ``In fact, when they asked for a schedule of
payments, I refused to do so, and they signed it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he hopes to repay the orchestra and vendors
someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did wrong was I shot too high, I aspired for too
much,'' he said. ``Not only did I dream, but they did too.''
</P>
<P>
   To almost everyone else, however, Zarro deserves most of the
blame.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who succeeded Tockarshewsky as president of the
orchestra's board, said ``You're at a disadvantage when you believe
people will do what they say they're going to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
