<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2535 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDIOS-FILMS-$ADV13-     06-11 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIOS-FILMS-$ADV13-1120(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE STUDIOS LEARN TO LIVE WITH LESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (for release Sunday, June 13) 
(rk) 
 By   BERNARD WEINRAUB and GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Ten years ago, the stars, and their agents, ruled
Hollywood. Duds like ``Legal Eagles'' and ``Family Business'' were
packaged by talent agents for clients like Robert Redford, Dustin
Hoffman and Sean Connery, and the studios, without batting an eye,
paid lavish sums to make them.
</P>
<P>
   But now the studios are regaining the upper hand, and their main
weapon is supply and demand. Under strict orders from their
corporate owners to pay more heed to the bottom line, studios are
making fewer films, forcing the people who work in the industry to
carve up a smaller pie.
</P>
<P>
   Midlevel actors and directors, hungry for jobs, are quietly
willing to take pay cuts. And while top stars and directors can
still usually write their own tickets _ Steven Spielberg and Tom
Hanks earned $40 million each from the success of ``Saving Private
Ryan'' _ sometimes even the most high-profile projects are dropped
altogether if their costs seem unlikely to be recouped.
</P>
<P>
   Those who control the big studios _ many of which have been
reduced to midsized operating units of giant conglomerates _ devote
much of their creative energies to conjuring up new ways to limit
the financial risks of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   The artists may not like it, but the corporate bosses know that
is the only way to get predictable earnings in a low-margin
business, one in which the flops far outnumber the hits. And that
mind-set has stripped the movie business of some of the sex appeal
that a decade ago _ in the pre-dot-com era _ made it a mecca for
investors the world over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the return on capital in the film industry, it
has to be in the midsingle digits, which is probably no better than
a Treasury bill,'' said David J. Londoner, a media analyst for
Schroder &AMP; Co. He estimated that overall profits from the major
film studios would drop about 20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The television divisions make money, the film library makes
money, but current releases lose money,'' Londoner said. ``It's
worse than it has been for the past couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood sky, of course, is hardly falling. Producers,
executives and talent agents still earn huge sums. Christopher
McGurk, a former top executive at Universal Pictures, was recently
hired as vice chairman and chief operating officer by the
floundering Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer for a five-year compensation
package worth at least $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   And though Tom Cruise deferred his customary $20 million-plus
salary for a hefty percentage of Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide
Shut,'' he may easily earn double that if the film is successful.
</P>
<P>
   But revenues have simply not kept up, as the average cost of a
film doubled between 1993 and 1998, from $26.1 million to $52.7
million, and marketing costs climbed 79 percent, to $25.3 million.
Something had to give. And it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time of creative deal-making _ and I mean that as a
euphemism,'' said Tom Strickler, a partner at the Endeavor talent
agency, which represents actors like Adam Sandler and Bette Midler.
``Artists can't be as selective as they once were.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some agents are being laid off. And a growing number
of producers _ as well as actors, filmmakers and technicians _ can
no longer count on being kept on a studio payroll as they scout for
projects or seek jobs in television.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the shift can be traced to changing film-industry
economics. In the 1980s and early 1990s, the home-video, cable and
pay-TV businesses exploded, creating new sources of revenue for the
studios.
</P>
<P>
   Box-office receipts, which generated 35 percent of film revenues
in 1990, dwindled to 24 percent last year. But in the last few
years, the growth in the home-video business has slowed, and DVDs,
which some studios are heralding as the next big source of revenue,
are still in their infancy.
</P>
<P>
   In this bottom-line atmosphere, studios negotiate with talent
agents, but their dictum is simple: Take it or leave it. This is a
striking turnabout from the 1980s and early 1990s, when Michael
Ovitz, then chairman of the Creative Artists Agency, dominated
Hollywood by packaging projects for actors and directors and
virtually telling studios the same thing studios are telling agents
now. Ovitz himself is seeking to return to Hollywood, this time as
a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were delivering product to very receptive buyers,'' said
Ron Meyer, who once worked as a partner with Ovitz at Creative
Artists but now sits on the other side of table as president of
Universal Studios. ``In today's climate, with the risks so great,
it's just much easier for a studio to say no to anything they
believe is not very commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Talent agents are adjusting. ``If a movie doesn't fit a studio's
financial model, they can do without making it,'' said David
O'Connor, a top agent at Creative Artists. He minimized the shift,
saying that the movie business was facing a ``correction.'' Studios
are reasserting financial controls, he said, but the talent _ or at
least top stars and a handful of directors _ are still the main
engine.
</P>
<P>
   But there are limits. Recently, Dreamworks refused to pay Brad
Pitt, whose last few films have fallen short of their studios'
expectations, his $15 million fee for a film about the world of
rock music written and directed by Cameron Crowe, who made ``Jerry
McGuire.'' Instead, Billy Crudup, a relative unknown, will play the
role _ for less than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage dropped his fee from $20 million to $8 million to
work within the budget of Martin Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the
Dead,'' about paramedics in Hell's Kitchen, due out in October from
Paramount. And after extensive wrangling with 20th Century Fox,
agents for Cuba Gooding Jr. have agreed to take less than his
customary $3 million for an action film, ``Navy Diver.''.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers, once an extravagant spender on hits like
``Lethal Weapon'' and flops like ``The Postman,'' surprised
Hollywood last year by shelving two big-budget films: a new version
of ``Superman,'' which was to star Nicolas Cage and Kevin Spacey,
and ``I Am Legend,'' an action-adventure film with Arnold
Schwarzenegger, whose career has lagged in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has been forced to see the cold realities of the
very narrow profit margins of the movie business,'' said Brian
Grazer, producer of films like ``Ransom'' and ``Apollo 13.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the influx of conglomerates, which have moved
into the business on the theory that while film operations may not
always be great moneymakers, they enhance the value of cable
channels and TV networks, and build lucrative film libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are really trying to do is to build asset values that
help your other businesses,'' Londoner, the media analyst, said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   News Corp., run by Rupert Murdoch, started the trend in 1985 by
buying 20th Century Fox. It was followed into the industry by Sony,
which bought Columbia; Viacom, which bought Paramount, and
Matsushita, which bought Universal and then sold it to Seagram.
</P>
<P>
   In the halcyon days of growth in home video and cable, the
number of films produced rose sharply. But the corporate owners
have finally begun to apply pressure on their studios _ which,
though glamorous, are much riskier enterprises than many of the
other business lines competing with them for management attention
and capital.
</P>
<P>
   Films and television accounted for 68 percent of Paramount
Communications' 1988 revenues; last year, they represented 39
percent of Viacom's sales. At Time Warner, they are around 30
percent of sales, down from 37 percent a decade earlier at Warner
Communications, before the merger with Time Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At Disney, it is almost impossible to figure out how the film
and TV business is doing, because its results are lumped in with
the ABC television network and other operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These used to be stand-alone entities, and as such they were
the total focus of the management,'' said Herbert Allen, who heads
Allen &AMP; Co., an investment banking firm in New York that
specializes in media deals. ``Now they are divisions of larger
companies, representing dramatically less of a percentage of sales
and earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, corporate chiefs are applying heavy pressure on
division heads to control spending so that even a bad run of films
will not crush earnings. ``The Eisners, Murdochs and Redstones have
all woken up and said, `This can't go on,''' said Joe Roth,
chairman of Walt Disney Studios, referring to the chief executives
of Disney, the News Corp. and Viacom, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   So Brian Mulligan, executive vice president at Seagram's
Universal, likes to talk about managing a ``portfolio of films''
assembled to reduce risk, while Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin
is quick to point out that Warner's film and television business is
only 11 percent of cash flow. (That helps to explain why Time
Warner stock climbed even while Warner Brothers studios endured
several flops in recent years like ``The Avengers,'' ``Quest for
Camelot'' and ``Father's Day.'')
</P>
<P>
   At Fox Filmed Entertainment, chairman Bill Mechanic and his
associates recently spent more than a year scaling back the budget
of the Sean Connery romantic adventure ``Entrapment.'' The film was
initially budgeted at $140 million, but the price tag was slashed
to $60 million, Mechanic said.
</P>
<P>
   The studio hired a new director willing to work within its
budget, dropped numerous costly action sequences and revised the
script to focus more on character. The film, which was released in
late April, has grossed $75 million and, with foreign ticket sales,
will probably turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Similar re-evaluations across Hollywood are having a striking
impact. For the most part, studios make either large-scale films
like ``The Mummy,'' ``The Matrix,'' or ``Armageddon,'' with appeal
to a wide, international audience, or smaller films aimed at
specific moviegoers, like teen-agers, women or African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies are either more global in their appeal, or they're more
focused and targeted to specific audiences,'' said Casey Silver, a
producer and a former chairman at Universal Studios, who gave the
go-ahead to ``The Mummy'' and acquired ``Notting Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Grown-up films _ movies more serious or sophisticated than, say,
the new hit ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' released
this weekend _ are increasingly left to independents.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of the leading ``independents,'' like Disney's
Miramax, Time Warner's Fine Line and Fox Searchlight, are not
independent at all but are owned by the same companies that control
studios. But the financial contrasts nonetheless are startling, as
these production outfits operate with lower overhead, and actors
expect lower fees when they make independent films.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fox Searchlight's ``The Full Monty,'' which cost $3.5 million
and grossed $250 million around the world, is one of the most
profitable films of the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's ``The Horse Whisperer'' and ``Six Days, Seven Nights,''
by contrast, grossed $190 million and $175 million, respectively,
but did not make a dime for the studio. The reason? Huge budgets
and marketing costs, and hefty salaries for the likes of Robert
Redford, Harrison Ford and the director Ivan Reitman.
</P>
<P>
   Roth made it clear that as a studio chief, he has limited
options. Fewer and fewer studios are making serious films _ those
designed for a relatively small audience ``that's older, requires
the most in terms of production value and wants to have movie
stars,'' he said. ``So if we make a high-end drama intended for
adults over 40, then you're dealing with an audience that shows up
only sporadically and that requires great reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I have it executed one degree short of perfection, I
may lose it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, he said, younger audiences do not require expensive
stars, often return to the same film two or three _ or even more _
times and are unaffected by critics. For studios like Disney, the
choice is clear.
</P>
<P>
   The mantra for many, but not all, studio executives in Hollywood
is now ``sharing the risk,'' or laying off part of a film's cost by
seeking a financial partner or pre-selling the foreign rights to
other distributors. The most notable example is ``Titanic,'' which
grossed $1.8 billion around the world but was notoriously over
budget before its Christmas 1997 release.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which had the film rights, put up $135 million of the $200
million cost and distributed the film overseas. Paramount paid the
rest and released the film in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After the costs were recouped, Fox has received 60 percent of
the revenues while the remainder has gone to Paramount. However
lucrative the film, though, the partnership was so tense that there
was a near-fistfight between two top studio executives over the
movie's release date.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of top executives and producers are ambivalent, at
best, about sharing costs. Those who make such deals, said John
Calley, chairman of Sony Pictures Entertainment, are letting their
anxiety about their own decisions stop them from capitalizing on
their successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you're betting the downside, you're not supporting
your creative choices,'' Calley said. Sony, which buys rights but
does not sell them, is now sharing the costs of two films with
Universal and one with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   A different corporate approach is typified by Jonathan Dolgen,
chairman of the Viacom Entertainment Group, Paramount's parent.
</P>
<P>
   Although Paramount owns most of its films outright, he said, the
studio strongly believes in spreading risks by splitting costs,
whether by taking on equity investors, acquiring limited rights to
movies or making other arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It substantially modifies the thing that people on the Street
most hate about the movie business, which is the wild swings,''
Dolgen said. ``If you have a movie that cost $100 million, you can
wake up on the first Saturday morning after it opens and realize
you've lost $50 million. There are a limited number of those
Saturday mornings that you actually want to entertain that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, there are some possible new revenues that may
ease the stinginess, with studio chiefs saying the advent of
higher-quality digital video disks, or DVDs, will prompt moviegoers
to rebuild their film libraries. Robert A. Daly, co-chairman of
Warner Brothers, is especially hopeful. ``DVD, pay per view, video
on demand _ these are the critical areas of the movie business over
the next few years,'' he said. ``And the good part about DVD is
it's going to bring in revenues in the area that doesn't push up
costs: the library.''
</P>
<P>
   But optimism is in somewhat short supply in Hollywood. Studio
executives have even noticed that the glitter of Internet riches is
shining brighter among ambitious college graduates than the glitz
of movieland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an explosion of industries with a visual
orientation, with the computer and the Internet, and for the
moment, those are far more interesting,'' said Allen. ``If you look
at the total compensation of the people in those industries, and
the wealth generated, the Internet businesses make everyone else
look small, boring and pale in comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   But Calley, who helped run Warner Brothers studios from 1968 to
1981, takes the long view. He recalled that Warner Brothers and
Stanley Kubrick were locked in a dispute in 1970 over the costs of
``A Clockwork Orange.'' Kubrick insisted on spending $1.32 million
on the film, while Calley wanted to spend $1.28 million. A
compromise was reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but we were having budget interviews with
Variety and The Hollywood Reporter in the mid-'70s about how these
out-of-control costs were going to destroy the industry,'' he said.
``What occurs over and over again is that as costs seem to have
reached the ultimate state of `out of control,' along comes a new
income stream, a la DVD, that takes up the slack and resuscitates
you through yet another cycle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
