<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-U.S.ATTORNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FEDERAL PROSECUTOR QUITS, ASPIRING SUCCESSORS RUSH IN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Calif.)   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among those seeking to become the U.S. attorney for
the Eastern District of New York when Zachary Carter steps down in
July is his chief assistant. But others who work or have worked in
Carter's office, and lawyers in private practice, have also
expressed interest, other lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   The chief assistant, Loretta Lynch, said this week that she was
a candidate for the job of top federal prosecutor for Brooklyn,
Queens, Staten Island and Long Island. The post involves heading
one of the busiest federal prosecution offices in the nation, with
a regular stream of high-profile cases, like the one that climaxed
this week: the prosecution of New York City police officers accused
of brutalizing Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., to recommend Carter's
successor to President Clinton. But a person close to the senator,
speaking on the condition of anonymity, said this week that no one
has an edge at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Donoghue, a Manhattan-based lawyer who is the chairman of
the senator's screening committee for federal judgeships and U.S.
attorney posts, declined Friday to say how many candidates there
were for the job, which pays $118,000 a year. He would not reveal
any of the candidates' names.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who has held the job for six years, announced several
weeks ago that he would be leaving to join the New York office of
Dorsey &AMP; Whitney, a Minneapolis-based law firm. Those who are
interested in applying for the job have until Tuesday to submit
their names.
</P>
<P>
   Once a candidate is nominated by President Clinton, the
appointment will be subject to confirmation by the
Republican-controlled Senate. If the entire process is not
completed by the time Carter leaves office, Attorney General Janet
Reno will appoint an interim replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials declined to speculate Friday on Ms.
Reno's likely choice. Schumer has directed his screening committee
``to move as expeditiously as possible,'' said a spokeswoman,
Cathie Levine.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said: ``It is the senator's choice, and I respect his
prerogative. I do believe Loretta Lynch, who is my chief assistant,
is extremely well qualified for the position of U.S. attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynch has been with the office for nine years and has been
No. 2 to Carter for the last 15 months. She was a member of the
prosecution team in the racially charged Louima trial, in which one
officer pleaded guilty in May to torturing Louima, a Haitian
immigrant, in a Brooklyn police station in 1997 and a second
officer was convicted on Tuesday of helping in the crime. Three
other officers were acquitted of other charges in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers who practice in the federal courts in New York said
Ms. Lynch's competition could include current and former
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have indicated interest in the job, they said,
are Alan Vinegrad, a member of the Louima trial team, and two
former top aides to Carter, Barbara D. Underwood and Valerie
Caproni.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad, who is chief of the criminal division in Carter's
office and has worked in the office eight years, declined Friday to
comment. He was a member of the prosecution team in another
racially charged Brooklyn case, in which two black men were
convicted in 1997 in the fatal stabbing of a Hasidic Jew in Crown
Heights in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caproni, who headed the criminal division until she left
last September to become regional director of the Pacific Regional
office of the Securities and Exchange Commission, said Friday from
her office in Los Angeles: ``I'm incredibly flattered that my name
is coming up, and I think that being U.S. attorney for the Eastern
District is one of the best jobs in the country. I was in the
office for a long time, and I feel close to it.'' She was the
second half of the team in the Crown Heights trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Underwood, who preceded Ms. Lynch as Carter's chief
assistant, left that post early last year to become principal
deputy solicitor general of the United States. Reached at her
office in Washington on Thursday, she declined to comment. Two
people who know her said they believed she had decided not to seek
to succeed Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Kamins, a lawyer in private practice, said he had
submitted his name after people ``who were in touch'' with the
screening committee suggested that he do so. He is a former
president of the Brooklyn Bar Association. Roger Adler, a lawyer
who is chairman of the bar association's federal courts committee,
said he was considering putting his hat in the ring.
</P>
</TEXT>
