<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELLFISH-HARVEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS WARN AGAINST HARVESTING SHELLFISH ON SEATTLE'S URBAN
BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ How much urban shellfish should a shucker shun if a
shucker should shun urban shellfish?
</P>
<P>
   All of them, say public health officials. Given that this
weekend is the beginning of the lowest tide of the year, they are
warning against harvesting shellfish on any urban beach because of
an ever-present pollution risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real potential that people will be exposing
themselves to chronic contaminants,'' said Wayne Clifford, manager
of shellfish safety for the Washington state Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   In King County, for example, most of the urban beaches are
considered unsafe for recreational shellfish consumption because of
sewage run-off and a toxic smorgasbord of chemical pollutants used
by homeowners and industry that sometimes ends up in Puget Sound
through storm drains.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking, which can eliminate most natural hazards, has no effect
on many chemical contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area is so urbanized and there are so many potential
sources of contamination we feel people need to go to beaches away
from populated areas,'' said Larry Kirchner, acting director of
environmental health for the public health department of Seattle
and King County.
</P>
<P>
   The only beaches in King County considered safe for recreational
shellfish harvesting are some of the beaches on Vashon Island,
Kirchner said. This appears to be because those areas have better
water flow and lower population density, he said.
</P>
<P>
   King County may have the highest number of contaminated beaches,
but it doesn't have all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just a problem for Seattle,'' emphasized Clifford.
</P>
<P>
   Many beaches in Pierce and Kitsap counties are equally risky
because of sewage runoff and chemical pollutants, he said. Even
some rural beaches that may look all right may not be because of
local industry effluent or a sewage treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   The risk posed by the naturally occurring organisms such as
``red tide'' _ technically, paralytic shellfish poisoning _ is a
separate concern that public health officials are often able to
monitor and warn against.
</P>
<P>
   The health risk from pollutants such as toxic heavy metals or
pesticides is too difficult to adequately monitor, Clifford said,
so consumers need to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Kirchner noted that there is already ample evidence of the
accumulation of toxic chemicals in sediments throughout Puget Sound
_ enough to suggest that frequent consumption of shellfish from
urban beaches could raise a person's risk of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination comes from sewage treatment plant runoffs and
stormwater outfalls that contaminate the water with bacterial and
viral toxins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shellfish that are commercially raised and harvested are
safe,'' said Dr. Alonzo Plough, director of public health for
Seattle and King County.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial shellfish beds are more carefully monitored and
tested for contaminants than are recreational harvest areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real well-equipped to monitor Puget Sound for bacteria
and bio-toxins,'' said Clifford.
</P>
<P>
   He said the state has about 1,000 water quality instruments,
many of them near commercial shellfish beds, that keep a constant
watch out for bacterial contaminants such as red tide or E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   But the monitoring program is not able to detect all potential
hazards, Clifford said, and cannot ever offer a complete guarantee
against the risk from shellfish consumption.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 Institute of Medicine report on ``Seafood Safety''
chaired by a former University of Washington professor of marine
food science, Dr. John Liston, found that ``chronic illness
resulting from seafood consumption is associated primarily with
environmental contamination.''
</P>
<P>
   A large proportion of the shellfish eaten in the United States
comes from recreational harvest, Liston's committee found, and very
little of it is adequately analyzed for potential health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water in Puget Sound is cleaner than it used to be,'' said
Liston, who is now retired from the UW. ``But some of the areas
subject to domestic pollution can contain all kinds of chemicals.
... There's so many of them and they're now used so liberally.''
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms associated with eating contaminated shellfish include
mild to severe stomach upset, diarrhea, nausea or fever. Symptoms
of infection from red tide begin with a numbness or tingling in the
lips that can progress to serious respiratory paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesser-known, naturally occurring hazard is vibrio, a
bacterium found more frequently in shellfish as the water
temperature increases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
