<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-1STLD-W     06-11 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOP MOVEMENTS RAISE CONCERNS OVER RUSSIA'S INTENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to recast as news analysis with updated information.)  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The arrival of Russian troops in Pristina, the capital
of Kosovo, before dawn Saturday raises disturbing questions about
the Kremlin's control of the military.
</P>
<P>
   After Russian troops moved into Yugoslavia on Friday, Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov assured the Clinton administration
that the force would not enter Kosovo until Russia had reached an
understanding with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours later, however, Ivanov was reading a dawn statement
on Cable News Network, declaring that the Kosovo deployment was a
colossal mistake and announcing that the Russian troops would
immediately be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War, Russian troops have been
bedraggled and dispirited but obedient. They have done what the
Kremlin has told them, despite their poor pay, declining status in
Russian society and resentment of NATO's expansion into central
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But following NATO's air raids on Yugoslavia, senior Russian
military officials increasingly seem to have had their own foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Alarm was generated Friday when a senior Russian defense
ministry official, Col. Gen. Leonid Ivashov, publicly warned that
Moscow might unilaterally send troops to Kosovo if NATO did not
drop its insistence that it command all of the peacekeeping forces
there.
</P>
<P>
   The same general raised eyebrows earlier this month when he
denounced as a sellout the settlement supported by Russian envoy
Victor Chernomydrin.
</P>
<P>
   With Moscow a battleground of intrigue, there were several
possibilities to explain what happened Saturday morning, none of
them particularly reassuring. Top Russian military officials may
have simply ignored their civilian counterparts and urged the
troops on in a mad rush to beat NATO's force to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Russian military's system of command and control may be
so frayed that Moscow found it impossible to stop the forces before
they entered Kosovo after the initial deployment orders had been
given.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing questions concerned the role of Boris Yeltsin,
Russia's president and the ultimate commander of the military.
Would he back Ivanov and hold Russian military leaders to account?
Or has his authority dissipated to the point where the military is
free to challenge the civilian leaders?
</P>
<P>
   Disturbingly, Yeltsin's top spokesman, Dmitri Yakushkin, was
initially unaware that Russian troops had left Bosnia for
Yugoslavia when he was asked about it earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The system of controls on Russia's nuclear forces is generally
considered to be strict. But the developments of Friday and
Saturday were bound to generate searching questions about the
checks on the military in that area, too.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's mini-crisis began without warning when about 175
Russian soldiers suddenly left their peacekeeping posts in Bosnia
and drove into Yugoslavia. The troops had painted ``KFOR'' on their
vehicles, the name of the peacekeeping force designated for Kosovo,
indicating they intended to take up positions there. The movement
of the Russian forces prompted fears among NATO leaders that the
Kremlin was preparing to seize its own peacekeeping sector in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Ivanov assured Washington _ wrongly, as it turned out
_ that the troops would not enter Kosovo, U.S. concern about a
potential political, and perhaps even military, confrontation with
the Russians was so great that U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott, en route to Brussels, Belgium, by plane, was
instructed to turn around in mid-flight and rush back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The column from Bosnia was not the only worry NATO had. Another
1,000 paratroopers were on alert, waiting to be flown to
Yugoslavia, the Russian defense ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said Washington anticipated additional troops
would be sent to Yugoslavia because Hungary had granted a Russian
request for overflight rights for its troop transport planes. The
official added that the United States had received conflicting
reports that a Russian IL-76 troop transport plane might have
already landed in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   It was the abruptness of the Russian troop movements and the
fact that the troops made their move after a deadlock about the
role of Russian peacekeepers in Kosovo that alarmed NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The allies had insisted that all of the peacekeeping troops in
Kosovo must be under a unified command led by a NATO general.
Russia, however, has adamantly refused to put its troops under NATO
control and has insisted that it be given a sector of its own to
control.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO insists that the Russians have never been under any
illusion about its demand, the issue was dealt with indirectly in
the resolution the U.N. Security Council adopted early this week.
An annex to the resolution refers to the need for ``unified command
and control'' but does not say explicitly that NATO must lead the
force.
</P>
<P>
   After generals from U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff and the Russian
defense ministry failed to agree in talks here Friday on a solution
on the question of command, the chief Russian negotiator issued a
blunt warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this agreement is not reached Russia has the same right as
NATO,'' Ivashov said. ``We shall announce a sector that will be
agreed with the Yugoslav side and which will meet our interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with reports of Russian troop movements, that statement
set off alarm bells at NATO's military headquarters in Belgium and
at the Skopje, Macedonia, headquarters for the allied peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military leaders were worried that the Russians might
simply drive into Kosovo, claim a sector in the northern and
heavily Serb part of the province and, in the words of one ranking
allied official, ``create facts on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is vehemently opposed to the establishment of a
Russian sector, fearing that ethnic Albanians would be afraid to
return there. This could create a de facto partition of Kosovo with
ethnic Albanians in some areas and Serbs in others, an arrangement
NATO has said it would never allow.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that NATO might have won its war with Yugoslavia only to
lose control of the peace, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who was visiting Macedonia, made an urgent phone call to her
counterpart, Ivanov, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially repudiating Gen. Ivashov, the Russian foreign
minister assured Albright that Russian troops would not enter
Kosovo without an understanding with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, Ivanov added, was simply doing what NATO has been doing
for months: assembling peacekeeping forces outside Kosovo in
anticipation that they will soon be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreign minister said he understands that there was to be
a unified command,'' Albright said. ``He also said this was a
preliminary step so that if and when they become part of the
international security presence today, they will be in a position
to deploy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ivanov's twin assurances to, first, prevent the
deployment and, now, reverse it, Russia remains deeply unhappy over
NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and the way the alliance is managing
the peace. The Russian foreign minister said on Friday that Moscow
would never agree to a command arrangement in which its troops are
``subordinated'' to NATO officers.
</P>
<P>
   One fear, a Russian official said Friday night, is that NATO
peacekeepers would enter Kosovo and spread out through the
province. By the time a solution for the command problem might be
found, the Russia peacekeepers would be superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are concerns that if NATO enters Kosovo first there
might be no place left for other forces,'' the Russian official
said. ``We will be begging for some place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time that the Russian military appeared
to have chartered its own foreign policy on Kosovo. After
Chernomyrdin, the Russian special envoy, returned from his mission
to Belgrade with the Finnish president, Gen. Ivanshov assailed the
accord as a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin later intervened to support a settlement. Ivashov,
however, not only kept his position; he led the Russian delegation
in the talks Friday on command arrangements for peacekeepers in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russian politics aside, the latest developments undercut efforts
to rebuild trust between the two sides following NATO's 78-day
bombing campaign, the most divisive event in Russia's relations
with the West since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong student of Russian politics, Talbott, the deputy
secretary of state, was one of the architects of the strategy to
include Moscow in a Balkan settlement and restore U.S.-Russian
relations. But Friday night, even Talbott's erudition was
challenged by the bewildering intrigue and pandemonium of Russian
politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-99 2250EDT &QL; 
