u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-NY     06-11 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTINE SUSPENDED AND FINED BY LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mets manager Bobby Valentine was suspended for two
games and fined $5,000 by the National League on Friday for
violating a league rule by not staying in the clubhouse after he
was ejected from the game Wednesday night. Valentine appealed the
suspension and may keep managing until his case is heard by NL
president Leonard Coleman early next week.
</P>
<P>
   After Valentine said he would not comment on the suspension or
the appeal, he proceeded vehemently to defend his actions to
reporters by saying he never returned to the dugout and was in the
stairwell leading to the dugout for only a matter of seconds. Like
a detective retracing a crime scene, Valentine even ushered two
dozen reporters from behind the batting cage to the position in the
first base dugout at Shea Stadium where he said he had stood.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's histrionics will probably wind up being irrelevant,
because Rule 5.1 states that any manager, coach, player or trainer
who is ejected must leave the field instantly and remain in the
clubhouse until the game is over.
</P>
<P>
   While ejected managers have often hidden in the dugout runways
during games and umpires have looked the other way, Valentine crept
too far and was visible to television cameras while using eyeblack
stickers for a fake mustache, borrowed black sunglasses and a black
baseball cap. Valentine said he was unaware that Rule 5.1 confined
him to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk about it,'' Valentine said. ``That's what an
appeal is. I want to make sure no one thought I was in the dugout.
I was in the clubhouse most of the time and then I came out and
made a couple of jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   The league did not laugh and acted swiftly to suspend Valentine
because it felt that his actions flirted with the integrity of the
game. If the Mets made a pitching change, used a pinch-hitter or
had a successful hit and run after Valentine was ejected in the
12th inning of the 14-inning game against Toronto, the Blue Jays
could have protested their 4-3 defeat and argued that Valentine had
orchestrated those moves. But Valentine scoffed at this notion and
claimed he never witnessed one pitch from his perch beside the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally out of players, except for one pitcher,''
Valentine said. ``There was not one move to make on my bench or in
my bullpen and I definitely wasn't sitting on the bench. Go
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   It is quite rare for a manager to be suspended, unless he is
connected with a brawl or has an altercation with an umpire.
Valentine was suspended for three games while with Texas in 1986
after an incident with an umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he wore the disguise as a way of loosening up his
team, and he felt it worked because virtually everyone who saw him
grinned and all of the Mets' pitchers donned fake mustaches before
batting practice Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret it,'' he said. ``It's going to cost me a lot of
money. I don't regret the fact that it lightened the team.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips declined to comment on
Valentine's behavior, other than to say that the organization would
not fine or punish him and that Phillips was upset that the Mets
might lose their manager for two games. Phillips repeated a
question and said: ``Did I laugh? No comment on that.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked Valentine to demonstrate where he had been on
Wednesday, he took the bait and invited a gaggle of reporters to
follow him. There are six steps leading from the dugout to the
runway, and Valentine asserted that he had stood there and moved
back and forth but never stepped on the top step, and so he had
never been in the dugout. While there is a picture of Valentine
seemingly sitting in the dugout, there is a duffel bag resting on a
ledge behind him in the photograph. There are no ledges behind the
seats in the dugout, but there is a ledge adjacent to the
staircase.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the pictures, it looks like I was in the dugout,
doesn't it?'' Valentine said. ``Have you guys seen that? Who else
thought I was in the dugout?''
</P>
<P>
   After several reporters nodded or raised their hands, Valentine
smiled and said, ``You're all wrong.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
