<SLUG> BC-TIDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURAL WONDER ON PUGET SOUND WILL HAVE HIGH AND LOW POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ In the south Puget Sound basin near Olympia,
they're talking about ``the bathtub slosh effect.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the name for the dramatic rise and fall of Puget Sound to
come just before noon Monday, when forces of nature will bring the
lowest and highest tides of 1999 _ minus 3.5 feet, followed by a
corresponding high tide of plus 12.5 feet about seven hours later.
</P>
<P>
   The swing of the salt water will mean a 16-foot rise and fall,
about twice the annual average.
</P>
<P>
   In Olympia, at the closed end of the Sound, the swing of the
tide is still more pronounced _ a 22-foot difference as the water
retreats and then sloshes back.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's extreme tides won't be a record _ that would be the
minus 4.5 feet that comes every 19 years and is due again in about
2007 _ but the natural wonder is notable enough to excite local
maritime folks and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a horrid time, however, to be a sea urchin, tidelands
snail, sponge, starfish or kelp. Caught in the struggle between sea
and land, these delicate forms of sealife are exposed to prolonged
predations from people and nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have nightmares, this would be one of the worst,''
says Megan Dephier, a University of Washington intertidal
specialist in Friday Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very stressful,'' Dephier says. ``With the air and sun,
there may be dying plants and animals, algae bleaches white, snails
close up tight. Dessication occurs, and people pull or rip them
from their homes'' even by doing something as innocent as turning
over a rock.
</P>
<P>
   The bulging tides that swing into the Sound from the Pacific
Ocean also carry more powerful current, especially at places like
the Tacoma Narrows where water bottlenecks between islands and land
masses. At Deception Pass on Whidbey Island, north of Seattle, the
current could reach 8.1 knots per hour, or about 13 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners will keep their eyes peeled as channels narrow. Pilots
who board the big freighters, grain ships and tankers that commonly
draw 55 feet pay attention in places like Guemes Channel near
Anacortes, the Duwamish Waterway in Elliott Bay and Hylebos
Waterway in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Bill Bock of the Puget Sound Pilots group said some
sailings may have to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions may prove a challenge for boaters, but the extreme
tides are opportunities for researchers, foragers, divers,
sightseers _ even Druids preparing to celebrate the summer solstice
a week hence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very aware of the tides,'' says Leon Reed of Seattle,
pursewarden for the 180-member Bards of Caer Pugetia and
representative to the British Druid Order. Ancient teachings for
Druids, who celebrate cycles of the sun and moon and revere
connections between earth, sea and sky, call for them ``to learn
thre new things each day: The phase of the moon; the day of the
week; and the state of the tide, without error,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   When the moon and the sun line up, combining their gravitational
pull, as they will next week, the resulting spring tides are always
more extreme than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The interconnection between the heavens and the earth that bring
about the seasonal effects aren't lost on modern scientists, who
consider it prime time to study intertidal life.
</P>
<P>
   UW's Dephier, for example, will board a helicopter with state
biologists to inventory kelp, sea grass, barnacles and mussel beds
while describing the consistency of sandy or gravelly soils and the
broadness of beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Divers will be out to enjoy the high tides around Alki Beach and
at Edmonds, where they have to be careful because the currents can
push them far from their boats, said Mary Jachetta of Sailfin
Diving Adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Brace yourself now. Here comes a little bit of science.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mumford, head of the state Department of Natural Resources
aquatic resources section, said Pacific Coast tides have more
dramatic ranges than Atlantic Ocean tides.
</P>
<P>
   He called the West Coast tides, and Washington tides in
particular, ``fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called mixed semi-diurnal,'' Mumford explained.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two high and two low tides in a 24-hour period, there's a
high-high tide and a low-high tide, with corresponding high-low
tides and low-low tides.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Atlantic and Pacific oceans have two low tides and two
high tides a day, but tide patterns are affected by the coastline
and the depth of the water. Atlantic Coast tides, for example, are
far more regular, Mumford said. In contrast, the Pacific Coast has
a high-high tide, a low-high tide, a low-low tide and a high-low
tide, due in part to the shape of each basin.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas of Washington, it might seem as though Atlantis
has risen, as the state's 3,438 miles of coastline grows
exponentially, he added.
</P>
<P>
   No one can say precisely how much coastline will surface, but
Shallow Willapa Bay will drain dramatically during low tide. West
of Port Angeles, long rocky reefs will become visible off Tongue
Point from tiny Salt Creek County Park. At Seattle's Alki Point,
the ruins of Luna Park, a turn-of-the-century amusement park, will
emerge, along with a field of sea grass, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, wrecks might become visible. Out on Cape Alava,
the westernmost point of the Continental United States and site of
the ancient Makah Indian whaling village of Ozette, fantastic rocks
and reefs will be exposed, including areas where tribal whale
hunters moved rocks to create a pre-historic boat ramp of sorts,
said UW oceanographer Richard Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland especially likes the sound of the bathtub sloshing
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those `Hail Mary' things you try to explain,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And then he tried:
</P>
<P>
   Wave motions flow down-Sound to the Olympia area, where they hit
a land wall, move up and turn the other way. The slow rhythms take
over, just as stirring a hand in a bathtub at a slow rhythm creates
more oscillation than rapid splashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just does what every kid figures out in the bathtub _ it's
not force, it's rhythm,'' Strickland said.
</P>
<P>
   Some spots are better than others to see the low tide. Rosario
Beach near Deception Pass is one. But the increasing numbers of
tourists need to remember beach etiquette lest they destroy fragile
life-forms, researchers warn.
</P>
<P>
   There's also concern that seaweed harvesting in some areas could
do lasting damage if kelp afficonados get carried away. In some
places, signs have been posted in several languages to caution
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take too much seaweed off the beach, it's sort of like
clear-cutting the forest,'' Dephier said. ``All that shade and food
provides the structure for the shoreline community. Some might grow
back, some won't grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Even walking on a beach can be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland and Charles Simenstad, a UW fisheries biologist, said
anemones and seaweeds are hardy enough to withstand crashing water
but are soft enough to be crushed under a heel. Sponges and fish
eggs can be destroyed when rocks are turned over. Starfish often
cling to overhangs because they can't stand sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Like most critters living in the no-man's land that day,
``they're not very happy,'' Strickland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
