<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON TO MEET WITH LAKERS NEXT WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Bill Bradley's campaign for the White House
will bring Phil Jackson to Los Angeles next week. A campaign for
another NBA championship might get Jackson to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson arrives Wednesday in his role as confidant to Bradley,
his former New York Knicks teammate and presidential hopeful. But
Jackson's own agenda includes stumping at the Forum, where he will
meet with Los Angeles Lakers brass amid reports he will sign a
four-year deal to coach the team.
</P>
<P>
   The former Chicago Bulls coach, owner of six championship rings,
has been negotiating with the Lakers through his agent, Todd
Musberger, but has not spoken directly with executive vice
president Jerry West. That will change in the next few days as the
Lakers try to consummate a deal with Michael Jordan's former
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Sources within and outside the organization confirmed Jackson
has been offered the job, for about $6 million per year. But
sources contradicted reports that a deal had already been reached.
Jackson, meanwhile, reportedly is vacationing in Alaska and has not
been in contact with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked to him, we've had some negotiations with him,
but I have not talked to Phil personally,'' West said Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   West would not confirm a contract had been offered, saying only
``we've discussed parameters'' of a deal. ``We're certainly not at
the finish line, that's for sure...
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to explore possibilities,'' West said. ``That
doesn't mean they're all with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility is retaining Kurt Rambis, previously the
favorite for the job, who remains on stand-by in case the deal with
Jackson fails to materialize. If Jackson is hired, Rambis has been
guaranteed a job within the organization, probably as an assistant
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis said he's still hopeful of winning the job, but he's not
surprised the Lakers, who up until a week ago were leaning toward
re-hiring him, changed direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, since it didn't happen immediately after the season
(ended), I knew they were going to be open to other
considerations,'' Rambis said Friday from Chicago, where he was
attending the NBA pre-draft camp. ``I'm basically just waiting to
hear what happens. I'm in a situation where I'm still in
consideration and I've also been given assurances from Jerry West
that if Phil Jackson is hired as coach, I will be retained with the
Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Rambis said, he ``absolutely'' would be comfortable working
under Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil is a highly respected coach, and I respect him,'' he
said. ``The Lakers are going to go out and get the best guy they
can for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current market of unemployed coaches, the undisputed
``best guy'' is Jackson, who among whose six championships are
second only to the nine won by former Boston Celtics coach Red
Auerbach.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson took the past season off after winning his sixth title
in eight years with the Bulls and has spent much of his free time
working for Bradley. The Bradley campaign is scheduled to go
through L.A. Sunday, then return Wednesday through Friday with
Jackson in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers players steered clear of the issue Friday, but there is
clear support for Jackson in the locker room, where some players
lost confidence in Rambis amid the Lakers' playoff collapse against
the San Antonio Spurs. Shaquille O'Neal, who advocated that Rambis
replace the fired Del Harris in February, declined to support
Rambis in May.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is why the Lakers waited until a week and a half
ago to enter discussions with Jackson. He has been courted heavily
by the New Jersey Nets and New York Knicks, but the Lakers had
given every indication that Rambis would be retained and given a
two-year deal. Those close to the situation simply opined that
owner Jerry Buss was taking his time and decided to explore
Jackson's interest.
</P>
<P>
   That has never been much of a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jackson openly mused about the possibility of
coaching the Lakers _ ``If someone like the Lakers comes after me
and wants me to coach a team that's ready to pursue a championship
... what can I do?'' he wrote in ESPN Magazine. And he enthused
about the possibility of incorporating O'Neal into the ``triangle''
offense he made popular in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Of equal value is Jackson's acumen for handling an array of egos
and personalities. Such skills are sorely needed in a locker room
where O'Neal and Kobe Bryant have feuded and Glen Rice has moped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to look for things we think will be positive.
You can't deny he's had enormous success with great players,'' West
said. ``His teams seem to have a resolve about them, he seems to
have wonderful interaction with his players, and that's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Jackson does not become the Lakers' 15th coach, expect
them to stick with No. 14. The 41-year-old Rambis remains a
sentimental favorite and stands to be rewarded for his loyalty to
the Lakers after a combined 13 seasons as player and coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us are comfortable with Kurt Rambis here,''
West said, ``and we value him. We really do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, West remains coy about his own future. He has
contemplated retirement but said he hopes to fulfill a four-year
contract extension that begins in September. He has ``had some
great discussions'' with Buss, though, and implied he's staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still working,'' West said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
