<P>
   (NYT2) QUINCY, Mass. -- June 11, 1999 -- COMPUTERS-SPEECH-BOS,
6-11 -- Dr. Octavio Diaz, chief of emergency services at Quincy
Hospital, uses voice recognition software to enter a patient's data
into a computer. Diaz and a staff of nine doctors enter about 90
percent of patient reports using medical transcription software
sold by Lernout &AMP; Hauspie. ``It's a very user-friendly system once
you get up and running on it,'' said Diaz, who has been using
speech-recognition software for about 10 years. (Tom Landers/Boston
Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- June 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FORCE-1,
6-11 -- As members of the U.S. Army's 82 Airborne Division prepare
for deployment into Kosovo, Spec. Kerey Stickel took advantage of
the idle time to practice looking for mines with a mine-probing
stick on Friday at a base in the Macedonian capital. Several
thousand mines, or ``greens'' as the military refers to them,
placed by Yugoslav forces, are suspected to littering Kosovo.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
