<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 06/11/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-3, 6-11
-- Larry Johnson of the New York Knicks being assisted off the
floor by teammates Chris Dudley and Herb Williams in Game 6 of the
Eastern Conference finals at Madison Square Garden. Johnson
suffered a sprained knee and was taken to the hospital for a
precautionary MRI. If victorious the Knicks would eliminate the
Pacers and advance to the league championship series against the
San Antonio Spurs. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo) `
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-2, 6-11
-- The New York Knicks Larry Johnson taking a shot against the
Indiana Pacers Friday night in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference
finals at Madison Square Garden. Johnson suffered a sprained knee
in the second quarter and was taken to the hospital for a
precautionary MRI. If victorious the Knicks would eliminate the
Pacers and advance to the league championship series against the
San Antonio Spurs. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1, 6-11
-- Latrell Sprewell of the New York Knicks taking a shot against
the Indiana Pacers Friday night in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference
finals at Madison Square Garden. If victorious the Knicks would
eliminate the Pacers and advance to the league championship series
against the San Antonio Spurs. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) KUKES, Albania -- June 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA-2,
6-11 -- A newly distributed poster warning refugees about the
danger of hand grenades in Kosovo hangs on the wall as ethnic
Albanian children play a game with sticks at an information tent in
a refugee camp near Kukes on Friday. Many refugees in the camp have
said that they are waiting for assurances from NATO and aid
agencies that Kosovo will be safe before considering returning to
their homes. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DES MOINES, Iowa -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
13 -- BIZ-PRIORITY-GROUP, 06-09 -- Connie Wimer, owner of Business
Publications Corp. in Des Monies, greets children at a debut of the
``Move Our Money'' bus. This national campaign was started and
developed by Ben Cohen, co-founder of Ben and Jerry's Homemade,
Inc. It is part of Business Leaders for Sensible Priorities, a
growing group of business people campaigning for fundamental change
in the way the Government uses its resources, a group which Cohen
organized. (Rodney White/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- June 11, 1999 -- BEIRUT BEACHES, 6-11
-- Beirut may have a slightly libertine air, but its culture
largely keeps women from its public beaches. Mohammed Tayid, left,
and his friends were inspired to build a woman out of sand. They
even gave her a soda. (Courtney Kealy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- June 11, 1999 -- GUN-CONTROL-2, 6-11 --
House Speaker Dennis Hastert on the Speaker's Balcony on Capitol
Hill before leaving for his home district on Friday. House
Republicans and Democrats filed more than 200 amendments on Friday
to a juvenile crime bill that has become a vehicle for the kind of
bitterly divisive gun-control measures that the Senate approved
last month. Republicans said that the stakes of getting something
through the House were high, with the very credibility of Hastert's
leadership on the line. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- SUB-PETS-MICROCHIPS-1, 6-11
-- Dr. Andrew Lang, left, is assisted by Aura Truslow in implanting
a microchip on a dog at the local ASPCA on Friday. At least 1.6
million American pets now have these chips in their shoulders and
dozens of shelters, including the Manhattan one, have them
automatically implanted when animals are adopted. The chips allow
shelters to quickly find the owners of lost dogs and cats. (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- June 11, 1999 -- CALIF-LA-SUBWAY-2, 6-11
-- Sculptured Hollywood style palm trees lead the way to the subway
station at Hollywood and Vine. After two decades of construction,
with some spans costing some $500 million per mile, the L.A.
subway, all 11 miles ofit, opens to the public on Saturday. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LOS ANGELES -- June 11, 1999 -- CALIF-LA-SUBWAY, 6-11 --
An automobile bench designed to reflect the car culture of Los
Angeles is found in the Hollywood and Vine subway station earlier
this month. After two decades of construction, with some spans
costing some $500 million per mile, the L.A. subway, all 11 miles
ofit, opens to the public on Saturday. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 13 --
BIZ-PROFILE-BONSIGNORI, 6-11 -- Michael Bonsignori, head of
Honeywell, during a pause in the merger action earlier this week.
When Honeywell Inc., the $8.4 billion company he has headed since
1993, and Allied Signal told the world they planned to merge, it
has been helicopters, airplanes, limousines, one after the other,
shuttling him between Honeywell's Minneapolis headquarters and
Allied's home in Morristown, N.J. (Chester Higgins, Jr./New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- June 11, 1999 -- RESTORATION-FLOATER, 6-11
-- The Capitol Rotunda where a plastic sheath protects layers of
lead-based paint from falling onto the floor while the mural,
painted by Constantino Brumidi depicting George Washington
surrounded by 13 women representing the original colonies, is
restored on Friday. Brumidi, who was born in Rome in 1805, had
painted in the Vatican and in the palace and villa of a Roman
prince before emigrating to the United States in 1852. After he
proved his skill in fresco painting in 1855, he spent much of the
next 25 years until his death in 1880 decorating the Capitol.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- June 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FORCE-3,
6-11 -- Thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo line the
road outside a refugee camp as a convoy of British military
vehicles made their way towards the Macedonian border with Kosovo
on Friday. British soldiers are expected to enter Kosovo early
Saturday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KUKES, Albania -- June 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 6-11
-- An ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo reads the latest news in
a camp run by the French humanitarian group Doctors Without Borders
on Friday. Many refugees in the camp have said that they are
waiting for assurances from NATO and aid agencies that Kosovo will
be safe for their return. Some refugees said they expected to
remain in the camps for as long as two more months, even though
many are only an hour's drive from home. (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- June 11, 1999 -- MUSIC-GEILS-BOS, 06-11 --
Members of the J. Geils band which is going back on tour are, from
left, Peter Wolf, J. Geils, Danny Klein, Magic Dick, Stephen Jo
Bladd, Seth Justman. ``We don't even think about whether we should
have done this sooner,'' says Klein, the band's bassist. ``We're
doing it now and that's what's happening.'' From 1967 to 1983, band
members toured like madmen and released 15 albums. (Suzanne
Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 13 --
COKE-CUBA-COX, 6-11 -- Cuban President Fidel Castro has threatened
to manufacture fake Coca-Cola in retaliation for a recent New York
court ruling against Havana in a fight over the trademark for
Havana Club rum, Cuba's most-prized liquor. The tug-of-war pits
Cuba and its French partner, Pernod Ricard, against the
Bermuda-based liquor giant, Bacardi, both of whom hope to sell
Havana Club rum in the United States. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 13 --
NITEOUT-WELLS, 06-11 -- Former Yankee's pitcher David Wells,
center, at his birthday party at Veruka on Broome Street. The party
marked a return to New York nightlife for Wells, who during his
years as a Yankee was known for his 91-mile-an-hour pitching and
barroom-brawling social life before being traded to the Toronto
Blue Jays. (Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 13 --
INDIA-FOLK-FASHION, 06-11 -- Christina Gitti, the head of her own
Milan-based company, Malatesta, with some of the items she sells.
Gitti, 31, sells block-printed sarongs and pashmina shawls to
Bergdorf Goodman and Calypso, a trend-setting purveyor of exotic
trinkets and clothing in SoHo. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- June 11, 1999 -- GUN-CONTROL, 6-11 -- House
Speaker Dennis Hastert finishes paperwork in his Capitol Hill
office on Friday prior to returning to Illinois for the weekend.
Hastert said Thursday that he would not pressure House Republicans
to vote for new restrictions on firearms, seemingly distancing
himself from several Republican gun- control proposals introduced
earlier in the week. The House is expected to continue debating gun
control legislation next week. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 13 --
ABOUT-CARS-AUDI-, 6-10 -- The new Audi TT sport coupe, both inside
and out. Unlike the Prowler, the T-Bird, and the Volkswagen Bug,
the TT manages to avoid airs of pining nostalgia. With its blunted
fenders and taut skin, its constant-radius roofline and its crisp
creases around curvilinear wheel arches, the TT recalls nothing so
strongly as other brilliantly executed new cars from Audi and its
parent, Volkswagen. (Steve Egan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
13 -- BIZ-HOME, 06-11 -- Owners of Informed Decisions
International, Jane Allen Petrick, center, and her husband, Kalle,
talk with Heather Cannon, left, who delivered a recent lunch to
their home. When couple started their own consulting firm out of
their home they realized they need to outsource their meals. (Susan
Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW ORLEANS, La. -- June 11, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
13 -- INVESTING-WITH-ARMSTRONG, 06-11 -- Arden Armstrong, lead
manager of the $887.6 million MAS Mid-Cap Growth fund, right,
enjoys a street musician with her mother, Carolyn Conover, at Cafe
Du Monde. ``We like to find quality growth,'' she explained from
her office in West Conshohocken, Pa. ``We're not momentum or
growth-at-a-reasonable-price investors.'' (Lee Celano/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- June 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FORCE-2,
6-11 -- A convoy of British military vehicles heads down a road
through the Macedonian capital on Friday. NATO massed thousands of
troops and equipment closer to Macedonia's border with Kosovo,
ready to move in to secure the way for hundreds of thousands of
returning ethnic Albanian refugees. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) QUINCY, Mass. -- June 11, 1999 -- COMPUTERS-SPEECH-BOS,
6-11 -- Dr. Octavio Diaz, chief of emergency services at Quincy
Hospital, uses voice recognition software to enter a patient's data
into a computer. Diaz and a staff of nine doctors enter about 90
percent of patient reports using medical transcription software
sold by Lernout &AMP; Hauspie. ``It's a very user-friendly system once
you get up and running on it,'' said Diaz, who has been using
speech-recognition software for about 10 years. (Tom Landers/Boston
Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- June 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FORCE-1,
6-11 -- As members of the U.S. Army's 82 Airborne Division prepare
for deployment into Kosovo, Spec. Kerey Stickel took advantage of
the idle time to practice looking for mines with a mine-probing
stick on Friday at a base in the Macedonian capital. Several
thousand mines, or ``greens'' as the military refers to them,
placed by Yugoslav forces, are suspected to littering Kosovo.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
