<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPECIAL-ED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY SEEKS ACCORD ON INTEGRATION OF SPECIAL EDUCATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Legislative leaders are nearing an agreement on
overhauling the state's special education program to discourage
schools from placing disabled students in segregated classrooms,
legislative aides from both parties said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's special education program has come under increasing
criticism in recent years for placing far too many children, a
disproportionate number of them black and Hispanic boys in New York
City, into separate classrooms, with little chance of graduating
with a regular diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have argued for years over proposals for change, but
are now facing a threat by federal officials to cut off $325
million in aid if they fail to act. Federal officials said New York
was the only state that still failed to comply with federal rules
for special education under the Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, school districts receive additional
state aid for each child placed in special education, which is for
students with problems including severe physical disabilities,
learning disabilities, emotional troubles and behavioral problems.
The extra money is intended to finance additional attention to the
severely handicapped, but critics say it has led educators to find
disabilities in children who are simply troubled or underachieving.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan being considered, the state would give school
systems more money to return disabled children to regular
classrooms, where they could continue to receive extra help. The
school systems would not be required to move the children back, but
would receive more aid if they did than if they kept the children
in special education classrooms, legislative aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a concession to lawmakers who were worried that their
local school systems would lose money, the plan would not reduce
aid to schools that fail to steer disabled students back into
regular classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a financial incentive for schools to place disabled
children into regular classrooms,'' said a participant in the
negotiations. ``The schools have to do it in order to get the extra
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The exact amount of the incentive would vary by district,
according to the state's complicated per-pupil aid formula.
Legislative officials would provide no estimate for how much more
the state would spend on special education, saying it depended on
how aggressively local districts moved to take advantage of the new
money.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was welcomed by educators in New York City, where
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has been trying to move disabled
students back into regular classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Allinger, a lobbyist for the Board of Education, said he
still had to review the details, but that he was nonetheless
encouraged. ``The board would welcome any proposal that assists
schools in appropriately integrating disabled children with their
nondisabled peers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Special education is one of the most contentious issues in state
government, and participants in the talks cautioned that some
details needed to be ironed out before lawmakers could adopt the
plan. The deal also requires the approval of Gov. George Pataki,
who has not been briefed on the plan but who has been calling on
the Legislature to overhaul special education for the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes after officials from the U.S. Department of
Education issued an ultimatum to the state this month. The
officials ordered the state to change its policies so as to place
more disabled students in regular classrooms, or risk losing about
$325 million in federal aid a year. That is roughly 10 percent of
the total amount that the state spends annually to educate children
with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials had urged New York for years to change its
program, contending that a disabled student should be educated in
the ``least restrictive setting'' _ ideally, a regular classroom _
unless that student cannot succeed there even with additional
specialized services, like individual tutoring. But the threat that
was issued earlier this month was the first time the federal
government set a firm deadline for the state to make those changes.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Green, a spokeswoman for the Department of Education, said
officials in the agency could not comment on the proposal because
they have not had an opportunity to review it. But, she added, ``We
would certainly be encouraged to see state action to change the
funding formula in compliance with federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Officials negotiating the plan said they were confident that it
would allow the state to avoid any financial penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real deadline here, and everyone here wants to get
this issue behind us,'' said one legislative aide speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``I think this will come together and
resolve that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The special education program, which includes 400,000 students
statewide, including 84,000 in New York City, is one of the fastest
growing parts of the state budget. The state is spending $1.4
billion in the current school year, up from $527 million in the
1985-86 school year, consuming roughly 12 percent of all the money
the state spends on aid to schools.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides aid to schools using a formula that covers
a broad range of disabilities, from deafness and blindness to more
ill-defined conditions like emotional disturbances and learning
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, most special education students do not have
readily defined physical disabilities like deafness or blindness.
Instead, they are classified as ``learning disabled'' or
``emotionally handicapped.'' Education experts contend that such
labels are often loosely applied, particularly in cases in which
teachers want to rid themselves of disruptive students.
</P>
<P>
   But changing the program has been politically thorny, with
lawmakers under pressure from parents' groups and school
administrators fearful that changes would deprive disabled children
of needed services. They were particularly concerned that the state
would attempt to wring savings from the program by putting disabled
students back into regular classroom settings without providing the
services those students needed.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal addresses those concerns by leaving the current
financing formula intact, while providing more money to give school
districts an incentive to provide services to disabled students
within regular classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the current system, a school district would lose the
additional money it receives for a disabled child once that child
was moved back to a regular class, even if he required additional
help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
