<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIR-OSCAR-TRIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT IS SAID TO CLEAR SAFIR OF VIOLATIONS IN OSCARS TRIP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City lawyers have concluded that the New York Police
Commissioner, Howard Safir, showed poor judgment but violated no
ethics rules or laws by accepting a free junket to the Academy
Awards from a corporate executive for Revlon, according to
officials familiar with a draft of a report on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   A final version of the report by Corporation Counsel Michael
Hess has not been released or presented to Safir, who requested the
review after questions arose about his excursion to the awards
ceremony in March, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the broad outlines of Hess' preliminary findings are
contained in a draft report, the details of which were reported
Friday in The Daily News. While the draft report clears Safir of
any ethical violation, it recommends that he avoid any appearance
of impropriety by reimbursing the Revlon executive, George Fellows,
approximately $7,000 for the cost of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Hess declined to comment Friday, saying it was premature to
discuss a document that is still being prepared by his office.
Safir's spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, said the Commissioner had not
been told of any preliminary conclusions. ``We don't know anything
about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Revlon spokesman, James Conroy, said, ``We have not heard
anything from the city concerning a report of the corporation
counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars trip was one in a series of ethical imbroglios in
which Safir found himself entangled this year. A few weeks after
the trip, Safir was criticized for having used city detectives to
investigate an auto accident involving his wife and to provide
security at his daughter's wedding. The commissioner said the
detectives were necessary in both cases because of threats made
against him, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani accepted his explanation,
saying the commissioner ``has excellent judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir's trip became a particularly contentious topic because it
appeared that he had planned to skip a City Council hearing on
police procedures in the wake of the police shooting of Amadou
Diallo to attend the late-night Oscar parties. Safir ultimately did
attend the hearing, after taking a late night flight home after the
ceremony. Critics said Safir suddenly changed his itinerary after
being videotaped by television crews at the Oscars. The
commissioner said he had planned to attend the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The City Charter bars officials from accepting gifts from people
who do business with the city or in situations in which the gift is
being bestowed because of their government position. Safir has said
that Fellows, the president of Revlon, invited him and his wife,
Carol, to accompany him to the ceremony because they are friends,
not because of a professional relationship. The Safirs were guests
aboard a corporate jet that Fellows had chartered. They stayed in a
$700-a-night suite at the Peninsula Beverly Hills Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation counsel's report, whose release has been
described as imminent for several weeks, is scheduled to be
disseminated next week, but it may not end the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Several people, including City Councilman Sheldon S. Leffler,
have formally asked the city's Conflicts of Interest Board, an
independent body, to review Safir's trip. While Hess' review is
advisory, the conflicts board is officially charged with
investigating possible ethical violations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wayne Hawley, deputy counsel for the board, said it is against
policy to discuss, or even confirm, an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Leffler, who is chairman of the Council's Public Safety
Committee, said reimbursements for such trips do not alleviate the
ethical concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a message to the average citizen that the worst
that can happen is, if you get caught, all you have to do is pay
what you should have had to pay to begin with,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
