A2670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SPEED-LIMITS-NYT &LR;      06-11 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPEED-LIMITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC MAYOR MAY GET POWER TO SLASH SPEED LIMITS TO 15 MPH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ State lawmakers are likely to give the Giuliani
administration the blanket authority it has sought to lower speed
limits on New York City streets to as low as 15 miles per hour, a
power the mayor says the city needs to make side streets safer for
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   State law generally prohibits local governments from setting
limits lower than 25 mph, so transportation experts and policy
makers at all levels of government are eager to see how such a
change would alter the fabric of city neighborhoods, and whether it
would reduce accidents. Their interest is heightened by the fact
that a number of cities and towns around the state, including some
of New York City's suburbs, have inquired about gaining the same
power to lower speeds.
</P>
<P>
   A bill allowing the city to lower speed limits passed last year
in the state Assembly, where Democrats are the majority, and
legislators and top aides say it is likely to pass this year in
both the Assembly and the Republican-controlled Senate. The state
Department of Transportation, controlled by Gov. George Pataki, has
raised some concerns about the bill but is not actively fighting
it, and the governor's office says he is not opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, the city's Department of
Transportation has taken steps to slow drivers on residential side
streets, which Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has called part of his
campaign to improve the quality of life in the city. Where there
were once only a handful of speed ``humps'' _ less steeply pitched
than the traditional speed bumps _ in the city, there are now more
than 200.
</P>
<P>
   In some spots, the city has experimented with raised crosswalks
and ``neck-downs,'' the narrowing of streets where they approach
intersections through wider sidewalks and raised crosswalks.
</P>
<P>
   The bill before the Legislature would allow the city to post
speeds of 15 and 20 miles per hour wherever it also used such
physical impediments to speeding, known as traffic-calming devices,
leaving it entirely to the city's discretion which streets those
should be. Giuliani has petitioned the Legislature for that power
since last year.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the great majority of city streets _ including those
where no limit is posted _ have a speed limit of 30 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   As for where the city would set speeds lower than 25 mph,
Michael Primeggia, deputy city transportation commissioner for
traffic operations, said the number of possible locations would be
in the hundreds and perhaps thousands. ``It would be
site-specific,'' he said. ``It wouldn't be wholesale. In each case,
it will be preceded by a thorough engineering study.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Giuliani, the number of pedestrian deaths and injuries has
declined sharply, as the police have stepped up traffic enforcement
at trouble spots and the Department of Transportation has taken
steps like giving pedestrians more time to cross wide streets
before the lights change. Even so, more than 200 people on foot are
killed by vehicles every year, and 12,000 are injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law is an incredibly important step toward making the
city safer for pedestrians,'' said John Kaehny, executive director
of Transportation Alternatives, a group that advocates making the
city more pedestrian-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The Automobile Club of New York, the local arm of the American
Automobile Association, has voiced some reservations about the
bill, though it does not formally oppose it. ``Fifteen miles per
hour is an unrealistically low speed limit, even on streets with
traffic-calming devices,'' said Mark Kulewicz, a traffic engineer
with the group. ``I ask anybody who's uncertain about it to get in
a car and drive 15 miles per hour, and you'll have a very difficult
time doing that, even in a parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``People who live near speed humps are subjected to a
fair amount of noise, either from cars bottoming out, or from stuff
rattling around in the backs of trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the push to install the humps invariably comes from a
street's residents, according to the Department of Transportation
and state legislators who field complaints about speeding and road
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Primeggia said the likeliest spots for 15-mph limits ``are the
smallest local streets, the residential streets where you want the
traffic to be local, not people trying to cut through to avoid
congestion on the major boulevards.''
</P>
<P>
   Another target would be side streets adjoining major traffic
arteries like Queens Boulevard, Flatbush Avenue or the Grand
Concourse, where people turn off the thoroughfares onto smaller
roads at relatively high speeds, Kaehny said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the No. 1 situation where pedestrians get hit by cars,
when the driver is making a turn too fast and hits someone in a
crosswalk,'' Kaehny said. ``By our analysis, that's how 17 percent
of pedestrian deaths happen.''
</P>
<P>
   State law allows limits below 25 mph immediately in front of
schools, but advocates of lower speeds say that the danger area for
children is often elsewhere, at back exits from school yards, or at
busy intersections a block or two from campus.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the bill stalled in the Senate Transportation
Committee. This year, it has moved out of the Transportation
Committee and to the powerful Rules Committee, controlled by
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some minor issues to work out, but we're confident
they will be worked out,'' said John McArdle, a spokesman for
Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the concerns raised by the state Department of
Transportation are not likely to stall the bill again. State
transportation officials are worried about instances when lower
speeds on city streets could affect state highways _ for example,
by causing traffic to back up at an expressway off-ramp. But city
officials say they would make any such speed-limit changes in
consultation with the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
