<SLUG> BC-JONES-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER KNICK ARRESTED IN SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ The Nashville police Friday arrested Dontae'
Jones, the former New York Knicks and Boston Celtics player, and
accused him and another man of shooting and injuring seven people
in April outside a Nashville nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was the Knicks' third selection in the first round of
the 1996 draft, surrendered to police early Friday afternoon after
news reports had named him as a suspect in the shootings, which
took place after a Nashville street festival.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7-inch Jones, 24, was charged with felony reckless
endangerment and felony vandalism. He was immediately released on
$7,000 bail, a Metro Nashville Police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The second man, Karshma Dardy, 26, was arrested Thursday in
connection with the shooting and faces the same charges as Jones.
He was also released on bail. No court date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the two men were connected to a Nashville
rap-music promotion company called Keep It Wicked Entertainment,
members of which were involved in a heated argument April 25 with a
Memphis rap group that erupted into the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   According to official reports and witnesses, the Memphis group
had paid Jones' company for the right to perform in an urban music
and entertainment festival called Street Nic in downtown Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   But the festival ended before the group performed. Members of
the rap group then went to a well-publicized party at the Players
Draft House nightclub in southern Nashville looking for
representatives of Keep It Wicked Entertainment to get their money
back.
</P>
<P>
   The police say that is when the arguing and shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Allen, 26, an event coordinator who organized the party
at the nightclub, said she hid in a walk-in refrigerator inside the
club for about 15 minutes when she heard there was shooting
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing next to Dontae' Jones earlier that night and he
was yelling and cussing,'' Allen said. ``I walked away from him and
he threatened my life and my best friend's life. So when we heard
there was shooting outside, about eight of us hid in the cooler
until it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Tyce, a security guard hired by the club to patrol the
party of about 1,000 people, was shot in the stomach. He told the
police that he had seen Jones and Dardy firing handguns in his
direction in the parking lot. Tyce, whose car was damaged by
bullets, was the most seriously hurt of the seven people shot.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who grew up in Nashville, was the junior-college player
of the year after averaging 28.7 points for Northeast Mississippi
Community College during the 1994-95 season.
</P>
<P>
   He played the next season at Mississippi State, where he
averaged 14.7 points and was named the most valuable player of the
Southeastern Conference tournament after his team advanced to the
Final Four, where it lost to Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Jones left college in his junior year to play for the Knicks,
who drafted him with the 21st pick overall in the 1996 draft. But
he was sidelined for his entire rookie season after foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-98 season, he played for the Celtics and averaged
2.9 points a game. His contract was not renewed for this year.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones is convicted of the charges against him, sentences
might range anywhere from one year to four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Torry Johnson, the Nashville attorney general, said it was too
early to comment specifically on the case. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
