</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAX-COMMUTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT HEARS CASE AGAINST SELECTIVE REPEAL OF COMMUTER TAX  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)   By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for New York City, New Jersey and Connecticut
charged in court Friday that the new law repealing the commuter tax
only for New York state residents was politically motivated and
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Justice Barry Cozier of state Supreme Court
in Manhattan said he would try to rule on the law's validity by
June 29. In two weeks, lawyers for the State of New York will argue
in defense of the law, which is scheduled to take effect July 1.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's session, Richard Blumenthal, the attorney general
of Connecticut who appeared on behalf of his state, was optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very confident that the tax will be struck down,'' he
said. ``The only question is when and what court.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that as a matter of policy, he opposed any
commuter tax.
</P>
<P>
   But if New York City was to have such a tax, then it should be
applied equally, he said, mirroring the position he took in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to strike down the commuter tax as it existed
for 33 years,'' Blumenthal told Cozier. ``Nor are we here claiming
that citizens of Connecticut should not pay for their fair share of
the services that they enjoy while in fact they work here in New
York City.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``People similarly situated ought to be treated
similarly.''
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 commuters, 58 percent of whom live in New York
State, pay the tax, which is .45 of 1 percent on earned income for
most people. The change in the tax code would cost New York City at
least $210 million in lost revenue from commuters from the New York
suburbs. Repealing the tax for out-of-state commuters as well would
bring the lost total to $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 240,000 residents of New Jersey and about 86,000 from
Connecticut commute into the city, according to lawyers and legal
papers filed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, like Connecticut, would prefer to see the commuter
tax disappear entirely, and New York City wants a return to the
original law that taxed all commuters.
</P>
<P>
   But the parties, including several out-of-state commuters who
had also sued, were united Friday in their opposition to the new
law.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Rubin, a lawyer with the City Corporation Counsel's office,
told the judge, ``This statute was targeted at New York City.'' She
added that the new law could not be justified given the history of
its enactment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature introduced and passed the legislation because
of its incredibly parochial concerns,'' she said, ``not an actual
statewide concern.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the closely contested special election for
a State Senate seat for Rockland and Orange counties that prompted
Senate leaders, in an effort to sway voters of the commuter-rich
district, to change the commuter tax law.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rubin also contended that the state may not repeal the
commuter tax without seeking permission from the city, through what
is called a ``home rule'' message.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick DeAlmeida, a New Jersey deputy attorney general,
suggested that the new law was a kind of economic protectionism,
which would penalize those who ``cross the border from New
Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has essentially erected a fence around New York
City'' for New Jersey commuters, he said, adding, ``There's no
justification for that discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the commuters who had filed suit, Richard Swanson, a
lawyer from Ridgewood, N.J., cited what he said was the sponsors'
justification that the change would allow residents of New York
outside the city to be able to spend more of their money on the
city's restaurants, theaters and museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that really is the justification,'' he told the judge,
``how on the green earth does that rationale not apply equally to
someone from New Jersey or Connecticut?''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It can only be explained one way _ lack of political
representation in Albany.'' He said that was the ``worst kind of
taxation without representation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer of New York did
not argue their case before the judge Friday. They are scheduled to
appear on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brown, a spokesman for Spitzer, said that the office was
still preparing its legal papers for the judge, but that as far as
New York City is concerned, ``our position is that the State
Legislature has the power to impose or repeal taxes'' without
seeking the local government's permission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
